<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTAUDIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT FINDS THAT COUNTIES' MONEY HANDLING KEEPS WOMEN OUT OF
DOMESTIC VIOLENCE SHELTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Thousands of Missouri women were turned
away from domestic violence shelters because many counties didn't
collect or didn't spend money earmarked for shelters, according to
a state audit released Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 5,000 women and children were refused shelter in 1998
because the shelters were full, said Claire McCaskill, state
auditor.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 43,000 reported cases of domestic violence
in Missouri in 1998, according to the Missouri Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Counties collect and disburse many funds for domestic shelters.
State law allows counties to collect as many as three different
fees to help fund shelters and requires counties to collect a $5
fee on marriage licenses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, such fees accounted for about 5 percent of funding for
domestic violence shelters.
</P>
<P>
   But, the audit found, more than half the counties in Missouri
did not impose the three optional fees. Others collect money but
don't disburse all of it. Some collect money but place it in the
wrong accounts.
</P>
<P>
   While audits don't carry the force of law, they are tools for
prompting changes in public policy. In this case, those changes
could come on several fronts: Counties could change collection and
spending practices, for example, or legislators could change state
laws to require fee collections.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill's audit found that in 1998, about $1.2 million was
collected for shelters through such fees. If all Missouri counties
collected all the fees, the total amount could increase by
$902,000.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, almost $500,000 in fee collections remained
undisbursed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that was in St. Louis, which kept more than $300,000,
the audit found. More than 1,300 people were turned away from full
shelters in St. Louis that year.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis authorities did not explain to auditors why the money
had not been disbursed. Sylvia Jackson, program manager for
shelters in St. Louis, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller counties kept money they collected because there
had been no requests for it or because there were no shelters in
the county.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County, where Kansas City is located, spent all of its
money. More than 3,000 women and children, however, were turned
away, the audit found.
</P>
<P>
   More money could have been raised through a state program that
gives tax credits to businesses and people that donate money to
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Over a three-year period, that program resulted in only $1.5
million out of a possible $12 million in donations.
</P>
<P>
   The program needs to be publicized better to be more effective,
McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   The human cost of underfunded shelters is enormous, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point in time when women are in the most danger is when
they separate'' from their abusers, McCaskill said. ``That's when
they need a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Miller, executive director of the Rose Brooks Center, a
50-bed domestic violence shelter in Kansas City, said the
availability of a shelter was key in helping women permanently
leave abusers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she has a safe place to go, she's much more likely to break
the cycle and not go back to her abuser again,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   To maximize funding and to help more victims of domestic
violence, a state agency should centralize the collection and
disbursement of money for shelters, McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Public Safety would be the best agency
to take over such a function, McCaskill said. It already
administers millions of dollars in state and federal grants for
domestic violence shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Centralizing the collection and allocation of money would solve
several problems, said Tom Brooks, spokesman for the Missouri
Coalition Against Domestic Violence, which requested the audit.
</P>
<P>
   A centralized agency could market the state tax credit program
better, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   And money not disbursed by individual counties would be paid out
to areas that need more funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for counties to be hoarding this money where
there's no expectation that a shelter will ever be built,'' Brooks
said. ``It's collected for a specific purpose. If you don't have
anywhere to spend it, it ought to be spent somewhere. It's not
serving anyone sitting in a bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other states already centralize fee collection and
distribution, McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   But political realities might prevent such a system in Missouri,
said Rep. Vicky Riback Wilson, a Columbia Democrat who sponsored
domestic violence legislation last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think the majority of communities would want to keep
local control of their funds,'' Wilson said. ``I think that
suggestion is going to need a lot more scrutiny and debate. We have
to find a way to maintain local control over funds in each county
to at least ensure that funds are being distributed equitably.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
