<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX     09-26 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAGUE, WOODSON EXPECT MORE REPERCUSSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A day after the game, the post-touchdown
taunting by San Francisco 49ers receiver Terrell Owens and the
response by Dallas Cowboys safety George Teague was still on
everybody's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what happens when there's nothing good on the
football field to talk about. Both teams are 1-3.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers ``suspended'' Owens for a week and fined him a game
check worth $24,294. Owens has been excused from practice and
Sunday's game against the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Teague was ejected from the game after tackling Owens in an
attempt to prevent him from celebrating a second touchdown on the
blue star at midfield at Texas Stadium. He is anticipating a fine
from the NFL. So is safety Darren Woodson, who was ejected in the
fourth quarter for arguing with the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Both players could also be fined by the Cowboys for leaving the
locker room before the game was over. Cowboys coach Dave Campo said
he was disappointed that Teague and Woodson didn't wait for the
team and listen to his postgame speech.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on whether the players will be fined will come this
week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Teague said that he was wrong for tackling Owens. But
he said he has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that his frustration was a result of the
Cowboys' poor play and that Owens' showboating was just a ``double
whammy'' to his psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said he doesn't condone fighting, but he didn't deny
supporting Teague's response.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, however, said he wants the Cowboys to fight for wins
rather than fighting out of frustration when they are losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no room in the game for that,'' Campo said. AIKMAN
AND BOOS
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman said Monday he isn't bitter about being
booed by fans at Texas Stadium during Sunday's 41-24 loss to the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said that kind of treatment comes with the job of being
the quarterback. And fans, he said, have the right to be upset with
his and the team's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'd be upset if I was them, too, after some of the
performances we have had as a team,'' Aikman said. ``They felt I
contributed to that, and I certainly do. I tend not to dwell on
(the boos). I just try to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was disappointed that Cowboys fans have turned
against him after the success he has had, Aikman again sided with
the fans' perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are a team that's 1-3,'' Aikman said. ``It
doesn't matter what I've accomplished or what this football team
has accomplished in the past.'' EKUBAN SIDELINED BY TOE INJURY
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban will miss Sunday's game against
the Panthers after dislocating a toe against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have a bye the following Sunday, so Ekuban could be
back for the Oct. 15 matchup against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Other injuries from Sunday were not deemed serious. Receiver
Raghib Ismail (ankle), defensive tackle Leon Lett (hamstring) and
center Mark Stepnoski (hamstring) are listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Wane McGarity, who sat out the game because of a
sprained ankle, could return to practice this week. However, the
Cowboys are being cautious, listing him as doubtful for the
Carolina game.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dat Nguyen, who missed the past two games with a
sprained knee, has been upgraded to questionable for the Carolina
game. Nguyen said he won't know if he'll be able to play until
Wednesday after practice.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Charlie Williams, who has been out since the
beginning of training camp after a staph infection complicated his
recovery from knee surgery, is also listed as questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Williams passed a physical Friday and will return to practice
this week. However, he likely will be held out until after the bye
for conditioning reasons. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0005 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1556 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-26 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN AN EASY TARGET FOR OBNOXIOUS FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At heart, you're a coward.
</P>
<P>
   You hide behind your anonymity in a crowd, hundreds of feet from
where the real action is, and show your mettle by booing your lungs
out. What courage that must take.
</P>
<P>
   You know exactly who you are and so do we. Maybe not personally,
but we know the kind of person you are. We know how obnoxious you
can be. We know how bad you make everyone around you feel.
</P>
<P>
   You're the worst part of us, and maybe that's why we feel so
ashamed. There's a little bit of you in almost all of us. It's the
part we try to scrub away in the shower every day.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, who dresses you anyway? You stand there, holding up
your ``Bench Ache-Man'' sign, your hairy underarms adding just the
right touch of ``savoir faire'' to the proceedings, hoping maybe
you'll get your shot on national television.
</P>
<P>
   And you dress like that, wearing a so-called muscle shirt when
whatever muscle you once had has turned to jelly? You must be so
very proud today.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that was you in your blue Dallas Cowboys' jersey,
hooting and jeering at Troy Aikman with drool rolling down your
chin and a beer bottle in your hand. Yeah, we saw you, too.
Unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
   There were hundreds, maybe thousands, of you Sunday at Texas
Stadium, mindlessly piling all the blame on one man wearing the No.
8 jersey. And I didn't see him miss a single tackle on Charlie
Garner while the 49ers' running back was rushing for 201 yards and
the 49ers were putting 41 points on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but Aikman is such an easy target, right? He's the
highest-paid player on the field. He's supposed to lead his team to
victory. If he can't do it, get another leader. As if Randall
Cunningham could have made a difference. What, you thought maybe
that Cowboys' offense was capable of scoring 42 points Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   Why not boo Emmitt Smith and his 31 yards rushing? Or that shell
of an offensive line? Or, best of all, that stop-nobody defense?
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is, the only thing worse than the
Cowboys' performance Sunday was you. You, and you, and you.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were embarrassing as a football team, but sometimes
that happens in the NFL. Sometimes you just have to go to the
bottom and start over. San Francisco has done that. The Cowboys did
it in 1989. That's the way the system is supposed to work.
</P>
<P>
   But you embarrassed us as a sports city by your ignorance. I've
never been one who believed paying for a ticket gives anyone the
right to be insulting and asinine, but I suppose if you feel
compelled to boo, at least target the entire team, not one man.
</P>
<P>
   That was a team loss Sunday and there will be more. So, if
booing is your bag, you're going to have plenty of opportunity to
make yourself heard.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know it comes with the territory for the quarterback.
Aikman understands that, too, far better than most. He's
maintaining as stoic a demeanor as possible under the
circumstances. But inside, he's hurting and hurting bad, because he
wants to be what you want him to be.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be a winner. He helped bring you three Super Bowl
championships, remember? Now, you've turned on him like a rabid,
slavering dog.
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth is, you know you can get away with it. You know
you can hide in the crowd and leather-lung yourself until you're
blue in the face. You can hurl invectives and insults, spew hatred
and venom, and Aikman can't do a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   What's he going to do, scream back? Flash you the bird? No, that
would make him no better than you and he won't stoop to your level.
</P>
<P>
   You also know that if someone came up and invited you to walk
into the locker room to meet Aikman face-to-face, giving you a
chance to tell him whatever you might like, you'd be as tongue-tied
and red-faced as a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, you'd ask him, your voice quivering, ``Please, Mr.
Aikman, sir, could I have your autograph? You're the best, Troy!''
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes you who you are. You're as despicably
two-faced as a bogus silver dollar.
</P>
<P>
   You want someone to blame? Then pay attention. Jerry Jones said
after Sunday's debacle that when you boo Aikman, you're really
booing him. Maybe you are, maybe you aren't, but if you just have
to boo, then there's your real target.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jones who made the decision _ maybe because he knows how
fickle you, the fandom, can be _ to try and keep this team together
for one or two more playoff runs. He knew exactly how fast you'd
bail on him if he admitted this team had no chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   So, Jones traded the Cowboys' immediate draft future to bring in
a speed receiver in Joey Galloway, now lost for the season. He has
played games with the salary cap, restructuring contracts, paying
out enormous bonuses, constantly extending the team's debt into the
future.
</P>
<P>
   You never complained. All you ever said was, ``Just do it,
Jerry. Just win.''
</P>
<P>
   The day of reckoning is now at hand. Did you really think it
would never come?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' dance is over and the band has to be paid. All of
us get a little piece of that action.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, for a lot of reasons, should just walk away, but his
pride and his sense of honor won't let him do that. He won't quit
on you like you've quit on him.
</P>
<P>
   He might, however, show up at your used car lot today and boo
the heck out of you while you're trying to make that all-important
sale.
</P>
<P>
   He'll scream gutter insults, demean your manhood and question
the legitimacy of your birth, but try not to let it bother you.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing personal. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
