<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN OPERA OPENS ITS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Opera has known its fleeting fames and forgotten
masterpieces, but `Don Giovanni' is not among them. Since its debut
at the Prague National Opera in 1787, Mozart's great work,
subtitled `The Libertine Punished,' has never been out of the
international repertory. Presented with a difficult piece fueled by
intricate ensembles and a swiftly moving libretto by Lorenzo da
Ponte, companies large and small have had their go at it. In the
`large' category is the Metropolitan Opera which opened its season
with `Don Giovanni' on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Opening night at the Met is not for the fashion-conscious faint
of heart. Neither, however, is Franco Zeffirelli's ponderous
production, which though less flamboyant than usual still delights
in dwarfing humankind under soaring pillars and furiously
decorative detail.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to wriggle free from these attention-grabbing
surroundings was the exceptional cast. Renee Fleming sang Donna
Anna; Bryn Terfel, known as much for his exquisite diction as for
his stage presence, played the Don. Most Mozartian baritones long
for the chance to do both major men's parts in `Don Giovanni, each
blessed with marvelous music attached to very different
personalities. Ferruccio Furlanetto, the evening's Leporello, has
made a mini-career of alternating the two parts. Terfel makes the
switch this season: a former Leporello in the house now in the
title role.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer, the Norwegian soprano Solveig Kringelborn, sang
Donna Elvira with a clean intensity. Hei-Kyung Hong was a Zerlina
of jewel-like precision. Paul Groves was the dignified, affecting
if modest sounding Don Ottavio. James Levine conducted with special
passion and customary elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Also elevating the evening above the level of spectacle was
Stephen Lawless's spruced-up restaging: a reworking terribly
effective not for any coups or startling effects but for the care
and intelligence of its detail. This was the kind of true theater
that opera in general, especially in a nightly repertory house,
does not often come near to. There was purpose in every gesture. In
keeping with the old laws of physics, for every action one
experienced thought-out and plausible reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Terfel comes to the Don with his own powerful if somewhat
repugnant point of view. If the production is about period
elegance, the character itself achieves a modern meanspiritedness.
Endearing naughtiness is replaced with outright sadism. This is a
coldly obsessive figure for whom rape and murder is not offhand but
committed with pleasure. This not very nice man, on the other hand,
sings like an angel.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming's Donna Anna had unusual breadth. `Non mi dir' at the
end luxuriated in the softness of her timbre, yet the early scenes
abandoned beauty for its own sake and took on a wonderful
fierceness. She is in both moods a splendid musician; the attention
to rhythm, phrase length and pitch legitimized the emotion.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cast without significant weakness. John Relyea was the
assertive Masetto, Sergei Koptchak a deeply eloquent Commendatore.
Lawless' prowess along with new costumes (Sylvia Nolan) and
lighting (Wayne Chouinard) helped take some of the gloom from Mr.
Zeffirelli's slightly aging stage pictures. Superior musicmaking
made it a very special night at the opera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0017EDT &QL; 
