<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-26 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE WHITE SOX ARE SHOWING THAT SOMETIMES LESS CAN BE
MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No greater irony could impose itself on the playoffs
than the presence of the Chicago White Sox. No. 26 in the Major
League Baseball payroll standing for most of the season, the White
Sox have the majors' best won-lost record and are the newly crowned
champions of the American League Central.
</P>
<P>
   That the White Sox could go so far on so little is a tribute to
every facet of their organization, beginning with Jerry Reinsdorf,
the chairman. But that's where irony rears its delicious head.
</P>
<P>
   As the players association's Enemy No. 1, as an owner who would
fight the players to the catastrophic end over control of players
salaries, Reinsdorf has produced a team that undermines every
argument the owners make about salaries and payroll disparity. At a
time when officials and owners have identified payroll disparity as
the game's most pressing problem, a team that pays its players
one-third the amount the Yankees pay theirs has already clinched
its spot at the postseason party, while the Yankees still plod on
to secure their place.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but the Cleveland Indians, with a payroll twice
that of the White Sox, have been bumped from their perennial place
in the A.L. Central and may not even earn an invitation to the
party.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in terms of economic impact, this has been a very
different season from last. Last season the playoffs were populated
by teams with 8 of the 11 highest payrolls. The trend was painfully
clear, officials and owners lamented, and would never be reversed
without some drastic change in the system.
</P>
<P>
   A big payroll did not guarantee postseason play, they said in a
frequent refrain, but a team could not reach postseason play
without a big payroll. But this is a new year. Times have changed
quickly. This season only four or five of the top 14 teams in
payroll will play games after next Sunday. They are the Yankees,
the Mets, Atlanta, St. Louis and maybe the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers and the Baltimore Orioles once again
lead the big spenders who have gained the least for their money.
One wonders if they'll ever get it right. The Arizona Diamondbacks,
who won a division championship last season, added about $10
million to their payroll this season, but may as well spend this
October in the swimming pool beyond the right-center-field fence at
their ballpark. Those three teams began the season among the top
five in payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, on the other hand, was 15th and San Francisco 17th.
Close to the bottom were the White Sox and just ahead of them the
Oakland Athletics. Three or all four of those teams will play
postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of having Reinsdorf, the most militant of
owners, explain how his poorly paid White Sox could outplay far
wealthier teams, a telephone call was placed to his office in
Chicago Monday and then a request for a telephone interview was
placed with the team's public relations department. The subject of
the interview was provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, thanks,'' came the reply from Reinsdorf via a club
spokesman. Maybe he's saving his secrets for a book. But is this
any way to persuade the players something has to be done to adjust
payrolls?
</P>
<P>
   Billy Beane, the Athletics' general manager, was not as reticent
about addressing the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we'd like to make that an antiquated argument,'' he
said, referring to the payroll-disparity issue. ``But the realism
of it all is I think this is a pretty unique situation in Oakland.
It's a testament to the talent of the young players who are here,
but the system hasn't allowed any guarantee that we can retain our
best players in the prime of their careers. These young players are
not going go be young and inexpensive for long.''
</P>
<P>
   Beane's last comment was one of the points Commissioner Bud
Selig made. ``I won't deny there's a potential for an aberration
once in a while,'' Selig said. ``But the fact is the cost of
keeping the White Sox up there will be so high. When the Reds
almost made it last year, Jim Bowden said don't think this
aberration makes the system right,'' he said referring to the
Cincinnati general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox and the Athletics aside, Selig said, disparity
remains a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you definitely have overwhelming evidence of a
correlation between high payroll and winning,'' he said. ``See me
next year. I'm confident of that. Remember, you still have the same
teams winning, the Yankees, Atlanta, the Mets. Let's see what
happens in the playoffs. If there's an aberration, it's a quick
short aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled what Drayton McLane Jr., the Houston owner, said of
the Astros' three division titles: ``Someone had to win the
National League Central, but we got banged out in the first round
each time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the people in the union office offered a
different view of this season's developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at a certain point you have to have some sympathy for
the owners,'' Gene Orza, the union's No. 2 man, said, then
proceeded to cite examples of dire projections some owners have
presented during labor negotiations in the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1985 it was Oakland going out of business and they turned
around and won three division championships in a row,'' Orza said.
``Then they picked Pittsburgh, and Pittsburgh won a few division
championships. Then it was San Diego, but San Diego was in the
World Series. It's been a string of bad luck for them, almost
Kafkaesque bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   If Reinsdorf shows up at any of the negotiating sessions next
year after talks for a new collective bargaining agreement begin,
the dialogue between him and Orza would probably be worth the price
of a playoff ticket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
