<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO EXPECTED TO MAKE QB CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA coach Bob Toledo hit the Paus button Monday.
Or was it the panic button?
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of UCLA's 29-10 loss to Oregon in Saturday's Pac-10
Conference opener, the UCLA coach announced that Cory Paus,
expected to be out for two more weeks with a separated right
throwing shoulder, has been cleared by doctors to begin practicing
in pads and will likely replace Ryan McCann as the Bruins' starting
quarterback against Arizona State Saturday night at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to evaluate him and see how he does (in practice),''
Toledo said. ``If Cory is ready to go and is 100 percent, then he
will start against Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a clear-cut decision to do anything yet. I'm
saying if he's physically ready and shows it in practice that he's
capable of doing it, then he'll start. He threw it and threw it
well (during a light practice Monday). I'll definitely have an idea
by tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo took great pains to emphasize that Paus is completely
healed from the separated shoulder he suffered on the first play of
the season opener against Alabama and that he isn't being rushed
back into action.
</P>
<P>
   But Paus, who was cleared Thursday to return this week by team
physician Dr. Gerald Finerman, had his right shoulder wrapped in
ice after practice Monday and said he's still experiencing some
level of discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get some timing back and conditioning,'' said Paus,
who expects to start. ``Last week I was able to throw the ball
progressively better each day. I can tell I did something to my
shoulder a couple of weeks ago. There's a clicking sound and some
discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the Bruins' Pac-10 championship
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   McCann's uneven performances might have been enough to allow
UCLA to beat Michigan and Alabama, but the loss to Oregon means
that the Bruins have almost no margin for error if they hope to go
to the Rose Bowl, let alone the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the Bruins could be out of the
Rose Bowl race by the first week in October.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Toledo would rather put the Bruins' season in the hands of
a rusty Paus, who hasn't practiced in 3 weeks, than a capable but
frustratingly inconsistent McCann.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his decision would have been the same if UCLA had
beaten Oregon with the same performance by McCann, Toledo paused
for a few seconds and said: ``Possibly.''
</P>
<P>
   When presssed, Toledo said: ``I'm being evasive now.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus did win the job convincingly in fall camp _ he was
consistently more accurate and had a better command of the offense
_ and Toledo said after the Alabama game that his players don't
lose their jobs because of injury. However, he left himself some
wiggle room, saying that if the team continued to win, it would be
tough to replace McCann.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we won and he played better, it would be a heck of a tough
question,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said. ``But when do you
do it? Right now is the time. Let's see what he can do. When Joe
Montana got hurt, Steve Young came in and when Montana was healthy,
he was the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus was originally expected to be cleared to return this week.
But two weeks ago, Toledo said he planned to hold Paus out against
Arizona State so that with next week's bye, he'd have an additional
two weeks before the Bruins played at Cal on Oct. 14. That would
give the shoulder additional time to heal and Paus plenty of work
in practice _ even if McCann had earned the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how healthy he was,'' Toledo said Monday. ``At
one point, they said it won't be until after the Arizona State
game. Now, he threw ball last week a little bit. This morning, they
came in and said he's cleared, he's ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann's statistics were certainly serviceable: 60 of 120 for
688 yards, four touchdowns and two interceptions. But his
inconsistency never gave Toledo or his offensive coordinator a
sense of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   While Toledo acknowledged a poor performance by the offensive
line and too many dropped balls by receivers against Oregon, much
of the blame for UCLA's decreased offensive production _ the Bruins
have scored fewer points each game _ was laid at McCann's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had basically 12 quarters to show improvement and to move
the team and score some points,'' Toledo said. ``He made some
plays, but I was expecting him to make probably more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offensive game plan has been cut down to about a third of
what we normally do. Because of Cory, because of the experience,
we'll be able to put some of it back in. If you watched the games,
the tight ends (who have caught five passes in four games) have
been open. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``When they've got nine guys on the line of scrimmage, you've
got to throw the ball. A year ago against Oregon, which was running
the same defense, Cory Paus threw for (332 yards and two
touchdowns) and we beat 'em. You've got to make 'em pay is what I'm
saying. When you can't make em pay, then you don't have an
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann, who suffered a bruised left throwing shoulder and a
slightly pulled hamstring against Oregon that kept him out of most
drills Monday, was asked if he felt like a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, say that Toledo's decision caught him by
surprise _ even if he's been through this before, losing the job to
Paus in fall camp and getting benched against Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roller coaster continues,'' McCann said. ``This is another
loop in the journey. It happens. It's rough _ it's really rough _
but I'm used to it now. The team didn't play well as a whole,
especially myself _ I contributed to that. There's not much to say.
They want to win and they didn't think I could be the guy who could
stay in there and win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
