<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUNTER-DRUGS-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTER DENIES DRUG CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The husband of Marion Jones denied on
Tuesday that he had taken steroids and said that a mislabeled
nutritional supplement was responsible for elevated levels of the
performance-enhancing drug nandrolone in his system.
</P>
<P>
   The shot-putter C.J. Hunter tested positive for nandrolone at
the Bislett Games in Oslo, Norway, on July 28, track and field's
world governing body said Monday. He withdrew from the Olympics
before the Sydney Games started after undergoing orthoscopic knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Tears streaking down his face, his voice breaking, Hunter said
at a news conference on Tuesday that he would do nothing to
embarrass Jones, or his children from a previous marriage. Jones is
attempting to become the first female track and field athlete to
win five gold medals in one Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very difficult past couple of days for C.J.
and I,'' said Jones, who accompanied Hunter to the news conference
but did not answer questions. Jones, who won the 100 meters, will
compete in the 200, long jump, 4x100 relay and 4x400 relay between
now and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here to show my complete support for my husband,'' Jones
said. ``I have total and complete respect, and believe the legal
system will do what's needed to clear his name.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, and Victor Conte, executive director of Balco
laboratories in San Francisco and a nutritionist for some of the
athletes competing in Sydney, said that the shot-putter had been
using nutritional supplements, including an iron supplement, that
has been found to contain nandrolone. Hunter said he was unaware
that the supplements contained nandrolone, but would not identify
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of data that strongly indicates C.J. was not
using the anabolic steroid nandrolone,'' Conte said.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Alexandre de Merode, chief of the International Olympic
Committee's medical commission, said that Hunter had failed three
other drug tests this summer. Hunter said on Tuesday that
supplements were responsible for the other positive tests as well.
</P>
<P>
   Nandrolone has been easily detectable for years, and scientists
have been puzzled why a rash of cases involving the steroid has
surfaced in the past year. One possible reason is improperly
labeled nutritional supplements, scientists said. A number of
international track and field stars such as Linford Christie of
Britain, the 1992 Olympic champion at 100 meters; and the Olympian
Merlene Ottey of Jamaica have tested positive for the substance.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles attorney Johnnie Cochran attended Tuesday's news
conference, saying he was a friend of the family. He represented
Jones when she was in high school and did not show up for a
scheduled drug test. She was later exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track and field has been great to me, but there is nothing
anyone could say or do or to get me to bring any kind of shame on
the people I love,'' Hunter said. He won the 1999 world
championship in the shot put and said he planned to retire after
the Sydney Games even before the positive drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be downright mean at times,'' Hunter said, ``but
nobody on the planet can say I don't love my wife, don't love my
kids. I have never in my life nor would I ever do anything to
jeopardize their opinion of me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to vigorously defend himself, that he
expected to be exonerated and that he would remain in Sydney to
support Jones through her remaining events.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can stop that,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hunter said he told Jones about the positive test on Monday
after reading and hearing news reports.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told her, ``I don't know what happened and I'm sorry.
She knows I would never do anything to hurt her.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Merode, the Olympics official, said the random tests were
analyzed by International Olympic Committee-accredited labs in
Rome, Barcelona and Oslo, which filed coded results with the IOC
and the IAAF, the international track federation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Associated Press, the IAAF decoded the test
results and informed USA Track &AMP; Field that Hunter had failed the
tests, according to de Merode. Messages left for officials of the
IAAF and USATF were not immediately returned, although the agencies
have defended themselves against previous allegations that they
covered up drug cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
