<HEADER>
A1574 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     09-26 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK HERO IS QUEEN FOR A DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The Australians almost voted out the Queen
of England as their figurative head of state in a referendum last
November, and the House of Windsor is fortunate they're not holding
an election today.
</P>
<P>
   No way Queen Elizabeth would survive it.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one queen who now reigns over this country.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Cathy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, Cathy Freeman vaulted into athletic royalty and into the
hearts of an entire nation Monday night by winning the women's 400
meters at the Olympic Stadium before 110,000 patrons who broke the
sound barrier when she zipped past the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   If she had lost, it would have been the greatest tragedy to
strike this country since Gallipoli, for never has an athlete in
its history been showered with more adulation _ and unparalleled
media coverage _ than this proud 27-year-old Aborigine of enduring
resolve and resilience.
</P>
<P>
   But Cathy Freeman didn't lose. She streaked around the track in
her resplendent, gold-and-green, top-to-toe body suit, blowing past
Jamaica's Lorraine Graham and Great Britain's Katharine Merry down
the stretch to win pulling away at 49.1.
</P>
<P>
   And, after she had done what everyone here expected her to do _
and everyone wanted her to do _ she collapsed to the ground, head
bowed, catching her breath, as her rivals came over to offer
congratulations and the huge crowd roared with deafening passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally overwhelmed at that moment,'' she would say
later. ``I was feeling the crowd all over me. I could feel
everyone's emotion. I could feel it in every chord in my body.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no one in Australia at the moment even close in
popularity to Cathy Freeman, not Prime Minster John Howard, not Mel
Gibson, not Paul Hogan, not Elle McPherson, not Kate Blanchette,
not even Ian Thorpe or Dawn Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Cathy Freeman's running skills that have inspired
such veneration that Monday's Australian newspapers were
overflowing with lengthy Freeman features. The Sydney Morning
Telegraph even printed ``The Race Of Our Lives'' as a main headline
above one of the stories.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Catherine Astrid Salome Freeman _ chosen to light the
Olympic cauldron at the opening ceremonies _ has become the
consciousness for a large segment of this country's population.
</P>
<P>
   She was running Monday night not only for Australia's sporting
glory but also for Aboriginal Australia, for a reconciled
Australia, for a hoped-for apology from the reluctant PM for past
injustices perpetuated by her people's government.
</P>
<P>
   She took her victory lap with the Australian and Aboriginal
flags draped around her shoulders, a not-so-subtle symbol of her
activism in regard to her heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope this victory would make a difference in people's
attitudes toward the Aborigines,'' she said during her post-race
press session. ``I would hope it also would change the attitude of
some of the politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cathy Freeman did not use her greatest triumph as a
political forum.
</P>
<P>
   She did not discuss the Aborigines' ``stolen generation,'' a
term used here in reference to those thousands of children who were
kidnapped from their parents and relocated in special camps by the
Australian government for a good portion of the 20th century. Her
maternal grandmother was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did she bring up other Aborigine grievances.
</P>
<P>
   She was in ecstasy on this brightest of nights for herself and
Australian athletics _ she is the first Aussie to win a gold in
track since Debbie Flintoff-King won the 400-meter hurdles at the
Seoul Olympics in 1988 _ and a soft smile never left her face as
she spoke in a voice that was hoarse.
</P>
<P>
   Someone wanted to know what moved her more, igniting the Olympic
flame or covering herself with gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say the Olympic gold medal means more to me
personally,'' she said. ``Getting to light the cauldron was a
tremendous honor, but that was more about the whole Olympic
movement. This was about me finally reaching my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   And reaching deep into the souls of her adoring countrymen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      09-26 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DAN KINCAID'S REVIEWS OF CURRENT MAGAZINES(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAN KINCAID(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are reviews of a Web site and current magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE: TERRESTRIAL IMPACT STRUCTURES
</P>
<P>
   http://gdcinfo.agg.emr.ca/crater/world_craters.html.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This site also can be accessed through a search engine like
Internet Explorer or HotBot by searching for ``Terrestrial Impact
Structures.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some awfully big stuff - comets, meteors, asteroids - has
slammed into our Spaceship Earth during the past billion years or
so, wreaking all sorts of havoc with the environment and, maybe,
even finishing off our favorite monsters, the dinosaurs. Well, this
nifty Web site lets you see, continent by continent, where the
blows landed. You can zero in on the impact crater of your choice
and get the stats {ndash} age, size, longitude and latitude - and
often photos of the craters taken from space. Our crater near
Winslow is just a pinprick: Check out the monster hole at
Manicouagan in Quebec or the alleged dino slayer in Mexico's
Yucatan. It's humbling to know that something like the cosmic
bullets that blasted out those basins could hit anywhere, anytime.
So be good, and watch the skies, watch the skies.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``DETAILS''
</P>
<P>
   This issue is the first of a ``relaunch'' of
(beginitalic)Details(enditalic), and it has been redesigned to send
it zinging with precision into the hands of men in their 20s and
30s with sophisticated tastes, or hopes of acquiring them. Robert
Downey Jr. poses bare-chested on the cover. Downey was sprung early
from a substance-abuse treatment center/prison, where he had been
an inmate since August 1999. Downey has led a wild life in recent
years and was busted for everything from packing handguns to doing
heroin and cocaine. Now, he's reformed, off drugs, got his GED (you
can be a movie star without a GED?), and is ``Mr. Clean.'' Hope he
stays that way. Other stories deal with Asia's burgeoning sex trade
and the most fabulous gym in the world.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``GEORGE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This issue introduces the first annual (beginitalic)George
(enditalic)Awards to honor seven Americans who have harnessed their
energies to push causes bigger than themselves. A Citizen of the
Year Award goes to Michael J. Fox who, stricken with Parkinson's
disease, is waging an all-out war against the affliction through
his own foundation, pouring his energies and talents into a drive
to find a cure within 10 years. The other winners include a
newspaper publisher who is fighting racism in the Ozarks; an
education-reform advocate; a medical missionary to impoverished
nations; a veteran civil-rights crusader; actress Sharon Stone's
sister, who helps homeless kids; and Fred Rogers - TV's Mr. Rogers
- for helping kids realize they are our future. How can you argue
with any of those? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``LATINA'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This mag targets, well, Latinas, a subset of a group that is
moving at warp speed into the mainstream of American society. This
issue celebrates the big impact Latin styles are making on the
world fashion scene. Latin influences have been felt before, of
course (think bolero jackets and gaucho pants), but the difference
this time is that Latino designers are making the splash, rather
than Europeans appropriating bits and pieces of Latin styles.
Another article identifies 10 Latina ``mujeres'' (women) who
achieved outstanding success in their fields. Among them:
Grammy-winning Christina Aguilera in music, Tina Ramirez in dance,
Julia Alvarez in literature and Jennifer Gutierrez in sports. Watch
these women - you'll be hearing more about them. Some articles in
(beginitalic)Latina(enditalic), by the way, are in English and
Spanish.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``VANITY FAIR''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you get through the fragrance wafting from the perfume ads,
you'll find a lot of good reading in this hefty hunk of a mag. The
cover piece is a love letter to Kate Hudson, Goldie Hawn's golden
girl, who is featured in Cameron Crowe's (beginitalic)Almost
Famous(enditalic) and Robert Altman's (beginitalic)Dr. T and the
Women. (enditalic)Annie Leibowitz provides the photos. The most
interesting article, though, is Gail Sheehy's bold stab at
analyzing George W. Bush's personality and his motives in running
for president. Her findings: Bush has shown a pattern in life of
exploding into ambition-fueled action when he has felt himself
teetering on the brink of failure. His personality has been molded
by trying to compensate for dyslexia and associated verbal
clunkiness, and short attention span ( but if so, how did the guy
manage to fly jet fighters in the Texas Air National Guard?). His
most heartfelt ambition may be to become baseball commissioner. Say
it ain't so, George.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0014 </DOCNO>
