<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1588 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-OLYSOFT-LADN-(SLA     09-26 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYSOFT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TOPS SOFTBALL DEMONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SYDNEY, Australia _ The two Australian batters standing between
Lisa Fernandez and a shot at a second consecutive Olympic gold
medal Monday were Peta Edebone and Joanne Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes! Talk about staring down your demons.
</P>
<P>
   Edebone's walk-off home run off Fernandez in the 13th inning of
a preliminary game last week had struck a stinging blow to the U.S.
team's hopes of successfully defending its 1996 title. Its only
loss of those Atlanta Games had come in a preliminary game against
Australia, when Brown broke up Fernandez's perfect game with a
10th-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. had done well to climb back into medal contention after
suffering three straight losses last week, quite a comeuppance for
a team that had previously cobbled together a 112-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez didn't want the climb to be all for naught, and it
showed as she led the U.S. to a 1-0 victory over Australia in the
semifinal matchup. Australia earned the bronze medal with the loss,
while the U.S. moves on to the final.
</P>
<P>
   The former UCLA standout was determined to give the U.S. another
chance to plant Old Glory on the Olympic summit. The Americans had
a 1-0 lead, having capitalized on two Aussie errors in the fifth to
post the game's only score.
</P>
<P>
   As she prepared to pitch to Edebone, the Long Beach resident
said a prayer: ``Help me make the best pitches of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She had pitched magnificently to that point, striking out 13 of
the 21 batters she had faced.
</P>
<P>
   She kept the ball down against Edebone and managed to get the
Aussie outfielder to hit a grounder to third. Jennifer Brundage
scooped the ball up nicely and her throw to first was just in time.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez then got Brown to hit a chopper back to the mound. She
fielded it cleanly and fired the ball to first for the game's final
out. Her pitching line, as usual, was sublime: 13 strikeouts, one
walk and one hit allowed in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. played Japan for the gold medal today.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Second baseman) Dot (Richardson) challenged me not to give
up,'' Fernandez said. ``She said, `Lisa, why would you play this
game if it wasn't challenging.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1589 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-1ST     09-26 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS CLINTON ADMINISTRATION CREATED AN `EDUCATION RECESSION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout; subs dateline)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT8,13 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOKANE, Wash. _ Sounding his new slogan intended to raise
anxieties about the nation's well-being, Gov. George W. Bush
accused the Clinton administration on Monday of helping create an
``education recession'' in which minority and low-income students
were routinely allowed to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to draw a clear link between the nation's future
economic health and the quality of its schools, Bush asserted that
the nation faced a reading crisis that had contributed to crime and
caused American students to fall behind their peers in other
industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a leading indicator of troubles to come,'' Bush told
500 supporters early on Monday at an elementary school in
Beaverton, Ore., 10 miles west of Portland. ``Children who never
master reading can never master learning. As uneducated adults,
they face a life of struggle on the fringes of our society. Some
will turn to crime and end up in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican nominee for president, outlined his
proposals to improve grade school reading programs, expand
scholarship programs for math and science students and encourage
annual testing of students in grades three through eight. He
accused his Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, of
promising change but instead protecting a failed status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call for new spending without real reform or
accountability,'' the Texas governor said. ``It's like pumping gas
into a flooded engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kym Spell, a spokeswoman for the Gore campaign, countered that
Bush would not be able to afford his education proposals because he
would need the entire federal surplus to pay for his military
programs and tax cuts. Bush denies that.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's school event kicked off a three-day swing on the West
Coast that on Monday took him through Washington and Oregon, states
where Democrats have carried recent presidential elections but
where polls show Bush running neck-and-neck with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In both states, Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, has
recently drawn enthusiastic crowds of more than 10,000 people and
is considered a threat to draw disaffected Democrats away from
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Later on Monday, Bush told several hundred supporters at an
airport rally here that he would oppose breaching hydroelectric
dams on the Snake River, as some environmentalists had proposed, to
improve salmon habitats. He also attacked Gore for having said he
wanted to study the issue further.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worried about some kind of group's not liking him,'' Bush
said. ``He wants to study it as way of not taking a position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also plans to spend two days in California, where polls
show Gore holding a comfortable lead. Part of Bush's goal is to tap
into the state's wealth: he plans to raise more than $1.4 million
for the state Republican Party at Silicon Valley and Los Angeles
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's communications director, Karen P. Hughes, asserted
that the governor also wanted to show that he planned to contest
California until Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't be going there, at a critical point in the
campaign, if we didn't think we could compete in California,''
Hughes said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Coming about a week before what will probably be among the most
important moments of the fall campaign _ a nationally televised
debate with Gore _ Monday's event in Beaverton also gave Bush an
opportunity to fine-tune his message on a signature issue before a
friendly audience.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not hold a news conference but instead fielded gently
worded questions from the largely partisan audience. With each
response, Bush expounded on his plans to cut taxes, increase
military spending and improve education.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has sought to lay blame for the nation's education
problems squarely on the administration's doorstep, many educators
contend that the federal government plays a relatively minor role
in primary and secondary education. The most important decisions _
on curriculum, standards, testing, personnel and construction _ are
made by state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself acknowledged the limitations of federal action on
Monday, noting that Washington provides only 7 percent of public
education spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if the federal government is going to solve 100
percent of the problems,'' he said. ``The best education is that
where it's focused at the state and local government.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of Bush's education plan is to ensure that all
children read proficiently by the fourth grade. He would provide
aid to help primary schools expand reading programs and reward
schools that administered standardized tests annually to help
educators identify learning problems early. For those and other
proposals, Bush has called for increasing federal education
spending by $47 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that failed to reduce the gap in test scores between
low-income students and their more affluent peers in three years
would lose some of their federal Title I funds, which are earmarked
for low-income children. That money, $1,500 a student, would be
given directly to parents of children in failing schools, who could
use it for other educational purposes, like hiring tutors or paying
private-school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has called for increasing federal education spending by
$115 billion over 10 years to help districts build new schools,
provide preschool for most students, hire more teachers and raise
teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, he has proposed withholding federal aid from states
where test scores do not improve. But unlike his opponent, he would
redirect that money to the local schools with the greatest
problems, rather than give it to parents.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the education event in Beaverton, Bush was
asked what could be done to help students reconnect with politics,
and he recommended that candidates not make decisions based on
polls or focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign is not completely averse to such tools;
the phrase ``education recession'' was carefully poll-tested before
Mr. Bush first deployed it on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was pitching his education ideas, his running mate,
Dick Cheney, continued his attacks on Gore, accusing him of having
a conflict of interest involving stock and oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney told reporters in Springfield, Ohio, that Gore supported
extending a moratorium on royalties paid by United States companies
drilling for natural gas in the Gulf of Mexico. That position,
Cheney said, would benefit Occidental Petroleum _ a company whose
stock is held in a trust belonging to Gore's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore continues to be the prospective beneficiary of holdings
of stock in Occidental Petroleum in the family trust,'' Cheney
said, ``and I think that that does constitute a conflict of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said the vice president should either recuse himself from
participating in decisions about energy policy or ask his mother to
divest the family trust of oil stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Spell, the spokeswoman for Gore, said that the vice president
neither owned nor controlled any stock in Occidental and that there
was no way of knowing what stocks would be in the family trust when
he inherited them.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
