<HEADER>
A1591 &Cx1f; kan-z
r d BC-NYTPOLL-KAN &LR;      09-26 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTPOLL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS BISTATE TAX FOR ARTS AND SPORTS STILL HAS SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   By more than a two-to-one margin, a new
poll shows that area residents support continuing the bistate
cultural sales tax, but this time with the money going to upgrade
sports stadiums and arts programs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One-third of respondents were people who would vote for
something they don't like because it would be good for the
community, according to the telephone poll commissioned by the
Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very encouraging results,'' pollster Neil Newhouse
said Monday during a series of local presentations on the results.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of sports and arts, Newhouse said, ``seems like
a shotgun wedding, but a lot of voters think this is what's needed
to keep Kansas City a major-league city.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one take on the findings. Kansas State Rep. Kay O'Connor
of Olathe has another view of public sentiment on the tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the reaction of my constituents: Two-to-one, they
hate it,'' O'Connor said. ``My problem with bistate is a loss of
sovereignty of Kansas dollars. We have tax dollars being spent by
people who aren't Kansans. I think it's a wrong use of state tax
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The original bistate cultural tax, a one-eighth-cent sales tax,
was passed by voters in four counties in 1996 to help renovate
Union Station. Now that the station has reopened, the chamber is
pursuing a second use for that tax. It successfully lobbied for
legislative changes in Missouri and Kansas to include sports
facilities in the definition of culture.
</P>
<P>
   A second bistate tax _ dubbed Bistate II _ can't go to voters
until after the original one expires in the spring of 2002. It's
not clear how much money it would raise, but the first bistate tax
was expected to net $118 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll, which asked whether residents would extend the tax
for 14 years for arts and improvements to the Truman Sports
Complex, nearly replicated the outcome of the first bistate
election.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County's support for the tax was 66 percent in the poll
_ and 66 percent in the bistate election. Johnson County's support
was 58 percent in the poll and 60 percent in the election. Clay's
was 59 percent and 60 percent, while Platte's was 67 percent and 61
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll combined results of two surveys, both conducted in
late August of 500 likely voters and both with a margin of error of
plus or minus 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 62 percent indicated they would definitely or probably
vote yes for a second bistate, with 30 percent saying they would
vote no or probably no and 8 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse's report, however, noted there are opponents to the
bistate tax who ``believe they are overtaxed...and they believe
that these cultural arts organizations and sports teams should be
paying their own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of those who oppose the continuation of the bistate do so
strongly, and express their opinions regarding it with passion,''
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   But the margin of support found by the poll surprised some
chamber leaders. When the Kansas House considered the bistate
legislation this past spring, some Johnson County legislators said
most of their calls and letters from constituents opposed a second
tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this would become a horrendously unpopular idea, and
that's not the case at all,'' said Steve Rose, a chamber board
member who led the Kansas-side election campaign for the original
bistate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said Bistate II has several things going for it that
the original bistate didn't.
</P>
<P>
   First, the new proposal _ which calls for renovating the
stadiums so the Chiefs and Royals aren't enticed to leave town _
feeds more on Kansas City's identity as a major-league city. In the
poll, more than 90 percent of respondents thought that status was
``important.''
</P>
<P>
   As one respondent put it, ``It's the difference between Kansas
City and Omaha.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, bistate now has a track record. Two-thirds of poll
respondents reported having a ``favorable'' impression of how Union
Station's redevelopment was handled. And the tax already is in
place so there's no need for a ``new'' tax, only an extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest stumbling block was faced four years ago,''
Newhouse said. ``This being a continuation is just more palatable
for voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the veteran Washington, D.C.-based pollster also
acknowledged that a lot of time remained between this summer's poll
and an eventual election and a lot could change.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the chamber and a metropolitan arts council are
beginning discussions with arts groups about how to divide bistate
money among different arts projects and organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
