<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LIEBERMAN-COUNTEROFFE     09-26 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-COUNTEROFFENSIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION BARB TRADE JUMPS UP AN OCTAVE 
 &HT;     BY CARLA MARINUCCI
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Sen. Joe Lieberman, aiming for a pre-emptive
strike at Texas Gov. George W. Bush's campaign stop Tuesday in
California, charged the GOP presidential campaign with resorting to
``personal attack politics'' instead of focusing on real issues
like improving schools.
<P>
   ``The campaign is about issues like Medicare and education
reform,'' Lieberman said in a telephone interview with The
Chronicle Tuesday. ``It seems to be the way they are trying to come
back up ... but it's not what this campaign should be about.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bush scheduled to arrive in the Bay Area last night, his
campaign is fighting close races in several states, attacking Gore
for ``making up facts'' about his life _ from his mother-in-law's
prescription drug costs to childhood lullabies he heard _ while
pushing hard on issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-day trip to California, Bush is expected to discuss
education policy in a meeting with students and teachers at Redwood
City's Sequoia High School this morning and attend a fund-raiser at
the Atherton home of Carol Bartz, CEO of San Rafael-based software
maker Autodesk.
</P>
<P>
   He will then fly to Los Angeles, where he plans an appearance
alongside Cardinal Roger Mahony in an event stressing science and
math education in a Latino area of South Central Los Angeles. Bush
will also appear on ``Larry King Live'' and attend another
political fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's trip to the Bay Area comes as a new KTVU/Examiner poll
released this week shows him continuing to run behind in the
nation's most populous state by double digits. His state campaign
insists he will continue to fight on here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said we planned to compete to win in California. And
that plan includes visits by (Republican vice presidential nominee
Dick) Cheney and Bush, a full ground game and paid media,'' said
Gerry Parsky, who heads the Bush campaign in California. ``We
believe that, although we remain behind, it's winnable.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the GOP candidate's campaign plane even touched down
in California, Lieberman was on the phone to political reporters in
the state _ where 54 electoral votes hang in the balance _ to
counter the Texas governor's message that the country is in the
throes of an ``education recession'' under the Clinton-Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comment is just not fair to educators and teachers and
parents all over America (who) worked very effectively with their
local, state and federal governments to improve the quality of
public schools,'' said Lieberman, who spoke between campaign
appearances in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman challenged Bush's suggestion that test scores have
dropped, saying they are in fact on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got a ways to go,'' he added. ``Al and I have said
we're not going to rest until America's public schools are the best
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Cheney plan lacks money to invest in education
``because they spend it all on their tax cuts,'' Lieberman said.
``There's a lot more beef in our proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker countered that the
Clinton-Gore administration has spent ``a lot of money in the last
four years (on education) and gotten nothing for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Gov. Bush has shown in Texas, if you hold schools
accountable and expect the best out of students, they will rise to
the challenge,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   With 42 days left until the presidential election _ and a week
until the first televised presidential debate _ the increasingly
tough back and forth between the campaigns illustrates a narrowing
focus on certain issues and on the undecided voters who will count
most.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's defense of Gore came the same day the vice
president, campaigning with his wife, Tipper, in crucial Florida,
released a 74-page plan for what he called ``a rock solid
commitment'' to Medicare. Gore promised he would put the program
``in an iron-clad lock box with a sign that says, `Politicians,
hands off,' '' and charged that Bush would force some elderly into
welfare offices to get prescription drugs, violating ``their sense
of dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's camp strongly refuted the charges, and counter-blasted
Gore's plan as a ``government-run pharmacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman took particular offense to that characterization
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's another name for a government-run HMO _ it's called
Medicare,'' he said. ``And it's one of the most successful and
effective and humane programs the federal government has created,''
he said. `It's providing medical services for the elderly and it's
keeping them healthier, and in many cases alive longer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of real money set aside _ more than a quarter
of a trillion dollars _ for this prescription Medicare drug
benefit. All I ask is seniors to compare,'' he told The Chronicle.
``Under the Bush-Cheney plan, the senior gets basically a slip and
has to go out and find an HMO that will give them prescription
drugs. ... I don't think the HMOs are going to want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman saved his toughest words for the Bush campaign's
recent strategy _ with appearances by Cheney on weekend talk shows
and in campaign e-mails _ suggesting that the vice president has
been guilty of ``making up facts'' about his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right about the vice president,'' Lieberman
responded. One charge _ that Gore said his mother sang him the
``union label'' jingle as an infant when the jingle wasn't yet in
use _ is distorted, he said. The remark, made during a speech to
union members, ``was a joke,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   And another controversial Gore remark about his mother-in-law's
prescription drug prices ``actually made an important point: that
seniors do pay more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky countered by saying ``there have been examples over the
last several weeks of Gore saying one thing and doing another. And
Californians are not going to react well to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
