<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DUFFER'S STROKE OF LUCK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ First Sign Of Fall: George Lazar and a friend
were in George's pickup truck last Wednesday, on their way to
opening night of the Symphony, when George realized his error.
<P>
   Lazar remembered that his golf clubs were in the back of the
truck. The truck has a camper shell, but he knew he would be
parking somewhere around City Hall, not the most secure parking
area of town.
</P>
<P>
   George found a spot near the Main Library. He couldn't leave the
clubs exposed to view, so he used a ratty old sleeping bag to
carefully hide his prized clubs.
</P>
<P>
   After the Symphony when Lazar and his friend returned to the
truck, they saw that the hatch of the camper shell had been jimmied
open.
</P>
<P>
   George's heart sank. His Titleist clubs are worth about $1,800.
Also in the bag were several specialty clubs, including a rare
Scottie Cameron putter. And Lazar is between homeowner's policies,
so this loss would be out-of-pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Cringing, George pulled open the back hatch. The clubs were
there. The thief had made off with the sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   SWEETEST RIDE: Parking shortage in San Francisco? What parking
shortage? You just need the right wheels.
</P>
<P>
   A mysterious Marin man went to Canada and bought himself a new
Go-4 Interceptor, the little putt-putt cart that San Francisco
meter maids drive.
</P>
<P>
   He got a blue-and-white model with yellow lights on the roof,
identical to the official S.F. model. It cost him about $18,000.
</P>
<P>
   And he's been using the cart to commute into the city, either
for errands or for work, although the vehicle isn't safe at freeway
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly the owner told the cart company people that he was
buying the cart for the express purpose of beating the S.F. parking
system.
</P>
<P>
   No Parking Control Officer (meter maid) is going to ticket
another PCO's cart. This man's cart doesn't have the official gold
S.F. seal, but apparently he was banking on PCOs not looking
closely enough to notice.
</P>
<P>
   But then one morning an alert Dept. of Parking &AMP; Traffic
employee spotted the cart speeding over the Golden Gate Bridge into
the city.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed that the cart had no official markings and no license
plate, and thought it was stolen, so he gave chase. But he
abandoned the pursuit when the cart driver blew through a red light
at Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Later DPT issued an internal memo, alerting all meter maids to
keep an eye out for the little hot rod, and if it is found
illegally parked, get it towed.
</P>
<P>
   So the heat is on and the mystery man's free-parking days might
be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: A high-speed chase through the hills of the city,
a legion of PCO putt-putts in hot pursuit of the Phantom
Meter-Cheater.
</P>
<P>
   Eat your heart out, Steve McQueen.
</P>
<P>
   THRILL RIDE: Little cable cars climbing halfway to the stars, no
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's the coming back down that we need to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying the beloved cable cars are dangerous. But it does
appear that Muni is having a harder and harder time finding
qualified people to coax and crank the cars up and down the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Some cable car grip operators (in the front working the big
levers) and conductors (in back working the wheel brake and
collecting fares) say there's a grip shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates Muni sends over for grip training are either too
old to handle the physical demands of the job or too young and
clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids today (training as grips) can't walk, talk and chew
gum,'' one conductor told me. ``I think it's computers. Kids don't
play ball, they don't develop coordination. A lot of (the
candidates) can't even qualify as conductors _ bells and brakes and
talkin' and taking money.''
</P>
<P>
   The grip on the same car, also a cable-car veteran, said, ``Last
year Muni sent over (from other divisions) 20 guys for (grip)
training, and only four of them made it through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus,'' he added, ``we've got a lot of people with bad
attitudes. Chips on their shoulders. We deal with tourists who ask
the same questions, and some guys develop an attitude. Hey, we're
here to make these people enjoy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury problem is still major, too. Pulling on the iron all
day requires strength, and backs give out.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest complaint, though, is still the turntable at Market
and Powell. It used to be possible for a child to spin a car around
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Now it takes both crewmen and sometimes a third helper, pushing
and straining, to turn the table. The mechanism has been in need of
repair for years, and has knocked dozens of crew people into
disability, costing the city millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The table needs to be be rebuilt or realigned, but hey, that
would cost a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   Ding-ding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OIL-POLITICS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-POLITICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OIL COLORS PRESIDENTIAL CONTEST  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After many years of prosperity spurred by low oil prices,
American voters are being confronted by an old bogeyman _ oil
politics.
</P>
<P>
   As crude oil prices soar to 10-year highs, gasoline prices
continue to climb and warnings of winter heating-oil shortages grow
louder, Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush are using
rhetoric not heard in America since the 1970s oil crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Gore rails against ``Big Oil'' and calls Bush and his running
mate, Dick Cheney _ both former oil executives _ tools of the
conglomerates. Bush, in turn, blames the Clinton administration for
coddling the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, which
dominates the world's oil markets and has helped push prices up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the big factors involved here is whether or not
we're going to have a president who is willing to fight for people,
willing to stand up to Big Oil and foreign oil,'' Gore said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush retorted that ``under this administration there has been no
energy policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP candidate criticized President Clinton's decision on
Friday to release oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve _ a move
that had been urged by Gore, who clearly smelled a winning populist
issue. Bush said the stored oil ``should not be used as a
short-term political fix for somebody whose administration has been
asleep at the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heated words, both candidates are ducking the fact
that U.S. dependency on foreign oil has increased, not decreased,
under both the Bush and Clinton administrations. Since President
Jimmy Carter declared his quest for energy self-sufficiency ``the
moral equivalent of war'' in 1977, the share of imported oil used
in the U.S. economy has risen from 40 percent to 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say there is no quick fix, and any real solution _
whether devised by Republicans or Democrats _ is years away.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's decision to release 30 million barrels from
the reserve is credited with bringing down the price of oil _ it
closed at $31.57 per barrel Monday, down from a high of $37.80 a
week ago _ analysts caution that prices are likely to stay near $30
a barrel for the foreseeable future, leaving Americans paying more
to fill their car tanks and heat their homes than they have in many
years.
</P>
<P>
   A barrel of crude fetched as little as $9 in early 1999, and
averaged less than $20 in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading candidates' proposals show markedly different
visions of America's future. Gore wants to reduce energy
consumption, stimulate production of natural gas and renewable
energy sources such as wind, solar and bio-fuels. Bush wants to
unleash domestic oil production from environmental restrictions and
aggressively pressure OPEC to increase its production and lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of low oil prices and economic boom, U.S.
consumers have been lulled into inattention to oil issues.
Gas-guzzling sport utility vehicles and vans comprise half of all
new cars sold annually, and the energy crises of yesteryear seem
far away _ if they are remembered at all.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say there is plenty to be concerned about:
</P>
<P>
   --Residents of the Northeast face steep heating oil prices this
winter and possible shortages. The supplies on hand, 48 million
barrels, are 34 percent below levels of a year ago. Industry and
government officials say that if temperatures this winter drop
significantly below normal, supplies will run out.
</P>
<P>
   --Gasoline prices are near 10-year highs, reaching an average of
$1.94 per gallon in Northern California last week.
</P>
<P>
   --California's electricity grid barely dodged blackouts this
summer. Consumer bills in San Diego and parts of Orange County
doubled this summer, prompting state regulators to institute rate
caps earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   --Because of increased oil and gas prices, Americans are
spending an additional $115 billion _ nearly 1 percent of the gross
domestic product _ on energy this year. But some of that money is
recycled into the economy through stepped-up domestic oil
production, so the net decrease to GDP is estimated by economists
at 0.8 percent annually _ relatively small change in the roaring
U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   --In Europe, the situation is far worse. Protests over high fuel
prices have embarrassed governments in many of the continent's most
economically powerful nations, with bus and truck drivers blocking
highways to demand reductions in fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As the higher energy prices ripple through the U.S. economy, the
biggest beneficiaries are obvious: oil giants such as Chevron,
ExxonMobil, Texaco and Conoco. Net income at some of these
conglomerates has almost doubled this year, their best performances
since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The oil firms _ which have long resented the negative publicity
they often receive _ have kept mum in the current debate.
</P>
<P>
   Major firms such as Chevron, Texaco, ExxonMobil and Halliburton
refused to comment for this article or did not return The
Chronicle's calls. The American Petroleum Institute, the major
industry federation, has limited its public comment to a communique
released last week criticizing Clinton's decision to release oil
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the political flak and consumer grousing have dominated
media coverage of the issue, an unusual consensus has developed
among oil experts in the United States and OPEC nations that OPEC's
production cuts over the past year are not to blame for the current
crisis. They point to three principal culprits:
</P>
<P>
   --Low inventories. Major oil firms in the United States and
Europe have drawn their stocks of oil down to near record lows,
because they are unwilling to buy large amounts of crude at its
current high prices and are hoping that prices will soon fall. As a
result, the companies are unable to cushion sudden price spikes.
</P>
<P>
   --Full refineries. U.S. gasoline and heating-oil refineries are
running at 96 percent of capacity, and thus are unable to increase
production, which would lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   --Rampant speculation. Traders at the New York Mercantile
Exchange, where the world's oil prices are determined, have been
feverishly betting on the unknown _ whether Iraq will cut off its
oil exports as a means of pressuring for an end to the U.N.
embargo; whether storms could interrupt a major oil shipping
channel; whether America's multiyear string of unusually mild
winters could suddenly end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental problem has little to do with supply, and it's
unclear from either candidate's proposals that there will be any
short-term change (ahead),'' said Paul Cheng, an oil analyst for
the investment firm Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   In Caracas, Venezuela, where OPEC heads of state will gather
this week for a summit meeting, Mazhar Al-Shereidah, who publishes
a respected oil-industry newsletter, described it this way: ``It's
much easier for U.S. politicians to criticize OPEC than to explain
why the United States has increased its dependency on foreign oil
under governments of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always easier to blame the foreigners, the Arabs, for
Americans' unwillingness to make hard choices'' on energy
conservation, he added.
</P>
<P>
   For both candidates, too much populist chest-thumping about oil
can get in the way of sensible policy making.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gore claimed that Cheney, as chief executive of the
Dallas-based oil services giant Halliburton Co., had praised OPEC
in early 1999  &LR; early last year for lowering production _ a move
that had the effect of raising oil prices. The Bush campaign
retorted that Energy Secretary Bill Richardson had said much the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the tit-for-tat exchange obscured the fact that both
sides had reacted correctly to a devastating price crash in oil _
about $10 per barrel at that time _ which was causing U.S. domestic
oil companies to lay off thousands of workers and cancel
much-needed investment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say that unless this year's fuel price increases
push the U.S. economy into recession, voters may be unwilling to
accept policies offered by either of the major parties _ the
Democratic recipe includes a more frugal lifestyle with lower
energy usage, while the Republican one calls for punching oil wells
into pristine Alaskan tundra and possibly offshore California
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has been reinforcing OPEC's price-hike
strategy with our own consumer desires,'' said Lester Brown,
chairman of Worldwatch Institute, an environmental group based in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although renewable energy sources provide only 4 percent of
current U.S. usage, Brown advocates spurring production in these
fields _ a policy that Gore backs, although more cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for environmentalists like Brown, the U.S. economy
is much stronger than it was before the oil shocks of the 1970s and
1990, when price rises caused recession and forced energy
conservation onto the public agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our abandonment of a real energy policy in the Reagan years is
still with us, and we will continue paying for it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
