<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1597 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-INTERNET-TAX-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOV. DAVIS VETOES TAX ON WEB SALES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Saying he is protecting California consumers, Gov.
Gray Davis Monday vetoed a bill first-in-the-nation bill that would
have forced many Internet retailers to charge sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's action protects California e-businesses from
being taxed immediately but leaves the door open for future
decisions on how best the state can reap financial rewards from the
rapidly expanding e-commerce industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for the Internet to reach its full potential as a
marketing medium and job creator, it must be given time to
mature,'' Davis said in his veto message. ``At present, it is less
than 10 years old. Imposing sales taxes on Internet transactions at
this point in its young life would send the wrong signal about
California's international role as the incubator of the dot-com
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, by Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco, would
have made Internet sales conform to laws governing catalog sales by
forcing Internet companies to charge sales tax if they have a
brick-and-mortar store in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The veto, while widely expected, leaves California still
wrestling with the highly charged debate about taxing the billions
of dollars of online sales of everything from books to patio
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is still there. How do we handle taxation of
e-commerce transactions?'' said Teresa Casazza, California vice
president of the American Electronics Association, which opposed
the Internet tax bill. ``We are very interested in moving forward
with that discussion, but (Migden's) bill was not the way to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he believes the matter should be reviewed in three to
five years, and he signed a bill creating a commission to further
study the issues surrounding sales tax and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member ``California Commission on Tax Policy in the New
Economy'' will make recommendations to the governor and Legislature
on tax issues. It will include representatives of business, local
government and the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``State and federal responses to taxation and the Internet over
the past few years have been awfully narrow and, as a result,
controversial,'' said the bill's author, Sen. John Vasconcellos,
D-Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   In his veto of the Migden bill, Davis said he did not want to
single out Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet must be subject to a stable and nondiscriminatory
legal environment, particularly in the area of taxation,'' he said.
``Unfortunately, AB 2414 does not provide such a stable
environment: it singles out companies that are conducting
transactions electronically and attempts to impose tax collection
obligations on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Migden and supporters of the bill say the governor missed
the substance of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is flat-out, plum wrong,'' Migden said Monday. ``This
measure is only about obeying existing law and making sure that we
all live by the same rules. The governor and some business people
favor making exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Goldberg, the lobbyist for the Northern California
Independent Booksellers, said the bill was meant to target the few
companies that violate current law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have told a handful of businesses that they had to
follow the law,'' he said. ``I'm not surprised it was made out to
be a bigger deal than that. It was a question of substance versus
the symbolism, and Davis reacted to the symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government and dozens of states are
considering taxing the Internet, officials in Migden's office said
her bill was the first attempt to enforce sales tax collection by
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, some e-tailers like Barnesandnoble.com and
Borders.com do not charge California sales tax because their
Internet subsidiaries are based outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   But other online retailers _ such as Macys.com and
EddieBauer.com _ do charge state sales tax because they do not use
separate, out-of-state subsidiaries to operate their online
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy stems from a 1992 U.S. Supreme Court ruling that
requires merchants to collect sales tax only in states where they
have a physical presence or `nexus.'
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Borders and Barnes &AMP; Noble have said that their
stores do not constitute nexuses for their Web subsidiaries because
their Internet operations are separate.
</P>
<P>
   Bill supporters say they will continue to push to level the
playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is not going away,'' Goldberg said. ``In the real
world of business people, the issue doesn't just disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   In other action, Davis signed two bills aimed at protecting
children:
</P>
<P>
   --Car safety seats or booster seats will be required for kids
either younger than 6 or lighter than 60 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, children must ride in safety seats until they are at
least 4 years old and also weigh at least 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The new age and weight requirements take effect Jan. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   --Schools must tell parents when pesticides will be used at
their children's school.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also creates a registry so parents can find out when a
pesticide is going to be applied.
</P>
<P>
   Davis vetoed a stronger bill last year because of its
requirements on how pesticides were to be used at schools.
</P>
<P>
   This year's bill contains no requirements, just the the
mandatory notification.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also requires schools to post warning signs at areas
being treated 24 hours in advance and 72 hours after a pesticide is
used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
