<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     09-26 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CONTROVERSY TO RUN FROM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Subs for rewriting throughout)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, AUSTRALIA _ It was quite the ambitious show, with Marion
Jones standing by her tearful man, pharmacology experts supporting
his innocence and a smiling Johnny Cochran providing legal support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it happened,'' said C.J. Hunter, suddenly
America's most vilified husband since the president. ``There is
nothing anyone could ever say or offer me to get me to bring shame
on the people I love. I've prayed for two years every day that if
what had to happen for my wife to win five gold medals was
something negative to me, then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't mean a failed drug test, confirmed Monday by the
International Amateur Athletic Federation. At a news conference
here on Tuesday afternoon, Hunter denied that he had used the
anabolic steroid nandrolone. He said reports that he had tested
1,000 times over the legal limit were false. He and Team Hunter
maintained that he was only guilty of having traces of nandrolone
in his system as the result of a flawed dietetic supplement.
</P>
<P>
   A somber Jones made a brief statement, gave her man a kiss and
left him to tell the eager photographers, ``I never thought I'd see
the day when you guys would want to photograph me more than my
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   How does anyone who saw in Jones the quintessential American
star and Olympic savior last Saturday night take a second look when
she returns to the track on Wednesday without noticing a little
bloom off the rose? It will be the understandable human reaction,
given what we've heard about Hunter, her career director and
spiritual guide.
</P>
<P>
   Yet barring further announcements or IAAF outings, our editing
process between mind and mouth should be on 24-hour alert, lest we
make a leap worthy of a medal via the process of guilt by
association. Hunter is the one who must prove himself clean. Jones
can still have America's blessings as she goes for more gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the recent situation, I hope she'll be able to
continue to focus on what she's here to do,'' Michael Johnson said
in quite the statesmanlike manner after winning the men's 200
meters on Monday night in an Olympic Stadium holding more than
112,000 people. ``Hopefully, all of you will allow her to focus on
what she's here to do.''
</P>
<P>
   We as a nation have done it before, paused for reflection after
revelation, upon learning two summers ago that Mark McGwire was
hammering his way toward the baseball record book with the aid of
little bottled helpers. McGwire wasn't breaking baseball's drug
rules but that was because baseball didn't have any. He was, on the
other hand, participating and essentially promoting pharmacology,
the plague of performance enhancement, and isn't that where the
competition credibility gap in the Olympics lies?
</P>
<P>
   America wasn't ready to take down a man in the process of
rewriting the storybook of our long, lost youth, so McGwire got a
free pass, a deferred trial for when androstenedione is as widely
denounced in the States as it happens to be here.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been easier for Americans to heap scorn on
Olympians, these disposable heroes, whom we only look to every four
years. As sports ethicists, we have a shifting set of standards, a
selective morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we believe anything we see here?'' is what you kept
hearing around the media center here on Monday night. Fair
question, but what shouldn't we believe _ the soccer, the
basketball, the tennis? We watch these things the rest of the year,
and we will also go home next week to watch baseball players, who
may well be mixing steroids with their crackerjack, for all we
know. No one cries to shut the parks down, but when it comes to the
Olympics, we are still demanding absolute purity from a movement
that long ago surrendered its innocence, no matter what the
mythmakers and marketers claim.
</P>
<P>
   The world has grown tired of our high mindedness, our appointed
commissions, with their how-to manuals for a kinder, cleaner
Olympics. It was delighted to have the report on Hunter leaked, to
have our drug testing program come under siege. Hunter was said to
have failed the test in Oslo not long after he passed the same
tests at the U.S. trials in July, according to U.S.A. Track and
Field's Craig Masback. The message came through loud and clear, and
was echoed on Monday by a variety of international sources: Shut up
and clean up your own house.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Olympics continued on Monday night, despite the
sensational news that Marion Jones' husband had joined an army of
eastern Europeans in the holding pen for drug cheats who claim the
laboratory lied.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Freeman enthralled two nations, Australia and the
indigenous Aborigines who wallow beneath its standard of living.
Johnson ran in the shadow of others as dynamically as he had in the
spotlight of Atlanta. The American, Stacy Dragila, became the first
woman to claim pole-vaulting gold, on a night track &AMP; field managed
to soar above the sordid matters of drugs and international
backroom vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   As with many track and field stars, there have been whispers
about Marion Jones, but she isn't Michelle Smith, the swimmer who
married a doper and became a sensation overnight. Suspicion isn't
fact, and the fact is that Jones has been a blur since she was 10.
Now she has this controversy to run from, as she goes for more
gold, as her husband attempts to clear his name, not hers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
