<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLAYTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' SHORTSTOP CLAYTON LACKING USUAL ENTHUSIASM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers shortstop Royce Clayton admits
this has been a difficult year for him. He traces it to one simple
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just like everybody else in this clubhouse,'' Clayton
said. ``What's personal is our record. It's an indication of my
season. Everybody is that way. We're all here to win. We didn't do
that, and that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said he let the losing get to him because, ``I hate to
lose, there's no doubt about that. If it doesn't bother me or if I
start to enjoy it, then that's an indication that it's time for me
to hang it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates does not want Clayton to ``hang it up.'' He
knows Clayton has been beaten up by the losing, but Oates said most
everybody in the Rangers' clubhouse, including the manager, has
also suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Oates knows Clayton's infectious enthusiasm is an important part
of the Rangers' chemistry, and he hopes it'll come back strong next
season.
</P>
<P>
   `He's not the only one,'' Oates said. ``It's a byproduct of
losing. Losing wouldn't beat you down if you didn't care. He cares.
His enthusiasm is a big part of our ballclub, and it's gone up and
down a lot. I'd like for it to be more consistent. But I'd like for
me to be more consistent, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the saying? It's not the size of the dog in the fight,
but the size of the fight in the dog. I don't think any of us enjoy
losing, but it doesn't mean you have to do it with your head down
and giving up. I don't think he has, and I don't think he has given
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton signed a four-year, $18 million contract with the
Rangers after the 1998 season because he thought there was a good
chance this club could win the World Series. The Rangers won the
division title last year, but this season turned sour quickly. They
finish the season with three games at Seattle starting today and
three games against Oakland this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand a lot of the guys like to see me walking around
the clubhouse and joking with them,'' Clayton said. ``That's part
of my nature. But sometimes you have to focus back on yourself or
you're just draining yourself. Just because we're losing doesn't
mean I'm going to drag around and pout about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I'm not going walk around and smile like
there's no problem and you're having a grand old time.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't helped that Clayton has sensed a change in the
Rangers' clubhouse from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a team to be good, everybody has to be pulling for each
other,'' Clayton said. ``We had that last year. Sure, we had
talent, but we also had good chemistry and everybody pulling for
each other. It can't be just one guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say that after awhile this year, it
became every man for himself. That's not the way it should be;
everybody has to support each other.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried raising that point early in the year, but it backfired
on him when he went public with his thoughts as well as complaints
about teammate Chad Curtis in an Internet column. That experience,
combined with the losing, has changed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things I'm willing to do and certain things
I'm not willing to do,'' Clayton said. ``On the field I'm still
going to give 110 percent. I'm going to play hard. I can't play any
different. Even if we lose 120 games, I'm not going to dog it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are some things in my heart and soul I tried to give
and ... it caused some hard feelings and pain. I'm not willing to
endure that again when it comes to the way things are handled in
this business. I'm still going to be around and stand behind what I
believe in. That's the way I was brought up. But there's a proper
time and a certain way to do things. As far as volunteering my
opinion on topics that have nothing to do with between the lines,
I'm going to leave that alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said he still loves playing for the Rangers, and Oates
said he's still more than happy with his shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won with him before, and we can win with him again,''
Oates said. ``If we put the right ballclub together, he's the right
guy for us. He's a very good defensive shortstop and a
complementary offensive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said: ``I'm still dedicated to helping us win. That's
all you can be and that's all you can ask of anybody in this
clubhouse. What makes me smile is winning ballgames. It's not about
what kind of year you have; it's about what you're doing to help
the team win.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
