   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-POLITICS (Undated) _ Poor people learn to keep hopes
small. So when President Clinton came calling on some of the
poorest places in the country last year with ideas to make things
better, it was like rain in the desert. The president's six-state,
four-day poverty tour, highlighting for the first time in his two
terms the places that remain untouched by the longest economic boom
in this nation's history, caused an excitement that bordered on the
spiritual. A year later, the president's modest proposals for tax
incentives to bring businesses to impoverished communities are
still awaiting Senate approval. The idea that anything big might
happen to places that have been down longer than they were ever up
has long faded. In dozens of interviews in communities that the
president visited _ Clarksdale, East St. Louis and the Eastern
Kentucky towns of Hazard and Annville _ what was clear is that
Democrats are Democrats, Republicans are Republicans and people are
more concerned with how to fix their own communities than in the
state of the country. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-SENATE (Washington) _ With Democrats growing more confident
about their chances of regaining control of the Senate this fall,
several colleagues of Sen. Joseph Lieberman are pressuring him to
let another Connecticut Democrat seek his seat so that the party
will not lose it if he becomes vice president. By Eric Schmitt with
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-ACTIVISM (Undated) _ Thirty-seven years ago, in the
autumn of another political season, Joseph Lieberman and a carload
of other Yale students headed south from New Haven on a trip of
nearly 1,300 miles, stopping only for gas and a quick dinner in the
Washington suburbs. They were eager to get to Mississippi, where
they hoped to make a little history. Recruited by William Sloane
Coffin Jr., Yale's radical campus chaplain, and Allard Lowenstein,
the crusading student organizer and future New York congressman,
Lieberman was among 67 Yalies who formed the first large group of
Northern white students to travel south for the cause of civil
rights. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
