<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1625 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MTA-STRIKE-LADN     09-26 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTA-STRIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S MTA STRIKE MAY SACRIFICE VALLEY TRANSIT ZONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Questions were raised about the role of state
Assemblyman Herb Wesson in brokering a deal to end the 10-day MTA
strike because of his support for legislation that effectively
kills a San Fernando Valley transit zone.
</P>
<P>
   As a news blackout over negotiations between the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority and the drivers union continued, Wesson's
ability to fairly intervene in the dispute was challenged by some
Valley transit zone supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Wesson's supporters, meanwhile, defended the Los Angeles
Democrat's ability to be impartial but they acknowledged he hopes
to use his prominent role as a steppingstone to becoming Assembly
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the negotiations say both sides are refusing to
settle the strike before Gov. Gray Davis decides whether to veto or
sign into law Senate Bill 1101, extending MTA contract provisions
to a Valley zone proposed to take over dozens of MTA bus lines. By
law, Davis has until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Valley attorney David W. Fleming, a member of the interim board
planning the Valley Transportation Zone, said Monday the
negotiations are a question of who caves in first -- Davis, the MTA
or the unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far the governor has held firm,'' Fleming said. ``But
obviously these negotiations put the interest of the people in the
San Fernando Valley in jeopardy since the union wants to control
the Valley the same way they control the rest of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the Valley is being held hostage to a settlement
here,'' he said. ``If the last straw to a settlement is to sell out
the Valley, believe me, we'll be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Transportation Union, representing 4,300 bus and rail
drivers, went on strike Sept. 16 after rejecting the MTA's proposal
for controlling costs, including overtime. The agency said it faces
a $438 million operating deficit over the next 10 years unless it
cuts costs or raises fares.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has stranded about 450,000 weekday riders who depend
on the MTA.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers said they are on strike to protect middle-class jobs,
and say they need SB 1101 to protect workers' gains. Wesson was
among Democratic lawmakers who voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unions have indicated they will settle if Davis will sign
the legislation so he'll probably sign it,'' Fleming said. ``One
way or the other, the probabilities are the Valley transit zone
will be stabbed in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesson was not available for comment Monday, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles,
said Wesson has the respect of his former boss, MTA Board
Chairwoman Yvonne Brathwaite Burke, as well as the unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect and trust are essential attributes for anyone who
wants to mediate issues as contentious as this one,'' said
Villaraigosa, who is an L.A. mayoral candidate. ``He also has a
patience about him that is important for efforts like this one when
the parties are entrenched in their positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa said Wesson is the second-leading Assembly
Democratic fund-raiser behind Speaker Bob Hertzberg and many people
see him as the next potential speaker of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Darry Sragow, chief strategist for Assembly Democratic
Campaigns, said Wesson has raised and contributed about $400,000 to
Democratic races this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that many people see Herb Wesson as having a good shot
at being the next speaker. Certainly, they will be looking at this
to see if he has the skills for the job,'' Sragow said. ``I believe
that no matter what happens with the mediation, he will prove he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, the governor said he hopes the strike will end
within days.
</P>
<P>
   In Northridge to sign legislation on pesticide use at schools,
Davis said state officials are doing everything in their power to
help negotiators ``so they can resolve this dispute in the next day
or two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything we can to persuade, nudge and cajole
the parties to be reasonable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Davis has not decided whether to sign or veto
SB 1101. ``The bill will be decided based solely on its merits,''
said Davis spokesman Byron Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Katz, co-chairman of the Valley Industry and Commerce
Association's transportation committee, said he's known Wesson for
years and believes his vote for SB 1101 will not bias his role in
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that compromises his ability to resolve the
strike,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have the ability to unilaterally impose anything.
What he can do is choose to make suggestions. Anything he comes up
with still has to be approved by the board of the MTA and union
membership.''
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa said Wesson will be fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do I think he can be fair, but both sides agree or
they won't have accepted him as a mediator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hefner, press deputy to Hertzberg, said the speaker
believes Wesson will not be biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Mr. Wesson's role is not to take sides but to help
the parties and gather the facts in terms of helping to frame the
issues,'' Hefner said. ``So certainly, Mr. Hertzberg has every
confidence in Mr. Wesson's ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefner said the speaker chose Wesson because of his extensive
experience in city and county government. Wesson served as chief of
staff to Burke -- who is a county supervisor as well as MTA board
chairwoman -- for six years prior to his election to the Assembly
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is excellent in terms of issues and organization,'' Burke
said. ``He was a good campaign manager and a hard worker. I think
he's going to move up fast. And a lot of people are saying he'll
probably be the next speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg's spokesman called Wesson ``uniquely qualified'' to
head the fact-finding panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Burke has played a central role in the management
side of the negotiations,'' Hefner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wesson) is also well-trusted and well-received by folks in
the labor community. That made him uniquely qualified to take on
this role.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
