</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-TRANSFORM-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE NATIONAL SECURITY BEAT 
 &HT;     `DIGITIZED' SOLDIERS TESTED AGAINST SKEPTICISM IN ARMY WAR
GAMES 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
    &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 25, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With four photos, of Lawrence Mullen (NNS10), Tom
Rogers (NNS11), an experimental computer system (NNS12) and Kurt
Fuller (NNS13); for information about purchasing art call
202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Optional trim to 1,850 words.mdnmn/
 &HT;     By DAVID WOOD 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT POLK, La. _ A humid darkness has settled and cicadas are
chorusing when the Army's new high-tech soldiers hurtle down out of
the sky: paratroopers wearing miniature computers with digital
satellite communications and pop-down eyepiece screens, gripping
assault weapons equipped with infrared and video sights.
</P>
<P>
   Out there in the black night, men wait with primitive weapons to
kill them.
</P>
<P>
   The experimental techno-warriors fight with blank rounds but
deadly purpose. Their aim: to help infantrymen survive the next
encounter with the kind of bloody chaos that killed 18 elite
soldiers in America's most recent battle experience, seven years
ago in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   The Army hopes that men linked with digital technology will be
able to fight faster, smarter _ and safer. Information, Army
leaders assert, is the most precious weapon on the 21st century
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics within the Army, meanwhile, hold that no technology can
banish the chaos of battle. An Army with its eyes glued to computer
screens, some fear, will lose the instincts and skills needed to
prevail. Some dismiss the Army's antenna-festooned techno-warriors
as ``bug men.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds after they hit the ground, two of the high-tech bug men
are killed by an enemy sniper.
</P>
<P>
   Score: chaos 2, technology 0.
</P>
<P>
   That tally will even up later during 11 days of fierce war games
in which units of the 82nd Airborne Division and the 10th Mountain
Division take on a no-tech but determined battalion of the 509th
Airborne Infantry, all to test the new technology at this sprawling
facility.
</P>
<P>
   It will take the Army months to fully analyze the results.
</P>
<P>
   But as 4,000 grimy and exhausted troops lit celebratory cigars
and swapped war stories at the mock conflict's end, this much was
clear: While digital technology can deliver immense battlefield
advantages, the ultimate outcome of America's next clash with a
chaotic world will ride, as always, on GI grit, skill and courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is not the hard part, it's the people,'' said
Col. Mark O'Neill, staff chief of the 10th Mountain Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part of this is the soldier, the average American
kid who's been asked to go out and make difficult decisions fast,
when he's tired, cold, hungry, wet and scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such misgivings, battlefield commanders here found the
technology holds huge potential.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart are digital satellite communications linked into a
tactical computer network. The system can track each individual or
vehicle and display it on a computer-generated map. A glance at the
screen shows a commander, and every other soldier with a receiver,
where all his men are. The screen also shows what's known about the
enemy's positions.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts can e-mail their reports back to headquarters rather than
repeat the information on static-blasted radios. Commanders can
e-mail changes in orders rather than assemble their unit leaders
for a map conference.
</P>
<P>
   One enthusiastic convert is Col. Bryan K. Stephens, who led a
tricky nighttime assault into a mock city of 26 multistory
buildings where the enemy was dug in behind roadblocks and
barricades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology helped tremendously keeping us together as we
moved into the attack,'' said Stephens, who commands the 10th
Mountain Division's 1st Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   In the dark and confusion, he said, ``I could see the lead
elements of my three battalions constantly, without having to stop
and call them on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That left me able to focus more on fighting the battle,''
Stephens said. Once his men got into the city, ``then it was basic
soldiering skills _ bayonet stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army's push to adapt digital technology to the battlefield
springs in part from its chilling experience in Mogadishu Oct. 3
and 4, 1993. Army Rangers and Delta Force commandoes had stormed
into the Somali capital to seize a handful of warlords.
</P>
<P>
   Intended as a lightning strike, the raid bogged down in a
pitched battle with Somali mobs who shot down two helicopters and
trapped the U.S. troops under withering fire.
</P>
<P>
   A key problem quickly emerged: No one could tell, in the city's
mazed alleyways and unmarked back streets, where they were, where
their buddies were, where the bad guys were.
</P>
<P>
   Infuriated, humiliated and vastly outnumbered, the elite
soldiers watched the combat advantage slide over to an untrained
mob of largely teen-agers armed with castoff, primitive weapons and
little or no training.
</P>
<P>
   Bullet-riddled U.S. convoys trying to bring in reinforcements
and ferry out the wounded got hopelessly lost. Trucks and Humvees
slick with the blood of the dead and dying crashed into ambush
after ambush, while commanders in helicopters overhead futilely
bawled out conflicting directions, according to Rangers' accounts
of the battle.
</P>
<P>
   They finished the mission, bringing out as prisoners the
warlords they'd gone in for. But the price was awful: 18 American
dead and more than half the assault force wounded. Three days
later, President Clinton announced that American troops would be
withdrawn from Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   That experience spurred the Army to tackle a problem that has
bedeviled commanders since warfare began: ``Where am I? Where are
my buddies? Where are the bad guys?''
</P>
<P>
   The Army has experimented with putting computers aboard tanks
and helicopters. But it wasn't until earlier this year that the
digital revolution reached foot soldiers _ Stephens' brigade and
some units of the 82nd Airborne Division.
</P>
<P>
   The impact was impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always fought off a folded paper map, and I'd be on the
radio all the time going, `Where are you? Where is Alpha
Company?''' said Stephens. One-third of his unit's radio
communications, he found, involved ``where are you?'' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Computers enabled the troops to work faster and more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   The airborne troopers landing on that pitch-black drop zone, for
instance, could see each other on their pop-down eyepiece computer
screens. Normally, it takes hours for paratroopers to regroup after
a night jump has scattered them. This time, they said, it took
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And when two of them fell to sniper fire, officers said, a third
paratrooper used his experimental long-range thermal rifle sight to
pick out the sniper on a drop zone crowded with paratroopers, and
felled him with one 300-meter shot.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing precisely where everybody is enables commanders to move
units faster. And faster, for today's Army, is critical.
</P>
<P>
   When American ground forces rush into action, the first to
arrive are the lightly armed infantry. And they may be the only
ones sent. Lacking heavy armor and almost always outnumbered, they
survive and win by being quicker than the enemy, protecting
themselves by surprising and shocking the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   When they get bogged down, as they did in Mogadishu, they're in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digitized'' soldiers can keep their bearings in difficult
conditions, on stormy nights or in jungles or crowded city
neighborhoods. They can maintain pressure on a foe, rather than
stopping to figure out where they are. And after the confusion of
battle, they can reorganize quickly to pursue the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digitizing ground units does not revolutionize land warfare,''
Col. Dan Bolger, commander of an infantry brigade in South Korea,
wrote in a recent essay in the book ``Digital War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it gives an edge to the guy who has the technology and
knows how to trust and use the stuff. In a game of inches, we'll
take a few however we can get them,'' Bolger said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a matter of more than inches.
</P>
<P>
   One night during the war game, Lt. Col. Kurt Fuller leads his
battalion in an assault on the small, enemy-held town of Huffton,
within the sprawling Fort Polk complex. The ``enemy'' forces have
no computers but, like the mobs in Mogadishu, know the local
terrain intimately.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard fight and his unit suffers heavy casualties, but it
eventually captures the town.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fuller discovers the enemy is holding a second town several
miles away. His men pile back into trucks equipped with the
position-locating computers and tear off cross-country with none of
their customary planning and rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, monitoring their progress on his computer screen,
``steers'' them in a coordinated attack, advising one or the other
unit to slow down or speed up.
</P>
<P>
   They attack simultaneously from different directions, catching
the enemy off guard. They easily take the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never could have done that without this computer stuff,''
Fuller said later. ``We'd have been stopping every few minutes,
getting out of our vehicles, getting out the maps and our
flashlights and getting on the radio and saying, `I think I am
here, where are you, over?' It would have taken us hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new stuff we just bombed on down the road and went
into the attack, and they were taken totally by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, senior commanders are cautious, and many are innately
suspicious of any over-reliance on gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is important but it's the least important part'' of
a successful military force, said Robert Killebrew, a veteran
paratrooper, Vietnam veteran and retired Army strategist.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Vietnam,'' he said pointedly, ``had no technology.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One potential problem is the difficulty of portraying today's
enemies on the computer screen. Tank formations, artillery
positions, ammunition dumps and troop quarters all can be observed
by satellite or unmanned spy planes, the data downloaded and
displayed as icons on everyone's computer.
</P>
<P>
   But how would the system have handled that disorganized mob in
Mogadishu? They ``were not soldiers in civilian disguise _ they
were real civilians,'' observed Larry Seaquist, a retired Navy
battleship skipper who is now a national security analyst in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   From Kosovo to Sierra Leone to East Timor, most of today's
conflicts are not fought with regular, identifiable military units
easily portrayed as computer icons.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are mindful of a sobering lesson from Vietnam: The
computers of then-Defense Secretary Robert McNamara relentlessly
digested detailed statistics from the field and churned out a
steady stream of charts and graphs that showed, precisely but
wrongly, that the United States was winning the war.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Defense Department said after the 1999 air
war against Serbia that its remote sensors showed 120 tanks, 220
armored personnel carriers and 450 artillery pieces were destroyed
by U.S. and NATO bombing. Neutral observers on the ground reported
after the war that less than a dozen tanks were destroyed; the
others were decoys.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, many officers are cautiously enthusiastic
about relying on information-age technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can get to near-perfect at knowing where we're at,
and maybe to `pretty good' at knowing where the enemy is,'' said
Lt. Col. Vance Nannini, who commands an artillery battalion in the
10th Mountain Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's better than the `OK' that we deal with today. Frankly,
a lot of times we guess.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   During one night attack here, Lt. Col. Fuller was just about to
launch his battalion when his computers went dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just burned up,'' Fuller said later. ``We had to do the
old-fashioned map-and-flashlight drill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than maintaining safe distance between the cavalry unit
in front of him, Fuller's battalion kept running into the cav's
rear units. The confusion blunted their attack and caused
additional casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mess,'' he said in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Tom Rogers also was supposed to take his squad of combat
engineers into an attack right behind the cavalry scouts. But the
electronics weren't working right and they got separated from the
column. Rogers, an experienced leader, quickly assessed the
situation and put his men into a position where they were most
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell in with a company of Marines, and we ended up killing
two BDRMs and a T-72 (Russian armored vehicles and a tank),'' he
exulted after the fight. ``Boom! Blasted those motha's!''
</P>
<P>
   Defense contractors have jumped eagerly into this technological
cornucopia. In a recent newspaper ad, Lockheed Martin, which holds
numerous Pentagon contracts to develop ``battlefield management
systems,'' showed a soldier behind a machine gun looking out into a
scary vista.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carry the right data and you carry the day,'' the ad boasted.
</P>
<P>
   But many professional soldiers reject that view, arguing that
soldier grit and battle skills are at least as critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what we do with the technology, we gotta hang on to
our core capability,'' said Fuller. ``In this light-infantry
battalion, my soldiers have to be physically fit, world-class
athletes and masters of their weapons day and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what will count in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   LF END WOOD
</P>
<P>
   David Wood can be reached at david.wood &LR; newhouse.com
</P>
