<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSING-EDEN27-COX     09-26 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-EDEN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFORMER URGES NEW MODEL OF COMMUNITY NURSING HOMES
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ The expansive country kitchen, with windows
overlooking a flowering garden and a cat curled up on a nearby
sofa, hardly looked like the dreaded image of a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   At one table, three residents of Goodwin House made cupcakes for
children who would be making their weekly visit from a preschool
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement and nursing home complex are part of a movement
to bring more humanity, respect and companionship, as well as
animals, plants and children, into nursing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Called the ``Eden Alternative'' after the biblical story, the
effort was founded almost a decade ago by Harvard-trained
geriatrist, William Thomas, and has spread to about 300 homes in
the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas visited Capitol Hill last week to urge the federal
government, which finances most long-term care costs, to accept new
ways of caring for people.
</P>
<P>
   His latest focus is on building homes in residential
neighborhoods, where a staff, with computer hookups to a hospital
center, would provide nursing care and housekeeping for six to
eight elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to abolish the practice of institutionalizing our
mothers and our fathers,'' Thomas said
</P>
<P>
   But with many of the nation's 17,000 nursing homes stubbornly
resistant to change and continuing to provide substandard care,
even the irrepressible Thomas is beginning to doubt if the nation's
nursing home system can be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, there's a long way to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas's new proposal envisions 4,000-square-foot ranch-style
homes. The first seven of these homes, dubbed the ``Green House
Project,'' are to be built next year by the Faxton-St. Luke's
Health Care System in Utica, N.Y., as it phases out a nursing care
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to create an environment where Eden-like ideas can
flourish more readily than in a 200 bed-nursing facility,'' Thomas
told a gathering. ``My heart breaks when I see how many people try
hard to make it work and are knocked down by an institutional
structure that is more powerful than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the new homes would cost 25 percent less per
resident to build than a standard nursing home. Staff training
costs are somewhat higher, but in the end, the new homes should be
no more expensive for clients than traditional care.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Caswell, director of health and wellness at Goodwin
House, said it has taken years to make the transition to the Eden
system, which is largely a matter of remodeling the building and
training the staff in what she calls ``common-sense'' caring for
each person as an individual.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one resident is served oatmeal for breakfast every
day because that's what she had at her home. Meals are served on
linen tablecloths, instead of trays, in homey dining rooms. Staff
members operate as teams that include nurses, nurse assistants and
housekeeping workers, who meet together to make decisions for each
wing.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have found mental and physical health of residents
improves in these ``Edenized'' homes.
</P>
<P>
   At Goodwin House, residents rarely have physical restraints, and
they take far fewer medications for mental disorders than nursing
home patients nationwide. Staff turnover, which is roughly 100
percent in nursing homes nationwide, is 30 percent at Goodwin
House.
</P>
<P>
   A study published last spring by Southwest Texas State
University in San Marcos tested the effects of applying the Eden
concept at five Texas facilities. Behavioral problems, bedsores,
and staff absenteeism dropped dramatically, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Eden Alternative: www.edenalt.com
</P>
<P>
   The Green House Project: www.thegreenhouseproject.org
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
