A1827 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0927-CO     09-26 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dating isn't what it used to be
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This morning, as usual, coffee and
conversation with my retired farmer buddies began on a lofty note.
Well, maybe not quite so exalted, since we were talking politics.
Amos was saying how he wishes Lieberman would stop Bible thumping,
and Cal admits he keeps hoping for a miracle where Bush will stop
talking all over himself and say something _ almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   John Deere ballcaps nod in a wave of agreement around the table.
</P>
<P>
   Benny says he doesn't like it that Gore wears boots instead of
shoes. Amos reminds him Gore's a farmer. ``Farmer, my Aunt
Fanny!,'' Benny snorts. ``I'm a farmer and I don't go around in
shiny boots. I wear work shoes.'' That said, he kicks a Red Wing to
the edge of the table as proof. For just a minute there he looks as
if he might not be able to get it back under the table without
help. But he manages.
</P>
<P>
   Amos says, with a knowing chuckle, ``I think he wears those
boots to keep from getting snakebit.'' Benny picks up on that one
right away and explains that political snakes don't bite on the
ankles. No one argues with that.
</P>
<P>
   There's a short silence, then predictably the talk turns to what
Cal calls ``he'in and she'in.'' Ed, a widower for a couple of years
now, is mumbling something about checking out a lonely hearts club
to see if maybe he can meet
</P>
<P>
   some nice ladies who'd like to spend time with a handsome guy.
Amos asks who the handsome guy might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dating services,'' Benny puts in his two-cents worth. ``They
don't call `em lonely hearts any more.'' Ed asks Benny how he knows
this, being a married man and all, and Benny says it's because he
reads the papers. ``Don't you ever read that section where ladies
are looking for men and men are looking for ladies and there's
even. . .'' Benny stops, thinks it over, and then adds, ``You'd be
surprised what folks are advertising for nowadays.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed says he has a friend who joined up and met a real nice lady
he now sees a couple of times a week _ sometimes at her place and
sometimes at his. Benny raises an eyebrow and asks the obvious.
``You mean they're. . . ?''
</P>
<P>
   Ed says sure, why not. ``They're both in their 70s,'' he
explains with a laugh, ``so they sure don't have to worry about
starting a family.'' The table goes momentarily quiet while the
guys take a nostalgic moment to think this one
</P>
<P>
   over. Then a discussion begins of how difficult it would be to
go back to courting.
</P>
<P>
   Amos says he's forgotten everything he ever knew about going on
a date. Cal tells him that wasn't much, but adds, ``Heck, I
wouldn't know where to begin either. I been married 53 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed says dating today isn't what it used to be _ his friend has
told him all about it. ``The problem is bucket seats. And seat
belts. The ladies can't slide over and sit real close like they
used to do when we were kids. Remember
</P>
<P>
   that?'' We all smile _ we all remember.
</P>
<P>
   Cal tells how he used to pretend his hand had accidentally
slipped off the gearshift knob and right onto the lady's knee. Says
he got slapped once or twice. Amos says he used to do the same
thing . . . and Benny. . . and Ed, and all
</P>
<P>
   the rest of them. I tell them how, once I was going steady, I
used to shift gears for my boyfriend Harry when he had his right
arm around me. I recall the first time I worked up enough courage
to put my hand on his knee. We were both so surprised we almost
wrecked the car.
</P>
<P>
   Ed says that's what he misses most, the little stuff. He plants
his coffee mug on the table and tells us he's off to Toledo.
``Doctor's appointment?'' Cal asks. Ed shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I'm gonna' join up with the lonely hearts and then I'm
going looking for a `39 Ford with a bench seat and three on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   We all wish him luck _ on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
