<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1828 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG27-COX     09-26 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rah rah, Uniformity U. Stick college students with more
standardized tests?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, Gandhi arrives at the portal of the afterlife. A specter
with a clipboard stops him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why the delay?'' asks Gandhi. ``Have I not lived a moral life?
Have I not fought oppression and sacrificed for mankind?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' says the attendant. ``It says here, however, you
haven't taken the algebra exit test.''
</P>
<P>
   You are entering testing purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   More and more it seems clear that a standardized test will be
the basis upon which every life is judged.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up your No. 2 pencil. Put down your Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The fixation on standardized tests in public schools has
benefits. It affixes some students' attention to basic skills they
lack. It also has drawbacks. It downshifts some Indy-car minds to
golf-cart speed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, alarmingly, the standardized impulse is tugging at certain
University of Texas regents. A ``discussion document'' is afloat
concerning standardized tests for core subjects _ math, science,
history, English, government, even fine arts _ and also in
students' majors.
</P>
<P>
   This is a response to nationwide concerns about grade inflation.
To such a pat response come faculty and student concerns about
homogenizing college education and driving up costs.
</P>
<P>
   UT Associate Vice Chancellor Joe Stafford, into whose lap this
notion has been dropped, warns against jumping to conclusions. The
initiative is still in the thinking stage.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford said the objective is some form of institutional
accountability. Whether that would take the form of standardized
tests or some other means remains to be proposed.
</P>
<P>
   When word first circulated about the proposed tests, proponents
said the idea was to rate educators and departments, rather than
students. Hmmm. A no-stakes test to gobble up a student's time? See
you down the road.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that for students to take such tests seriously,
they'd need a little fear of God drummed into them: class credits
hinging on passing.
</P>
<P>
   Either way you've got something certain to induce much sameness
in classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Questions, questions. How to pay for these tests? We don't know,
but we can imagine. Just stick it on a student fee list already
longer than the credits for ``Gunga Din''.
</P>
<P>
   Questions. Who would decide what test questions to ask? Teams of
UT professors, of course. Supposedly that would make things
collegial again. Suppose again.
</P>
<P>
   Questions. How to have a standardized means of assessing someone
whose major is art, music, drama or other lively arts that can't be
captured in a vial?
</P>
<P>
   Stafford agreed that such offerings seem to defy any notion of
standardized testing. But he said that doesn't mean a standardized
means of assessment couldn't be devised, say through portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   All of which begs the question. What are professors doing now?
Are they not assessing, not testing? Of course they are. That's
their job. We hire the best we can, with the expertise and the
teaching skills, and we ask them to assess based on their skills.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, board certification or professional exams will be
the ultimate delineators for graduates. Do they need one more test?
</P>
<P>
   The state already has TASP _ the Texas Academic Skills Placement
test _ which freshmen must pass in reading, writing and math unless
they score sufficiently high on the SAT, ACT or TAAS. Obviously,
what higher education needs is more acronyms. Acronyms mean
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   If the issue is grade inflation, instead of imposing more tests
Texas could consider what Great Britain, New Zealand and Hong Kong
do: audit grading practices and classroom offerings based on a
nationally normed set of standards.
</P>
<P>
   But one more test? One more cost?
</P>
<P>
   Students would have moral standing to resist.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
