<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-26 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, Sept. 26, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MINING-POLLUTION (San Francisco) _ Thousands of pounds of
mercury leaking from dozens of old gold mines in the Sierra Nevada
is contaminating downstream lakes and streams and triggering health
warnings on game fish. The warnings concerning tainted fish are the
first in California's historic gold mining regions, including the
Sierra and the Trinity-Klamath Mountains. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (El Cenizo, Texas) _ Tensions are escalating
between the U.S. Border Patrol and residents of this tiny town that
made national headlines last year after it adopted Spanish as its
official language. El Cenizo, population 1,775, has formed a
``truth commission'' to investigate allegations of human rights
abuses by Border Patrol agents here. By BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DANCE-HALL (New Braunfels, Texas) _ Gruene Hall is a
special place to anyone who has scooted across the well-worn wooden
floor. But the oldest dance hall in Texas means even more to those
who make the music. ``It's the `Austin City Limits' of dance
halls,'' country artist Charlie Robison says, comparing it to the
venerable PBS television show that spotlights Texas musicians. By
JOHN GOODSPEED.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-REVIEW-BUSH (San Antonio) _ Almost every song on Johnny
Bush'S latest album deals with rejection and the ways people cope
with it, from bouncing back to love again to homicidal rages.
``Lost Highway Saloon'' is the country music legend's two-year
effort to record old songs he's always loved along with carefully
chosen new ones in an album that crosses a little outside his usual
bounds of honky-tonk, Western swing and traditional country music.
By JOHN GOODSPEED.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FALL-CHANGES (Undated) _ Sally Field, the ``Flying Nun,'' is
returning to television this fall on ``ER'' and possibly another
show. Other returning shows will undergo a variety of changes this
season, which kicks off in earnest next week. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-CRIME (Undated) _ The more horses, jockeys,
racetracks and steeplechases, the more I like to read a Dick
Francis book. Unfortunately for me, ``Shattered''(G.P. Puntam's
Sons, $25.95, 289 pages) only has racing in the first chapter.
Nevertheless, Francis is in top form as a storyteller in this new
book. By ROBERTA MARTHA MARY ELIZABETH HESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PALM-CONVERGENCE (San Francisco) _ Plans for a hybrid mobile
phone and electronic organizer unveiled by Palm and Handspring
signaled a renewed push in the race to roll out all-in-one
communication devices, analysts said. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   LUBY'S-CEO (San Antonio) _ The president and chief executive
officer of Luby's Inc. resigned, leaving the San Antonio-based
cafeteria chain searching for its fourth leader in five years. By
ELIZABETH ALLEN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-OWENS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ With steely eyes and a
furrowed brow, Steve Mariucci resembled a disappointed father
forced to mete out a painful punishment to his wayward child. But
Terrell Owens didn't lose the keys to the car or the privilege of
playing with his video games for a week. He paid a much heftier
price for his nationally televised misbehavior in Sunday's 41-24
win over Dallas. Owens has been grounded. By MICHELLE SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Terrell Owens ought to be angry
with the San Francisco 49ers. He ought to be downright livid. Not
because he was suspended for a week. That one, he has to eat. And
not because he lost $24,000 and change with the suspension. I mean,
what's money to a millionaire like him? No, the bone he has to pick
with management boils down to the fact that nobody in a position of
authority bothers to notice a new and unique touchdown celebration
any longer. I mean, what's an artist got to do? By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GIANTS (San Francisco) _ The Giants want it all now. The
World Series or bust. If it's not a Fall Classic, in their minds,
it'll be a classic fall. After clinching the National League West
last week, the Giants made it known they wouldn't settle for
anything less than a final showdown with the New York Yankees, or
any other team the American League submits. By JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX (Sydney, Australia) _ After you've done seven years of
hard time in the Illinois State Penitentiary with guys named
Pharaoh and Mongoose, nothing much figures to scare you, not even a
6-foot-6 Cuban named Felix Savon. That's the attitude former
convict turned Olympic boxer Michael Bennett took into his Tuesday
afternoon heavyweight bout against Cuba's latest Lord of the Ring.
By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUGS (Sydney, Australia) _ The search for an Olympic sport
without a doping controversy continues. On Tuesday, it led to the
doorstep of synchronized swimming, surely a haven for the weary and
jaded. What could be safer? Hair gel doesn't make the ban list. Nor
do sequins, at least until someone discovers a way to swallow them
and go faster, higher, stronger. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Ten days ago, the Catholic
Church and filmmaking lost a smart and tender friend. The Rev.
Ellwood E. Kieser died in Los Angeles of colon cancer at the age of
71. The founder of a non-profit movie company that is run by and
named for his clerical order _ Paulist Productions _ Father Kieser
was a television and film producer whose efforts brought him six
Emmy Awards. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
