r e BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-BUSH-HNS     09-26 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JOHNNY BUSH'S NEWEST ALBUM IS ALL ABOUT REJECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Beaumont, Houston)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GOODSPEED  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Johnny Bush is making rejection an art.
</P>
<P>
   Only he's not into jilting. He's into commiserating.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every song on the country music legend's latest album
deals with rejection and the ways people cope with it, from
bouncing back to love again to homicidal rages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea began with, `What makes a country song?''' said Bush,
who knows a little about the genre. His career began in Houston in
1952, when he played with Ray Price and Willie Nelson and recorded
such hits as ``Undo the Right,'' ``I'll Be There,'' ``You Gave Me a
Mountain'' and ``Whiskey River,'' which he wrote and Nelson later
took as his signature song.
</P>
<P>
   ``A country song deals with real situations that people face
every day, and not necessarily cheating and drinking and running
around. But I thought it would be fun to pick out songs that show
how people handle rejection,'' said Bush, a longtime San Antonio
resident who still two-steps through the Texas dance-hall circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Lost Highway Saloon,'' Bush's two-year effort to
record old songs he's always loved along with carefully chosen new
ones in an album that crosses a little outside his usual bounds of
honky-tonk, Western swing and traditional country music.
</P>
<P>
   Bush knows a little about rejection, too.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, he was engaged to a high school girl and working seven
days a week in the oil fields near Beaumont to save enough money to
get married. After working double shifts for time off, he went to
visit her in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``She dropped my engagement ring in my hand and said it's over _
that she loved a football player,'' Bush said. ``I had to drive all
the way back to Beaumont with this pain in my heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too young to drink, but Lefty Frizzell and Hank Williams
sure started sounding better to me. You really don't know how much
meaning those country songs have until you're hurting, and then
they all start making sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The rejection songs include:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Same Ole Me,'' a twin-fiddle shuffle Ray Price recorded
just before Bush joined Price's Cherokee Cowboys in the early
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wall,'' a new song by Clay Blaker of New Braunfels, who's
written songs for George Strait and Barbra Streisand. Bush's duet
with Leona Williams nails the tale about a couple going through the
motions after the flame has died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands Can Say A Lot Beneath the Table'' is a self-explanatory
story of a cheating wife that's a pure honky-tonker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're Hanging Me Tonight'' shows how rejection can lead to a
violent end for everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Highway Saloon'' is the first release on a new label,
Lone Star Records, which also will release ``Johnny Bush Sings Bob
Wills'' in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better way to start a new country label than with an
album from Johnny Bush _ one of the true legends of Texas country
music,'' said Heinz Geissler, manager of the Texas Music Group,
which oversees Austin's Lone Star Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it when artists stretch a little bit, and that's what
John did here,'' Geissler said. ``I always commend artists who
don't just try to re-create what they've been doing forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush doesn't step that far outside the box, but when he does,
it's memorable:
</P>
<P>
   A cover of ``I'll Never Be Free,'' an early 1950s duet by
Tennessee Ernie Ford and Kaye Starr that was one of the first
crossover country hits, reaching No. 1 on the pop chart. Bush's
version with Houston singer Kate McCarthy is a love song in a
silky-smooth arrangement that proves that country is cool.
</P>
<P>
   For something really different, Bush chose the title cut of
``Lost Highway Saloon.'' The ballad is about a man stopping for a
drink in a bar reminiscent of ``Twilight Zone'' where a haunted
jukebox conjures the legends _ ``I could smell the whiskey on
Hank's breath and Patsy Cline's perfume.'' After leaving, he can
never find the bar again.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had been trying to write a song with the same
concept for 20 years but a young man from Dallas, Brian Burns, beat
him to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard it, it just destroyed me,'' Bush said. ``I knew
it wasn't a Johnny Bush-type song, but I had to try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new one for Bush is a hidden track that starts about a
minute after the last song ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-McCarthy duet on ``I'll Never Be Free'' is repeated
through an electronic filter that introduces the snaps, crackles
and pops and tinny tone that replicates the sound of a 78 rpm
recording.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hopes the range and depth of the 14 songs on the album will
provide something for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my intent to introduce new songs to my old friends and to
revive some old songs to new fans,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he finishes the album with a tour de force of
rejection, despair and redemption with the last three songs.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pride Goes Before a Fall,'' a Leon Payne song Jim Reeves
covered in the 1960s, a man joins the winos after being rejected by
a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The next is an extension of that song, ``So This Is the Fall
(That Pride Goes Before),'' written by the late Neal Merritt and
covered by Stonewall Jackson. The same man hits rock bottom,
selling the ring she returned to buy a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine Into Water'' is a cover of T. Graham Brown's 1998 song
about an alcoholic who turns to Jesus to keep from destroying
himself and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this guy's last resort, which I think should always be the
first resort if you have a problem, is to turn to the Lord and ask
him to be delivered from it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from someone with Bush's credentials, that's some advice
about rejection that shouldn't be rejected out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Goodspeed's e-mail address is
jgoodspeed(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
