<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TEXAS-DANCE-HALL-HNS &LR;      09-26 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DANCE-HALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLD DANCE HALL GIVES NEW COUNTRY ALBUM A SPECIAL TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GOODSPEED  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Gruene Hall is a special place to anyone
who has scooted across the well-worn wooden floor. But the oldest
dance hall in Texas means even more to those who make the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `Austin City Limits' of dance halls,'' alternative
country artist Charlie Robison said, comparing it to the venerable
PBS television show that spotlights Texas musicians. ``The first
time you get a Saturday night there, you are accepted. It means you
pass muster.''
</P>
<P>
   For Robison, his younger brother, Bruce, and Jack Ingram,
recording a live album at Gruene Hall last December was a
triumphant return to their roots.
</P>
<P>
   That effort, ``Unleashed Live,'' hit the shelves this week as a
document of the final concert in a 40-city tour in support of each
artist's album on Sony's Lucky Dog Records.
</P>
<P>
   Each selected four songs from the Gruene Hall session, and most
are from their latest albums _ Bruce Robison's ``Long Way From
Anywhere,'' Charlie Robison's ``Life Of The Party'' and Ingram's
``Hey You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that happens live that's irreplaceable in
the studio,'' Ingram said. ``You've got all these screaming people;
it's like live theater . . . it's this energy. The cool thing is
that we recorded it at Gruene Hall, where that kind of stuff was
happening that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruene Hall, located in a historic area of New Braunfels, a
short drive from San Antonio, was one of the first venues for the
Robisons. They began playing there _ without a cover charge _ in
the early 1990s. Ingram, a Houston native who now lives in Dallas,
started visiting Gruene Hall as a kid with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Unleashed tour put the Robison brothers together
with their friend Ingram, whom they got to know at gigs across the
state. Since they got along well and played in a similar rocking
roadhouse style tinged with traditional country, Lucky Dog decided
on the joint tour to promote each of their albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were having a blast every night, going up and singing on
each other's sets,'' Charlie Robison said. ``We were ending the
tour in Texas, and the people at Sony thought it was a good idea to
record one of those shows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who love my music have an equal passion for
Charlie and Bruce, and I think it goes that way around the table,''
Ingram said. ``So that's why it was such a good tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The album kicks off with a twanging 4/4 shuffle, ``The Good
Life,'' from Bruce Robison, who lives in Austin. Charlie joins him
on the yearning ``Rayne, Louisiana'' before Bruce's wife, fellow
county artist Kelly Willis, sings a duet on the bittersweet ``Angry
All The Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Robison's contributions include ``My Hometown,'' a
coming-of-age ballad with an attitude: The crowd joins in on the
college part, ``I don't think I seen a single classroom/but I drank
a lot of beer.''
</P>
<P>
   His unnerving ``Loving County,'' about a killing a rich woman in
order to get a ring for his girlfriend, is balanced by the raucous
``Barlight,'' where a nursery rhyme becomes a rocking salute to
saloons.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram includes the no-place-like-home song ``Travis County,''
which he's never recorded but was in the movie ``Hope Floats.'' An
extended guitar riff introduces a flaming hot ``Mustang Burn,''
while ``Barbie Doll'' _ a warning about vacant blondes _ provides a
bring-the-house-down, sing-along ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love those guys,'' Gruene Hall owner Pat Molak said.
``Their music is so lively and they're good entertainers. We're
totally flattered to have them record that album here.''
</P>
<P>
   The dance hall was built in 1878 for the then-thriving German
farming community of Gruene. Molak revived the hall after buying it
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of magic between the artists and the
crowd,'' he said. ``You can get pretty close to them, and there's a
lot of interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Robison, who has moved to Sony's Colombia Records, said
his next album would be released in late December or early January.
Ingram, who will return to the studio in January, is adding a few
of the new songs to his concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Robison is scheduled to be back at Gruene Hall on Nov.
24 and Ingram will follow on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Robison said his songs on ``Unleashed Live'' are some of his
favorites because he wrote them in the town of Bandera, a stone's
throw from Gruene Hall, at a time when he was playing anywhere with
just his guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now playing where we sell out weeks in advance, it's
really come full circle,'' Robison said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Goodspeed's e-mail address is
jgoodspeed(at)express-news.net)
</P>
