<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-FALL-CHANGES-HNS &LR;      09-26 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-CHANGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FALL TV SEASON BRINGS OLD FACES IN NEW ROLES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ``The Fugitive'' can return to television, why not the Flying
Nun?
</P>
<P>
   While CBS is remaking the 1960s David Janssen drama, Sister
Bertrille is not coming back. But Sally Field is returning to
television _ and maybe in more than one place.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar-winner people really, really liked (she spoofed her
famous acceptance speech in a recent Super Bowl commercial) will
play a recurring character on ``ER'' (NBC) for six episodes
starting this fall. She will portray the mother of Abby Lockhart
(Maura Tierney).
</P>
<P>
   Field is also the target of several jokes in the premiere of
``Bette,'' the new CBS comedy in which Bette Midler plays herself.
Field's 1980 best actress Oscar for ``Norma Rae'' made Midler a
loser for ``The Rose.'' The set-up screams for a guest appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Other returning shows will undergo a variety of changes this
season, which kicks off in earnest next week. Here are some
highlights:
</P>
<P>
   _ Less Fox on Fox: David Duchovny's Fox Mulder, apparently
abducted by aliens in last year's finale of ``The X-Files'' (Fox)
will appear in only 11 episodes this season. Robert Patrick (the
shape-shifting cyborg assassin in ``Terminator 2'') teams up with
Gillian Anderson's Dana Scully.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bad boys, bad boys: Two of Hollywood's more notorious movie
actors will try to leave their troubles behind as they transition
to television. Fresh from the slammer, Robert Downey Jr. joins the
cast of ``Ally McBeal'' (Fox) for eight episodes, playing a
potential love interest for Calista Flockhart's flighty attorney.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Spin City'' (ABC), Charlie Sheen has the unenviable duty of
replacing Michael J. Fox. In a scheduling quirk, Sheen will be
going head-to-head on Wednesday nights against dad Martin Sheen of
NBC's Emmy-winner ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he beats the pants off of us,'' Dad said this past
summer with a shrug. ``That's fine.'' Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   _ The DA departs: The venerable Adam Schiff (Steven Hill)
departs the top chair in the New York County DA's Office on ``Law &AMP;
Order'' (NBC).
</P>
<P>
   In a show that's lasted 10 seasons because of regular cast
changes, Hill's departure is significant in that he is the last
remaining actor from its inaugural 1990 season (although he was not
an original cast member).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Steven's decision,'' said Executive Producer Dick Wolf.
``Ten years on anything is an amazing run. It's the second decade
of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill will be replaced by Dianne Wiest (an Oscar winner for
``Bullets Over Broadway''). ``She's brand-new in the job,'' Wolf
said. ``She won't have quite the shorthand with Sam (Waterston, who
plays Assistant DA Jack McCoy) that Steven had. There will be some
decided differences of opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Wolf isn't distraught by the departure of a cast
member. ``In ensemble dramas there's a wear-out factor with any
original cast,'' he said. ``You have four or five seasons, and then
the audience knows everybody's moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience has not only come to expect but to embrace the
character changes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving on over: In what ought to be a record, three shows have
switched networks this fall: ``The Hughleys'' moved from ABC to
UPN; ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch'' shifts from ABC to the WB, and
``The PJ's'' slides over from Fox to the WB.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paging Drs. Bayliss and Pembleton: The lead detectives of
``Homicide: Life on the Street'' have traded avenging the dead to
saving the living. Kyle Secor, who played Detective Tim Bayliss,
joins the cast of ``City of Angels'' (CBS), while Andre Braugher
(Detective Frank Pembleton) is the title character in the new ABC
hospital drama ``Gideon's Crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' is being completely revamped. Gone is lead
actor Vivica A. Fox, as is Executive Producer Paris Barclay.
</P>
<P>
   _ More changes: Andrea Thompson (who played Detective Jill
Kirkendall) and executive producer David Milch departed ``NYPD
Blue'' (ABC); James McDaniel (Lt. Arthur Fancy) leaves at
mid-season ... Tony Danza joins the cast of ``Family Law'' (CBS)
... ``The Jamie Foxx Show'' (WB) is a guaranteed mid-season
cancellation _ the show is going off the air to make way for a new
comedy-variety series from Foxx. Jessica Biel, who posed almost
nude for Gear magazine last year, got her wish and is getting out
of the squeaky clean ``7th Heaven'' (WB) ... Buffy (Sarah Michelle
Gellar) gets a younger sister named Dawn (Michelle Trachtenberg) on
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (WB).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
