 Attn. Sports Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic stories from The New York Times News Service for
Wednesday, Sept. 27:
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUGS-ANALYSIS (Sydney) _ As C.J. Hunter, the husband of
Marion Jones seeks to clear his name, the entire system of drug
testing in the United States has come under fire from international
Olympic officials who consider the Americans hypocritical, laggard
and deceptive in their handling of doping cases. U.S. officials are
firing back. The recrimination has symbolized the messy state of
drug testing internationally and the lack of trust and cooperation
that undermines renewed efforts to curb the widespread use of
performance-enhancing drugs. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Caryn James assesses NBC's Olympic
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BASE (Sydney) _ Doug Mientkiewicz slammed a home run in the
bottom of the ninth inning to give the United States a stormy 3-2
victory over South Korea on Tuesday, setting up an Olympic baseball
final against arch-rivals Cuba. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-MEN (Sydney) _ U.S. men lose to Spain, 3-1, in the
soccer semifinals Tuesday night. They can still capture the bronze
medal with a victory over Chile. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX (Sydney) _ Tuesday, the Sydney Olympic boxing tournament
got serious. Tuesday was the day, figuratively, that the quality
boxers in the tournament braced their feet and threw punches with
unfeigned malice. The medal rounds await, and everything in the
Olympic boxing tournament was a little bigger, louder, faster.
Little of this was good news for the Americans in the field. By
Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOF (Blacktown, Australia) _ The U.S. softball team came to
Sydney favored to defend its Atlanta gold model. They lived on the
edge, game to game, inning to inning, even losing three straight
games before rallying back. When the Americans finally defeated
Japan in the gold medal game Tuesday night, 2-1, they did it with
only one hit. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WRESTLING (Sydney) _ Matt Lindland's circuitous route to the
Olympic wrestling mat took him from the trials, to the rulings of
arbitrators and into federal courtrooms. Tuesday he won a silver
medal. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Sports of The Times Column on
the Olympics' most notable couple, C.J. Hunter and Marion Jones,
husband and wife as well as track star and coach, and now two
people making news for very different reasons. By William C.
Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO (Sydney) _ Feature on Lauren Jackson, the 19-year-old
Australian basketball star who may soon take her talents to the
WNBA. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DIV (Sydney) _ Olympic springboard champion Xiong Ni of
China staged a stunning fight to defend his title on the final dive
here Tuesday, and win his country's first diving gold of the Sydney
Games. By Bill Brink.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SAIL (Sydney) _ It's been said that into everyone's life a
little rain must fall. And Tuesday, under bleak skies on Sydney
Harbor, it descended on U.S. skipper Russ Silvestri and his two
dozen opponents in the Finn singlehanded dinghy class as the second
week of the Olympic sailing competition continued. By Herb
McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
