<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTWOOD-DOCUMENTARY-LADN </SLUG>
bc-EASTWOOD 
EARLY EASTWOOD IS EASILY FORGIVEN (For use by New York Times News
Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Wed., Sept. 27.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critics sneered at Clint Eastwood's spaghetti westerns when they
first hit theaters, and now, the Man With No Name's essayist is the
subject of hagiography from PBS, which was born about the same time
as Eastwood's film career. ``Clint Eastwood: Out of the Shadows''
is an enjoyable documentary overview of the actor and Oscar-winning
filmmaker's career.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood buffs may rightly grouse that it doesn't bring much new
or surprising to the party. Casual fans, however, may learn a thing
or two about a guy who was dismissed for too long as just another
action hero and who, in fact, preferred to insist in interviews
that he was more interested in telling stories than any subtext and
the depth he brought his films.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't last that long without being very smart,'' observes
screenwriter William Goldman early on in the documentary. Sure
enough, we get a glimpse into Eastwood's plain-spoken,
unpretentious intelligence, ranging from his Depression-era youth
(which inspired his intrigue with drifters) to reactions to his own
success with films ranging from ``Bronco Billy'' to his Oscar
winner, the stark western ``Unforgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors from Meryl Streep to Gene Hackman and directors like
Martin Scorsese and Curtis Hanson offer their perspectives on what
Eastwood has managed to achieve in his career. Richard Burton, in
archival footage, aptly describes Eastwood's on-screen presence as
``a dynamic lethargy''; Barry Reardon, formerly of Warner Bros.,
admits some in the studio initially considered his monkey movie
``Every Which Way but Loose'' ``unreleasable.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some curious oversights. One of Eastwood's most
interesting deconstructions of his anti-hero persona,
``Tightrope,'' is overlooked completely. The production, naturally,
glosses over Eastwood's hacky, fallow period of the late '80s and
early '90s, which produced such listless duds as ``The Dead Pool,''
``The Rookie'' and ``Pink Cadillac.'' (Curiously, directorial
triumphs such as ``Bird'' and ``White Hunter, Black Heart,'' the
first of his films to meditate on the themes explored more fully in
``Unforgiven,'' came in this same time span; ``Bird'' is expounded
upon at length, while ``Hunter'' is dismissed in a sentence or
two). Likewise, the star's personal life is discussed only enough
that its more tabloidlike omissions seem disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it's a pretty intelligently compiled 90 minutes,
and casts Eastwood who made one of the few movies of the past
summer you didn't feel like an idiot for seeing, ``Space Cowboys''
in the unlikely but justly heralded role of bashful auteur. To
contradict his character in ``Unforgiven,'' ``deserve's'' got
EVERYTHING to do with it. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
``CLINT EASTWOOD: OUT OF THE SHADOWS'' &QL; 
-What: ``American Masters'' documentary about the star/filmmaker. &QL; 
-When: 8 tonight. &QL; 
-Where: KCET. &QL; 
-Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
