<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-PALM-CONVERGENCE-HNS &LR;      09-26 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-CONVERGENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMPANIES TAKE STEP TOWARD ALL-IN-ONE COMMUNICATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Plans by Palm and Handspring to create hybrid
mobile phone and electronic organizer signal a renewed push in the
race to roll out all-in-one communication devices, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the gold at the end of the rainbow: to have one
device,'' said analyst James Johnson of A.G. Edwards, an investment
bank in New York. ``We're going to see a convergence of products
from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   Past industry attempts, such as Qualcomm's PDQ and Nokia's
Communicator, have been too big and too pricey to attract users.
</P>
<P>
   But Santa Clara, Calif.-based Palm announced Monday that it
would team with Schaumburg, Ill.-based Motorola to develop a
``smart phone'' _ combining wireless Internet access, mobile phone,
and electronic organizer _ for delivery in 2002. Customers would
purchase the device through their wireless service provider.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership marks the first time Palm will jointly develop,
market and brand a combo device with a mobile phone manufacturer.
With this deal, the market's most popular hand-held organizer will
deploy its operating system and software on a wider range of
devices and sales channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of a couple dollars per unit from licensing fees per
device, this way, the revenues are more substantial,'' said analyst
James Faucette, of Pacific Crest Securities, an investment bank in
Portland, Ore., that specializes in communications technology. ``It
also extends their market penetration, taking it into wireless
(phone) stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Motorola can tap into the hand-held organizer's
expertise. Motorola, the world's second largest mobile phone maker,
made a $65 million investment in Palm in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to seamlessly bring together features and technology,
so users will feel comfortable getting the best of both worlds,''
said Leif Soderbergh, Motorola's senior vice president of the
personal communication sector. ``We wouldn't get that through
straight licensing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Palm licensed its operating system with
Kyocera's Qualcomm mobile phone division and the Finnish Nokia, the
world's No. 1 mobile phone maker.
</P>
<P>
   Palm said that for the period ended Sept. 1, operating profit
rose to $23.9 million, or 4 cents a share, up from $10 million, or
2 cents per share, a year ago. Sales rose to $401 million from
$176.5 million. The company shipped about 1.5 million Palm devices
in the quarter, contributing to a total of more than 8.7 million
Palms sold.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Mountain View, Calif.-based Handspring announced
Monday it would begin selling the $299 VisorPhone module by
mid-November. The module snaps into expansion slots on any Visor
hand-held _ which licenses the Palm operating system _ to allow
wireless Web access, text messaging and Caller ID, among other
features.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Handspring will sell the module and phone service
plan through Handspring.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
