<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CEO OF SOUTHERN CAFETERIA CHAIN RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH ALLEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The president and chief executive officer of
Luby's Inc. resigned Monday, leaving the San Antonio-based
cafeteria chain searching for its fourth leader in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Barry J.C. Parker, who came to Luby's from the retail clothing
company County Seat in 1997, ``wished to resign to pursue other
interests,'' according to a statement. Parker's resignation is
``subject to finalizing a separation agreement,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman David B. Daviss has assumed the duties of chief
executive officer, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Luby's operates 220 cafeteria-style restaurants mainly in the
South and Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Parker's salary was $375,000, and he received a bonus
of $93,500. He was employed under a three-year contract effective
Oct. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some former managers, who had said in interviews that they were
unhappy with Parker's strategy and personal approach, greeted the
news of Parker's resignation with glee.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Parker's resignation, Tommy Griggs, a 40-year
veteran and former member of Luby's board of directors, said:
``That's tremendous. He's taken the stock from $21 down to five and
a quarter. It was something that was needed a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Schubert, who left the company earlier this year to open
his own cafeteria in San Antonio, said the move is a signal by
Luby's board of directors that they are paying more attention to
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managers themselves I know will throw their arms up and
give a great big cheer,'' Schubert said.
</P>
<P>
   And stockholders, some of whom had seen the value of their
stocks decline 70 percent in three years, also expressed optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Les Greenberg, a shareholder who has led a campaign to shake up
the board of directors and who seeks a board seat, said he thought
the company would ``get back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Luby's announced in August that it would close 15 stores and
would downgrade its fourth-quarter earnings expectations from more
than 20 cents a share to one to five cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company's same-store sales (or sales at stores opened at
least one year) were off 5.5 percent, in part because of new
bundled-meal offerings, which bring in less money than the same
dishes a la carte, Laura Bishop, chief financial officer, said at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   That bad news sent the stock price plunging more than 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Luby's, one of Texas' best-known restaurant brands, once earned
plaudits for its strategy from Forbes magazine. Yet Luby's
struggles began before Parker was hired.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, John E. Curtis Jr., the company's president and
chief executive officer of two months, committed suicide. The
company's chairman, Ralph ``Pete'' Erben resigned days later,
leaving John B. Lahourcade to hold down the positions of both men
until Parker was hired in September of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Changes instituted under Parker include outsourcing some of the
restaurants' food preparation, experiments with breakfast and later
hours, expansion of take-out services, construction of
drive-throughs and a reworking of management compensation that
resulted in a sharp income cut for some top managers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
