<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON...
</HEADLINE>
bc-ROSH-SIDEBAR (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: SIDEBAR TO ROSH HASHANA RECIPES) 
 
ByNATALIE HAUGHTON 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
SPOTLIGHT ON... 
Faye Levy
<TEXT>
<P>
   Age: 40-something.
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Cookbook author, food writer and cooking teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Food background: Levy grew up in a traditional Jewish family and
learned about Jewish food as part of her culture. However, it
wasn't until her college years in Israel that she started cooking
and experimenting with food. After graduating, she trained as a
chef and worked for six years at La Varenne cooking school in
Paris. When she returned to the United States, she began writing
free-lance food stories and developing recipes. She has written 21
cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking style: Mediterranean-Jewish (Sephardic) with an emphasis
on lots of vegetables and heathy cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite foods: Vegetables; vegetarian cuisine; French cuisine;
Mediterranean cuisine; chocolate; good bread.
</P>
<P>
   Most popular dish she makes: Cocoa Applesauce Cake With Honey
Ganache frosting.
</P>
<P>
   Secret food passion: Sweetbreads (the meat) and foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite thing to cook and eat: Homemade bread.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite cookbook: ``Le Guide Culinaire,'' by Auguste Escoffier
for French cooking; and ``The Kitchen Garden Cookbook,'' by Sylvia
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite restaurant: L'Auberge de L'Ill in Illhaeusern, France.
</P>
<P>
   Worst kitchen disaster: Before she learned how to cook, she
tried baking an eggplant without first pricking the skin. It
exploded making ``a scary noise and a mess of the oven.''
</P>
<P>
   Pet peeve: People who are rude for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   What does she do when not cooking?: She gardens and checks out
ethnic markets.
</P>
<P>
   If she could dine with anyone (current or in history) who would
it be?: Auguste Escoffier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-NAPSTER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     09-26 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-NAPSTER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... action: ``Dinosaurs.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No doubt, the tension must give at some point. ``It's an issue
that has to be dealt with,'' says Walter McDonough, a Boston
entertainment lawyer and director of business and legal research
for an advocacy group called the Future of Music Coalition. ``We
are obligated to work this out without impeding the growth of the
Web,'' McDonough says.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you make that happen when the content owners and the
technology companies are duking it out in court? McDonough suggests
there is a ``common sense solution'' similar to the compulsory
license system used by radio stations. Under this proposal,
Internet music companies would need compulsory licenses to stream
music online and the funds generated would go into a pool to be
redistributed to the record labels and music publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Some academics have pointed toward a more radical solution,
suggesting a tax and royalty system in which money is collected
through a tax on either the electronics needed to play digital
content or on Internet services needed to access such
entertainment. The money would be distributed to creators in
proportion to how frequently their materials are used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is conceivable that something as radical as that would be
necessary,'' says Fisher of Harvard. ``The effect of a dramatic
intervention of that sort would be to provide an alternative
revenue to creators.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have suggested that the music business will morph into a
service industry, with consumers paying for all-you-can-play
subscriptions in the same way they pay for cable television.
Meanwhile, the film industry has been talking about offering its
products online on a pay-per-view basis, but only when it finds a
way to protect the work from piracy. Technical experts contend,
however, that any protection system, no matter how sophisticated,
can eventually be cracked. ``It is important to recognize that
security isn't going to work,'' warns Sheirer of Forrester
Research.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the primary battlefield is in the courts. The
Napster appeal will be heard in court in the next few weeks, and
the Scour lawsuit has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle lines are beginning to blur as entertainment
companies merge with technology companies. If the AOL-Time-Warner
merger is completed, the nation's largest content provider will be
under the same umbrella as the country's largest Internet service
provider. Likewise, Sony finds itself in a strange position in the
Napster case: Its record division is a plaintiff in the case, but
as a member of the Consumer Electronics Association, its
electronics business effectively signed onto an amicus brief filed
in defense of Napster.
</P>
<P>
   These are strange times, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. The struggle for control over content gets
more intriguing every day. Back in March, Napster inventor Shawn
Fanning said he wrote the file-sharing software because he was
suffering from ennui during his short-lived tenure as a
Northeastern University student. ``I was bored,'' he said in a
Globe interview. ``I had some time.'' Today, the controversy is
anything but ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Patti Hartigan is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at hartigan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
