<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-CRIME-HN     09-26 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FRANCIS' NEWEST BOOK IS SHORT ON HORSES, LONG ON ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Also reviews on ``The PMS Outlaws,'' By Sharyn McCrumb;
and ``Texas Crime Chronicles,'' from the editors of the Texas
Monthly.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick Francis is published in Britain in the spring, then in the
fall in the United States. For years, I would find someone going to
Britain in the spring and beg them to bring me back the new Dick
Francis mystery. I would read it, then send it to my dad as part of
his Father's Day gift.
</P>
<P>
   This went on for about 10 years until my dad told me he really
didn't like Dick Francis, especially because he didn't like reading
about racehorses.
</P>
<P>
   It is the whole racing scene that makes me grab Francis' latest
as soon as it comes out. The more horses, jockeys, racetracks and
steeplechases, the more I like the book. Unfortunately for me,
``Shattered'' (G.P. Puntam's Sons, $25.95, 289 pages) only has
racing in the first chapter. Nevertheless, Francis is in top form
as a storyteller in ``Shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 31, 1999, glassblower Gerard Logan rides to the
Cheltenham races with his best friend, jockey Martin Stukely. In
the Coffee Forever Trophy race, Stukely's mount, Tallahassee, ahead
by seven lengths, ``lost his concentration, hit the roots of an
unyielding birch and turned a somersault over his rider, landing
his whole half-ton mass upside down with the saddle tree and his
withers crushing the rib cage of the man beneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Stukely dies en route to the hospital. About to leave the
racetrack, Stukely's valet, Eddie, rushes after Logan and hands him
Stukely's racing saddle. Eddie also gives him a package containing
a videotape that Stukely planned on giving Logan after the race.
Logan jams the package into one of the inside pockets of his
raincoat, returns to his glassblowing shop and works late into the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   After closing up shop, he places the bag containing the day's
earnings and the videotape on a counter. Before he can lock up,
Tallahassee's owner, Lloyd Baxter, shows up with a bottle of
Champagne and they drink a toast to Stukely's memory. When the
Millennium fireworks begin, Logan goes outside to watch. When he
returns, he finds Baxter unconscious on the floor and the money bag
and videotape missing.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Logan goes to visit Stukely's family and finds
they have all been rendered unconscious. Stukely's mother-in-law is
on the stairs, her chauffeur, Worthington, ``sprawled like a
drugged medieval guard dog at her feet.'' He finds Stukely's widow,
Bon-Bon, on the floor of the den. Then Logan is hit with a heavy
object and he too is unconscious on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   When they all regain consciousness, they find that every
videotape, VCR and TV set has been taken. When Logan gets home, he
finds that someone has broken in and stolen all his videotapes. A
few days later, masked men grab Logan outside his shop, demanding
that he give them the videotape. When he says he doesn't have it,
they begin beating him up. They flee when one of Logan's neighbors
shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Logan has no idea what is on the videotape, but he knows he must
find it before someone gets seriously hurt or even killed.
</P>
<P>
   Francis has created a crazy cast of intriguing heroes and
lowlifes spouting witty dialogue within a very complex plot.
``Shattered'' is vintage Dick Francis, even if it is short on
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``The PMS Outlaws.'' By Sharyn McCrumb. Ballantine Books. $24.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Sharyn McCrumb's latest cozy is a bit like having
English tea _ satisfying at the time, but not very lasting.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic anthropologist Elizabeth McPherson has just returned
from Scotland following the disappearance of her husband, believed
lost at sea. Depressed and unable to accept that he is dead, she
checks herself into the mental institution Cherry Tree, which her
family has considered its spa of preference for many decades. Her
depression doesn't improve, but she learns quickly that the
appearance of insanity allows you to be rude and say anything you
want.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her brother Bill and his partner, A.P. Hill, decide
their law office in Danville, Va., is in too shabby a part of town
to attract top-notch clients. Hill is headed for Richmond on
business, so it is up to Bill to find their new offices. What he
finds is an old mansion, big enough so they each can have
apartments on the second floor. The only drawback is that the man
who built the house still lives in the sun room and is so old Bill
can't evict him.
</P>
<P>
   When Hill gets to Richmond, she learns her law school rival,
P.J. Purdue, has broken one of her clients out of prison and the
two have gone on the lam, seducing men, stealing their cars,
clothes and wallets and moving on. The tabloids nickname them the
PMS Bandits.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, McCrumb makes it all come together as she moves between
the three disparate storylines, aided by some wickedly funny
dialogue. One of Elizabeth's fellow inmates who equates success
with beauty says: ``Anorexia is not a disease; it's a career
move.'' A nice little read for a football Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Crime Chronicles _ Outrageous True Stories of Murder and
Mayhem in the Lone Star State.'' From the Editors of the Texas
Monthly. Warner Books. 514 pages. $6.99 paperback.
</P>
<P>
   If you like true crime, some outrageous Texans and terrific
writing, this one's for you. All the articles have run in the Texas
Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   The first in this collection ran in 1975 and tells the
background of pit bull fighting in Texas. Another, titled ``I Loved
the Dapper Bandit,'' is told from a prostitute's view of her affair
with a man she did not know was a bank robber until he got caught
and tried to shoot himself in the head. Being a poor shot, he ended
up in a wheelchair and in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 story, ``Midnight in the Garden of East Texas,'' is a
tale of Bernie Tielde, a likable assistant funeral director who
befriends widows and becomes the sole companion of the town's
richest but nastiest widow.
</P>
<P>
   When she disappears for nine months, no one worries. When her
body is found in the bottom of her deep freezer with a bullet in
her back, no one is sorry. When Bernie confesses, almost everyone
in town thinks he should get off. Really a bizarre story.
</P>
<P>
   Other tales include the University of Texas sniper Charles
Whitman and the cheerleader mom who tried to kill her daughter's
rival.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible tales told by some marvelous writers. Check it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-FUTURE-BOS &LR;      09-26 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE NEXT NEW THING ON YOUR INTERNET DASHBOARD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL TORCHIA AND MATT CARROLL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past five years, the creative breeding ground of the
Internet has changed our lives with a dizzyingly long list of
innovations: browsing, e-mail, online auctions, day trading,
instant messaging, Napster. While not all consumers have used
everything, most have become dependent on at least one.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been an altogether smooth ride. People have thrown up
their hands in frustration after wandering in the Internet
wilderness searching for, say, the cheapest airline ticket. Or they
have cringed at the idea of handing over personal information to
anonymous online vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the problems that have spawned the next big thing on
the Net, one that is expected to give more power to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon: software applications that will search the Net for
you, comparison shopping for a used car, and taking into account
your desire for something with CD player and six cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   Another application will search out blue-chip stocks with solid
earnings that will appeal to your conservative financial views. And
a third will alert the local oil dealer with the best price around
that you are low on heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   These separate applications _ and others that collect specific
information on everything from stamp collecting to medical records
_ will be viewed through one overarching, personal ``dashboard''
that will display all the information that has been collected.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard program will also jealously protect a consumer's
personal and financial privacy by releasing just the data needed to
make a purchase, and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   These changes will flip the traditional business model on its
head. Until now, companies have told consumers what was available
and at what price. Now a customer's software will tell a company
what the consumer wants and what price the person is willing to
pay. Interested companies will need to scramble to fulfill that
need.
</P>
<P>
   Leverage will shift to a new type of proactive consumer _ a
``prosumer,'' perhaps? This consumer _ no longer locked into any
one particular company _ will be empowered to pick and choose based
on criteria they establish, and it will be up to companies to meet
it.
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces of this are available now and more are coming.
ByAllAccounts.com of Woburn, Mass., which was launched in July,
offers consumers a single place to monitor and analyze financial
data. The idea is to help individuals, who might have portfolios
with a half-dozen or more financial companies, pull that
information together, said L. Patrick Gardner, co-founder and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Users set up online accounts with the company, which collects
the information from the companies where the user keeps accounts.
The software offers tools to measure investment performance and can
send alerts when there are important changes.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like this allow consumers to gain more control. With
information centralized, consumers can more easily measure their
own financial health, as well as more easily measure the
performance of the financial institutions that are caring for
users' investments. Gardner sees this as just a start, and ``the
next step is to offer guidance or advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Another startup, VigilTech.com in Acton, Mass., has built
software that searches the Internet to provide desktop information
on specific topics to business users, said Gidi Cohen, founder and
chief executive officer. Users can create their own custom
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our technology takes input from the user and then adapts as it
scours the Internet, to provide information to the desktop on what
you need and want, when you need and want it,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have developed software that makes it easy for
buyers to comparison shop. Frictionless Commerce of Cambridge,
Mass. sells its software to sites such as Lycos.com, which uses it
in its comparison shopping section, said Robert H. Guttman,
co-founder and chief technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   The software can be used to find the best prices on everything
from car seats to laptops; from printers to in-line skates. ``We
have pieces of software that crawl the Web and find pieces of
information,'' Guttman said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is just the beginning. These companies, or new
companies, will push this concept into new directions. The end
result will be greater ease for users in finding what they need.
</P>
<P>
   Changes are also being driven by concerns about protecting
personal privacy. People have read about online thefts of credit
card numbers and the recent bankruptcy fight over Toysmart.com, in
which supposedly protected personal data about customers may be
tossed on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Pattie Maes, an associate professor at MIT's Media Lab, is
acutely aware of the concerns people have over protecting their
personal data. Maes founded Firefly Network Inc., which was one of
the first companies to commercialize technology for building
profiles of its users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it has to be the user that has control,'' she
said. While obstacles remain from legal to cultural, the time is
right for consumers to grab much greater control of their own data,
she said. ``It is a real need right now.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that personal profile data is sold to other
companies without your knowing it. There is no reason, she says,
that users should not be able to use their own data to negotiate
better deals.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, some of the new software fulfills old business
ideas called ``sense and respond.'' It's not an original online
idea. It is, for example, what oil companies have done for years by
counting degree days and thus knowing when to fill a customers'
tank before it is empty.
</P>
<P>
   But online companies can carry the idea a step further. What if
consumers didn't lock into one particular oil company? What if they
bought from whichever dealer happened to have the lowest price? And
what if this all happened automatically?
</P>
<P>
   That's the promise of the new era in software. Soon it will
suggest we transfer money to a new bank with higher interest rates
on CDs, look through our doctor's computer to get the results of
the latest lab test, get test scores from school, and maybe catch a
note from the baseball coach about how Junior needs to work on
ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   We're not quite there yet. But it's where smart consumer
companies are headed. They know that we, the consumers, want _ make
that, deserve _ the ultimate in customer experience. Smart
companies will work hard to find out exactly what consumers want,
educate them about their product or service, and then provide it
when asked. It's the next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Paul Torchia is a managing director for Scient Corp. in Cambridge.
Mass. Matt Carroll is a Globe reporter, and designed the
newspaper's first Intranet site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
