<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR AND ANGST ON THE TECH FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Santos was having a rough morning.
</P>
<P>
   Intel had just reported an earnings shortfall, and the Nasdaq
Composite index was crumbling. Santos's fund, the brand-new Putnam
Technology Fund, was taking its lumps, along with the rest of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   But Santos's basic optimism about technology wasn't dented at
all. ``When you invest in technology you are going to have periods
of fear and angst,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Santos's $180 million fund was launched in July, but he has been
investing in tech stocks for Putnam Investments since 1992. We
spoke with him to get his take on the current market.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's been hurting tech stocks this year?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: A few different things. We came into this year with some
very aggressive expectations for sales of wireless handsets. After
the second quarter, it became clear that demand was not going to be
as strong as anticipated. Sales are still going to be very healthy,
just not as strong as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you are still upbeat about wireless technology?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: We are still comfortable with the wireless story. The
market is just emerging for wireless data and wireless Internet
access. That should drive substantial demand for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How worried should we be about the bad news from Intel?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: The problem seems to be centered in Europe. The euro
could be affecting the market. In general, the corporate market for
personal computers in Europe has not reaccelerated in 2000. We
don't think there is a problem with global demand for personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of investor angst is the telecom sector. A lot of
carriers seem to be in real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   You have to make a clear distinction between the very large,
well-established telecom companies _ SBC, Verizon, WorldCom _ and
the emerging carriers. Right now, we are seeing a shakeout among
the emerging carriers. Every week, a company you never heard of
says it is running out of cash and it is going bankrupt. But I am
firmly convinced that the large players will continue to spend
money on equipment at a healthy rate. They cannot afford not to.
The competitive environment is only getting more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How about one more problem _ the slowing economy. Does it
matter to tech companies?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: Our position is that if the Fed slows the economy down
from a 5 percent growth rate to a 3 percent growth rate, tech
spending will be fine. If the economy slows a lot more than that,
we would be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK. We've hit a lot of negatives. What areas in technology do
you like?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: One area is networking. We like the blue-chip leader,
Cisco Systems, plus a number of other names: Juniper Networks,
Redback Networks, Nortel Networks, and Sycamore Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You didn't mention Lucent Technologies in that list.
</P>
<P>
   Santos: Lucent missed a significant product cycle. It is still a
high-quality company but it has a disadvantage to overcome. Time
will tell if it can do that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What else do you like?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: One of our major themes is software. Because of the
Internet, companies are Webifying their organizations, reaching out
to customers, lowering their costs, and enhancing service. It is a
clear and powerful trend in technology, and we are in the early
stages of it. Some of the names we like there are I2 Technologies,
Verisign, BEA Systems, and Art Technology Group.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Everyone seems to love the storage companies. Are you high on
that sector, as well?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: Yes. There is a tremendous need for data storage. There
are four key players in storage: EMC, Veritas, Network Appliance,
and Brocade Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some of the tech stocks you like trade at awfully high
valuations. Do you just ignore that?
</P>
<P>
   Santos: We don't ignore valuations, but we want to be focused on
companies that can continue to deliver earnings results above
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So your basic position on tech stocks is ``stay the course?''
</P>
<P>
   Santos: I have been investing in technology long enough to know
that longer term, the trends are overwhelmingly positive. That
doesn't mean we won't go through events like the Asian crisis and
Y2K that cause fear and angst. When you invest in a sector with
high valuations there will be periods when the market is robust and
periods when the market is skittish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
