<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVON OF CUBA ROUTS BENNETT OF U.S. IN HEAVYWEIGHT BOXING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT-OLY 1,2,3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Tuesday, the Sydney Olympic boxing
tournament got serious. Tuesday the quality fighters braced their
feet and threw punches with unfeigned malice. The medal rounds
await, and everything about the tournament has become a little
bigger, louder, faster.
</P>
<P>
   Little of this was good news for the U.S. boxers in the field.
Or those bounced from it _ a number that swelled to seven Tuesday.
Only one member of the U.S. team on Tuesday matched the increased
intensity that accompanied the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Clarence Vinson, who fought spectacularly in
defeating the reigning bantamweight world champion, Olteanu
George-Crinu of Romania, by 26-19 on points, the United States
would have been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. fighter, Michael Bennett, lost his bid to unseat the
famed Cuban heavyweight Felix Savon, who stopped Bennett on points
23-8 at the end of the third round. The U.S. middleweight Jeff Lacy
didn't get out of the third round either, losing on points to the
Russian Gaidarbek Gaidarbekov, 18-3. In the Olympics, bouts are
stopped if one fighter trails by 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   While two of three Americans were wilting Tuesday, the Cuban
boxing team continued its unrelenting march through the brackets.
Only 2 of 12 boxers from Cuba have lost, and Tuesday, five Cubans
advanced to the semifinals, including middleweight Jorge Gutierrez,
who won with a one-punch, first-round knockout.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The feature of the day was Savon against Bennett, a fight that
brought something of a title fight atmosphere to the arena. What
developed was an action-packed fight, one that seemed closer than
the judges' totals, although Savon clearly had a command of the
ring and a huge reach advantage on Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. boxing coach Tom Mustin, however, believed that Savon,
a six-time world champion, received points for his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judges gave Savon too many points for right hands that
landed on Bennett's arms and shoulders,'' Mustin said. ``I thought
the fight was getting closer and if it kept going, there would have
been a great fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when Savon throws that right, they just expect it to
land, so they score it. But Michael wasn't getting hit in the head.
At the end of the fight, one of the officials said Savon was the
one who looked hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Savon had forfeit his chance to face Bennett in last year's
world championship final, allowing Bennett a victory as a way of
protesting a controversial decision against a teammate earlier in
the competition, there had been at least some wonder if Bennett
couldn't challenge Cuba's nearly silent, mythic champ, who is now
33 years old.
</P>
<P>
   That Bennett, 29, has been fighting competitively for only two
years after having served seven years in jail for armed robbery
added intrigue to the bout. Certainly, Bennett did not figure to be
awed by Savon, a two-time defending Olympic heavyweight champion,
and indeed, he wasn't. Bennett fought aggressively from the
beginning, landing the fight's first punch, and continued to throw
lefts and rights even as he was being backed up.
</P>
<P>
   But at 6-feet-6{ inches, Savon was more than half a foot taller
than Bennett and he kept the American at arm's length for most of
the fight. And his right hand, one of the most famed weapons in
Olympic boxing history, scores points _ justly or not _ with
startling frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett did briefly stun Savon with a crisp right hand early in
the third round, but Savon kept piling up points, and just as the
round ended, the score was 23-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Savon was the better warrior today,'' Bennett said afterward.
``I did my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting inside Savon's reach was harder than he expected,
Bennett conceded. Bennett had also planned to avoid getting into a
slugfest, but he acknowledged that it's easier to talk about doing
it, harder to do it when your 6-6 opponent is hitting you every few
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Savon, as has been his custom throughout the Sydney Games, did
not speak with reporters afterward. He was unusually animated in
the ring, briefly taunting Bennett, and he left his corner after
the fight smiling and waving his arms at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Savon is now the runaway favorite to join the other great
heavyweight never to turn professional _ Cuba's Teofilo Stevenson _
as a three-time gold medal winner in the same boxing weight class
(91 kilograms).
</P>
<P>
   Fighting in 75-kilogram class, Lacy had knocked out one opponent
and stopped another in the second round, but Tuesday against
Gaidarbekov, a 24-year-old Russian with little international or
major competition experience, Lacy looked timid and overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited 54-kilogram quarterfinal, Vinson traded
combinations with George-Crinu across four lively rounds. Vinson
was cut across the bridge of his nose in the third round but
responded with punches in flurries that left George-Crinu's face
red and swollen, and in the end, a loser. George-Crinu, four years
older than the 22-year-old Vinson, appeared stronger and was
unyielding in his advances.
</P>
<P>
   But Vinson, who fought after Bennett and Lacy had lost, stood
his ground and threw dozens of punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hurt to see those guys lose,'' Vinson said. ``But
Michael Bennett came to me and said: `I fell off the ship, you've
got to handle it now.' And he was right. I needed a win and the
team needed a win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
