u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN &LR;      09-26 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT STEPS OVER THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first sounds over the radio are those of an excited
classroom. Then a rich (if slightly dissipated) baritone is heard:
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, OK, I need an easy question now. Hey, who's that little
fellow in the fourth row?''
</P>
<P>
   A proud young student pipes up: ``I'm Billy. Senator, where do
you stand on the privatization of at least a portion of a worker's
Social Security tax?''
</P>
<P>
   Senator: ``Oh, boy, that's right important to me, 'cause as you
can see I'm getting on in years. But aren't you a little young to
be worrying about something like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Billy: ``Not really, since studies show that the Social Security
system will be running a deficit by 2012 and will go bankrupt by
2034.''
</P>
<P>
   An announcer booms: ``With Microsoft Encarta Reference Suite
2001, learning has never been easier or more enjoyable. Combining
the rich content of a CD-ROM with the latest information from
carefully reviewed Web sites, Encarta immerses children in the most
engaging learning experience ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator: ``Well, it sounds like you really know your stuff,
little man!''
</P>
<P>
   Billy: ``Yeah, and so do people ages 18 to 34. Studies show that
they believe more in UFOs than in any chance they'll collect Social
Security benefits. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Senator, interrupting: ``Uh, don't you have soccer practice or
something to go to?
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ``Pick up your copy of Microsoft Encarta Suite . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the text of a commercial for a the digital encylopedia
that Microsoft Corp. bought some years ago and built on after
Encyclopaedia Britannica declined to become a partner.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial has been running recently in the Boston area
during sports talk shows and it is as revealing a detail as any on
which to dwell on the occasion of the 25th anniversary of
Microsoft's founding.
</P>
<P>
   Is the advertisement mistaken? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the dates are wrong. They are taken from an
outdated Trustees' Report; the current official guesstimates are
2015 and 2037. It's no big deal unless it's an encyclopedia you're
selling.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the concept of ``bankruptcy'' is deeply
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Even if no adjustments are made to the current schedule of
benefits and taxes _ if the Social Security surplus is indeed
exhausted by 2037 _ then current taxes still will cover 70 percent
of benefits in 2038. That's a shortfall, for sure. But it's hardly
a government bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Is the advertisement outrageous? Certainly it seems so to me.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the Social Security system is one of the two or
three central issues of the 2000 presidential campaign _ and
probably will remain at the center of politics for another dozen
years.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations fund advocacy groups to lobby against government
programs all the time. But it's rare, if not unheard of, for a big
company to take its political views directly to the public cloaked
in the authority of one of its products.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the audacity is typical. The government's recent
successful antitrust trial exposed a history of corporate misdeeds
that you wouldn't believe if you saw it on a television
cops-and-robbers show. Microsoft is trying to overturn the verdict,
by fair means and foul.
</P>
<P>
   Now those rich kids in Seattle are using their ``encyclopedia''
to attack Social Security. Goodness knows what other partisan
malarkey may be in that compendium of ``fact.''
</P>
<P>
   To judge from the ad, Microsoft wants to disassemble not just a
mainstay of the American social compact, but the wall of custom
that keeps business out of popular politics. It's time to send them
back to a little honest industrial competition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
