   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REDUCE GAS TAXES; RAISE TAXES ON DIRTIER ENERGY SOURCES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RETHINK-GAS-TAX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps something good has come out of the recent fuel crisis
after all. The protests over high oil prices during the past two
weeks are now forcing many European governments to rethink their
taxes on fuel. In America too, the threat of a winter heating-oil
crisis has led to a noisy debate over energy policy. In principle,
this is good news. These countries' confused energy-taxation
regimes need some serious scrutiny. But that, of course, is not
what is happening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIES IN LIMA: MORE DIRTY TRICKS FROM ALBERTO FUJIMORI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUJIMORI'S-FOLLY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in Latin America has democracy been more openly flouted
this year than in Peru. By standing for a third, constitutionally
dubious term after a decade in power, and then staging a deeply
flawed election, Alberto Fujimori succeeded only in dividing his
country and antagonizing the outside world, notably the United
States. So Fujimori's sudden call for fresh elections, this time
ruling himself out as a candidate, is welcome. It offers Peru the
chance to make the fresh democratic start it needs. Alas, there are
plenty of dangers and uncertainties ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
