<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-WARTIME-SLAVES-BOS &LR;      09-26 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARTIME-SLAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAVE LABOR COMPENSATION: A RUSSIAN-GERMAN FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ Mariana Ignaczak and Jan Belina have much in common.
Both are Polish, both are senior citizens, and both were forced to
work as slave laborers in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But as various courts and bureaucrats decide the degree to which
each has been victimized, and what they should get in return, one
important distinction emerges: Ignaczak was a slave in Nazi
Germany, Belina toiled in the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Ignaczak, 82, is eligible for as much as to $6,500 in
compensation from Germany, which has pledged to redress the crimes
committed by the Nazis. Belina, 74, has not received so much as an
apology from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans have recognized what they did and are paying the
victims. The Russians have recognized nothing,'' said Belina, who
spent six years in a Siberian labor camp.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since Communist rule ended, Poland has established
itself as a stable democracy. But this nation of 38.5 million has
also been forced to grapple with the ghosts of a brutal 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   About half the size of Texas, Poland sits between Russia and
Germany, in Europe's historical stomping ground, and has a long
history of being abused by its neighbors. In World War II, it was
subject to successive occupations by Germany and the Soviet Union.
And now, hundreds of thousands of ordinary people here, who
suffered under Nazi and Stalinist rule, want redress.
</P>
<P>
   The country has hundreds of thousands of victims like Ignaczak
and Belina. But sorting out who did what to whom, and who should
pay, has proven tricky. Germany, which has already paid $60 billion
in compensation for other war crimes, has now agreed to also pay
slave labor victims. Moscow, which sees its victory in World War II
as sacrosanct, will not even acknowledge the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question with compensation is how far should it go and
where it should end,'' said Konstanty Gebert, a Polish newspaper
columnist. ``My worry is that the whole bloody history of the 20th
century will be turned into one giant litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hitler and Stalin signed a secret treaty dividing up
Poland _ and Europe _ Nazi forces marched into Poland in 1939.
Soviet forces later attacked from the East, partitioning the
country into two occupied zones.
</P>
<P>
   Poles bravely resisted occupation _ and paid dearly. Some 6
million died at the hands of the Nazis, including 3 million Polish
Jews. To beef up its war machine, Germany also rounded up slave
laborers in countries it occupied. As many as 2.3 million of these
people are still alive, including 500,000 in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Soviets executed tens of thousands of
political, business and military leaders. The Soviets also deported
an estimated 1.5 million Poles, deemed not loyal enough to Moscow,
to labor camps. Most perished there, but about 100,000 are still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, Hitler reneged on his treaty with Stalin and took over
all of Poland _ and held it until the Soviets moved in, in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the German government, and corporations that
used forced labor during the war, established a fund to compensate
victims across Eastern Europe. In Poland, each slave laborer is
eligible to receive between $3,250 and $6,500.
</P>
<P>
   Among these is Ignaczak, who sat patiently in the Warsaw offices
of the Foundation for Polish-German Reconciliation, which is
handling the payments. She clutched at a stack of decades-old
photographs and documents as she waited to file her claim.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 the Nazis sent Ignaczak, then 22, to Germany to work on
a farm. For four years she worked 16-hour days, milking cows,
cleaning stables, and planting crops. She has suffered from a bad
back ever since. ``They treated the dogs better than they treated
us. When I got sick, they told me if I didn't want to work I could
go to a concentration camp.''
</P>
<P>
   No amount of money, she said, could make up for those years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my health and my youth. Nothing can give this back,''
she said, wiping away tears.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Belina, 74, sat in the offices of the
Siberian Union, an advocacy group representing Poles deported to
the Soviet gulag. Belina was 14 in April 1940 when bayonet-wielding
Soviet soldiers showed up at his home. They marched him, his
parents and brother onto a train bound for a Siberian labor camp.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't allowed to return to Poland until 1946. Belina's
father, a Polish diplomat, died of tuberculosis in Soviet
captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Belina and other gulag survivors say they would also like a
German-style settlement for their suffering. The group has written
former Russian President Boris Yeltsin demanding compensation from
Moscow, and petitioned the Polish government to support their
efforts _ all in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discussion has been going on for 10 years. We expect
nothing from Russia. They just say that their own citizens also
suffered under the communists,'' said Edward Duchnowski, who in
1940 was exiled to a Soviet labor camp at age 10. Duchnowski's
father was executed for refusing to renounce his Polish
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Jacek Sasin, director of Poland's Department of Veterans'
Affairs, said the Polish government adds $47 a month to gulag
survivors' pensions, and $238 a month to the pensions of those
whose health was severely damaged in Russian camps. ``Of course the
Russians should pay. What they did was similar to what the Germans
did,'' Sasin said. He added that the Polish goverment has raised
the matter with Moscow, which refuses to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Embassy in Poland said it was not Moscow's issue _
these days. ``This was done by the Soviet Union not by Russia,
which was only one of 15 republics in the USSR,'' said Pavel
Dyechenko, press attache for the Russian Embassy in Warsaw. He said
that anybody, including foreign nationals, who can prove that they
were repressed by Soviet authorities can request redress from
Moscow, but the requests are decided on an individual basis. He
could not provide information about any foreigners who have
received compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has tried to improve its relations with Warsaw. In April,
President Vladimir V. Putin telephoned his Polish counterpart,
President Aleksander Kwasniewski, and offered to assist in
investigating the execution in 1940 of 5,000 Polish army officers
by Stalin's secret police.
</P>
<P>
   Polish officials say they do not expect cash-strapped Russia to
offer a German-style settlement in the near future. But gulag
survivors say they would at least like an apology for the suffering
they endured. ``It isn't just the money,'' Belina said. ``It is a
question of our dignity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
