<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-RETHINK-GAS-TAX-ECONO     09-26 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETHINK-GAS-TAX-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDUCE GAS TAXES; RAISE TAXES ON DIRTIER ENERGY SOURCES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Perhaps something good has come out of the recent fuel crisis
after all. The protests over high oil prices over the past two
weeks are now forcing many European governments to rethink their
taxes on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In America too, the threat of a winter heating-oil crisis has
led to a noisy debate over energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, this is good news. These countries' confused
energy-taxation regimes need some serious scrutiny. But that, of
course, is not what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's governments are thinking only about how they can
respond to demands for lower gas prices without looking as though
they are giving in to blackmail or losing too much revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The French government made things awkward by caving in, and now
other governments are under pressure to follow suit. Should they do
so? Not right now, certainly. Such a move would send the wrong
signal to the throwers of bricks and the blockers of roads _ that,
as in France, street protests will be rewarded with speedy
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   It would also send the wrong message to OPEC _ that price hikes
will not result in lower consumption (as market forces would
dictate), because it can always count on governments to cut taxes
to reduce the price volatility that might hurt their economies. For
OPEC, then, there would be no downside to pushing up the price of
oil.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, however, those governments that tax gasoline
most heavily should think about bringing rates down _ but only as
part of a rethink of their energy-tax policies.
</P>
<P>
   Gas taxes are designed to achieve three things: to reduce
congestion, to reduce pollution and to raise money. They are not
much good at achieving two out of those three objectives.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, governments seem justified in using gas taxes
to tackle congestion. After all, guzzling gasoline leads to clogged
roads, and it seems to make sense to price fuel to reflect that
cost to society.
</P>
<P>
   The snag is that gas taxes are too blunt an instrument for the
task. Urban car use creates more congestion than rural car use, but
gas taxes do not distinguish between the two.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no public transport available, then gas taxes make
people poorer without changing their behavior. So piling on
ever-higher gas taxes as the main weapon to fight congestion makes
little sense.
</P>
<P>
   Road pricing, taxes on urban parking and other targeted measures
would be far better at tackling the traffic jams that occur at
particular times and in particular places.
</P>
<P>
   Greenery too seems an appropriate goal of gas taxation. That is
because cars produce local air pollution, which damages human
health and the environment, and also produce greenhouse gases,
which contribute to global warming. Congestion makes this worse, by
concentrating the polluters in a particular spot.
</P>
<P>
   Given these social costs, it seems reasonable to tax gasoline to
discourage its use. Yet taxes should be proportionate to the
problems caused _ and gas actually causes lower social costs than
some other fossil-fuels.
</P>
<P>
   A better way forward is a carbon tax, which penalizes dirtier
fuels like coal more than cleaner ones like natural gas. Yet, at
the moment, governments have got things exactly backwards: they
subsidize the filthiest fuel and put roadblocks in the way of the
cleanest.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Spain and Germany subsidize coal, while America grants
special exemptions to old coal-fired power stations so that they do
not have to meet emissions laws.
</P>
<P>
   Clean alternatives face regulatory and other obstacles, while
gasoline, which is less polluting than coal, attracts
disproportionately high taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gas taxes are certainly good at their third job _ raising money.
Road pricing or carbon taxes could replace some of that lost
revenue, but new taxes are always hard to impose, because those who
lose out oppose them and those who benefit keep quiet. Still,
current levels of fuel taxes are going to be hard to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   As they review their regimes in the light of their troubles,
governments may decide that the alternatives are economically
better, and politically no worse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2064 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RETHINK-GAS-TAX-ECONO     09-26 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETHINK-GAS-TAX-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDUCE GAS TAXES; RAISE TAXES ON DIRTIER ENERGY SOURCES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 700-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
