fuels like coal more than cleaner ones like natural gas. Yet, at
the moment, governments have got things exactly backwards: they
subsidize the filthiest fuel and put roadblocks in the way of the
cleanest.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Spain and Germany subsidize coal, while America grants
special exemptions to old coal-fired power stations so that they do
not have to meet emissions laws.
</P>
<P>
   Clean alternatives face regulatory and other obstacles, while
gasoline, which is less polluting than coal, attracts
disproportionately high taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gas taxes are certainly good at their third job _ raising money.
Road pricing or carbon taxes could replace some of that lost
revenue, but new taxes are always hard to impose, because those who
lose out oppose them and those who benefit keep quiet. Still,
current levels of fuel taxes are going to be hard to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   As they review their regimes in the light of their troubles,
governments may decide that the alternatives are economically
better, and politically no worse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2065 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FUJIMORI'S-FOLLY-ECON     09-26 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUJIMORI'S-FOLLY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIES IN LIMA: MORE DIRTY TRICKS FROM ALBERTO FUJIMORI  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 675-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Nowhere in Latin America has democracy been more openly flouted
this year than in Peru. By standing for a third, constitutionally
dubious, term after a decade in power, and then staging a deeply
flawed election, Alberto Fujimori succeeded only in dividing his
country and antagonizing the outside world, notably the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   So Fujimori's sudden call for fresh elections, this time ruling
himself out as a candidate, is welcome. It offers Peru the chance
to make the fresh democratic start that it needs. But there are
plenty of dangers and uncertainties ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It was always going to be a stretch for Fujimori to govern Peru
for another five years amid international opprobrium. Indeed, it
has taken less than two months of his new term for his regime to
hit a brick wall. Sorting out the wreckage could be tricky and will
take a lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori built his autocracy on the support of the armed forces.
In the shadows, Vladimiro Montesinos, a cashiered former army
captain, ran the powerful intelligence service, and exercised
political control: through threats and rewards, he ensured the
quiescence of Congress, the courts, the television stations and
most of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has become a political liability. First came a scandal
involving the sale of rifles from Peru to Colombia's guerrillas.
Then came the leaking last week of a videotape which showed
Montesinos offering $15,000 to an opposition congressman, one of
more than a dozen who have defected to the government.
</P>
<P>
   This provided irrefutable evidence of the corruption and
chicanery through which Fujimori's regime has clung to power, and
forced the president to announce that he would ``de-activate'' the
intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   Is Montesinos still in league with Fujimori, or plotting with
the generals to overthrow him? Either way, the fear is that the
army may try to prevent the holding of a genuinely democratic
election.
</P>
<P>
   As outsiders need to keep reminding them, the armed forces as an
institution ought to have no place in politics. Ideally, new
commanders should be appointed as soon as possible: the existing
ones are tainted by their dealings with Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Peru's opposition is right to insist that Montesinos
should be put on trial. But if that is to do much good, Peru also
needs an independent prosecution service and judiciary. All this
will take time.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Montesinos's removal could in itself help to create
some of the conditions for a genuinely free and fair election, by
allowing the media to operate with less state interference. The
discredited electoral authority, too, needs a radical overhaul and
a new boss.
</P>
<P>
   Can this be done quickly? Can it be done at all?
</P>
<P>
   Whether a fresh election is held within four months, as
Alejandro Toledo, the opposition leader, wants, or in March or May,
as ministers have suggested, is less important than creating the
democratic framework to ensure that the election this time is fair.
</P>
<P>
   In this, much still depends on Fujimori. But there are doubts as
to his authority, and his intentions. He has implied that he wishes
to return as president in 2006. Meanwhile he may be hoping to
retain power, perhaps even with Montesinos, after a cosmetic
election to install a crony.
</P>
<P>
   This week's events have shown how unstable Fujimori's regime has
become. Outsiders should do all they can to encourage a genuine
democratic transition in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, that requires a transitional administration, involving
both government and opposition leaders. Failing that, talks on
democratic reforms begun last month under the Organization of
American States (OAS) should move forward more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Transitions from authoritarian rule are invariably messy. At
best, Peru faces several months of instability. That is the price
of Fujimori's folly in trying to steal an election in order to
prolong his rule. But that price would be worth paying if the
result of the next election were a more democratic Peru. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
