<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-26 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIVE STARS FOR A PRIESTLY FILMMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two weeks ago, the Catholic Church and
filmmaking lost a smart and tender friend. The Rev. Ellwood E.
Kieser died in Los Angeles of colon cancer at the age of 71.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of a nonprofit movie company that is run by and
named for his clerical order _ Paulist Productions _ Kieser was a
television and film producer whose efforts brought him six Emmy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his finest hour was as executive producer of the 1989
feature film, ``Romero,'' which starred the late Raul Julia as El
Salvador's martyred archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romero'' isn't just a good religious, historical or political
movie; it is a very fine film.
</P>
<P>
   I met ``Bud'' Kieser (pronounced KYE-zer) in late-autumn 1996.
He and I both had brought bruised hearts to the Redwoods, an
isolated but healing Cistercian monastery near Northern
California's Lost Coast.
</P>
<P>
   My misery was caused by a doomed love affair. Kieser, a
lumbering, bespectacled man who stood 6-feet-7-inches, had been
wounded by some terrible reviews of his new movie, ``Entertaining
Angels: The Dorothy Day Story.''
</P>
<P>
   (Harbinger of ``West Wing'' successes to come, the film starred
Moira Kelly as Day and Martin Sheen as her mentor, the anarchist
and visionary Peter Maurin.)
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the dozen or so cloistered nuns and handful of
retreatants like me, Kieser said he felt as if he'd just watched a
child of his get attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Romero,'' Kieser and Paulist Productions had to scratch
and dig for every penny they got to shoot and distribute
``Entertaining Angels.'' Hardly based on a sure-fire box office
formula _ liberated, socialist single mom finds God and ministers
to the poor for 60 years _ the Day movie went almost immediately
into video release.
</P>
<P>
   After Kieser's talk, a puckish Trappist monk led me to the
monastery's library and pulled out a copy of Kieser's
autobiography, then-titled, ``Hollywood Priest.'' (It has since
been renamed ``The Spiritual Journey of a Show Business Priest.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie and TV stuff is interesting,'' he said, ``but the
really good part is the chapter called `Genevieve.'''
</P>
<P>
   The monk was right. The movie and TV stuff were interesting.
Especially Kieser's memories of his 23-year stint as the producer
of the television drama series, ``Insight.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the actors who worked in that message-based show were
Walter Matthau, Carol Burnett, Jane Wyman, Patty Duke and Bob
Newhart. During the 1979 season, a bearded, hippie-looking Martin
Sheen and comedian Flip Wilson took turns playing God.
</P>
<P>
   Equally interesting was Kieser's description of the filming of
``Romero,'' which ended in a wrap party and Mass for 350 cast and
crew members and their families. Raul Julia, who had deliberately
fallen away from the Catholic Church, was so spiritually touched,
he made his first confession in years and took communion from
Kieser.
</P>
<P>
   The monk was right about ``Genevieve,'' too.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional name for a nun Kieser met in 1964 and fell in love
with in 1967, Genevieve turned out to be the young priest's
crucible.
</P>
<P>
   Though never consummated, their love affair led to Genevieve
asking for dispensation from her vows and leaving her order. When
Kieser got to the same crossroads of choice, he could not follow
her.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``in the context of our love for each other I was coming
alive and becoming myself in a new and deeper way,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But then he asked himself (and God), ``Who is Bud Kieser?'' The
answer came back clear and strong:
</P>
<P>
   ``He is that unique human being who in the pit of his being has
been loved by God in a unique way, and who, from the pit of his
being, has tried to accept that love and respond to it. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``God had spoken in the depths of my soul, and He had invited me
to be a priest. And I, wanting to respond to His love, accepted his
invitation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Priest is the essential expression of my relationship with
God, and it is my essential way of relating to other people. It
constitutes my identity. I am essentially priest. Priest is who I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   And priest is who Bud Kieser stayed. In Hollywood, of all
places. Doing lunch, raising capital and making movies _ all for
love of the ultimate studio head.
</P>
<P>
   For his life's work, these are the reviews he deserves:
</P>
<P>
   Two thumbs-up!
</P>
<P>
   Bravo!
</P>
<P>
   Five stars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
