<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2070 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-AM`BUSH'ED?-ECONOMIST     09-26 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AM`BUSH'ED?-ECONOMIST-CORRECTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBYA STANDARDS: IS THE PRESS BEING TOO TOUGH ON GEORGE W.?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENT to correct headline typo)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 1,100-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ One of the good things about politicians is that you
can poke fun at them. Humor helps to puncture pomposity, alleviate
boredom and reconcile the governed to being bossed around. David
Letterman and Jay Leno are as essential to the political process as
the Brookings Institution and the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But can the mocking go too far? And can it become so one-sided
that it prejudices the election?
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, all the sniggering not only risks creating the
impression that George W. Bush is unfit for office _ which is going
too far _ but also of obscuring the real battlegrounds of the
election.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of good reasons to laugh at W. He comes from an
eccentric social class, where boys become head cheerleaders, grown
men are called things like Poppy and Prescott, and everybody ends
up as governor of some state or other.
</P>
<P>
   He has difficulty remembering the names of leaders of obscure
foreign countries like Pakistan. And he has an extraordinary talent
for mangling the English language.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just a matter of mangling words _ turning
``subliminal'' into ``subliminable'' or ``analysis'' into
``analyzation'' _ but also of mangling whole sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a man who maintains that ``we ought to make the pie
higher,'' and who knows ``how hard it is for you to put food on
your family.'' But are such Bushisms really so bad as to eclipse
everything else?
</P>
<P>
   Mangled syntax does not automatically denote stupidity. Bush
scored in the top 10 percent of the country in his SATs _ in the
same region as Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is high intelligence the most important qualification for
the presidency. Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton were both
intellectually outstanding; Ronald Reagan was not.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan was famously a great communicator. But some of the most
articulate politicians have had mediocre careers: think of Adlai
Stevenson and Herbert Hoover. And some of the most inarticulate
have been successes. George Bush senior, who suffers from exactly
the same tongue-twisting problem as his son, grows in stature.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower said things like, ``I do not engage in
personalities.'' Richard J. Daley, Chicago's greatest mayor (and,
incidentally, the father of Gore's campaign manager) was legendary
for verbal infelicities, such as his desire to see people ``reach
greater and greater platitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   What matters, surely, is Bush's record rather than his syntax.
Once again, he has certainly made mistakes, not least in choosing a
lame running mate and engaging in a futile debate about the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   His tax plan is a hard sell _ too generous to the rich and too
risky for an economy that is already operating at full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   And his decision to retool his campaign after Labor Day to
appeal to the great American middle class _ about 70 percent of the
population _ raises the question of who he was trying to appeal to
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   But these mistakes need to be weighed against four things. The
most obvious is that Bush has a respectable record as governor of
Texas. He can point to legitimate achievements, and not just in
cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Bush's instincts as a party manager are generally sound.
The only chance that the Republicans have of thriving in the long
term is to make themselves more open to minorities and immigrants.
This will clearly take time, and will involve some theatrics, like
the somewhat forced multiculturalism of the Republican Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But a Bush administration is likely to have both Colin Powell
and Condoleezza Rice in senior positions, giving blacks a higher
profile than they have in the current Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Bush has produced some bold policies. He has had the
courage to touch the ``third rail'' of American politics, Social
Security reform. He has also had the ingenuity to raid Democratic
think-tanks for ideas. And he is finally giving his disparate ideas
some coherence.
</P>
<P>
   He stands for markets against government, he argues, for
innovation against stasis, for using the surplus to create new
social services rather than just to patch up old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Spin, of course; but pretty good spin.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Bush is sailing against difficult winds. It is
exceedingly hard to unseat an incumbent in a time of peace and
unparalleled prosperity. It is particularly hard when the issues
favor the other side.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the Republicans won on issues like crime and the
Cold War; now they have to fight on health, education and Social
Security, where Democrats enjoy a double-digit lead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Bush being treated as a laughingstock? The Republicans
are quick to blame the liberal bias of the media.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of journalists voted for Clinton-Gore in
1996, and most strongly disapprove of Bush's positions on abortion
and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, John McCain's adjutant during the primaries, points
out that the Gore team has been ``playing the media like a
violin.'' Every time Bush tries to talk about the issues, the press
corps interrupts him with loud questions about trivia instead.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious rejoinder to this is that until recently the press's
main target for abuse was Gore, for reinventing himself as an alpha
male and dubbing illegal fund-raising ``community outreach.''
</P>
<P>
   Most journalists were surprised by how well Gore's snog 'n'
speech at the Democratic Convention went down with the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   The American media's main fault is that of the playground bully:
whoever is losing gets the bulk of the derision.
</P>
<P>
   Republican charges of bias will have more sting if the press
fails now to chase Gore for fabricating a story about the relative
prices of medicines being consumed by his dog and his mother-in-law
(hardly Pulitzer stuff, but surely a more egregious sin than Bush's
over-covered one of making an obscene reference to a hostile
journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   None of this should be taken as an apologia pro Bush. There are
plenty of good reasons to reject him as president, but not many
being considered by the American press at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, the election offers a choice between two
well-qualified, if not outstanding, candidates, and between two
contrasting philosophies, one rooted in the protective power of the
government, the other in the liberating effects of the market.
</P>
<P>
   A decent contest to get your teeth into. Unless of course you
are Bush, and you have to take your foot out of your mouth first. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
