<HEADER>
A2072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ADMIRAL-MEDITERRANEAN     09-26 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADMIRAL-MEDITERRANEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICE ADMIRAL TAKING COMMAND OF MEDITERRANEAN FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He grew up on a farm of potato fields and henhouses
in the northern tip of Maine, walking a mile to and from a one-room
schoolhouse, which had seven students in grades one through six.
Three were members of his family.
</P>
<P>
   From those beginnings, Gregory G. Johnson rose through the ranks
of the Navy, to the highest levels of the Pentagon, to his new job
this week in which he will be eyeballing President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a three-star vice admiral, left his position this week
as senior military assistant to Defense Secretary William S. Cohen
to take command of the Sixth Fleet, where he will oversee 15,000
sailors and Marines and 30 warships.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of assuming formal command on Friday at the home port of
Gaeta, Italy, as planned, Johnson will immediately face a test. He
is to fly to his command ship, the USS LaSalle, which has been put
on alert in the Mediterranean to monitor the aftermath of Sunday's
chaotic voting in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In case something goes very wrong following the elections, the
fleet _ soon to be Johnson's fleet _ will be poised to take a
variety of possible actions.
</P>
<P>
   He welcomes the challenge. He's happy just to be back at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 54, has spent 16 years at sea, about half the duration
of his marriage. His naval background is as an aviator, part of a
community known for its swagger, but that is not Johnson. His
aviator-given nickname is Grog, a handle that conjures images of
late-night drinking, but that is not him either.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the new commander of the Sixth Fleet, a man of
moderation, is to throw out the stereotypes of military officers
and see him through the lens of growing up in Maine, specifically
Westmanland, Maine, population 40, of having roots in land
purchased by his Swedish great-grandfather in the late 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a fanatic. I'm a zealot when it comes to Maine,'' he said
one night recently in Washington after returning from his 50-acre
salt farm in Harpswell, Maine. ``And beware of zealots.''
</P>
<P>
   In his one-room schoolhouse, Johnson and his late brother,
Warren, only 10 1/2 months younger, were the janitors, each earning
30 cents a day to bring in a bucket of water for drinking and
``washing the chalkboard, putting a scoop of lime in the latrines,
carrying in the wood, and getting the fire going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such chores, he said, helped prepare him for the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful thing about that community in Maine is several
circles of families embraced you, cared about you,'' he said. ``If
you did something that wasn't right, you not only let down your
immediate family, you let down your community family, let down your
church family, let down your 4-H family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You had all these different communities _ just like the
military is an ever-increasing circle of families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maine shaped who he is,'' said his daughter Ashley, 24, who
lives in Boston's North End. ``It made up his character. The same
hard work that allowed his parents to persevere up there is the
same work ethic that allowed him to climb the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a sense,'' said his other daughter, Sydney, 28, who
lives in Washington, ``he knows what his place is. A lot of people
out there _ and he loves to say this _ are a lot smarter than he
is. He is humbled by his past, and he lives that way. I don't think
he ever dreamed he would be where he is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, slightly taller than 6 feet, his posture erect, his
stride that of a long-legged distance runner that he is, now faces
a job that calls for substantial military and diplomatic skills.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has served as military assistant to the
former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman Colin Powell, former deputy
defense secretary John Hamre, and, for the past 16 months, Cohen.
It has been a highly unusual career path, one viewed by outsiders
as being one plum job after the other but seen by some inside the
Navy as being away too long from operational command.
</P>
<P>
   Working for Cohen _ a Bangor native, although the two met in the
Pentagon _ has been a selfless job, reviewing every classified
document for him, acting as liaison between Cohen and the armed
services, and briefing him on matters ranging from deployment
orders to heated interagency battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to act in a manner that leaves no footprints, no
fingerprints,'' he said. ``I have no agenda. I have the secretary's
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he must develop his own agenda. He faces multiple issues in
the Mediterranean, including Turkish-Greek relations, the future of
the disputed island of Cyprus, Israel's interaction with its Arab
neighbors, and the unpredictable Balkans _ starting on his first
day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be working 22-hour days and he's going to be on
professional pins and needles,'' said Hamre, now head of the Center
for Strategic and International Studies, a Washington think tank
that has long studied defense issues.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, when he lands on the USS LaSalle, carrying his
two nearly worn-out L.L. Bean tote bags, he must address those
under his command.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hamre: ``His big challenge is to convince people who don't
know him that he was the best commanding officer for the Sixth
Fleet, not that he was a political appointment. I think he'll take
care of that right away. If I could pick the perfect embodiment of
a military officer, I think it would be him.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the last year or so, even as he traveled around the
world with Cohen and worked long hours in the Pentagon, his life
wasn't all centered on military.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a decade, he and his wife, Joy, and their
two daughters lived in the same city.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been great is the small things; it's Greg coming home
from work, the kids being here for dinner,'' said Joy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   That time is over. The vice admiral and his wife leave Monday
for Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sadness, but we are ready to roll,'' said Joy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful year,'' said the vice admiral. ``But when
you grow up in a fairly cloistered corner of the world, you develop
a sense of adventure. It's something we didn't have. The Navy sort
of fills that itch. In Washington, you mature, you gather wisdom,
you learn diplomatic skills, but it's not like being out there.
That's where I want to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SOF-ART-NYT &LR;      09-26 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOF-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOFTBALL TEAM RALLIES TO CAPTURE GOLD MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT-OLY 9 through 15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ATTN: Calif.) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKTOWN, Australia _ Laura Berg saw the ball sailing, and the
Japanese left fielder, Shiori Koseki, straining. Halfway down the
first-base line, Berg realized Koseki would be there, in position.
She watched the glove go up, and the catch being made. Suddenly,
Koseki was falling, the ball dislodging as Koseki landed on her
back.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Jennifer McFalls was in full stride off second, and
Berg was watching the moment unfold, the gold medal moment. She
wanted to feel it, freeze it, because traumatic experience has
taught her that, ``You never know what comes from one moment to
another.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that way for the U.S. women's softball team here at the
Olympics, favored to defend its Atlanta gold medal, but having to
live on the edge, game to game, inning to inning. When the
Americans finally defeated Japan by 2-1 Tuesday night, they did it
with only one hit and the decisive play came in _ what else? _ an
extra inning, the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It was another tense duel that featured Lisa Fernandez, the iron
lady of the U.S. pitching staff. After shutting out Australia in
the semifinal the previous night, after exorcising home run demons
named Peta Edebone and Joanne Brown on the final two outs,
Fernandez knew she would not be likely to have her best stuff. Her
coach, Ralph Raymond, still told her, ``It's yours to win or
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's why Lisa Fernandez is who she is,'' Fernandez's
catcher, Stacey Nuveman, would say after Fernandez's three-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Japanese, who finished undefeated in the preliminary
round, listed their employment in the tournament media guide as
``office clerk,'' and they played with a neat and orderly
efficiency. They didn't surprise Raymond, the native of Worcester,
Mass., who looks weathered enough to have managed the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said back in June Japan would be the sleeper,'' he said.
``They've been getting better and better.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Their starting pitcher, 20-year-old Mariko Masubuchi, didn't
throw as hard as Fernandez, but mixed up her pitches well. Her
fielders made the plays. And the Japanese coaches, who know
Fernandez well from the years she has played professionally in
Japan, may have been stealing the early innings signals from
Nuveman.
</P>
<P>
   The American side became suspicious when Reika Utsugi led off
the visitors' fourth inning by sitting on a Fernandez changeup and
clocking a rising liner to deep center field. Berg, one of the
team's shorter players at 5 feet 7 inches, went back to time her
leap. The ball sailed on past her, though, over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I should have had it, and that I owed Lisa one,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   After winning 112 straight games, the Americans suffered through
a numbing scoring drought against the three other teams that would
make the medal round. They dropped three straight last week for the
first time in 35 years of international play. They were demoralized
by the time Edebone's two-run homer cleared the left-field fence
and gave Australia a 2-1 victory over Fernandez after Australian
hitters had been struck out 25 times over 12 and two-thirds
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Berg was one of the vocal players who snapped them out of it. A
25-year-old assistant coach at Fresno State, she had played on the
1996 team, when winning and losing was life and death. A year ago,
in August, she found out differently. She was home in Fresno, and
had just been dropped off by her fiance, Eric Kidd, after they had
watched a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The dreaded phone call soon came. Kidd had gone to a friend's
birthday party. He got involved in some horseplay, stumbled, and
hit his head as he fell backward. He broke two vertebrae and was
paralyzed from the chest down.
</P>
<P>
   They have remained engaged, but only after Berg insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it's not fair for me to have to take care of him,''
she said. ``It's a natural feeling for him to have but it doesn't
matter. We have our good days and our bad days but I love him
unconditionally.''
</P>
<P>
   She awoke Tuesday, believing it would be one of the best days.
Back in Las Vegas, where Kidd lives, it was still Sept. 25, his
33rd birthday. They have not seen each other since Valentine's Day
because of Berg's Olympic commitments. They spoke by phone, and he
told her to bring home the gold.
</P>
<P>
   That plan looked endangered with the United States being no-hit
into the fifth inning Tuesday night. With one out, Michele Smith
was hit by a pitch and took second on a ground out. Up came
Nuveman, who had hit the ball cleanly into right field her first
time up, only to be thrown out at first. This time, she compensated
for her catcher's speed, lacing the ball into the right-center gap,
all the way to the fence. She lumbered no further than first but
the game was tied.
</P>
<P>
   By the home eighth, with Fernandez in a groove, the Japanese had
changed pitchers, bringing in Juri Takayama, who was unscored on in
the tournament. It was raining now, the ball was slick and the
grass was wet. Takayama walked Nuveman on a close 3-2 pitch. With
one out, she also walked Dot Richardson, sending McFalls, the
pinch-runner for Nuveman, to second.
</P>
<P>
   With the winning run in scoring position, the outfield had to
play shallow. A lefty contact hitter, Berg was told by Raymond to
go ahead, take her healthiest cut. She lofted the twisting fly that
would fall into and out of Koseki's glove. Koseki would tearfully
explain that she misjudged the ball. Officially, it was ruled an
error, but to Berg, and to her U.S. teammates, the scoring of the
play was lost in celebration, in the rain that washed away last
week's failure and put them on the gold medal stand again. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
