<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAVE-BIZ-KENTUCKY-ECO     09-26 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVE-BIZ-KENTUCKY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY'S OLD CAVES GET A NEW LEASE ON LIFE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kentucky)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   HORSE CAVE AND PARK CITY, KY. _ More than 100 years ago, the
small town of Horse Cave became the second city in Kentucky to be
wired for electricity. It did this by harnessing the swooshing
waters of the Hidden River, an underground stream that briefly
opens to the sky in the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   After this great feat, Hidden River cave remained unused for
most of the 20th century _ except as a particularly nauseating open
sewer. Now, once again, it is the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, a small Virginia-based group, the American
Cave Conservation Association, came to town and started a
reclamation project. A new sewer was built.
</P>
<P>
   The town center now features a popular theatre, a folksy
bookshop-restaurant, an environmental museum devoted to caves _ and
the cave itself, now reached by a swooping staircase. Last year,
some 17,000 visitors trekked down into its cool, misty innards.
</P>
<P>
   Caves are once again becoming big business in central Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and 1930s, this part of the state was riven by a
``cave war'' _ a bitter and sometimes unscrupulous competition for
the dollars of passing motorists. Then, in 1941, the federal
government opened the Mammoth Cave National Park. It proved an
immediate hit: even today, it attracts 1.8 million visitors a year
and people are required to reserve a spot in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The fiercely independent cave-owners blame Mammoth for many of
their problems. Bill Austin, a fourth-generation cave-owner, still
rails at the National Park Service for forcing him to sell off a
portion of his cave land in 1961. He also complains with some
justification that the park charges far too little.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of his industry's woes have stemmed from other
things _ the blossoming of amusement parks, the advent of cheap air
travel, and the arrival of Interstate 65, which sped drivers from
Nashville to Louisville in air-conditioned cars, rather than
encouraging them to stop for a breather at a cave.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the caves have discovered a new lease of life _ as
environmental edutainment.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the tacky colored-light shows. Instead, the caves have
begun to sell themselves as places where a family can learn
together about geology and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not some cold fact in a science book,'' boasts Gary
Berdeaux, who recently bought and spruced up Diamond Caverns in
Park City. ``Things come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was in his 20s, Berdeaux successfully revived the
abandoned Endless Caverns in Virginia, both by opening them to
tourists and bottling their water for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he teamed up with four other cave-loving professional
couples to purchase Diamond Caverns from a big resort company. In
the past year, he has doubled traffic at Diamond Caverns and is
gunning for more.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Austin, Berdeaux maintains cordial relations with his
neighbor, the National Park Service (from whom he snares a sizeable
number of overflow visitors).
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the prior generation of cave-owners consisted of
``promoters,'' Berdeaux likes to talk about things like
``stewardship.'' This approach has won backing from the American
Cave Conservation Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, some people think that if you make a dollar off
the environment, it's a dirty dollar,'' argues its president, Dave
Foster. ``I think you can make that dollar and at the same time be
a preservationist.'' Just so long as there are no more smelly
sewers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0078 </DOCNO>
