A2077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-MENSWEAR-BOS &LR;      09-26 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MENSWEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN'S STYLES TAKE CUES FROM '80S LADIES LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Men aren't the only ones confused about what they
should be wearing. Fashion designers seem mixed up as well, showing
off spring collections last week that ranged from grass-stained
jeans (intentional) to cropped pants and shorts with suit jackets.
</P>
<P>
   For guys.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was a unifying theme to the otherwise disparate
designs: An overtly casual overlay, with neckties being one of the
few noticeably absent accessories during several days of heavily
accessorized productions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reinterpreting, say, khakis, designers seemed to be
scanning their sketch pads of women's clothes for inspiration from
the punk and disco eras, as well as more recent trends.
</P>
<P>
   One of the only complete men's suit ensembles came from Cynthia
Rowley, whose model, in a trim black jacket and pants, white dress
shirt, thin tie, and narrow-toed shoes, could have stepped off a
Joe Jackson album cover from the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow tie, while very new wave, also could have been a wink
to neckwear's shrinking importance in these days of business casual
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley also thought up the idea of jeans with grass stains or
flowers or bumbles bees stitched on them, often paired with campy
T-shirts with images of cats.
</P>
<P>
   Just as leather will be strong for women throughout the year,
designers relied heavily on the material for men.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Lang's collection, revealed in a stark white Chelsea
studio, was wrapped up in bondage references. Lang seemed to be
playing with the ideas of skin on skin and flesh tones by dressing
a model in leather boxer shorts that poked out of his
salmon-colored suit pants worn with nude-colored leather shoes.
</P>
<P>
   With his signature minimalistic style, the Viennese-bred
designer found a way to dress down suit jackets by mixing them with
unmatched pants and finely woven T-shirtlike tops.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Anna Sui's collection also incorporated leather and
relaxed looks for men. She showed a white leather coat over a black
stretch jersey tank with black leather pants. And she paired a
T-shirt with a white silk tuxedo jacket and black silk tuxedo
pants, as if to pronounce that no occasion is too dressy these days
to leave a tie behind.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors, whose show was heavy with earth tones (organically
named barley, sienna, heather, pueblo, and cornflower), displayed
ribbed muscle shirts under suit jackets and drawstring pajama pants
in suede, muslin, or striped cotton. A signature combination
comprised a canvas-backed suede jacket, a cashmere pullover, and
cotton twill shorts. Everything looked soft and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Kors, whose theme song ``Ride Like the Wind'' set the
driving-through-the-desert tone for his show, also used wide
leather belts on some of the men, but as more of a hippy reference
than an '80s one prominent among women's fashions throughout the
7th on 6th shows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A change for capri pants
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, capri pants became the item that propelled
ladies' warm weather fashions. But last spring, there was no such
fad, and retailers are still smarting from the season's clothing
bust.
</P>
<P>
   However, one designer decided to see if men would go for cropped
pants, too. Joop! (pronounced yope) showed off midcalf length white
cotton trousers, or slim striped ones with a floral design shirt.
One Joop! model also wore tight, hip-hugging swim trunks that
looked very old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking it to the streets
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A typical post-Fashion Week observer asks: Who wears this stuff?
The typical answer would be: Movie stars, especially those
populating the front rows of the shows; club kids; and those whose
jobs don't involve banks and courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   However, better questions might be: How will these fashions
translate on the street? What themes will be drawn from the
collections and reinterpreted? In other words, what knock-off looks
will Banana Republic or Urban Outfitters stock?
</P>
<P>
   The likely answer is that guys will see their pant legs narrow,
just like jacket lapels and ties, which are as much of a bellwether
for menswear as skirt lengths are for women.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores likely will be selling lots of jackets and
pants in suede and leather. And denim jackets and jeans _ often
with a twist _ will be wardrobe staples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
