<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 350-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; THREAT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, America: I gave you the Internet and I can take it
away.'' (Al Gore on the ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS,
Sept. 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JEWISH MOTHER OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``To my friends in the media: please be good to my son.''
(Marcia Lieberman, mother of the vice-presidential candidate, in a
note attached to a freebie-bag for journalists, Time, Sept. 25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOO MUCH INFORMATION: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is trying hard to show his lighter side to
reporters, ``inviting them to the back of his plane and regaling
them with tales of his honeymoon.'' (Washington Post, Sept. 16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOREIGN POLICY OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kofi Annan), your lease on Turtle Bay has run out. We want
the United Nations out of the United States by year's end. And if
you're having trouble leaving, we'll send up 10,000 Marines to help
you pack.'' (Pat Buchanan pledges the Reform Party to
internationalism at Bob Jones University, Sept. 18) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIP OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I care what 51 percent of the people think of me.'' (George W.
Bush, responding to Oprah Winfrey's question about whether he cares
about others' opinions. He also kissed her twice, thus eliminating
part of the Republican snog deficit. ABC, Sept. 19) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLEASE BACK DOWN: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Petty has asked the Bush campaign to stop using his song,
``I Won't Back Down,'' at campaign events. John Mellencamp and
Sting have also requested that the governor stop using their songs.
The Bush campaign currently favors ``We the People,'' which was
specially written for Bush by Billy Ray Cyrus, a country singer.
(Salon.com, Sept. 16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRECIOUS BABY: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Rick, let me be the first to offer him my support.''
(Hillary Rodham Clinton's spokesman, responding to a claim by Rick
Lazio, Republican senatorial candidate in New York, that media
criticism of his debating style is sexist. New York Times, Sept.
20) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
