<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-WRESTLING-NYT &LR;      09-26 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDLAND, LEGAL VICTOR, FINISHES SECOND ON THE MAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Matt Lindland's circuitous route to the
Olympic wrestling mat took him from the trials to the rulings of
arbitrators and into federal courtrooms. Back and forth the tussle
went over whether he or Matt Sieracki would be placed on the U.S.
Greco-Roman team. One day, Sieracki was the 167{-pound
representative. The next, it was Lindland.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the balding and goateed Lindland was the one to come
to Sydney, and Sieracki stayed home in Colorado. As if to justify
the wisdom of the federal judges who backed him, Lindland rolled
through his class, defeating Georgian, Algerian and Ukrainian
opponents to reach Tuesday night's gold medal match against Mourat
Kardanov of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Lindland's best maneuvers seemed to be left for his legal
fight and his 76-kilogram bouts before he met Kardanov, who won the
gold with a 3-0 shutout. In the bronze medal match, Marko
Yli-Hannuksela of Finland beat David Manukyan of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett Lowney of the United States took a surprise bronze medal
in the 97-kilogram (214-pound) class, defeating Thanos Konstantinos
of Greece, 3-1. Sweden's Mikael Ljungberg, a two-time world
champion who beat Lowney in the semifinals, won by 2-1 over David
Saldadze of Ukraine for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had a lot of talent and a lot of good shots at
medaling,'' Lowney said. ``The people who didn't think we had a
chance just weren't following Greco-Roman.''
</P>
<P>
   Kardanov dominated Lindland early, scoring a 1- point takedown
and a 2-point gut wrench in the first period. Then Kardanov totally
contained Lindland, frustrating him into inertia. They grasped at
each other's heads and shoulders, but Lindland rarely put himself
in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second period, Lindland was poised to turn Kardanov
but failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was who got on top early and got their turns when we
were dry,'' Lindland said afterward. ``The second period got
slippery'' with perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``He didn't want me to turn him. He was defending, and
it was wet out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Through an interpreter, Kardanov said: ``I was told he would be
tough to the last second and I based my defense on that. My main
task was to win this with my technique.''
</P>
<P>
   In Greco-Roman, no holds can be made below the hips, and the use
of legs is prohibited except for support.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland's resemblance to the actor John Malkovich is uncanny,
as is his brooding demeanor and unshakable confidence in his
talent. ``I got here because I'm a better wrestler than Keith is,''
he said, his silver medal dangling from his neck.
</P>
<P>
   At no time in his legal quest to make the Olympic team, he said,
did he expect to lose. ``It was well worth it because I was always
planning to wrestle in this tournament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland lost to Sieracki, 2-1, in the Olympic trials in June,
but protested that Sieracki had illegally tripped him. The United
States wrestling federation twice rejected his appeal, but an
arbitrator ordered a rematch, which Lindland won, 8-0. Sieracki
appealed to a second arbitrator, contending that he was not invited
to the first arbitration; this time, Sieracki's original victory
was upheld.
</P>
<P>
   But the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals eventually forced the
U.S. Olympic Committee, which was backing Sieracki, to name
Lindland to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all that put pressure on me, hopefully it helped my
performance,'' Lindland said. ``If there isn't enough pressure, it
doesn't seem important.'' Regarding his relationship with the
Olympic committee, he added, ``I'm sorry I had to get on the team
this way, but I think the best guy got on the team.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another U.S. wrestler, Rulon Gardner, is still alive in the
130-kilogram (286-pound) superheavyweight division. But the
unquestioned favorite on Wednesday is Aleksandr Karelin, the
three-time Olympic champion and member of the Russian Parliament,
who has never lost in international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Also in contention for a medal on Wednesday is Jim Gruenwald of
the United States in the 58-kilogram (127{-pound) class.
</P>
<P>
   The medal ceremony for the 54-kilogram (119-pound) class saw the
gold medalist, Sim Kwon Ho of South Korea, stand beside the bronze
medalist, Kang Yong Gyun of North Korea. The two nations,
technically at war, are joined as one team in the Olympics, and
marched together in the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   A modest cheering section of Koreans cheered for both wrestlers.
Sim said he got tips from the North Korean wrestlers about Lazaro
Rivas, of Cuba, in their gold medal match.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me the Cuban is pretty good and to be careful,'' he
said through an interpreter. ``When athletes play and practice
together, this is expected.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
