A2082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-BETHEL-BOS &LR;      09-26 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BETHEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETHEL HAS SERENITY, CHARM AND SPECTACULAR FOLIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, Maine _ There are already touches of color in the
countryside in this inland corner of Maine, just to the east of the
foothills of the White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The rows of sugar maples lining the village common are about to
turn scarlet and will stay that way deep into fall. The common,
with its classic white bandstand, will be abuzz with activity this
weekend as the focal point of the Bethel Harvest Fest.
</P>
<P>
   The annual festival kicks off the fall foliage season in a part
of New England where peak foliage comes a bit earlier than most
places and arrives with a brilliance that rivals anything to be
seen in the Berkshires, Vermont, or just over the mountains in New
Hampshire. The White Mountains are entirely in the Granite State,
of course, but the White Mountain National Forest straddles state
boundaries and extends deep into western Maine.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's festival on the common boasts a crafts fair,
logging competitions and demonstrations, chain saw sculpture, a
farmers' market, and even a chowder judging competition. The
gateways of the old houses around the common, and elsewhere in
town, are decorated with scarecrows, imaginative specters that in
the best upcountry Yankee tradition make creative use of such
seasonal materials as fallen leaves, corn husks, and pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   A town of 2,500, Bethel is a four-season resort that is busiest
in winter when the two local ski areas, Sunday River (Maine's
largest) and Mount Abram, are in full operation. Though winter is
the livelier time, many Bethelites much prefer autumn. ``This is
the best time of year,'' declares Melody Bonnema. ``The hiking is
fantastic, the colors are beautiful, and you aren't overwhelmed
with people.'' A potter whose kiln and showroom, Bonnema Potters
(207-824-2821), are on lower Main Street, Bonnema calls fall her
season of inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to go into the National Forest,'' she says, ``making
sketches and noticing the colors.'' The scenes and autumnal
shadings she sees and records on these trips eventually decorate
the colorful tiles, porcelain, and stoneware she displays and sells
in her shop.
</P>
<P>
   Other Main Street stores also carry distinctly local crafts. For
instance, Maine Line Products (207-824-2522) specializes in such
made-in-Maine gift items as wooden birdhouses, Maine woodsmen's
weather sticks (they droop when it's going to rain), and stuffed
moose toys.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely in the category of gifts for people who have
everything, however, are Maine Line's earrings and pendants made
from moose droppings. Gathered in midwinter, when moose chew bark
and twigs for sustenance, these polished droppings are said to be
99 percent wood. ``They look all right,'' notes one shopper, ``but
that 1 percent bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mount Mann Jewelers (207-824-3030), also on Main Street, Jim
Mann crafts jewelry, mostly using local stones, some of which he
mines himself.
</P>
<P>
   This part of Maine is surprisingly rich in semiprecious gem
stones, including tourmaline, amethyst, morganite, and aquamarine.
The region is home to both commercial mines and public areas where
amateur rock hunters are free to try their luck. The Crystal Cave,
in the basement of Mann's shop, is a dimly lit replica of a gem
mine where children can browse through bins of rocks and stones,
learning about geology and gemology the hands-on way.
</P>
<P>
   Although trekkers visit all summer, autumn is the height of the
local hiking season. ``This is when I do my hiking,'' says National
Forest ranger Mary Jo Kelly. ``It's cool now so you don't get all
sweaty when you climb and there aren't any bugs, which is nice.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular hikes are in the National Forest, which begins
about 5 miles from Bethel Village. The views from Evans Notch are
spectacular, and trails in Grafton Notch State Park lead to such
renowned scenic spots as Step Falls and Screw Auger Falls. Trail
maps and hiking information are available at the National Forest
ranger station on Route 2 in Bethel.
</P>
<P>
   One unusual hiking option is llama trekking. You do the
trekking, and llamas, the traditional beast of burden of the Andes,
carry backpacks and supplies. Llama treks of varying lengths are
offered by Telemark Inn (207-836-2703, www.telemarkinn.com), a
rustic lodge and former private sporting camp surrounded by the
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   An even easier way to reach a great view, including a glimpse of
the Presidential Range of the White Mountains, is to take the
Sunday River Ski Area chairlift to the top. Open year-round, Sunday
River (800-543-2754, www.sundayriver.com) has a mountain bike park
(rental bikes are available) and hosts special events such as a
crafts fair and fall festival Oct. 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   Canoeing and kayaking on the Androscoggin River, which flows
through Bethel, is another popular outdoor activity. Once badly
polluted by industrial waste from upriver paper mills, the river
has been cleaned up in the past decade and is once more a
recreational asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Androscoggin is a gorgeous river to paddle on now and one
of Maine's environmental success stories,'' says Jeff Parsons, who
operates the riverside Bethel Outdoor Adventure and Campground
(800-533-3607/207-824-4224, www.betheloutdooradventure.com) on
Mayville Road (Route 2). The outfit rents canoes, kayaks, and
bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a century ago the area's many opportunities for healthy
outdoor exercise helped transform Bethel from a sleepy lumber and
farming town into a resort community that attracted wealthy
health-seeking ``rusticators'' from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Gehring, a Cleveland physician, came here to recuperate
after he suffered a physical and mental breakdown. He credited
Bethel's serenity, natural beauty, and outdoor lifestyle with his
rapid and full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1895, he founded a pricey but innovative institute for
``nervous disorders'' that offered lots of fresh air, hard physical
activity, and good food (formal eight-course dinners were served
nightly). Grateful patients showered philanthropy on Bethel,
helping to found, among many other things, the Bethel Inn, which
opened its doors in 1913. Its golf course is located on land
cleared of trees by Gehring's patients, who paid handsomely for the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Rambling along one side of the common, the 98-room Bethel Inn
(800-654-0125, www.bethelinn.com) was long the town's social center
and remains the grande dame of local hostelries. However, there are
many other good places to stay in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Centrally located inns and B&AMP;Bs of note include the Victoria Inn
(888-774-1235, www.thevictoria-inn.com) on Main Street, a small inn
with high Victorian decor and a popular restaurant. Chapman Inn
(877-359-1498, www.chapmaninn.com) is a comfortable 10-room inn on
Broad Street. The very pleasant 16-room Sudbury Inn on Main Street
has a restaurant many consider the area's finest and a basement tap
room, the Suds Pub, known for its pizza and 26 beers on tap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2083 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-VOJISLAV-KOSTUNICA-EC     09-26 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOJISLAV-KOSTUNICA-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOJISLAV KOSTUNICA, THE SERBS' HOPEFUL ALTERNATIVE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: Timely for Sunday's Election, Serbia)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 850-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE 200-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750; 1,050 WORDS UNCUT.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A military adage holds that a man under fire will
show the best or the worst side of his character. Judged by that
standard, Vojislav Kostunica, the stolid law professor who is
leading the opinion polls in Yugoslavia's presidential race, comes
out rather well.
</P>
<P>
   In Mitrovica, the Serb stronghold in Kosovo, his appearance at
the hustings drew a hail of rotten tomatoes, potatoes and other
smelly vegetables. It was a well-organized provocation by
supporters of Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian strongman whose
bloody, 11-year reign he is trying to end.
</P>
<P>
   But Kostunica, sensing that his mettle was being tested, still
managed to get through most of his speech. Realizing that
association with the western forces that bombed his country last
year could be a kiss of death, he refrained from asking French
soldiers standing nearby to protect him; only when a stone hit his
face did his bodyguards pull him aside.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's unlikely champion of democracy, until recently a worthy
but obscure member of Belgrade's hard-pressed opposition, has
proved equally stoical in the face of a different sort of flak:
vitriolic personal attacks by the pro-Milosevic press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about Vojislav Kostunica is a lie,'' said one
paper, Politika, which called him a dull, narrow-minded pedant who
had falsified his family history and was so stiff he could be
wearing a bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these impediments, he was alleged to philander
compulsively with women under 25, and to share his house with 17
cats. About the dullness, the mudslingers may have a point; but
many Serbian voters feel they have had an overdose of charisma.
</P>
<P>
   In any case almost everyone, including Kostunica, agrees that he
will have to endure even heavier fire _ including, perhaps, the
literal kind _ before he has any hope of unseating the Yugoslav
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic machine, a network of loyal security chiefs,
sanctions-busting criminals and political apparatchiks, is unlikely
to yield power gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faced with the choice between holding on to power and a
war-crimes trial in The Hague, Milosevic will opt for the former,''
says Filip Vujanovic, prime minister of Montenegro, Serbia's
semi-detached partner in the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kostunica has questioned the legitimacy of the tribunal
at The Hague, refusing to give any promise that on becoming
president he would deliver his opponent into its tender care.
</P>
<P>
   But given the murky political traditions of Serbia, where power
has never changed hands by democratic means, a defeated Milosevic
could face an even worse fate at the hands of his fellow Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   If the poll were fair, opinion surveys suggest that Kostunica
would win at least a third of the vote in the first round on Sept.
24, while the president could hope for no more than a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Vojislav Mihailovic, a second opposition candidate, may garner
up to 10 percent in round one but will urge his supporters to back
Kostunica in round two, scheduled for Oct. 8. But nobody expects it
will be that simple; the runoff may never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the best guess is that within a couple of hours of the
polling stations closing, Milosevic will claim victory, however
people vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica and the coalition of 18 parties which back him will
probably do the same. Then predictions become even shakier.
</P>
<P>
   The final outcome might be determined by street demonstrations,
the loyalty of the security forces, or by the calculations of
Milosevic's ruthless inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the election, General Nebojsa Pavkovic, the head
of a Yugoslav army whose senior ranks have been thoroughly purged
by Milosevic, gave an ominous pledge that his troops would prevent
any move by the opposition to ``take power in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But would they? While Serbia's well-armed police have always
been a pliant instrument of the regime, the loyalties of the middle
and lower ranks of the army are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In any showdown, Kostunica may have some appeal to Yugoslavia's
battered servicemen. In campaign speeches, he has insisted that the
army fought honorably in Kosovo last year and stridently denounced
NATO's air war.
</P>
<P>
   His complaint against Milosevic is that he provoked the western
alliance to intervene and then abandoned the Serbs in Kosovo to
revenge attacks by the province's Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   This, as Kostunica and others have observed, was a repetition of
the Serb bully's behavior during the Croatian and Bosnian wars:
first, provoke unspeakable ethnic violence, then leave the ethnic
Serbs to their fate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (200-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, too, can claim to have behaved consistently over the
years _ in a better sense. At the age of 30, in 1974, he lost his
job as a law lecturer because he opposed political changes designed
to decentralize communist Yugoslavia and to devolve power to the
republics and provinces.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, with Yugoslavia still under Marxist control, he
stuck his neck out by demanding a multi-party system. Then, in
1989, he helped create such a system, by co-founding the small
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, he supported the cause of the Serbs in
that republic but kept his distance from their leader, another
war-crimes suspect, Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   He fell out on various matters of principle with Zoran Djindjic
and Vuk Draskovic, Serbia's more prominent opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the Serb-nationalist strongholds of Montenegro,
where Milosevic got a rave reception this week, Kostunica is
respected for being straight.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it is much to his advantage that he is not
identified with Milosevic's better-known foes at home. These have
become easy meat for Serbian government propagandists by hobnobbing
with the likes of Madeleine Albright, America's secretary of state,
seen as an architect of last year's air attacks on Serbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   But given that Kostunica is so stern a critic of NATO policy,
why are western governments putting so much faith in him?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that, though they know he would fight the Serb
corner in a tough and consistent way, he would abide by his
commitment to democracy and law _ and eschew Milosevic's tactics of
stirring up ethnic hatred and terror.
</P>
<P>
   That alone would be a huge improvement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
