<SLUG> BC-VOJISLAV-KOSTUNICA-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOJISLAV KOSTUNICA, THE SERBS' HOPEFUL ALTERNATIVE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 850-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE 200-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750; 1,050 WORDS UNCUT.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A military adage holds that a man under fire will
show the best or the worst side of his character. Judged by that
standard, Vojislav Kostunica, the stolid law professor who is
leading the opinion polls in Yugoslavia's presidential race, comes
out rather well.
</P>
<P>
   In Mitrovica, the Serb stronghold in Kosovo, his appearance at
the hustings drew a hail of rotten tomatoes, potatoes and other
smelly vegetables. It was a well-organized provocation by
supporters of Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian strongman whose
bloody, 11-year reign he is trying to end.
</P>
<P>
   But Kostunica, sensing that his mettle was being tested, still
managed to get through most of his speech. Realizing that
association with the western forces that bombed his country last
year could be a kiss of death, he refrained from asking French
soldiers standing nearby to protect him; only when a stone hit his
face did his bodyguards pull him aside.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's unlikely champion of democracy, until recently a worthy
but obscure member of Belgrade's hard-pressed opposition, has
proved equally stoical in the face of a different sort of flak:
vitriolic personal attacks by the pro-Milosevic press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about Vojislav Kostunica is a lie,'' said one
paper, Politika, which called him a dull, narrow-minded pedant who
had falsified his family history and was so stiff he could be
wearing a bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these impediments, he was alleged to philander
compulsively with women under 25, and to share his house with 17
cats. About the dullness, the mudslingers may have a point; but
many Serbian voters feel they have had an overdose of charisma.
</P>
<P>
   In any case almost everyone, including Kostunica, agrees that he
will have to endure even heavier fire _ including, perhaps, the
literal kind _ before he has any hope of unseating the Yugoslav
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic machine, a network of loyal security chiefs,
sanctions-busting criminals and political apparatchiks, is unlikely
to yield power gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faced with the choice between holding on to power and a
war-crimes trial in The Hague, Milosevic will opt for the former,''
says Filip Vujanovic, prime minister of Montenegro, Serbia's
semi-detached partner in the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kostunica has questioned the legitimacy of the tribunal
at The Hague, refusing to give any promise that on becoming
president he would deliver his opponent into its tender care.
</P>
<P>
   But given the murky political traditions of Serbia, where power
has never changed hands by democratic means, a defeated Milosevic
could face an even worse fate at the hands of his fellow Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   If the poll were fair, opinion surveys suggest that Kostunica
would win at least a third of the vote in the first round on Sept.
24, while the president could hope for no more than a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Vojislav Mihailovic, a second opposition candidate, may garner
up to 10 percent in round one but will urge his supporters to back
Kostunica in round two, scheduled for Oct. 8. But nobody expects it
will be that simple; the runoff may never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the best guess is that within a couple of hours of the
polling stations closing, Milosevic will claim victory, however
people vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica and the coalition of 18 parties which back him will
probably do the same. Then predictions become even shakier.
</P>
<P>
   The final outcome might be determined by street demonstrations,
the loyalty of the security forces, or by the calculations of
Milosevic's ruthless inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the election, General Nebojsa Pavkovic, the head
of a Yugoslav army whose senior ranks have been thoroughly purged
by Milosevic, gave an ominous pledge that his troops would prevent
any move by the opposition to ``take power in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But would they? While Serbia's well-armed police have always
been a pliant instrument of the regime, the loyalties of the middle
and lower ranks of the army are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In any showdown, Kostunica may have some appeal to Yugoslavia's
battered servicemen. In campaign speeches, he has insisted that the
army fought honorably in Kosovo last year and stridently denounced
NATO's air war.
</P>
<P>
   His complaint against Milosevic is that he provoked the western
alliance to intervene and then abandoned the Serbs in Kosovo to
revenge attacks by the province's Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   This, as Kostunica and others have observed, was a repetition of
the Serb bully's behavior during the Croatian and Bosnian wars:
first, provoke unspeakable ethnic violence, then leave the ethnic
Serbs to their fate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (200-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, too, can claim to have behaved consistently over the
years _ in a better sense. At the age of 30, in 1974, he lost his
job as a law lecturer because he opposed political changes designed
to decentralize communist Yugoslavia and to devolve power to the
republics and provinces.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, with Yugoslavia still under Marxist control, he
stuck his neck out by demanding a multi-party system. Then, in
1989, he helped create such a system, by co-founding the small
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, he supported the cause of the Serbs in
that republic but kept his distance from their leader, another
war-crimes suspect, Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   He fell out on various matters of principle with Zoran Djindjic
and Vuk Draskovic, Serbia's more prominent opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the Serb-nationalist strongholds of Montenegro,
where Milosevic got a rave reception this week, Kostunica is
respected for being straight.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it is much to his advantage that he is not
identified with Milosevic's better-known foes at home. These have
become easy meat for Serbian government propagandists by hobnobbing
with the likes of Madeleine Albright, America's secretary of state,
seen as an architect of last year's air attacks on Serbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   But given that Kostunica is so stern a critic of NATO policy,
why are western governments putting so much faith in him?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that, though they know he would fight the Serb
corner in a tough and consistent way, he would abide by his
commitment to democracy and law _ and eschew Milosevic's tactics of
stirring up ethnic hatred and terror.
</P>
<P>
   That alone would be a huge improvement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
