<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-LEE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI
Director Louis Freeh defend their handling of the case against Wen
Ho Lee, saying the nuclear scientist who pleaded guilty to a charge
of violating security is ``no hero or absent-minded professor.''
Freeh said the government could have proven more serious
allegations against Lee if it had taken the case to trial, but that
national security concerns pushed prosecutors to accept a plea
bargain. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION-STATES (Washington) _ Seventy-five years after the
Scopes ``Monkey Trial,'' a report concludes that more than
one-third of the states are doing an abysmal job of teaching
evolution, with 12 receiving an ``F.'' Ten states never use the
word ``evolution'' in science standards. One state _ Kansas _
deletes all references to the age of Earth or universe, including
radioactive decay. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ACCUSED-SPY (Washington) _ After nearly a year of confinement, a
U.S. sailor is expected to be formally arraigned Wednesday in a
military court, accused of giving the Russians secrets about the
U.S. submarine fleet. Petty Officer 1st Class Daniel King, an
intelligence analyst who is being held in the U.S. Marine Corps
brig at Quantico, Va., faces one count of espionage and two counts
of improperly disclosing classified information. He could receive
the death penalty if convicted. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ Republican George W. Bush and
Democrat Al Gore clash over rival plans to strengthen education and
overhaul Medicare as they limber up for the presidential debates
with televised question-and-answer sessions. Gore, campaigning in
Michigan, fields questions from young people on a town hall meeting
staged by the Music Television cable network. Bush, pressing his
effort in California, fields questions from CNN talk show host
Larry King. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTE (Washington) _ NARAL, a leading advocacy organization
for abortion rights, launches a $5-million, 15-state campaign to
persuade independent and Republican voters who favor abortion
rights to support Democrat Al Gore for president. By JENNIFER A.
DLOUHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Stem cells extracted from human
embryos have become the center of a bitter political debate that
pits victims of Parkinson's disease, diabetes and other serious
illnesses against anti-abortion activists. The Senate is
considering a bill to expand stem cell research following certain
ethical guidelines. In August Congress lifted a ban on such
research, which scientists believe could lead to cures for many
diseases. Texas Gov. George W. Bush would reinstate the ban despite
a campaign pledge to accelerate other medical research. Vice
President Gore supports the Senate bill. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
