<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-MEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN DEFEATS U.S. IN SOCCER, 3-1 ; WILL MEET CAMEROON FOR GOLD
MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT-OLY 6,7 and 8 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The unimagined has become almost a
necessity. Having lost to Spain, 3-1, in the semifinals Tuesday
night, the United States wants to bring back a medal from the
Olympic soccer competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be disappointing if we didn't win one,'' said Josh
Wolff, the forward from the Chicago Fire, after the United States
was e stunned early by the offensive aggression of the Spaniards.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a medal to feel good about this excursion was hardly a
position the Yanks could afford to take when they arrived here
early in the month. They raised expectations by winning their group
and then beating Japan in the quarterfinal round, already the
farthest any U.S. men's team has gone in the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Now they must play Chile, a tough squad that lost, 2-1, on a
questionable penalty call against Cameroon Tuesday night in
Melbourne. The United States and Chile will play here Friday night.
On Thursday evening, the U.S. women will defend their Olympic
championship against their traditional rival, Norway, also here, at
5 p.m. Cameroon and Spain will meet for the gold Saturday night in
Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night the Americans were outclassed early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a yard off,'' said Clive Charles, the U.S. coach who
played at the top level in his native England and totally
understands just how big a yard is in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Spain came out smoking, sparked by Jose Mari Romero, a 6-foot
21-year-old forward who was sold by Atletico Madrid to AC Milan
last December.
</P>
<P>
   In the 17th minute Tuesday night, Romero bolted down the right
sideline, turned the corner and fired a perfect low cross, which
Raul Tamudo of Espanyol Barcelona guided home with a sliding shot.
</P>
<P>
   Eight minutes later, Romero was the key man in a second Spanish
goal. The defender, Ivan Amaya of Atletico Madrid, lofted a ball
from the right side. Romero went up for it while his marker, Dan
Califf of the Los Angeles Galaxy, slipped on the wet grass. Romero
controlled the ball near the biceps of his right arm _ a hand-ball
foul if the referee had seen it _ and the ball plopped down neatly
at his feet. He flicked a pass to Miguel Angulo of Valencia, who
had no problem tapping the ball past Brad Friedel, the reserve
goalkeeper from Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   Admiring Romero's offense was Wolff, who is more opportunistic
than most U.S. forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize the stage you're on,'' Wolff said later. ``You
only get two or three scoring chances a game, and you have to
convert them. They're good at that. They are so talented, and they
interact. They're all on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniards had a 2-0 lead because they showed a sense of
privilege. At the 31st minute, Chris Albright of D.C. United, could
not pull the trigger on a centering pass from Wolff. Eight minutes
later, Charles removed Albright and Ramiro Corrales of the
MetroStars to get more offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You show the other team what your tactics are before halftime,
which gives them time to adjust,'' Charles said. ``But we had to do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The move paid off, as many of Charles' moves have. In the 41st
minute, Frankie Hejduk of Bayer Leverkusen in Germany collided with
Angulo in the penalty box. It was the kind of foul a referee might
not call in a tie game, but here he called it. Peter Vagenas, the
self-designated penalty kicker from the Galaxy, calmly whacked the
ball into the corner, and the margin was cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half, Spain played more conservatively than
some of its World Cup teams have done with a lead. The United
States threw some elbows but not to much avail.
</P>
<P>
   In the 87th minute, Friedel made a two-handed punch save, only
to have Romero lurking in goalmouth for the easy rebound and the
3-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the United States was not pushed around the
field the way the 1990 and 1998 World Cup squads were in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've closed the gap,'' Charles said. ``We've played European
teams. We've played everybody. The gap is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is making good progress,'' Inaki Saez Ruiz,
the Spanish coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, progress is not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never won a medal,'' said Chad McCarty of D.C. United,
the defender with the red goatee. ``Every one of us wants to win
one. It's been great so far. Every game, more and more people back
in the States are paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   After the respective gold and bronze medal games, the players
from these two squads will return to their teams, the Spanish
players to major European teams, the Americans mostly to Major
League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be all right without a medal,'' said Wolff, whose Chicago
team is about to begin a playoff series with the MetroStars. ``But
a medal would be a tangible to take back with us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
