<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     09-26 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING, PRAYING IN EQUAL PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It has come down to this for the Patriots. It has come
down to a wing (Drew Bledsoe's) and a prayer (Lawyer Milloy's).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to catch it,'' the Patriots' iron-tough safety
was saying softly late Sunday afternoon, not long after he watched
Bledsoe loft a pass in the direction of tight end Eric Bjornson on
what is aptly called a fade route. Generally it's called that
because the receiver fades toward the corner up the sideline and
the quarterback tries to drop the ball over the defender and into
his hands. It is a delicate throw, a touch pass based on timing and
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   However, it could be called a fade route today because that's
what the Patriots have done this season in such situations. They've
faded out of sight on plays just like that one.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that, as the football spiraled toward Bjornson, Milloy
watched and waited. Watched and waited and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted our guy, for once, to come down with the ball,''
Milloy said. ``I was praying to God, `Please let this one bounce
our way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   God didn't because God isn't all that concerned about the
outcome of football games, even NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, neither did Miami cornerback Patrick Surtain,
who held up Bjornson at the line of scrimmage just long enough so
that the tight end couldn't get to the spot he was supposed to get
to when the ball was thrown. Bjornson, frankly, also was interfered
with later in the pattern, but why talk about that? When you're
0-4, you don't get those calls at the end of a game against a team
that's 3-1, and you don't get those calls on the road in the NFL
most of the time regardless of your record.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, if you get off the line of scrimmage clean on that
play and don't let a shrimp of a corner like Surtain get his hands
on you in the first place, it's not an issue. It's a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no touchdown and no divine intervention at the end
of Sunday's 10-3 loss, and that's how it's been at the end of all
four of the Patriots' losses. Passes uncaught (or not even thrown)
and prayers unanswered. Considering where they're headed this
Sunday, a repeat of that scenario would be considered a victory
because at the worst of times these Patriots, losers of 10 of their
last 12 games, are headed to Denver, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   It is bad enough that they will be facing an angry Broncos team
that thought it had the Kansas City Chiefs beaten Sunday only to
blow a lead and an opportunity to reassert themselves in the AFC
West. Bad enough that the Broncos are likely to have running back
Terrell Davis and quarterback Brian Griese back. Bad enough to be
on the road at all, but that is not the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that the last time the Patriots won in Denver,
Lyndon Johnson was president. That is a long time ago, but then
again, it feels like a long time ago since these Patriots have
beaten anybody worth talking about, so the Denver jinx is the least
of their worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys understand why we're losing,'' Bledsoe said. ``I
don't see a lack of effort. We're simply doing the wrong thing at
the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they are. They are doing the wrong thing or nothing at
the worst of times because they are not yet good enough to do
anything else. Eventually, if this group does not implode mentally,
it will begin to do the right things once in a while. Then, when
their personnel gets better, they will do more things right than
they do wrong when it counts and they will win.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen often this season because they simply do not
have enough talent. What they do have is enough talent to lose
closely, as they have done time and time again. They have lost
because their margin of error is zero.
</P>
<P>
   They are not losing because they aren't working hard or being
well coached or being run ably by their quarterback. They are
losing because they are not quite good enough to make the plays you
need to make at the moments you need to make them.
</P>
<P>
   Two examples of the problem involve not two of the Patriots'
worst players but two of their best: Troy Brown and Kevin Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is one of the best slot receivers around, a solid
third-down receiver who can make plays that move the chains. But
because they have no second receiver worth playing, their third
receiver is now playing in situations that weaken the Patriots in
two spots instead of strengthening them in one. Not because Brown
is lacking but because guys like Tony Simmons end up getting 8
yards on third down when they need 9, something Brown has seldom
been guilty of.
</P>
<P>
   Then you have a good young third-down back, Faulk, playing every
down. Faulk has done a good job for the most part, but when he
fumbled Sunday on the goal line, it was typical of the problem head
coach Bill Belichick is faced with. Faulk is not the back to be in
on such a situation very often. If he were a goal line runner, he
would know the simplest rule of that trade: stay low.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk has seldom played in that situation and wouldn't be in it
now if the Patriots had a true lead back. Because of his
unfamiliarity with the job, Faulk didn't go low through what
appeared to be a gaping hole in Miami's defense; he went high and
got hammered by safety Brian Walker and fumbled in a situation in
which he normally wouldn't have even been given the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Until such personnel matters can be rectified _ and it won't be
this season _ all that Patriot fans can hope for is that the team
continues to play hard, continues to keep games close and,
eventually, makes a play or two when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, that may not come until late in the season, as it did
in 1993, when the Patriots started 0-4 under a new coach named Bill
Parcells but finished with a rush to go 5-11. That team lacked
talent, as does this one. That team had to learn how to win, as
does this one.
</P>
<P>
   That team finally figured it out, as will this one.
</P>
<P>
   They figured it out when the talent got better. It's the same
story this year. Until then, prayer can't hurt, whether God is a
football fan or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
