u a BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      09-26 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN GAS GIVE YOU HEADACHES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Having suffered from headaches throughout my life, I disagree
with specialists that say they are caused by eye or neck muscle
strain. Since they are used every day the same way. I believe
headaches are caused by trapped gas within the body and are
effected by weather pressures. What's your take on this? Do you
know if any studies have been done on how body gasses, that build
up or might be trapped within the body, affect the body.
</P>
<P>
   P.C., Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are many reasons for having a headache, ranging from
purely psychosomatic headaches (i.e., it's all in your head, as it
were) to potentially fatal brain tumors. Muscle strain can also
certainly cause headaches, and many people find relief from this
sort of pain through massage or exercise.
</P>
<P>
   You also point out, quite correctly, that headaches can come
from trapped gas, often in the sinus cavities. Normally, pressure
inside the sinuses and outside balance each other and life is good.
If air is trapped inside (due to congestion, perhaps) and the
pressure outside drops, the air inside will push outward and this
can indeed cause pain that manifests in the form of a sinus
headache. These are usually easy to distinguish as the pain tends
to be in the face and around the eyes and clears up readily with
decongestants.
</P>
<P>
   If you go up in an airplane, as the cabin pressure drops, this
can be spectacularly painful, as I well know from personal
experience. Much the same effect can cause a painful pressure in
your ears, and you may have to do odd things like yawning or
chewing to help get the air pressure to equalize between the inside
of your head and outside.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped gas in your body is less likely to cause headaches, as
it's just a bit far away from your head, but you can certainly
experience bodily pain from gas.
</P>
<P>
   Always keep in mind that pain is your body's way of telling you
that something might be wrong. If you find yourself having
unusually frequent or painful headaches, or headaches that feel
different from what you're used to, you should definitely seek
expert medical advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions to drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston
Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107.
Please include your initials and hometown. Selected questions of
general interest will be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
