<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESS APPROPRIATELY FOR `BANNED BOOKS WEEK'  
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an ink-stained wretch, I've always had a soft, smudgy spot in
my heart for the American Library Association's annual ``Banned
Books Week.'' I've never been quite sure what it is we're supposed
to do to observe it, though.
</P>
<P>
   We're in the midst of the holiday week right now, in fact, and
I'm at a loss again. It's not exactly a Hallmark occasion _ ``Sorry
to hear you've encountered a nose so blue. Give me a call, and I'll
read `Of Mice and Men' to you'' _ or the sort of thing you'd want
to commemorate with, say, a mug of warm cider, a wagon ride and a
big bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Reading is an obvious possibility, of course, but for most of
us, that really wouldn't distinguish the week from any other. My
2-year-old daughter, for instance, thinks no evening is complete
without a spirited, rattle-the-rafters rendition of ``Go Dog Go!''
and at least three joyful recitations of ``Goodnight Moon.'' I
don't think I could explain this whole anti-book thing to her,
except maybe in terms of ``the old lady whispering hush.''
</P>
<P>
   We could all get together every year, I suppose, and solemnly
read excerpts from the books that were targeted at U.S. schools and
public libraries during the past year. It might do us good to read
aloud the merry-go-round scene from ``The Catcher in the Rye,'' or
recite whatever it is that people still dislike about ``To Kill a
Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter, of all people, is a special guest on this year's
list of censored books. This puzzles me. I can't go to the local
Conglomerated Books Inc. to pick up a newspaper without tripping
over urchins zipping and buzzing about for copies of the latest
Potter best-seller.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't read more than a passage or two, but apparently these
books contain a little hoo-doo and wizardry that some people
believe to be inspired by the devil. Sorry, but I'm skeptical the
Publisher from Hell is clever enough to come up with a way to get
these kids to drop their infernal video games and Pokemon trinkets
to actually read a book.
</P>
<P>
   The work of Satan? Sounds like a miracle from above to me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm inclined to agree with Billy Smith, an 11-year-old from
Garden Grove, Calif., who's being honored at the Library of
Congress this week for an essay he wrote about his love of reading.
It seems Harry Potter inspired the young man to delve into Greek
mythology and Latin and, in turn, cast a book-reading spell over
his entire class.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they try to ban books,'' Billy says, ``it's like trying
to get rid of kids' imaginations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people just can't get into the spirit of the season,
though. Last week, on the eve of our big banned-book extravaganza,
officials at Foley High School in Foley, Ala., yielded to a single
parent's complaint and yanked, at least temporarily, Aldous
Huxley's ``Brave New World'' from a reading list for 11th grade
students taking advanced English. The book, ranked fifth on the
Modern Library's top English-language books of the 20th century,
``is not the kind of thing the school should be reading,'' the
parent said.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite holiday story emanates from my old home state of
Virginia, where the Lynchburg City School Board recently voted to
remove a drawing of a vagina from an anatomy and physiology book
used by high school juniors and seniors. The board, amid public
ridicule, later reversed its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Lee Greever, who favored removing the drawing, said
he'd received at least 10 calls from people objecting to the ``in
your face'' picture. He acknowledged that the book has ``good
parts'' but said it ``seemed to me to use unnecessarily gratuitous
nude illustrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Nude illustrations. In an anatomy book. Imagine that. The folks
at the textbook publishing company said they'd never fielded a
complaint quite like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, drawings of male genitals were not to be ripped
from the textbooks. Apparently they aren't gratuitous or, if they
are, Greever and crew deem them to be, uh, necessarily gratuitous.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, none of the news accounts I read noted what would
have happened to the offending illustrations if they had been
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Call me crazy, but I'm thinking they'd have made a rather nice
Hallmark card: ``Here, dear students, is the rest of your lesson,
in its original condition. Just be thankful no one on the School
Board was your mother's obstetrician.''
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
