<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CARRY DOUBT, QUESTIONS ON ROAD WITH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Off they went for their last hurrah, a deflated Red Sox
team Monday launching a season-ending road trip with a cargo of
questions:
</P>
<P>
   Will Nomar Garciaparra become the first righthanded hitter since
Joe DiMaggio to win consecutive American League batting titles?
</P>
<P>
   Will Pedro Martinez become the only Sox pitcher other than Roger
Clemens to win back-to-back Cy Young Awards?
</P>
<P>
   Can there be a happy ending to the frayed relationship between
Carl Everett and Jimy Williams? Or between Williams and Dan
Duquette?
</P>
<P>
   Will the Sox muster enough intensity to play out six
anticlimactic games with dignity? Or will the team that Sports
Illustrated picked to win the World Series languish a dismal third
in the American League East and finish as far back as fifth in the
wild-card race?
</P>
<P>
   Among other notable questions with short-term implications: Will
the Sox exact some payback for last month's bean brawl in Tampa Bay
when they end their season in St. Petersburg this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   The worn and weary Sox enter the twilight of the 2000 campaign
with Martinez facing the White Sox in Chicago, perhaps his last
start of an ultimately unfulfilling year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my numbers are good enough to win whatever,'' Martinez
said. ``But I'd trade whatever individual achievements you can give
me for a championship or a chance to go to the playoffs. If there
was a possibility, I would trade one for one right now.''
</P>
<P>
   No can do. So, Martinez and his mates will play a low-stakes
three-game series against the playoff-bound White Sox before they
head south for a three-game finale with Tampa Bay. Rookie Paxton
Crawford will start Wednesday night, and Ramon Martinez Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had planned to give Pedro Martinez one more start, in
the season finale, but with so little left to fight for, the team
may choose not to risk an injury to The Franchise in such a
meaningless contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox could be officially eliminated from contention in the
wild-card contest as early as Tuesday. They already are toast in
the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have six games left and we have to find a way to win
as many as we can,'' said closer Derek Lowe, whose 38 saves place
him only three behind Detroit's Todd Jones for the league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe has finished 60 games this year, just one behind the league
leader, New York's Mariano Rivera. And his ERA of 2.58 ranks third
among AL relievers.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowe said the Sox, as uninspiringly as they have played
since last week's crushing Cleveland series, need to pursue more in
their final games than individual stats and accolades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, it's tough, because you know no matter what you do,
you're not going to make it to the playoffs,'' he said. ``But
you're still getting paid to play and you still have to go out
there and play as hard as you have all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lowe acknowledged, ``The intensity probably has not been
there the last couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Drained physically and emotionally from the three-day, five-game
showdown with the Indians that shattered their postseason dreams,
the Sox avoided getting swept by the lowly Orioles over the weekend
only when Baltimore reliever Ryan Kohlmeier walked in the winning
run in the 10th inning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the Sox, the journey to Chicago and Tampa Bay will
be the last trip they take as part of this team _ ever. From
pitchers Tim Wakefield, Pete Schourek, and Jeff Fassero, to catcher
Scott Hatteberg and others, there are questions about where they
fit in Boston's future.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention how the Sox front office feels about Williams
staying at the helm. Everett has made no secret of his disdain for
the manager, and the front office has yet to publicly rebuke the
slugger for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who have been around him know he's first-class,''
Hatteberg said of Williams. ``We're going to go out there and play
as hard as we can for him because we know he's going to fight for
us. He's got my utmost respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lowe, ``Hopefully, he'll be here for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are nearly united, though, in their lack of respect for
the Devil Rays, who responded to Martinez hitting Tampa Bay's
Gerald Williams last month by waging a war on Brian Daubach. They
repeatedly threw at Daubach, though he already had injured his left
elbow in a brawl that followed the plunking of Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays also hit Garciaparra in the back with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, everything is over with,'' said Daubach, who hasn't
fully recovered from his injury. After entering the Tampa Bay
series on a hot streak, he has hit only .173 (9 for 52) since then.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the Sox are not in a forgetful frame of mind. ``What
happened there was very wrong,'' Hatteberg said. ``It left a bitter
taste in a lot of people's mouths. We don't like what happened last
time, but what happens this time is anybody's guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, in typical fashion, said he harbors no bitterness
toward Tampa Bay. It was all part of baseball, he said. And he
indicated he was more concerned about winning pennants than spite
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez left town in a reflective mood, disappointed by the
team's failures. ``Even in our last game (a 1-0 loss Sunday at
Fenway), we didn't play as well as we could, but the fans were
there for us,'' he said. ``We have to keep that in our hearts and
come back next year with a different attitude, more willing to
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
