</P>
<P>
   The latest recall, announced this week, affects up to 200,000
tires supplied by Germany's Continental, mostly on Ford's Lincoln
Navigator SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Though far less serious than the first recall _ so far it has
been linked to only a few minor fender-benders and no deaths _ it
is nonetheless embarrassing for Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the rest of America's auto industry, which has come to
rely on SUVs for a disproportionate share of earnings, like the
idea of a spotlight shining on them.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how you look at them, SUVs are either menace or
salvation. Despite their propensity to roll over more frequently
than other vehicles, a passenger is more likely to survive a crash
in an SUV than in a smaller sedan.
</P>
<P>
   That has led millions of Americans to trade their cars in for
off-roaders in recent years. But it is also prompting officials
with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to consider
tougher regulations on SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also fault SUVs for their below-average fuel economy.
The massive Ford Expedition does as little as ten miles a gallon;
even the mid-size Explorer falls short of 20.
</P>
<P>
   And although sales showed little impact from surging American
fuel prices last spring, fuel economy is becoming a bigger issue
among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It seems less and less likely that the industry can maintain the
huge profit margins that SUVs have been generating _ in the
Navigator's case, $25,000 or more per unit.
</P>
<P>
   Softening sales have put a squeeze on the segment's older
models, such as the Jeep Cherokee, and manufacturers are offering
cash-back incentives of up to $3,000. These come-ons are likely to
increase, most analysts say, even if the overall American market
remains buoyant.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, there were barely a dozen ``sport-utes'' on the
market. Today, the number is fast approaching 70, according to
AutoPacific, a consultancy. But as many as a third are sheep in
wolves' clothing, so-called crossovers that clad a car-like body in
an SUV's macho exterior.
</P>
<P>
   They are pretty useless off the road, but few American motorists
ever drive on anything rougher than gravel anyway. On the road, by
contrast, the crossovers handle better than conventional SUVs,
deliver better fuel economy and are less prone to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   Considering what can happen when a Firestone loses its tread,
that's something the vehicles' owners will be happy to hear. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1401EDT &QL; 
