<HEADER>
A2113 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-26 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS ATTACK HURTS FOR TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, MASS. _ He blamed the execution, not the talent of
the players. That's what Bill Belichick said in the wake of a 10-3
loss to the Miami Dolphins Sunday. What else can he say?
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's defense is drawing kudos. Dolphins fullback Rob
Konrad called the Patriots defense ``the best I've played against
the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, there's another story to tell. A sad one.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the Patriots must have been blindfolded when they
selected the personnel for their 2000 squad. On a team that once
had options like Curtis Martin, Sam Gash, Dave Meggett, Shawn
Jefferson, and Ben Coates, they're now relying on backup-type
players for the same production that Pro Bowl types used to give
them.
</P>
<P>
   A fade in the end zone to Eric Bjornson on fourth down? Why not?
In years pastm it was 6 points, guaranteed, when Coates would fight
off two defenders and make the play. A handoff to Kevin Faulk
inside the 5? Pretty logical. In years past, Martin brought it in
for a score.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of execution? True. But everyone knows the Patriots had
salary cap problems and weren't able to spend a lot of money on top
players so they often settled on minimum-salaried veterans, hoping
there was incentive for those players to excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lack of confidence in the players or the
talent,'' said Belichick, who added that he would be hard-pressed
to find better players at any position. But is that based on having
no money to spend or is it because he really feels that way? The
talent, he said, ``is displayed. It's not like you can't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Belichick can see what mere mortals can't.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wannstedt, the Dolphins' head coach who may at some point
this season have an offensive meltdown similar to New England's,
said he game-planned defensively to stop the big play down the
field. It's what every defensive coordinator does against the
Patriots. Don't allow Terry Glenn to beat you. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   It's also obvious now that Drew Bledsoe, who injured his right
hand on a quarterback sneak in the fourth quarter, doesn't have
faith in the people he's throwing the ball to. Bledsoe used to take
more chances and lay a ball in where he knew the receiver would
make the play. Now he's throwing it only when the receiver is wide
open. He also doesn't have a security blanket to dump the ball off
to, as he used to in Coates or Martin or Gash or Keith Byars.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents know this. Deep down, Belichick knows it, too, but he
talks about execution and precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put in a play and you practice it and you practice it
and you practice it, you're banking on that working in the game,''
he said. ``They practice the stuff against a three-man line,
against a zone, and a two-deep safeties and one-deep safety and we
still don't execute in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like the second-to-last play of the game to Glenn.
Talk about double coverage and all that, but the ball didn't end up
in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are now 3 for 14 in the red zone, after going 0 for
2 Sunday. What gives? Do they continue to practice, practice,
practice, hoping at some point they'll execute, execute, execute?
Or will there be changes? Whatever happened to Michael Bishop?
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether there was a scenerio in which Bishop might be
called upon, Belichick said, ``I don't see that.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the game, after watching a game film so surreal that
it must have rivaled ``A Clockwork Orange,'' Belichick didn't seem
to have a handle on how his team would act with their backs pinned
against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how this team is going to respond,'' said
Belichick. ``I'm sure the team is feeling some frustrations. We had
opportunities at the wire. We had the ball in our possession and we
could have made a play or two to turn things in all four games. We
didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Better this way than getting blown out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-nine to nothing has its own frustrations,'' said
Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   The optimist would say the Patriots are close to turning it
around. But four games in the hole, in a tough division, isn't the
reality at the moment. The pessimist would say the season is over.
Play Bishop. Play J.R. Redmond. But that isn't the reality, either.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that the Patriots have the beef on defense to
hold down a lot of teams. But the team is lopsided: a lot of talent
on defense and much less on offense.
</P>
<P>
   It may be about precision and execution as Belichick will
insist, but as Rick Pitino once said, ``Larry Bird, Kevin McHale,
and Robert Parish aren't walking through that door.'' And neither
are Ben Coates, Curtis Martin, and Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
