<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-BOX-HNS &LR;      09-26 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A MODEL CITIZEN, BEFORE AND AFTER OLYMPIC LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ After you've done seven years of hard time
in the Illinois State Penitentiary with guys named Pharaoh and
Mongoose, nothing much figures to scare you, not even a 6-foot-6
Cuban named Felix Savon.
</P>
<P>
   That's the attitude former convict turned Olympic boxer Michael
Bennett took into his Tuesday afternoon heavyweight bout against
Cuba's latest Lord of the Ring.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter to Bennett that Savon was a two-time Olympic
gold medalist and six-time world champion. What mattered was
Savon's superior height and reach advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With his pedigree and physical skills, the 33-year-old Savon
easily dispatched the 29-year-old American from Chicago in their
quarterfinal fight. Under amateur boxing rules, when Savon built up
a 23-8 lead at the end of three rounds in the four-round contest,
the referee was mandated to stop the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``RSCO'' is the official designation _ referee stops
contest/outclassed. At any point in a bout when a boxer has a
15-point lead, the fight is stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett lasted about the same as teammate Jeff Lacy, who was
stopped late in the third round of his quarterfinal fight with
Gaidarbek Gaidarbekov. The 165-pound Russian was awarded the
victory when his lead increased to 18-3 late in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   The losses mean the U.S. team will not match its medal total in
Atlanta, where American boxers won one gold and five bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the American boxers objected to the decision to stop
his bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules are rules,'' Bennett said. ``I have no quarrels over it.
If that's the way it has to be done, that's the way it has to be
done. I can't complain . . . I'm pleased. I feel OK, as long as my
heart is in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years Bennett's heart and mind have been in the
right place, the straight and narrow world of people going about
their business in a law-abiding manner. It wasn't always thus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Bennett was attending college in the Chicago area and
working part-time at UPS. By his admission, ``I started hanging out
with the wrong guy over the summer.'' The wrong guy persuaded him
to come along for a stick-up of a Toys R Us store.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Bennett became the Toy Store Bandit and was sent to the
big house on a 26-year stretch for armed robbery and unlawful
aggravated restraint. As a first-time offender, Bennett had his
sentence sliced to 15 years. He was released after seven for good
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While in prison, three cons serving a combined 440 years for
murder, attempted murder and armed robbery took a liking to Bennett
. . . no, not that way. His prison experience was nothing like the
HBO series ``Oz.'' Pharaoh (Harry Jenkins), Mongoose (Earl Good)
and Papa Sun (Isaiah Spann) taught the 20-year-old to box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget them,'' Bennett told the Chicago Sun-Times.
``I wanted to stay physically fit and I grew to like boxing. They
taught me the fundamentals. They passed their knowledge to me along
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett was released on July 29, 1998. By all accounts, he's
been a model citizen. He earned a college degree and a spot on the
Olympic team in the heavyweight class, although he's not
particularly imposing at 6 feet and 198 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now Savon, he's imposing. His 201 pounds are stretched along his
6-6 frame, his arms as long as sugarcane stalks but quite a bit
thicker.
</P>
<P>
   Savon used those arms to great advantage in the bout at the
Sydney Convention Center. He jabbed away at Bennett in the first
round and emerged with a 7-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett scored with a left in the second round but a straight
right and a right uppercut by Savon enabled him to win the round
10-4 for a 17-6 advantage entering the third round. When the Cuban
won the third round 6-2 to lead by 15 points, the fight was
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the presence of former heavyweight champion Evander
Holyfield at ringside urging him on could help Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him too many straight shots,'' Bennett said. ``I stood
in front of him a lot. I gave up too many shots. He's a single-shot
fighter and I gave him too many chances. . . . I should have been
able to cut the reach off but I was a step too slow to take his
advantage away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a true warrior. He's done a lot for amateur boxing. He
deserves what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Savon's 395 amateur fights and Bennett's
60 was too great for the American to overcome. Bennett tried to
counteract Savon's superior reach by crouching and looking for an
opening, but the referee warned him several times to keep his head
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of difficult to get past that,'' Bennett said. ``I
can't let that be a factor. It was between me and Savon and he was
the better man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said he is unsure of his post-Sydney plans. He might
turn pro, although 29 is an advanced age to be getting into the
punch-for-pay racket. He might work with children, serving as a
mentor, in much the same way _ but in a vastly different context _
that Pharaoh, Mongoose and Papa Sun did for him behind the bars and
the barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he decides to do, Bennett at 29 seems to be a different
man than he was at 20. That's why he wasn't distraught over his
loss to Savon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm healthy, mentally and physically,'' Bennett said. ``I did
my best. I can't be anything but happy. I reached for my star and I
fell short.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
