<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      09-26 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMC: MAKING THE VENTURE CAPITAL COMMITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY 
c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They call their venture group, conspicuously, EMC.
</P>
<P>
   But they're quick to point out that their group is not an arm of
the computer storage giant in Hopkinton, Mass. Rather, EMC is short
for Egan Managed Capital, a pool of family money that's invested in
early-stage start-ups for EMC founder Richard Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Egans nor the partners in the fund mind the
confusion over the name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Dick's idea. The name helps,'' said Mike Shanahan, one
of six partners at the $110 million downtown venture group, which
was started by Jack Egan, son of Richard and former EMC Corp. sales
guru.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in February 1997, Egan Managed Capital has
done about 20 deals and claims to have reaped triple-digit returns
each year. Winners include Network Engines, a $3 million investment
that turned out to be worth more than $100 million, and Epicon, a
$1 million investment on which Egan made about 13 times its money.
Egan also invested in Caldera Systems, a Linux company, and Top
Layer Networks, a switch maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has turned out to be even better than we expected,''
Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Egans are happy enough to have renewed their venture capital
commitment. They recently launched a second fund, of $66.7 million,
following the first $43 million fund. Four investments have already
been made from the new pot. Shanahan said it took only an
hour-and-a-half meeting with Jack Egan to get the nod on the new
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, this isn't big money for the Egans. In its latest
survey, Boston magazine ranked the senior Egan as the 17th-richest
man in the Commonwealth, with a fortune worth $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Shanahan contends this is more than a rich man's angel
hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very deliberate effort to create an institution with
their brand on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also outside the realm of corporate venture capital, the
hot fad of the moment, in which big companies, including EMC
itself, make side investments in start-ups. Companies from
Microsoft and Intel to Fidelity Investments have large venture
capital businesses. And many other companies have dabbled in what
turned out to be riskier business than they had planned.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp. does make its own corporate venture investments, and
there is no distinct cooperation between Egan and the company.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Barry, senior editor of the Corporate Venture Capital
Report, says that could cause controversy. For example, Dell
Computer's venture arm gets a shot at investing in companies that
Michael Dell's venture group, MSD, backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If shareholders of Dell were to find out that Michael Dell
invested in a company, and (Dell) itself didn't get a chance to
look at those deals, investors might be upset,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   That's if the investment turned out to be a good one, of course.
Investors would surely bark, too, if the company followed the
founder's personal investments and lost money.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the Egan funds is information technology and
business-to-business players. The goal, Shanahan says, is to make
investments of $2 million to $4 million in 12 to 15 companies over
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   These are good times in venture capital, Shanahan says. As the
years go on, it will be tougher to impress the Egans, holders of
one of the best stocks of the past decade, with a rise of more than
75,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I check EMC's stock price every time we're on the phone, to
know how Jack's feeling,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This will doubtless go down as the year in which venture capital
made a mint for Harvard University's massive endowment fund.
</P>
<P>
   The private equity portion of the $19.2 billion endowment
provided a 155 percent return for the 12 months ended June 30, said
Harvard Management Co. The overall return was 32.2 percent, thanks
largely to help from the venture returns. The total fund's return
marked the send-best showing since 1974, when Harvard Management
was started. In 1983, the return was 43.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
