<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-DIV-NYT &LR;      09-26 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DIV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE DIVER XIONG NI REPEATS GOLD MEDAL PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL BRINK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ For five rounds of diving, Xiong Ni had
watched Dimitri Sautin whirl through the air in tightly wrapped
spins and somersaults, building a lead that neither Xiong nor
Sautin's 10 other rivals appeared ready to match. Xiong had come
out of retirement specifically to help the Chinese team counter
Sautin's pre-eminence, and now he was waiting and hoping for the
Russian to give him an opening in the 3-meter springboard final.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Xiong, Sautin saved his hardest dive for last,
but not his best one. His slip-up enabled Xiong to surpass him and
claim the gold at the Olympic Park Aquatic Center Tuesday night.
Sautin dropped to third behind Mexico's Fernando Platas, who
finished 0.3 points behind Xiong.
</P>
<P>
   Xiong, 26, became only the second diver to win medals at four
Olympics _ Italy's Klaus Dibiasi was the other, from 1964 through
1976 _ and he repeated his springboard victory from the 1996
Atlanta Games. Xiong also won a bronze in the platform in 1992 and
a silver in the platform at the 1988 Games in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only when the points came up did I believe that I was the
champion,'' said Xiong, who came out of retirement two years ago at
the urging of Chinese sports officials. ``This is the best, most
valuable reward for the hard work and sweat of the last few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Two American divers, Troy Dumais and Mark Ruiz, finished sixth
and seventh, respectively. Dumais lost his chance when he gambled
and changed his third dive, increasing the degree of difficulty
from 3.0 to 3.5. His form was off, and he was effectively
eliminated with a low score of 49.50. Ruiz, whose specialty is the
platform, was never in serious contention in the final round.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to be a serious contender to Sautin for most of
the night. Xiong was more than 30 points behind after two rounds,
and the way Sautin was diving there seemed little chance that Xiong
would catch him. Platas was staying close with a series of
somersaults in the pike position, but Xiong moved past him into
second on the fifth dive with a beautiful reverse 1{ somersault
with 3{ twists. With one dive to go, Sautin led Xiong by just under
11 points, and Platas by just over 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Platas, Sautin and Xiong were the final three divers, and the
Mexican turned in his best dive of the night. Sautin faced his
toughest dive of the night, a reverse 2{ somersault with 1{ twists,
and failed to execute it. He received his lowest score of the
night, and fell below Platas.
</P>
<P>
   Xiong finally had his opening, and he seized the opportunity.
Knowing he was 81.30 points behind Platas, he executed a
near-perfect inward 3{ somersault and watched as the scoreboard
registered marks of 7.5 to 8.0 for an 81.60. Xiong pumped his fists
and joyfully hugged his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Sautin acknowledged that he might have erred in
putting his most difficult dive at the end. ``I led from the
beginning to the final dive,'' Sautin said afterward, ``so it is
very disappointing to lose. My last dive is the most difficult in
my program, so maybe it was a mistake to include it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
