<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-RETAIL-ART-BOS &LR;      09-26 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-RETAIL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SUMMER'S OVER, TIME TO PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Send.com mastered the dot-com business formula last year: Throw
thousands of products onto a Web site, spend millions of dollars on
prime-time television commercials, and then pray.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a change typical of the survivors of this year's dot-com
bloodbath, the company is acting more like a real merchant _
cautious about spending, savvier about consumer behavior, and
nervous as hell about the holiday selling season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what you saw in the last few years of e-tailing was
driven by a technology perspective rather than a consumer
perspective,'' said Michael Lannon, chief executive of Send.com, a
Waltham, Mass. online seller of gifts. ``You can't be a technology
company that sells stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, Lannon's holiday preparations would have
appalled any traditional merchant. That's when Lannon began ramping
up for the Christmas bonanza in the fall. He has since learned that
planning for the following season should start, well, right after
Christmas. And like a true retail executive, he now starts
panicking in September rather than December.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Labor Day ended, it was like, `Summer's over. My life is
over,' '' Lannon said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Lannon and other Send.com executives got an early
start on mapping their holiday strategies. They decided to slash
advertising spending, revamp their Web site, and offer a smarter
selection of gifts. Hiring for the company's customer call center
began in September, a few weeks earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Send.com, a closely held company known for its advertisements
featuring ``The Giver,'' is actually the third version of a company
that Lannon started three years ago. Initially, he started selling
bottles of wine by phone, using merchants across the nation to
package and deliver the orders.
</P>
<P>
   But Lannon's first Web site, Sendwine.com, won over customers.
In October 1999, the company became Send.com, reflecting its much
larger offering: cigars and champagne as well as gift certificates
for fine dining, spas, and exotic car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company's annual sales are growing 10-fold, and the
business has an enviable return rate of less than 1 percent.
Hundreds of merchants have signed on as partners, with 90 percent
expected to be using Send.com's MerchantLink order-management
software by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making the Web practical for the merchants,'' said Mary
Obana, the company's marketing director. ``Most of them don't have
the expertise or a Web site. We provide them with a simple solution
to allow them to go on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing smaller retailers onto the Web initially took more
hand-holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a bit scared,'' said Steve Marchlik, who manages
MerchantLink for Send.com. ``They picked up a mouse . . . and were
like, `What is it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the merchants have become more sophisticated. Today, even
retailers with Web sites has signed on, viewing Send.com as a way
to broaden their appeal. For example, Tealuxe Inc., A Franklin,
Mass. company that runs tea bars and its own Web site, wants to use
Send.com to attract corporate gift givers as well as tea lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't competing with our Web site,'' said Diana Rodgers,
marketing director for Tealuxe. ``Most of our customers are from
our stores, and our Web site is a convenience for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the growth in Send.com's sales and merchant
partnerships, these are leaner times for virtual retailers. Today,
Send.com executives are under pressure to deliver profits, which
they plan to do in the fourth quarter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But they are well aware of what can happen when investors lose
their patience. In the last year, investors have pulled their
support from such Internet merchants as Boo.com, Toysmart.com, and
Craftshop.com.
</P>
<P>
   The hostility has spread to suppliers, advertising agencies, and
even landlords. In the spring, Send.com had hoped to move to larger
offices in Waltham. But after a commercial real estate agent
demanded a special ``dot-com'' security deposit of $1 million,
company executives abandoned their search and decided to spend
$50,000 renovating their headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the backlash, Send.com executives are wielding the
budget ax. Last year, the Internet retailer spent a staggering $13
million on TV commercials to raise awareness for its brand. For
this holiday season, ``there will be no TV,'' Lannon said.
</P>
<P>
   The compay will instead target customers through less expensive
e-mail, regular mail, and radio promotions. Send.com's gifts also
will be displayed on CNBC.com and other sites that attract a busy
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Executives have sought other cost-trimming opportunities. They
have cut $100,000 in photography fees by doing the work in-house,
for one.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Send.com is set to debut a new site design that will
help the company quickly update its Web pages, moving slow sellers
and products with low inventory to the bottom of the pages. The new
functionality was needed as the company began offering more
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were collapsing under the weight of our product
selection,'' Lannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Send.com also will tweak its Web pages to reflect consumer
behavior. The company has learned that lost customers log off, so
it will add navigational tools, a search box, and product
categories on every page.
</P>
<P>
   Executives also have learned that online shoppers only buy what
you show them. That means more pictures, less chatty text, and
better use of the site's prime real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Customers rarely scroll down, the company discovered, so
displaying products at the bottom of a Web page is like storing
them at the top of an 11-foot shelf in the rear of a store.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very visual, and we were making them read too
much,'' Obana said.
</P>
<P>
   Insights into consumer behavior are crucial for Internet
retailers. For instance, Send.com now knows that men don't buy men
golf lessons. (It's considered an insult to the male ego, Send.com
officials say.) The company also has realized that it needs to
prepare for two order surges for Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valentine's Day was a two-week holiday for us this year,''
Obana said. ``The week before Valentine's Day, women were buying
gifts for men. The week of Valentine's Day, men were looking for
gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers also have informed Send.com that they want more
products under $50 and a wider variety of gift suggestions. In
response, the company has added a collection of teas and tea sets.
Its holiday lineup will include steaks, hams, fresh-baked cookies,
and wide array of gift baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep updating,'' Obana said. ``Customers don't
want to give people the same thing again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Stoughton is a member of the Globe staff. She can be
reached by e-mail at stoughton(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
