<HEADLINE>
DISHING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're in the market for Internet access faster than a
dial-up modem but are cursed to live somewhere with neither cable
modems nor digital subscriber line telephone access, you still have
hope: Net links through satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that, for now, the main broadband-for-computers
service, Hughes' DirecPC product, costs more and delivers less than
AT&AMP;T Broadband, RCN, or the various DSL offerings from Verizon,
FlashCom, and others.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that later this year, perhaps as soon as next
month, both DirecPC and the Dish Network plan to offer much faster,
two-way satellite broadband services. They will probably still cost
more than landline alternatives but deliver faster access than
satellite systems do now, especially for sending information out to
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   For now, DirecPC, the dominant offering in the computer Net
market (leaving aside WebTV, which provides Internet access through
your TV set and a keyboard), can give you download speeds about
eight times faster than a dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   Installation charges are often waived during promotions, but
generally it costs $150 to get the dish, or $200 for a ``DirecDuo''
dish that brings in both the Internet and hundreds of channels of
television.
</P>
<P>
   For $30 a month, with DirecPC you can surf the Web for 25 hours
a month, paying $2 for every extra hour, or under a new unlimited
access plan pay $50 a month. Those charges include $10 for an
Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   If you live somewhere you can get DSL or a cable modem but don't
plan on using the Net more than an hour a day for the next two
years, factoring in monthly charges plus the one-time dish cost,
you might come out ahead taking the 25-hour plan.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts note that, once you've had a taste of
always-on, high-speed Internet access, you are very likely to make
using the Net a much bigger part of your life and entertainment and
might find it hard to limit yourself to 25 hours a month.
</P>
<P>
   The DirecPC service is not quite true broadband because it uses
a dial-up modem to transmit information from your computer _ such
as a request to load the Boston.com Web page _ and then blasts the
contents of the page back down to your computer through a satellite
dish on the side of your home at up to 400 kilobits per second.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little like mailing a postcard out to someone and getting
an overnight package sent back. And the satellite is not aiming
content to your address, but rather including it in a huge stream
of thousands of transmissions, encoded so that you receive only the
Web page you asked to get.
</P>
<P>
   While noticeably faster than a dial-up modem, DirecPC, at 400
kilobits, is still considerably slower than the
640-kilobit-per-second service offered by Verizon DSL or the 1.5
megabit connections of AT&AMP;T Broadband. Verizon and AT&AMP;T's
RoadRunner generally cost about $40 a month, and more for faster
DSL. Installation and modem fees may run to $100 but are often
waived during promotions or through coupons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems expensive for a consumer in the Boston area relative
to a cable modem or a DSL hookup, but in a lot of rural areas it's
going to be the only way'' to get broadband services, said John
Galego, director of service provider relations with
GetConnected.com. The site is a Boston service that offers unbiased
comparison shopping for Internet access and other communications
and energy services.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Massachusetts, which is blessed to have some of the
widest-ranging cable modem and DSL offerings of any state, there
are still many broadband gaps _ either towns where the cable
franchise has not been upgraded for Internet access, or areas of
cities and towns more than about two and a half miles from a
``central office'' equipped for DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   While satellite Internet access can be a good choice for someone
whose only alternative is pokey dial-up access, Galego said that
``one of the biggest considerations for satellite access'' is
decidely low-tech: your neighborhood geography.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, to get DirecPC reception you have to be able to
get a clear view to the southwest sky from some part of your home
or property where you are willing to install a dish, with no trees
or other homes in the way.
</P>
<P>
   People often wonder whether satellite reception will suffer
during heavy rain or snowstorms _ or when a flock of geese flies by
_ but Galego said in his experience service outage problems are
``negligible'' for satellites compared to cable or DSL.
</P>
<P>
   DirecPC also requires a fairly powerful Pentium-chip computer to
function, running Windows 98 and containing at least 32 megabytes
of RAM memory and 20 megabytes of space on the hard disc for the
DirecPC software.
</P>
<P>
   Both DirecPC and Echostar have been pouring money into rolling
out new two-way satellite Internet services they plan to unveil
this fall, and even more offerings are expected in the next three
years, such as iSky and Astrolink.
</P>
<P>
   Working with an Israeli company called Gilat-to-Home, EchoStar's
Dish Network plans a two-way broadband satellite offering that
could go live as soon as next month in some parts of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing and performance are still a little fuzzy, however.
EchoStar and Gilat-to-Home say users ``can expect Internet access
speeds up to 10 times faster than normal modem speeds, with burst
rates considerably higher.'' Bursting refers to one-time downloads
of big files such as songs or video clips.
</P>
<P>
   EchoStar plans to use an oval-shaped dish, about two feet by
three feet in size, that can bring in both Internet access and the
500 channels of the Dish Network.
</P>
<P>
   DirecPC also says it will launch a two-way broadband service
sometime this fall, still offering about 400 kilobits downstream
but allowing somewhere between 128 and 256 kilobits upstream. To
make it work, you will need to install a transmitter in the USB
port of your computer.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, DirecPC also offers a service allowing them to
blast out content to multiple locations without getting hung up in
bottlenecks. For less than $100, for example, a company could
transmit a 30-mb file to 10,000 personal computers across the
country in less than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One user of this service is RLM Software of Brighton, Mass.,
which pumps up-to-the-minute data on airline flight arrival times
to customers across the country such as shipping companies. It also
provides much of the data used by Travelocity.com's flight status
service, through a direct link to Federal Aviation Administration
radar data showing the actual location of thousands of airplanes,
which is used to calculate expected arrival times.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Flynn, a senior executive with 20-person RLM, said the
company decided to use DirecPC for its FlightView service because
``all our customers don't necessarily have access to a high-speed
Internet connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also determined that using satellites to steer clear
of the Internet would prevent lots of headaches trying to determine
the cause when customers reported they were not receiving data.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an outage on the Internet, and that still happens a
lot, you have to go track it down,'' Flynn said. After some early
rocky going, Flynn said, ``They have made improvements in the last
18 months. The reliability is there now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Peter J. Howe can be reached by e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
