<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2140 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CHINA-SEX-BOS &LR;      09-26 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE BLUSH, BUT S-E-X SITE'S A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Three years ago, Leslie Kenny took her brand-new
Harvard MBA and moved to China to sell family values. When that
didn't work, she decided to sell sex.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the ``oldest profession'' kind of way. But as a hip,
no-holds-barred Dr. Ruth-meets-the-MTV-generation for a society
where sex has been a taboo subject for a good 5,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   With online polls and quizzes, Q&AMP;A's with an unflappable Chinese
MD and sexologist, uncensored bulletin boards where youths share
anxieties and advice, and ``virtual girlfriends'' for young men to
practice dating techniques, Kenny's Dotlove.com Web site and
minimagazines have brought levity and fun to sex education _ two
words that make most young Asians blush and run for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny didn't set out to be a sex guru. She used to work for Walt
Disney, promoting the Disney Channel across Asia. But with limited
cash during the regional financial crisis, cable and satellite
operators were turning her away. She asked what they were buying
instead, and they told her: ``the Playboy Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized there was an innate curiosity in Asia about sex,
and the only sources of information seemed to be pornography or
very clinical information on reproductive health from the
government,'' said Kenny, 35, who was born in California to a
Chinese mother and an Anglo-American father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if I wrote down everything I knew about sex . . . I
could turn a hobby into a profession,'' said Kenny, who retired
from the trendy nightclub scene when she married a British Internet
entrepreneur two years ago. ``Sex, love, and relationships _ I like
all three things, and I'm not ashamed to admit it!''
</P>
<P>
   So Kenny started an entertainment company, Dotmedia, and
launched a brand called Dotlove to promote fun and responsible sex
in a hip pop-culture format.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, she has raised $4 million in venture capital,
established an exclusive marketing partnership with Channel V, a
leading music video television channel, grown her shop from two
people to 40, and earned the title ``the high priestess of Internet
sex in China'' from a Hong Kong newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Her next target _ and the site of her newest office _ is India,
home of the Kama Sutra, but also home to some of the most
conservative sexual mores on earth.
</P>
<P>
   One might think racy material would run afoul of the usually
controlling and strait-laced Chinese government, which routinely
blocks Web sites it considers controversial, including this
newspaper's. But instead of keeping a low profile, Kenny decided to
seek support from government-backed organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Her Hong Kong-based company cosponsored a forum on adolescent
sex education in Beijing with China's leading government newspaper,
and she hobnobbed with the country's top sex educators.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff was huge: Eager to curb unwanted pregnancies and
sexually transmitted diseases, and aware that a dry and technical
approach was turning off increasingly sophisticated youth, the
China Family Planning Association last month agreed to partner with
the American to promote sex education. The vice president of the
group, a high-ranking Communist Party member, joined Kenny's
advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Logging onto her Chinese- and English-language Web site, it's
easy to see how Dotlove.com has captured the imagination of youth
here. The site registers 110,000 different visitors and 3 million
page hits a month _ dwarfing the reach of local youth magazines or
even the Hong Kong edition of Cosmopolitan and other magazines that
treat sex openly.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny has never advertised the year-old site in mainland China,
yet nearly half of Dotlove.com's visitors are from there. (A
quarter are from Hong Kong, 20 percent from the United States and
India, and the remaining 10 percent from Southeast Asia and
Taiwan).
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Chinese family planning group has not criticized or
tried to censor the site's frank features or its risque online
chatter. But Kenny said she will defer to her new partners if they
have suggestions for an upcoming, mainland-targeted site.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those changes may be practical ones, such as an emphasis
on birth control methods that are cheaper or more accessible than
others. But what if Dotmedia's new partners balk at the raunchy
language or discussion of ``deviant sex'' in the free-for-all
postings and chat rooms?
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger issue is to get sex education into China in a
friendly and fun way,'' said Yishane Lee, executive producer for
Dotmedia.
</P>
<P>
   The site also deals with issues surrounding homosexuality. Laws
against homosexuality were abolished in China more than 15 years
ago, but it remains a sensitive topic.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with every passing year, more taboos are broken, said Kenny,
whose grandfather taught gynecology in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masturbation used to be one of those issues, but attitudes
have changed,'' she said. ``People realize this can prevent
unwanted pregnancies and sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government is very practical _ think of the money
they can save, and the burden on millions of women that can be
avoided'' by promoting birth control instead of abortion to limit
family size.
</P>
<P>
   If Chinese family planners are practical, so are Kenny and her
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, as well as the 'zine distributed free at raves,
avoid obscenity charges by using lighthearted cartoons instead of
photos. Features answer questions that every young person _ and a
lot of older people, too _ are embarrassed to ask.
</P>
<P>
   But with hip graphics, horoscopes, movie and music reviews, and
Japanese-style cartoons, it has an unabashedly youthful edge. Even
if the message is the same, this is no online version of ``The Joy
of Sex.'' It's 100 percent Generation X and younger, more Sony
Playstation than ``Our Bodies, Ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said she looked at ``The Joy of Sex'' when she was
researching her concept, but found the classic 1970s love manual,
with its pencil drawings and unshaven, hippie couple, to be a
``period piece.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hard for me to relate to,'' she said. ``I might as
well have been watching Pilgrims make out in their buckle shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even for timeless questions like sex, the way you answer them
and package the response has to be rooted in pop culture,'' said
Kenny, who wrote the original material for the site but has turned
over content and creative duties to a staff that is even younger
and hipper than herself. They brainstorm in a corner of the office
she has decorated with plush Ikea couches, slouchy lime- and
tangerine-colored chairs, and pink and purple yoga mats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times and cultures change, and sex changes with it,'' Kenny
said.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, even the retro arcade favorite Pac-man is getting a
face lift from Dotmedia's team. They dreamed up a game called
``Utrack'' that will soon appear on the Web site: A sperm is
released in a maze and munches hearts, representing love, on its
way to the egg at the center. Multicolored monsters representing
HIV, herpes, and chlamydia chase the sperm, and woe to the player
who doesn't pick up condoms in the maze first.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Hoochi-Koochi girlfriends'' allow viewers to try their
hand at virtual dating of cartoon characters with various
personalities. Like the electronic Tamagotchi pets that children
fed and nurtured to keep alive, a Hoochi-Koochi girlfriend rewards
or dumps her date depending on whether he treats her with respect.
(There are plans for virtual boyfriends too).
</P>
<P>
   The newest feature, launched last week, is a free matchmaking
service that allows vistors to fill out a personality profile and
find a match with a click of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Dotlove's team is also building a online city so matchmaking
candidates will be able to create cartoons of themselves and meet
online in a virtual cafe, karaoke bar, arcade, disco, even private
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a 31-year-old Chinese-American and Brown University
graduate, said she wishes Dotlove.com had existed when she was a
teen. Like most Asians, she said, ``I was raised pretty
conservatively . . . My parents never talked about sex with me,
even though I was raised in the US.
</P>
<P>
   ``This site is so useful _ there are so many questions you have
when you're 13 and may have no one to talk to . . . And it's better
than hearing it from your friends,'' she said wryly, ``because your
friends usually don't know what they're talking about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
