<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-KARELIN-0927-COX     09-26 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KARELIN-0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S KARELIN A SOURCE OF PRIDE TO NATION SEARCHING FOR
HEROES
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By CRAIG NELSON 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODOLSK, Russia _ Forget Marat Safin.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open tennis champion from Russia may yet prove a flash
in the pan. Forget, too, president and judo expert Vladimir Putin.
Smirking about last month's sinking of the nuclear submarine Kursk
with 118 sailors aboard during a recent CNN interview isn't likely
to improve his stature.
</P>
<P>
   No, for a country desperate to restore its former greatness and
grasping for a unifying symbol, Olympic wrestler Aleksandr Karelin
_ a.k.a. ``The Experiment'' _ is the closest thing Russia has to a
national hero.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Wednesday's medal round at the Sydney Olympics, the
32-year-old Karelin boasts one of the most astounding records in
international sports competition: 12 European championships, nine
world championships and three Olympic gold medals. The 285-pound,
6-foot-four-inch superheavyweight from Siberia has not lost a match
since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He is the unquestioned favorite to win in the 130-kilogram
(286-pound) superheavyweight division, as he always is.
</P>
<P>
   With roots still deep in rural Russia, Karelin provides a rare
glimmer of pride in a nation that even now, almost 10 years after
the fall of communism, can't agree on words for its national anthem
and whose economy barely outranks Belgium's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bear. He's unbeatable. And he's ours,'' says Anatoly
Manedov, a 55-year-old cab driver in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Probably no one's shoulders are broad enough to bear the burden
of Russia's pent-up aspirations. Yet Karelin, whose boyhood
ambition was to become a truck driver like his father, may come as
close as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Start with his physique. No, chuckled Karelin during a recent
pre-Olympic tournament south of Moscow, he wasn't created in a mad
scientist's laboratory. Still, the tax policeman and member of
Russian Parliament easily could be mistaken for a menacing giant.
</P>
<P>
   His cauliflowered ears flair from his shaven head like bent
wings. His jutting brow topples into eye sockets hollowed by months
of three-a-day practices. His face, like a battered catcher's mitt,
is furrowed by years of encounters with flying elbows, gouging
fingers and the polyurethane wrestling mat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what's remarkable about Karelin is not his shoulders that
slope like the sides of a mountain or his chest that spreads like a
river delta. It's his hulking hands, which resemble in thickness
and length the steel claws of an earth-mover. With those hands, he
once lifted a refrigerator twice his size and carried it up eight
floors to his apartment. Human opponents fare worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Wyoming and wrestled with cows. When Karelin
grabs you, it's kind of the same thing,'' says Rulon Gardner, the
U.S. Olympic team's superheavyweight and a top challenger for the
gold medal. ``He basically grabs you the way he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Upper-body strength is key in Greco-Roman wrestling, which bars
moves below the waist, and Karelin sports a trademark move that
matches his power with the nimbleness of a far lighter wrestler.
Benignly called the ``reverse body lift,'' it is anything but
friendly: He grips his arms around the waist of his 286-plus pound
opponent, hoists him off the ground and hurls him over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin is not the move's only practitioner, but in a weight
class where fat is usually a friend and girth no enemy, he's
unique. ``It's a beautiful move,'' says Karelin, who likens a
wrestling match to a four-line couplet of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the move's beauty _ much less the rhyme _ are
lost on Karelin's foes. Alexey Kolesnikov, the No. 3
superheavyweight on the Russian team who has sparred with Karelin
in practice for eight years, says every bout with Karelin ``is like
the last.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They prefer to be pinned rather than wrestle him. I've seen
the fear in their eyes many times,'' says Anatoly Nazarenko, an
assistant U.S. Olympic team coach and a former Olympian and
three-time world champion from Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is well-founded. Indeed, Karelin's finest moment on the
mat may have come when he wasn't even at full strength. After
rupturing a chest muscle, he won the gold medal at the '96 games in
Atlanta wrestling largely with one arm.
</P>
<P>
   Even referees are awed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he received from his colleagues before
officiating a Karelin match, Kevin Maxwell of Utica, N.Y., sounded
less like a referee than an air-traffic controller: ``Just stand
back and get out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Comic book stuff,'' huffs Karelin when the subject of his
fear-stricken opponents comes up. He dismisses as fluff the
suggestion he's a shoo-in to win the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponents are obviously very generous to me with their
predictions, but they're totally different on the mat. They are not
at all peaceful there.''
</P>
<P>
   Karelin wears his celebrity like a badly-fitted suit. He insists
he has done nothing extraordinary, shies away from adoring fans and
said he struggles not to get ``blown up like a balloon with pride''
_ self-effacing statements that only enhance his popularity
further.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Karelin's aura here stems from his enduring ties to
Siberia, not usually included in Top-10 lists of the world's garden
spots. While many Russian sports stars now live abroad _ Anna
Kournikova in Florida, Safin in Spain and swimmer Alexander Popov
in Australia _ Karelin still lives with his wife and three children
in his hometown Novosibirsk, where his upbringing was by all
accounts Lincolnesque: besides being the son of a truck driver, he
grew up chopping firewood and fetching water from an outdoor well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karelin is humble, not like those other superstars. That makes
him unique,'' says Manedov, the cab driver.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Russian politics still lags behind the media slickness of its
Western counterparts, but it wasn't difficult to see Karelin was a
political consultant's dream. Putin's Unity party, needing a boost
in the polls in the run-up to last year's parliamentary elections,
recruited him to run on its slate. He and Unity won handily.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Kuznetsov, Karelin's longtime coach, denies the wrestler
had any interest in politics before the high-level Kremlin
officials came knocking on his door.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never chased it but he couldn't refuse the offer. They just
used his name,'' says Kuznetsov, who refused to identify the
officials.
</P>
<P>
   For all his professed distaste of the limelight, Karelin has
profited from it. The vaunted Soviet sports machine, like so much
other infrastructure in Russia since communism's collapse in 1991,
is a rusty wreck that can no longer shower athletes with perks. Yet
Karelin is by all accounts well-off financially. His image adorns
fruit-juice packages, billboards and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   And one vestige of the machine remains: government bonuses.
While U.S. sportswear manufacturer Reebok is the Russian Olympic
team's sponsor, Putin has promised the team's athletes US$50,000
for a gold medal, US$20,000 for a silver and US$10,000 for a
bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin laughs off rumors of presidential ambitions after, as
expected, his Olympic career ends in Sydney with another gold
medal. But with more success will no doubt come pressure to take on
the mantle of the Russia's frustrated dreams.
</P>
<P>
   It's not coincidental that the Russian media's latest nickname
for Karelin is the pet name of both of his political party and the
West's symbol for the once-feared Soviet Union: ``The Bear.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
