<HEADLINE>
`ENDURANCE`: THE BOOK, THE MOVIE, THE FLAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Endurance, the book: I was among the thousands of readers
captivated by Caroline Alexander's 1998 bestseller, ``Endurance.''
It's better to be born lucky than talented, but Alexander was born
both. While researching an ``adult children's book'' on Mrs.
Chippy, the cat who accompanied Sir Ernest Shackleton on his doomed
1914 Antarctic expedition, Alexander struck gold: a treasure trove
of glass plate negatives taken by ship's photographer Frank Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Shackleton's 20-month, ultimately successful quest
to march, sled, row, sail, and trek his 27-man crew off the polar
ice cap is one of the most gripping survival tales of the 20th
century. Alexander curated a Hurley show at New York's Museum of
Natural History, and wrote the text for the exhibit catalog. Her
reconstruction of the oft-told Shackleton saga was so crisp that
Alfred A. Knopf published it as a book that lingered on The New
York Times bestseller list for five months.
</P>
<P>
   --Endurance, the film: Hurley was not only the Endurance
photographer; he was also the ship's cinematographer. Included in
the 60 minutes of film he shot were scenes of the dog sled races
that Shackleton organized to preserve morale during the ice-bound
winter of 1915, and of the ship's masts collapsing under the
unforgiving pressure of the pack ice. As the book gained
popularity, Alexander and her longtime beau, documentary filmmaker
George Butler (``Pumping Iron,'' ``In the Blood'') started working
on a movie.
</P>
<P>
   --Endurance, the flap: Their first investor was Paula Apsell,
executive producer of WGBH's acclaimed science series, ``Nova.''
For $600,000, ``Nova'' acquired half of the deal, which was to
include a feature film, a two-hour PBS television special, and a
jumbo-screen movie for the lucrative IMAX market. Butler,
Alexander, and their film crew began outfitting an expedition to
retrace Shackleton's Antarctic voyage.
</P>
<P>
   Then the storm struck. Butler went out and raised another $3
million from Morgan Stanley. Suddenly, ``Nova'' looked like a
minority partner _ but it had no intention of playing that role.
``Nova'' decided that it wanted Butler off the project. Lawyers got
involved. Twice, ``Nova'' tried to fire Butler from his own movie,
and twice the Directors Guild reinstated him. Don't even ask about
the 'GBH lawyers chasing Butler down to Montevideo; no one is
supposed to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   Butler and Alexander finished working on their footage earlier
this year. Apsell wrote them a letter disparaging it, saying it
``never rose above the pedestrian.'' Nonetheless, for contractual
reasons, her name appears on the movie as executive producer. 'GBH
has some film, and $300,000, that Alexander and Butler believe is
theirs. They know they'll never see it. ``This has been long,
bloody battle,'' says Alexander, who apparently won't be sending
Christmas cards to Apsell and her producer, Susanne Simpson, this
year. ``This is a woman's story; this is estrogen-rich craziness.
These people (Apsell and Simpson) always get their way.'' A 'GBH
spokeswoman, speaking for Apsell and Simpson, says the principals
have ``differences that have unfortunately carried over into the
creative realm.''
</P>
<P>
   Where do we stand now? 'GBH now plans to make the ``Nova'' show
and the IMAX film without further input from Butler and Alexander.
Butler and Alexander have their movie, which has premiered to
enthusiastic audiences at the Telluride film festivals in Colorado
and in New Hampshire. It's a darned good movie, but it's not
perfect. Even at 94 minutes, it drags a little. And there's a hole
in the heart of the narrative: Hurley stopped filming, and stopped
taking large-format pictures, about halfway through the expedition.
The most dramatic part of the book _ the astonishing 850-mile
lifeboat voyage led by Shackleton across storm-tossed Antarctic
seas _ has to be recreated in the movie. This is one instance where
the pen is mightier than the lens.
</P>
<P>
   Butler made tons of money selling ``Pumping Iron'' into
theaters, and he's confident he can do the same with ``Endurance.''
Maybe. But the irony is that his movie is tailor-made for the
literate, historically minded public television audience. If only
we could all get along . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
