<HEADLINE>
US OIL SPIGOT OPENS, AND EURO GETS A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Awash in good times, and until recently awash in
crude oil, Americans have probably forgotten how slowly their
economy recovered from stagnation and worse before it took off. But
that's what happened. What's more, Americans have also forgotten
how perilous this yellow brick road has been at times.
</P>
<P>
   But that's also what happened, and each time the wise guys got
nervous, it was because international events made them so.
</P>
<P>
   This is the context for a fascinating week of geopolitics that
linked two of the key commodities in our already linked world _
currency and crude. There has been too little demand for Europe's
new benchmark monetary unit, the euro, and too much demand for the
cartelized supply of oil.
</P>
<P>
   We already know that Bill Clinton, Al Gore, and their advisers
spent hours talking through the president's decision to release _
for contractual replenishment later _ oil from the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve in order to avert a heating oil emergency in the
looming winter, to keep prices from rising any further and maybe
nudge them down, and to hope voters in the North remember the
vigorous response in November more than they remember the
disruptions that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans are probably less aware how much international
phone, fax, and computer traffic accompanied last week's
high-stakes move by the industrial world's giants to gamble on a
currency market intervention to halt dangerous, downside
speculation in the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic was not just among industrialized powers worried
about the euro's value and the potential of ridiculous oil prices
to halt economic growth. It was also among developing countries and
the export machines in Asia, equally worried about the health of
their customers. Even reasonably responsible members of the
ultimate export machine, OPEC, share that concern.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the oil and euro moves need to be seen as linked,
because they were. For proof you need look no further than the
statements made over the weekend by the Group of Seven finance
ministers and central bankers who were hanging out in Prague for
the latest International Monetary Fund conference.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan commentary in this country is welcome to chuckle about
an alleged flip-flop (presumably for Gore's benefit) by Treasury
Secretary Larry Summers on the president's decision. But it is
interesting that no such commentary marred a move by another
statement signatory, to wit Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that each had opposed a 60-million-barrel release
from the 570-million-barrel strategic reserve when crude oil prices
were in the mid-20s and OPEC had recently committed to moderate
production increases. But a 30-million-barrel release when the
price passed $35 and the additional oil was barely in sight was
another matter, as the weekend statements made explicit.
</P>
<P>
   The same reflection of reality also characterized their feelings
about responding to the pleas from across the pond and joining in
the intervention to prop up the euro. The United States has opposed
interventions as a general rule in recent years, but a euro testing
a value of 85 cents on its way south (its debut value was $1.17)
constituted a genuine threat to the international economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton era, that has consistently been the trigger for
action. We did it when Mexico's finances nearly collapsed and there
was brief danger of international contagion; we did it when
Russia's finances came even closer to collapse and there was even
more danger of spread; and we did it in the biggest test of all
when Asian currencies plummeted in value and many smart people were
predicting the kind of financial meltdown that would send the
United States into recession. For all those responses, the world is
still praising Clinton, Greenspan, and former Treasury secretary
Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Why should we behave any differently now, election season or no
election season?
</P>
<P>
   Europe's ability to maintain its late-starting economic recovery
was in jeopardy, and the peril was made more extreme by the spike
in oil prices, which has provoked protest on a much larger scale
than here.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the initially positive market responses to the oil and
currency moves, the near-term future makes for pointless
speculating. Those who speculate for a living, however, are again
on notice that a nearly a decade's worth of successful
industrialized world resolve is again on the table.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, George W. Bush offers no home heating oil supply
for the inventory-depleted North and Midwest, an income tax cut
that would drive up interest rates far more than incomes, no
understanding of international codependence, indifference to
national debt reduction, and an allies-be-damned approach to
everything from Kosovo and Bosnia to missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Call him Pat Buchanan in a three-piece suit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Thomas Oliphant's e-mail address is oliphant(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
