<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH ABOUT FACTOID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was innocently amusing his readers, just punctuating his
column with some Olympic factoids, he thought. So my colleague Alex
Beam was surprised when two indignant readers let him know that as
far as they were concerned, the tidbits of information he was
handing out were facts, not factoids _ true, not false or dubious
assertions.
</P>
<P>
   So what is a factoid these days? Etymologically speaking, Beam's
readers have it right. An ovoid is something egg-shaped, but not an
egg; a humanoid resembles a human but isn't; a rhomboid is not
quite a rhombus. The Greek ending -oid means ``having the likeness
of,'' so a factoid should be a near-fact, a sort-of fact, a dubious
fact.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Norman Mailer, the apparent coiner of factoid,
intended when he used the word in 1973: Factoids, he wrote, were
``facts which have no existence before appearing in a magazine or
newspaper, creations which are not so much lies as a product to
manipulate emotion.'' He forgot to mention press releases, like the
factoidal sales pitch that just arrived by e-mail: ``Studies show
that employees are happier and more efficient when their office is
filled with personal items that reflect their personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Dictionary makers would like factoid to go on meaning what what
Mailer said it meant, and they're doing their best. The Oxford
English Dictionary, which traces factoid from 1973 to 1992, defines
it as ``something that becomes accepted as a fact, although it is
not (or may not be) true'' and, adjectivally, as ``quasi-factual .
. . designating a a mixture of fact and supposition.'' Two
brand-new dictionaries prefer that meaning, too: Merriam-Webster's
Collegiate defines factoid as ``an invented fact believed to be
true because of its appearance in print,'' though it allows, as a
second meaning, ``a brief and usually trivial news item.''
(Incidentally, the searchable CD-ROM version of the M-W Collegiate
is an excellent source of true factoids: Searching by date, I find
that factoid debuted the same year as designated hitter, feeding
frenzy, gas guzzler, and no-brainer.)
</P>
<P>
   The fourth edition of the American Heritage Dictionary, also new
this month (and with all those little marginal illustrations in
color, for the first time) is sterner in its defense of factoid's
original meaning. Its second definition _ ``a brief, somewhat
interesting fact'' _ is labeled a Usage Problem, and followed by a
sober Usage Note explaining why facts and factoids should not be
confused. Only 43 percent of the dictionary's usage panel _ a group
that includes humorist David Sedaris and fearless flier Erica Jong,
as well as more sober consultants _ approves of using factoid to
mean a minor bit of information, we are told: ``Many Panelists
prefer such terms as statistics, trivia, useless facts, and just
plain facts.''
</P>
<P>
   But list-loving Americans _ and English-speaking journalists
around the world _ are paying them no mind. Even in the '70s,
factoid was being used as, essentially, the singular of trivia
(trivium has already turned down the job). ``They've taken her life
and turned it into factoids,'' printed in the Washington Post in
1979, was not implying that the author of the book in questions had
fictionalized it _ merely that a complex tale had been greatly
simplified.
</P>
<P>
   And nowadays, despite the intentions of Mailer and the
preferences of usage panels, factoid to mean ``little fact'' is
whomping factoid as ``factlike datum.'' Yes, you still see factoid
used to mean ``lie'' _ the Washington Times last week said that
presidential aspirant Al Gore had ``made up not just an isolated
factoid or two _ but rather a whole story about an arthritis
medication called Lodine.'' But in the year 2000, some 90 percent
of newspaper citations (there's a factoid for you) use factoid to
mean ``factlet,'' an appetizer-sized bit of information, not a
dubious or erroneous statement. So entrenched is the factual
reading of factoid that a Houston sportswriter went so far as to
call something an ``alleged factoid.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely that the dictionaries are going to win this
round; factoid really ought not to mean fact, but it does, most of
the time. H.W. Fowler called this sort of thing a Sturdy
Indefensible _ an expression that couldn't be justified but was
indisputably English, used almost universally. His S.I.'s are not
ours, but we have attendees, who, by analogy with employees and
honorees, should not be attending but attended upon; we have
shoplifters, who don't lift shops; and we have factoids, which have
assumed the status of facts, logically or not.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: The Arizona Republic was recently taken to task
for labeling an item ``Random factoid.'' Writer Scott Craven
acknowledged that he was defying the dictionary: ``We'd like to
reassure you the facts in past `Random factoids' were true. Very
true. Extremely true,'' he wrote. ``We just like the way `factoid'
sounds.'' And so, apparently, do the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0127 </DOCNO>
