<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE DOPE ON OLYMPIC COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The search for an Olympic sport without a
doping controversy continues. On Tuesday, it led to the doorstep of
synchronized swimming, surely a haven for the weary and jaded.
</P>
<P>
   What could be safer? Hair gel doesn't make the ban list. Nor do
sequins, at least until someone discovers a way to swallow them and
go faster, higher, stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Kisseleva and Olga Brusnikina won the duet gold medal with
a lovely routine. They spun and slid under the surface so smoothly
that they barely made a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Kisseleva looked a whole lot chunkier than she
did in the Olympics. So she started taking a nutritional supplement
to help her lose weight. She said she got approval from the Russian
Olympic federation, which checked with the supplement manufacturer
and verified that her diet aid would pass a urine test.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story she told FINA, the governing body of aquatics
in August. Ephedrine, a banned substance, turned up in Kisseleva's
system at a meet in July, and she had to persuade FINA to shorten
the recommended suspension of three months so she could compete at
Sydney. The committee believed her explanation and let her off with
a one-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   With that reprieve, Kisseleva came and won gold. She received
her medal on the same day that little Andreea Raducan lost hers.
The 82-pound Romanian became the first gymnast to lose a medal
because of a positive drug test.
</P>
<P>
   She had an excuse similar to Kisseleva's. She had a cold. The
team doctor gave her a pill. It turned out to contain
pseudoephedrine, a stimulant like the one in the synchro star's
test.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials said they felt terrible about taking Raducan's
medal, and it's no wonder. She was the all-around gymnastics
champion, the queen of Olympic glamour. Now, the two
highest-profile events in the Olympics _ all-around gymnastics and
the 100-meter dash _ have produced dethroned gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Raducan's medal doesn't rank with the Ben Johnson scandal
of 1988, partly because the public has become understandably
cynical since then (Seoul was the Watergate of the sports world)
and partly because Raducan truly seems like an innocent victim.
</P>
<P>
   She seems very much like Rick DeMont, the American swimmer who
had to surrender his 400-meter freestyle gold medal in 1972 because
doctors told him that he could legally take asthma medication that
turned out to have illegal components. DeMont has been a
sympathetic figure ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Raducan certainly seems to have more in common with him than
humongous shot-putter C.J. Hunter or any of the weightlifters
who've been flunking drug tests as if they were advanced calculus.
</P>
<P>
   She's too small to be pharmaceutically enhanced, just as
Kisseleva appears too dainty to be on the juice. A gymnast and a
synchro swimmer? Blame the doctors, or the ridiculous scope of the
testing, which turns a cold pill into a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Except that no one is exempt. There are drugs to help every
athlete, to improve any kind of performance. Early in the Games, an
Australian newspaper published a chart of drugs, their effects and
side effects. It looked like a Wheel of Fortune game board, renamed
Drug of Choice.
</P>
<P>
   Archers and shooters look beyond reproach, right? Beta blockers,
which calm the nerves and steady the hand, can help them out. They
might improve a wayward golf game, too.
</P>
<P>
   The pixies of the gym, without discernible hips and breasts, may
look untainted. But their sport is believed to employ the most
pernicious doping tactics of all. So-called brake drugs, such as
cyproterone acetate, can retard adolescence. The absence of womanly
curves should not alleviate suspicion. It should sound alarms.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that athletes should be able to use drugs if they
wish, that their willingness to dope merely signals extraordinary
commitment, crumbles when brake drugs enter the debate. Most of the
beneficiaries are underage girls, often reared in autocratic
nations. Free will is the one thing they're not expected to
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is meant to imply that the Kisseleva and Raducan
lied about inadvertently doping. To this day, no one seriously
questions DeMont's innocence, so why challenge theirs?
</P>
<P>
   But the nutritional supplements that Kisseleva took raise
serious questions about the future of doping control. In Hunter's
defense, some have said that the steroid that appeared in his test
could have come from a legal supplement. Stanford swimming coach
Richard Quick found an adviser to recommend a supplement regimen
for his athletes, in the belief that they could achieve steroidal
effects without doping.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the line? Why are so many supplements, like the
androstendione taken by Mark McGwire during his 70-homer season,
available on the open market? And isn't it disturbing that athletic
officials went to such lengths to help a synchronized swimmer find
diet pills?
</P>
<P>
   All we really know is that no Olympic venue is safe from drug
talk. After her gold-medal performance on Tuesday, Kisseleva talked
about trying to vindicate herself, placing the blame for her brief
suspension on the manufacturer who misled her.
</P>
<P>
   So, as they ask athletes after great performances: ``What's
next, Maria?''
</P>
<P>
   She's not going to Disneyworld. She's going to court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
