<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-26 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN SHOWS OFF N.Y. CITY'S GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes a great city great? The answer can be found through
Jan. 7 at New York City's Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art and the Empire City: New York, 1825-1861'' explores the
visual arts in America during this time, chronicling New York's
ascendancy to the position of the nation's primary art center and
capital of culture, a role it has claimed ever since.
</P>
<P>
   By the second quarter of the 19th century, New York City _
already the nation's financial center _ was poised to become a
``world city'' on a par with London and Paris. With the completion
of the Erie Canal in 1825, which linked the Great Lakes and the
Atlantic Ocean via the Hudson River, the great port of New York
became the gateway to the West, assuring the city's commercial
preeminence. During the next 35 years, until the outbreak of the
Civil War in 1861, New York grew rapidly, becoming the ``Empire
City'' _ the largest city in the Western Hemisphere and the
nation's center of domestic and foreign trade, culture, and the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit includes more than 310 works, many brought together
for the first time, from around the world. Visitors will be able to
experience the moment when New York City first began to perceive
itself as the center of culture in America. Among paintings will be
the 1825-26 full-length portrait of the Marquis de Lafayette by
Samuel F.B. Morse. The portrait was commissioned in 1824 when
Lafayette, much loved in the United States for his role in the
Revolutionary War, returned for a grand national tour of the
country. While here he witnessed the opening of the Erie Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Ten galleries are filled with paintings, drawings, decorative
arts, sculpture, period jewelry (including pieces made by Tiffany
and Co. for Mary Todd Lincoln for her husband's inaugural ball),
even presentation boards from Frederick Law Olmsted on his
proposals for Central Park, which was under development in the
1850s.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which is being sponsored by Fleet, is the first one
the financial institution has sponsored at the Met. As such, Fleet
is offering its customers free admission to the Metropolitan Museum
for the duration of the exhibition by showing any Fleet ATM or
debit card. During September, Fleet is also sponsoring ``Museums on
Us!,'' a program that grants Fleet customers free admission to 37
museums throughout the Northeast, including the Metropolitan and
other museums in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is open daily from 9:30 a.m., except Mondays and
major holidays, to 5:30 p.m., except Fridays and Saturdays when it
is open to 9:30 p.m. Suggested admission is $10 adults, $5 students
and seniors. For more information, call 212-535-7710 or visit
www.metmuseum.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New map-guide &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a map, it's a guide, it's handy, it's colorful, and it's
made for touring. It is a Cognoscenti Map Guide, and these ``maps''
are now available for cities such as New York, Paris, Rome, London,
and other destinations. The New York map-guide, for example, offers
the ``best list'' of restaurants, sights, hotels, nightspots,
shopping, and entertainment. Produced in Cambridge, Cognoscenti
maps not only have the information you need but are weatherproof,
use clever icons as locators, and, as the company notes, ``are the
guidebook for the new generation of travelers _ stripped down,
revved up, and ready to go.'' In addition to the maps noted,
Cognoscenti offers nine others, at $7.95 each. For information,
call 888-826-4667, fax 617-666-8685, or write to Cognoscenti, PO
Box 380700, Cambridge, MA 02238. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Finding a room &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOTRES.com offers a Web site that promises to find a New York
City hotel room at discounted prices even during the busiest
tourist seasons. The company says it offers more than 30 hotels,
and visitors to the site simply choose a hotel or category of
hotel, and enter the date of arrival and length of stay. HOTRES.com
then responds with pricing and alternatives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Value of agents &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Premier Cruises suddenly shut down Sept. 14, passengers
aboard the Rembrandt who booked through Vantage World Travel of
Boston only had to look to a Vantage manager on board to help them
continue their vacation, which included a stay in Montreal, with
little inconvenience. Passengers on future trips were offered full
refunds and alternative vacations at discounted prices.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12, just about every airline in the United States
increased the fuel surcharge from $10 one way and $20 round trip to
$20 one way and $40 round trip on most routes, increasing the price
on most ticket prices by $60 or more, including airport surcharges.
Joe Galloway, American Society of Travel Agents president, noted
that the new surcharges ``are still excluded from the base ticket
price, many consumers are unaware that the tickets they are about
to purchase will cost quite a bit more than they thought.'' At
present Alaska and Southwest airlines have not imposed additional
surcharges. Galloway said, ``In minutes, a savvy travel agent can
suggest alternate carriers and routes of travel and compare the
price of all available flights. Ultimately, you may even save
enough money by using an agent to cover the price increased by the
carriers, and then some.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
New York in fall &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for ideas on visiting New York in the fall,
call for a free ``I Love NY Autumn Guide'' at 800-CALL NYS or visit
www.iloveny.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
St. Croix deal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Purchase tickets before Sept. 24 and enjoy St. Croix for as low
as $234 per person per ticket. The deal is good at St. Croix's
Finest, a collection of three oceanfront hotels with affordable
rates. The hotels _ Hotel Caravelle, Tamarind Reef Hotel, and
Hibiscus Beach Hotel _ offer special rates between now and Dec. 14,
depending on property. The air fares are valid through Feb. 1. Call
800-260-2603 or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   southerlandtours.com for details and restrictions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Canal celebration &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Union College in Schenectady, N.Y., is celebrating the 175th
anniversary of the Erie Canal with a major exhibit. The canal, once
referred to as ``Clinton's ditch'' _ a reference not to the
president but to the then New York governor DeWitt Clinton _ was a
major accomplishment for its day, with 363 miles and 83 locks,
almost entirely hand built. A merchant of the time described it as
``somewhat calculated to bewilder the senses.'' Through Oct. 29 the
college's Schenectady Museum will feature 122 items, including 31
drawings between 150 and 175 years old never before shown to the
public. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Free night &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buy a guidebook and receive a free night at one of more than
1,500 inns. Inside each copy of the 12th edition of ``Bed &AMP;
Breakfasts and Country Inns'' is a certificate valid at any of the
inns described in the book and valued at between $50 and $650
depending on inn. You must purchase the first night at regular
rates. The book is $21.95, but by mentioning the Globe the price is
$16.95 plus $2.25 for shipping (shipping for additional books is 75
cents each). For a copy, call 800-397-4667, fax 949-499-4022, or
send a check to American Historic Inns, PO Box 669, Dana Point, CA
92629. &QL; 
