<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY'S POPULARITY SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought New York City had lost its luster, think again.
</P>
<P>
   Last year NYC was the number one destination for international
visitors and moved past Las Vegas as the nation's second most
popular destination after Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is New York the best restaurant city in the world,
it's also home to the best culture, shopping, theater, nightlife,
and attractions,'' says a man who knows restaurants, Tim Zagat,
president of the Zagat Survey restaurant guides.
</P>
<P>
   Zagat was speaking not as a restaurant reviewer but as chairman
of NYC &AMP; Company, the city's privately financed tourism marketing
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exceeding all expectations, the 1999 visitor figures show that
what attracts millions of visitors from around the world is New
York City's amazing range of activities,'' Zagat added.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of visitors jumped 11 percent over 1998 to 36.7
million and is projected to top 38.4 million this year. Since 1995,
the visitor figures have surged 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Orlando has more visitors mainly because of that mouse,
but Mickey is also contributing to New York's visitor totals with
three shows within the great lights of the new, cleaned up, and
almost crime-free Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Disney, New York City has been, is, and always will
be a great place to visit _ there's no other city like it. Sure,
Las Vegas now has a New York _ and a few other pseudo destination
casino resorts _ but there's still only one Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   As Zagat says, it is home to the ``best'' and certainly the
amazing, as the city goes beyond skyscrapers, dining, theater, and
culture. ``More than anywhere else on the planet, it's the place
people go hoping to transform their lives,'' noted Kurt Andersen in
last week's New York Times Magazine's special issue on the city and
the people who have made it home.
</P>
<P>
   And for these reasons, anytime is the time to visit. But the
upcoming seasons of fall and winter are special. Fall marks the
beginning of the cultural season _ if you want to know why NYC is
the Empire City, take in the Metropolitan Museum of Art's exhibit
on the making of the Empire City _ and winter brings the magic of
the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your reason for visiting, chances are you'll find
yourself in Times Square; it's not known as the ``Crossroads of the
World'' for nothing. Some 27 million tourists annually visit the
30-block area.
</P>
<P>
   Yes it is overcrowded at times, but that along with the bright
lights and all the new attractions is what makes it so exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Times Square is where you'll find theaters ('99 was a record
year for Broadway), hotels (20 percent of NYC's hotels are here),
high-tech entertainment, TV studios, bright lights, and shopping.
Times Square has changed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Here's just a sampling of what you'll find in the Times Square
area: high-tech electronic and entertainment centers for all ages;
the ESPN Zone, a dining and sports center; NASDAQ Market Site where
you can learn about investing; TV studios for CNBC, ABC, and MTV;
even the World Wrestling Federation is here, and you can dine and
watch a live match.
</P>
<P>
   Museums are bursting with reasons to come. The Metropolitan
Museum of Art is featuring an exhibit that tells how NYC became the
Empire City; the American Museum of Natural History is where you'll
find the fantastic Rose Center for Earth and Space; and, beginning
Oct. 21, is ``Vikings: The North Atlantic Saga,'' commemorating the
1,000-year anniversary of the Vikings' arrival in North America;
even the New York Police have a new museum (25 Broadway between
Morris Street and Battery Place); beginning Thursday, the Museum of
Modern Art will focus on post-1960 works from its collection in
``Open Ends,'' the final exhibition of the MoMA2000 series;
beginning Oct. 5, the Whitney Museum of American Art offers a
retrospective of works by Edward Steichen, one of the greatest
photographers of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little of what is happening in Manhattan _ but hardly
all. The holiday season begins with the world-famous Macy's
Thanksgiving Parade; the Radio City Christmas Spectacular runs Nov.
2-Jan. 7; the Rockefeller Center Tree Lighting is Nov. 29 at 8
p.m.; and there will be great lights at the New York Botanical
Garden during its Holiday Garden &AMP; Train Show Nov. 24-Jan. 7; and
the Empire State Building will put on its own colorful show during
December and January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
