<HEADLINE>
SEQUEL TO DROUGHT BOOK WOULD BE THE SAME OLD DRY STORY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas drought is not over because it rained in a few places,
but talk of the drought might subside.
</P>
<P>
   That would be welcome news to Elmer Kelton, the San Angelo
writer who penned the fictional, but defining, book on dry Texas
weather, ``The Time It Never Rained.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's still been dry out here,'' he said from his home near
the campus of Angelo State University. ``We haven't had any rain
since June, so people I run into invariably ask if I'm going to do
an update, or additional chapter, or another book.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelton said he figures there really isn't any incentive to do a
new book on the seven-year drought of the 1950s. ``It would be like
a remake of an old movie,'' he said. ``There might be some new
faces, but it would still be the same old story.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's really nothing new to the story of Texas drought.
</P>
<P>
   In Kelton's introduction to ``The Time It Never Rained,'' he
opens with the ageless West Texas joke about the man who bet
several of his friends that it would never rain again _ and
collected from two of them.
</P>
<P>
   In an essay written this month by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, she noted that a child born in Texas who started
kindergarten this fall would not know anything but drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go again; parched, panting, having lived through
another one of the worst summers on record,'' Hutchison wrote.
``Temperatures averaged up to 5 degrees above normal over large
parts of our state through August. Central and West Texas received
less than 25 percent of normal rainfall in July, and parts of Texas
were without rain for a staggering 68 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Fort Worth, we staggered way past that mark.
</P>
<P>
   West Texans might be used to it, but not us.
</P>
<P>
   Texas historian Walter Prescott Webb once decided that the 98th
meridian was where the landscape changed in Texas. West of that
line people's lives were affected more by the weather, he said, and
it etched its marks on their characters and culture.
</P>
<P>
   That line cuts between Weatherford and Mineral Wells. The latter
city, by Webb's accounting, would be West Texas; Weatherford would
not be.
</P>
<P>
   But the real demarcation point between West Texas and the rest
of the state is more indefinite than Webb's declaration. Many
people believe that West Texas is out beyond towns such as
Breckenridge and Throckmorton and Albany. Some folks believe that
West Texas is more attitudinal than longitudinal.
</P>
<P>
   In this current drought, the lines are smeared illegibly anyway.
We've all suffered our share of blast-furnace heat and endless dry
winds.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, in her essay, tallied the loss of the state's No. 1
cash crop, cotton, at an estimated $285 million. Other losses
include $125 million in wheat and $50 million in forage crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hay production reached a standstill by mid-summer and
producers face soaring feed, water and added irrigation costs,''
Hutchison wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Agricultural Extension Service reports that, by the
end of August, Texans had suffered $595 million in agriculture
losses, and they are still counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with some people out on the land, and I think the
economics of this drought is worse than in the 1950s,'' Kelton
said. ``The prices of the commodities _ the sheep, goats, cattle,
crops _ haven't increased very much from the '50s, but it costs so
much more to produce them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelton said he knew that some ranchers had reduced their herds
to 25 percent of their normal numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But the talk of drought is dwindling a little now that fall has
inched its way across Texas, and showers have made grown people
gaze, open-mouthed from their office windows.
</P>
<P>
   Kelton appreciates the lull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drought is not one of my favorite subjects,'' he said. ``I've
said about all I ever want to about it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
