<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LL COOL J AGING WITH AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LL Cool J has the top-selling album in the country _ but, to
bite one of his most famous rhymes, don't call it a comeback, he's
been here for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``G.O.A.T. Featuring James T. Smith: The Greatest Of All Time,''
debuted in the top slot of Billboard's album chart, hip-checking
St. Louis upstart Nelly's ``Country Grammar'' out of the penthouse
for the first time in five weeks. Of course, having a rap album
enter the charts at No. 1 isn't news _ Eminem, Jay-Z, and DMX,
among others, have all done it. But LL Cool J gets big props for
accomplishing the feat nine albums into a career that began before
Lil' Bow Wow was born, before hip-hop blew up on Madison Avenue,
and when Eminem was just a skittish slab of bully bait in Detroit
named Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   While some troublemaking rappers are more likely to face 15-year
sentences than 15-year hitmaking careers, LL Cool J has enjoyed
longevity in a genre with a notoriously short attention span _
anyone remember Skee-Lo, Yo-Yo, or Speech? From the beatbox
minimalism of his first hit, ``I Can't Live Without My Radio,'' to
the rabbit punch of ``Mama Said Knock You Out,'' to his latest
slinky single, ``Imagine That,'' he has stayed current without
pandering to the bling-bling blahs of contemporary rap. And save
for the Beastie Boys, LL Cool J is the only rapper from hip-hop's
nascent years who remains a playa, and is still making vibrant,
vital music for a whole new generation of hip-hop heads.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, LL is one of rap's elder statesmen, and may be one of the
few who deserves to lay claim to the title, the greatest of all
time _ Vibe magazine calls him ``the Muhammad Ali of hip-hop.''
He's crossed over into a successful film career, but it's the music
that has sustained him, and he's done it all without a platinum
grill, waving a gun at anybody, or making headlines with ``Behind
the Music''-style excesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey yo, this is the infinite, intelligent, extravagant and
eloquent,'' LL says by way of introduction on this latest CD, his
most consistent effort since 1991's ``Mama Said Knock You Out.'' On
``G.O.A.T.'' there are lots of guest appearances, including DMX, Ja
Rule, Snoop Dogg, Method Man, Kelly Price and Prodigy, but LL is
always the center of attention. Cuts like ``Queens Is,'' and ``Back
Where I Belong'' are as hard-hitting as anything LL has done in
years. On ``Homicide,'' the CD's standout track, he laments that
murder in the inner city never garners the outrage or attention
afforded violence in the suburbs:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(lyrics style &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean this in a disrespectful way
</P>
<P>
   But Columbine happens in the ghetto everyday
</P>
<P>
   But when the (expletive) goes down
</P>
<P>
   Y'all ain't got nothing to say
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end lyrics style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, as usual, LL's got plenty to say. He smacks up
actor-comedian Jamie Foxx, his co-star in Oliver Stone's ``Any
Given Sunday,'' in unprintable terms, and just plain hurts
Canibus's feelings on ``Back Where I Belong.'' LL and Canibus have
been trading barbs in a manner reminiscent of LL's inspired
``feud'' with Kool Moe Dee back in the day. (And since LL's topping
the charts, and Kool Moe Dee hasn't had a hit record since the late
'80s, I guess we know who won the war.)
</P>
<P>
   Born James Todd Smith, LL Cool J first burst onto the scene in
1985 as a cocky 16-year-old with ``I Can't Live Without My Radio,''
his ode to that ultimate old-school accessory, the ghetto blaster.
With his Kangol, sweatsuits, fat-laced sneakers, and gold chains
heavy enough to anchor an ocean liner, he was a b-boy straight of
Queens, N.Y., which also produced his stylistic forefathers,
Run-DMC. With such instant classics as ``Rock the Bells'' and ``I
Need a Beat,'' he established himself as a rapper with a hard,
clear style similiar to Joseph ``Run'' Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more to LL than just block-rockin' beats. He was
rap's first sex symbol. He was singing the praises of the ample
female posterior on ``Big Ole Butt'' long before Sir Mix-a-Lot or
Juvenile, and dared to put a ballad, ``I Need Love,'' on his 1987
album, ``Bigger and Deffer.'' It was a masterstroke for someone who
has always been more lover man than gangsta, and he lived up to his
moniker, which stands for ``Ladies Love Cool James.'' (Of course,
having the sexiest pair of lips on earth certainly hasn't hurt
either.)
</P>
<P>
   ``G.O.A.T'' is proof that LL will stay at the top of the hip-hop
heap until he's ready to come down, and all indications are he's
loving the view. At a time when fellow pioneers like Ice-T and
KRS-One are releasing career retrospectives, LL isn't coasting on
his reputation, he's adding to his legend. Fifteen years into a
career that shows no signs of waning, LL Cool J may be bigger and
deffer than ever, still rockin' his peers, and puttin' suckas in
fear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
