<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      09-26 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITY OF TEARS THEY JUST HAD TO SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILBAO, Spain _ The sign at the off-ramp is irresistible:
``GUERNICA 9 Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go back,'' said Ron Sampson, and the van driver was
amenable to the detour. ``Of course we do,'' agreed Judythe Gitlin.
</P>
<P>
   That name plinked some memory chords within the group that had
been rolling through the Basque country of northern Spain.
Destination: Bilbao to goggle at the Goomongous Goog, that
glistening titanium-skinned leviathan somehow risen from a muddy
river, and whose straight name is the Guggenheim Museum. A big fish
in the little stagnant pond that Bilbao had been until its arrival
three years ago, the Goog makes the city a go-go-round for gawkers
from all over.
</P>
<P>
   But it had to wait a while for us. There was no ignoring the
intriguing highway sign, indicating that Guernica _ with its own
ties to the art world _ wasn't far away.
</P>
<P>
   For 63 years the name Guernica has been branded on the universal
human conscience (if there is such a thing), ever since a ghastly
air raid previewed the horror from on high that was in store for
mankind over the remainder of the century.
</P>
<P>
   In a time before television, and because it took place within a
police state, Franco's Spain, where information was tightly
controlled, the destruction of the Basque community near the north
coast might have gone largely unnoticed. The man who made that
forever impossible was Pablo Picasso, the Spanish artist
self-exiled in France.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso's huge oil portrait of terror from the sky, (11 1/2 by
25 1/2 feet), titled ``Guernica,'' quickly became known, eventually
an all-time renowned painting, an indelible reminder of brutality
as mirrored in the faces of Guernicans. It was put on display in
Paris shortly after the April 26, 1937, raid, and has traveled, now
belonging to the Prado in Madrid. I recall being chillingly
transfixed by it at New York's Museum of Modern Art some time ago.
It stays with you in funereal black, white, and gray.
</P>
<P>
   Guernica was especially infamous because the remorseless Fascist
dictator, Francisco Franco, called in foreigners' bombs on his own
people. To him the independent-minded Basques, siding with his
wartime enemies, were irritants, deserving of a jolt. (Some of
them, the assassination-minded separatists, still are troublesome.)
</P>
<P>
   Be my guest, was the message Franco gave his dictatorial soul
brothers, the German Hitler and Italian Mussolini, who had been
lending him a helpful air arm during the Spanish Civil War
(1936-39). Thus German and Italian planes, practicing for imminent
World War II, were directed toward Guernica, the spiritual home of
the Basque people.
</P>
<P>
   Franco denied all. Naturally. The truth came out after his death
in 1975 freed Spain for democracy. Plans were carefully made to hit
Guernica on a market day when bloodshed would be the greatest, and
1,645 perished, out of a population of 7,000, during the incessant
pounding of a long, vile afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But does a Guernica exist? Or is it just a name symbolic of a
tragedy, remaining only on canvas in a museum? Inland, away from
the main coastal highway, it does indeed appear in a pine-rimmed
valley, rebuilt, not particularly noteworthy in structure _ except
that the revered oaks, so dear to Basque hearts, are in place, and
the elder, a sapling in 1860, survived the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Boughs of an oak have traditionally sheltered Basque lawmakers
since the Middle Ages. Theirs was an outdoor legislature. Today the
territory's General Assembly meets in the severely handsome granite
Assembly House, that goes back to 1826, while the honored trees _
the Guernica Oaks _ stand in the surrounding garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represent our heritage,'' says a guard. ``There will
always be a Tree of Guernica (Gernika in the Basque tongue). To
make sure, we have three currently.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to a section of dead trunk within a pillared cupola, he
says, ``That's the oldest, a remnant about 300 years old. Its
successor, over there, was planted 140 years ago, and is healthy.
Thankfully, bombs missed it.'' Next in line is the baby, a mere 38.
</P>
<P>
   Decorated with large historic paintings, and boasting a
sprawling oak in stained glass, the chandeliered Assembly Chamber
is very formal. It must have been more fun for earlier
representatives casting acorns at each other, as well as their
votes, beneath the old oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   The new money-tree museum _ a whale of a building, and a gamble
_ with its roots in the brain of American architect Frank Gehry,
has enriched Bilbao, an otherwise undistinguished industrial city.
Underwriting the Goog (a branch of New York's Guggenheim Museum),
Bilbao and the Basque government took a $100 million fling that
paid off in tourism dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Gehrymandering of a tired town has perked it up in the form
of other new construction, and plans for more. A luxury hotel, a
music hall, and a convention center are going up in the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago Calatrava, the brilliant Spanish architect, has built a
feathery steel footbridge across the Nervion River that flows
beside the Goog. His delicate-looking metal works have brightened
Lisbon (a bridge and train station) and Milwaukee (an addition to
the art museum).
</P>
<P>
   ``This place,'' says a Goog guide, Ainhoa Telletxea, ``is what
you Americans would call `the franchise.' Bilbao needed
revitalization, and the Guggenheim started it. The price has been
recovered already. We will have over 2 million visitors this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling kinship with Gehry's gleaming gargantua of titanium
plating, my right hip of the same stuff tingles in admiration.
While Gehry has gotten rave notices for his work, I have only rave
notices for orthopedic architect/carver Tucker Aufranc, who
restored my maneuverability at the New England Baptist Hospita.
</P>
<P>
   The Goog, Gehry's dreamscape, seems to maneuver constantly as
you circumnavigate it on foot. Undulation is its occupation. It is
never still, flashing more curves than a chorus line _ ``sensual
contours,'' says my friend, Aurelio _ and heaving waves of metal
that bring to mind both Moby Dick and the Pequod's prow. Ahab would
try to harpoon it and end up feeling like Quixote.
</P>
<P>
   Offsetting the silvery dazzle of sunlight against the walls is
the gigantic rain-bowlegged guard dog designed by Jeff Koons at one
corner. A steel frame constantly emblazoned with fresh flowers, his
Fido is a 50-foot tall, barkless bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   Only the floors inside are flat. An interior of varied levels is
interrupted by precipices and peaks, canyons, vast galleries, and
lots of glass that takes two months to clean, a task that is
undertaken two or three times a year.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is trouble. The titanium is showing alarming
signs of rust that has startled the management, but is being
fought. Andrea Gerlin writes in the Philadelphia Inquirer, ``But
one thing seems clear: This creation of space-age glimmer and
technology is also a monument to the law of unintended
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the monument wear a rust belt? Aurelio, ever a diligent
scrubber, and crazy about the Goog, wants to volunteer for the
battle with a Teflon pad and Rustoleum. I tell her to leave her
name at the reception desk. ``Don't call them _ they'll call you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Getty Museum in Los Angeles, the Goog itself is the
objet d'art, rather than the collections on exhibit. Among the few
Picasso paintings is a blank space reserved for the expected visit
of honorable ``Guernica.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
