<HEADLINE>
HOW IT WAS WAY BACK WHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Lion King'' wasn't on Broadway and you couldn't buy a
counterfeit Rolex on the street. But despite those shortcomings,
1898 was an amazing year for a certain city that never sleeps. That
was when the boroughs of Manhattan, the Bronx, Brooklyn, Staten
Island, and Queens were officially consolidated into the colossus
known as New York City. Today's travelers might enjoy a look at the
way it was a little more than a century ago. According to the New
York Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   --The population was 3,350,000 _ less than half what it is
today.
</P>
<P>
   --The tallest building had 23 stories. (The tallest building
today has 110 stories.)
</P>
<P>
   --Thirty-five percent of New Yorkers were foreign-born and 7
percent were illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   --The Lower East Side was the most densely populated place in
the world. It was almost five times as crowded as the rest of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   --But if 1898 was a big year, it couldn't compare with what
happened in 1899. In that year, the city raked in $38,000 by
issuing permits for masked balls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: You may know that in New York City, SoHo stands
for South of Houston Street and that Tribeca is short for Triangle
Below Canal Street. But what does DuMBO stand for? (Answer at end
of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: Latinos and others call New York's Washington Heights
``Platano Heights'' because of the great number of Dominicans
residing in that part of town. Platano is Spanish for plantain, a
fruit that is plentiful in the Dominicans. (With thanks to Albis
Mejia of West Roxbury, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``You know what you learn if you're a New Yorker? The
world doesn't owe you a damn thing'' _ Lauren Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speedy: Bathtubs fill in 60 seconds at the Four Seasons Hotel
New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A mighty big ``if'': If the Great Wall of China started in New
York and went west, it would end in Topeka, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ye olde taxi service: Taxis made their first appearance in New
York City in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nosey: The Statue of Liberty's nose is 4 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You're a good exhibit, Charlie Brown: Beginning Oct. 7, the
Children's Museum of Manhattan will honor the late cartoonist
Charles M. Schulz with an interactive exhibit featuring the
``Peanuts'' characters and titled ``Good Grief!'' Youngsters can
scamper through Linus's pumpkin patch, navigate Snoopy's WWI Flying
Ace plane, and navigate kites so they'll avoid the kite-eating tree
_ something Charlie Brown never could do. For more information on
the yearlong exhibit, call 212-721-1234 or visit www.cmom.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? Down under Manhattan Bridge Overpass. (We
thank faithful contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As we noted last week, there are alternative explanations for
familiar expressions that some say originated aboard ships. Milton
Paisner of North Andover, Mass., for instance, tells a delightful
story that covers two phrases:
</P>
<P>
   ``At a country fair in England some years ago a con man spotted
a country bumpkin and called him aside. He said to the lad ...,
`You have walked around the fair and you have seen prime young pigs
offered for 10 pounds each. Now I have one of those pigs and
because I like you, I want you to have it, not for 10 pounds, but
for just one _ on condition that you take it home in this bag
without showing it to anyone else. That way, no one else will see
what a bargain you have.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The young man paid his pound and took his bag home. When he
opened it, he found a mangy old cat inside. What happened? He
bought a pig in a poke and when he opened it he let the cat out of
the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the same topic, Mary Roever of Hingham, Mass. writes,
``According to other sources, `mind your P's and Q's' was said in
every bar, tavern, and taproom in colonial Boston at closing time,
and referred to Pints and Quarts. This sounds much more
straightforward and logical than (a cruise line's theory involving)
jackets and pigtails, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian reader's suggestion that US residents call themselves
something else besides ``Americans'' (perhaps ``Usanians'' or even
``Bob'') continues to draw reader comment. Peter N. Antonellis of
West Quincy, Mass. writes, ``US citizens are called Americans
because the official name of our country is the United States of
America, which makes us Americans. ... All the people of the North
and South American continents are not Americans. ... They are
Canadians, Mexicans, Brazilians, Argentinians, etc., because of
their country, not their continent. Before anyone considers
`Usanians' or `Bob', we've already got a great name _ it's
American!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
