<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-EYEWITNESS-BOS &LR;      09-26 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EYEWITNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERGEN ON BEING A PRESIDENT'S MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Eyewitness to Power: The Essence of Leadership, Nixon to Clinton 
By David Gergen 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 382 pp., $26 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Gergen, whose lanky frame and wise counsel have stood
behind four US presidents, was distressed one day in 1983 by a
speech prepared for Ronald Reagan. The speechwriter, a Pulitzer
Prize-winner named Tony Dolan, was much more conservative than the
moderate Gergen, who served as a communication adviser to Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   With Gergen's prodding, the speech to evangelicals in Orlando
was watered down and almost certainly would have been forgotten if
Dolan had not stubbornly insisted on retaining a favorite phrase.
With Gergen ``reluctantly'' agreeing, Reagan went on to deliver
what was arguably the most important sentence of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union, Reagan declared in Dolan's words, was an
``Evil Empire.'' It must go. Eventually, of course, it did. Gergen
has since decided Dolan was wise to fight for the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Words alone, of course, did not tear down the Berlin Wall and
dissolve the Soviet state. But words are Gergen's business, and it
is to his credit that he tells this story on himself in his memoir,
``Eyewitness to Power,'' about serving Presidents Nixon, Ford,
Reagan, and Clinton. As Gergen shows, a cleverly crafted speech and
fine-tuned public relations campaign can at least start to turn the
course of a presidency. What he also shows is that presidents most
often seem to defeat themselves. Nixon had Watergate; Ford had his
Nixon pardon; Reagan had Iran-contra; and Clinton had health
insurance and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With some exceptions, ``Eyewitness to Power'' is not a
kiss-and-tell memoir, which may disappoint some readers. Anyone
looking for new dirt on Nixon, for example, will not find it in the
chapter titled ``The Bright Side.'' (To wit: Nixon was a visionary
who worked with a Democratic Congress for a moderate domestic
policy, and he opened doors to China). The bright side doesn't
sound so bright, however, as Gergen also repeats many familiar
tales of Nixon's faults, which lose little of their sting after all
these years.
</P>
<P>
   The book is at its best when it comes to Gergen's close-up view
of President Clinton. Gergen had been a longtime ``FOB'' _ Friend
of Bill _ and voted for the Democrat in 1992. But he never expected
to work for the Clinton White House. Then Clinton, who had suffered
through a disastrous first few months of his presidency, called
Gergen and said, ``I'm in trouble. I need you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gergen arrived with the hope that he could be a bridge to
Republicans on Capitol Hill, but his effort was derailed, in part
by the first lady. Gergen wanted a health insurance compromise that
moderate Republicans could embrace; Hillary Rodham Clinton wanted
her plan, which depended almost wholly on support from Democrats.
The president, stuck in the middle, got into shouting matches with
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clintons had talked that way in front of campaign staffs
and even gubernatorial aides for a long time, and their friends
ignored it,'' Gergen writes. ``But the White House is different.
One felt party to a massive violation of his privacy. Later on, one
of the participants told me that this happened frequently. In the
middle of a conversation, she would launch a deadly missile
straight at his heart and just before it hit, the missile would
explode, the shrapnel hitting the staff. He would respond, and
tempers would flare. Get over it, I was told. I never did.''
</P>
<P>
   One night in 1994, the explosion was louder than ever. When talk
of moderating the health insurance plan came up at a meeting, ``the
president exploded . . . his face was flushed with anger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't trust the Republicans and I am not backing down!''
Clinton said. ``We won't compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gergen was thunderstruck. ``At 10:22 p.m. tonight, health care
died,'' Gergen recalls thinking. And so it did.
</P>
<P>
   Gergen blames Hillary Clinton as much as Bill. She did not have
the background to develop a massive health insurance plan, and he
did not have the political prestige to pass it. But he succumbed
because, as Gergen writes, ``Does anyone doubt that he wanted to
placate her?''
</P>
<P>
   Gergen had long since left the White House by the time Clinton
had his affair with intern Lewinsky and lied about it. But Gergen
said that given what he knew about Clinton, ``it was not surprising
that he succumbed to the temptation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gergen remains proud of his service to Clinton but saddened by
the waste of the man's promise and intellect. Clinton has the
finest grasp of policy of any president he served, Gergen writes.
Clinton's work for a deficit-reduction package in 1993 helped pave
the way for economic prosperity, Gergen believes.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest frustration of this book is that Gergen mostly
keeps quiet about his strong relationship with Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee. Gergen met with Gore
every week or so during the year and a half that Gergen served in
the Clinton White House, discussing the world and the White House
privately over ginseng tea. ``No conversations I had over the
eighteen months in the administration were more enlightening,''
Gergen writes.
</P>
<P>
   And what did Gore say? Gergen, perhaps not wanting to upset yet
another potential boss, doesn't enlighten his readers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that lapse, whoever wins the election in November would
do well to read this book carefully. It is subtitled ``the essence
of leadership,'' but it is filled with warnings about the mistakes
and pitfalls that seem to be repeated by every president. Perhaps
the biggest mistake for an incoming president would be to ignore
what Gergen has seen and learned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
