<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6133 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-MARTINEZ-ARGENTINA-SC     09-26 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-ARGENTINA-SCANDAL-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL IN THE ARGENTINEAN SENATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Wednesday, Sept. 27, or thereafter.) 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's MARTINEZ COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the MARTINEZ COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ 
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, N.J. _ Over the last 70 years government crises
in Argentina were not notable so much for the things that happened
as for what was prevented from happening.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of allegations and even proven claims of corruption,
influence peddling, bribery and sudden illicit wealth were
reported. But most of those charges ended in nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The impression that guilt goes away with the help of government
power and the passage of time has sown such a skepticism in an
Argentinean society already disgusted with the absence of
accountability, that the advent of political adventurism is now a
real possibility. So, Argentina is a country whose future is
unforeseeable.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, what might not happen now could be far more serious
than what has happened already: In August a rumor surfaced, and
since been verified, that members of Fernando de la Rua's
government paid a number of senators _ it is believed to be between
six and 15 _ to ensure passage of a labor reform bill that had been
mired in Congress for months.
</P>
<P>
   The president himself appears to be innocent, but the same
cannot be said of his people. The bribery scandal, exposed by daily
newspaper La Nacion, revealed an amazing network of corruption that
has shocked Argentineans.
</P>
<P>
   If De la Rua does not identify those from his office who are
responsible for the bribes, every government institution in the
country, including the presidency itself, will be seriously
impaired. Surveys show faith in the president is still high, but
that confidence could disintegrate in much less time than it took
to build if the president holds back the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, it will be extremely hard to penetrate the web of
secrecy spun by corrupt senators and their partners and even some
sectors of their parties. But common sense dictates that it is not
impossible for the president to determine where the money came from
to buy the labor reform law, who was responsible for the payouts
and who accepted them.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, if even clean senators remain silent out
of fear of colleagues' revenge or of being smeared by the same
dirt, they too will appear as guilty as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   In the years before military takeovers, corruption was almost
unknown in Argentina. For sure, there was serious mishandling of
public funds, such as the extravagant printing of money in 1889 and
1890 during President Miguel Juarez Celman's administration, but it
didn't involve theft or dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   After 1930, the idea that power could be assailed not only by
arms but also by greed, became an attraction for the ambitious
elite. In some cases, public office changed from being what it
should be _ public service _ to being a source of benefits that
allowed functionaries to repay favors as well as pay off officials
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   The corrupt are not many in number, but those who pretend not to
see the corruption among their peers and have allowed it to
prosper, through perhaps some misguided sense of solidarity,
constitute the overwhelming majority.
</P>
<P>
   For today's bribery scandal in the nation's senate to finally
come to light, there must have been countless others before,
representing barely the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   With the perverting of power, came the perfecting of impunity
and brazen shamelessness.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, dozens of alleged cases of corruption
have been exposed by the press, and even by the U.S. Embassy, with
only an occasional public official prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation of illegal payoffs to the Swift Corp. in 1991 by
a brother-in-law of President Carlos Menem; the sale of tainted
milk by his former private secretary, Miguel Angel Vicco; money
laundering and the countless suitcases stuffed with money coming
and going through the Ezeiza International Airport (run at the time
by Ibrahim al Ibrahim, the Syrian husband of another of Menem's
in-laws); and the decision to sell the postal service to a company
owned by Alfredo Yabran, a mysterious friend of the government, who
ended up committing suicide in 1988 ...
</P>
<P>
   All these incidents were hushed up with the discreet removal of
the perpetrators after no hearings in any known forum, and with the
explanation from the presidency that the attorney general's office
could not find sufficient evidence to prove the charges.
</P>
<P>
   And, in all, it was the press that lifted the lid off the shady
dealings, not the authorities. The government's inaction or
complicity, together with judicial indifference, has engendered
greater public trust in the press than in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a trend that could be called a media-ization of politics
has developed. A vast number of public officials have turned to the
media for legitimacy and publicity. Thus, the politician who
manages to grab the headlines or appear on prime-time television
most frequently, is seen as the more effective and better
qualified.
</P>
<P>
   This has encumbered the media with the thankless function of
being judge and jury and, in so doing, has degraded the political
system: the press cannot and should not do the job of political
institutions, nor should institutions perform their duties with the
sole intent of impressing the media.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy readers' appetite for scandal, however, certain
newspapers, in a quest to beat corruption, fail to distinguish
between serious allegations of impropriety and irresponsible,
unfounded accusations.
</P>
<P>
   A cloud of suspicion currently hovers over all government
institutions, prompting the public assumption that ``they are all a
bunch of crooks,'' and that there is no alternative but to accept a
corruption that cannot be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to obsessive public opinion, the media is now guilty of
concentrating on today's newest scandal, while already forgetting
yesterday's big story.
</P>
<P>
   So, corruption cases that had only a few weeks earlier gripped
the nation, have faded into nothing. Few are interested now in the
trials of two close Menem associates _ Victor Alderete y Maria
Julia Alsogaray _ test cases to demonstrate that government
functionaries are not all immune to prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, a newspaper expose brought into question the integrity
of the U.S. political system, when it revealed illegal government
snooping into opposition party campaign offices at Washington's
Watergate Building. On that occasion, the U.S. Senate appointed a
special commission that, with the help of an independent counsel,
investigated the case and determined the guilt of people close to
President Richard Nixon, and even of the president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Could not Argentina exercise the same power?
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the Argentinean Senate will get a shot of fresh air
when members will be elected for the first time by public ballot,
and not through negotiations with provincial governments and
legislatures as before.
</P>
<P>
   But without a thorough house cleaning, unethical practices from
the past may die hard. The mounting corruption is simply too great.
</P>
<P>
   All that the State fails to clear up will irremediably affect
the future of the government and, above all, the faith of voters
who elected the government on promises of openness and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   What doesn't happen, from hereon in, will be much worse that
what has already happened.
</P>
<P>
   (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the author of ``The Peron Novel'' and
``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American studies
department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an editor
and journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
</P>
