<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOUT BETTY CROCKER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Who was Betty Crocker?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Betty Crocker was invented by the Washburn Crosby Flour Co.
in 1921 to answer questions from customers about baking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty was chosen because it sounded light, cheery, wholesome
and folksy,'' Susan Marks-Kerst writes in Hennepin History
magazine. Crocker's last name was chosen to honor former company
director William G. Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   The character began hosting radio shows in 1924, moved to TV in
the 1950s and writes a syndicated newspaper column today that
appears in 1,000 newspapers. Washburn Crosby merged with several
companies to form General Mills in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   To submit your own question, write to Ask Betty Crocker, One
General Mills Blvd., Minneapolis, MN 55426, or call (888) 275-2388.
</P>
<P>
   The column is available on the Web at
www.bettycrocker.com/ask/news.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many $2 bills are in circulation today?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.C.W., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: There were 583 million $2 bills in circulation as of February
1999, according to the U.S. Bureau of Engraving and Printing.
</P>
<P>
   The same report indicated that there is $486.3 billion in U.S.
currency in circulation, so less than 1 of every 400 dollars is
represented by those $2 bills.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau sells uncut sheets of $2 bills and other currency.
You can order a sheet of 32 $2 bills for $85, a sheet of 16 bills
for $48, 8 bills for $28 and 4 bills for $19.
</P>
<P>
   To order, visit the bureau's Web site at www.bep.treas.gov/store
or send a check to Bureau of Engraving and Printing, Mail Order
Sales, Room 515M, 14th &AMP; C Streets, SW Washington, DC 20228. Call
(202) 874-3315 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Bill Maher of ``Politically Incorrect?''
</P>
<P>
   _ C.C., New Milford. N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to him in care of Incorrect Inc., CBS Television City,
7800 Beverly Blvd., Los Angeles, CA 90036.
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to be in Los Angeles, you can request free
tickets for a taping of the show by calling the show's audience
department at (323) 575-4321 or visiting the Web site
abc.go.com/pi.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
