<P>
   POLIO _ This summer, world health officials - including the CDC
- acknowledged they would not meet an oft-stated goal of ridding
the world of polio by the end of this year. Today, (Sept. 27), many
of those officials leading the fight will join Ted Turner and other
big spenders who are helping to fund the effort, in a ``polio
summit'' to explore why the fight is not being won on time. The NYC
meeting is intended to redirect attention away from the
public-health failure and focus media attention on the last push to
eradicate polio - which WHO hopes to accomplish shortly. To set up
the conference, we take a look at why 15-20 of the 30 countries
which had polio at the end of 1999 still do and ask ``What's taking
so long?'' (McKenna, The Altanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POVERTY _ WASHINGTON _ WASHINGTON _ Americans enjoyed
substantial income gains for a record fifth consecutive year in
1999, with inflation-adjusted earnings rising to $40,816 for a
typical family, its highest level since income data were first
recorded in 1967, the Census Bureau reported Tuesday. The strong
economy also drove the poverty rate to its lowest level since 1979
-- with the number of poor people falling by 2.2 million compared
to 1998. The effect of the rolling good times were felt equally by
whites, blacks, Hispanics and other ethnic groups, according to the
income and poverty data. A national story with state inserts.
(Holmes, Cox News Service). 30.
