<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2191 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MINING-POLLUTION-HNS &LR;      09-26 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINING-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SAYS GOLD MINE LEAKS THREATEN LAKES, RIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thousands of pounds of mercury leaking from
dozens of old gold mines in eastern California's Sierra Nevada
range is contaminating downstream lakes and streams and triggering
health warnings on game fish, the U.S. Geological Survey reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings concerning tainted fish are the first in
California's historic gold mining regions, including the Sierra and
the Trinity-Klamath Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   A study released by the U.S. Geological Survey found that the
fish in the watersheds of the South Yuba and Bear rivers contained
mercury, a potent neurotoxin that can damage the nervous system in
humans.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted in the northwestern Sierra, also located
more than a dozen toxic waste sites at the mines that probably need
cleanup to stop the spread of mercury.
</P>
<P>
   California Environmental Protection Agency officials said Monday
they were helping the affected areas _ Nevada, Placer and Yuba
counties _ to issue public health notifications that would limit
consumption of fish caught in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Tested were fish in five lakes: Camp Far West Reservoir, Lake
Combie, Rollins Lake, Scotts Flat Reservoir and Englebright Lake.
Also tested were water, sediments and aquatic life in 14 streams,
including Deer Creek, a main waterway in the Bear River watershed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're recommending that everyone limit their
consumption of bass to one meal per month, particularly pregnant
women and children under 6,'' said Allan Hirsch, spokesman for the
state EPA's Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch added that people should limit consumption of other fish
species such as channel catfish, crappie, green sunfish, bluegill,
brown trout and rainbow trout, to one meal per week.
</P>
<P>
   The data still are relatively sparse, Hirsch said, ``but we felt
there was still enough information on mercury that we should
recommend some prudent consumption limits.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Geological Survey scientists gave the test results to the
state EPA in August. After reviewing for several weeks, the state
agency asked for more study. The U.S. Geological Survey made the
study public Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first startling find of mercury contamination in
the state. By 1999, California had issued warnings for 12 bodies of
water, including San Francisco Bay and the delta formed by the
Sacramento and San Joaquin rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Of 2,506 advisories against consuming wildlife in the United
States, 1,931 were for mercury. Forty states have issued advisories
for mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings are strictest for the most sensitive populations:
children, pregnant women, nursing mothers and women of
child-bearing age. Mercury _ particularly in the organic form of
methyl mercury _ can cause damage to the nervous system, including
impairing mental and physical development.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Alpers, a U.S. Geological Survey research chemist and
the chief scientist on the study, said there are many lakes in the
Sierra that have not yet been sampled but where gold had been
mined.
</P>
<P>
   At risk are lakes between the elevations of 2,000 and 6,000
feet, he said. Lake Tahoe, at 7,000 feet, and other high lakes are
above the former gold mines, Alpers said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the mercury from hundreds of abandoned mine tunnels
ends up in the Sacramento River by way of the Lower Feather River.
</P>
<P>
   While the test results are showing problems for fish and
wildlife, they haven't shown mercury at high enough levels in these
big rivers _ or their larger tributaries _ to contaminate drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Geological Survey, Alpers said, is advising the Bureau
of Land Management and the U.S. Forest Service where to clean up
mines on federal land that might be polluting the water.
</P>
<P>
   Miners used the mercury _ or quicksilver _ to separate out gold
at hundreds of mines in the Sierra Nevada from the 1850s through
the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   In California, most of the mercury pollution comes from the
hydraulic and dredging methods used until 1884. With high-pressure
water, the miners stripped the ground of soil, sand and gravel
above the bedrock. Slurries of water and sediment coursed through
sluices, or troughs, over mercury, which separated out the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that 10 to 30 percent of the mercury was lost in the
environment at every operation, 8 million pounds or more may have
been dumped, according to the U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
