<P>
   OLY-KARELIN _ PODOLSK, Russia - Forget Marat Safin. The U.S.
Open tennis champion from Russia may yet prove a flash in the pan.
Forget, too, president and judo expert Vladimir Putin. Smirking
about last month's sinking of the nuclear submarine Kursk with 118
sailors aboard during a recent CNN interview isn't likely to
improve his stature. No, for a country desperate to restore its
former greatness and grasping for a unifying symbol, Olympic
wrestler Alexander Karelin _ a.k.a. ``The Experiment'' _ is the
closest thing Russia has to a national hero. Entering the Sydney
Olympics, the 32-year-old Karelin boasts one of the most astounding
records in international sports competition: 12 European
championships, nine world championships and three Olympic gold
medals. The 285-pound, 6-foot-four-inch super heavyweight from
Siberia has not lost a match since 1987. (Nelson, Special to Cox
News Service).
</P>
