<SLUG> BC-FEAST-DUCHY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Roving Feast is a bi-weekly column by food writer
and cookbook author, Marlena Spieler. She will lead us through her
special world of food locally and abroad. &HT;     
 The Roving Feast: The Prince of Wales Grows a Very Fine Turnip  By Marlena Spieler  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; LONDON _  &LR; Last spring, as one of the contributors to BBC Radio 4's
``Food Programme,'' I was invited to the first annual Food
Programme Awards. It was an emphatically feel-good event, where
food media folk met organic farmers and organizers of community
food projects, all of us drinking Champagne and nibbling canapes in
St. James Palace, rubbing shoulders with His Royal Highness Prince
Charles and snagging those little lamb sausages as the tray glided
by.
<P>
   There were shepherds, cheesemakers, gardeners, people rescuing
heritage seeds such as ancient apple varieties in the Thames Valley
(there is a whole charity devoted to the cause) and winemakers.
</P>
<P>
   The venue was like a dream, of course _ a real palace, real
servants (lots of them), red drapes, red carpets and big carved
chairs that looked like . . well, like thrones _ they really did.
There was a lot of red flocking on the walls, and chandeliers
hanging on swags.
</P>
<P>
   The walls were decorated with portraits of ancestors _ former
kings and queens, and their dogs and their horses. This is not the
sort of thing we have in our home _ my ancestors were too busy
fleeing the Cossacks to have portraits painted of their horses.
Anyhow, who had a horse?
</P>
<P>
   If you're like me, you'll want to know the canape menu _ lamb
sausage chunks with artisan-made chutney; Mediterranean vegetable
tartlets; crisp crostini with shrimp; goat cheese and sun-dried
tomato tidbits; baby scones with Devon cream and jam; and _ what's
this? _ chocolate brownies! Naturally, I popped a few of St. James'
finest right into my purse. How often does one get a doggie bag
from the Palace?
</P>
<P>
   A marvelous time was had by all, the whole BBC gang, the award
nominees . . and Prince Charles was as nice as can be. So, when
several months had passed, and I received an invite from The
Prince's Duchy Originals, part of The Duchy of Cornwall, to visit
Highgrove, HRH's organic farm in Gloucestershire, I RSVPed pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up in Northern California with organic gardening in
the ether, Highgrove was almost a full circle _ a serious business
of growing vegetables, grains and animals and marketing the results
really deliciously.
</P>
<P>
   It's the delicious part of that last sentence that appeals to
me. What is the point of growing anything, and packaging anything,
organically or not, if it is not well grown and delicious?
</P>
<P>
   I am a sucker for good food, and I want my food grown and
produced (as much as possible) by people who enjoy their work in
life _ the likes of many of the Northern California farmers,
ranchers and the like profiled in the Food Section's At the Source
columns.
</P>
<P>
   Farm manager David Wilson took us tromping around the fields,
from oats to rye, potatoes to carrots, and charmed us completely
with his real love of the country. At one point we stood in the
middle of the herd of cows, and just stood there, listening to them
chew. (I do this sort of thing myself, whenever I have a chance.)
</P>
<P>
   Highgrove, despite its connections in high places, is a working
farm, not a bijou little showpiece. They even sell fruit and
vegetables in the local farmers' markets. It might be unlikely to
find HRH standing there selling you a turnip, but it is not
impossible. Highgrove even has a sustainable Vegetable Box Scheme:
each week Highgrove can send you a box of vegetables in season,
though unfortunately you do need to live in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that continues to impress me is that here is a person,
famous and rich, born into a position of incredible privilege who
could choose to do almost anything _ and he has chosen to grow (and
market) organic food. HRH is very involved in each step of the
business _ from sampling and developing products and deciding which
crops to plant, to interviewing prospective employees. One
applicant told me, ``Being interviewed for a job is alarming
enough. I thought I'd faint when I walked through the door and
there was the heir to the throne!''
</P>
<P>
   Duchy Originals was established to create products made from the
raw ingredients grown at Highgrove, HRH's home and farm. They're
sold at many Northern California markets, including Whole Foods in
San Francisco, Berkeley, Mill Valley, Palo Alto, and several other
Bay Area locations; Wild Oats in Berkeley, Sacramento, San Anselmo
and Sunnyvale; and Berkeley Bowl. The goodies are all organic,
quite delicious and traditional, such as my favorite, oatcakes _
rich and crumbly and tasting of oats. To those who are uninitiated,
an oatcake is like an oaty cracker, but made from oats. They are at
their best when eaten with a chunk of really good cheese and
chutney.
</P>
<P>
   Other products _ some available only in Britain _ include
organic bacon from their pigs, crusty sourdough bread from their
wheat, beer from their barley. From ingredients further afield,
there's thin bittersweet chocolate wafers and a drink called Lemon
Refresher _ a slightly bitter very lemony soda, something like a
grown-up 7UP.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Refresher is said to be a favorite of The Royals,
especially the late Lord Mountbatten. It's good with classic Pimms,
but I adored the tall glasses of fruity red refreshment we were
served at Highgrove _ a Duchy Cocktail, red with strawberries and
heady with Campari and gin. We drank glasses of this gorgeous stuff
as we lolled on the terrace enjoying the sun and _ British weather
being what it is _ dodging the rain. We ate our way through the
table, from the bacon to the sourdough bread, leafy salads and
homemade chutney, fresh mayonnaise and cold ham.
</P>
<P>
   We ate and ate and ate; then we drank some more cocktail and
stumbled, I mean wandered, around the gardens. Before I left, I dug
up a cache of earthy fresh organic potatoes for ``VegTalk,'' the
BBC radio program I was scheduled to do later that week. A few days
later, I cooked them up on the radio, in a way that I'm sure Prince
Charles hadn't thought of. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DUCHY COCKTAIL
</P>
<P>
   Red and fresh and tangy and bitter-sweet, this is a marvelous
warm-weather drink. It's not too alcoholic, and is very refreshing.
The amounts are adjustable, according to your taste. Do make it at
the last minute, though, so it will keep its freshness and fizz.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 (750 ml) bottle of Lemon Refresher (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup gin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Campari
</P>
<P>
   1 basket of strawberries, hulled and lightly mashed so there are
lots of pieces and lots of juice
</P>
<P>
   Lots of ice
</P>
<P>
   Sprigs of mint
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Pour the Lemon Refresher into a pitcher then pour in the gin
and Campari.
</P>
<P>
   Next, add the strawberries, which will fizz a surprisingly large
amount then subside. Add the ice to the pitcher and garnish with
mint. Drink right away.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Lemon Refresher, the Royals' favorite drink, is marketed
by Duchy Originals, and is available at Andronico's, Whole Foods,
Wild Oats and Berkeley Bowl. If you can't find it, use any not too
sweet, very lemony carbonated drink.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 170 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 16 g carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat, 0 cholesterol, 15 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MEXICAN MASHED HIGHGROVE POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   In the control room at the BBC, we ate this with spoons from a
communal bowl. Being radio, of course, no one could see us. It
makes a terrific side dish for a barbecue, picnic, Mexican-inspired
menu or a simple roast chicken. Highgrove potatoes, by the way, are
all-purpose potatoes, somewhere between a mealy baking type and a
waxy variety.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 poblano chiles, or 1 Anaheim chile + 1 green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 pounds potatoes, whichever are your favorites for mashing
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   10 cooked tomatillos, chopped, or several tablespoons very mild
green salsa (optional)
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lime (more if you don't use tomatillos)
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Roast the peppers over a gas burner until the skins char. Place
in a plastic bag and seal well. Set aside for at least 30 minutes.
Remove the peppers and peel them. Cut off the stems, slice the
peppers open and scrape out the seeds. Coarsely chop the flesh and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the potatoes, peel if desired, then cut into chunks. Put
the potatoes into a saucepan and add water to cover, along with 1/2
teaspoon salt and the sugar (it doesn't make the potatoes taste
sweet, but brings out their flavor. It will get drained, as well).
</P>
<P>
   Cook over medium-high heat until the potatoes are just tender.
Drain and transfer to a bowl. Mash the potatoes coarsely, then
blend in the tomatillos, garlic, olive oil, roasted chiles, cumin,
sour cream, lime juice and cilantro. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 310 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 46 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 13 g fat (2 g saturated), 2 mg cholesterol, 24 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
