<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2213 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-COOK'SBOOKS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOK'SBOOKS-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Cook's Books: Two Choices for the Jewish Holiday Table  &HT;       
 By Miriam Morgan 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Just in time for the Jewish High Holidays _ they
begin at sundown Friday with Rosh Hashanah and end at sundown Oct.
9 with the conclusion of Yom Kippur _ I was delighted to see a new
cookbook that promised a fresh approach to traditional holiday
meals.
<P>
   ``Healthy Jewish Cooking'' _ I couldn't help but be intrigued.
After all, much of Jewish food is renowned for its high fat
content. Silky chopped liver, puffy cheese blintzes, feathery matzo
balls _ these get much of their appeal from hefty doses of
 &LR; schmaltz  &LR; (rendered chicken fat), butterfat and the like. If
there's a way to reduce some of the calories and cholesterol yet
still maintain flavor, great.
</P>
<P>
   The book's author, Steven Raichlen, certainly has the
credentials to do it. Raichlen has won two James Beard Awards for
his books, numbering 20 and often focusing on the ``High Flavor,
Low Fat'' theme. His approach is solid, based on using cooking
techniques like roasting and grilling, eliminating egg yolks
whenever possible, using low-fat dairy products, and substituting
broth for fat to moisten and bind.
</P>
<P>
   The methods make sense, and the recipes that use them are simple
to follow. Unfortunately, the results can be disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Take potato kugel, for example _ ``Jewish soul food,'' Raichlen
rightly calls it. The best versions of this potato casserole _
which is essentially potato  &LR; latke &LR;  (pancake) batter spooned into a
dish and baked _ are crispy outside, velvety inside, with a perfect
potato-onion balance. All this is usually achieved by a good dollop
of  &LR; schmaltz  &LR; and  &LR; gribenes &LR;  _ chicken skin cracklings and onions
cooked in the rendered fat.
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen's version calls for Yukon Gold potatoes, which have a
buttery flavor and relatively creamy texture on their own. They're
grated and mixed with sauteed onions and garlic, along with chopped
parsley and celery leaves. Baking powder gives some lift and egg
whites (and one yolk) some glue. Vegetable cooking oil spray mists
the surface to crisp it.
</P>
<P>
   It's all well and good, but it's not potato kugel. The casserole
has little of the  &LR; tam &LR;  _ a Yiddish word roughly meaning depth and
soul _ that's the essence of the dish.
</P>
<P>
   The brisket to go with it _ the entree for a typical Rosh
Hashanah dinner _ is better, but not wonderful. Brisket needs to
cook a long time and then be cut into thin slices, which is easiest
to do when it's cool. For those reasons, it's best to cook it early
in the day or the day before, slice it and then reheat the slices
in the braising juices.
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen proposes a two-step cooking method, where the brisket
is taken out halfway through cooking, sliced while it's still firm,
then the slices put back in the roasting pan and braised until
done. It's a messy procedure, but OK if you can't cook ahead. The
seasonings _ dried fruit and sweet Concord wine _ are pleasant
enough but don't have the character to stand up to the beefy
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   The brisket recipe, like all those in the book, comes with a
nutritional analysis. Raichlen specifies removing all visible fat
from the brisket and skimming any fat from the juices before
serving, and maybe that's how the analysis can list just 469
calories per serving. The Chronicle's analysis, done with the ESHA
program used for all Food Section recipes, comes up with a more
realistic 578 calories per serving.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, many of Raichlen's other recipes are naturally
lower in fat and require less tinkering, especially those from the
Sephardic tradition. They use Mediterranean ingredients and pungent
spices and just aren't as rich as the Ashkenazic dishes _ those
from Eastern Europe _ that make up the dominant strain of Jewish
cooking in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Healthy Jewish Cooking'' is a noble effort, and for those with
serious health concerns it may be fine. Otherwise, better to have
the real thing and just less of it.
</P>
<P>
   For my own holiday meals, I'll probably turn to a book that
arrived just at press time _ ``1,000 Jewish Recipes,'' by prolific
author Faye Levy. A much more ambitious work than Raichlen's, it
includes traditional as well as contemporary Ashkenazic and
Sephardic dishes. It's a promising-looking compendium from an
expert in Jewish cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Healthy Jewish Cooking,'' by Steven Raichlen (Viking; 200 &LR; 
 &LR; pages; $29.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``1,000 Jewish Recipes,'' by Faye Levy (IDG Books; 625 pages; &LR; 
 &LR; $35). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HOLIDAY BRISKET WITH DRIED FRUITS &AMP; SWEET WINE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   One 3-pound brisket, trimmed of all visible fat
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 celery stalks, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped parsley (preferably flat-leaf)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups Concord grape wine
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups beef or chicken broth or water, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups dried apricots (8 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups pitted prunes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly score the brisket on both sides in a cross-hatch pattern
using a sharp knife. Season the brisket all over with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a nonstick frying pan. Add the onion, carrots,
celery, garlic and 3 tablespoons of the chopped parsley and cook
over medium heat until lightly browned, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon half of the vegetable mixture into a roasting pan or deep
baking dish just large enough to hold the brisket. Lay the brisket
on top and spoon the remaining vegetables over it. Add the wine,
broth and bay leaves. Tightly cover the pan and bake the brisket
for 11/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the brisket to a cutting board and thinly slice it
across the grain. Stir half of the dried fruit into the roasting
pan juices. Lay the sliced brisket on top. Arrange the remaining
dried fruit on top. Season with salt and pepper. Add broth as
needed to cover the meat and fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the pan and place it back in the oven. Continue baking the
brisket until the meat is tender enough to cut with a fork, an
additional 11/2 to 2 hours. Add broth or water as needed to keep
the meat and fruit moist. If there's too much cooking liquid,
uncover the pan the last 30 minutes to allow some of it to
evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the brisket to a platter. Using a slotted spoon,
transfer the fruit to the platter around the meat. Discard the bay
leaves. Pour the pan juices into the sort of gravy boat that allows
you to pour the broth off from the bottom, leaving the fat on top.
If you don't have one of these, pour the gravy into a bowl or
measuring cup and skim the fat off the top with a ladle. Spoon some
of the gravy over the meat and fruit, serving the rest on the side.
Sprinkle the remaining 1 tablespoon chopped parsley over the meat
and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 469 calories, &LR;   &LR; 31 g protein, 51 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 12 g fat (3.7 g saturated), 84 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 134
mg sodium. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
