<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Vertical Tasting Proves a Study in Development  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; In wine-tasting circles, you hear a lot of talk
about vertical and horizontal tastings. The former compares one
wine from a number of successive vintages, while the latter allows
tasters to evaluate one type of wine from the same vintage but from
different producers. It's the wine version of the games people
play.
<P>
   There is a tendency among some people to turn these tastings
into beauty contests, pitting one wine or wine type against
another. It's a difficult, if not impossible, exercise comparing
wines that, as the Aussies might say, are as different as chalk and
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   At Niebaum-Coppola's recent 25th anniversary tasting of 12
Cabernet Sauvignon-based wines from 1985 and 1995 _ both considered
excellent vintages _ winemaker Scott McLeod made it clear that the
aim was to see how advances in winemaking and grape growing, added
to changes in the wineries themselves, may have altered the styles
of the wine. For each year, there were six Napa Valley wines and
six Bordeaux wines.
</P>
<P>
   We began by tasting the '85s, knowing the identity of each wine.
But for the '95s, younger and less likely to show their identity or
heritage, McLeod and Larry Stone, sommelier for Rubicon, a San
Francisco restaurant in which Coppola is involved, wisely decided
to taste ``blind.'' Sometimes I worry about the use of that term,
because it once described someone in his cups, as it were. But for
wine tasters, tasting ``blind'' means that the tasting is done
without knowing the identity of the wines until the end of the
tasting.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing noticeable changes in the wines due to winemaking or
vineyard practices was difficult, but I thought all showed a
freshness beyond the fact that they were younger than the 1985s. As
a group, the wines had consistently deep colors, very ripe fruit _
a factor, no doubt, of the ripe vintage in both locations _ and an
attractive layering of concentrated flavors. These are wines that
drink nicely now, but will offer even more to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy to pick a favorite, but of the 1995 Napa Valley
wines, I liked the Stag's Leap Wine Cellars Cask 23, Phelps
Insignia, Chateau Montelena and Neibaum-Coppola Rubicon. My
favorite Bordeaux of the group were Chateau Pichon-Lalande, Chateau
Margaux and Chateau Lafite Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   The two '95s that generated the most fervent support and mild
indifference (not dislike) were Chateau Haut-Brion and Heitz
Cellars Trailside Vineyard _ the Heitz only because it was a
different wine from the '85 Heitz Martha's Vineyard tasted in the
first group and a wine noted for its characteristic eucalyptus
accent that wasn't evident in the Trailside Vineyard wine. Heitz
did not produce a Martha's Vineyard Cabernet Sauvignon in 1995.
Opinions differed on the Haut-Brion because of its style. I liked
the wine, but some tasters felt it was too lean and hard.
</P>
<P>
   While this kind of exercise can be viewed as so much stuffy
esoterica, it did allow serious wine collectors and tasters the
opportunity to see a dozen great wines at two different times a
decade apart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Visitors' Center &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chateau St. Jean, one of the premier wineries in the scenic
Sonoma Valley, has opened its new Visitor's Center just in time for
the 2000 harvest. The new wine tasting and retail room is at the
center of an elegant garden with terraces and fountains. Beginning
Oct. 1, the Chateau St. Jean Visitor's Center will offer a Wine
Education Program consisting of classes such as Wine 101 and
Blending Seminars.
</P>
<P>
   The Visitor's Center is open daily from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
Chateau St, Jean is located at 8555 Sonoma Highway (Highway 12) at
the northern end of Kenwood. For more information, call (707)
833-4134 or log on to  &LR; www.chateaustjean.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Malts &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Once the exclusive spirit of Scotland, single-malt whiskies are
now being distilled in New World sites such as Oregon, Nova Scotia
and Alameda. New World and Old World single malts are great holiday
gifts for someone who enjoys a wee dram.
</P>
<P>
   Jorg Rupf, German-born owner of St. George Spirits in Alameda,
has just released his first Single Malt Whisky. Distilled only from
the heart of the spirit run, St. George Spirits Single Malt ($40)
was aged in used Bourbon barrels, French-oak barrels and used port
wine casks. The result is a light-bodied whisky with lovely floral
and citrus accents over toasted oak.
</P>
<P>
   In style, the St. George Spirits Single Malt is more similar to
a Lowland or lighter Highland malt whisky. It is available in
limited quantities at select wine shops at at the distillery, 2900
Main St., Alameda.
</P>
<P>
   Glenmorangie, a single malt whisky from the northern Highlands,
has added an exclusive 21-Year-Old malt called Glenmorangie
Elegance to its extensive line of excellent whiskies. Presented in
a glass decanter, handcrafted by Scotland's leading glassmakers,
Caithness Glass, in Wick, to replicate the distillery's tall
swan-neck stills, Elegance is priced at about $400 and is available
at fine wine shops.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More Holiday Cheer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dolce, from Far Niente Winery in the Napa Valley, is one of the
best late-harvest wines produced in California. Made from
late-picked Semillon and Sauvignon Blanc grapes, the honeyed
dessert wine has been available only in 375ml bottles. Now, in
addition to the 375ml ($75), the 1997 Dolce will be available in
750ml ($150) and magnums ($300). Or, you can buy the three-bottle
set for $640.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
