<HEADER>
A2220 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FASHION-NYWOMEN5-HNS &LR;      09-26 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NYWOMEN5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOFTER SIDE OF SPRING 
WITH PHOTOS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
NEW YORK _ Showings of spring 2001 women's wear came to a end in a
swirl of girlishness. Even the usually subtle Calvin Klein could
not resist the pull of soft colors and sheer fabrics.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His collection alternates between _ and sometimes mixes _ soft
and crisp, as fabrics range from superfine jersey and tulle to
papery taffeta and radzimir. Colors include violet, plum, coral,
strawberry, petal pink dusty rose, aubergine, banana and lapis,
while neutrals run to buff, fog, asphalt, stucco, oyster and
plaster. Except for plaster, a bright white, all these shades are
softened, almost as if they were washed by the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's piece de resistance comes in bicolored, bateau-neck,
sleeveless dresses and tops, almost athletic in feel, in which he
inserts a wide strip of sheer fabric around the armhole, allowing
it to fall to a deep V down the side bodice. Think of the sheer
fabric as an air vent, although it almost looks like a sheer
T-shirt worn under a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Blouson shapes are evident in Klein's little taffeta jackets
worn with slim skirts, and although not visible from a distance,
there are micro stripes and shadow plaids.
</P>
<P>
   Separates of metalized calf or silk tissue radzimir suffice for
all but the dressiest evenings, and those are accommodated with
tricolor iridescent satin and silk tulle dresses or pale
sequin-block camisoles and dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan nailed down her message of soft graphic stripes even
before her show began, featuring invitations and program notes
sheathed in deep caviar and white pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   At last abandoning her cramped showroom quarters, she chose a
spacious tent at Bryant Park to show off ensembles that mostly
seemed deep-toned petals or handkerchiefs of sheer gauze or
chiffon. Topped with a structured jacket or coat, the fluttering
skirts give an ambivalent message of strength and femininity for
which Karan has long been known.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much to wear to work in either the Klein or Karan
collections; but for evening, Karan's collages of striped chiffon,
buff and pastel scarf dresses and sunset orange blouson dresses and
slips with diamante trim are like moths drawn to flame.
</P>
<P>
   Former stylists Josh Patner and Bryan Bradley are the designers
behind the Tuleh line, a brightly colorful conglomeration of styles
culled from vintage shops, styles one can imagine on Loretta Young
as she swirled down her staircase in the early years of television.
</P>
<P>
   The showing at Sotheby's lended credibility to the collection,
but heaping on that auction house's large and very expensive
necklaces was distracting on some of the otherwise delicate dresses
and separates.
</P>
<P>
   Tuleh includes lots of ruching, blousing, flutter sleeves, full
sleeves slit up the sides, scarves tied at the waist and bows tied
at portrait necklines. Lime, lavender, red, coral and orange
predominate in graphic, floral and dot prints, with some black
chantilly lace for evening.
</P>
<P>
   One of the prettiest outfits, among the confections such as
black strapless tiers of crystal pleats, is a fuchsia silk dress
with a skirt overlay of lime green beads worked in a lattice design
so that the fuchsia peeks through. Segue into shifts sprinkled with
floral beads and hems of wavy ostrich feathers, and you have the
whole of Tuleh. Short and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming trend from collections here is femininity,
achieved with a variety of means. Soft or fluttery fabrics. Pale
and pastel colors. Skin-baring cuts. Blousons, pleats, A-lines and
draping. And the most telling of accessories _ stiletto sandals.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
