<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 The Working Cook: Ragtag Naples Spawns a Jewel of a Pasta Dish  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; When it finally gets warm here and the tomatoes
are ripe, I think of summers in Naples, Italy, where my parents
were stationed at a U.S. Navy base while I was in college.
<P>
   Other people have culinary epiphanies in romantic places like
Provence or Tuscany _ the moment when they first taste good olive
oil, for example, and almost faint with the realization of what
they'd been missing all their lives. We had ours in the port town
that most Italians _ other than the Neapolitans, who adore their
city _ consider the nation's armpit, although it has undergone a
renovation of sorts during the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Down-trodden, crowded, lawless, beautiful Naples. We loved it
with a passion, and what we wouldn't do to go back there and eat
dinner outside in the cooler hours of the evening, looking out at
Mt. Vesuvius curve over the gorgeous, albeit polluted, bay.
</P>
<P>
   In Naples, you have culinary epiphanies in the most unexpected
places. For a summer job, I waitressed at a restaurant on the base,
where we served breaded shrimp and defrosted steaks to homesick
Americans and Brits. Sometimes, toward the end of the night, the
Neapolitan cooks, dismayed by our lame attempt at cuisine, would
gather money and send someone out to buy tomatoes and mussels.
After service, we happily slurped up their creation _ spaghetti
studded with chunks of sweet ripe tomatoes and tender, briny
bivalves.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much else involved in this quintessential Neapolitan
dish other than a generous dose of olive oil, garlic and a sprinkle
of parsley. The main issue is dealing with the mussels, which have
to be super fresh. Some stores sell them debearded, which means
they could be over the hill (they die soon after debearding). It's
usually better to scrub and beard them yourself, though that takes
an additional 20 minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   Today's other Working Cook recipes have nothing to do with
Naples. Cantonese-Style Turkey, Bok Choy &AMP; Shiitakes is for those
who like mild-tasting Chinese food. The simple formula for this
dish is based on my studies with Rhoda Yee at the California
Culinary Academy, who enlightens her students about the fresh and
light food that's popular in Southern China.
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla Soup with Sweet Corn has the warm-weather flavors of
lime, corn and green chiles. When saving leftovers, freeze the soup
only and add fresh chips and cilantro after reheating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   CANTONESE-STYLE TURKEY, BOK CHOY &AMP; SHIITAKES
</P>
<P>
   Many markets carry boneless, skinless turkey tenderloins. If you
can't find them, however, you may substitute chicken breasts. Serve
with steamed jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless skinless turkey breast tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   1 pound bok choy
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound fresh shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 one-inch knobs of fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cornstarch, sesame oil, soy sauce and a sprinkle of
salt in a wide, shallow bowl. Slice the turkey very thinly and add
to the cornstarch mixture, turning the slices to coat them evenly
with the marinade. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the bok choy into 1-inch lengths. Stem the shiitakes, then
thinly slice the caps. Smash the garlic cloves and the ginger with
the flat side of a chef's knife. Combine the sauce ingredients and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 teaspoons of the vegetable oil in a wok or large skillet
over high heat. Add 1 garlic clove and 1 knob of ginger. Stir-fry
for about 1 minute, or until fragrant. Discard the ginger. Add the
bok choy and mushrooms to the wok, stir quickly, sprinkle with
sugar and a little salt, then add the water, cover and let simmer
for 2 minutes, or until the bok choy is just wilted. Remove from
pan.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 2 teaspoons vegetable oil to the wok and place
over high heat. When the oil is hot, add the remaining garlic and
ginger and stir-fry for 1 minute, until fragrant. Discard the
ginger. Add the turkey and stir-fry for 3 or 4 minutes, until just
cooked through. Return the vegetables to the pan and quickly heat
through, then add the sauce. Simmer for about 1 minute, stirring
constantly, until the sauce has thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 210 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 6 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 454 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   SPAGHETTI WITH MUSSELS &AMP; SUMMER TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   This dish may also be made with fresh clams instead of mussels,
or a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 pound vine-ripened tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds mussels, scrubbed and debearded (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Start bringing a large pot of salted water to a boil for the
pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Thinly slice the garlic. Cut the tomatoes in half widthwise and
gently squeeze to remove the seeds, then chop the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Start cooking the pasta to al dente according to package
directions. When done, drain, reserving 1 cup of the cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   Place the mussels in a pot with the 4 tablespoons water and 1
tablespoon of the olive oil. Cover and bring to a boil, then cook
for 1 to 2 minutes, until most of the shells seem to be open. Do
not overcook. Remove from heat; leave covered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat the remaining 3 tablespoons olive oil in a large
skillet over medium-high heat. Add the garlic and saute for about 1
minute, or until fragrant. Add the tomatoes cook for about 2
minutes, or until just heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Add the mussels and their liquid to the tomatoes. Add the pasta
and half of the parsley; toss to combine (if it doesn't all fit in
the skillet, put everything in the pasta pot). Add enough of the
reserved pasta-cooking water to create a brothy sauce; warm over
low heat for 1 to 2 minutes. Season with pepper and salt, if needed
(the mussels provide salt).
</P>
<P>
   Spoon into bowls and top with the remaining parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Before starting, check the mussels and discard any dead
ones (they will have open shells that don't close even when you tap
them together, whereas live mussels will close their shells when
prodded).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 700 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 92 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 21 g fat (3 g saturated), 85 mg cholesterol, 376 mg
sodium, 6 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   TORTILLA SOUP WITH SWEET CORN
</P>
<P>
   This soup has a slight kick. If you would like to adjust the
heat level, add half of the chiles at the beginning, then add more
to taste about 20 minutes after adding the broth.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken legs (about 21/2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   6 serrano chiles, stemmed and thinly sliced (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped drained canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (7 ounces each) diced green chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Kernels from 2 ears of fresh corn
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce bag thick, hand-cut, salted tortilla chips (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   Lime wedges for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Finely chopped cilantro for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Remove the skin and any excess fat from the chicken legs,
then cut each leg in half at the joint. Season the chicken lightly
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Add the
onion and saute for 5 minutes. Add the garlic, chiles and oregano
and saute for 5 minutes. Add the chicken and saute until browned on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Add the broth and water and bring to a simmer, stirring to
dislodge the browned bits clinging to the bottom of the pot. Bring
to a boil and add the tomatoes, canned chiles and the bay leaves.
Reduce heat and simmer for about 40 minutes, or until the chicken
meat starts to fall from the bone. Add water as needed to keep the
chicken fully submerged in the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the chicken from the soup and let cool slightly, then
pick the meat off the bones (discard bones) and cut or tear it into
large bite-size pieces. Skim any fat from the top of the soup.
Return the chicken to the pot, add the corn and heat for 3 to 5
minutes, until the kernels are just cooked through. Add lime juice
to taste (1-2 tablespoons) and adjust the seasoning with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Break some of the tortilla chips into bite-size pieces, leaving
the rest whole to pass at the table.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve: &LR;  Place a few broken tortilla chips in each bowl.
Bring the soup to a boil, then ladle some into each bowl. Let sit
for 1 to 2 minutes to let the chips to soften.
</P>
<P>
   Pass bowls of lime wedges and cilantro and a basket of tortilla
chips at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Look for fresh chiles in the produce section of your
supermarket, or go to a Mexican foods market. Serranos are small,
tapered chiles, about 2 inches long, and are dark green to scarlet
when ripe. You may substitute jalapenos _ about 4 of them should
equal the heat of 2 serranos. &QL; 
Use the thickest, best quality tortilla chips you can find _ Casa
Sanchez is a good brand. Do not use Doritos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 240 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 22 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 12 g fat (1 g saturated), 36 mg cholesterol, 172 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
