 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Fritos Jalapeno Dip Is the Big Cheese  By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; With the Olympics, baseball and football all in
full swing, it's a great time for watching sports on television _
and for pulling out favorite snack foods like a big bag of tortilla
chips and some spicy cheese dip.
<P>
   Today's panel tasted six chile-cheese dips from cans and jars.
One emerged as the clear winner, with the other dips receiving
demerits for starchy texture and lack of cheese flavor.
Interestingly, water is the first ingredient listed on the labels
of all the products except the panel's favorite. The top product
has nonfat milk as its first ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fritos Jalapeno Cheddar &LR;  (9 ounces, $2.39 at Mollie Stone's)
was the overwhelming favorite, citing creamy texture and cheesy
flavor with a spicy finish. However, many panelists objected to the
neon orange color. Two thought it would be particularly good heated
and poured over a mound of tortilla chips for almost-instant
nachos. Three panelists would buy it; two might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Rankings dropped dramatically and second place went to
 &UR; Tostitos Salsa Con Queso &LR;  (151/2 ounces, $3.19-$3.39 at many
supermarkets). Some tasters liked the creaminess and spicy finish
(one commented she could taste chile peppers) but others disliked
the starchy quality and bland flavor. One would buy it, one might
buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place was a tie between  &UR; Fritos Chile Cheese &LR;  (103/4
ounces, $2.49 at Safeway) and  &UR; Taco Bell &LR;   &UR; Salsa Con Queso &LR;  (151/2
ounces, $3.39 at Safeway).
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists compared the texture of the Fritos Chile Cheese to
mayonnaise; others thought there was too much bell pepper and an
artificial cheese taste. One might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Many panelists thought the Taco Bell dip was too starchy and had
no discernible spiciness. One panelist described it as ``colored
mayonnaise.'' None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Trader Joe's and Padrinos, but they scored
too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Flo Braker, cookbook author and Chronicle food
columnist; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia Hart,
dietitian and food consultant; Roland Passot, chef-owner La Folie
in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. A perfect score for
any product would be 100. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
