<SLUG> BC-SECRET-GOAT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets of Success: Goat Cheese Rocks Zax's Fluffy Souffle  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Back when California cuisine was just emerging,
goat cheese became the lightening rod of ridicule and wisecracks.
<P>
   Today goat cheese has gone mainstream and is about as common as
Gouda; but no dish is as uncommonly good as the Twice-Baked Goat
Cheese Souffle at Zax.
</P>
<P>
   The souffle, which is baked in individual ramekins, then cooled
and baked again right before serving, may be served alone or
surrounded by lightly dressed greens such as arugula. It also
shines with baby spinach dressed with an apple cider vinaigrette,
apples, celery and fennel.
</P>
<P>
   The souffle puffs up again during the second baking. The
textures are seductive: A crisp, toasty exterior gives way to a
light and tangy interior. The recipe was devised by
husband-and-wife team Barbara Mulas and Mark Drazek, who produce
some of the best California-Mediterranean food at their 49-seat
restaurant, which is tucked away in an out-of-the-way location
between North Beach and Fisherman's Wharf. It's an exciting find.
</P>
<P>
   Mulas and Drazek met in 1986 at the California Culinary Academy
during the final weeks of classes and they've been cooking together
ever since, opening their restaurant in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   She has an affinity for savory dishes and creates most of the
appetizers and main courses. He is responsible for the desserts,
including one of the best apple galettes in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The modern storefront restaurant, decorated in soothing soft
colors, features bright art work and a soffit ceiling that casts a
warm glow over the dining room. It's a quiet, understated backdrop
to their vibrant food. The menu changes often, depending on what
the team can find on daily trips to Monterey Market in Berkeley.
Fortunately, you'll always find the goat cheese souffle on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Zax, 2330 Taylor St. (near Columbus Avenue) San Francisco; &LR; 
 &LR; (415) 563-6266. Dinner Tuesday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cake flour. &LR;  Finer than all-purpose flour, it gives the
Twice-Baked Goat Cheese Souffles their airy, refined texture. Since
the souffles are turned out onto a baking sheet and reheated just
before serving, the flour is the key to the texture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Breadcrumbs. &LR;  The ramekins are lined with breadcrumbs, which
help give the souffles structure after the first baking. In
addition, the crumbs provide a crunchy coating, which contrasts
dramatically with the soft interior of the souffles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TWICE-BAKED GOAT CHEESE SOUFFLE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter + butter for coating ramekins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup egg whites (about 7 large)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the rack in the center of the oven and preheat the oven
to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Butter eight 5-ounce ramekins, making sure to coat them well.
Fill each ramekin with the breadcrumbs then turn them over and tap
out the excess. Reserve any remaining breadcrumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the 3 tablespoons of butter in a stainless-steel saute pan
over medium-high heat. Whisk in the flour and cook for 20 seconds,
whisking constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk in the milk and cook for about 1 minute, whisking
constantly, until the mixture has thickened to the consistency of a
thin pourable pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Crumble 8 ounces of the cheese into a large mixing bowl. Pour
the hot milk mixture over the goat cheese and mix well. Add the egg
yolks and mix again. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer with clean dry beaters, beat the egg
whites in a large bowl until stiff peaks form. Fold half of the
whites into the cheese mixture to lighten it. Then gently fold in
the remaining whites.
</P>
<P>
   Divide half of the souffle mixture among the prepared ramekins.
Crumble the remaining 2 ounces of goat cheese and divide among the
ramekins, then top with the remaining souffle mixture, dividing it
equally among the ramekins. Sprinkle the remaining breadcrumbs over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Place the ramekins in a large baking pan and pour in boiling
water to come halfway up the sides of the ramekins.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for about 25 minutes, or until the souffles are golden.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the oven and let stand, still in their water bath,
for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a towel to hold the ramekins, run a knife around the
inside rim to loosen. Turn out the souffles onto a baking sheet.
The souffles may be held at room temperature for up to 6 hours
before the final baking.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, bake the souffles in a 425-degree oven for
5 to 7 minutes, or until deep golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 250 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 14 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (9 g saturated), 112 mg cholesterol, 320
mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
