r d BC-POPFOOD-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 2598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPFOOD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Fifteen Minutes of Fame: Julia's name will last but what about  the
newest breed of celebrity chefs?  By Kim Severson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Julia, what have you wrought?
<P>
   When you took up your cleaver and stepped behind the camera in
1962, could you have foreseen that People magazine would choose a
chef as one of the year's most eligible bachelors? That a
restaurant tell-all book would be on the New York Times best-seller
list? That an entire television network would be devoted to food,
featuring the spectacle of Emeril ``Kick it up a Notch'' Lagasse or
hunky Bobby Flay?
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 21st century, when more people than ever eat
out, the restaurant has become a pop culture icon. Not only are
chefs the new rock stars, but tales from behind the swinging
kitchen doors are obsessing people who a decade ago couldn't have
cared less about their waiter's opinion on child-rearing or how a
chef kicked a drug habit.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the media is jammed with books on the inner workings of
the kitchen, movies about chefs and Web sites devoted to cooking
gossip. What's next? ``Dishwasher: The Musical''?
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get a society more interested in food as art, people
will increasingly be interested in the artists,'' says Bertram
Gordon, a food historian and acting provost at Mills College in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Child believes American's new obsession is a direct reflection
of an American food renaissance. ``You've had so many other people
become celebrities, why not chefs?'' she asks. ``And we have so
many good-looking chefs around now.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, in the year 2000, if you're in the restaurant
business _ whether chef, waiter or reservationist _ you can be a
media hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fry man is thinking of getting a publicist,'' jokes New
York chef Anthony Bourdain, author of ``Kitchen Confidential,'' a
raucous trip through his life as a dope fiend, chef and kitchen
pirate.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; The New Obsession
</P>
<P>
   To get the full impact of how restaurant-obsessed our culture
has become, consider the arenas in which the professional kitchen
is taking center stage.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Movies &LR; . A couple of months ago, Richard Gere starred as a
restaurateur in love with Winona Ryder in the widely panned
``Autumn in New York.'' Last week saw the opening of ``Woman on
Top'' featuring Penelope Cruz as a heartbroken Brazilian chef who
comes to San Francisco and makes it big as a TV chef. These follow
a decade's worth of great food-based films, including ``Like Water
for Chocolate,'' ``Eat Drink Man Woman'' and ``Big Night.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Magazines &LR; . People magazine has become the chef's favorite
star vehicle. New York chef Marcus Samuelsson landed on the June 28
cover as one of the nation's 100 most eligible bachelors. In the
Sept. 4 issue, the magazine ran a two-page feature on French chef
Alain Ducasse who opened his eponymous dining room in New York,
America's most expensive restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Books &LR; . Bourdain's confessional has muscled its way onto
national best-seller lists, while Debra Ginsberg's ``Waiting: The
True Confessions of a Waitress'' is heading for additional
printings. Ginsberg has taped a stint on the new
nationally-syndicated ``To Tell The Truth'' and a segment on CBS
Sunday Morning with Charles Osgood, which will air in November.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Television.  &LR; The 24-hour Food Network, born in 1992 and now
reaches 50 million homes, has made superstars out of otherwise
little-known chefs. Consider that every week more than 150,000
people request one of the 1,500 seats at ``Emeril Live.'' And
Americans have latched on to the network's Japanese cooking show,
``Iron Chef,'' which has had American chefs Ron Siegel of Charles
Nob Hill and Bobby Flay as challenger contestants on the show. Even
Courtney Cox-Arquette's character Monica is a chef on NBC's
``Friends''.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Internet &LR; . The Food Network has the most popular food site on
the Web, with well over a million visitors each month. Other hot
Web sites include the saucy  &LR; ontherails.com &LR; , written by restaurant
employees;  &LR; www.starchefs.com &LR; , a chef's online fan magazine; and
 &LR; www.ifilm.net &LR; , which features goofy food-inspired Internet movies
like ``Pies Wide Shut,'' an R-rated spoof about a pastry chef.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Theater &LR; . ``Fully Committed'' is a one-man show about a
reservationist in a swanky restaurant. It's a hit in New York and
also has enjoyed a wildly successful San Francisco run. (It ends
Oct. 22.) ``Fanny at Chez Panisse,'' a play based on the life of
Alice Water's daughter, opened last week in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Etc. &LR;  If you're still not convinced that the chef has become
the hottest pop culture icon going, add this to the mix: The star
of a current Viagra commercial is a smiling chef overseeing a busy
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eat Out Now &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So why is this happening now? The leading theory is that since
there are more restaurants than ever and a record number of people
are spending more time in them, it's only natural that devotees
want to know more about the inner workings.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has some 3,700 restaurants _ about 400 opened in
1999 alone, according to the San Francisco Dept. of Public Health,
which licenses them. Nationally, almost half of all adults eat at
least one meal out a day, according to the National Restaurant
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The public's urge to get behind the scenes is the same one that
fuels the popularity of movie gossip magazines and movie studio
back lot tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like people being desperately interested in the
secret lives of movie stars and soap opera stars. (Restaurant
workers) have become the major focus of the entertainment life,''
says Bill Wallace, a longtime San Francisco food purveyor and chef
who now works as culinary director for the online company Tavolo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an opera lover and theater lover but I go to restaurants
10 times a week. So of course I'm interested in who is putting on
the show,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers say restaurants offer two things Americans
desire the most _ status and intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that being able to get a table in good
restaurant offers status, so does knowing the hottest gossip about
the city's most popular restaurant or chef.
</P>
<P>
   The dining experience also offers intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a good restaurant you are the star of the evening. Someone
knows you, calls you by your name and you have identity. If you
know the chef, there is this pretend intimacy and you are
somebody,'' says Rose Marie Morse, media agent for ``Kitchen
Confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers point to the fact that the restaurant experience
can even mirror a relationship. At the beginning, everyone is on
his or her best behavior. The diner and waiter strengthen their
relationship through the ordering process, which brings on a
sensual experience _ eating the food. But then the end comes. One
of you leaves and it ends up costing money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sort of a strange, enforced intimacy. I keep
comparing waiting tables to prostitution,'' says
waitress-turned-author Ginsberg. ``Food is one of these very
essential needs that has to be met but you're also getting this
human interaction. We live in this electronic age where everything
is data. Eating out is personal and intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Know It All &LR;
</P>
<P>
   America is more obsessed with food now than 20 years ago.
Although people are eating more convenience and take-out food than
ever before, enrollment in cooking schools, sales at high-end
cookware stores and the variety of goods in grocery stores all
continue to climb.
</P>
<P>
   People may not cook all the time, but they are more
knowledgeable about food. As a result, they're more interested in
the people who cook for a living.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's one theory.
</P>
<P>
   Balderdash, says Mimi Sheraton, author and former New York Times
restaurant critic. The current fascination with celebrity chefs and
restaurants is merely a bigger version of what came in the 1980s
with nouvelle cuisine and chefs like Wolfgang Puck and Jeremiah
Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The latest craze is not at all about food, she says, but about
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a love of celebrities so they're finding them in
all fields,'' she says. The elevation of chef to star has chefs
working out so they look better, hiring publicists and opening more
restaurants than many can handle, Sheraton says. However, she sees
a fall coming.
</P>
<P>
   `` `They're cruisin' for a bruisin',' as we used to say in
Brooklyn, because it gets to be ludicrous and the most ludicrous
right now is Alain Ducasse. He'll be famous for failing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon agrees that the current fascination is an extension of
the celebrity chef craze that hit in the late 1970s and early '80s.
That initial hit is tied directly to the rise of regional cooking _
and in particular California cuisine. But Gordon points out that
the popularity of everyone from Child to the latest Food Network
star parallels the rise of women in positions of power in American
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sleeper in all of this is the role women have had,'' he
says. ``Julia Child was successful in large part because her timing
was right. She had a message a lot of people _ women in particular
_ wanted to hear. In the same way, women are creating a culture
around food that's receptive to the kinds of celebrity we see
today.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It's the Food, Stupid &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But Child herself worries the public's current fascination with
chefs will give aspiring cooks the wrong impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it's difficult for the people who are going to
culinary schools because they all want to have TV shows and be
stars,''' she says. ``It's a 10-year discipline at least. It's
about like trying to be a doctor. You've got to train for many,
many years.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, Sheraton points out, when people appreciated
what this training meant, and went to restaurants for the food, not
for the chefs themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she and others agree, the chef-obsession will fade,
just as it has with other fleeting icons of American pop culture.
The public may not tolerate celebrity on its own, without something
_ great food, in this case _ to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What becomes dangerous,'' Sheraton says, ``is when (chefs)
think they know better than the public, when they forget they are
in the business of serving people food. We went through that in the
'80s. I'm holding my breath because I believe they are going to
make the same mistake again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; The Big Screen Spotlights Chefs and Their Passions &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Laura Perkins &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Food, glorious food. It may be primary and basic, but it's also a
mark of civilization and artistic expression. Here is a short list
of movies featuring restaurants or chefs that use food to explore
passion visually.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore &LR;  (1974). Ellen Burstyn won an
Oscar for her performance as Alice Hyatt, a funny, spirited widow
who takes a job as a waitress to support herself and her son. Alice
is horrified she has to take a job waiting tables at Mel's diner.
But there she gathers courage and self-respect. Diane Ladd is great
as the wise-cracking waitress Flo. The movie inspired the
long-running TV series ``Alice'' that starred Linda Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Big Night &LR;  (1996). Stanley Tucci and Campbell Scott
co-directed this intimate movie about two Italian immigrant
brothers struggling to make their restaurant a success. Tucci plays
Secondo, a pragmatic entrepreneur, and Tony Shalhoub is Primo, a
brilliant chef who is unwilling to compromise his art. The
brothers' deep, conflicted love is tested when they stage an
elaborate meal thinking trumpeter Louis Prima will visit and help
launch their restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The Cook, The Thief, His Wife &AMP; Her Lover &LR;  (1989). Director
Peter Greenaway's film is grotesque, horrifying and fascinating.
The stylized fable about love and revenge, civilization and
barbarism is set mainly in an opulent restaurant. We see food in
every stage, from carcass to preparation, fanciful display to
wrecked aftermath. Michael Gambon, the tyrannical thief, holds
court there with Helen Mirren as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Eat Drink Man Woman &LR;  (1994). Food is at the center of
director Ang Lee's story. Master chef Chu, played by Sihung Lung,
has lost his sense of taste and is losing touch with his three
daughters. A ritualized Sunday night dinner provides a stage for
the family to communicate complicated, tightly held emotions. The
footage of Chu preparing their elaborate meals is tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Frankie and Johnny &LR;  (1991). Al Pacino plays Johnny, a
short-order cook who falls in love with Frankie, a waitress played
by Michelle Pfeiffer, in this adaptation of Terrence McNally's
play. The play is set in Frankie's tiny New York City apartment,
but the movie lets us see a kaleidoscope of characters at the
Apollo Cafe. There was a lot of guff at the time about casting
Pfeiffer as a lonely, frumpy woman but she's vulnerable and
believable in the role.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Fried Green Tomatoes &LR;  (1991). This is a quirky, captivating
film that tells two tales of loving relationships. The frame story
is set in the present and focuses on the friendship between Evelyn
Couch and Ninny Threadgoode, played by Kathy Bates and Jessica
Tandy. The central story, set in the 1920s and '30s, is about Idgie
Threadgoode and Ruth Jamison, played by Mary Stuart Masterson and
Mary-Louise Parker. These women create a haven at the Whistle Stop
Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Who Is Killing the Great Chefs of Europe? &LR;  (1978) This
comedy-mystery directed by Ted Kotcheff opened the San Francisco
International Film Festival in 1978. The late British actor Robert
Morley plays a pompous gourmand, the chief murder suspect as famous
chefs are found dead in comic situations related to their
specialties. Jacqueline Bisset plays a sexy pastry chef and George
Segal is her ex-husband who owns a fast-food franchise called the
Humpty Dumpty Omelette Shops.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Not Ready for Prime Time: TV Fails to Cast Chefs as Stars &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Scott Clapp &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Kitchens and chefs are popping up everywhere from the Internet to
the New York Times best-seller list (see accompanying story). But
still our hero hasn't shown up as a network star. No prime time
equivalent to ``LA Law,'' ``NYPD'' or ``ER'' for our stove
warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Is Hollywood blind to this cultural tsunami? Where is ``Hill
Street Cafe'' or ``Thomas, the Rabbit Slayer''?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, restaurants and cooks have been central to plots over the
years, but other than ``Alice'' more than 20 years ago and
``Chef!,'' a British sitcom, most are quickly forgotten.
``Nightmare Cafe,'' ``It's a Living'' and ``Tattingers'' were never
even blips on the Nielsen ratings. Most recently, a pizza place
co-starred with two guys and a girl. Sadly, the pizza place took
the blame for poor viewership and was cut after only one season.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few successful shows have had a chef or cook as a major
character _ Mel in ``Alice,'' Monica on ``Friends,'' Nat from
``Beverly Hills 90210'' and Jack on ``Three's Company.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a cook or chef has made an impact in a one-time or
recuring role. Who can forget the Soup Nazi from ``Seinfeld''?
</P>
<P>
   But with the current fascination with restaurants, a chef or
kitchen is likely to show up soon in our prime-time sitcoms and
dramas. Having practiced law, worked with physicians and spent time
in commercial kitchens, I, for one, can't wait. If writers can make
the fairly mundane day-to-day worlds of law and medicine into
award-winning television series, I'd love to see what they can do
with the kitchen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
