<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, Sept. 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ENGLAND-FOODS (Westport, Mass.) _ The southern coast of New
England is the source for oysters so fine they are sold by name,
and for wines that are served in some of the leading restaurants in
Boston and New York. One of the best American blue cheeses is made
here, not far from centuries-old apple orchards and farms that are
experimenting with cutting-edge technology in fish farming. In
Westport, they have a plan to preserve their rural coastline and to
make the region as famous for its food and wine as Sonoma County in
California or the Hudson Valley in New York state. By Marian
Burros. (With map)
</P>
<P>
   KOSHER-RESTAURANTS (Undated) _ For truly observant Jews, kosher
restaurants were traditionally the only alternative to staying home
or going to grandma's. Now those old-fashioned places have given
way to more modern kosher options _ Chinese, Japanese, Indian,
Mexican and French steakhouses among them. And the newest additions
to the kosher scene are high-end restaurants featuring ambitious
dishes like bison, rack of lamb and whole roasted sea bass, with
wine lists and elegant surroundings. By Alex Witchel. (With photos)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSHER-CHEFS (Undated) _ Chefs who are finding new ways to make
kosher food stylish are not pushing the limits of dietary laws but
instead are simply rethinking their approach to it. By Melissa
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-OVENS (Undated) _ The new breed of oven combines
conventional and microwave technology to roast a chicken in 30
minutes, and roast it well. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-COOKBOOK (Undated) _ It's not a stretch to call Faye
Levy's 625-page volume, ``1,000 Jewish Recipes,'' a culinary bible.
It may be the only Jewish cookbook you'll ever need. Reviewed by
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL-FOOD-LAWS (Undated) _ Before Congress adjourns next month
it may vote on a bill that would prohibit state and local
governments from passing food safety laws that are tougher than
federal laws, as well as void any such laws that already exist. By
Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: Chef Eberhard Mueller's
poached halibut with herb vinaigrette. Written with Jack Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Scallops with curried
tomatoes. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINETALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: Legislation,
interstate wine shipping and the Internet. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: On the language used to
describe wine. By Erik Asimov.
</P>
