<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Wednesday, Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   STREISAND-ARTISTRY (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook on Barbra
Streisand, who is performing sold-out concerts this week in New
York. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP-AUDIENCE (New York) _ The patrons of the Brooklyn
Museum's new exhibit, ``Hip-Hop Nation: Roots, Rhymes and Rage,''
looked markedly different from the museum's typical weekend crowd.
They were younger, and more ethnically diverse, and a striking
proportion of them said they had a personal connection to the
material on display _ whether they were record company executives,
former graffiti writers, young aspiring deejays, or teenagers who
simply said they had never known life without hip-hop. By Nina
Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS-NEW-ACCESS (Undated) _ Two major photography institutions
_ the George Eastman House in Rochester and the International
Center of Photography in New York City _ have entered an alliance
that will give New Yorkers more access to one of the world's
greatest collections of photographs and motion pictures. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ROCK-CONCERT (Beijing) _ At the first mega-band rock
concert allowed to grace a stadium in the nation's capital since
the spring of 1989, a horde of bands making up for lost time forced
themselves upon a crowd that, at certain moments, didn't seem to
know what had hit them. By Jonathan Ansfield.
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE-SYMPHONY (New York) _ On the Nashville Symphony at
Carnegie Hall. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ For many Americans, Iran conjures
up the hostage crisis, terrorism, the crowds chanting ``death to
America'' and the fierce Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini denouncing the
United States and Israel. Elaine Sciolino, a New York Times
correspondent, shows a different Iran in ``Persian Mirrors.''
Reviewed by Ira Lapidus.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's probably fitting that
Takeshi Kitano goes by the nickname Aniki in his yakuza spectacular
``Brother,'' because he stirs up some serious anarchy on the Los
Angeles crime scene. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BEST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ If you thought yuppie arrogance and
entitlement had been satirized to death, you haven't met Hamilton
and Meg Swan (Michael Hitchcock and Parker Posey), the hysterically
doting dog owners who have the funniest scenes in Christopher
Guest's dog-show mockumentary, ``Best in Show.'' Reviewed by
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   TWILIGHT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ With ``Twilight: Los Angeles,''
the documentary and video maker Marc Levin has transformed Anna
Deavere Smith's much-honored performance piece ``Twilight: Los
Angeles, 1992'' into something both more and less than itself.
Reviewed by Dave Kehr.
</P>
