<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-PHILADELPHIA-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC PHILADELPHIA ROMPS INTO THE 21ST CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
  (NOTE: This column moved Sept. 26 for use the weekend of Sept. 30.)
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material, the ninth destination
column in the MICHELIN ON TRAVEL feature from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by MICHELIN clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photos and a map of Philadelphia are available on Newscom
or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By TERESE LOEB KREUZER 
 c.2000 by Michelin. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   American novelist Mark Twain once observed, ``In Boston, they
ask, How much does he know? In New York, How much is he worth? In
Philadelphia, Who were his parents?''
</P>
<P>
   This happens to be true. It's not so much that Philadelphians
are snobbish as that they're rooted in history. The past is alive
in Philadelphia in the most tangible way.
</P>
<P>
   In the oldest part of the city, down by the Delaware River, for
instance, 18th-century houses abound and every block _ and
sometimes every house _ has a plaque describing a person who lived
there or a momentous event that took place there.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of Philadelphia's grand old department stores,
Strawbridge &AMP; Clothier at 8th and Market Streets, devotes a front
window (where other stores might show their most enticing
merchandise) to a display stating that Thomas Jefferson once had an
office on that site.
</P>
<P>
   Some twists of fate conspired to make Philadelphia the time
capsule that it is. By the 1770s, Philadelphia was the richest,
most important city in the New World, second only to London in the
amount of trade that moved through its well-protected harbor.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States struggled into being, the Declaration of
Independence and the Constitution were drawn up and ratified in
Pennsylvania's State House, known today as Independence Hall, and
Philadelphia was the nation's first capital from 1790 to 1800.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress Hall _ a two-story, Georgian, brick building which
flanks Independence Hall _ the House of Representatives and the
Senate met for the first time. This is where the Bill of Rights was
drawn up and ratified, and where John Adams was sworn in as the
second president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many prominent Philadelphians hoped that their city would become
the nation's permanent capital and did all they could to make that
prospect enticing, but Adams moved the capital to Washington, D.C.
And so Philadelphia, once the geographic and financial keystone of
the colonies, became peripheral.
</P>
<P>
   The city remained an industrial powerhouse and an important
medical and educational center, but New York became the nation's
financial capital, just as Washington became the country's
political epicenter.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia brooded and slept, demoted by the end of the 20th
century to the fourth largest city in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But diminished importance (and diminished property values) had
unanticipated benefits. Often as much by neglect as by design,
historic buildings were preserved. Today, when people, individually
and in groups, seek their roots, these beautiful buildings are
buffed and prized as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia shines _ an endlessly fascinating city where the
ghostly figures of the past hobnob with sophisticates who crowd the
outdoor cafes, the top-notch restaurants and the world-class
cultural attractions. The Philadelphia Museum of Art (N. 26th
Street and Benjamin Franklin Parkway) has one of the most important
permanent collections in the country, while Philadelphia's beloved
Academy of Music, built in 1857 as an opera house and currently
home to the magnificent Philadelphia Orchestra, anchors a stretch
of South Broad Street called the ``Avenue of the Arts'' because of
its many theaters.
</P>
<P>
   However, these attractions are Johnny-come-latelys compared with
Philadelphia's colonial core.
</P>
<P>
   Any first-time visit to Philadelphia should begin with
Independence National Historical Park, an area of roughly 12 blocks
_ bordered by Second and Sixth Streets on the east and west and
Market and Walnut Streets on the north and south.
</P>
<P>
   Justifiably, this has been called the ``most historic square
mile in America.'' Here, you can see the First and Second Banks of
the United States (the latter, an architectural masterpiece),
Franklin Court, where Benjamin Franklin and his family lived,
Christ Church, where Franklin, George Washington and Betsy Ross
worshipped, and many other buildings of historic and architectural
importance.
</P>
<P>
   A Visitors Center at 3rd and Chestnut Streets provides
orientation and a suggested itinerary. Two days would not be too
much to spend here.
</P>
<P>
   The most important monuments, of course, are the Liberty Bell
which once hung in the tower of Independence Hall and which
summoned the people of Philadelphia to hear the first reading of
the Declaration of Independence on July 8, 1776, and Independence
Hall itself.
</P>
<P>
   Here, you can stand in the room where the Declaration was
ratified and the Constitution was discussed and signed. The silver
inkwell that the Founders used to sign the Declaration still
reposes on the desk in the front of the room and George
Washington's chair, with a sun carved into the back, sits behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   On a quiet Sunday morning (before the crowds descend), with the
sun streaming through the tall, broad windows, it's easy to imagine
the discussions that took place here _ and to wonder why these men
of property risked everything, including their lives, to sign the
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there are the details recounted in books and by the
Park rangers that bring these long-ago events to life: Caesar
Rodney, for instance, from Delaware, gravely ill, riding through
the night to break a tie in the Delaware delegation and vote for
independence _ or Ben Franklin, so old and sick that he had to be
carried into that room in a sedan chair, bringing his wisdom and
experience and his gift of compromise to the Constitutional
Convention _ and they say, when the time came for him to sign the
Constitution, crying silently.
</P>
<P>
   Across the park from Independence Hall, the Liberty Bell now
resides in a glass pavilion. Millions of people visit it every
year. Some stand quietly. Others photograph it. Parents bring their
children and hold the little ones up so that they can touch the
bell.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, history is not just an abstraction but an
electrifying force. It lives.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SERVICE BOX
</P>
