<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade) _ Developments following the Yugoslav
elections. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-U.S. (Washington) _ On the Clinton administration's
response to the elections in Yugoslavia and its emerging strategy
toward that nation. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-MONTENEGRO (Dateline to come) _ The head of Slobodan
Milosevic's party in Montenegro has begun distancing himself from
the Yugoslav leader and is talking about the future. By Carlotta
Gall.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, the Netherlands) _ The two Libyans
accused of blowing up Pan Am Flight 103 above Lockerbie, Scotland,
in 1988 were linked to the bomb during testimony on Tuesday by the
prosecution's long-awaited star witness, Abdul Majid Giaka, a
Libyan secret agent turned CIA informer. But the testimony was not
as strong as expected. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-MEET (Caracas, Venezuela) _ On the opening of the OPEC
summit meeting Wednesday, with emphasis on the political climate as
Saudi Arabia tries to be a moderating influence and Brazil says it
is prepared to increase production immediately to help stabilize
oil prices. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAELIS-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ The meeting between Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, late Monday night was more like a suburban dinner party.
They ate, drank and offered plenty of hugs and kisses. It was more
chemistry than substance, but might it help break the deadlock? By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAQ (United Nations) _ The air embargo on Iraq continues
to crumble, with Jordan announcing it will be the first Arab
country to send a flight to Baghdad, and the French sending a
second plane. The United States is trying to raise the issue in the
Security Council. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-WORLDBANK (Prague, Czech Republic) _ Global financial
leaders opened their annual meeting on Tuesday with the head of the
World Bank saying he shared the ``passion'' of the demonstrators,
who threw firebombs at the police officers stationed outside the
building where the meeting was held. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-PANAMA (Panama City) _ An interview with the foreign
minister on Peru's decision to allow its intelligence chief to seek
asylum here. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-VATICAN (Beijing) _ China launched a scathing attack on
the Vatican on Tuesday over its plan to canonize 120 martyrs on
October 1, communist China's National Day. China said most had been
agents of Western imperialism. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-POLITICS (Paris) _ Two letters addressed to President
Jacques Chirac have shed more light on the videotape scandal. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILMS (Undated) _ On the film industry's marketing
of violent films to children. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   N.C.-TEACHERS-MONEY (Concord, N.C.) _ In North Carolina, money
is the new incentive for student performance. Teacher bonuses of
$1,500 for all teachers, including the gym teacher, and student
shopping discounts are tied to test scores. As California and
others move down the same path, North Carolina's experiment is
being watched. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   GA-RACE-RELATIONS (Atlanta) _ In the Buckhead neighborhood here,
tensions between young black clubgoers and affluent white residents
have raised racial animosity in the city. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TERROR-TRIAL (New York) _ Federal prosecutors were scheduled
on Tuesday to present their case against Ihab M. Ali, a Florida
taxi driver who is among the Americans indicted in the Osama bin
Laden conspiracy. By Benjamin Weiser. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-RADIO (Undated) _ The nation's first Spanish-language
all-news radio station will begin broadcasting in the NY area
Wednesday. By Jayson Blair.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news category)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ Researchers have found that a
previously unknown gene seems to increase the chance of developing
Type 2 diabetes, the most common form of the disease. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SUN-IMAGES (Undated) _ A NASA satellite has taken the most
detailed pictures ever of fiery magnetic loops on the sun, perhaps
solving the mystery of why the sun's corona, or atmosphere, is
nearly 1,000 times as hot as its surface. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LEE (Washington) _ The Senate opened hearings Tuesday
on the Justice Department's handling of the case of Wen Ho Lee, the
former Los Alamos National Laboratory scientist. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-RATE (Washington) _ Poverty rate hits lowest level in 20
years. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court has announced the cases
it will hear this term, including an immigration case, a case on
the free speech rights of prisoners who want to represent other
prisoners in their legal affairs, and a cutting-edge technology
search case involving thermal imaging. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STRATEGY (Dateline to come) _ A Political Memo: As he tries
to topple an incumbent vice president after nearly a decade of
prosperity, Gov. George W. Bush has taken on the daunting task of
trying to convince the public that the nation is on the brink of
crisis. This week he is talking about an ``education recession.''
And laced through his stump speeches are references to rising crime
rates, stagnant farm prices and soaring oil costs. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PA-SENATE (Harrisburg) _ The Democrats' estimate that Sen. Rick
Santorum is ripe for defeat has not been born out so far in a rough
political year for his challenger, Congressman Ron Klink. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Dateline to come) _ On the campaign trail with
Vice President Al Gore. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT6
</P>
