<P>
   INSIDER-TRADING (Undated) _ A new Securities and Exchange
Commission rule will make it easier for corporate insiders to sell
their companies' stock without running afoul of insider-trading
laws.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ The Supreme Court has rejected
the Justice Department's request for a ``fast-track'' review of
Microsoft's appeal, sending the case to the appeals court in
Washington where Microsoft won in 1998. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-OUTLOOK (San Francisco) _ What at least another year
of litigation in the Microsoft antitrust case means for the company
and the industry. By John Markoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Eastman Kodak warns that
third-quarter earnings will be below estimates because of
lower-than-expected September sales. The company says it had been
expecting a strong month to counter the effects of higher raw
material costs, increased investment in digital photography and the
weak euro. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   3COM-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ 3Com is scheduled to report
first-quarter earnings after the stock market closes. By Lawrence
M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-CORN (Undated) _ The maker of bioengineered corn that
was not approved for human consumption has suspended sale of the
corn; the Senate is scheduled to hold a hearing on biotech food. By
Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CORPORATE-PR (Tokyo) _ Corporate Japan has suddenly
awakened to the need for crisis control. Alarmed by how companies
like Mitsubishi Motors, Bridgestone and Snow Brand fumbled in
public relations blunders in recent months, other companies are
calling in PR consultants, scheduling training sessions and
rethinking how they handle a public crisis. By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
