<P>
   EDITORS: The following photos of Tuesday's Olympic semifinal
baseball game between the U.S. and South Korea have been sent from
the New York Times News Service photo desk.
</P>
<P>
   (OLY19) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-BASEBALL-3 --
Tommy Lasorda, manager of the United States baseball team, before
their game against South Korea. The wettest and wackiest game in
Olympic baseball history ended with a solo homer in the ninth
inning to beat South Korea 3-2 in the semifinals early Wednesday in
Sydney. (Joey Ivansco/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY18) UNDATED -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-BASEBALL-2 -- Doug
Mientkiewicz raises his arm in celebration of his game-winning home
run as he is joined by other members of the U.S. baseball team
early Wednesday in Sydney. Mientkiewicz, the first baseman who was
banished to the Minnesota Twins' farm system this season, ended the
wettest and wackiest game in Olympic baseball history with a solo
homer in the ninth inning to beat South Korea 3-2 in the
semifinals. (Joey Ivansco/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY17) UNDATED -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-BASEBALL-1 -- Doug
Mientkiewicz celebrates his game-winning home run, early Wednesday
in Sydney. Mientkiewicz, the first baseman who was banished to the
Minnesota Twins' farm system this season, ended the wettest and
wackiest game in Olympic baseball history with a solo homer in the
ninth inning to beat South Korea 3-2 in the semifinals. (Joey
Ivansco/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Olympics photos include:
</P>
<P>
   (OLY16) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOFTBALL-7 --
Lisa Fernandez shows off her gold medal as Leah Amico, right, helps
to hold up the flag during the medal ceremony for members of the
U.S. softball team, Tuesday. At far left is Christie Ambrosi. The
American women's softball team completed a stunning comeback by
edging Japan 2-1 Tuesday night in extra innings to win their second
straight gold medal. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY15) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOFTBALL-6 --
Laura Berg of the United States, lying on the bottom, is
congratulated by teammates after driving in the winning run against
Japan, Tuesday. The American women's softball team completed a
stunning comeback by edging Japan 2-1 Tuesday night in extra
innings to win their second straight gold medal. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY14) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SAILING --
Olympic 49er class yachts from Germany and the Netherlands pass the
Sydney Opera House at the start of the final race of the series in
Sydney Harbour, Tuesday. The class was won by Finland with Britain
coming in second and the United States third. (Barton Silverman/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY13) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 --
OLY-SOFTBALL-5-B&AMP;W -- Laura Berg of the United States drives in the
winning run against Japan, Tuesday. The American women completed a
stunning comeback by edging Japan 2-1 Tuesday night in extra
innings to win their second straight gold medal. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY12) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOFTBALL-4 --
Members of the United States softball team after receiving their
gold medals, Tuesday. The American women completed a stunning
comeback by edging Japan 2-1 Tuesday night in extra innings to win
their second straight gold medal. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY11) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOFTBALL-3 --
The American women completed a stunning comeback by edging Japan
2-1 Tuesday night in extra innings to win their second straight
gold medal. Drenched by rain that grew heavier as the game reached
extra innings, Lisa Fernandez struck out eight and allowed just
three hits. Fernandez during Tuesday's game. (Barton Silverman/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY10) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOFTBALL-2 --
Japanese catcher Miyo Yamada walks off the field as Jennifer
McFalls is congratulated by her U.S. teammates after reaching home
on a hit by Laura Berg to give the United States the gold medal
Tuesday in the 2000 Summer Olympics. The American women completed a
stunning comeback by edging Japan 2-1 Tuesday night in extra
innings to win their second straight gold medal. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY9) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOFTBALL-1 --
Dot Richardson of the United States, foreground, leading the
women's softball team around the field after winning the gold medal
against Japan, Tuesday at the 2000 Summer Olympics. The American
women completed a stunning comeback by edging Japan 2-1 Tuesday
night in extra innings to win their second straight gold medal.
(Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY8) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOC-3 --Jeff
Agoos of the U.S., left, gets wrapped around Spain's Puyol, Tuesday
during their Olympic semifinal match. After advancing through the
tournament to an unprecedented and unexpected semifinal, the
Americans got a reality check Tuesday in a 3-1 loss to Spain.
(Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY7) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOC-2 --
Spain's Jose Mari scoring the third Spanish goal of the night
during their Olympic semifinal match at the Sydney Football
Stadium, Tuesday. After advancing through the tournament to an
unprecedented and unexpected semifinal, the Americans got a reality
check Tuesday in a 3-1 loss to Spain. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY6) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-SOC-1 -- Chad
McCarty of the U.S. looks on after Spain's Jose Mari, right, scored
the third Spanish goal of the night during their Olympic semifinal
match at the Sydney Football Stadium, Tuesday. After advancing
through the tournament to an unprecedented and unexpected
semifinal, the Americans got a reality check Tuesday in a 3-1 loss
to Spain. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY5) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-DRUGS-2 --
Shot put world champion C.J. Hunter, of the United States, left,
husband of Olympic gold medalist Marion Jones, right, during a news
conference in downtown Sydney on Tuesday. Fighting back tears,
Hunter denied Tuesday that he would ever take anabolic steroids,
saying his career means nothing compared to wife Marion Jones'
quest for five Olympic gold medals. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY4) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-DRUGS-1 --
Shot put world champion C.J. Hunter, of the United States, husband
of Olympic gold medalist Marion Jones, speaks during a news
conference in downtown Sydney on Tuesday. Fighting back tears, his
voice quivering with emotion, Hunter denied Tuesday that he would
ever take anabolic steroids, saying his career means nothing
compared to wife Marion Jones' quest for five Olympic gold medals.
(Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY3) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-BOXING-2 --
Felix Savon of Cuba, left, after defeating Michael Bennett of the
United States, right, Tuesday in a 91kg quarterfinals boxing match
in Sydney. The most anticipated fight of the Olympics turned
instead Tuesday into a showcase for Savon, the fearsome Cuban
heavyweight who has dominated amateur boxing for the last decade
with a right hand that lands with devastating frequency. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY2) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-BOXING-2 --
Felix Savon of Cuba after defeating Michael Bennett of the United
States, Tuesday in a 91kg quarterfinals boxing match in Sydney. The
most anticipated fight of the Olympics turned instead Tuesday into
a showcase for Savon, the fearsome Cuban heavyweight who has
dominated amateur boxing for the last decade with a right hand that
lands with devastating frequency. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY1) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- OLY-BOX-1 -- Felix
Savon of Cuba, right, during his bout against Michael Bennett of
