<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-BUZZ0927-COX     09-26 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BUZZ0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carl Lewis not going away
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Lewis has been in Sydney for a couple of weeks acting as a
corporate schmoozer, but he pointedly has avoided coming out to
watch the sport he dominated for 15 years. Lewis, who retired after
winning a fourth straight long jump title and ninth gold medal in
1996, said he would go to Olympic Stadium only to watch his friend,
Floyd Heard, later in the week. Maurice Greene, who has taken over
Lewis' role as the world's fastest human as the new Olympic
100-meter champion, feels the man known as King Carl cannot accept
relinquishing his throne. ``It's not a good thing,'' Greene said.
``He's doing what makes him feel good. The sport was on his
shoulders for so long, I really believe he didn't think it could go
on without him. Now he's seeing it going on, and I think he's
bitter. I hope he gets over it.''
</P>
<P>
   As tickets continue to sell at a fast clip, scalpers say those
for finals should command up to 30 percent over face value if
Australians are involved in the competition. For a non-Aussie
final, expect to pay a 20 percent premium. However, Closing
Ceremonies tickets aren't as much in demand. They can be found for
up to 30 percent less than face.
</P>
<P>
   While the ``wave'' is long gone as a crowd favorite at sporting
events in the U.S., it remains popular in other countries. At the
Olympic Stadium Tuesday morning, spectators kept a wave going for
several minutes. When it reached the media section and slowed down,
the crowd booed, but fans in the upper deck kept it alive.
</P>
<P>
   So, what does ``oi, oi, oi,'' really mean? ``Annoying, annoying,
annoying,'' said one Australian.
</P>
<P>
   The places journalist will go to get a story! As a ferry slowly
made its way to Manly, a North Sydney suburb, passengers noticed a
lone boat floating off to one side of the Olympic regatta. The tiny
motorboat was flying a flag that said ``Media.'' There were one
reporter and one photographer aboard, and they looked like they
were enjoying lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
