<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-DEVERS0927-COX     09-26 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DEVERS0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Devers starts her quest for Olympic medal
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - Gail Devers would show up at the start line in full
body cast, if need be. Adversity and injury seem to track Devers
like a puppy _ from a bout with Graves' disease, to never-ending
muscular aches and pains, to stumbling over the final hurdle at the
1992 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The injury du jour? A troublesome sciatic nerve, shooting jolts
of pain up her left leg and lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody always kids me, `You go to the track or for
treatment. Those are the only two places you go,''' Devers said.
</P>
<P>
   With the semifinal and final today in the 100-meter hurdles,
Devers ranks the favorite for gold after the best season of her
career. Sharon Couch has also advanced to the semis.
</P>
<P>
   The issue for both is whether they can hold up to the rigors of
two races in a day. Devers injured herself Aug. 25 at a meet in
Brussels, while Couch has labored all season with a strained
abdominal muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't let myself feel the pain,'' Devers said. ``This is
what I work for. I can't let the medal that keeps eluding me be
lost because of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   With Atlanta gold medalist Ludmila Engquist in retirement and no
other finalist from four years ago still in the field, the elusive
gold medal appears Devers' to lose.
</P>
<P>
   If the script had gone as planned, Devers might be lugging
around two Olympic medals from the 100 hurdles by now. She had the
race won in Barcelona and fell coming off the last hurdle. Then in
Atlanta, after the worst start of her life, she rallied only to be
nosed out for the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
