<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-CODE-WARRIOR-NEE     09-26 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-CODE-WARRIOR-NEEDED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ONLY A CODE WARRIOR OR XML GURU WILL DO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 By JANE FRITSCH  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In Seattle, an e-commerce start-up is looking for an Internet
Code Warrior. In San Francisco, a high-technology company needs an
XML Guru. In Albany, a computer maker has an opening for an
E-Commerce Solution Architect.
</P>
<P>
   Those job titles, from a recent batch of electronic help-wanted
ads, are at once grandiose and vague, designed to suggest the
limitless possibilities of careers in cyberspace. In a labor market
so tight that stock options and BMWs elicit a yawn, some personnel
managers hope that titles with a little panache will give them an
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Exotic job titles have been part of cyberspace culture since the
beginning, before computer geeks were masters of the universe and
were simply looking for respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weird titles are so much the norm in Silicon Valley that after
you've been here for any time at all, you stop noticing it,'' said
Paul Saffo, director of the Institute for the Future in Menlo Park,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The practice began at Apple Computer in the mid-1980s, he said.
Everyone was allowed to have two business cards, one with a formal
title and the other with any title they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Titles were more entertaining then, Saffo said. One Apple
employee called himself Director/Off-Planet Operations. But after a
junior employee put ``chairman'' on his second card, Apple put
limits on the practice, he added.
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest and most creative titles belonged to Guy
Kawasaki, who was known as Apple's ``Software Evangelist,'' when
the company was struggling for a share of the evolving personal
computer marketplace. Kawasaki joined Apple in 1983, when the
Macintosh PC was viewed as innovative but too slow for business
users.
</P>
<P>
   His job was to use the fervor of a missionary to persuade
software developers to write programs for the machines. Since then,
others have used the term, and others like it, but they have become
so commonplace that they now have little meaning, Saffo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first man to compare his lover's lips to a rose was quite
possibly a genius, but the second one and everyone after that were
quite certainly not.''
</P>
<P>
   Titles like ``visionary'' came into being because in
cyberspace's early days, people saw themselves as having a broader
mission than the ordinary worker, said Jan English Lueck, the
chairwoman of the anthropology department at San Jose State
University in California. ``It's very closely linked to a world
view that they're doing higher work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many in the computer industry do not take themselves
quite so seriously.
</P>
<P>
   At America Online, David Baker, a graphic designer, was known as
the Vice President of Cool in the mid-1990s. His job was to think
of ``cool and interesting ways'' to present the company's site to
users, said Tricia Primrose, a spokeswoman for America Online. And
Russ Leatherman, the voice and president of AOL Moviefone, is
commonly known as Moviefone.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the English language just does not contain words
adequate to describe what's happening in cyberspace, and so, it
would seem, new words must be invented. One is ``cybrarian,'' which
has forced its way into some acceptance. No less staid a body than
the American Library Association has begun publishing a
``Cybrarian's Manual,'' with sections on ``cyberciting'' and
``civic cybrarianship.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Geller Ettenheim, who holds the title of cybrarian at
Cybergrrl Inc., said she was a combination of librarian and
Internet specialist. Her services are available through
www.femina.com, a directory of international links to Web sites for
women.
</P>
<P>
   But some job recruiters offer a warning to companies tempted to
get too creative with job titles: potential employees may not know
what you're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simpler you make the title, the more likely you are to
attract a candidate,'' said David Garcia, a recruiter for Hall
Kinion, an information technology employment firm in Cupertino,
Calif. Someone searching for a job as a senior software engineer is
likely to search using those key words, he said. If the position is
advertised as a ``guru,'' the applicant may never see it.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Garcia said, the title should be
comprehensible. He said he once tried to fill a company's request
for a ``product manager for syndicated services,'' but no one was
able to explain what that was. ``I have no idea. I never did know.
And they wanted someone with two to three years' experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as he knows, Garcia said, the company is still looking.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
