<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. loses, but will play for soccer bronze
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - Just when it looked like Spain would embarrass the
United States in one of the biggest men's games ever for the young
Americans, they showed some of the pluck that has made them one of
the biggest soccer surprises of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up a 2-0 lead in the first 25 minutes of their
semifinal match at the Sydney Football Stadium today, the U.S. got
back one of the goals before halftime and made a brief game of it
against a squad that features promising talent for some of the top
clubs in Spain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But their ``pretty wild'' ride, as Josh Wolff referred to their
unexpected run though the tournament, ended three minutes before
the end of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   A tap-in goal by AC Milan striker Jose Mari in the 87th minute
provided the crushing blow by Spain in a 3-1 victory. The United
States can still win a medal on Friday when it meets Chile for the
bronze. In Saturday's gold medal match, Spain will meet Cameroon,
which shocked the heavily favored Chileans 2-1 in Melbourne today.
</P>
<P>
   Easy goals by Tamudo and Angulo threatened to inflict the kind
of searing wound the U.S. has suffered all too often against
top-flight international opposition. The swift, elegant Spaniards,
many of whom were part of last year's under-20 world championship
team, dominated possession and showed dangerous skills that the
Americans were slow to counter.
</P>
<P>
   And the Americans, who got away with numerous defensive mistakes
in outlasting Japan Saturday on corner kicks, paid for their errors
dearly in the early going. They also had enormous trouble keeping
up with Xavi, Barcelona's emerging playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
