<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCCW0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The U.S. kids have grown up
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - When Mia Hamm, Kristine Lilly and Julie Foudy were the
``kids'' of the U.S. women's soccer team in the late 1980s, they
really were kids. High school kids.
</P>
<P>
   None of them have turned 30 yet, but they're among the
undeniable veterans of the team. Earlier this year, Hamm and Lilly
became the first soccer players ever to make more than 200
international appearances. Foudy recently was tossed the captain's
armband and has always been the vocal leader of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The kids on the 2000 Olympic team are grown women. The youngest,
Michelle French and Danielle Slaton, are missing the first part of
their sophomore seasons in college and are here mainly to soak up
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Still others, like midfielder Nikki Serlenga, bound for Atlanta
in the Women's United Soccer Association, recently finished their
college eligibility and are awaiting their turn to play.
</P>
<P>
   But the retirement last month of icon Michelle Akers after 15
brave, but injury-riddled years, may have signalled that a gradual
transition already is underway.
</P>
<P>
   Three key performers during the stretch run of last year's
Women's World Cup do not have active playing roles with the team in
the Olympics. Akers, indispensable in the final two games of that
tournament, couldn't overcome shoulder surgery over the summer.
Former captain Carla Overbeck, so instrumental in the World Cup
final, and goalkeeper Briana Scurry, who made the memorable save
during penalty kicks, also have been injured all year.
</P>
<P>
   In their places are three faces who represent a gradual changing
of the guard on a team that has become the best in the world
because of its familiarity and camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see that many more people with 13 to 15 year careers
again,'' U.S. coach April Heinrichs said. ``You just won't see that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will play in Thursday's final against Norway, the
closest thing they have to a nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
