r s BC-OLY-SOFT0927-COX     09-26 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOFT0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After three losses, U.S. rallies to claim gold medal
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - The scrappy U.S. women's softball team arrived here as
favorites only to see its prospects fade quickly with an
unprecedented three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Backs to the wall, the United States had to win five games in a
row to repeat as gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional tournament for this team,'' said ace
pitcher Lisa Fernandez. ``We had to fight for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, with Fernandez on the mound, the team clawed its way
back to gold by defeating Japan 2-1 in an extra inning game that
saw the U.S. muster only one hit.
</P>
<P>
   But in the bottom of the eighth inning, with rain falling and
the score tied 1-1, pinch runner Jennifer McFalls came home from
second with the winning run when Japanese left fielder Shiori
Koseki misjudged and then dropped a fly ball hit by Laura Berg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great coming off the bat and when the ball came out of
her glove, I knew it was ours,'' Berg said. ``We have been very
unlucky this whole tournament and, finally, luck went our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Koseki waited too long to go back on the ball. She managed to
catch it, but the ball popped out as she fell backward on the
grass.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team then stormed the field in jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most amazing feeling to win this,'' Berg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always sweeter the second time around,'' added head coach
Ralph Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the game, however, it looked like Japan, which had
gone undefeated, might dethrone the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, the Japanese scored first when third
baseman Reika Utsugi ripped a home run to straight away center
field over Berg's outstretched arm.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. managed to tie the game in the fifth inning after
Japan's starting pitcher Mariko Masubuchi hit designated hitter
Michele Smith with a pitch. Smith advanced to second on a ground
ball and then scored on a single to right center by catcher Stacey
Nuveman.
</P>
<P>
   Nuveman accounted for the team's only hit and started the eighth
inning magic with a walk from reliever Juri Takayama. McFalls then
replaced her on first as a pinch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Dot Richardson, who blasted a home run to win the 1996 Games,
also walked. That brought Berg to the plate to hit the game-winning
fly ball to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it and started to run, I was watching her (Koseki)
all the way,'' Berg said. ``I saw her going back on it. Then she
just went down and the ball came right out of her glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez got the win. She was able to fan eight and give up
only three hits, while the Japanese left four on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to fight until we came out on top,'' Fernandez
said, adding that she was successful in ``nit-picking at the
corners.''
</P>
<P>
   She was aided by some good defensive play at shortstop by Crystl
Bustos.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the U.S. players talked about the emotional
roller-coaster ride they've been on during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been full circle, emotionally and physically,'' Nuveman
said. ``Winning tonight shows so much about the athletes that we
have, that we can win against those that have beaten us.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the tournament, Japan defeated the U.S. 2-1 in 11
innings.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the breaks went the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played our hearts out,'' said Smith, a member of the gold
medal team at the Atlanta Games. ``We have a lot of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
