<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2292 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-WRESTLY0927-COX     09-26 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLY0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lindland runs out of appeals
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - There was no arbitrator to save him. No appeals court
to overturn the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Lindland, who took Olympic litigation to new heights _ or
depths, depending on one's point of view _ ran out of adjudicating
luck Tuesday in the gold-medal match of 76 kg Greco-Roman
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The referee awarded Russian Mourat Kardanov three points on a
pair of early maneuvers. Kardanov made no attempt to pad his lead,
instead assuming a defensive posture that foiled Lindland to the
end. He never scored.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland became an Olympian after negotiating through enough
legal twists and turns to take up a week of ``People's Court''
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   He lost at the U.S. Trials to Keith Sieracki. Lost an appeal to
USA Wrestling. Won an arbitrator's decision that dictated a
rematch. Won the match. Lost when Sieracki found another arbitrator
to rule in his favor. Won when a U.S. District Court judge ruled
against the USOC, which had placed Sieracki on its roster. Won when
a U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals backed the judge. Won, finally,
when a U.S. Supreme Court justice declined the USOC's emergency
request on Sieracki's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The case was enlivened by Sieracki's accusations that Lindland
bit his ear in the Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland's success streak extended to Sydney. He won three
matches to reach the finals of a weak weight class. After the
semis, his opponent lost an appeal on a scoring decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Chandler, the U.S. Greco-Roman coach, acknowledged that the
ordeal disrupted Lindland's training and the team's psyche. Two
team photos were taken, one with each 76-kg'er.
</P>
<P>
   One of his obscure teammates, Garrett Lowney, secured a
surprising bronze in 97 kg. He outpointed Konstantinos Thanos of
Greece 3-1. Lowney is only 20 and a temporary convert from
freestyle wrestling. He whipped a five-time world champion in the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times Ne
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
