<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2293 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-NOTES0927-COX     09-26 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTES0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orestes Kindelan, the cleanup hitter on Cuba's two gold medal
teams, drove in three runs with a pair of singles for a 3-0 victory
over Japan in the semifinals. The Cubans will play either the
United States or South Korea, who met in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Canoe-Kayak
</P>
<P>
   U.S. flagbearer Cliff Meidl and Phillipe Boccara were eliminated
in the two-man, 1,000-meter kayak event. Meidl was picked to lead
the U.S. team in the Opening Ceremony to honor his recovery from a
30,000-volt electrical jolt. The U.S. four-man squad reached the
finals with a third-place finish in their 1,000-meter heat. But
</P>
<P>
   solo canoeist Jordan Malloch failed to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Cycling
</P>
<P>
   Leontien Zijlaard of the Netherlands won the women's road race
for her second gold medal. Americans Karen Kurreck and Mari Holden
of Colorado Springs, Colo., dropped out during the race. Nicole
Freedman finished 47th.
</P>
<P>
   Diving
</P>
<P>
   Defending Olympic champ Xiong Ni of China led after the
semifinals of the men's springboard. Mark Ruiz and Troy Dumais
advanced to the 12-man final.
</P>
<P>
   Equestrian
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of the 1996 finish, the U.S. dressage riders were in
third place midway through the team competition with Germany and
the Netherlands ahead of them. Robert Dover and Susan Blinks rode
for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Field Hockey
</P>
<P>
   Jay Stacy's goal in the 62nd minute lifted Australia into the
semifinals with a 2-1 win over South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan and Charlie McKee of Seattle won a bronze medal in the
new 49er class, the first sailing medal for the U.S. in these
Games. The two U.S. 470 skippers, Paul Foerster and J.J. Isler,
also have a good shot at a medal.
</P>
<P>
   Synchronized Swimming
</P>
<P>
   The U.S failed to win a medal for the first time since the sport
was introduced in 1984. Anna Kozlova and Tuesday Middaugh settled
for fourth behind Russia, Japan and France. Americans have won five
golds and two silvers in the past four Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams was assured of a second Olympic medal, teaming
with sister Serena for a semifinal victory in doubles. The
Williamses beat Els Callens and Dominique Van Roost of Belgium 6-4,
6-1. Monica Seles defeated Australian Jelena Dokic to win the
singles bronze. In the men's singles, Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia
and unseeded Tommy Haas of Germany will meet in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Volleyball (beach)
</P>
<P>
   Americans Dain Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana surprised Brazil for
the gold, defeating favored Ze Marco de Melo and Ricardo Santos
12-11, 12-9 in the final. The Brazilians grabbed the silver and
bronze in women's and the men's silver. They have dominated the
sport in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Water Polo
</P>
<P>
   The American men's team led lost 10-9 to Hungary. Hungary moves
into the Olympic quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Weightlifting
</P>
<P>
   U.S. champion Shane Hamman set national records for the snatch
and total lift while finishing second in the B group of the super
heavyweight division. Hamman broke his U.S. record in the snatch,
lifting 429 3/4 pounds. His total lift of 925 3/4 pounds also broke
his record set at the trials.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
