<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-WRESTLER27-COX     09-26 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas wrestler goes from Amarillo to Australia, via Pennsylvania
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ From Amarillo to Australia is not a common journey, and
for
</P>
<P>
   a wrestler it's almost an impossible one.
</P>
<P>
   But Brandon Slay is here at the Olympics. Born and bred in a
state
</P>
<P>
   where wrestling meant rasslin' and the Von Erichs, he's the only
native
</P>
<P>
   Texan on the United States wrestling team. He may well be the
only U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic wrestler ever brought up in the Lone Star state, where
until
</P>
<P>
   recently real wrestling was a pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Slay was a three-time state champion at Amarillo Tascosa High
School
</P>
<P>
   from 1991-93 and was a runner-up in 1990. But that was back in
the days
</P>
<P>
   when the University Interscholastic League, the main governing
body of
</P>
<P>
   Texas high school athletics, didn't sanction the sport. Only in
the past
</P>
<P>
   few years has the UIL become involved with wrestling, and Slay
is very
</P>
<P>
   conscious about what a boost he could give his sport in his home
state
</P>
<P>
   with an inspiring performance here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely special. It means so much to me. I'll do
whatever it
</P>
<P>
   takes to promote wrestling in Texas,'' said Slay. He'll be
competing in
</P>
<P>
   freestyle wrestling here at 76 kilograms, 167.5 pounds.
Competition
</P>
<P>
   there runs from Thursday through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   To learn his craft Slay turned his back on football, where he'd
been
</P>
<P>
   likened to Zach Thomas. He had to head east to college, to the
</P>
<P>
   University of Pennsylvania, to wrestle and study business. He
never won
</P>
<P>
   an NCAA championship there, but he did finish second in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   He steadily improved and developed a reputation for learning how
to beat
</P>
<P>
   wrestlers who'd beaten him earlier in his career.
</P>
<P>
   He finally got a win against Joe Williams, but it was Williams
who was
</P>
<P>
   favored at the U.S. Olympic trials in Dallas. It seemed Slay was
</P>
<P>
   destined to meet him in the final when Williams was upset by
Brian
</P>
<P>
   Dolph, an assistant coach at Penn, who was Slay's wrestling
partner and
</P>
<P>
   friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of anxiety came over me. I spent 80 percent of my time
</P>
<P>
   preparing for Joe. There was a lot of negative things going
through my
</P>
<P>
   mind for awhile,'' Slay admitted. ``I had to approach it that
Brian was a
</P>
<P>
   mound of flesh in my way. Once it was over I could re-connect.''
</P>
<P>
   After a rather rough match, Dolph congratulated his pupil. He
also
</P>
<P>
   later worked with him at Colorado Springs, where Slay trained
after the
</P>
<P>
   trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the trials I was on Cloud Nine. I had to refocus,'' Slay
said
</P>
<P>
   He spent his time there doing two-hour session, twice a day,
getting
</P>
<P>
   ready for the trip. Dolph ended up getting a ride here, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm allowed to bring a training partner to Sydney, so I picked
Brian,''
</P>
<P>
   Slay said.
</P>
<P>
   While training, Slay developed a persistent infection in his
arm. With
</P>
<P>
   the Olympics approaching he and the wrestling staff took no
chances. He
</P>
<P>
   was hospitalized and given strong antibiotics. He found a bright
side to
</P>
<P>
   that, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I was training, my body needed some time off,'' Slay
said. ``In
</P>
<P>
   the hospital I was on the seventh floor looking out at Pike's
Peak or
</P>
<P>
   watching college football. I had nurses coming into my room; it
was like
</P>
<P>
   room service.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay isn't favored to win a medal here.
</P>
<P>
   The gold medal favorite is probably Bouvaisa Saitiev of Russia,
</P>
<P>
   considered by many to be the best freestyle wrestler in the
world. He
</P>
<P>
   won the gold medal in Atlanta and also captured three world
</P>
<P>
   championships in non-Olympic years. Alexander Leipold of Germany
was the silver medalist in the world championships last year. Moon
Eui-jae of
</P>
<P>
   Korea is also a strong medal threat.
</P>
<P>
   Slay, however, is hoping the big names, and some of the smaller
ones,
</P>
<P>
   will overlook him. He's not looking past any wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got tapes of everybody,'' said Slay, who thinks going to
the tape
</P>
<P>
   is an invaluable tool. ``Wrestlers don't change. You can pick up
their
</P>
<P>
   tendencies, their favorite move and when they like to try it.
You can
</P>
<P>
   even see speed and strength. If someone's snapping a guy all
over the
</P>
<P>
   place, you can tell he's strong. If he's hitting a double leg
through a
</P>
<P>
   guy before he reacts, you know he's really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``A lot of guys watch tape, but they don't do it to
the extent
</P>
<P>
   I do it. A lot of guys will start jumping around twitching when
they're
</P>
<P>
   watching. They'll be wrestling the guy instead of watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay will fly under the radar of most of the national media
here, which
</P>
<P>
   often only cares about gold. But a medal, any medal, would be a
first
</P>
<P>
   for Texas and a huge boost for the sport in the state. Slay
knows it and
</P>
<P>
   wants to be Texas' Lone Star in Olympic wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1552EDT &QL; 
