<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-MIGRATION-0927     09-26 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MIGRATION-0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN PRESIDENT-ELECT WANTS TO EASE MIGRANT MONEY TRANSFERS
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican president-elect Vicente Fox will try to
make it easier and cheaper for Mexican migrants in the United
States to send more than $7 billion in annual earnings home to
sustain families, a top Fox aide said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox migration advisor Juan Hernandez _ a professor at the
University of Texas at Dallas _ said one of Fox's priorities is to
help migrants avoid exorbitant money-wiring fees and low exchange
rates that cut these vital earnings by up to 30 percent by the time
they reach families in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The money Mexican migrants send home is one of Mexico's greatest
sources of revenue generated from abroad _ after manufacturing, oil
and tourism. The migrants' earnings helps pay for food, housing
construction, public works and the establishment of small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to sending money through wiring services might be
via U.S. credit unions that migrants' families can access in Mexico
using ATM cards, Hernandez told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's dream big, as Vicente would say,'' Hernandez said,
outlining a number of ambitious ideas on migration that, in part,
would require U.S. cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, of UT-Dallas' Center for U.S.-Mexico Studies, worked
on Fox's campaign, which made history by toppling the 71-year-old
reign of the Revolutionary Institutional Party, called the PRI.
Fox, who belongs to the National Action Party, takes office on Dec.
1 for a six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually haven't gotten over that we won,'' Hernandez said.
``It gives me incredible faith that we can do incredible things in
the next six years.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday and Friday Hernandez travels to Dallas and Austin,
the Texas capital, for meetings with Mexican and Mexican-American
businesses and UT representatives. Accompanying him will be Pablo
Salazar, a Fox ally who was recently elected the first opposition
governor of Mexico's strife-torn Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar will visit official trade offices and private businesses
that opened in the Dallas area from Fox's home state of Guanajuato
while he was governor. Fox wants to replicate the idea on a bigger
scale, with all Mexican states participating.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said Fox aims to improve a range of existing Mexican
federal programs designed to help migrants. He wants to expand a
pilot program that allows migrants to pay US$350 to enroll their
relatives in Mexico's national health insurance program. Migrants
often send money back home to pay for medical needs of elderly
parents or other family members.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also wants to review the controversial policy of charging
tariffs on goods brought back by migrants, including televisions
and other appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans in the United States have had to live in the shadows,
and I think it's the fault of both federal governments,'' Hernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican migrants help both the U.S. and Mexican economies, but
have to live ``as if they were criminals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who once headed Coca-Cola Co.'s Latin America operation,
views migrants in the United States as investors and wants to
channel more of their earnings into job-producing businesses in
their home states, Hernandez added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incredible business opportunity, a way of
bettering the lives of Mexicans by linking them up,'' Hernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said Fox would like to finance development projects,
too, with an expansion of the San Antonio-based North American
Development Bank, or NADBank. The bank was set up by the 1994 North
American Free Trade Agreement among Mexico, the United States and
Canada and is authorized to loan money only for environmental
clean-up projects now.
</P>
<P>
   With an expanded role, the NADBank could offer educational loans
or offer funds that match business investments by migrants,
Hernandez suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicente Fox would like it to have a huge fund, billions and
billions, for development in areas that need it,'' Hernandez said.
Mexico would also have to contribute to increasing the bank's
assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, Hernandez said, ``is willing to put the money where his
mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Web see:
</P>
<P>
   www.pan.org.mx
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
