<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TV-REVIEW-NYT     09-26 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT JUST THE TIME DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To much of the television audience _ especially the women and
other casual sports followers NBC claims to be eager to court _ the
Olympics is not an athletic event, but rather an entertainment
event that happens to be about sports. You wouldn't want to go to a
cocktail party and not know who Tiger Woods is. In theory, the
Olympics should produce the same need-to-know buzz. You wouldn't
want to go to a party and not know what was going on in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   But to those of us watching at home, what's going on in Sydney
is an overproduced, misbegotten mess. This marathon of coverage
should have been as huge as ``Survivor,'' but is turning out to
more like ``Big Brother'': People only talk about it to say how
dull it is. The features are more mawkish than ever and the
competition coverage packaged in snippets so busy they make a music
video look leisurely.
</P>
<P>
   In its relentless search for high drama, NBC has stumbled into
high camp. One of its most memorable segments came early and may be
hard to top. ``It has been 6,000 years since man first forged a
relationship with the horse,'' Harry Smith said in a feature about
the equestrian competition, using the grandiose tone that puts the
development of the human-animal bond up there with the first cave
painting. ``The journey has brought us,'' he went on, (``us'' being
people and horses), ``together in a place called trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things, like the killer time difference, are beyond the
network's control. Knowing the results is unavoidable, even on NBC.
Typically, on Saturday's ``Today'' show, David Bloom warned viewers
to turn down the volume if they didn't want to know results; then
there was a picture of Marion Jones holding a gold medal. You think
she won?
</P>
<P>
   But NBC could have avoided its lethal mix: Features so
melodramatic they are unintentionally comic, and a style so choppy
it attenuates suspense instead of building it, so slick it is
nearly impossible to tell the commercials from the so-called
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   All the drama, of course, is artificially constructed half a day
after the fact. But it is constructed in a predictable pattern that
is already a parody of itself. Lead in with a 15-second travelogue
about Tasmania (with an Australian-accented narrator), go to Bob
Costas' introduction, a feature about a Chinese gymnast who sees
her parents only twice a year, then a snippet of an actual
competition, followed by a commercial and a medal ceremony for an
event that was covered a half-hour ago. Throw in yet another Marion
Jones profile (now with the endlessly replayed tape of her hulking,
weeping, shot-putter husband, C.J. Hunter, insisting he would never
disgrace his wife and kids by using banned drugs no matter what
those positive test results suggest), and you have a recipe for
disastrous coverage.
</P>
<P>
   After Cathy Freeman's gold-medal winning race on Monday, there
was a commercial, a few minutes of women's pole vaulting, then
Freeman's medal ceremony. But there was a mere glimpse of her
wearing both the Australian and Aboriginal flags on her victory
lap, which should have provided more drama.
</P>
<P>
   Wait long enough and dig hard enough and you'll run across an
athletic feat that is both awe-inspiring and emotional, like Laura
Wilkinson's unexpected gold-medal dive. But watching television
shouldn't be that much work. NBC's producers have made a mistake
any music video director would have been be able to avoid: Being
busier doesn't make a show more interesting, just more cluttered,
and the viewing experience becomes claustrophobic and annoying.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NBC, of course, has to justify the $705 million it has spent for
these games. It has not only spread each night's coverage over five
grueling hours, it has also held several of the Americans'
gold-medal winning races until after 11 p.m. ET. In track, Marion
Jones and Maurice Greene were seen winning gold medals after 11; in
the men's 50-meter freestyle, in which the swimmers and training
partners Gary Hall Jr. and Anthony Ervin dramatically shared the
gold medal, Costas set up the event, broke for local news, then
returned for the race after 11:30.
</P>
<P>
   This is not some juggling act meant to accommodate East and West
Coast viewers at once. The network sends three feeds to the
different time zones, as with any prime-time presentation. The
strategy, another backfire, is meant to lure viewers into the last
hour, in which there has been a fall-off in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Making the Olympics appealing to a broader television audience
is, of course, about constructing celebrities. The commentators are
now dancing around the public relations damage to Jones, their best
hope for stardom, and saying they hope the accusations against her
husband won't be ``a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the star-making machinery is oddly out of touch, with
huge streaks of lingering Cold War mentality and sexism. The
American swimmer Lenny Krayzelburg is one of the most appealing
personalities, low-key, modest and good-looking. One of the many
features about him _ born in Odessa, moved to California _ began,
``He's known life behind the Iron Curtain and in the land of
opportunity.'' When is the last time you heard the term Iron
Curtain used with a straight face?
</P>
<P>
   And after Amy van Dyken spit in Inge de Bruijn's lane, one of
two male swimming commentators noted that ``Inge hissed at her like
a cat.'' The other commentator said, ``I guess this IS going to be
a catfight.'' To the commentators, Gary Hall was cute when he
taunted the Australian swimmers that he would crush them like a
guitar; the women were being catty. That's not the smartest way to
attract female viewers. (And NBC wonders why critics hiss at them.)
</P>
<P>
   Viewers aren't fools. We can tell the difference between Michael
Johnson's race and his commercial for a digital phone service, in
which he runs with a cell phone in his hand and says, ``Hey, coach,
we did it.'' But the Olympics shouldn't be so much like those
familiar commercials that they are just as easy to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   There are alternatives. (Not the CBC's live coverage; all of
Canada is not watching at 5 in the morning.) On MSNBC during the
day, events like men's and women's baseball and rowing have been
unfolding in a leisurely way, with fewer features, like a sports
event instead of a badly packaged show.
</P>
<P>
   But prime time is what matters, and even though those evening
ratings have crept up in the past few days, marginal improvement
doesn't count for much in the midst of so much that has been
botched.
</P>
<P>
   Even a feature about ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' was out of
touch with reality. The song, the report says, ``vaporizes all
cynicism.'' Have they been listening? Instead of a stirring
version, the official Olympic rendition of our national anthem has
a fast-paced ``Play ball!'' style.
</P>
<P>
   Something should be vaporized here, but it's not cynicism; the
cookie cutter for this stale Olympic coverage is the thing that
should vanish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
