<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BASE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-26 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9TH-INNING HOME RUN SENDS U.S. INTO GOLD MEDAL GAME WITH CUBANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT-OLY 17,18,19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Moments after he was cut last spring, a
stunned Doug Mientkiewicz had to make a torturous 500-yard walk
across the parking lot, from the Twins glamorous major league
facility to its minor league outpost.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Mientkiewicz was angry with Minnesota Manager Tom
Kelly for lumping him into a group of young, but petulant talents.
He was bitter toward the Twins management for casting aside their
incumbent first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he wanted to thank Kelly. Those 500 yards had
turned into Mientkiewicz's own walk of fame. If he had played in
the major leagues this year, he wouldn't have had a chance to find
glory as pure as this on a world-wide stage. For the second time in
a week, the 23-year-old Mientkiewicz delivered the game-winning
home run against South Korea's unflappable pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he gave the United States a 3-2 victory in the ninth,
and pushed this American mix of potential and experience into the
Olympic gold medal game Wednesday night against their geopolitical
rival, the mighty Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really amazing,'' Mientkiewicz said. ``I want to shake
Tom Kelly's hand for saying I wasn't ready for the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The roster is full of guys like Mientkiewicz. Some older, some
younger. But all of them have taken the lead of Manager Tommy
Lasorda and found joy in the pressure of representing their
country. Now, faced with Cuba _ the only team that has beaten them
in Sydney, and the only ones that have brought out the Americans'
fighting side _ they want to remember to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing against Cuba, believe me,'' said Lasorda,
whose team was involved in a bench-clearing brawl during their 6-1
loss to Cuba last week. ``We just want to have a good game against
them, and may the best team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the team with the keenest survival instincts won.
Mientkiewicz's solo home run with one out in the bottom of the
ninth ended a game that crossed the border of the bizarre. There
was nightlong drizzle, plus a lightning storm that scared the first
base umpire off the field before plate umpire Cesar Valdes summoned
him back into position. Finally, after one too many thunder claps,
the game was delayed two hours while a storm passed through.
</P>
<P>
   Just after play resumed at midnight, the odd-ball atmosphere
began again. The United States had the bases loaded with one out
but a controversial double play ended their chance to break a 2-2
tie. After a throw to the plate for a force out, South Korean
catcher Jang Sung Ho turned to fire to first in hopes of turning a
tough double play. But Jang was whacked by a forearm in the back of
the head by the incoming American, Brent Abernathy. Jang dropped
the ball on the play. Much to Lasorda's dismay, Valdes called
interference and the double play was awarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it,'' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Mientkiewicz's last plate appearance was normal. When
he came up to bat, the plan was for Mientkiewicz to bunt. But
Travis Dawkins, the pinch-runner put into the game for his
base-running savvy, was picked off by reliever Park Seok Jin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was, `Now I don't have to bunt,''' said
Mientkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   As he swung through the ball, Mientkiewicz threw his bat in the
air and started to celebrate until he realized the ball was
starting to die in the drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it, I thought it was going over,'' he said. ``If it
didn't, I would have felt like the biggest idiot. I didn't know
what to do, if I should take my shirt off or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Launching into a pantomime routine, he waved his arms, trying to
coax the ball to go a little farther. And it did, arching just over
the right-field fence. The South Korean team was devastated _
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, you're heart goes out to them,'' said Mientkiewicz,
whose team was baffled for six innings by the South Korean
submarine pitcher, Chong Tae Hyon. ``They got it ripped out
again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He knows how that feels. Last spring, Mientkiewicz's spirits
were crushed when he was sent down to the minor leagues. After
playing first base for the Twins for the entire 1999 season, he was
unceremoniously demoted. At one frustrating point, he reportedly
said he would rather toil in the minors than play under Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he didn't want to be anywhere else but here: In
Sydney, playing for a chance at a gold medal. It didn't matter if
most of the fans had gone home during the rain delay. He didn't
care who saw it live _ or tape-delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one person or 100 were left, it didn't put a damper on
anything,'' Mientkiewicz said. ``We get to play for a gold medal.
Tonight, this hit was bigger than the last one against this team.
There was much more at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night the gold medal will be on the line.
Mientkiewicz, who resides in Miami, understands the political
atmosphere that will hang over the game. But after such an
emotional journey here _ a path that included an endless 500-yard
walk last spring _ he wants to put politics aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba, to me, has no face,'' Mientkiewicz said. ``If Italy was
the best in the world, I'd want to beat Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
