<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-LEE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI
Director Louis Freeh defend their handling of the case against Wen
Ho Lee, saying the nuclear scientist who pleaded guilty to a charge
of violating security is ``no hero or absent-minded professor.''
Freeh said the government could have proven more serious
allegations against Lee if it had taken the case to trial, but that
national security concerns pushed prosecutors to accept a plea
bargain. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN (Washington) _ With a federal spending package
still in limbo for next year, Congress takes steps to prevent a
government shutdown this weekend and draws nearer to an agreement
to make cheaper, imported medication available to U.S. consumers.
At the same time, Republicans and Democrats grew farther apart on
how best to provide the elderly with an affordable prescription
drug plan. By KAREN MASTERSON.
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION-STATES (Washington) _ Seventy-five years after the
Scopes ``Monkey Trial,'' a report concludes that more than
one-third of the states are doing an abysmal job of teaching
evolution, with 12 receiving an ``F.'' Ten states never use the
word ``evolution'' in science standards. One state _ Kansas _
deletes all references to the age of Earth or universe, including
radioactive decay. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-INCOME (Washington) _ The Census Bureau says America's
poverty rate has dropped to its lowest level in 20 years as the
median household income climbed above $40,000, economic milestones
trumpeted by President Clinton and welcomed by Al Gore's
presidential campaign. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   ACCUSED-SPY (Washington) _ After nearly a year of confinement, a
U.S. sailor is expected to be formally arraigned Wednesday in a
military court, accused of giving the Russians secrets about the
U.S. submarine fleet. Petty Officer 1st Class Daniel King, an
intelligence analyst who is being held in the U.S. Marine Corps
brig at Quantico, Va., faces one count of espionage and two counts
of improperly disclosing classified information. He could receive
the death penalty if convicted. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-VISAS (Washington) _ The Senate agrees to act,
possibly as soon as next week, on legislation to increase the
number of highly skilled foreign workers allowed to enter the
United States. The measure, the top priority for America's
high-tech industry, is caught up in a partisan dispute over whether
to include a Democrat-backed provision to give amnesty to more than
500,000 illegal immigrants, mostly Hispanics. By JENNIFER HOYT.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CASES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to consider
a Houston father's challenge to federal law blocking his effort to
get citizenship for his foreign-born son. The justices also agreed
to hear arguments by the PGA against disabled golfer Casey Martin's
use of a cart during professional golf tournaments. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ Republican George W. Bush and
Democrat Al Gore clash over rival plans to strengthen education and
overhaul Medicare as they limber up for the presidential debates
with televised question-and-answer sessions. Gore, campaigning in
Michigan, fields questions from young people on a town hall meeting
staged by the Music Television cable network. Bush, pressing his
effort in California, fields questions from CNN talk show host
Larry King. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Redwood, Calif.) _ Although education is a centerpiece of
George W. Bush's campaign, it presents him with a bit of a dilemma,
since he's running for the top federal office but believes along
with most Republicans in local control of schools. So when the
audience at a high school in Redwood, Calif., asked about key
education issues such as teacher pay and class size, he said those
issues would be up to the state of California. In Los Angeles, he
and Texas first lady Laura Bush appear on the Larry King talk show.
By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE-TAPE (Undated) _ Bush campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes
complains about the FBI handling of the flap over George W. Bush's
debate practice video that was sent to an operative for Vice
President Al Gore. Hughes says the agency has focused on a possible
dirty trick by the Bush camp rather than espionage. By CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Ann Arbor, Mich.) Vice President Al Gore talks about
Medicare, racial profiling and other issues during an on-campus
taping of an MTV show. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTE (Washington) _ NARAL, a leading advocacy organization
for abortion rights, launches a $5-million, 15-state campaign to
persuade independent and Republican voters who favor abortion
rights to support Democrat Al Gore for president. By JENNIFER A.
DLOUHY.
</P>
