<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BKO-JACKSON-NYT &LR;      09-26 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEISTY 19-YEAR-OLD AUSSIE READY TO TAKE ON THE BEST OF THE U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Lauren Jackson ran upcourt after a brief
altercation under the basket with the frustrated U.S. player.
</P>
<P>
   This happened two weeks ago in Melbourne when the lithe,
6-foot-5 19-year-old from the Australian national team was bumped
by center Lisa Leslie _ who had come to the aid of her U.S.
teammate Sheryl Swoopes _ raising the emotional ante during a tense
exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, she chested me,'' Jackson said recently. ``I wasn't sure
what she did at first, but then I went back at her, like, `You want
a piece of me?' _ as the Americans like to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very good player, but I don't think she outplayed
me,'' Jackson said of Leslie. ``She got a lot of her points at the
end of the game, when it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition, Team USA's depth eventually wore down the
Opals, the nickname for the Australian national women's team. After
another uprising from the peasants, order was again restored to the
U.S. women's basketball universe.
</P>
<P>
   But for how long? As Jackson keeps maturing, as she transforms
herself into the most dangerous inside-outside threat the women's
game has known, while Nike plasters her image across the globe,
America's gold medal reign is no longer a given.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the United States is 5-0 here entering their quarterfinal
with Slovakia Wednesday evening, but so is Team Australia, which
takes on Poland in the afternoon game. The two teams have a decent
shot of facing off in the gold medal match on Saturday at the Super
Dome in Olympic Park. Beyond the drama of the host nation trying to
knock off Goliath, the world will be treated to a glimpse of the
evolution of a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we played the Yanks, I felt so good after the game even
though we lost,'' Jackson said of the exhibition loss. ``I feel
we've got a real good chance of beating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cocksure and quirky, Jackson is the daughter of the former
Australian national team players Gary and Maree Jackson. Her father
used to show her tapes of Wilt Chamberlain as a youngster, and
Lauren cried when she heard that the Hall of Fame center had died.
Along with the basketball pedigree, she possesses a crossover
appeal crucial to her sport's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could be the Michael Jordan that women's basketball hasn't
yet had,'' said Michele Timms, a guard for Australia and a member
of the Phoenix Mercury in the Women's National Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Jackson is like any other 19-year-old, tugged at by
images and people competing for her time and attention. She listens
to the gothic rocker Marilyn Manson more than her elders do, and to
accompany the lightning bolt on her hip she had her country's flag
tattooed on her left arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a dark person, contrary to some of the music I listen
to,'' she said, smiling. ``So please don't paint me that way. I'm
actually quite fun and upbeat about life. But I am a bit different,
I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   On the court, she sets herself apart. Relentless inside, Jackson
leads the Opals in scoring and rebounding in the Olympic
tournament, using her quickness and skill to dominate. She has one
more season to fulfill a contractual obligation for her
professional team in Canberra, where she averaged 23.4 points last
season. She could be playing in the WNBA as early as next summer,
dropping in soft running jump shots in the key, spotting up from
behind the arc or maneuvering her sinewy frame along the baseline
for a reverse layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really go to my left and my defense is shocking, but I
am picking up many things about the game,'' she said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, the 27-year-old All-Star of the Los Angeles Sparks, has
called Jackson ``a future WNBA star, an awesome player.'' But she
bristles at the notion that a rivalry between the two exists. And
she disputes Jackson's account of their confrontation in Melbourne,
which carried over to the other end when Leslie made a strong
baseline drive only to have her shot sent to the floor by a leaping
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I misunderstood her,'' Leslie said, playing down the
encounter. ``Maybe our languages are different. I didn't hear that
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``There is no rivalry until we play them. That's when
it matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes said: ``She's very competitive for her age, a great
player. But she also needs to understand, you're playing against
players who are better than you are and who could teach you
something. She shouldn't forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson forgets when the teen-ager within often gives way to the
ultracompetitive professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one side to her that still loves to be a kid and
another that won't back down from anyone at anytime,'' said Kristi
Harrower, the Opals' point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be one of the best players the world has ever seen,''
the Australian forward Michelle Griffiths said. ``She hasn't even
found her stripes yet. She hasn't even got the complete game yet. I
don't think the world has even touched the surface for Lauren
Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
