<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSHER-CHEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSHER AND DELICIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With KOSHER-RESTAURANTS)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chefs who are finding new ways to make kosher food
stylish are not pushing the limits of dietary laws but instead are
simply rethinking their approach.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than looking to the traditional sources of inspiration,
like Eastern European or classic French cuisine, many are homing in
on Mediterranean cooking, which is not just trendy but surprisingly
well suited to kosher constraints. Il Patrizio, for instance,
serves pizza, roasted fish and vegetable appetizers like potatoes
with artichokes, spinach and Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mediterranean food doesn't use much dairy,'' said Joseph
Amatruda of Prime Grill, ``so we can borrow freely from it, just as
long as we stay away from the shellfish dishes.'' He encrusts rack
of lamb with Syrian spices, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Frankel of Shallots said she is also focusing on the foods
of France, Spain, Italy, Morocco and Greece, which she said ``lend
themselves well to kosher cooking _ there's a lot of oil, fresh
herbs and lemon juice.'' One of her dishes is a red lentil soup
seasoned with Moroccan spices.
</P>
<P>
   These chefs are also tracking down versions of fashionable
ingredients that have been certified kosher. Amatruda has found
kosher nori wrappers, wasabi and rice for his sushi bar but says he
is still searching for kosher truffle oil and sherry wine vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel relies on the Internet to help her find kosher versions
of ingredients like chestnut flour and porcini powder.
</P>
<P>
   Neither substitutes margarine for butter to make their meat
meals kosher. For his mashed potatoes, Amatruda mixes in vegetable
or herb purees, or even plain olive oil, instead of butter. Frankel
does not make sauces finished with butter or cream but instead uses
infusions and reductions. ``It ends up healthier anyway,'' she
said.  &QL; 
PAN SAUTE OF ARTICHOKES, POTATOES, SPINACH AND PARMESAN  &QL; 
Adapted from Il Patrizio &QL; 
Time: 45 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 medium Idaho potato, peeled and cut into \-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   12 baby artichokes, tough outer leaves removed, ends trimmed
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 large sprig fresh rosemary, minced
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds spinach, washed and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe tomatoes, seeded and cubed.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a pot of rapidly boiling water, cook potatoes until
tender, about 5 minutes. Drain and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Thinly slice artichokes lengthwise. In a skillet over
medium-low heat, warm 6 tablespoons oil and gently saute
artichokes, half the garlic and the rosemary until artichokes are
tender, about 15-20 minutes. Add cooked potatoes and saute for 2
minutes. Stir in 2 tablespoons Parmesan and season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, in a skillet over medium heat, warm remaining
tablespoon oil and saute spinach with remaining garlic until
wilted, about 3 minutes. Stir in 2 tablespoons cheese and season
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Spoon spinach into bottom of a 1-quart gratin dish. Divide
artichoke mixture among 4 6-ounce ramekins, packing it down very
hard. Let artichoke mixture cool in molds.
</P>
<P>
   5. Just before serving, heat oven to 500 degrees. Run a small
knife around sides of artichoke mixture in ramekins, then unmold
them on top of spinach. Sprinkle with remaining 2 tablespoons
Parmesan, and bake for 5 minutes, until cheese browns. Garnish with
tomatoes and serve. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIAN SPICED RACK OF LAMB  &QL; 
Adapted from Prime Grill &QL; 
Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon allspice berries
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cardamom seeds removed from the pod
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 racks of lamb (4 chops each, 1 { pounds total)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large skillet over medium heat, toast cumin,
peppercorns, allspice, coriander, cardamom and cinnamon stick until
fragrant, about 3 minutes. Grind spices along with paprika and a
pinch of salt in a spice grinder or coffee grinder.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Salt lamb, then pat spice
mixture all over. Let rest for 15 minutes at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat oil in a large skillet. Brown lamb on all sides.
Transfer to a rack set in a roasting pan and roast lamb until done
to taste, about 25 minutes for medium rare (130 degrees on a meat
thermometer). Carve lamb into chops and serve. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
