<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PEN LED BY THE NOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By   ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As satirists know, the language for describing wines can reach
pretentious and even absurd heights. Recently, I enjoyed a
description of a port with a ``fumy, high-toned nose.'' Yet wine
does present an awkward problem: the vocabulary for describing
subtle differences in smells and flavors is imprecise. So wine
experts have to describe by analogy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their more bizarre descriptions seem nonsensical. Would
anybody really want to drink wine that smells like road tar, wet
rocks or gasoline? What about cured meat, tobacco or sweat, or even
what can politely be called cat's litter box? Of course not. Yet
these terms, when taken in the context of a spectrum of sensory
impressions, can be surprisingly accurate.
</P>
<P>
   For example, as German rieslings age, they sometimes get a
pronounced aroma that suggests fuel to me. Rieslings can also have
mineral smells. The Lingenfelder here has a smell like wet river
rocks, or to be more urban, the sidewalk after a morning rain.
</P>
<P>
   Italian reds are often troves of strange smells. The Roccaccia
here has a meaty, almost sweaty aroma, like that of boiled
cotechino sausage. The Zenner, like many other Sicilian and
southern Italian wines, has a smoky aroma that reminds me of tar, a
smell I like. Bordeaux, particularly well-aged wines from Pauillac
and Graves, smell legendarily like tobacco and cedar. The
Pontet-Canet '97 gives a hint of that.
</P>
<P>
   As for that litterbox, it is meant to describe a piercing
pungency that sauvignon blancs sometimes achieve. There is even a
New Zealand wine that celebrates this odor with humor, calling
itself Cat's Phee on a Gooseberry Bush, gooseberry being the other
obscure aroma in sauvignon blanc. Smells more like cold metal and
lemon to me.  &QL; 
Listed alphabetically. Prices are those paid in Manhattan wine
shops.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CAT'S PHEECON A GOOSEBERRY BUSH, SAUVIGNON BLANC, &QL; 
NEW ZEALAND, EASTCOAST1999 $9  &QL; 
It has a pronounced pungency, clean yet tart in the mouth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LINGENFELDER, RIESLING SPAETLESE, HALBTROCKEN, PFALZ, &QL; 
GROSSKARLBACHER OSTERBERG 1998 $22  &QL; 
Smells like wet rocks and dried flowers; mineral and orange
flavors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHATEAU PONTET-CANET, BORDEAUX, PAUILLAC 1997 $30 &QL; 
Soft, sweet aroma with a mild cedar component; peppery flavor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TENUTA ROCCACCIA, FONTENOVA, TUSCANY 1998 $13 &QL; 
A real meaty, sausagelike scent, but sweet and fruity in the
mouth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
C. VON SCHUBERT, RIESLING SPAETLESE, MOSE -SAAR-RUWER, &QL; 
MAXIMIN GRUENHAEUSER ABTSBERG 1994 $25  &QL; 
You'll swear you're sniffing gasoline. In the mouth, sweetness,
acidity.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
ENNER, TERRA DELLE SIRENE, NERO D'AVOLA, SICILY 1998 $18 &QL; 
Dense and rich with pronounced aroma of smoky tar and berries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
