<HEADER>
A2364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-26 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW MATH: ONE BLUNDER PLUS ONE BLUNDER EQUALS 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Terrell Owens ought to be angry with the San
Francisco 49ers. He ought to be downright livid.
</P>
<P>
   Not because he was suspended for a week. That one, he has to
eat. And not because he lost $24,000 and change with the
suspension. I mean, what's money to a millionaire like him?
</P>
<P>
   No, the bone he has to pick with Steve Mariucci, his teammates
and the 49ers organization relates to a far more damning act than
his desecration of the Dallas Cowboys star.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, the fact that nobody in a position of authority bothers
to notice a new and unique touchdown celebration any longer. I
mean, what's an artist got to do?
</P>
<P>
   Owens scored twice in Sunday's 41-24 win, the first by the 49ers
in about forever. He also celebrated twice in a most unusual way _
by running from the end zone, past all his teammates, to stand on
the star and raise his hands to God.
</P>
<P>
   Or Don Hutson. We're not sure which.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the second celebration, the one that drew such a cranky
reaction from Dallas safety George Teague, is the one that caused
Mariucci to apologize to every 49er, living or dead, and to suspend
Owens for this Sunday's dead-calm game against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But an odd thing happened as Mariucci was crawling so fervently
toward the high moral ground. He said he didn't see the first Owens
celebration, which lasted longer and started all the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, none of his assistant coaches saw it. None of the
other players saw it. None of the 49er brass upstairs at Texas
Stadium saw it. Nobody, except a few million people who know how to
find Fox on their television dial.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, nobody thought to mention it to anyone in authority
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   So of course Owens is torqued off. Playing in Jerry Rice's
shadow ... embarking on what looks to be an extended stay below the
.500 line ... struggling to find an identity for himself ... and
when he finally creates a signature move, nobody is watching.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who claim to know Mariucci believe his story that he
didn't see Owens' first salute to the star. OK, fine, we'll give
him that one. And it is certainly reasonable to think that
offensive coordinator Marty Mornhinweg was too busy to notice, and
that special teams coach George Stewart was occupied hustling the
conversion team onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody has the time to appreciate the Terpsichore, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody? Not one person on the 49ers' payroll?
</P>
<P>
   Surely someone in a position of influence must have caught it.
Owens was getting his head booed off by the angry Dallas crowd,
which ought to be sufficient tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   And if it was wrong the second time, surely it was wrong the
first time. If you buy all that 49ers winning-with-class stuff,
anyway. That ``class'' thing has always been set to a flexible
standard, anyway; winning comes first through sixth, and the class
comes later.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine all the good that could have been done if someone had
told Owens after the first one, ``Bad move there, T.O. You're gonna
start a fight, we're going to have to back your play, and someone
could end up with an accordioned knee. Someone you know and care
about. Someone like, say, me. So stop now while you still have us
at your back.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, everybody with a 49ers logo on his or her shorts was off
going through playbooks for the next grand scheme, throwing down a
congratulatory wine spritzer, hitting the john or knitting a wool
cap for winter.
</P>
<P>
   That's a head coach, a dozen assistants, 53 players,
miscellaneous trainers and equipment men, two public relations
guys, some front office bigshots, two broadcasters and Skippy the
engineer. They all missed Owens' first big moment, thus causing the
second big moment, thus causing all this flap.
</P>
<P>
   So Terrell Owens has a beef, and a legitimate one. What does he
have to do the next time he scores, lift his leg against the goal
post? Grab a baby out of the stands and take a victory lap?
Spontaneously combust?
</P>
<P>
   There are only so many ways to celebrate a score, and most of
them are taken already. Is it asking too much to notice when
someone comes up with something new, even if it is only insulting
and incendiary?
</P>
<P>
   No, I say, it is not. So you keep thinking, T.O., and let your
creativity take wing. And if you seize on something really radical,
like laying the ball down in the end zone, or handing it to an
official, you'll have at least one person watching you. Never mind
the distracted philistines you work for. They don't appreciate a
great mime when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   Or, they claim, when they don't see one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
