<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-COST27-COX     09-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-COST27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KEEPING MEDICARE BENEFITS WILL REQUIRE A TAX HIKE, EXPERTS SAY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ None of the leading proposals for reforming
Medicare will fully solve its long-range financial problems,
meaning taxpayers will have to pay more for future benefits, a
nonpartisan panel of experts reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an expected doubling in the number of elderly people,
longer life spans and rising medical costs, Medicare will need a
111 percent increase in tax revenues in order to provide the same
level of benefits by the year 2030 as in 1998, said the report by
the National Academy of Social Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Using the projected federal budget surplus, cutting costs
through a more efficient delivery of services, or relying on more
competitive pricing of premiums will not solve the long-range
problem, the panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the experts agreed it will take a combination of
factors _ including higher taxes _ to meet the long-term needs of
the federal program that provides health care to more than 39
million elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a robust economy and new cost containment measures have
substantially improved Medicare's financial outlook, Medicare will
still require significant additional revenues if we are to offer
Baby Boomers the type of coverage enjoyed by current
beneficiaries,'' said Marilyn Moon in a statement accompanying the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, a former trustee of the Social Security and Medicare trust
funds, headed the 12-member panel, which brought together experts
with a broad spectrum of political views.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members declined to speculate on how much money will need
to be raised to keep Medicare solvent in the coming decades.
Instead, they estimated the share of Medicare costs as a percentage
of the nation's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Medicare will spend an anticipated $3.4 trillion
over the next 10 years, Moon said the amount of money that will be
needed by 2030 is ``a big, big number.''
</P>
<P>
   The future of Medicare has become a pivotal issue in the
presidential and congressional campaigns. Both presidential
candidates Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush, have
offered plans for reforming Medicare while providing a
pharmaceutical drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Although the panel did not specifically review either the Gore
or Bush proposals, it analyzed several major reform proposals that
have been advocated on Capitol Hill and among health care experts.
</P>
<P>
   Among those proposals was one offered last year to the
Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare by Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif. In it, the government
would subsidize the average cost of competing private Medicare
insurance plans. That proposal, which was not formally adopted by
the commission, has been the basis for bipartisan legislation in
Congress and is a key feature of the reform plan offered by Bush,
the Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The academy panel predicted that the Breaux-Thomas proposal
would fall 86 percent short of money needed from taxpayers by 2030.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a prescription drug benefit with a $2,000 cap on
out-of-pocket expenditures by beneficiaries would increase the need
for additional taxes by 171 percent. Gore, the Democratic
candidate, has proposed a $4,000 cap on out-of-pocket prescription
drug expenditures, while Bush has proposed a $6,000 cap which would
eventually cover all Medicare out-of-pocket expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Medicare proposal _ which he has outlined in greater
detail this week _ would rely on a ``lock box'' provision that
would ensure that the projected federal surplus is used to finance
the Medicare trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   But academy members said the lock box would not solve Medicare's
future financing problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help to pay down the current debt, and it will mean
that, in the future, if you decide to increase the debt again, it
will make it easier to do so,'' said Sheila Burke, a panel member
and former longtime aide to Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, the GOP's 1996
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to expand Medicare by offering it to those 55 and older,
as Gore proposes, or providing prescription drug benefits as both
Gore and Bush propose, will further exacerbate the program's
long-term financial problems, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members suggested a series of options to begin meeting
future financing needs including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Raising the payroll tax, which is equally shared by employers
and employees, from 2.9 percent to 4.84 percent. A worker making
$35,000 would see an increase from $508 to $847 a year; the
employer would pay a similar increase.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adding an 8.43 percent surcharge on income taxes. That would
increase the taxes of a family with an income of $34,900 (below the
national median) by $494, based on 1999 figures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a national 2.02 percent consumption tax on all goods
and services except housing, financial services and some labor. A
family with a $25,000 income would pay roughly $500 in consumption
taxes. If food, medical care and other necessities were excluded,
the rate would increase to 3.29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Academy members acknowledged that getting the public to accept
the need for higher taxes to finance Medicare will be difficult.
Recent rosy projections have delayed the impending date for
Medicare to become insolvent to 2025.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public doesn't perceive that there is a crisis, but I
think policy makers are beginning to understand it,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Academy of Social Insurance: www.nasi.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
