u s BC-OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN     09-26 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: MESSIN' WITH THE GOLDEN COW 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ They entered the room holding hands. Marion
Jones, one of the world's greatest sprinters, and her husband, C.J.
Hunter, were, fairly or unfairly, coming off as the world's biggest
jerks.
</P>
<P>
   The hastily arranged news conference was put together in the
wake of news reports that Hunter, a world-class shot-putter, had
tested positive for performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of Team Nike meetings it had been decided: Hunter
would go out front and face the music. As one Nike official put it,
``You define the situation, don't allow the situation to define
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion did not wear a Nike Swoosh Tuesday. No warmups. Tuesday
she was a partner in marriage. There are times when one partner
gives 90 percent. This was one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you all know, this has been very difficult, the past couple
of days for C.J. and I,'' Jones began. ``I am here pretty much to
show my complete support for my husband. Aside from him being an
athlete and me being an athlete, he's my husband and I'm here to
show support for him. I believe that the legal system will do
what's needed to be done to clear his name.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is attempting to accomplish the feat of her life here, one
of the greatest feats in Olympic history. She is attempting to win
five gold medals. She has already won the 100 meters with ease and
was to begin her quest for the 200 in a preliminary heat here
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday she appealed to the news media for understanding. ``I
hope that all of you would respect the fact that I am competing
here in the Sydney Games. I have four more events to do. So if we
cannot get anymore phone calls to our hotel, we would really,
really appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   With that Jones stood up, kissed Hunter and left. Next to Jones,
who is natural, charismatic, bright and jubilant, Hunter looked as
he often looks: uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 15 minutes Hunter explained and re-explained his
position. ``I may not be the most agreeable person and I might be
downright mean at times, but nobody on the planet can say that I
don't love my wife and I don't love my kids,'' Hunter said through
tears. ``I would never ever do anything to jeopardize her opinion
of me. Track and field has never been that important to me where
I'd do something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The veil of suspicion is so thick, so all encompassing and, in
Hunter's case, so unforgiving. One writer pointedly asked Hunter:
Whether you were taking the steroid or not, does that excuse the
fact that you had a level in your system that exceeded what was
allowed? Everyone knew, including Hunter, the writer said, that you
can't have that stuff in your blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had listened to anything that was said, if it was in a
supplement, how would I know it was in the supplement?'' Hunter
responded. ``Nothing says calcium and nandrolone, it's calcium.
</P>
<P>
   ``So am I reasonably expected to take every supplement I buy?''
Hunter asked rhetorically. ``Find someone to test it and then take
it? Is that what I'm expected to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes, if it keeps your wife focused on the greatest
event of her life. In hindsight, Hunter should have left the sport
in this Olympic year while Jones competed. He should have taken a
year off to become her fulltime Rock of Gibraltar. He told me last
summer that he did the shot because he was good at it, not because
he loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I do this, the reason I come,'' he said
Tuesday, ``is to be able to fly for free.''
</P>
<P>
   They have earned enough for Hunter to pay his own air fare. If
Jones wins the five gold medals, they won't have to pay for a
flight from now till kingdom come.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday someone asked how long he had been carrying the news of
his positive drug test around? Hunter balked. ``One of the things
that we're not going to do is get into any questions that are going
to cause conflict with the IOC, the IAAF or the USOC,'' he said,
referring to the world and American governing bodies of the
Olympics and track and field. ``We're going to take the information
we have, we're going to take it through the proper channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to defend myself vigorously. We've put together a
great team,'' Hunter said. ``And I'm quite positive that when
everything is said and done ,I'll be exonerated. And your opinions
will be totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Hunter and his camp knew in July about the positive tests.
Jones did not find out until two days ago when the news leaked from
the International Olympic Committee here in Australia. A Nike
official confirmed that Hunter knew about this in July. Through
back-and-forth conversations with the IAAF, members of the Jones
camp were confident that the matter would not surface until the
Games ended. They miscalculated. Hunter cried Tuesday.
Intentionally or not, he knew that he had compromised his wife, put
his family in an awkward and embarrassing position.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is that for Jones' competitors, the playing field
just became level. For Marion Jones, the phrase in her wedding vows
_ ``For better or for worse'' _ has assumed a whole new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
