<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SKIPPER NEEDS A BREEZE TO CATCH A BRONZE OR SILVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT-OLY 14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By HERB McCORMICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It has been said that into everyone's life a
little rain must fall. Tuesday, under bleak skies in Sydney Harbor,
it descended on the U.S. skipper Russ Silvestri and his two dozen
opponents in the Finn single-handed dinghy class as the second week
of the Olympic sailing competition continued.
</P>
<P>
   After four previous races in the 11-race series, Silvestri, a
38-year-old investment banker from San Francisco, started the day
in seventh place. When it was over, after a second-place finish and
a 16th in the other pair of races sailed in cool, southerly winds
that peaked at about 15 knots and ultimately fell to a mere zephyr,
he had moved up a notch to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Iain Percy, who began the day as the overall leader,
continued to sail a consistent series with fifth- and sixth-place
finishes and, just past the midway point of the regatta, is
maintaining a hefty lead.
</P>
<P>
   Silvestri acknowledged his day had been up and down.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first race everything that could go right went right,''
he said. ``It gave me a lot of confidence. I thought I had it all
figured out. But it backfired a bit on the second race.''
</P>
<P>
   With 27 points, Percy is 13 points ahead of Fredrik Loof of
France, in second. In the Olympic sailing competition, sailors
receive points for the order in which they finish each race. The
low score wins.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Silvestri, with 56 points, remains in medal
contention, the U.S. sailing team's results thus far have been, at
best, mixed. In the 49er class competition, which finished Monday,
the Seattle brothers Jonathan and Charlie McKee earned bronze
medals. And Wednesday, with one race left in their respective
divisions, the men's 470 team of Paul Foerster and Bob Merrick, and
the women's 470 duo of J.J. Isler and Pease Glaser, have a good
chance at either silver or bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Soling team skippered by Jeff Madrigali was eliminated
early. And another pre-Games medal favorite, the Star boat helmed
by Mark Reynolds, is a distant seventh at the midway point of that
series. The U.S. Tornado team, and the men's and women's
boardsailing entries, whose racing has ended, all finished out of
the money.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening week of competition the weather was probably too
ideal, as the sunny, early spring conditions were accompanied by
minimal breeze. The weather has changed, however, and on Course D,
just inside the prominent Heads that guard the harbor entrance _
the site of Tuesday's Finn sailing, and one of six available racing
circles _ the day's first race began in a chilly downpour.
</P>
<P>
   Storm clouds are nothing new to Silvestri, who won a spot on the
U.S. team for the 1984 Games but then lost it because of a rules
protest. So he is enjoying his first Olympic experience, the
highlight of which so far has been leading the fleet to the first
turning mark in the opening race of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty exciting,'' he said. ``I was getting
teary-eyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Silvestri didn't repeat that performance Tuesday, but he managed
an excellent start just to windward of the defending Olympic
champion, Mateusz Kusznierewicz of Poland, and parlayed that into a
second-place result. Xavier Rohart of France was first.
</P>
<P>
   By the start of the second race the rain had halted, but the
breeze was extremely fluky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get little rivers of wind here and there,'' Silvestri
said. ``If you're in the right place you get them. If not, you
don't. Sometimes you're on the good elevator, and sometimes you're
on the bad one.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the race, Silvestri was holding ninth. But on
the last downwind leg, he picked the wrong corridor. ``The guys on
the right smoked me,'' he said. ``And the guys on the left smoked
me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Drifting across the finish line in the dying breeze, Silvestri
was 15 places behind the winner, David Burrows of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Although Percy has a solid lock on the lead, it has been a
surprising series. After Tuesday's racing, Kusznierewicz, a
dominant sailor who was last year's International Sailing
Federation sailor of the year, is fourth.
</P>
<P>
   And after waiting 16 years for his Olympic moment, Silvestri is
not yet willing to concede defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real light air I think I'm a little vulnerable, but in
anything over 5 knots I think I'm going pretty good,'' he said.
``Percy's been fabulous, but second and third are still wide open.
If I don't get cocky, there are still a lot of races to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
