r e BC-BOOK-PAGANBABIES-TEX     09-26 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PAGANBABIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET FATHER TERRY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKE COCHRAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Pagan Babies''
</P>
<P>
   by Elmore Leonard
</P>
<P>
   Mystery
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Father Terry Dunn is a scotch-swilling, pot-puffing priest with
a slinky one-armed housekeeper, a Rwandan church full of dead
bodies and a couple of dirty little secrets in his shadowy past.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second.
</P>
<P>
   Is Father Terry really a priest, or is he a fugitive felon? Or
both? Or neither? And is the sultry Chantelle really a housekeeper
or a harlot? Or both?
</P>
<P>
   Or neither?
</P>
<P>
   With ``Pagan Babies,'' Elmore Leonard has struck again. That is
to say, he's created another weird plot and peopled it with equally
outrageous and unforgettable characters.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody's quite what he or she appears to be.
</P>
<P>
   Things begin to really liven up with Father Terry's sudden, but
quite timely, departure (escape?) from Africa, and his
serendipitous rendezvous in Detroit with super-cool legal
investigator Debbie Dewey.
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible Ms. Dewey is just freshly removed from a
three-year stint at Florida's Sawgrass Correctional for assault
with a deadly weapon _ a rent car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was visiting my mom in Florida and happened to run into my
ex-husband _ in a Buick Riviera,'' she says, telling the story for
laughs. Real laughs. Outside prison walls, she is trying to make it
now as a stand-up comic using _ you guessed it _ prison humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rental, but it did the job,'' she deadpans.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it wasn't her ex-husband, but her ex-boyfriend, Randy,
and it was a Ford Escort and not a Buick Riviera, but she was
hugely successful in putting Randy in a body cast. What's more,
she's eager to resume exacting her revenge on the womanizing snake,
who scammed her for a total of $67,000.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Detroit, Father Terry is also casting about for a huge
bundle of cash, ostensibly for the starving children of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the mysterious priest and the comely comedienne share
not only common agendas but a splendidly sardonic wit and whatever
bed happens to be handy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, everyone's mixed up with gangsters, con artists, crazies
and killers, most memorably a hit man named Mutt, who offs his
targets with borrowed weapons and only minimal rancor.
</P>
<P>
   There is this wonderfully Leonardesque exchange between Mutt and
small-town mobster Johnny Pajonny:
</P>
<P>
   Mobster: ``I know a guy at Jackson (prison) was a hit man. He
got ten grand a pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutt: ``I get more'n that.'' (He's just agreed to a $500 hit.)
</P>
<P>
   Mobster: ``You must be good at it. ... You say you took out a
truck driver, a convict and one other guy?''
</P>
<P>
   Mutt: `` ... Guy wouldn't pay his street tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobster: ``You didn't shoot the convict?''
</P>
<P>
   Mutt: ``No, I shanked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobster: ``So you only actually shot two guys?''
</P>
<P>
   Mutt: ``Yeah, but I got one coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons best left unexplained, Mutt is recruited by wretched
Randy to dispose of Father Terry, and amid all manner of mayhem the
saga hurtles toward a hilarious, yet suspenseful, close.
</P>
<P>
   This one will surprise even those legions of Leonard fans who
have come to expect the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   As pointed out earlier, Elmore Leonard has struck again. And
this time, as with ``Get Shorty,'' a superb earlier novel, he's
struck pure gold.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
