<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-FLATTERY-TEX     09-26 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FLATTERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU LOST SOME WEIGHT? THOUGHT SO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``You're Too Kind: A Brief History of Flattery''
</P>
<P>
   by Richard Stengel
</P>
<P>
   Sociology
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Flattery is more than just kissing up to someone. It is, in
fact, a vital part of our lives, culture and civilization. At
least, that's the premise of ``You're Too Kind: A Brief History of
Flattery,'' by Richard Stengel.
</P>
<P>
   If you're open to that concept _ and surely you are, since you
are one of those very special open-minded individuals who reads the
Books section _ this is an interesting, entertaining and perhaps
even enlightening few hundred pages. Plus, Stengel's writing is
sharp and amusing.
</P>
<P>
   For most, ``flattery'' suggests images of blowing smoke,
toadyism, sycophancy and brown-nosing. But we can't all be king, or
even a mid-level boss.
</P>
<P>
   Stengel believes status hierarchies are endemic in nature, and
that flattery is the accepted technique for raising your status.
Even if the flattery is transparent, the mere attempt is usually
worth a few points, he writes.
</P>
<P>
   You can overthrow the boss, king, queen or whatever. But this
usually involves some kind of confrontation, sometimes a bloody
one. The alternative is to make your situation as pleasant, or at
least as tolerable, as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evolution seems to have ultimately favored sycophantic weenies
over self-reliant bruisers, the Uriah Heeps and Eddie Haskells and
Dick Morrises over the Samsons and the Schwarzeneggers,'' Stengel
writes. ``Smooth talk trumps brute strength every day of the
week.''
</P>
<P>
   This history begins with primates. Winning the alpha male's
favor means better food for other males, and access to choice
females. Stengel suggests that flattery may be biological ``because
it helps you get your genes into the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Where office flatterers compliment the boss on a new suit, a new
car or lost weight, chimpanzees have to pick nits off their alpha's
backside. But the effect is the same.
</P>
<P>
   In today's world, workers employ flattery to acquire better
income, which results in a better car, better house and, thus, a
better sexual partner more likely to carry the flatterer's genes
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Other chapters delve into the subgroups of royal flattery,
personal flattery and political flattery.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the book puts flattery into perspective. At its
most basic, it helps us all ``get along.'' We all do it, even
really wonderful people like you who read what I write. Feel free
to present your fleas for my immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-VERONIKA-TEX     09-26 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-VERONIKA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PATIENT OFFERS AN INTIMATE LOOK INSIDE THE ASYLUM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By AMRITA SHLACHTER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Veronika Decides to Die''
</P>
<P>
   by Paul Coelho
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $24
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian author Paulo Coelho's new novel, ``Veronika Decides to
Die,'' about the final days of a young woman who has chosen to end
her own life, is a chilling tale depicting a world with which most
of us are only vaguely familiar. Coelho explores mental illness and
life within the walls of a psychiatric institution with surreal
detail and intimacy, such as only a been-there-done-that type of
writer could accomplish. The book, we are told, is based on events
in the author's own life.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho's quiet, unadorned style produces effects as compelling
as the shock treatments he describes. Though Villete is a
fictitious institution, it is easy to forget the place isn't real,
especially when Coelho makes a third-person appearance early in the
story. He declares he will tell Veronika's story because he, too,
has been locked up, and he feels compelled to expose the ``madmen
who run lunatic asylums.'' But if the novel begins as Coelho's
personal vendetta, he settles for the role of fly-on-the-wall. The
story takes on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The curtain rises with Veronika _ 24 years old, beautiful,
gifted and loved by family and friends _ overdosing on sleeping
pills. She hopes to end the inexplicable ``void'' in her life.
Instead of dying, she comes to in a psychiatric hospital. She's
told that she has caused irreversible damage to her heart, and that
she has less than a week to live.
</P>
<P>
   Veronika decides to permit intensity of feeling to dictate those
final days. This leads her to indulge in all sorts of bizarre
``truthful'' behavior, including slapping an elderly hospital
inmate who appears to have ridiculed her and performing sexual
antics in the presence of a young man whom she physically desires,
but who is unable to reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Veronika plays piano with such ferocious intensity
that she stirs up dormant emotions in other patients. One of them
is Eduard, the same young man who refused to have sex with her
(although he is mesmerized by her piano playing). Said to be
afflicted with a ``rare'' type of schizophrenia, Eduard was
hospitalized following a breakdown, one apparently prompted by
pressure from overbearing parents who forbade him to pursue art _
not unlike Coelho's own experience. Other patients touched by
Veronika's antics include Mari, a middle-aged lawyer, whose husband
has committed her because of a severe panic disorder, and Zedka,
whose depression is being treated with insulin shots.
</P>
<P>
   The time span for the story is all of five days. The setting is
inside an asylum. But within that framework, the narrative weaves
back and forth, encompassing past and present. The main focus is on
Veronika, but the minor players are superbly fleshed out, and help
readers feel they have entered a very real world that operates by
its own rules and eerie ``normalcy.'' Not the least among the cast
are the shadowy figures of Dr. Igor, whose patients serve as
research guinea pigs, and Igor's retinue of nurses and aides, all
of them brandishing their arsenal of syringes and straitjackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veronika Decides to Die'' winds down with an unexpected twist,
which makes you wonder if the crazy practices at Villete are to be
condemned or condoned. Coelho brings the story to a very fluid
closure, and, ultimately, wants readers to draw their own
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
