<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, Sept. 27. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Henry Warnken, phone: 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927; e-mail: hwarnken(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The
government-controlled Federal Election Commission announced on
Tuesday night that President Slobodan Milosevic had won enough
votes to force a second-round runoff for the presidency against
challenger Vojislav Kostunica, challenging Kostunica's claim of an
outright victory in the first round of voting on Sunday. Opposition
leaders immediately called the commission figures fraudulent and
said they would insist that Kostunica had won without the need for
a runoff, which would take place on Oct. 8. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-WORLDBANK (Prague, Czech Republic) _ Black-masked protesters
hurled cobblestones ripped from Prague's medieval streets and
attacked police with homemade gasoline bombs, trying desperately,
and ultimately unsuccessfully, to shut down a global finance
meeting here. Riot police had to escort government ministers
attending the annual conference of the International Monetary Fund
and World Bank into special subways cars to whisk them away from
their meeting at day's end. The violence, which both police and
many protesters said was provoked by squadrons of European
anarchists and communists, did not stop the meetings. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, the Netherlands) _ The Libyan
double agent considered the most crucial witness in the Lockerbie
trial testified on Tuesday that the two defendants brought to Malta
a brown Samsonite suitcase like the one believed to contain the
bomb that destroyed Pan Am Flight 103. But in his testimony, which
lasted less than one day, the witness never said he saw a bomb put
into the suitcase or the suitcase put aboard a flight. He also did
not say that either defendant had admitted the bombing to him. By
Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LEE (Washington) _ After weeks of criticism in the Wen
Ho Lee case, Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis J.
Freeh on Tuesday defended their actions, asserting that Lee had
committed a serious crime when he removed atomic weapons data from
a classified computer system at Los Alamos lab. At the hearing on
Tuesday, a joint session of the Senate Judiciary and Intelligence
committees, none of the senators disputed the seriousness of the
information that Lee was accused of placing at risk. But several
assailed the Justice Department and the FBI for lapses in the
investigation and for their insistence on keeping Lee in solitary
confinement _ and sometimes shackled _ in the months before the
plea bargain. By David Johnston. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILM (Undated) _ On the film industry's marketing
of violent films to children. By Doreen Carvajal. (With photo and
graphic)
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ The Supreme Court handed a major
victory to Microsoft on Tuesday when it summarily rejected the
government's plea to immediately hear the appeal of its landmark
antitrust case and instead returned the proceeding to an
intermediate appeals court, in effect prolonging the legal battle
by at least a year. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
