<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      09-26 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DREAM OF ZINFANDEL, DELIVERED TO THE DOOR  
 VIA AIR MAIL IN SOME ESTATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Texas, Fla., N.C., Utah)   By   FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year around this time, the mail brings a raft of notices
from California's small exclusive wineries offering their latest
vintage. The wines are listed with prices, and an address to which
I should send my check.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem: they won't sell me any wine. There are
29 states to which it is illegal to ship wine directly to a
consumer from another state. I live in one of them, New Jersey, and
work in another, New York.
</P>
<P>
   These laws are strongly supported by the liquor and wine
wholesalers and by most retailers. They are terrified that the
Internet, through which most of these direct sales are made, is
going to put them out of business. The states support these laws
for fear that direct shipping will elude their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   I might not be so exercised over all this if, with the mails
blocked to me, I could slip around to my local marchand du vin and
buy the wine there.
</P>
<P>
   But I can't.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 40 years, the number of liquor wholesalers has
shrunk by a staggering 97 percent. While their numbers have
dwindled, the number of wineries has exploded. There are more than
800 in California alone, producing some 4,000 different wines. The
wholesalers are more interested in volume than variety, and that
leaves most people without access to some of best small producers
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, hundreds of small wineries, desperate for an
outlet, have turned to the Internet and mail order, but they find
themselves largely stymied there as well.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the frustrated wine makers and their customers
have begun to fight back. They are finding a sympathetic ear in
some courts. In the past year, wineries and consumers have filed
lawsuits in six states asserting that to single out wine for
special controls is discriminatory, a restraint of trade and a
violation of the Interstate Commerce Clause, which grants Congress
the exclusive authority to regulate commerce among states.
</P>
<P>
   In two of the suits, in Indiana and Texas, the plaintiffs won.
On Sept. 13, the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the
Indiana decision, a ruling that a spokeswoman for the Wine and
Spirits Wholesalers of America, Juanita Duggan, called ``a major
step forward for the state officials who are trying to prevent
out-of-state alcohol shippers from evading taxes and selling wine,
liquor and beer without checking IDs.''
</P>
<P>
   John DeLuca, the president of the Wine Institute, a trade group
that deals with legislation and consumer issues affecting the wine
industry, said that the decision seemed to be based mostly on
courtroom technicalities. A consumer group, the Informal Coalition
to Preserve Consumer Access to Wine, noted that with laws being
challenged in New York, Virginia, Texas, Florida and North
Carolina, ``the 7th Circuit opinion will certainly not be the last
word on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, the U.S. District Court in the Southern District
of New York denied a motion by the wholesalers' lawyers to dismiss
the New York suit. New York liquor laws make it illegal to ship or
advertise wine in the state without a license. Out-of-state
wineries are ineligible for licenses. In allowing the suit
challenging the New York laws to go to trial, Judge Richard Berman
cited U.S. Supreme Court cases that declared states' laws invalid
if their purpose was ``mere economic protectionism,'' which
opponents say is the fundamental purpose of the laws being
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesalers hotly deny this, claiming they are equally
concerned about the effects of the underage drinking that direct
shipping would surely encourage. ``The Constitution prevailed over
reckless disregard for temperance, tax collection and local
custom,'' said Duggan, the wholesalers' spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate is expected to consider a new direct shipping
bill, probably in the remaining weeks before the end of the current
session. Sponsored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and called the 21st
Amendment Enforcement Act, the bill would, in essence, allow the
states to get federal help in prosecuting out-of-state wineries
that ship wine directly to a wine drinker.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the bill probably would not get anywhere. Tacked onto
one appropriations bill or another, it will probably pass, but
direct shipping advocates say it will have minimal effect on the
growing number of suits in the federal courts aimed at overthrowing
the states' shipping laws.
</P>
<P>
   The whole fracas will almost certainly end up in the Supreme
Court, not because it's important that some dot-com plutocrat gets
his Pahlmeyer Chardonnay from Jason Pahlmeyer himself, but because
it affects the future of e-commerce and what many consider outmoded
interpretations of the 21st Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1933, the idea behind the 21st was to keep gangsters out
of the liquor business. The thugs never did get out; they just went
legit, as Damon Runyon would say, and with the people who had been
locking them up on their side, they prospered.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time, they face a serious threat. Not just
from a passel of wine geeks. The rise of the Internet has created a
new dynamic in the business world, one that a group of outmoded
monopolists, with a few prohibitionists along for old times' sake,
cannot long withstand. Besides, once the wineries agreed to pay
state taxes _ which they have _ it was all over but the shouting.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while, but one day not too far off, clicking on
zinfandel and waiting for the Federal Express delivery will be an
essential part of the wine experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
