<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-AR     09-26 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A LOOK AT KOSHER NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT12, 13 and 14 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lobster, yes. Pork chops, no.
</P>
<P>
   Oysters, always. Bacon, never.
</P>
<P>
   As an assimilated Jew, this was the particular brand of culinary
schizophrenia I grew up with. At home, my family was kosher with a
vengeance. We had one set of dishes and silverware for meat,
another for dairy, and never the twain did meet. I remember hearing
that unkosher food was dirty, so pig remained reviled even when
served in restaurants, while shellfish (equally unkosher), had
somehow received a divine pardon. When the steamers hit the table
at the Clam Box you would have thought it was gefilte fish.
</P>
<P>
   But for truly observant Jews, the 24/7 variety, kosher
restaurants were traditionally the only alternative to staying home
or going to Grandma's. The atmosphere in these restaurants echoed
home _ large groups eating Old World classics like roast chicken
and potted meatballs at meat meccas like Gluckstern's or Lou G.
Siegel's. Or the same groups eating the cardiologist's special at
the dairy Ratner's: cheese blintzes fried in butter, topped with
sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, those old-fashioned places have given
way to more modern kosher options, Chinese, Japanese, Indian,
Mexican and French steakhouses among them. These days, within a
half block of West 72nd Street alone you can find kosher pizza at
Pizza Cave and kosher ribs (albeit beef) at Dougie's Bar-B-Que &AMP;
Grill _ the only barbecue place I've ever seen that serves chicken
soup.
</P>
<P>
   But the newest additions to the kosher scene are high-end
restaurants featuring ambitious dishes like bison, rack of lamb and
whole roasted sea bass, with wine lists (hold the Manischewitz) in
elegant surroundings. As more and more affluent young people are
returning to the Orthodox tradition, they are demanding a new level
of sophistication to match the mainstream, with their own
cutting-edge choices. The latest entry in this category, Shallots,
has opened in the Sony Building on the former site of the Quilted
Giraffe, with prices to match its uptown digs: $47 for rack of
lamb. The Four Seasons, by comparison, charges $45. So much for
potted meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upscale kosher has exploded in the last five years,'' said Sol
Kirschenbaum, an owner of Levana, a contemporary Continental
restaurant on the Upper West Side that opened in 1986. The Zagat
Survey calls it ``the kosher Four Seasons,'' though it gives the
food a rating of 21 versus the Four Seasons' 26, and the average
meal at Levana is $44 instead of $67.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, people weren't used to kosher fine dining
establishments,'' Kirschenbaum said. ``Now they're no longer
satisfied with five places to go, they want 25. The choices have
become so broad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with a whole new set of demographics now,''
said Menachem Lubinsky, publisher of Kosher Today, a trade
publication, and the owner of Kosherfest, a kosher food trade show.
``Young Orthodox Jews are going upscale in every way, with cars,
homes and now restaurants. The cross-fertilization between the Joe
Liebermans of the world with Wall Street and the media means that
they need places to entertain them. The young Orthodox want
everything that the general population has, but they want it to be
kosher. At a typical wedding now, you're more likely to have sushi
than chopped liver.''
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad. I prefer chopped liver. Then again, being raised
in the school of Lobster Dinner Judaism means I have plenty of
choices when it comes to eating out. For those who don't, the brave
new world of nouvelle kosher offers not only Shallots, an offshoot
of a successful Chicago-based meat restaurant of the same name, but
two other entries: Il Patrizio, an Upper East Side Italian dairy
restaurant on the former site of Peaches, Marla Maples' place; and
Prime Grill, a steakhouse in Midtown that was most recently
Blackbird. Besides their culinary options, all three offer a lesson
in New York restaurant real estate: It pays to know your audience.
None of these locations made it with the mainstream (Shallots was
most recently Drew Nieporent's Berkeley Bar and Grill) though they
are in heavily trafficked areas.
</P>
<P>
   As Laura Frankel, the executive chef at Shallots, said, ``It's a
mistake these days to open a restaurant without a customer group in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides good food, that group wants ambience; the owners of
Prime Grill are spending close to $2 million for renovations by the
designer Matt Markowitz, who also did Jean-Georges Vongerichten's
Mercer Kitchen. The opening is scheduled for the end of October.
``We will serve steak and sushi, and by the way, we're kosher,''
said the manager, Chris Schienle. ``Instead of shrimp cocktail or a
raw bar, our customers can substitute sushi for shellfish.''
</P>
<P>
   For those wondering what ``by the way, we're kosher'' means,
kosher is not a cuisine. It is a strict adherence to dietary rules,
which, broadly defined, include a complete separation of milk and
meat, and a restriction to meat that comes from animals that have
split hooves, chew their cud and are slaughtered in accordance with
Jewish law; certain poultry, if it's killed correctly; and fish
that has fins and scales, which is why shellfish is a no-go.
</P>
<P>
   The good news these days, though, is that kosher suppliers have
broadened their inventory, benefiting from the general upgrading of
American restaurants _ though if my grandmother were here to see
Jews sitting down in fancy restaurants to eat buffalo, she would
surely call it meshuga. .
</P>
<P>
   The strides in dairy are a little less revolutionary. Il
Patrizio opened in May with a menu offering fish, pasta and
stone-oven pizza. Its chef, Cesar Moina, cooked at Mezzaluna and
Torre di Pisa, and on a recent visit, he made me, my sister,
Phoebe, and my aunt Evelyn very happy. Our favorite appetizer was a
combination of artichoke, potato, spinach and Parmesan, which was
the kind of thing you could eat a potful of on a cold night without
even realizing it.
</P>
<P>
   All three of us had fish, and it was nothing like the old days,
sitting on the plate in its own liquid, tasting like punishment.
The salmon with a mustard crust was crispy on the outside, tender
within; the whole roasted sea bass was moist and flavorful, and the
red snapper with olives, tomatoes and capers was downright festive.
</P>
<P>
   Il Patrizio's surroundings are simple and elegant, with exposed
brick walls and full-blown roses in glass bowls on white
tablecloths. The clientele was decidedly stylish, with one young
couple sporting shopping bags from Barneys and Stephane Kelian, and
a young guy (cute) eating alone at the bar. If the men weren't
wearing skullcaps, you'd have no idea the place was kosher, which,
in the lexicon of separate but equal, is the ultimate compliment.
</P>
<P>
   I brought my parents to Levana, where James Lenzi, the chef,
formerly of Tavern on the Green and Cafe des Artistes, stretches
the borders past brisket to venison, quail and bison. I especially
liked the pepper-crusted venison, which tasted like gourmet
pastrami. Lenzi also turns out beef fillets, veal chops and
sweetbreads, though the Israeli wine we ordered, Galil Merlot,
Carmel Private Collection, did none of them justice. The restaurant
is modern in design, a bit spare for my taste, but jammed with
everyone from young couples to large families, not to mention a
table of 10 women, one man and a blinding video camera. Most seemed
like satisfied regulars.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
