r l BC-HOMEWORK-STRATEGIES-T     09-26 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWORK-STRATEGIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES H-O-M-E-W-O-R-K SPELL HEADACHE?
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by HOMEWORK-HELP)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Fort Worth mother wakes her daughter
before sunrise each morning so she can practice piano before she
goes to school. It's an activity her daughter used to do in the
evenings _ but now that she's in the fifth grade, there's no time.
</P>
<P>
   Evenings are spent doing homework, often right up to bedtime,
and the 10-year-old's leisure and outside activities have been
eclipsed by math problems and worksheets, writing assignments and
science projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several times my little girl has been in tears because she
can't do it (all) without my help,'' says the mother, who asked not
to be identified. ``She's running out of time, it's 9 and she's got
to go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   This mother believes homework is necessary, but it's
counterproductive when it starts to take over kids' lives. With
kids' activities and obligations, the time between school and
bedtime seems to be shrinking just as homework assignments are
expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Are they really expanding? A University of Michigan study
released last year indicates that kids are indeed spending more
time on homework than they used to. Between 1981 and 1997, the
study says, the mean length of time children ages 3-11 spent on
homework increased about 50 percent, to two hours, seven minutes
per week from one hour, 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Patty Yoxall of the National PTA, based in Chicago, says
that's not necessarily true for every student. In fact, she can't
find any obvious patterns or trends in student homework loads at
all _ reports vary from region to region, district to district,
school to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear everything,'' she says. ``We hear, `My student has
four hours of homework every night and it's a burden' to `My
student doesn't have enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the Fort Worth area, reports seem to vary just as much, even
in the same district. But it's safe to say that many children (and
their parents) are frustrated, trying to fit homework time into a
hectic lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are involved in so many out-of-school activities. By the
time they get home at night ... homework seems to be `what's left'
to do at night,'' says Elouise Perry, who teaches fifth grade at
Wimbish Elementary in Arlington. ``Homework is something parents
probably see as just one more thing to add to their schedules in
the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   It's especially difficult when both parents work and there's
more than one child doing homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big struggle is probably more for the parents _ coming
home at 5:30 or 6 and having to get dinner ready and do the
homework and get them in bed,'' says Catherine Puente of Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Puente and her husband have three children (two are school-age),
and both parents work full-time. Puente says she's a strong
believer in homework. Getting it done, though, is a matter of being
efficient and organized.
</P>
<P>
   Puente says she and her husband take turns working with each
daughter in the evenings. The Puentes' first-grader, Meredith,
spends more time on homework than her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has homework every day,'' Puente says. ``She brings home a
different book every evening that she has to read, and a spelling
list she has to learn two words from, each night.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Meredith has started dancing in the Ballet Folklorico, and
evening lessons and practices make time even more precious.
</P>
<P>
   So how much time should kids be spending on homework, anyway?
There's no clear answer. Teachers say the workload varies from
class to class and student to student _ and even day to day.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago, the National Education Association and the
National PTA came up with rough guidelines for appropriate amounts
of homework. The group recommended 10 minutes of work per grade
level _ for instance, a first-grader should have about 10 minutes
of homework, a second-grader should have 20, and a sixth-grader
should have about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Based on estimates given by several local parents and teachers,
many kids are spending substantially more time than this guideline
recommends.
</P>
<P>
   While some parents say their children's homework load is too
much, others are more radical and say any homework is too much.
</P>
<P>
   Etta Kralovec and John Buell question homework's value
altogether in a book published this year, ``The End of Homework:
How Homework Disrupts Families, Overburdens Children, and Limits
Learning'' (Beacon Press, $18). They say that children's main
``job'' is developing a social self, and it harms the maturing
process when students are forced too early into the ``work before
play'' mold of the adult workplace. In addition, Kralovec and Buell
say that homework stresses out kids and disrupts family life, and
that all work should be done at school _ not taken home and dragged
out through the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, a popular argument against homework is
that adults go to work, do their job and go home; for children,
``school'' is that job, and the work should end when the bell
rings.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bartolotta, who teaches fourth-, fifth- and sixth-graders
at Fort Worth's Como Montessori School, disagrees with this theory.
It's not valid, he says, because adults do take their work home.
Homework prepares kids for this responsibility in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get these kids socially ready for the world,''
Bartolotta says. ``If they learn early that they don't need to take
their job home, what's going to happen to them when they ``need''
to take their job home?''
</P>
<P>
   Learning that kind of responsibility takes time, though, and
many teachers are willing to compromise with students and their
parents in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bartolotta assigns plenty of homework, he says he's aware
that his students' evening time might already be spoken for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very conscious of their extracurricular activities
after school,'' Bartolotta says. ``That's family time. I don't want
to take away from their family time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Cooper, who teaches first grade at Fort Worth's A.M. Pate
Elementary, says she's also willing to compromise if homework is
becoming a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of gauge (workload) on kid response and parent
response,'' Cooper says. ``If I hear parents saying, `That's too
much,' I pare it down a little.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she says: ``Usually I have parents say they've noticed
problems in a certain area, and they say, `Can you give us more to
do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers say this sort of parental concern is crucial _ it helps
them use homework to enhance a child's education. If parents are
involved in constructive communication with the teacher, they can
usually work with him or her to find homework assignments that meet
the child's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really need to take an active role,'' Bartolotta says.
``They need to know what's going on in their child's classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   And this may be the bottom line on afterschool assignments: If
parents know what goes on in the classroom, they can fully
understand what needs to happen at home. Maybe parents should
consider that the real homework.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-AR     09-26 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: satisfied regulars.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Far more formal is the two-month-old Shallots. There is only one
word to describe this restaurant, and that is chutzpah with a
capital C. Its style is corporate ornate, and perhaps a little
too-too for some of its customers. The man at the table next to
ours was shooed outside by his wife all three times his cell phone
rang. By the time dessert came, he looked as if he wished he were
back at Ratner's.
</P>
<P>
   Shallots drives the point home that you need more than kosher
food to make a kosher restaurant succeed; if you're going to play
in the big leagues, you need a top-of-the-line dining room staff.
While the service at Il Patrizio was unfailingly courteous, as it
was at Levana (if less polished), at Shallots it was case-study
bad. From the moment Phoebe and I walked in, we fought the urge to
leave. Granted, the sight of two women alone makes most
restaurateurs as happy as an unannounced visit by the health
inspector, but this was a new low. We were first led to a table
next to the restrooms, a service area and a table set for 18. When
we balked, we were relocated to the rear banquette; the
free-standing tables were reserved, we were told. Apparently, our
reservation didn't count.
</P>
<P>
   The chef, Frankel, is from Shallots Chicago and trained at the
Cooking Hospitality Institute of Chicago. Her $47 stuffed rack of
lamb seemed to indicate the scope of her ambitions, so Phoebe
ordered it and I ordered the grilled rib-eye, my favorite steak.
But here was an example of the new kosher gone wrong. While the
lamb was tasteless (forget the apricots, where's the salt?), the
rib-eye was downright unrecognizable. I called over a waiter, who
summoned a manager. ``What is this?'' I asked, genuinely confused.
``It's rib-eye,'' he explained. ``The chef orders it without the
bone and takes off the lip, which is the meat surrounding the eye.
That's the part with the fat in it, which is why there's no flavor.
Do you want something else?'' No. I wanted my steak with all the
fat in it so it tasted like steak _ the kind, actually, we used to
eat at Grossinger's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most of the other customers seemed suitably
impressed, though some remained skeptical. A man at one table _
where a laptop was up and running for most of the meal _ surveyed
the menu and asked loudly, ``What the hell is French melon
sorbet?,'' referring to an ingredient in the heirloom tomato salad.
</P>
<P>
   After two forgettable desserts, we got the check, which came to
$100 a person, about $20 more than it had been at Levana, $40 more
than at Il Patrizio, which, granted, had no meat. At Shallots, I
added a 15 percent tip without realizing that an 18 percent
gratuity had been added for me. I read it only after I'd left, in
the fine print at the bottom of the menu. Do I need to tell you
that no one pointed out my error?
</P>
<P>
   These glitches aside, however, kosher fine dining has clearly
made strides, and judging by the full dining rooms, it is
definitely satisfying its audience. But as much as I miss the onion
rolls at the old Ratner's, there is one thing I'm still certain of:
when it's time to eat out, I'll have the lobster. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
