<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2401 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PORTRAIT-WASHINGTON-$     09-26 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTRAIT-WASHINGTON-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMILE WARMED MARTHA WASHINGTON'S HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.H., Pa., Va., Britain)   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ On a Saturday in early October 1789, George Washington
powdered his graying brown hair, donned a yellow waistcoat, lace
cravat and the blue uniform with gold epaulettes that he had worn
as commander of the Continental Army and set off to meet John
Ramage, the most popular miniaturist in America. He probably went
to Ramage's studio on Williams Street in Lower Manhattan, 10 blocks
south of where he was staying on Cherry Street. There Ramage
painted his portrait, the first produced of Washington since he had
become president five months earlier. That night, he recorded the
event in his diary, writing, in his idiosyncratic way, ``Sat for
Mr. Ramage near two hours to-day who was drawing a miniature
Picture of me for Mrs. Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   The miniature, a half-length portrait in watercolor on ivory,
depicts Washington not as a man of power and authority but as
Martha Washington's husband of 30 years (she had also been married
previously). His thoughtful face, turned a bit to the right with
shadows accentuating the high brow and aristocratic nose, is
softened with a wisp of a smile, a Ramage trick. No doubt,
Washington knew how much Martha would treasure the intimate look of
the miniature, which he had Ramage, who was also a goldsmith, frame
in a 2[-inch elliptical gold locket edged with beading. On the
back, Ramage inscribed Washington's monogram on an oval of glass
covering a lock of hair said to be the president's.
</P>
<P>
   The locket has for most of the last two centuries remained in
the hands of two different families. A year or so after Washington
died, in 1799, Martha gave the locket to a niece, Betty Lewis
Carter, the daughter of his sister Betty, who had died before him.
In 1907, the locket was sold to Lucy Wharton Drexel, a member of
the Philadelphia family of bankers. In 1988, a descendant sent it
to Christie's in London. At a November auction that year, two
Americans _ Alexander Acevedo, a New York dealer, and Eddy G.
Nicholson, a New Hampshire investor and collector _ vied for the
locket by telephone from their homes in America at 5 o'clock in the
morning. The bidders, who knew each other well, were unaware that
they were competitors at the sale, until later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was almost as stubborn as I was,'' said Acevedo, who bought
the locket for $623,000 _ 10 times the Christie's estimate _ a
price that remains the record for a miniature portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Acevedo exhibited the miniature at his booth
at the Winter Antiques Show in Manhattan, and Nicholson, his first
customer, bought it for $650,000. Now he is selling it at
Christie's in New York on Jan. 19. It is expected to bring from
$600,000 to $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington's loathing of sitting for his portrait is
well-documented, but this portrait is different because it is so
personal'' said Susan D. Kleckner, Christie's specialist in
American folk art and miniatures. So was the second image of
Washington that Ramage painted at the same sitting, a frontal view,
that is now in the collection of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
(Ramage also made a copy of each; the second of the frontal
versions is in the Robert Hull Fleming Museum at the University of
Vermont; the whereabouts of the fourth miniature is unknown.)
</P>
<P>
   Miniatures painted by Ramage were prized for their brilliant
colors and long delicate brush strokes. The rich, layered surfaces
were livelier than those on the enameled images that were also
popular in the period. Ramage's portraits differ from many others
of Washington because they are more personal, less formal and each
has a trace of a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The two versions that Ramage painted that day also differ in
more than the way the subject is posed. The differences are readily
apparent when the portraits are seen side by side. Recently,
Kleckner brought Martha's miniature to the Metropolitan Museum,
where it was placed alongside the museum version for comparison. In
Martha's slightly larger miniature, Washington seemed to be looking
into the distance, lost in thought. In the other version, he looks
equally intense, but his eyes are directly on the viewer, as if he
were about to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Martha's miniature, on which virtually every owner is
identified by engravings on the back of the locket, the museum's
work was of unknown provenance until 1924. It was then that the
last owner, Charles Allen Munn, a collector of Washington paintings
who was the publisher of the Scientific American, bequeathed it to
the museum.
</P>
<P>
   What is less well known to the public today is Martha
Washington's feelings about miniatures and lockets. She cherished
these pictures and had many painted of her children from her first
marriage, and she often enclosed locks of their hair as expressions
of intimacy. To many mourners who sent her letters of condolences
after Washington's death, she sent locks of his hair.
</P>
<P>
   What was the significance of the hair? ``Hair was precious,
intimate and incredibly meaningful,'' said Carrie Barrattc, a
curator of American Paintings and Sculpture at the museum who is an
expert on miniatures. ``We forget today _ when most everyone's hair
is so visible, and hair is being swept into dust bins in beauty
parlors everywhere _ that in the 18th century you rarely saw
people's hair. They wore hats, veils and kerchiefs; they powdered
their hair or wore wigs. Hair helped to commemorate a person. In a
locket it made a portrait into a token of affection rather than a
record of a likeness. These are secular reliquaries, watercolor on
ivory _ bone _ and occasionally, hair at the back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
