<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TAX-PENSIONS27-COX     09-26 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-PENSIONS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE LOGJAM IMPERILS RETIREMENT SAVINGS BILL
 &HT;    750&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You'll be able to put a lot more money into a
tax-protected IRA or 401(k) retirement savings account _ if the
Senate can get its act together in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The popular pension bill is one of the few small measures to
survive this year's battle over major tax cuts between President
Clinton and Congress. But it remains stalled in a legislative
traffic jam in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's just a question of getting agreement on
what vehicle (piece of legislation) that will be attached to in
this session,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said
Tuesday. But he said he didn't know when that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   The House has voted twice for a bipartisan plan crafted by Reps.
Rob Portman, R-Ohio, and Ben Cardin, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had some minor objections, but didn't
issue a veto threat. In any case, the measure passed by veto-proof
margins of 401-25 in July and 401-20 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, it would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Raise the $2,000 annual limit on Individual Retirement Account
(IRA) contributions to $5,000 for someone under 50, and $10,000 for
someone 50 or older. The new limits would apply both to a regular
IRA, in which contributions are tax-free but withdrawals are
taxable, and to a Roth IRA, where contributions are taxable but
withdrawals are tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raise the $10,500 annual limit on contributions to a regular
401(k) plan to $15,000 for those under 50, and $20,000 for those 50
or older. In addition, companies for the first time could offer
their employees a Roth 401(k) plan, which would have the same
higher limits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make technical changes supported by most groups of employees
or employers. The changes would simplify and clarify federal
pension laws, raise the income ceilings for all tax-favored
retirement savings and pension plans, tie future IRA and 401(k)
contribution limits to inflation and increase the portability of
pension benefits for job-hoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bipartisan and thoroughly vetted, and I hope we can dig
it out of the political back-and-forth,'' Portman said. ``This is
urgently needed, because about half the work force lacks any
pension coverage at all, and in small businesses the percentage
covered by pension plans is below 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's primary beneficiaries would be people who are well
off _ the 2 percent of taxpayers who already give the $2,000
maximum to their IRAs, and the 6 percent of 401(k) plan users who
already give the $10,500 maximum. Older people who didn't save much
when they were young would also benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how many savers take advantage of the opportunity,
the Treasury would lose between $42 billion and $100 billion in
revenue over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the economy would benefit if personal savings
increase. Moreover, the extra fees and commissions from savers who
increased their retirement savings or switched from taxable to
tax-protected investments would help the securities industry,
giving it new revenue far in excess of the $25 million a year that
it contributes to the major parties.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Senate Finance Committee approved a modified
retirement savings bill drafted by its chairman, Sen. William Roth,
R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   Roth included similar IRA and 401(k) provisions and added a
non-controversial proposal to require that companies switching
pension plans disclose to the workers whether their benefits would
be bigger under the old plan or the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   But two of Roth's other changes could make it harder to obtain
bipartisan agreement without a Senate floor fight.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives criticized a provision offering tax credits that
would match part of the retirement savings of some low-income and
middle-income taxpayers. Those eligible would include about 24
percent of families, those with adjusted gross incomes below
$10,000 per adult, according to calculations by Professor Jeffrey
Liebman of Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's other change enraged the employee-directed Pension Rights
Center and the AARP, an advocacy group for people 50 or older. It
would protect companies from age-discrimination suits when they
switch from old-fashioned ``defined contribution'' pension plans
(which reward seniority and early retirement) to new ``cash
balance'' pension plans (which discourage early retirement and
reward younger workers who job-hop).
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the wrong way to go,'' said policy analyst David
Certner of the AARP. ``There are more than 500 complaints pending
(at the Equal Employment Opportunities Commission) about age
discrimination filed by older workers who say their benefits were
reduced by these pension-plan switches.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Havey(cq), director of pension policy at the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, said the national business group ``strongly
supports'' Roth's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that early retirement subsidies were put in place in a
different era, when employers made an effort to avoid layoffs by
encouraging employees to retire,'' Havey said. ``Now a lot of our
members have hundreds of jobs they can't fill, and they don't want
to offer a bonus for some of their best and brightest employees to
walk out the door early.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who is preparing an amendment that
would gut the plan-switching provision, said, ``Instead of
providing additional protection from age discrimination, this
proposal appears to allow some employers to disregard existing
legal employee protections.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokeswoman for Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who
wrote the law that prohibits age discrimination in pension plans,
said Grassley believes Roth's proposal is ``a huge improvement over
current law.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about his bill's chances, Roth said, ``That's
going to become law. Well, I hope it will.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Arguments for the plan:
www.senate.gov/(tilde)finance/106-447.htm
</P>
<P>
   Arguments against the plan: www.cashpensions.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
