<HEADER>
A2407 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-HOMEWORK-HELP-TEX     09-26 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWORK-HELP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 WAYS TO MAKE HOMEWORK TIME PRODUCTIVE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies HOMEWORK-STRATEGIES)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting involved is the most important thing you can do to help
your kids with homework. An interested and active parent can help a
child learn, make sure the assignments are completed, and talk to
the teacher if problems develop.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this doesn't mean making your child's homework your
own. Or strong-arming teachers into what you may think is best.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and education experts offer these tips for parents who
want to help make homework time a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. Establish a routine: It's important to set aside a certain
time for doing homework each night. That way, it's more difficult
to push it aside.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Cooper, a first-grade teacher at Pate Elementary, can
vouch for routine as a parent: ``My son works at the kitchen table
while I'm doing the cooking,'' she says. ``By the time I finish
dinner, he's usually finished with his homework.''
</P>
<P>
   He can relax a little bit after school _ but once she starts
dinner, Cooper says, he knows it's homework time, and he gets
started.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. Establish a location: Provide a good place for studying _ a
quiet, well-lit desk or table. Designating a specific area makes it
easier to stay focused. Turn off the TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're doing (homework) in front of the TV, they can spend
three hours in front of the TV and still not have studied for a
test,'' says Joe Ferrara, who teaches seventh- and eighth-graders
at Fort Worth's Riverside Middle School. ``Try to keep that area
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. Establish communication: Get to know your child's teacher.
Express concerns. Teachers want you to talk to them. Your teacher
will help you figure out if your child is truly overchallenged by
the work, or just resistant to doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like some parents are scared to come,'' says Como
Montessori School teacher Jeff Bartolotta. ``It's such a help. It
makes our job so much easier when parents come and say what they
need to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't be confrontational _ the teacher probably wants to
help your child just as much as you do.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4. Pay attention: Know what your child is learning. Sit with
her, let her read to you, ask her questions. But don't do her
homework for her _ her teacher needs to see where she's having
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I was a kid, I did my homework with my
parents,'' Bartolotta says. ``They were helping me and I was
teaching them. Now, I don't believe that happens as much.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps to check your child's homework after it's completed _
as long as your ``child'' is the one making the corrections.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   5. Offer guidance: Figure out your child's learning style, and
help him find the way he learns best. Talk to him about what he's
learning, and make sure he understands lessons and assignments.
</P>
<P>
   This might mean you have to do a little prodding _ ``A lot of
times, students don't always tell parents they have homework,''
Perry says. Be aware of the assignment and do what you can to help.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   6. Do some troubleshooting: If your child's having trouble, find
out what is troubling her, says Patty Yoxall with the National PTA.
Pinpoint the problem and work on it together _ and go to the
teacher if it's something you can't fix.
</P>
<P>
   Many problems can be solved, though, with a little parental
guidance. If disorganization is the problem, get your child a
calendar or assignment book and help her learn to use it. If time
management is a struggle, take charge, and gradually teach your
child to budget time on her own.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   7. Make it bearable: If the assignment is overwhelming, break it
up into parts for your child.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a stack of worksheets due the next day, your child might
do part of the work immediately after school, then take a break and
finish it later. If it's a spelling test on Friday, don't let your
child try to memorize all the words Thursday night. Start on
Monday; have her write the words for a couple of days, then start
quizzing her midweek.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   8. Do the hardest part _ the dreaded part of the assignment _
first. Get it over with and ``the rest is pure pleasure,'' Yoxall
says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   9. Introduce the shocking idea that homework can be enjoyable.
``Make it an exercise in learning as opposed to a drill that's
going to be graded,'' Yoxall suggests. Your attitude will influence
your child's attitude; help them realize the work is important, she
says, ``not just a grind that's keeping them off the softball
field.'' Play Hangman with spelling words; make word searches and
other games to help with exercises aimed at memorization.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   10. Be realistic about time: Your child might be involved in too
many activities. If he is sleep-deprived and never seems to have
any downtime, re-evaluate his activities schedule. But don't be
rash: Don't automatically decree that your child has to drop band
or leave the soccer team he loves _ involvement is good for kids,
too. Yoxall suggests talking to your child's teacher before
dropping any activities.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _ Alyson Ward
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Decrease homework hassles with tried-and-true incentives
</P>
<P>
   If your child is dawdling over his spelling list, ``forgetting''
science projects and arguing about the importance of long division,
maybe he just needs a little incentive. You, concerned parent, can
help.
</P>
<P>
   Child discipline expert Dr. Sal Severe, author of ``How To
Behave So Your Children Will, Too,'' (Viking Press, $23.95), offers
some suggestions in his book. Try these tactics to motivate your
child:
</P>
<P>
   Make a checklist or a chart your child can fill out. Make a list
of the necessary steps for completing homework (''write down
assignments,'' ``start on time,'' ``check your work,'' etc.) and
offer daily, weekly or long-term rewards. This instills good habits
and helps your child know what is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and educational software can make work much more
appealing. Try some educational software programs, a CD-ROM
encyclopedia or an online research service. They're effective and
their novelty can make work more interesting. Our editors' picks:
Titles by The Learning Company, including the Reader Rabbit series
(good for beginning readers).
</P>
<P>
   Don't use punishment as a motivator. Punishment doesn't work
that way, Severe says _ you can't make your child learn by
punishing, and arguments over homework only give kids another
button to push. Instead, encourage your child. Instead of fighting
over homework, be positive and help your child develop
self-discipline.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _ Alyson Ward
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
