<HEADER>
A2427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-CANNED-PUMPKIN0927-CO     09-26 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNED-PUMPKIN0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canned pumpkin fills the bill for many busy hometown cooks
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - My mother always made pumpkin pie from scratch,
using the little pumpkins my father grew. She did it even when she
made 20 pies for the church circle meeting.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Mom, I'll admit I keep a couple of cans of
pumpkin puree on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   I use it for my Thanksgiving pie (my excuse is that most of the
pumpkins are gone by then). And canned pumpkin is good for a quick
pumpkin bread.
</P>
<P>
   Now everyone has a recipe for pumpkin bread, that cheap, quick
bread that's a fall staple. I call this one Not Your Mother's
Pumpkin Bread. It's adult bread that includes sherry. It is not as
sweet, and the spicing is more delicate.
</P>
<P>
   And nut oil, either walnut or hazelnut, adds heady flavor. Yes,
that oil is expensive but this is a quick bread to serve with tea
or sherry rather than feed the troops. You can use cheap sunflower
oil, but the aroma and taste will be more neutral.
</P>
<P>
   I added nuts for more texture. Use walnuts with walnut oil,
hazelnuts with hazelnut oil.
</P>
<P>
   This is a big recipe, and the batter will nearly fill your
largest mixing bowl. Expect some splatters while you mix.
</P>
<P>
   NOT YOUR MOTHER'S PUMPKIN BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 loaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 26-ounce can pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup walnut or hazelnut oil
</P>
<P>
   4 2/3 cups unbleached all purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons each ground cinnamon, cloves and coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cream sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups walnuts or hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease three 8-by-4-inch loaf pans.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl combine the sugars, pumpkin, eggs and nut oil.
Beat with an electric mixer one minute.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl combine the flour, baking soda, spices and salt.
</P>
<P>
   With a large spatula combine the wet and dry mixtures and beat
until smooth. Stir in the cream sherry. Beat with an electric mixer
until thoroughly blended, 1 to 2 minutes. Mix in nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the batter into the loaf pans, filling each no more than
3/4 full.
</P>
<P>
   Bake immediately in the center of the preheated oven for 65 to
75 minutes, until a cake tester inserted into each center comes out
clean. Let stand 5 minutes in the pans before turning out onto a
rack to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap tightly in plastic wrap and let set at room temperature
overnight. The loaves can be kept at room temperature for as long
as 4 days, or frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 341 calories, 14.7
g fat, 35.5 mg cholesterol, 291 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to convenience, canned pumpkin isn't my only
culinary sin. Although it's true you can save the pumpkin seeds
from a pumpkin, cleaning them is just too much trouble for the
rewards. I'd rather buy green pumpkin seeds (found with bulk nuts
in some stores) and take just a few minutes to fix this addictive
appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY PUMPKIN SEEDS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, halved
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound hulled green pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Place the oil and garlic, cut side down, in an 8-inch skillet.
Heat, lightly browning the garlic. Remove garlic from the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pumpkin seeds to the skillet and stir to coat well with
the oil. Sprinkle the cayenne over the seeds and stir to mix. Cook,
stirring frequently, until the pumpkin seeds have popped and begun
to turn brown, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the seeds on paper towels, then place in a medium bowl.
Sprinkle with salt. These can be made as long as a week ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 101 calories, 6.5
g fat, no cholesterol, 70 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   When I want a pumpkin pie taste without the trouble, I dig out
an old recipe for pumpkin custards. This version, from Short &AMP;
Sweet by Melanie Barnard (Houghton Mifflin, $25) is even easier.
You do need to bake the custards in a water bath for the proper
texture, but that's actually easy. Use a large baking pan or
roaster, fill halfway with hot water, and place the filled cups in
the bath to bake.
</P>
<P>
   SPICED PUMPKIN CUSTARDS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups half and half
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup unsweetened pumpkin puree
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pumpkin pie spice or ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bourbon or dark rum, optional
</P>
<P>
   ginger lemon cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a small saucepan, bring the half
and half to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl whisk together the pumpkin, eggs, brown sugar,
spice and bourbon or rum. Slowly whisk the hot cream into the egg
mixture until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the custard among 6 custard cups. Place the cups in a
high-sided baking pan half filled with hot water. Bake the custards
in the water bath until they are nearly set in the center, about 25
to 30 minutes. Remove the cups from the water bath (it's easy if
you use sturdy tongs). Let cool for a few minutes to serve warm, or
refrigerate for as long as 8 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with ginger lemon whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Whip 1 1/2 cups cream, add the grated zest of one lemon and 2
tablespoons minced ginger or crystallized ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 169 calories, 7.5
g fat, 89 mg cholesterol, 50 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
