r d BC-CRUMBS-COLUMN0927-COX     09-26 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUMBS-COLUMN0927-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ByAUSTIN, Texas - Update: A couple of readers called to say they
had seen the frozen peanut butter and jelly sandwiches in the
freezer case at Sam's Clubs. The sandwiches were mentioned in this
column last week, but Smucker's had said they were not yet in
Texas, only the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Pyle on the veggies: Star Canyon's Stephan Pyles serves up his
favorite vegetarian recipes in a brand new cookbook that gives a
southwestern flavor to most of the dishes. But face it, you just
can't keep this fifth-generation West Texan down on the ranch, so
expect a few departures like Eggplant-Roasted Garlic Curry With
Lentils in ``Stephan Pyles Southwestern Vegetarian'' (Potter, $30).
Some of the recipes are fiveingredient simple; others, like the
Tortilla Vegetable Napoleon, go up to 40 ingredients (and beg for a
photograph.)
</P>
<P>
   Pyles acknowledges that he is still a card-carrying carnivore
and that these recipes could be served as entrees or side dishes.
Wonder which ones will appear on the menu at his Austin Star
Canyon, slated to open at the Stephen F. Austin Hotel in December?
</P>
<P>
   Tapioca tea: Sounds strange, but the San Jose Mercury News
reports that this cold drink is on the rise. Also known as pearl
tea or frothy milk tea, the mixture is shaken like a cocktail so
the resulting drink has a froth on top and pearls, or tapioca
balls, on the bottom. Made from yams and soaked in brown sugar, the
tapioca balls are slightly chewy and slippery, sucked up through an
oversized straw. The drink was introduced in Taiwan more than a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   With a Spanish accent: Cooking Light, the country's largest food
magazine, has announced that it will publish a new magazine geared
toward the Hispanic market. Gusto! will be out in April,
reflecting, like Cooking Light, both food and lifestyle. The editor
will be Cuban-born Viviana Carballo, whose work has appeared in the
Miami Herald and El Nuevo Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-Com Combo: In Austin, we tend to find most foodstuffs we
need. For those who have not, however, maybe this new partnership
will help. Dean &AMP; Deluca, that well-known New York food retailer,
has hooked up with Epicurious.com, one of the country's top food
Web sites to offer some 800 items. Click on a food and Epicurious
will tell how to cook or serve it. A nice touch, but cooks can get
similar information by going directly to deandeluca.com. (FYI: The
price of Beluga caviar (2.2 pounds) is $2,350 at both sites.)
</P>
<P>
   Items for this column are drawn from wire reports, mail,
personal observation and comments from readers. To pass on a
suggestion, call food editor Kitty Crider at 445-3656, or write to
Food, Austin American-Statesman, P.O. Box 670, Austin 78767.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
