r d BC-PUMPKIN-BOX0927     09-26 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKIN-BOX0927 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 6-pound pumpkin sitting on the kitchen counter can be an
intimidating ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   So when the recipe calls for ``peeled, seeded pumpkin cubes''
here's what you do:
</P>
<P>
   Forget about using a vegetable peeler. Get out a big, heavy
knife.
</P>
<P>
   Put the pumpkin on a cutting board and cut into quarters. Use a
spoon or melon baller to remove seeds. Place a quarter pumpkin cut
side down. To cut off the skin, slice down from top to bottom.
Don't worry about the waste _ this is a cheap vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Then cut the pumpkin flesh into wedges or cubes, depending on
the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   If the recipe calls for pumpkin puree, as most desserts do,
steaming the pumpkin is better than boiling it, which can make the
pumpkin even more watery than it is naturally. Chef Diana Alspaugh
suggests oven-steaming pumpkin cubes. Put them in a large roasting
pan or a foil-lined broiling pan, add 1/2 cup of water, cover with
foil (dull side out), and roast in a 350-degree oven. Timing varies
with the density of the pumpkin. It ranges from 30-60 minutes. The
pumpkin cubes should be tender and easily pierced with the tip of a
sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   Puree the pumpkin in a ricer or food mill. A food processor can
be used for the very smooth puree that's desirable in a pie.
</P>
<P>
   For many side dishes the cubes are seasoned and oven-roasted
uncovered until browned, adding to the flavor. Be sure to oil the
bottom of the pan and lightly oil or butter the squash cubes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ann Heller
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
