<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-PUMPKINS0927-COX     09-26 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKINS0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't be a pumpkin bumpkin
 &HT;    Cooking varieties are good for more than just making pies
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - There's more to pumpkin than jack-o'-lanterns and
more to eat than pumpkin pie.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Bonnie Mercuri of Bonnybrook Farms in Centerville.
She's been growing specialty pumpkins for four years, and this year
her harvest of cooking pumpkins ranges from an oversized
muffin-shaped blue pumpkin called Queensland Blue to tiny Wee B
Little specimens.
</P>
<P>
   And while she's not one to put down a pumpkin pie, the dish
etched in her memory is pumpkin stew.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the dishes fixed by chef Diana Alspaugh, who's
been on the receiving end of Mercuri's cooking pumpkins in recent
years. Alspaugh rides at Bonnybrook's stables, and when the owners
found out she's a chef, they started giving her pumpkins to test.
</P>
<P>
   Alspaugh, executive chef at Sinclair Community College, has a
history of using fresh pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Kitty's (a former downtown restaurant), I
roasted pumpkin cubes and served that with sage cream on penne,''
she says. At The Courtyard, another downtown restaurant, she used
fresh pumpkin puree in cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   Her experiments with Bonnybrook's cooking pumpkins have expanded
her repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Not all pumpkins are good for eating. Certainly not the one sold
for the traditional jack-o'-lantern. And even some sold as cooking
pumpkins can be watery and bland. It pays to buy by name.
</P>
<P>
   In three years of cooking with specialty pumpkins, Alspaugh has
identified the best varieties.
</P>
<P>
   The deep red Rouge Vif d'Etampes, a French heirloom pumpkin,
springs to her mind first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all edible with low water content and not a lot of
seeds,'' she says. ``And it has flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckskin is prized for its deep orange flesh. Whangaparoa, a
gray-blue pumpkin from New Zealand, is ``outstanding,'' she says.
The Jarrahdale, another blue-skinned pumpkin from Australia,
``makes the best pies.'' Hokaido, with a fiberless and dry flesh
that's like a winter squash, is another favorite but it's not
always available.
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans pumpkin is synonymous with pie, and that's
pie made with a can of pumpkin puree. Pumpkin bread also has a
small following and pumpkin muffins show up alongside seasonal
pumpkin ice cream scooped up at Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   The key for a new attitude about pumpkin, Mercuri says, is just
thinking of pumpkin like winter squash. And chefs around the
country are adding their own spin to the native harvest. In the
past decade, various styles of pumpkin soup began showing up on the
menus of chefs who like to focus on native produce.
</P>
<P>
   They also have borrowed extensively from other cuisines, which
have taken a more imaginative approach to pumpkins and squash.
Italians may lead the way. Consider this specialty: wedges of
pumpkin, dusted with flour and sauteed, then topped with fresh
tomato sauce. Or pumpkin turned into a soup made hearty with broken
spaghetti. Or that signature dish of northern Italy, tortelli (or
ravioli), filled with a mixture of pumpkin and Parmesan, and sauced
with butter and more Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   American chefs have followed that lead, adding Indian curry to
the pumpkin soup and Sichuan peppercorns to sauteed pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   We don't go quite that far, but we're taking pumpkin to a new
level with recipe on Page 4C for Alspaugh's pumpkin stew.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
