<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKINSTEW0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No need to get in a stew over this dish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUMPKIN STEW
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 entree servings
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried dill weed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   6 cups diced pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   1 red pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups frozen corn
</P>
<P>
   1 can kidney beans
</P>
<P>
   Splash of vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 can diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 cups water or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy pan heat the oil and add the onion and cook until
tender. Add the garlic and mushrooms and dried herbs. Cook until
the mushrooms release their liquid and add remaining ingredients
except the cornmeal.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil, then turn the heat down to a low simmer. Cook
just until the pumpkin becomes soft.
</P>
<P>
   Taste and add additional salt and pepper if needed. Add the
cornmeal as a thickener if the stew is too soupy. Cooking time is
about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving (for 8 servings):
126 calories, 3.8 g fat, no cholesterol, 19 mg sodium (plus salt to
taste).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
