<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH POUNDS EDUCATION , RAISES CASH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush pressed for new incentives for math and science
teachers Tuesday in Redwood City, Calif., on the edge of Silicon
Valley, and raised money for Republicans in California, where he
trails Al Gore. Bush spent a second day on the West Coast promoting
his 10-year, $47 billion education package and reiterating his
claim that the nation is in the grip of an ``education recession.''
He also was headlining two fund-raisers in California designed to
bring $1.4 million for the state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY HITS GORE ON CREDIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney charged Tuesday that Al Gore ``has failed to speak
the truth'' about all sorts of things, from claiming he helped
invent the Internet to misrepresenting the Republican presidential
ticket's Medicare plan. In a speech at a Polish cultural center in
Troy, Mich., Cheney accused Gore of ``distorted and demagogic''
characterizations of George W. Bush's prescription drug plan for
Medicare and presented a laundry list of other Gore assertions that
he called ``not true. False.'' Cheney said seniors would be much
better off with Bush's Medicare plan, saying Gore's proposal ``is
not leadership; it's gimmickry.'' Cheney also was visiting Detroit
and Philadelphia today.
</P>
<P>
   SERIOUS QUESTIONS FOR GORE ON MTV
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxers or briefs'' is so yesterday, so Bill Clinton. For Al
Gore, MTV was the place today to talk about more substantive
issues. Gore promised that a ban on the police practice of racial
profiling will, if he is elected president, ``be the first civil
rights act of the 21st century.'' He made the pledge at the
University of Michigan during a taping of the hip cable channel's
``Choose Or Lose'' program, to be broadcast at 8 p.m. tonight. En
route to Michigan from Florida, Gore appeared flummoxed when a
reporter asked if he was prepared to answer ``boxers or briefs?''
``Oh, God. I'd better . . . work on that one,'' he moaned. MTV
representatives said George W. Bush has been invited to make a
similar appearance, but has not yet accepted.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING TO SOLIDIFY LEAD IN NEW JERSEY
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman took a swipe at George W. Bush's claim that he
offers ``real plans for real people,'' telling senior citizens
Tuesday that Bush's Medicare package is ``a real problem for real
seniors.'' In an address to about 300 senior citizens in Union,
N.J., Lieberman said that with the prices of prescription drugs
increasing and the number of baby boomers entering the Medicare
system expected to skyrocket, ``That's not just a price crisis in
my opinion; it is a prescription for a humanitarian crisis.'' The
Democrats hoped that Lieberman's appearance before seniors -- and
later, before union bricklayers in Atlantic City -- will help
solidify the Democratic lead in New Jersey. The state, with 15
electoral votes, favors the Gore-Lieberman ticket, according to
recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   PRESSURE ON TO EXIT SENATE RACE
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats growing increasingly hopeful about their chances
of regaining control of the Senate this fall, several of Joe
Lieberman's colleagues are pressuring him to let another
Connecticut Democrat seek his Connecticut Senate seat so that the
party won't lose it if he becomes vice president. Among those
Senate colleagues are Harry Reid (Nev.), Byron Dorgan (N.D.) and
Robert Torricelli (N.J.). Under state law, Lieberman is permitted
to run for both offices at the same time. But if he wins both, he
would give up his Senate seat and Gov. John Rowland, a Republican,
would be able to appoint his replacement. Lieberman's rival for the
vice presidency, Dick Cheney, took a shot Tuesday, saying
Lieberman's decision to stick with the Senate contest shows a lack
of confidence in his vice- presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL TO TARGET VOTES IN 15 STATES
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League is
about to announce plans for a $5 million, 15-state grass-roots
campaign designed to affect the outcome of the presidential race as
well as key Senate and House contests by targeting independent and
Republican voters who support abortion rights. The organization has
established a ``worst choice'' list of candidates that the
organization will be ``aggressively seeking to defeat,'' beginning
with George W. Bush, said NARAL President Kate Michelman. Beyond
the presidential race, NARAL hopes to affect the outcome of nine
Senate races and about two dozen House contests.
</P>
<P>
   APPEAL MADE TO FOLLOW N.Y. LEAD ON SOFT MONEY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's leading supporters of campaign finance legislation
appealed to Al Gore and George W. Bush to follow the lead set in
New York's Senate race and ban soft money ads in their battle for
the White House. ``In the same spirit that motivated the
Lazio-Clinton agreement, we respectfully encourage you to attempt
to make a similar agreement in your race,'' wrote Sens. John McCain
(R-Ariz.) and Russell Feingold (D-Wis.). ``Specifically, we urge
you . . . to reject any efforts by political parties to use soft
money to run independent radio or television advertisements in an
attempt to influence your race, and to appeal to independent
organizations to refrain from doing the same.'' Similar letters
were sent to all candidates for the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON WILL STILL HELP RAISE SOFT MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton said that she'll continue to help raise soft
money for the Democratic Party even though she's agreed with her
opponent, Rick Lazio, not to allow advertisements in their New York
Senate race paid for with the largely unregulated contributions.
Clinton said that she had helped raise money over the years for
Democratic candidates and that she had promised the party she'd
participate in additional fund-raising activities before the
election on Nov. 7 _ a pledge, she said, not affected by her deal
with Lazio to ban the use of soft money in their television and
radio advertising. Campaign officials said Clinton would be out of
the state on Thursday and Friday raising money. Clinton said that
she would have no say in how the soft money she raised would be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   GOP SPENDING IN DEMOCRATIC-LEANING STATES
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee contributed at least $1
million to nine different state parties last month, Federal
Election Commission records show. Besides giving millions to state
parties in Ohio and Michigan, the RNC also made seven-figure
transfers last month to California and Washington state, both of
which voted Democratic in recent presidential elections and where
close races for seats in Congress are being waged this year. The
RNC transferred $2.3 million to Pennsylvania, $2.2 million to Ohio
and $1.7 million to Michigan last month, three key battlegrounds.
The RNC also gave $1.7 million apiece to the Washington and
California state parties. Recent polls give Gore a double-digit
lead in the Golden State, and a slight edge in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG COMPANY DONATIONS TO GOP
</P>
<P>
   Three major pharmaceutical companies contributed $600,000 to
Senate Republican campaign coffers in a 13-day period in August as
Democrats in a number of tight Senate races stepped up promotion of
a prescription drug benefit opposed by the industry. The three
$200,000 ``soft money'' contributions, from Eli Lilly,
Bristol-Myers Squibb and Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Co., indicated growing
concern by the companies and the GOP that the prescription drug
issue is proving a potent one for Democrats in a number of close
races. Campaign reports for August filed with the Federal Election
Commission also show contributions to the Republican National
Committee of $100,000 and $107,200, respectively, from
Bristol-Myers and another pharmaceutical giant, Schering-Plough.
</P>
<P>
   PLOT THICKENS IN PURLOINED TAPE CASE
</P>
<P>
   While aides to George W. Bush say there may be a mole in their
midst, Texas Democrats are blaming the Republican campaign's top
dog for leaking sensitive information to the enemy camp. At issue:
How a debate preparation tape and confidential campaign documents
made it into the hands of a confidant of Al Gore. The FBI is
investigating. The Bush camp suggested the Gore campaign had
planted a spy in Austin. But Molly Beth Malcolm, Texas Democratic
chairman, offered up a different scenario: Karl Rove, Bush's chief
political consultant, manufactured the incident to create a
distraction from a campaign struggling to regain its footing.
``This has Karl Rove's fingerprints written all over it,'' Malcolm
said. She offered no proof to back up her contention.
</P>
<P>
   SUBLIMINAL REACTION FROM MAGAZINE
</P>
<P>
   The cover of The New Republic's Oct. 2 issue looks a lot like
any other cover of the weekly political magazine. But careful
readers might notice something different. In the solid red bar that
appears on cover of every issue are these barely visible words:
Don't Trust Arafat. But inside, there is no article on Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat. What gives? Editor Peter Beinart said he ran
the hidden headline as ``a response to the media obsession with
subliminal advertising,'' referring to the brouhaha that erupted
after the barely visible word ``RATS'' flashed in an ad for George
W. Bush, intentionally or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone was suddenly venting their deepest darkest
obsession in subliminal ways,'' said Beinart, ``why not us? It's a
humorous caricature of our position.''
</P>
<P>
   HOPING THAT PRACTICE MAKES PERFECT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush jokes that the problem with engaging in mock
debates with Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire is that often ``he
wins.'' Gregg has been playing the role of Al Gore in practice
sessions with Bush. And while Bush likes to give the impression
that he isn't putting much time or energy into such rehearsals, the
preparation has been under way for months. With the first debate a
week away (Oct. 3), Bush was heading to Austin on Wednesday for a
practice session. And at least one full 90-minute session with a
moderator and formal trappings is planned for the weekend. But
there's a danger in rehearsing too much, Bush says: ``Either you're
ready or you're not ready.'' He thinks he is.
</P>
<P>
   GORE AND BUSH: BACK TO BACK
</P>
<P>
   Joe Menichini, owner of the Keystone Massage Therapy Center in
Kingston, Pa., gave massage therapy to both George W. Bush and Al
Gore on successive days this month, according to the Wilkes-Barre
Citizen's Voice. Menichini said he was approached by Secret Service
agents on Sept. 5, then introduced to Bush. The masseur said he was
``nervous,'' but that Bush was ``really nice.'' The very next day,
Gore received a massage from Menichini's therapy center. The Gore
campaign had booked an appointment weeks before. Menichini said
Gore ``talked for the first five minutes, but he was really tired
and just relaxed because it was late.''
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATIC WIVES ON THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Lieberman, wife of the vice-presidential nominee, and
Hillary Clinton visited Riverdale Young Men's and Young Women's
Hebrew Association in the Bronx, N.Y. They met with local seniors
to discuss providing a voluntary prescription drug benefit for
seniors on Medicare, extending the solvency of Medicare and
modernizing Medicare. Tipper Gore, wife of the presidential
candidate, was campaigning in Cincinnati and Paducah, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   PORNOGRAPHERS FOR GORE?
</P>
<P>
   Comedians and competitors have made Al Gore sorry for claiming
credit in the birth of the Internet. Now online pornographers are
being encouraged to show their gratitude to the candidate. Reuters
new agency reports that a featured speaker at a trade show for the
Internet adult entertainment industry said a Gore presidency would
be good for business. ``The big message from the Gore camp has been
that there should be no control over the content of speech, but
control over access to the speech by individuals who are
underage,'' attorney Paul Cambria was quoted as saying at the
gathering. He labeled George W. Bush the pro-censorship candidate.
</P>
<P>
   NO HOLDS BARR-ED IN GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican, is airing his first TV spot
against Democrat Roger Kahn. The Barr camp, in a prepared
statement, described the ad as ``a lighthearted look'' at Kahn's
``recent move to the Seventh District.'' Barr calls Kahn a
carpetbagger, saying he moved to the district only last year. Kahn
previously lived in Key West, Fla., and the Buckhead section of
Atlanta before moving to Bartow County, according to the Barr
campaign. Barr, himself, is originally from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER SURGERY FOR N.D. GUBERNATORIAL HOPEFUL
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota Democratic gubernatorial candidate Heidi Heitkamp,
the state attorney general, underwent cancer surgery, five days
after doctors discovered the cancer in her right breast. The
operation is normally accompanied by weeks of follow-up treatment,
including chemotherapy and radiation, but campaign manager Denise
Lawson said Heitkamp, 44, intends to continue her run for governor.
Her Republican opponent, John Hoeven, said he was ``deeply
concerned about Heidi's health. We wish her a full and speedy
recovery, and will keep her and her family in our prayers.''
Hoeven, a banker, had ordered his campaign ads on radio and
television pulled for a few days after Heitkamp's diagnosis was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY'S FOSTER LINKED TO STRESS ILLNESS
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party vice-presidential candidate Ezola Foster was
prescribed an anti-depressant drug for most of 1997 and took breaks
from her job as a Los Angeles schoolteacher several times during
bouts of depression dating to the 1970s, according to records of
the state workers' compensation appeals board. The records indicate
Foster filed for workers' compensation three times, twice claiming
that she was mentally unable to return to a hostile work
environment. The reports were released to the Los Angeles Times
after a workers' comp judge denied Foster's request to seal her
file. Foster, an outspoken black conservative, is Reform Party
presidential nominee Pat Buchanan's choice for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG VOTERS: HIGH INTEREST, LOW INTENT
</P>
<P>
   Young voters are very interested in the top political issues,
but that doesn't appear to translate into plans to vote. Fewer than
half of adults ages 18 to 24 say they definitely will vote in
November, a new poll says. The survey, sponsored by the Kaiser
Family Foundation and MTV, noted that 64 percent of all adults say
they plan to vote, while only 46 percent of those younger than 25
say they are ``absolutely'' certain to vote in November. ``Voting
participation has been lower for young adults ever since the
18-year-olds got the right to vote in 1972,'' said Vicky Rideout,
who directed the survey. ``It's been going down every year except
for 1992. And we're on track again for low participation of young
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
