<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS-POVERTY27-COX     09-26 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-POVERTY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS BUREAU REPORTS RISING INCOMES, FALLING POVERTY
 &HT;    530&AMP;add.
 &HT;    With CENSUS-DATA.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The typical American family broke the $40,000
barrier last year as the humming economy pushed income levels to
record highs and poverty rates to record lows, the Census Bureau
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Americans enjoyed income gains for a record fifth consecutive
year in 1999, with inflation-adjusted earnings rising to a median
$40,816, its highest level since the survey began measuring income
data in 1967. Half of all households made more than the median
amount, and half made less.
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy also drove the poverty rate to its lowest
level in two decades, with the number of poor people last year
falling by 2.2 million compared to 1998. It was the third straight
year that the nation's poverty rate declined, to 11.8 percent from
12.7 percent in 1998. However, the rate remained above the historic
low of 11.1 percent set in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, a total of 32.3 million people lived below the poverty
line, defined as $17,029 for a family of four and $13,290 for a
family of three.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the rolling good times were widely felt by whites,
blacks, Hispanics and Asians, according to the income and poverty
data. However, poverty among foreign-born residents remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty in the South remained statistically unchanged from 1998,
but still at its all-time low of 13.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 median household income reached record levels in the
South, at $37,422, and in the Midwest, but remained unchanged from
1998 in the Northeast and West.
</P>
<P>
   While the numbers were positive _ median inflation-adjusted
income up 2.7 percent from $39,744 in 1998 _ the 1999 figure was
only about $2,000 higher than the level in 1989, or about a $4 a
week increase in earnings when averaged over the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Overall household earnings did not grow as fast in 1999 and they
did the previous year, and did not keep pace with the overall
growth of the economy. Incomes rose 2.7 percent from 1998 to 1999,
compared to a 3.5 percent jump from 1997 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is evidence that wage growth is actually
slowing in an economy that has been growing,'' said Jared Bernstein
of the labor-backed Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, a Washington research group, calculates that
middle-income families had to work 33 more hours in 1999 to
maintain the same standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   The government's annual snapshot of wealth and poverty, based on
a survey of 50,000 American households and released each year in
late September, provided fodder for Democrats and Republicans just
six weeks before the election.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton immediately hailed the report as ``another
economic milestone'' for the Clinton-Gore administration. ``This is
a good day for America,'' Clinton said. ``We have proved that we
can lift all boats in a modern, global, information-based
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans credited the welfare reforms they
endorsed and enacted in 1996 with lowering the numbers of poor
people. Rep. E. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., a member of the House Ways and
Means Committee, said that without welfare reform, there would be
``more children in poverty and more adults getting a welfare check
instead of a paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Except for whites, the poverty rate for the nation's major
racial and ethnic groups set or equaled historic lows, the Census
Bureau said. The rate for African-Americans was 23.6 percent;
Hispanics, 22.8 percent; Asian and Pacific Islanders, 10.7 percent;
and non-Hispanic whites, 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While some regions fared better than others, no state saw income
fall or poverty increase from 1998 levels, based on comparisons of
two-year averages.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in poverty was concentrated in major cities, while
poverty rates in suburbs, small towns and rural areas changed only
slightly. Poverty dropped in just seven states and the District of
Columbia, while remaining at 1998 levels elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Economic analysts said the report was positive, but pointed to
some trouble signs:
</P>
<P>
   _ The poverty rate for children, 16.9 percent, was the lowest
since 1979, with 1.4 million fewer children classified as poor in
1999. Yet children remain particularly vulnerable, since they make
up 26 percent of the total population, but 38 percent of the poor.
The news is worse for children under the age of 6 living with a
mother but no father. Their poverty rate last year was 50.3
percent, more than five times the rate for children living in
two-parent families.
</P>
<P>
   _ After reaching an all-time high in earnings compared to men in
1996, women's income relative to men is backsliding slightly.
Full-time working women earned 74 cents on the dollar compared to
men in 1996, and 72 cents last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ While the report says the poorer are not getting poorer, the
Census Bureau figures do not fully calculate just how much richer
the rich are becoming.
</P>
<P>
   The study defines wealthiest Americans as households earning
more than $1 million, but does not analyze further what is
occurring at the upper reaches of that group, where other economic
surveys show that wealth as grown in recent years as a result of
the booming economy and gains in equity markets. Also, the Census
Bureau measures income based on wages, and not income from capital
gains, dividends and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what's happened in this country since 1993, it doesn't
tell us much. The top group (of earners) has done amazingly well
and the census data simply doesn't pick it up,'' said Isaac
Shapiro, an economist with the Washington-based Center on Budget
and Policy Priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Only a more detailed economic analysis using data from income
tax returns and other sources would give a more reliable picture of
the nation's affluent, said Daniel Weinberg, chief of the housing
and household economic statistics division of the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau, the Office of Management and Budget and other
federal agencies are conducting a long-term study on other possible
measures which could revise the way income and poverty are
measured. The current formulas have changed relatively little since
the system was created in the mid-1960s as part of President Lyndon
Johnson's ``war on poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
