<HEADER>
A2453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      09-26 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HERBS AND MORE HERBS, VINAIGRETTE GOES BEYOND SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This is the seventh column of a series by Eberhard Mueller,
who is the executive chef and owner of Lutece; this was written
with JACK BISHOP.) 
 By EBERHARD MUELLER 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home cooks rarely think of vinaigrette as a sauce. In most
kitchens, vinaigrette has only one use: as a dressing for salad
greens.
</P>
<P>
   But if you bulk up oil and vinegar with plenty of good mustard
and fresh herbs, the familiar vinaigrette turns into something else
entirely, with a consistency almost like pesto. That shouldn't be
such a surprise: vinaigrette is a cold sauce, after all, just like
pesto, aioli and tapenade.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite herb vinaigrette calls for as much minced herbs as
oil. This sauce is too thick for drizzling over lettuce, but it
naps a piece of poached fish perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   For my herb vinaigrette, I use bits of every herb growing behind
my farmhouse. Minced basil, mint, chervil, garlic chives, parsley,
cilantro and chives create a vibrant sauce bursting with fresh herb
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can trade some complexity for simplicity and use
fewer herbs. Substitute more of another herb with similar intensity
if you can't track down every herb in the market. And remember that
freshness is as important as variety. Dull herbs make a dull
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Another key to great herb flavor is a good mincing technique.
The first thing I teach young cooks in my restaurant is how to
handle herbs. Most cooks rock a chef's knife through herbs,
grinding them down into the board. This motion bruises the cell
structure and causes flavorful oils to be lost. If your cutting
board is dyed green every time you mince herbs, you're doing
something wrong. You want that flavor in your food, not the cutting
board.
</P>
<P>
   When I mince or chop herbs, I use a slicing motion. I pull the
front of the knife backward through a pile of herbs, rather than
pressing down and pushing the knife forward. (Using the front of
the knife is important. When most cooks mince, they grind the herbs
with the heavy back end of the knife.) I keep slicing the herbs
until they reach the texture I'm looking for. When I'm done, my
cutting board is clean.
</P>
<P>
   Minced this way, herbs have tremendous clarity of flavor. Even
though my vinaigrette calls for seven herbs, you can taste each
one.
</P>
<P>
   Because halibut is lean but meaty, it is the perfect fish for
this sauce. I poach the halibut, rather than grill or saute it, so
you can really taste the herbs. The poaching liquid is a quick
broth flavored with vegetables as well as white wine and vinegar
for acidity.
</P>
<P>
   You can easily play around with the vegetables in the broth,
adding fennel, celery, tomatoes, or even lemon grass. Or subtract
vegetables to make things simpler: just leeks, carrots and a bay
leaf will do, if that's all you have on hand. The idea is to use a
fair amount of vegetables _ as well as wine and vinegar _ so that
the broth is strong enough to flavor the fish. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POACHED HALIBUT WITH HERB VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 medium leeks, white and light green parts only, halved
lengthwise, cleaned and cut crosswise into several pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, sliced thick
</P>
<P>
   1 medium garlic clove, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   15 white peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Several sprigs each fresh thyme and basil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grapeseed oil
</P>
<P>
   Lemon juice to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons minced chives or garlic chives or a mixture of
both
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons of mixture of 2 to 4 minced herbs: basil, mint,
cilantro and chervil
</P>
<P>
   4 skin-on halibut fillets, 8 to 9 ounces, about 1{ inches
thick. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine leeks, carrots, onion, garlic, kosher salt,
peppercorns and bay leaf in medium casserole with 6 cups water.
Bring to a boil, reduce heat, cover, and simmer until vegetables
are soft, about 20 minutes. Add wine and white vinegar, cover, and
cook 10 minutes. Add thyme and basil sprigs. Turn off heat and cool
to room temperature. Strain broth.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk mustard, sherry and red wine vinegars, and salt and
pepper to taste with 4 teaspoons water in bowl. Whisk in oils until
dressing is emulsified. Add a few drops of lemon juice. Whisk in
herbs. Let stand at least 10 minutes. (It can be covered and set
aside for 1 hour.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour broth into large deep skillet. Add the halibut. (Liquid
should just cover pieces; if not, add water.) Bring to a simmer
over medium heat; by then the fish should be opaque and firm. (If
not, turn off the heat and cover pan.) Peel off the skin. Divide
the fish among 4 plates, and spoon vinaigrette over. Yield: 4
servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      09-26 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALLOPS WITH SNAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A crisp edge on scallops really brings out their sweetness. It's
easy to achieve when you saute them: dredge them in flour, cornmeal
or bread crumbs before adding them to the hot pan. But if you give
the crunchy crust an intense flavor, they're even better.
</P>
<P>
   The most basic technique is to season the flour or cornmeal with
herbs or spices. But it's even easier to skip the flour and dredge
the scallops in spices. It can't be done with dried herbs, which
don't get crisp, or with spices that are too strong to use in
quantity. But it works perfectly with curry powder, which also
seasons whatever is cooked with the scallops' sauce. I add chopped
tomatoes, which liquefy to make a light sauce that is wonderful
over rice.
</P>
<P>
   Curry powder is not really a spice itself but a mixture of
cumin, turmeric, coriander, pepper and other spices. Since you're
using a large quantity, two tablespoons, it should not be super-hot
or the dish will be fiery. I prefer a mild, sweet curry powder. It
should also be fairly fine; if it is too coarse, the crust will be
gritty rather than crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Once the scallops are very lightly dredged in the curry powder,
you sear them quickly. They brown in just a minute or two, and you
don't want to cook them longer than that: scallops are best rare.
The dish is finished with the tomatoes, lime juice and cilantro or
another herb.
</P>
<P>
   I like to add a little fresh or sour cream or yogurt to the
sauce, which turns it pink and creamy. If you use yogurt, the sauce
must not boil after you add it or it will curdle; a minute after
adding the tomatoes, turn the heat down to a minimum and just let
the yogurt warm gently in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   You could also use chili powder or any other spice mix in place
of curry powder.
</P>
<P>
   As for the herb, cilantro marries perfectly with the lime and
curry, as does mint. But basil, especially the fragrant, minty Thai
basil, is a more surprising and equally delicious option.
</P>
<P>
   CURRIED SCALLOPS WITH TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ to 2 pounds large sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons curry powder, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   { cup heavy cream, sour cream or yogurt, optional
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped fresh cilantro, Thai basil or mint.
</P>
<P>
   1. Core tomatoes, and squeeze and shake out their seeds. Chop
flesh into {-inch pieces and set aside. Heat the oil in a 12-inch
nonstick skillet over medium heat about 3 minutes. While it heats,
sprinkle scallops with salt and pepper, and spread curry powder on
a plate.
</P>
<P>
   2. When oil is hot, work quickly to dredge scallops lightly in
curry powder, and add to pan. About 2 minutes after you add first
scallop, turn it; it should be nicely browned. (If not, raise heat
a bit.) When scallops are all browned and turned, cook a minute
longer, and add tomatoes and heavy or sour cream if you're using
it. (If you are using yogurt, lower heat immediately; it must not
boil.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat tomatoes through. Taste and add more salt and pepper if
necessary. Sprinkle with lime juice, stir in herb and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
