<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2464 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SKYWATCH-AZR &LR;      09-26 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKYWATCH-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SKYWATCH-OCTOBER-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PEGASUS SOARS IN OCTOBER SKIES(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: in ``A'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JOHN STANLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pegasus, the flying horse of Greek mythology, is well-placed for
evening viewing as it soars through the skies of October.
</P>
<P>
   The legends say Pegasus was created by Poseidon, the god of the
sea, from sand and sea and the blood of Medusa, the snake-haired
monster slain by Perseus. The arrogant hero Bellerophon tried to
ride Pegasus up to Mount Olympus, but Zeus intervened and sent him
crashing down to earth. Pegasus arrived riderless on Olympus and
stayed to fetch Zeus his lightning and thunderbolts.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Square of Pegasus, one of the most prominent patterns
in the sky, is easy to find in October. Just face south and look
high overhead three or four hours after sunset. Though the corners
of the square are not overwhelmingly bright, they are easy enough
to pick out.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the four stars that mark the corners of the great
square actually belong to Pegasus. Alpheratz, in the northeast
corner, is a part of the constellation Andromeda.
</P>
<P>
   The great square is a good marker of celestial longitude, called
right ascension by astronomers. The east side of the square lies
very nearly on the 0 hour mark, the west side on the 23 hour mark.
And the stars of the west side point the way to the bright star
Fomalhaut in the south, the brightest member of the constellation
Piscis Austrinus.
</P>
<P>
   In the southwest corner of the square is Markab (''the
saddle''), the brightest star of Pegasus, a little more than 100
light-years away. Scheat, the northwest corner, is a huge, red
variable star, about 150 times bigger than our sun. More than 200
light-years distant, Scheat slowly and irregularly changes its
brightness.
</P>
<P>
   The southeast corner of the square, Algenib, is also a giant
star, about 570 light-years away.
</P>
<P>
   Enif, from the Arabic (beginitalic)Al-Anf(enditalic), ``the
nose,'' is about 780 light-years away, and is a handy guidepost to
one of the finest globular clusters in the sky. M15, about 4
degrees northwest of Enif, is a ball of hundreds of thousands of
stars 35,000 to 40,000 light-years away. Through binoculars it is a
small, faint patch of light, easily overlooked. But even a small
telescope reveals its true nature. Astronomers calculate that M15
is about 130 light-years in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting object can be found about 4 and  &QC;  degrees
north of Eta Pegasi, and just slightly west of it. NGC7331 is a
spiral galaxy about 50 million light-years away. It's faint, but
you can make out its oval shape with backyard telescopes.
Long-exposure photographs display its true splendor, however. The
beautiful spiral arms and dark dust lanes that wrap around
NGC7331's central core give us a good idea of what our own Milky
Way galaxy would look like if we could view it from the depths of
intergalactic space.
</P>
<P>
   ELSEWHERE IN THE SKY ------
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Jupiter and Saturn rise early enough in October
to be observed in the east by late evening, but best views are
still during the wee hours of the morning. The planets, high
overhead before sunrise, form a distinctive triangle with the
bright star Aldebaran.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mars rises a couple of hours before the sun, it is so dim
it's not easily seen.
</P>
<P>
   After sunset on Oct. 29, take a look at the crescent moon, just
to the right of Venus, in the western sky. By next evening the moon
has slipped to the left of Venus.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Stanley's Skywatch column once a month on The Arizona
Republic. He can be reached at john.stanley(a)arizonarepublic.com
or (602) 444-4414.
</P>
</TEXT>
