<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      09-26 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE--AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S ``NEW &AMP; NOTABLE'' BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' AND ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``CHERRY''
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Karr
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not very successful as a little girl,'' Karr wrote in her
diary when she was 11. ``When I grow up, I will probably be a
mess.'' But look at the stories she has to tell. This sequel to her
acclaimed 1995 memoir, (beginitalic)The Liars' Club(enditalic),
takes her from a scrappy adolescent to a bored and rebellious
teenager about to leave for California with a truck full of boys,
her ticket out of the dreary Texas refinery town that had held her
captive for so long. Though she tries to make us think otherwise,
Karr's life in this book has an air of stability. Both parents are
finally under one roof for good (Karr's mother was married seven
times, twice to Mary's father), and her adolescent longings are not
so different from those of a thousand other girls. But if it's less
harrowing than (beginitalic)The Liars' Club(enditalic), its appeal
is the same: Karr is a born storyteller. Mary's voice is funny,
irreverent, profane, defiant and irresistible. And just think.
She's in her 40s. There might be more memoirs to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I LOVE YOU RONNIE''
</P>
<P>
   By Nancy Reagan
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   He called her things like ``Nancy Pants'' and ``Nancy Poo'' and
``First Mommie'' in his letters, and they are so guileless and
unabashedly adoring that it seems almost voyeuristic to read them.
Over the years she kept them in a shopping bag, of all things, and
when Alzheimer's disease began to destroy his memory and his
ability to write anything at all, she took the letters out and
found solace in them. Now Nancy Reagan has written a biography of
her marriage and sprinkled it with her husband's letters. Many are
reproduced as he wrote them, some on White House stationary. The
book ends with a photograph of the couple on his birthday in
February, and with her thoughts on seeing her husband through this
last, difficult chapter of his life. Alzheimer's is truly a long
goodbye, she writes, ``but it's the living out of love.'' Royalties
will go to the Alzheimer's Foundation and to the Ronald Reagan
Library and Museum. To read a letter from the book, log on to azcen
tral.com/rep/books.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE NEW YORKER BOOK OF LITERARY CARTOONS''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Bob Mankoff
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a title yet, or even a subject,'' a young man
tells his publisher. ``All I have is the price: twenty-three
ninety-five in hardcover.'' An agent gives his happy client the
news that ``Oprah is definite, Barnes and Noble is giving you front
windows, and Norman Mailer has agreed to a feud.'' A wife reminds
her husband that ``you may very well be from Mars, but the children
and I are from Westchester.'' And Charles Dickens squirms as an
editor waves the first page of his manuscript and says, ``I wish
you would make up your mind, Mr. Dickens. Was it the best of times
or was it the worst of times? It could scarcely have been both.''
We are cursed with the task of describing this book without benefit
of the drawings, so we'll cut to the chase: It's great fun. Our
favorite is the ``To Do'' list on James Joyce's refrigerator: 1.
Call bank. 2. Dry cleaner. 3. Forge in the smithy of my soul the
uncreated conscience of my race. 4. Call mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``KANGAROO DREAMING''
</P>
<P>
   By Edward Kanze
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra Club, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This was their plan: They would have no plan. Inspired by the
writings of Ralph Waldo Emerson (''The health of the eye seems to
demand a horizon.'') to dump their dreary office jobs and travel
unfettered, and drawn to Australia by Kanze's recurrent dream about
kangaroos, they pulled up stakes and followed their noses. Kanze
and his wife were naturalists. Setting out to make the acquaintance
of Australia's wildlife, they met up with monitor lizards, snakes,
crocodiles and quicksand, as well as some friendlier natural
wonders. They spent nine months driving around the country. That's
a lot of Australia for readers to absorb, but our appetite for it
is big right now. And Kanze? He overplays his role as a latter-day
Odysseus, but there's something engaging about a man who deplanes
in Melbourne and says to his wife, ``We're not in Kansas anymore.''
And what do you know, he's still dreaming about kangaroos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROTHER-FILM-REVIEW-N     09-26 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROTHER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` BROTHER ' : KEEPING CODE OF HONOR, ON 2 CONTINENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's probably fitting that Takeshi Kitano goes by the
nickname Aniki in his yakuza spectacular ``Brother'' because he
stirs up some serious anarchy on the Los Angeles crime scene.
Kitano directed, edited and wrote ``Brother'' (aniki is Japanese
for brother), and his style of close-to-the-vest brutality travels
extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because he's sharp enough to use the two settings
of the picture _ Los Angeles and Tokyo _ for their physical and
spiritual connotations. Los Angeles is wide open spaces. Tokyo is
dense and intimate, with gangsters seemingly nose to nose. (The
orchestral jazz score by Joe Hisaishi, has the roomy lilt of the
compositions by Maria Schneider; it's lovely and powerful.) And
Tokyo is where Yamamoto (Kitano) is far more demonstrative and
angry than he is when he's in America.
</P>
<P>
   The mournful Kitano, who goes by the sobriquet Beat Takeshi,
actually looks more like that nickname than ever; he's exhausted by
the burden of keeping the code of honor in the underworld on two
different continents. It's the way that screen icons age to become
more vivid versions of themselves, and Kitano's evolution has
demanded that he reduce himself even more, given that he's
channeling Clint Eastwood through Toshiro Mifune with a little bit
of Buster Keaton thrown in to keep the mix from crashing under its
own ponderous weight.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, one wonders if Kitano will even bother to open his
eyes in his next movie (though in films directed by others, he
doesn't rely chiefly on the tortured minimalism). By this time, his
right cheek jumps like Michigan J. Frog, a twitch that shows the
strain in containing his own sad implacability while mayhem goes on
about him. (He's often the cause of the mayhem.) Kitano walks with
his head down slightly; it's not a retiring gait, but rather a
guarded one that says if you're looking for trouble, you've come to
the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Aniki ends up in the United States, fleeing waves of trouble
left in his wake in Japan, where the murder of his boss has caused
a gang war. Packing up his steamer trunk of black Yohji Yamamoto
wool crepe suits and silk work shirts _ which make him look like
the world's most malevolent agent _ he transplants himself to Los
Angeles, where his half-brother Ken (Claude Maki) is a small-time
drug dealer who runs with a crew of lowlifes who seem to be even
worse at a criminal lifestyle than he is.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Aniki has raised the roof on Ken's drug business _
eliminating the competition with breathtaking cruelty _ and has
shown his younger sibling that, yes, loosely translated, ``yakuza''
means gangsta. Aniki and his new world pickup crew are dropping
some old world vengeance on any pack of criminals in their way and
setting into motion the kind of forces that will demand addressing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence in his films, Kitano is a rigid moralist,
and a karmic retribution usually takes place in most of his work.
That Zen-like attention to the cosmic scales can feel a little
monotonous and too heavily worked out _ a Post-It carved in stone.
Though this is territory that Kitano has covered before, he
underlines the differences between Japan and the United States to
make dramatic points and give his solemn toughness a context. And
at the oddest times, a noise somewhere between a chortle and giggle
escapes from his lips and a twinkle dances in his manly squint.
</P>
<P>
   He lightens up as he becomes closer to Ken and like a brother to
Ken's mates, and gets very close to Denny (Omar Epps). Their bond
becomes a source of humor, given the unusual way they met. When
Kato (Susumu Terajima) goes to Los Angeles to join Aniki, the
``family'' is complete and he takes to dressing them in Yohji
finery as well. Unfortunately, they get the kind with contrasting
lapel highlights that make them look like part of a Color Me Badd
reunion tour.
</P>
<P>
   Kitano often plays around with the theme of the only man left on
earth with a shred of integrity _ a Gary Cooper who shoots first _
and in ``Brother'' he's so distanced that he barely speaks; he has
no dialogue in the first five minutes of the film. That's probably
because much of the movie takes place in English, a language he's
obviously uncomfortable with. The American actors are left, it
seems, to improvise their own dialogue around the framework Kitano
gave them.
</P>
<P>
   This works well more often than not. The scenes between Kato and
Jay (Royale Watkins), who develop a competitive and squabbling
relationship, have a goofy warmth. The basketball scenes are
especially good, although there are other times when the actors
stand around, unsure of what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Kitano's scenes with Epps have an intriguing give-and-take, with
the exception of an extended last scene that is all too clearly _
and badly _ improvised by Epps alone. If the film had ended a
couple of scenes earlier, on a touch that's a tribute to Westerns
and showdowns, Kitano would have finished things off beautifully.
But that's a minor quibble.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: BROTHER Written, directed and edited by
Takeshi Kitano; director of photography, Katsumi Yanagijima; music
by Joe Hisaishi; produced by Masayuki Mori and Jeremy Thomas;
released by Sony Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
With: Tatyana Ali (Latifa), Lombardo Boyar (Mo), Omar Epps (Denny),
Ryo Ishibashi (Ishihara), Masaya Kato (Shirase), Claude Maki (Ken),
Joy Nakagawa (Marina), Ren Oshsugi (Harada), James Shigeta
(Sugimoto), Beat Takeshi (Yamamoto), Susumu Terajima (Kato) and
Royale Watkins (Jay). &QL; 
Running time: 107 minutes. This film is not rated.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
