<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 27, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   An exceptionally dry weather pattern will develop across most of
the nation for the next few days. High pressure moving southeast
from central Canada will keep most of the East unusually cool, with
areas of early morning frost. Meanwhile, a warming trend will occur
in much of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer air will temporarily reach the Northeast Wednesday as
sunshine and breezes from the southwest prevail ahead of a cold
front. The front will produce clouds and a few light showers from
extreme northern New England to the eastern Great Lakes Wednesday
afternoon. Cooler air will spread over the Northeast Wednesday
night in the wake of the front.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be plentiful over a large area from the West
through the Plains to the Southeast. Clouds and a few showers will
occur in the mountains of Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FIRST FROST
</P>
<P>
   During the next few mornings, the first frosts of the fall
season will occur in many areas of the upper Middle West and
Northeast. However, local effects will make some spots more prone
to freezing temperatures than others. Large bodies of water, which
act as reservoirs of warmth, protect nearby locations from chill.
Heat generated by human activities in cities helps stave off early
frost. In some metropolitan areas, the first frost in the suburbs
is up to 30 days earlier than in the city. Also, on calm nights in
rolling terrain, the cold, dense air drains toward the low spots
keeping nearby ridge tops warmer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
