<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST IN SHOW': DOG OWNER EAT DOG OWNER KIND OF WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you thought yuppie arrogance and entitlement had been
satirized to death, you haven't met Hamilton and Meg Swan (Michael
Hitchcock and Parker Posey), the hysterically doting dog owners who
have the funniest scenes in Christopher Guest's dog-show
mockumentary, ``Best in Show.'' When we first meet these monsters,
both lawyers from Illinois who cooingly recall first locking eyes
from behind the windows of adjacent Starbucks coffee shops, they
are in the middle of a tense therapy session.
</P>
<P>
   After they complain to the therapist that their child's jealousy
has ruined their sex life, the camera pulls away to reveal the
offending brat, none other than their moody, overprivileged pooch,
Beatrice, a pure-bred Weimaraner. Sprawled languorously on a couch,
wearing an expression of utter disdain, Beatrice momentarily turns
her head toward the camera, then looks away in abject disgust.
</P>
<P>
   As we quickly discover, the Swans are the sort of pet owners who
throw tantrums and threaten lawsuits in airports when someone
stoops to pet their precious but extremely hostile animal. They
also scream at the help in stores that don't happen to carry exact
replicas of their little darling's favorite squeaky toy. And when
these rage-oholics have no one left to terrorize, they savagely
turn on each other. Before the movie is over, Beatrice aggressively
asserts her independence at the Mayflower Kennel Club Dog Show, the
canine pageant that draws the film's major characters and their
prized pets to Philadelphia. It is a most satisfying comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best in Show'' reunites many of the same brilliant comic
actors who appeared in Guest's last movie, the cult comedy classic
``Waiting for Guffman.'' In its hip, condescending way, the new
movie is every bit as funny as the earlier film, which painted an
amusing but patronizing portrait of a Missouri town staging a tacky
historical pageant with Broadway pretensions. As before, the actors
improvising from a bare-bones screenplay (by Guest and Eugene Levy)
riff off one another like jazz musicians to create what may be the
cleverest on-the-spot caricatures since the heyday of Mike Nichols
and Elaine May.
</P>
<P>
   The Swans are nearly matched in nasty hilarity by Gerry and
Cookie Fleck (Levy and Catherine O'Hara), a milquetoasty men's wear
salesman who was literally born with two left feet, and his
hotblooded wife, a woman with a checkered past. At every turn, the
Flecks keep running into Cookie's ex-lovers, none of whom she
recalls but who to Gerry's excruciating chagrin remember her all
too well and excitedly begin recalling their encounters in clinical
detail. Arriving in Philadelphia with their Norwich terrier Winky,
Gerry and Cookie, who have driven all the way from Fern City, Fla.,
discover at the hotel desk that their credit cards are invalid and
are ceremoniously ushered to a utility closet.
</P>
<P>
   From New York City come Scott Donlan (John Michael Higgins), a
flouncing gay dog breeder with a sartorial weakness for ruffles,
and his more sedate older partner, Stefan Vanderhoof (Michael
McKean), with their prized Shih Tzu, Agnes (after Agnes Moorhead).
Next, in descending order of humor, are Leslie Ward Cabot (Patrick
Cranshaw), a doddering-unto-death millionaire and his buxom trophy
wife (Sherri Ann Cabot), and Christy Cummings (Jane Lynch), the
upwardly mobile lesbian trainer of the May-December couple's
standard poodle, Rhapsody in White.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we have Harlan Pepper (Guest), the owner of a
fly-fishing shop in Pine Nut, N.C., and his beloved bloodhound,
Hubert. Harlan is an aspiring ventriloquist who, when not
practicing with a dummy, gets into the heads of his dogs and starts
talking for them. The role is a huge and successful stretch for
Guest, whose last screen character, Corky St. Clair, a gushy,
petulant small-town theater director (and exile from Off Off
Broadway) supplied ``Waiting for Guffman's'' biggest laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Guest's brand of comedy has been called ``deadpan,'' it
was only the first of his three movies, the rock spoof ``This Is
Spinal Tap,'' that kept its tongue firmly in its cheek. ``Best in
Show,'' like ``Waiting for Guffman,'' is a subtly smirking gallery
of caricatures, most of whom don't seem to belong to a particular
region or class.
</P>
<P>
   The humor of Guest and his cast emanates from the
post-collegiate baby boomer belief in an elite ``hipoisie'' who,
unlike everyone else, know what's cool and what's not. And dog show
habitues, small-town Midwestern chamber of commerce boosters and
even successful second-level rock groups are definitely not cool.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's weaknesses are inextricable from its form. For
``Best in Show'' is essentially a well-organized, exquisitely
nuanced skit comedy, ``Saturday Night Live''-style sketches loosely
stitched together and refined to the Nth degree. Although the movie
pretends to have narrative structure, it doesn't really go much of
anywhere. It is futile to look for deeper patterns in this kind of
storytelling. The whole point is to savor the moments. This comic
jigsaw puzzle is crammed with deliriously funny little bits.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite joke is the running commentary by two antagonistic
television announcers, a reserved, erudite Englishman named Trevor
Beckwith (Jim Piddock) who is well versed in dog show protocol and
his loutish know-nothing partner, Buck Laughlin (Fred Willard), who
finds a smutty innuendo in every dog-show maneuver. Buck reaches a
height of flailing yahooism in a garbled monologue that imagines
the Mayflower piloted by Christopher Columbus landing at Plymouth
Rock in 1492. Or something like that. When ``Best in Show'' focuses
on a character like Buck, its aim is deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Best in Show'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). The screenplay is loaded with off-color humor and
sexual innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BEST IN SHOW'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Christopher Guest; written by Guest and Eugene Levy;
director of photography, Roberto Schaefer; edited by Robert
Leighton; production designer, Joseph T. Garrity; produced by Karen
Murphy; released by Castle Rock Entertainment/Warner Brothers.
Running time: 89 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Christopher Guest (Harlan Pepper), Parker Posey (Meg
Swan), Michael Hitchcock (Hamilton Swan), Eugene Levy (Gerry
Fleck), Catherine O'Hara (Cookie Fleck), John Michael Higgins
(Scott Donlan), Michael McKean (Stefan Vanderhoof), Patrick
Cranshaw (Leslie Ward Cabot), Jennifer Coolidge (Sherri Ann Cabot),
Jane Lynch (Christy Cummings), Bob Balaban (Dr. Theodore W.
Millbank 3rd), Don Lake (Graham Chissolm), Jim Piddock (Trevor
Beckwith) and Fred Willard (Buck Laughlin).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
