A2483 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ACCUSED-SPY-HNS &LR;      09-26 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCUSED-SPY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ACCUSED NAVY SPY TO GET GRAND JURY HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Ohio)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Navy sailor, accused of giving the Russians
secrets about the U.S. submarine fleet, is scheduled to go before a
judge Wednesday for the first time since his arrest nearly a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer 1st Class Daniel King, an intelligence analyst who
is being held in the U.S. Marine Corps brig at Quantico, Va., faces
one count of espionage and two counts of improperly disclosing
classified information. He could receive the death penalty if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's proceeding is called an ``Article 32'' hearing,
which is the equivalent of a grand jury in the civilian system.
Navy Cmdr. Roxie Merritt described the session as ``a pre-trial
hearing.'' Essentially, the court will determine whether the
evidence against King is strong enough to proceed to a trial. The
proceeding could last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   King worked as a cryptography, or code, expert at the National
Security Agency at Fort Meade, Md. Investigators believe that King
gave the Russians a computer disk containing U.S. submarine data in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-year Navy veteran and a native of Elyria, Ohio, King was
arrested in the Washington, D.C., area by the Naval Criminal
Investigative Service last Oct. 28 and accused of espionage a week
later. He has been held in the Quantico brig ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have said that King, 40, confessed to
espionage after failing a lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   King's lawyers counter that he is innocent and that during his
interrogation, King referred to the confessions as ``dreams'' and
``fantasies.'' His lawyers also accuse the Navy of ``outrageous
misconduct'' by interrogating King for unusually long sessions of
19 hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   King only now is going before a judge because of a controversy
over how the Navy has handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Vice Adm. Joseph S. Mobley, commander of the U.S.
Atlantic Fleet's Naval Air Force, issued a highly unusual
protective order barring all contact between the defendant and his
lawyers unless a Navy security officer was present at the meetings.
The Navy said some of King's attorneys lacked high-security
clearance called ``special access,'' reserved for some of the
nation's most guarded secrets, higher than ``top secret.''
</P>
<P>
   King's lawyers objected, asserting that the order violated
attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Military Justice, a private
organization that monitors military courts, agreed that the
security officer ``seemingly shatters the concept of
confidentiality and the attorney-client relationship along with it.
In our corporate experience and research, such an order is
completely without precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the National Association of Criminal Lawyers said
that the protective order ``raises grave and fundamental
constitutional concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is counsel to prepare for cross-examination, to know what
defense witnesses and evidence is available if they cannot
communicate with the accused with a certainty of privilege,'' the
group asked. The Navy has ``functionally barred the effective
assistance of counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   King's civilian defense lawyer, Jonathan Turley, a George
Washington University law professor, appealed to the military's
highest court, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces, to
strike the protective order and won. But the order had the effect
of preventing King from meeting with his lawyers for nearly six
months, from March to August.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Turley's office said that King ``has now been
held for a period longer than the scientist Wen Ho Lee,'' the
Energy Department scientist accused of spying for China. Lee, who
was incarcerated for nine months though never tried, faced 59
felony charges accusing him of downloading nuclear secrets from
Energy Department computers. Lee was freed Sept. 13 after pleading
guilty to one felony count of mishandling weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``King, unlike Lee, however, has never been formally charged or
given an opportunity to appear before a trial judge to secure his
release,'' Turley's statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
