<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Chicken thieves outfox sheriff
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Dale Denney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Special to Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chicken thieves had hit again in our small community in the
middle of Oklahoma in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   And they left this poem:
</P>
<P>
   ``We steal from the rich, we steal from the poor. We leave you a
hen and rooster, to raise some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knew it was the Montrose brothers doing it, Elzie and
Alfred. Elzie was tall and skinny; Alfred, short and fat. Both were
red-headed.
</P>
<P>
   They always seemed to have money, keeping themselves supplied
with expensive Beech Nut chewing tobacco and paying cash for it.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were they chinchy about sharing. They generously passed the
package along to anybody who might be standing around.
</P>
<P>
   Most everybody liked Elzie and Alfred. Their daddy was a poor
sharecropper who housed his large family in a small, two-room
clapboard shack.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while Elzie and Alfred would actually work, helping
their daddy on the farm, but mostly they slept late.
</P>
<P>
   At first people thought the poems were a good joke, but times
were hard and chickens were chickens _ meat for the table, eggs for
cooking and feathers for mattress ticking.
</P>
<P>
   The county sheriff was determined to catch Elzie and Alfred,
preferably in the act.
</P>
<P>
   He appointed a committee of the more prosperous farmers and made
a map of the area. Then they put the date the chickens were stolen
on all the hen houses.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, they came up with a pattern, and it was decided that the
Williams place would be the next chicken house hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll teach them a thing or two about stealing chickens'' the
sheriff declared. ``I'll fix me a bed in the chicken house and have
my loaded shotgun handy. A good dose of bird shot in their behinds
will put an end to their chicken stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff took the rear seat out of his car and hauled it to
the chicken house to use as a bed.
</P>
<P>
   But it was such a good bed that he went to sleep and didn't wake
up until sunrise when the old red rooster was crowing in his ear.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff sat bolt upright and grabbed for his gun. But the
gun was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Pinned to his vest was a piece of paper with writing on it. He
ripped it off and read what it said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We steal from the rich, we steal from the poor. We came for
the chickens, but your shotgun is worth more.''
</P>
<P>
   And since it was worth more, it was almost a year before folks
lost anymore chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people thought swapping a county shotgun for a year
free of chicken thieves was a pretty darn good trade.
</P>
<P>
   (Dale Denney is a retired weekly newspaper editor who lives in
Jay, Okla.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
