u s BC-OLY-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     09-26 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BASEBALLERS HEAD FOR GOLD-MEDAL GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ USA Baseball waited eight years for this opportunity.
Waiting a few more hours was no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   The rag-tag American baseball team will finally get to play a
gold-medal game against the Cubans Wednesday night. After eight
years of disappointment and frustration, the Yanks are where they
want to be _ playing one game for world supremacy against the Sons
of Fidel who act as if they invented our national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba won its medal-round game, beating Japan, 3-0, Tuesday
afternoon. The Americans played Korea in the nightcap and _ after
waiting through a two-hour rain delay _ won it, 3-2, on a
post-midnight, ninth-inning, walk-off homer by first baseman Doug
Mientkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week earlier, Mientkiewicz hit an eighth-inning grand
slam to beat Korea. He called that the biggest homer of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me if I had one more in me,'' said Mientkiewicz,
who played with the Minnesota Twins in 1999. ``I can't take much
more of this. But my country is playing for a gold medal now.''
</P>
<P>
   American manager Tommy Lasorda was his usual buoyant self. At
the postgame press conference early Wednesday, he unveiled a
patriotic stuffed creature that resembled an Uncle Sam snowman.
When Lasorda activated the toy, it played ``Stars and Stripes
Forever,'' and announced, ``America. Home of the free and the
brave. USA. No. 1!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it in the dugout all night,'' said the Hall of Fame
skipper. ``And we'll have it in the dugout tomorrow night. We know
we're the underdog. We're just a bunch of youngsters with not much
experience. But we're hoping just maybe we can turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Korea assures the Yanks of at least a silver medal, but
it didn't come easily. After two weeks of perfect weather, Sydney's
spring roared back early this week and it was raining lightly when
the ubiquitous Dawn Fraser threw out the first ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans again had problems solving Korean submarineballer,
Chong Tae-hyon. Our lads looked like the Baltimore Orioles trying
to hit Kent Tekulve in the 1979 World Series. In the first week of
competition, Chong pitched seven shutout innings against the
Americans, only to watch Mientkiewicz's granny against Korean
reliever Park Seok-Jin in the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Chong was on his game again Tuesday. He held the Yanks hitless
in the first three innings and was staked to a 2-0 lead in the
third when American starter Roy Oswalt gave up a walk, a pair of
doubles, and a sac fly. Chong warmed up in front of his team's
dugout during the long inning.
</P>
<P>
   The US struck back in the bottom of the fourth when center
fielder Brad Wilkerson led with a double to right and scored on a
double to center by John Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Franklin came on to pitch the seventh for the Americans and
he teamed with Todd Williams to shut down Korea the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The US chased Chong and tied the game, 2-2, in the bottom of the
seventh. Mike Kinkade reached on a bunt single (questionable call
at first), moved to third on a single to right by Mientkiewicz, and
scored on a sac fly by Marcus Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   Them came the weird stuff. In the bottom of the eighth, American
second baseman Brent Abernathy led with a double down the
left-field line. He went to third on a ground out. At this point,
thunder rocked the stadium. With the count, 2-1, on Mike Neill and
lightning flashing all around, Cuban home-plate umpire Cesar Valdes
pulled the teams off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, they had a tarp. It got especially raw and windy
during the delay, but Olympic baseball officials insisted the game
would be resumed. After the delay (Kitty Litter was spread around
the infield), Neill returned to the plate and was intentionally
walked (the Koreans had a lot of time to think about the move).
Then Ernie Young was hit by a pitch to load the bases and Cotton
hit a grounder to third. The Korean third baseman fired home to
erase Abernathy.
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy had other ideas. Already out, he delivered a crackback
block to the Korean catcher. It was a cheap shot and the ump
immediately called a double play. Lasorda argued. Not Tommy's
finest moment.
</P>
<P>
   On to the ninth. Kinkade led and was hit by a pitch. Travis
Dawkins pinch ran and was picked off while Mientkiewicz was
batting. It appeared the US would do anything to avoid scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mientkiewicz struck.
</P>
<P>
   And so Lasorda and his boys get their wish. It could be the
fullfillment of an American dream that began in 1992 when baseball
was first played as a medal sport in the Olympics. The '92 US team,
which included Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek, lost to Cuba
but advanced to the bronze-medal game and lost to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   We lost to Cuba again in Atlanta in '96, but won a bronze,
beating Nicaragua in the consolation medal game. Cuba, meanwhile,
went 9-0 in both Olympiads and came to Australia intent on winning
gold again.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans were beaten by the Netherlands, 4-2, in the first
round of the 2000 games, but have been otherwise perfect. They
crushed Lasorda's men, 6-1, in a combustible joust that featured
one bench-clearing episode and several other contentious incidents.
Americans accused the Cubans of playing dirty. US cleanup hitter
Young is still smarting from a Jose Ibar pitch that nailed him on
the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban manager Servio Borges announced he'll start Norge Luis
Vera (don't count on it). Ben Sheets, a 22-year-old righty from the
Brewers system, gets the ball for the US. There've been no
sightings of Fidel Castro in Sydney. The Cubans are 25-3 lifetime
against America in international competition, 25-1 overall in three
Olympiads.
</P>
<P>
   Mientkiewicz said, ``If we play them the way we played Australia
and let it hang out a little, we'll give them a better game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
