<HEADLINE>
LINDLAND'S OLYMPIC SAGA ENDS EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ On first viewing the man, there is but one thought in
your head.
</P>
<P>
   John Malkovich wrestles? It is astonishing. It
(itals)is(unitals) John Malkovich, albeit with two spectacular
cauliflower ears.
</P>
<P>
   But this much we know: If and when a movie entitled ``Being Matt
Lindland'' ever appears on the big screen, it's unlikely that
anyone from the USOC will be queuing up for a ticket. For them,
Matt Lindland represents mounds of paper, innumerable phone calls,
and lawyers' fees.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland's Olympic saga ended Tuesday evening, with the man who
litigated his way to Sydney and then wrestled his way to the
championship match falling short of the ultimate goal. Mourat
Kardanov of Russia defeated Lindland by a 3-0 score to take home
the gold in the 76 kg (167 1/2 lb.) division of Greco-Roman
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in second to a Russian,'' Lindland said. ``That's not a
bad place in the Olympic Games. But it's not what I wanted. I
wanted to be first.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the aggravation he has caused the USOC in the past few
months, no one in authority is about to refuse the medal. We are
talking Greco-Roman wrestling, after all, and medals for the US in
this sport do not fall from the sky too often. Top 10 finishes are
rare enough, let alone medals. We're still looking for our first
non-boycott Olympic gold, and so if any of our lads can provide the
squad with something as prestigious as a silver medal, that's
breaking-out-the-bubbly time in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland certainly made news this summer. It all began when he
lost to Keith Sieracki in the 76 kg Olympic trials finals. But for
Mr. L., it was definitely not over. Arguing that Sieracki had
benefitted from an illegal leg lift (in this branch of wrestling,
there are no holds allowed below the legs and the legs themselves
cannot be used for anything other than support and balance),
Lindland protested. The fun was just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The battle raged on, right up to the time the American squad
embarked for Sydney in early September. Sieracki kept prevailing
via the official USOC internal arbitration system. Lindland kept
winning via the American judicial system. It actually went all the
way to Supreme Court Justice John Paul Stevens, who declined to
hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of it all there was a curious arbitration-mandated
re-match in Colorado Springs, which an unhappy Sieracki
participated in under his own protest and against his better
judgment. Lindland won this one, 8-0, and in his mind that should
have settled everything, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   It was so ridiculous that the wrestling team was forced to take
two official team photos, one with Sieracki and one with Mal . . .
er . . . Lindland.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, there are Sieracki guys and Lindland guys. There are
people who think Lindland was right to protest and those who think
Sieracki won, fair and square. It just turned out to be a tedious,
boring, and damn near interminable process. Suffice it to say that
the summer of 2000 will not be fondly recalled by either the USOC
or USA Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Lindland has remained outwardly unflappable
throughout the whole thing. He appears to be almost righteous in
his belief that all he did was rectify a clear wrong by utilizing a
process available to anyone. If anyone makes him out to be a bad
guy, and he can't possibly understand why, that's too bad. To his
way of thinking, the silver medal is proof that justice has
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry I had to get on the team that way, and that things
went the way they did,'' he shrugged, ``but I think the best guy
got on the team, and that's that. I got here because I was a better
wrestler than Keith was. I beat him in the re-match. It was 8-0 and
that's hard to get. So what people think won't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he'd like to say to Sieracki, he seemed almost
bewildered anyone would be interested. ``To Keith?'' he inquired.
``I'd just say good luck to you, and God bless you. I don't know
what else to say to him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, quite clearly, a hard guy, and one quite capable of
focusing on the task at hand. He refused to allow the summer's
proceedings to interfere with his training, and it was obvious to
everyone he was very well prepared by the way he wrestled his way
to that gold-medal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As for the gold-medal match, he quickly fell behind, 3-0, when
he was turned in the first period, and when he couldn't capitalize
on his one good scoring opportunity in the second three-minute
period, he was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was who got on top early,'' he explained. ``You want
to do it early if you can, because it's much slipperier in the
second period. But I knew he'd be tough. I hadn't wrestled him
before, but the Russians are always tough. Every time you wrestle a
Russian, it's a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that his teammates held nothing against him and
understood that he was only trying to seek justice. ``We're a close
team,'' he declared. ``The Greco-Roman community is very close in
the US. Actually, worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   But it must be reported that there were more than a few rolled
eyes in USOC circles this past week or so whenever the name of Matt
``The Litigator'' was brought up. They're accepting the medal while
holding their nose.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? He's not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' he said. ``I'll be
talking it over with my wife. But I enjoy it, and I don't see why I
wouldn't want to continue. I'm not old. I'm not hurt. So why not?''
</P>
<P>
   So there it is, USOC. You've still got Matt Lindland, which
means your dangerous liaison will continue to keep you in the line
of fire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
