<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOS-NEW-ACCESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 PHOTOGRAPHY CENTERS JOIN TO FORM A VAST COLLECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two major photography institutions _ the George
Eastman House in Rochester and the International Center of
Photography in New York City _ have entered an alliance that will
give New Yorkers more access to one of the world's greatest
collections of photographs and motion pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``One organization has the advantage of location,'' said Willis
Hartshorn, director of the International Center of Photography,
which has galleries in New York and runs the city's largest
photography school. ``The other has the advantage of an
extraordinary collection. In terms of the public, the benefit is
mostly access.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald H. Fielding, board chairman at the George Eastman House,
said that the alliance, which is not a merger, would result in a
series of operations _ from joint cataloging to a Web site _ to
benefit both institutions and the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The educational programs are very complementary,'' Fielding
said. ``The ICP is very strong in degree programs for photographic
creation, whereas the strong point at Eastman House is preservation
and conservation.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 5 million objects related to photography and film
in its 50-year-old collection, the Eastman museum owns 400,000
photographs by 8,000 photographers going back to the art form's
earliest years. Its collection of 25,000 motion pictures is a rival
to that of the Cinematheque in Paris and its library of
photographic books and journals is one of the world's most
encyclopedic.
</P>
<P>
   The International Center of Photography's collection
concentrates on the 1950s through the '70s, with special emphasis
on photojournalism. There will be a regular exchange of
exhibitions. The first program in an eight-part series called ``New
Histories of Photography'' is to open on Nov. 3 at the center's
expanded gallery space at 1133 Avenue of the Americas, at West 43rd
Street (reopening on Nov. 3 after renovations). The show, called
``Daguerreotypmania!,'' will feature rare artifacts connected with
the early years of photography.
</P>
<P>
   A show of photographs by Alfred Stieglitz donated to the Eastman
House by Georgia O'Keeffe and now on tour in Cologne, Germany, will
also come to the ICP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a purpose of a nonprofit museum is to make its
collection available to the public,'' Fielding said. ``The Web does
that, but in terms of physical access, New York has a zillion more
people visiting museums as well as more funding resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is one of the top tourist attractions in Rochester,
the Eastman museum, named after the founder of the Eastman Kodak
Co., who produced the first mass market amateur camera, has been
stretched thin financially as it struggled to maintain its
collection. After a proposal to transfer the collection to the
Smithsonian Institution in Washington was quashed by local
protests, an endowment drive began that collected $35 million,
helping to build a modern archive building next to the original
George Eastman mansion.
</P>
<P>
   By teaming up with the ICP, the Eastman museum seeks to
strengthen its fund-raising, exchange information and staff, and
expand the opportunity for research. Filing jointly for their first
shared grant, the two institutions have already received $120,000
from the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   For the center's 5,000 students, most of them enrolled in
continuing education classes, the arrangement will provide a wealth
of material for research.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, to be running next spring, will include 10,000
images from the museums' collections as well as material on the
history of photography.
</P>
</TEXT>
