<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-ED27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARENTS WANT MORE SEX EDUCATION IN SCHOOLS, SURVEY FINDS
 &HT;    By KAVITA KUMAR
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Parents want public schools to offer more
information on sex education topics such as birth control,
abortion, rape, and sexual orientation, the Kaiser Family
Foundation reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group's survey revealed a seeming contradiction: While most
parents want their children to abstain from sex, they also want
them to be taught about birth control and safer sex.
</P>
<P>
   Even among the one-third of parents who said they wanted their
school's main message to be abstinence until marriage, most said
educators should teach about how to get tested for HIV/AIDS and
other sexually transmitted diseases (STD), how to use condoms, and
where to get and how to use other birth control.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comes from this study is that parents looks to schools to
prepare their children for real life,'' said Tina Hoff, director of
the Foundation's public education program. ``Their concerns are
practical, not political.''
</P>
<P>
   Of students surveyed, small majorities said they want to learn
more about what to do in cases of rape or assault or how to get
tested for STDs, and 46 percent said they want more information on
how to discuss birth control and STDs with a partner.
</P>
<P>
   In a panel discussion that followed release of the report,
Michael Nesbitt, an 11th-grade student in the nation's capital,
said there's no alternative to talking about safe sex and birth
control in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they said the average age of marriage is 25 or 28,''
Michael said. ``That's a long time, and it's not realistic for many
to wait that long'' to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's mother, Deborah, said she would welcome a
comprehensive sexual education program for her three sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most information they can get could not be any
harm to them,'' she said. ``I'd rather they learn it in a school
environment and from what I enforce at home rather than other
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   But some, like Liz Alston, chair of the Charleston County (S.C.)
School District's board of trustees, said it is hard to reconcile
parents' desire to protect their children and their willingness for
schools to teach more about sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents want their cake and to eat it too. They want it both
ways.'' said Alston, who is a proponent of abstinence-only sexual
education. ``You can't talk about things like sexual orientation
(in the classroom), because then people will start questioning
their identity.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic models of sexual education used in the
United States: ``abstinence-only'' and ``comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   In abstinence-only curricula, the message is that students
should wait until they are married to have sex. Comprehensive
programs, which are more prevalent, follow the philosophy that
young people should wait to have sex, but if they don't, they
should use birth control and practice safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows that in practice, the lines between the two
types of sex education blur in the classroom. Abstinence-only
classes often discuss birth control, while comprehensive programs
usually stress abstinence and address pressures to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Soule is a teacher in Silver Spring, Md., for 15 years,
said that three of the 18 weeks in her 10th-grade health class are
spent dealing with sexual education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buck stops here,'' Soule said. ``This is 10th grade, and
this is the only place students are going to get this information.
It might be the last time they get it in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   While Soule stresses abstinence in her class, she says she's
wary of dictating a norm to her students, many of whom have parents
who are not married. And while she has a comprehensive program, she
can't introduce the topics of abortion or sexual orientation
because of local school policies. But she can answer questions
about those issues if students raise them, and they inevitably do,
Soule said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser foundation, an independent health care organization
based in California, surveyed more than 4,000 students, parents,
teachers and principals in public schools, grades 7 through 12,
about the status and needs of current sexual education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Fieldwork for the report, titled ``Sex Education in America: A
View from Inside the Nation's Classrooms,'' was completed between
February and May, 1999. Responses to questions in the survey have a
margin of error of three to six percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita Kumar's e-mail address is kkumar(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
