<P>
   OLY-SOCCW-ADV _ The United States women's soccer team arrived
here after weeks of training and playing at satellite venues and
will face Norway Thursday in the gold medal match. It would be hard
to find more evenly matched, or familiar, rivals at these Olympics
in any sport. The U.S. squad, the reigning Olympic and World Cup
champions, began this tournament by beating Norway 2-0 even before
the Olympic torch was lit. ``After we played them I knew we would
see them again,'' said U.S. star Mia Hamm, now an Austin resident.
(Maher, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BEACH _ SYDNEY _ Coverage of beach volleyball, with American
men in the final. (Tierney, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WRESTLE _ SYDNEY _ Coverage of Matt Lindland, U.S. wrestler
who had to go to court to get in the Games. Now he's in gold medal
match. (Tierney, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WRESTLER _ SYDNEY _ From Amarillo to Australia. It's not a
common journey, and for a wrestler it's almost an impossible one.
But Brandon Slay is here at the Olympics. Born and bred in a state
where wrestling meant rasslin' and the Von Erichs, he's the only
native Texan on the United States wrestling team. He may well be
the only U.S. Olympic wrestler ever brought up in the Lone Star
state, where until recently real wrestling was a pariah. (Maher,
Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BASE _ SYDNEY _ Coverage of U.S. baseball team in
semifinals. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   OLYSOFT _ BLACKTOWN, New South Wales _ Coverage of U.S. softball
team in gold medal game. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOFT-GEORGE 27 _ BLACKTOWN, New South Wales _ There is
crying in softball. Tuesday night's Olympic gold medal game, won by
the U.S. on a dropped fly ball in extra innings, started a flood
for both teams. For the American women, who lost their air of
invincibility in this tournament but not their prize, and for the
Japanese, who won every game but this one, this was as wrenching as
any World Series, as dramatic as any trumped-up movie scene. ``I
fought for this country the best way I can and that is on the
softball field,'' said Lisa Fernandez, who clouded up during
interviews last week when the U.S. was in the midst of a shocking
three-game losing streak and did it again Tuesday when the
four-year mission to repeat as Olympic champions had reached it
successful conclusion. (George, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
