   SEX-ED _ WASHINGTON _ The Kaiser Family Foundation releases a
study showing broad support for sex education in public schools.
(Kumar, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Education.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-COST _ WASHINGTON _ None of the proposals by
presidential candidates or others for reforming Medicare will fully
solve its long-range financial problems, meaning taxpayers will
have to pay more for future benefits, a bipartisan panel of experts
reported Tuesday. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Social
Issues.
</P>
<P>
   PROVISIONAL _ Plans to scrap the provisional admission program
at UT-Austin have raised questions over why the University of Texas
can't say no when it comes to Longhorn wannabes. While colleges
across the country have eliminated their second chance admissions,
UT is likely the last holdout. Some say it's the longheld Texas
belief that graduating from UT is every Texan's right. Others say
it's time UT is realistic about getting a hold on its numbers. The
proposal has sparked lots of debate just as UT System regents are
to consider the plan this month. (Jayson, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-PENSIONS _ WASHINGTON _ You'll be able to put a lot more
money into your tax-protected IRA or 401(k) retirement savings
account, if the Senate can get its act together in the next two
weeks. Twice, the House has voted overwhelmingly for the bipartisan
pension reform/tax-cut plan assembled over three years by Reps. Rob
Portman, R-Ohio and Ben Cardin, D-Md. The Clinton administration
would like to see some fine-tuning. But the basic problem is that
the Senate GOP leadership can't find time to consider the bill,
even though it could help many millions of rich and middle-class
Americans, while hurting only a few million working-class
employees. (Mollison, Cox News Service). With Textbox.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS _The Baptist General Convention of Texas's executive
committee is expected to vote around 3:30 p.m. Tuesday on whether
to send a proposal to defund Southern Baptist Convention
seminaries, including Southwestern, to BGCT messengers at the
BGCT's big meeting in Corpus Christi next month. SBC leaders say it
could be the begining of the end for the BGCT, as the rift widens.
(Perkes, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TURNER _ WASHINGTON _ CNN founder Ted Turner is honored by the
League of Conservation Voters and addresses the group. (Kumar, Cox
News Service). 14.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory
</P>
<P>
   Other.
</P>
<P>
   POLIO _ This summer, world health officials - including the CDC
- acknowledged they would not meet an oft-stated goal of ridding
the world of polio by the end of this year. Today, (Sept. 27), many
of those officials leading the fight will join Ted Turner and other
big spenders who are helping to fund the effort, in a ``polio
summit'' to explore why the fight is not being won on time. The NYC
meeting is intended to redirect attention away from the
public-health failure and focus media attention on the last push to
eradicate polio - which WHO hopes to accomplish shortly. To set up
the conference, we take a look at why 15-20 of the 30 countries
which had polio at the end of 1999 still do and ask ``What's taking
so long?'' (McKenna, The Altanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC _ The music was loud and Latino. The message was
custom-made for the crowd packed into Miami's Coconut Grove
Convention Center for a GOP rally. ``We Hispanics have become the
most important electoral block in the country,'' said George P.
Bush, the Mexican-American nephew of the Republican presidential
nominee. But barring large-scale, last-minute population shifts,
George P. is overstating the case in the current presidential race.
(Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POVERTY _ WASHINGTON _ WASHINGTON _ Americans enjoyed
substantial income gains for a record fifth consecutive year in
1999, with inflation-adjusted earnings rising to $40,816 for a
typical family, its highest level since income data were first
recorded in 1967, the Census Bureau reported Tuesday. The strong
economy also drove the poverty rate to its lowest level since 1979
-- with the number of poor people falling by 2.2 million compared
to 1998. The effect of the rolling good times were felt equally by
whites, blacks, Hispanics and other ethnic groups, according to the
income and poverty data. A national story with state inserts.
(Holmes, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory U.S.
Government.
