<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2508 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-WOMEN-VOTERS-1STLD-WR     09-26 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-VOTERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABORTION RIGHTS GROUP WANTS PRO-CHOICE REPUBLICANS TO SUPPORT
GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: News grafs 8-10 with anti-abortion group's response.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A national abortion rights organization announced
Tuesday that it is launching a $5-million, 15-state campaign to
persuade pro-choice independent and Republican voters to support
Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League
(NARAL) will target two million voters who favor abortion rights.
NARAL President Kate Michelman said the organization will use
direct mail, Internet advertising and phone calls ``to mobilize the
pro-choice vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This election will be won on the ground, voter by voter,
neighborhood by neighborhood district by district from
congressional races all the way up to the presidency,'' Michelman
told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL also released its list of House candidates who the group
believes are unlikely to support abortion rights. In those
districts, NARAL will lobby for the pro-choice alternatives,
Michelman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defeating these candidates will enable us to pick up key seats
in the House, returning leadership to the hands of House members
committed to protecting a woman's right to choose,'' Michelman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee,
is at the top of the NARAL's ``worst choice list.''
</P>
<P>
   Targeted Republican or independent voters will be contacted
between four and seven times before the Nov. 7 election, Michelman
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said NARAL is targeting voters in California, Florida, Iowa,
Michigan, Missouri, Minnesota, Montana, New Hampshire, New Mexico,
Ohio, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, New York, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Michelman said NARAL has compiled its list of pro-choice
Republican or independent voters from previous get-out-the vote
drives and from records of campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-abortion advocacy group _ the SBA List Candidate Fund _
responded to the NARAL announcement by issuing a statement claiming
that ``NARAL'S success will be measured by how deceptive'' it is to
voters because most voters support a ban on late-term abortions, a
ban vehemently opposed by NARAL.
</P>
<P>
   The SBA group _ named after Susan B. Anthony, the crusader for
women's suffrage and abortion opponent _ also accused NARAL of
being ``deceptive'' in claiming that abortion rights would be
terminated if Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush wins
the election and nominates anti-abortion U.S. Supreme Court
justices.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court then reversed the Roe Vs. Wade abortion
decision, it would mean that abortion policy would once again be
the responsibility of voters in the states, ``rather than in the
hands of nine justices in Washington,'' the SBA List statement
asserted.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL joins Emily's List, another abortion rights advocacy
organization, in seeking support of undecided women voters to elect
pro-choice Democratic women to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Women hold unprecedented power as a voting bloc, said Ellen
Malcolm, president of Emily's List, a political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are going to determine the outcome of this election,''
Malcolm said. ``Women make up the vast majority of the undecided
electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   According to an Emily's List-sponsored poll earlier this month,
12 percent of registered women voters were unsure who they would
vote for president, compared to 6 percent of male voters.
</P>
<P>
   In congressional races, 24 percent of women were undecided,
compared to 17 percent of men. The survey of 1,267 voters had a
margin of error of plus or minus 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Emily's List is working to mobilize female voters likely to
support women and Democratic candidates with a $10 million
campaign. In 1998, the organization sent nearly 8 million pieces of
mail and made over two million telephone calls to 3.4 million women
in 26 states as part of its get-out-the-vote initiative. In 1998,
members of the organization contributed $7.5 million to Democratic
women candidates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Dlouhy can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address jdlouhy(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
