<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
Q2392 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-LILEKS-GORE-NNS &LR;      09-26 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-GORE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INTERESTING WEEK FOR GORE, IF YOU LIKE IT THAT WAY 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
    &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 26, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Commentary 
 &HT;     By JAMES LILEKS 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) It's been an interesting week for Al Gore _
``interesting'' in the sense that watching someone saw your legs
off is interesting, if you're sufficiently sedated. The race has
tightened, as everyone knew it would; the issues are taking second
place to vague perceptions about the candidates, as they usually
do. Some highlights from Gore's week of weakening numbers:
</P>
<P>
   1. The Union Lullaby Gaffe. Appearing before some union folks,
Gore touted his lifelong union credentials and shared a warm
recollection of hearing a union jingle as a lullaby. Unfortunately,
the jingle wasn't used until Gore was in his mid-20s. Perhaps Pappy
sang some other union jingle at baby's bedtime _ ``Kill the Bosses!
Grind Their Bones! Drink Their Blood! Burn Their Homes!'' was a
popular number in those days, but it gave children nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the video, you can almost see Gore struggling with the
anecdote, as if he has a nagging suspicion that it's actually
false. Anyone who's seen ``Blade Runner'' knows exactly what's
happening here: It's the point where he realizes he is a synthetic
being, programmed with the memories of other people. No one's tried
the Android Defense yet, but they've dragged out the usual excuses:
He was tired. He was misquoted. He was caught by surprise. He was
hopped up on goofballs. He will lie about anything, to anyone,
anywhere, to achieve and maintain power. Hah! Just kidding about
that last one. No, it was the cold medication.
</P>
<P>
   The press has a good chuckle and moves along to the job at hand:
debating whether George W. Bush is stupid, dim, congenitally daft,
or just charmingly ``tetched'' like the small-town lunatic who
lives in a shack behind the gas station and SEEMS harmless until he
strangles eight little girls.
</P>
<P>
   That's the real story, don't you know.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Mole in Bush's Camp. Gore's people have allegedly
inserted an operative into the Bush camp, and this guy is feeding
Gore inside info. Stories like this make the media nervous; where's
the Bush-Is-Stupid angle here? Ah: too stupid to catch a spy under
his own nose! Can't trust him with national security. Why, it would
have taken Bush twice as long to mishandle the Wen Ho Lee case.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Richard Nixon broke into Watergate _ that's right,
Nixon. He slipped away from a state dinner, slipped into a black
ninja outfit, slipped into the Watergate from the roof, greased
himself with oil and slid through the ventilation ducts,
chloroformed the guard, stole the Democratic secrets, lasered a
hole in the window, rappelled to freedom and ran back to the White
House in time for the second course. Tricky Dick? You don't know
the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   So ... even if Gore had a mole in Bush's camp, Nixon was first
and Nixon was worse. But even if it's true, and even if laws were
broken, isn't it time we moved beyond the politics of hate? The
politics of division? The politics of prosecuting people for laws
they've broken?
</P>
<P>
   3. Winter's coming; demand for heating oil has risen; prices
follow. To quote a variety of tenured economists: Duh. Gore regards
this as a calamity and petitions President Clinton to release a
laughably minuscule amount of oil from the strategic reserves. This
gave the nation a reminder of Gore's energy policy:
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't nobody drill for nothing nowhere ever, amen. Doesn't
matter if people freeze _ better Granny in Boston has blue lips to
match her hair than one Alaskan elk get the runs from licking
grease off an oil well.
</P>
<P>
   B. Support alternative energy. Examples of successful
replacements for gas: welllll ... none. So far. But only because we
haven't spent enough! If we spend just a few hundred billion more,
a perpetual motion machine will magically appear from the eighth
dimension. Besides, Big Oil probably has assassins that stifle any
successful new technology. That's how it is in the movies, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Training the population to think that government can micromanage
markets is short-sighted, since the people will expect government
to do it again. The price of bread goes up? Why, tap the Strategic
Bread Reserve. Anyone deluded enough to think this will work
deserves a president who holds them in such contempt _ which is why
it was heartening to see Gore lose numbers. He may think we're
stupid; he depends on it. But not everyone seems to be as stupid as
he needs them to be.
</P>
<P>
   LF END LILEKS
</P>
</TEXT>
