<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2513 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RENO-LEE-HNS &LR;      09-26 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-LEE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO AND FREEH DEFIANTLY DEFEND U.S. TREATMENT OF LEE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis
Freeh offered no apologies on Tuesday for their treatment of Wen Ho
Lee _ including holding him in solitary confinement _ and insisted
that the nuclear scientist was a ``national security risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI believed solitary confinement was needed to restrict
Dr. Lee's ability to pass information through intermediaries that
could have the consequence of disseminating the nuclear secrets he
had stolen,'' Freeh told a joint meeting of the Senate intelligence
and judiciary committees investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Lee's lawyers never complained about their
client's treatment while in jail. ``We were not aware of this being
a factor,'' Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said: ``Dr. Lee was a national security risk and needed to
be treated carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Lee was kept in manacles during exercise periods and
when being transported ``because that was the treatment of all
prisoners in the area where he was being held, and we didn't want
to have Dr. Lee treated differently from the others.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Lee, a physicist at the nuclear weapons laboratory
in Los Alamos, N.M., was indicted on 59 counts alleging the
scientist of transferring huge amounts of secret atomic research
data from the classified computer system at Los Alamos weapons lab.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this month, Lee pleaded guilty to a single felony
count of mishandling information at the laboratory. Under terms of
the plea bargain, the 58 other counts of breaching national
security Lee faced were dropped and he was sentenced to 278 days _
essentially the time he's served since his arrest last December.
Lee also agreed to tell FBI agents what he did with seven missing
computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   During Lee's sentencing hearing, the case's presiding judge,
James A. Parker, apologized to the scientist for what he said was a
questionable indictment. Parker also said the FBI ``misled'' him
about Lee's supposedly deceptive behavior and ignored his urgings
that the government ease the ``demeaning, unnecessarily punitive
conditions'' under which Lee was being held.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, several senators echoed Parker's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Penn., questioned whether the government's
treatment of Lee was an attempt to pressure the scientist into
admitting to crimes he never committed.
</P>
<P>
   `` The manacles, the false testimony given by the FBI raise a
possible inference _ and I say only possible _ that these were
pressures to compel a guilty plea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., while acknowledging that Lee broke
the law, said the scientist's treatment ``far exceeded legitimate
measures designed to prevent the possible compromise of
information, including, we are told, his shackling and a light in
his cell 24 hours a day, even shackling when he was performing his
authorized exercise each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harsh criticism, neither Freeh nor Reno refused to
back away from their handling of the case, saying Lee put the
entire world at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not careless. It was not innocent,'' said Freeh, adding
that Lee deliberately transferred nuclear weapons secrets that
``could change the global strategic balance'' to computers open to
anyone on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said: ``Dr. Lee is no hero, he is no absent-minded
professor.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general also staunchly denied charges that Lee _ a
Taiwanese-born naturalized citizen _ was a victim of racial
profiling. ``There was no effort on anybody's part to target him
because of his race,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh repeatedly insisted that the FBI could have successfully
prosecuted Lee if the case had gone to trial. ``Each of those
counts could be proven in December 1999, and each one of them could
be proven today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said that the government sought a plea bargain to settle
the case only to avoid disclosing nuclear secrets in court and to
find out what Lee did with seven tapes he made of secret material
taken from Los Alamos computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice and the FBI concluded that this
guilty plea, coupled with Lee's agreement to submit to questioning
under oath and to a polygraph, was our best opportunity to protect
the national security by finding out what happened to the seven
missing tapes, as well as to the additional copies of the tapes
that he now admitted to have made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Freeh, Lee came under investigation in 1982 and
1994 for contacts he made with foreign scientists, including
China's top nuclear scientist, but his security pass was not lifted
because he passed polygraph tests.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said that it was not until last year that FBI agents and
Los Alamos computer engineers concluded that Lee deliberately
worked from 1994 to 1999 to get around Los Alamos security systems
to transfer classified files from secure Energy Department
computers to computers open to the public and to computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least seven _ and possibly 14 or more _ tapes containing
vast amounts of our nation's nuclear secrets remain unaccounted
for. This is not rhetoric. It is a simple, frightening fact,'' a
joint statement by Reno and Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan called the probe ``a Keystone Kops investigation,'' saying
lab officials should have taken away Lee's top secret security
clearance ``years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, said he would call Reno and Freeh to a closed session of
the committee to provide further details of what secrets were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said the government has yet to resolve the central
question of how China obtained some of America's most sensitive
secrets on how nuclear bombs are made and assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a select House committee, chaired by Rep.
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., charged that China had stolen
information on every warhead in the U.S. ballistic missile arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
