<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VATICAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PROTESTS VATICAN'S PLAN TO CANONIZE MISSIONARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China stepped up its attacks on the Vatican Tuesday
for its plans to canonize 120 Catholics who were killed in China
between 1648 and 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Vatican considers them martyrs for their faith, a
Chinese government spokesman contended that many had ``committed
monstrous crimes against the Chinese people,'' and he accused the
Vatican of glorifying Western imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of these people were executed for violation of
Chinese laws during the invasion of China by imperialists and
colonialists, or were killed for bullying Chinese people during the
Opium War or the invasion by the eight allied powers,'' the
spokesman, Sun Yuxi, said on Tuesday at a foreign ministry news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute appears to reflect a recent worsening of relations
between China and the Vatican, despite reports of secret talks
during the past year apparently aimed at reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   European invasions of the 19th century _ the Opium War of
1839-42, which forced China to allow sales of the drug, and the
invasion by Western powers in 1900 to suppress the anti-foreign
Boxer movement _ are remembered bitterly here as national
humiliations.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's recently announced plan to give sainthood to 87
Chinese Catholics and 33 European missionaries, many of whom were
killed during those events, has touched a raw nerve among political
leaders, who say the Roman Catholic Church itself helped to
subjugate China in the past and plotted against the Communist
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has scheduled the canonization ceremony for Oct. 1,
which is the anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic.
Vatican officials say the date was selected simply because it is
the feast of St. Theresa of Lisieux, patron of missions.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued late Tuesday, Joaquin Navarro Valls, the
Vatican's spokesman, said, ``Next Sunday's ceremony has no
political motivation and is not directed against anyone.'' The
missionaries to be canonized, he said, had sacrificed ``to serve
the Chinese people,'' and he accused Chinese officials of a
``unilateral reading of history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese spokesman's attack and another stinging denunciation
of the Vatican on Tuesday by China's official Patriotic Catholic
Church, which does not accept the authority of the pope, were
featured on the television news here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   China and the Vatican broke ties in 1951 and Chinese Catholics
have been split ever since. Today, the official Patriotic Catholic
Church says it has 70 bishops and 4 million followers. Vatican
officials have estimated that 8 million Chinese, along with many
priests and bishops, remain loyal to the pope in a parallel illegal
church that faces frequent police harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an effort to minimize the provocation of Beijing,
the Vatican did not include any Catholics killed under Communist
rule in its new list of prospective saints.
</P>
<P>
   But Vatican leaders were angered in January when China made a
show of ordaining several new bishops of its official church on the
same day the pope was to ordain bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a top Vatican official, Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, 77,
made a rare public visit to Beijing to attend a conference, giving
rise to speculation about a possible breakthrough in relations.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little sign of that this week when Etchegaray, in
an interview in Rome, said that in his meetings with church
officials here, he had ``protested energetically against a new wave
of arrests of the faithful, even of bishops, which took place when
I was in China.''
</P>
<P>
   The official church in China issued a statement on Tuesday
accusing the Vatican of attempting ``to distort and tamper with
history'' and of ignoring traditionally stringent requirements for
sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few of those to be canonized are notorious,'' the
official church's statement said, calling them ``accomplices of
imperialists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
