<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HIP-HOP-AUDIENCE-NYT &LR;      09-26 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIP-HOP-AUDIENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, HIP-HOP SHOW IS NOT HIP ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Bett, an art director for a hip-hop music
label, drove to the Brooklyn Museum of Art on Saturday with his
wife and three children, playing L.L. Cool J on the car stereo to
prepare them for what they were about to witness.
</P>
<P>
   Orvil M. Minott, 24, a rock and hip-hop musician, walked to the
museum with a group of ``at risk'' teen-agers he works with at a
nonprofit group in nearby Flatbush. And Joe Correale, 28, who as a
teen-ager in the Bronx took part in ``park jams,'' where DJs and
MCs spun the first fledgling raps, arrived by subway to see how his
borough's history was being displayed.
</P>
<P>
   The patrons of the Brooklyn Museum's new exhibition, ``Hip-Hop
Nation: Roots, Rhymes and Rage,'' listening to rap music in
educational kiosks, watching videos about subway graffiti artists
and marveling over the enormity of the rap star Biggy Small's
sweatsuit, looked markedly different from the museum's typical
weekend crowd. They were younger and more ethnically diverse, and a
striking number said they had a personal connection to the material
on display, whether they were record company executives, former
graffiti writers, young aspiring DJs or teen-agers who simply said
they had never known life without hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   And although many praised the museum for presenting the show,
the first of its kind in a major American museum, and said they
enjoyed its vitality and its comprehensive approach to the music,
some walked out with the lingering feeling that the hip-hop they
saw on the walls was quite different from the hip-hop they knew
from the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The show, originally mounted by the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
in Cleveland and changed only minimally (a few graffiti art pieces
were added) by Kevin Stayton, a curator at the Brooklyn Museum, was
sponsored in part by Def Jam Records. It features hundreds of items
_ including rappers' clothes, concert posters and historical
memorabilia linking hip-hop to older cultural touchstones _ and
several video displays, all in four galleries on the first floor.
The exhibition focuses primarily on music icons and commercial
aspects of the culture, but is tame in its approach, presenting
some information on gangsta rap without addressing the harsh lyrics
and videos that have given rap its troublesome reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But because there was little material about break-dancing and
only a handful of graffiti paintings, some patrons said they were
disappointed that the exhibition did not reflect more deeply the
various forms that gave birth to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially right here in our neighborhood, I was hoping it
would be something we could come to and feel connected to,'' Minott
said. ``But I don't feel connected. This is giving us the glamour
of hip-hop, but it doesn't give any of the political message and
the political struggle that the music is about.''
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by other artists who consider themselves
part of hip-hop's history. Aaron Goodstone, 34, who has been a
graffiti artist for 20 years and goes by the name Sharp, said that
the exhibition placed too much emphasis on music and did not
adequately represent the two other essential components of the
culture, the visual arts and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all focused on people who rap,'' Goodstone said. ``I
think it's so unfair that because rap is already an industry, all
the other people who contributed to the movement and the arts in it
were cast in shadow behind the rappers.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said they felt that the exhibition paid appropriate
homage to the pioneers of the genre, highlighting the links to jazz
musicians like Cab Calloway, funk artists like George Clinton and
spoken-word innovators like the Last Poets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely kept it real,'' said Courtney E. Beatty, 26, a
warehouse foreman from Amityville who is a hip-hop MC and music
producer in his spare time. ``Especially where they went to the old
school, like Kurtis Blow and Grandmaster Flash. They took us back
to the roots, and that was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also much debate about the kind of audience the
exhibition was intended to attract.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Reyes, a musician and graphic designer from Los Angeles who
goes by the name Sketch, said that the show was a primer on hip-hop
culture, touching on only its most basic aspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's oriented for a mainstream viewer _ who's popular now,
who's making money,'' he said. ``But I would have liked to see
alternative artists mentioned, people who really made an impact in
creating the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   But others who consider themselves mainstream viewers, like Jan
Girard, 54, a home furnishings designer from the Williamsburg
section of Brooklyn, said they thought that the exhibition was
created with hip-hop fans in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably too old for this,'' she said. ``I think it was
more about people who are already familiar with it.'' Girard said
she took her friend and her friend's teen-age son to the museum
because it was one exhibition she knew the boy could tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Resto, 19, a high school student from Williamsburg, was
thrilled to find an exhibition he could relate to. ``It's
definitely cool, because I've never seen anything like this in a
museum before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bett, who has designed several covers for rap albums in the
past, said he thought the subject matter was tame enough for his
children and unlikely to spawn the kind of conflict stirred last
year by ``Sensation,'' the Brooklyn Museum's exhibition of works by
young British artists that included animals suspended in
formaldehyde and an image of the Virgin Mary decorated with bits of
cow dung.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is trying to be very positive,'' he said. ``Hip-hop is so
deep, it's hard to get into all of it, and so much of it is still
underground. For mainstream hip-hop, it does a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the dearth of controversial material and the abundance of
commercial artifacts in the show upset some viewers. Miguel
Nogueres, 33, an art director for an advertising agency from the
Pelham Bay section of the Bronx, said he grew up in the Throgs Neck
public housing projects, where he had a front row seat on the
emergence of hip-hop culture in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's not as intimidating now as it used to be,'' he
said. ``People thought it belonged to gangsters and drug dealers,
though it never really did. It was a form of expression, language
and art and dance. I don't really think clothing and photographs
will ever do it justice, because it's such a lively and energetic
form. This exhibit is like one color in the palette of hip-hop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
