<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT27-COX     09-26 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUPREME COURT DECLINES DIRECT APPEAL OF MICROSOFT CASE
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BRUCE HIGHT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. won a significant tactical victory
in its antitrust battle Tuesday when the U.S. Supreme Court
declined to take the Justice Department's case against the software
giant on direct appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company's fight to keep from being split into two
independent units will now go to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia, which has sided with Microsoft in
past rulings. Whoever loses there can still appeal to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court's vote Tuesday was 8-1. Justice Stephen Breyer
dissented, saying that ``speed in reaching a final decision may
help create legal certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court also refused to take up a related case against
Microsoft brought by 19 state attorneys general in support of the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals moved quickly, acting on its own motion
Tuesday afternoon to order Microsoft to submit by Monday its
proposed schedule for handling the appeal. The court also said
Microsoft and the government could submit a joint proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to presenting our case to the court of appeals
as expeditiously as possible,'' said a Justice Department
spokeswoman, Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Jim Cullinan, said the court's ruling
means the company will now ``get a chance to challenge what we
believe were a significant number of legal, factual and procedural
errors committed by the District Court which we think, in the end,
will result in this judgment being reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock finished up 1 7/16 at $62 11/16 in trading
Tuesday on the NASDAQ stock exchange. Its 52-week high was $119
15/16, hit late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department won a landmark victory this year when
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled that Microsoft,
with annual revenues of about $23 billion, had illegally used its
market power to protect a monopoly on its Windows operating system
software for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   At the government's urging, Jackson ordered the company divided
in two, with one taking Windows, the other getting applications
such as the Word processor and Excel database programs.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft moved to appeal, but the Justice Department wanted to
skip the intermediate appeals court and go directly to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Although such a direct appeal is rare, the Justice Department
argued that ``the sooner a meaningful remedy is in place, the
better it will be for consumers and the marketplace by providing
increased innovation, more choices and better products.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, however, argued for the usual route through the court
of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   William Kovacic, a professor of law at George Washington
University Law School who has tracked the case, said the high
court's refusal to hear the case on direct appeal means that the
chances that Microsoft will actually be broken up ``were
extinguished today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals will not vindicate Microsoft completely,
Kovacic predicted, but ``the government now has to run a very
demanding gantlet, and I don't think they'll pass through that
gantlet unscathed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic said that as time passes, ``the logic of a breakup might
be far from apparent, as the industry itself changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, the government case already has had an
impact, as seen in ``a somewhat chastened Microsoft, a somewhat
more emboldened group of competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision, announced without explanation, also
gives Microsoft more time to weigh the impact of two changes that
could affect its appeal: the presidential election and the
impending departure of Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein, the
Justice Department prosecutor who as head of the antitrust division
successfully pushed the government's case against Microsoft. Klein
leaves at the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Cullinan said the Supreme Court will benefit from the appeals
court's taking ``an initial review of this case to clear out that
legal and factual underbrush'' and focus on the most important
issues.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the major party presidential candidates, Vice
President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, has said much
about antitrust issues, though some have theorized that Bush's more
pro-business record suggests he would be less interested in forcing
Microsoft to break up.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cullinan said the presidential election won't affect
the case because it ``is already in the appellate process. We think
that the issues are clear, and we think we are going to win on the
merits of our appeal. We believe wholeheartedly that this issue
will be decided in the court system.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rise in Microsoft's stock price Tuesday, some
experts said that the ruling may hurt the company because it
postpones the day when markets will know the company's likely
future standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the marketplace, and the stock market in particular,
would like an earlier resolution of this case,'' said Steven Salop,
an economist who teaches antitrust law at Georgetown University Law
School. ``They wish Microsoft could just get the case behind it.
This means it's going to take longer.''
</P>
<P>
   In a step related to the court's Microsoft order Tuesday, Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist said he would not stay out of the
Microsoft case despite his son's position as a partner in a Boston
law firm employed Microsoft in another case.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son's personal and financial concerns will not be affected
by our disposition of the Supreme Court's Microsoft matters,'' the
chief justice said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
