<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
Q2399 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ISSUES-SOCSEC-NNS &LR;      09-26 2393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISSUES-SOCSEC-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAMPAIGN 2000 
 &HT;     SOCIAL SECURITY AND MEDICARE: THE ONLY GUARANTEE IS CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
    &HT;     Second in a series of four articles, each transmitted in
successive weeks, on issues in the 2000 presidential campaign 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 26, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With a photo of Sharon and Greg Diekman (NNS3);
and with a graphic outlining candidates' positions; for information
about purchasing art call 202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Analysis 
 &HT;     Two optional trims to 1,800 words 
 &HT;     By MILES BENSON 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the presidential campaign heats up, both major
candidates are offering what sound like ironclad guarantees that
Americans now getting Social Security and Medicare benefits and
those who'll soon qualify need fear no cuts whatsoever, and that no
new taxes will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But demographics, actuarial tables and economics say such
promises cannot be kept for succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
   When the tidal wave of baby boomers rolls in, new taxes, benefit
cuts or massive federal borrowing will be necessary, experts say.
And when politicians and their policy advisers finish saving these
two entitlement programs, which cover every American, it's a good
bet that both will look quite different than they do today.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush have
made only cautious proposals in the direction the country will be
forced to go. Their rhetoric promises ``lock boxes'' to safeguard
the surpluses that both programs are generating for the moment. And
they back plans to pay down the national debt as a strategy for
``protecting and strengthening'' Social Security and Medicare in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Beware.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are being offered ``lock-boxes'' much as they were once
offered ``trust funds,'' a concept they have been told they can no
longer trust. The ``lock-box'' is a law Congress would pass to
ensure that funds dedicated to Social Security and Medicare would
not be spent for any other purpose.
</P>
<P>
   And while paying down the national debt may be a good idea,
doing so could just as easily be described as a way of ``protecting
and strengthening'' national defense, education, farm programs or
any of the nation's other high-priority concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma facing Social Security and Medicare is not hard to
understand. Payroll taxes on today's workers support both retiree
programs. In 1950 there were seven workers to every retiree. By
2030, the ratio of workers to retirees will be less than three to
one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Social Security and Medicare, therefore, face real long-term
financing problems that unattended will build to crisis proportions
over time.
</P>
<P>
   These problems can be erased painlessly if the nation has a new
run of economic growth even longer and stronger than that of the
past eight years, a possibility that few reputable economists are
forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would currently imagined budget surpluses be sufficient to
balance the books. Medicare, Social Security and the appetite for
increased spending on defense and other national needs will devour
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the most plausible long-term scenarios, the government
faces an annual fiscal deficit, not a surplus,'' economists Alan J.
Auerbach of the University of California, Berkeley, and William G.
Gale of the Brookings Institution declare in a recent report. As a
result, they warn, the ``current frenzy of proposals for allocating
the surplus to additional spending and tax cuts is misplaced.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If the president elected in November gets two terms, he will
leave office just as the baby boomers start to retire. The big
fiscal challenge will be finding ways to pay their Social Security
and Medicare benefits during their lengthening life expectancies.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Social Security is the less difficult problem to
solve, requiring only small increases in taxes, raising the
retirement age slightly and reducing benefits a touch _ providing
that these things are done soon.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Gore nor Bush proposes this. Instead, both
candidates would sweeten the retirement packages for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would rely on surpluses that may not materialize, and Bush
would rely on private profits that may not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Both postpone tough decisions about higher taxes, benefit cuts
or new deficit spending that will have to be made later.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledges Social Security's double-barreled problem:
Retirees will claim an increasing share of gross domestic product,
and payroll taxes will be inadequate to finance the present benefit
structure.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Blinder, Gore's economic adviser, says that both can be
solved ``without doing what I certainly thought four years ago was
going to be necessary: cutbacks in benefits or a higher payroll
tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Using current budget surpluses to pay down the debt should lead
to lower interest rates, more business investment and faster
productivity growth, he said. ``With a bigger pie you can pick out
a bigger slice for seniors, and if the pie can grow fast enough,
there won't be any pain at all,'' Blinder said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gore intends to credit the Social Security trust fund
with the money the government saves in interest on the national
debt, thereby eliminating half _ but only half _ of the program's
projected fiscal shortfall. And while this accounting device makes
the books look better, it does not actually set aside the money
that will be needed to pay benefits. For that, the government would
still eventually have to divert money from other programs, raise
taxes or borrow.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore would raise benefits for mothers, widows and
widowers.
</P>
<P>
   Parents would be eligible for credit toward Social Security for
as long as five years spent raising children, if during that time
they could work only part time or not at all. The child-raising
years would be counted as if the caregiver had earned one-half the
average national wage over the period.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the so-called motherhood penalty would provide an
average additional benefit of $600 annually to 8 million Americans,
mostly women.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also proposes to raise the widow/widower benefit to 75
percent of the combined couple's benefit, capped at the average
Social Security retirement benefit. More than 3 million widows and
widowers would see their benefits rise by as much as $4,100
annually under Gore's plan.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Gore seeks to match and even surpass Bush's
promises of greater wealth for all retirees by creating a new
program to subsidize personal investment savings accounts, so that
families may build tax-free nest eggs to supplement Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's plan, ``Retirement Savings Plus,'' a married couple
earning up to $30,000 could put $500 a year from each spouse into a
special private account. The federal government would add $1,500
per spouse, for a total of $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Couples earning between $30,000 and $60,000 would get a maximum
$1,000 per person; those earning up to $100,000 would get $500 per
person.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Social Security solution envisions a major change in the
program's structure, allowing younger workers to invest an
unspecified portion of their Social Security payroll taxes in
private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the stock market, this money will earn a higher rate of
return and generate wealth, Bush predicts. It also presumably
cushions against future reductions in Social Security benefits,
although Bush does not indicate whether he would propose such cuts.
</P>
<P>
   This is an approach favored by many Democrats as well as
Republicans. But unanswered is how Bush would protect checks
flowing to current retirees if taxes on younger workers, which now
support those benefits, are diverted to private retirement
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush's plan is far less defined than Gore's, and that is
no accident, said Lawrence Lindsay, Bush's chief policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, why don't we spell out the exact program we are
going to enact? The answer is straightforward. If you did, it
wouldn't be enacted,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy operators get things done differently in Washington, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do is come to town as flexible as possible with a
mandate to do something,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   Then you set up a bipartisan commission: ``You get the relevant
players in a room and you take away the key to the bathroom until
they get their heads together and come up with a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Lindsay said, would go into such negotiations pushing six
principles:
</P>
<P>
   _ No changes in benefits for retirees and near-retirees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Current Social Security tax surpluses must be protected by a
lock box.
</P>
<P>
   _ Social Security payroll taxes must not be increased.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government itself must not invest Social Security funds in
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Modernization must preserve the Social Security disability and
survivors' benefit programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Modernization must include individually controlled voluntary
personal retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The plans offered by Gore and Bush have disappointed many
objective policy analysts, like the bipartisan Concord Coalition,
which has sounded alarms for several years about the fiscal train
wreck awaiting Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are left with is a choice between two free lunch
proposals,'' the Concord Coalition reported recently. ``That kind
of political debate, which rules out changes in current benefit
promises or tax rates, is perhaps worse than no debate at all
because it locks the new president into an indefensible position.
The window of opportunity for phased-in modest changes is beginning
to slide shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more imposing are Medicare's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Medicare serves 39 million beneficiaries, everyone over
65 and many disabled. Those numbers will more than double to 80
million as the boomers retire. As with Social Security, there will
be relatively fewer workers paying taxes to support the program.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare's financing is more daunting given the rising cost of
health care itself, the result of both inflation and medical
advances that generate new, better and often more expensive
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush offer dramatically different solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Both would add benefits for seniors, including prescription drug
coverage not now available under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would expand the 35-year-old government-run Medicare
program by adding prescription drugs to its standard benefits,
requiring most _ but not the poorest _ beneficiaries to pay a $25
monthly premium.
</P>
<P>
   The drug benefit would pay half the cost of all prescriptions up
to $5,000. Beneficiaries would be solely responsible for the next
$1,500 in costs, but 100 percent of prescriptions after that would
be government-paid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also proposes to reinforce Medicare financing with
accounting devices that he claims would extend the solvency of the
Medicare trust fund to 2030, after which further adjustments would
be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would overhaul Medicare, encouraging seniors to shift from
the government program to subsidized private health insurance plans
that include drug coverage. Seniors could elect to remain in
traditional Medicare, with the option of buying a subsidized
prescription drug plan. Those choosing to leave Medicare would get
subsidies to buy government-approved private health insurance that
would vary in costs and benefits. The elderly themselves would pay
extra for more generous benefit packages if they so desired.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also promises to cover the full cost of drug coverage for
the low-income elderly, and add an entirely new and important
benefit for all seniors. Bush would have the government pay for all
catastrophic medical expenses, defined as those costs above $6,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush believes his changes will take several years, he
would set up a temporary program giving states $48 billion in
grants for immediate needs _ to subsidize prescription drug
coverage for the low-income elderly and those with unusually large
drug bills.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Bush nor Gore offers a reliable solution to
Medicare's long-term financing problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan raises twin problems that ``we don't know yet how
to solve,'' said Henry Aaron, an economist at the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   By giving people funds to buy private health insurance and
telling them that if they want a more expensive plan they must pay
for it themselves, Bush encourages them to shop for economy, Aaron
said. Insurers, however, would have a powerful incentive to
``cherry pick,'' enrolling only the healthiest, lower-cost
beneficiaries, Aaron said. To offset that consequence, policymakers
must find a way to make payments to insurance companies vary with
the risks. ``But we don't know how to do that,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   A second problem with the Bush plan, Aaron warned, is that many
seniors may not be able to handle the aggressive sales techniques
of private insurers or process complete information about alternate
benefit packages. ``We would need a regulated market to assist
people in making intelligent decisions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Aaron's view, the Gore plan has its own defects, the worst
being that it ducks the problem of long-term financing.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of that deficit have been volatile in recent years.
Today's projection is two-thirds smaller than it was three years
ago as a result of cutbacks in payments to health care providers,
the strong economy and easing in the growth of health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that could turn around,'' Aaron said. ``The fact is that
Medicare is inadequate insurance, and making it adequate is going
to cost more. Eventually we have got to find more money either by
raising the payroll tax, or more general revenue transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in the end going to walk away from Medicare and
therefore there will be some painful choices made down the road.
It's not the sort of thing we want to talk about, but it's the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   LF END BENSON
</P>
<P>
   (Miles Benson can be reached at Miles.Benson(at)newhouse.com)
</P>
