<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAELIS-PALESTINIANS     09-26 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAELIS-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CORDIAL DINNER PARTY, ARAFAT AND BARAK REGAIN MOMENTUM FOR
PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ It was just a little suburban dinner
party, nothing fancy. The host and his guest of honor cracked
jokes. They strolled in the garden for an intimate chat. And then
the host kissed his guest goodbye, walked him to a waiting Israeli
military helicopter and waved as the guest, wearing his trademark
kaffiyeh, flew back to Gaza City.
</P>
<P>
   A senior adviser to Yasser Arafat said the late-night supper, at
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's private home in Kochav Yair on Monday,
was the single best meeting ever between the Palestinian and
Israeli leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser, Nabil Shaath, said Tuesday that it had been ``very
cordial,'' even congenial. He noted that the two men had walked
together to the balcony twice _ ``and both came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Barak said the evening had been ``warm and open.''
</P>
<P>
   How did the two leaders move from tense, strained relations to
hugs in a single evening? Only their advisers know. Has improved
chemistry shortened the distance from a deadlock to a permanent
peace treaty? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing substantive was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday both sides were willing to declare fresh momentum
and, as their negotiators were landing in the United States, to
move forward once more into yet another ``decisive'' phase of
peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, in my home in Kochav Yair,'' Barak said Tuesday,
``we met with Arafat and the entire Palestinian leadership for a
warm, open meeting that I believe will help us in our efforts to
renew the negotiations. I would say that we are at the entrance to
a very intensive effort and, in a way, to the last effort in this
round to reach a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an intimate meeting between Arafat, once Israel's mortal
enemy, and an Israeli leader would have been unthinkable just years
ago. Arafat only made one previous visit to an Israeli prime
minister's home, and that was to pay condolences to the family of
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin after he was assassinated by a Jewish
extremist in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Shaath said the Kochav Yair meeting had been engineered by an
American Jewish businessman, S. Daniel Abraham. Abraham, founder of
the Slim-Fast Food Companies, is a leading contributor to the
Democratic Party's election campaigns this year and a backer of
Israeli-Arab peace efforts through the Washington-based Center for
Middle East Peace and Economic Cooperation, which he co-founded.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And shortly before Arafat flew off to see Barak, the Palestinian
leader met with a separate contingent of 15 American Jewish leaders
in Gaza City. Michael Sonnenfeldt, chairman of the dovish Israel
Policy Forum, said the Americans had visited Arafat to declare that
American Jews were probably more centrist than he imagined, and
willing to support both sides in the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him that the American Jewish community, which is
committed to Israel's longterm security, understands that a peace
agreement will bring security in region only if a Palestinian state
takes hold,'' Sonnenfeldt said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Barak and Arafat made an effort at developing a
relationship last fall and earlier this year, they never clicked.
Since the Camp David peace talks ended two months ago, they have
not communicated directly, although they did shake hands at the
United Nations gathering of world leaders earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-day meeting at Camp David, presided over by President
Clinton, did not produce a permanent peace accord to end 52 years
of bitter conflict, as planned. But it provoked substantive debate
on all of the issues and something close to a meeting of the minds
on the key issues of territorial division, water resources and
security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   After Camp David, though, both sides say the momentum evaporated
and they lost ground on those issues. In a rare news conference by
a senior Palestinian official Tuesday, Shaath, the minister of
planning and international cooperation, blamed the Israelis for
focusing too much on the most difficult issue, the future status of
the holy site known to Jews as the Temple Mount and to Muslims as
Haram al Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can live without turning our feuds into religious issues,''
he said. ``And the stalemate cannot be broken if we just
concentrate on Haram al Sharif. It wouldn't be at all bad if
instead where we are close we made things closer. Trust would be
created if on five to seven issues we could measure some
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are to meet
separately with American mediators to review a bridging proposal
that seeks to reconcile conflicting demands on all of the key
issues on the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Shaath said President Clinton first reviewed a final copy of the
document on Friday and suggested summoning the parties to review it
rather than making it public, to the risk of provoking further
discord.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is agonizing over it,'' Shaath said, referring to
Clinton, ``because he doesn't want another failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians do not feel the same sense of urgency as Barak,
who will face a possible dissolution of his minority government
when the Israeli Parliament reconvenes at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Shaath said Barak could find a way to reconstitute his
coalition. He also said the Palestinians thought that there were
advantages to dealing with a ``lame duck'' American president after
the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians will not be setting any new dates for a
declaration of Palestinian statehood after two deadlines were
broken, Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
   If no agreement can be reached this fall, he said, the
Palestinians will ask the Israelis to fulfill their unfulfilled
commitments under the most recent interim agreement _ for example,
another land transfer _ ``to create a safety net and prevent
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis are trying to create a mental picture of
Palestinians like croupiers at a casino pocketing all the chips and
not giving anything in return,'' he said. ``I think the giving has
already happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel has had a great two years'' because of
Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation that has reduced
terrorism, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
