<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-26 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES SATISFIED WITH THE BRONZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The medal will be bronze, and that is just fine with
Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a medal in my life, and I had to fight hard for
it. I'm just happy that I won a medal.''
</P>
<P>
   After turning down two Olympics, and faltering in another, Seles
got her medal by beating the raw, gloomy weather plus 10,000 folks
who wanted her to lose because she was in the paved rectangle with
one of them _ Aussie Jelena Dokic, 6-1, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   It could be zinc rather than bronze, and Seles would be just as
happy because ``I take nothing for granted since the stabbing.''
There was something about the dastardly Guenther Parche plunging a
knife into her back seven years ago that makes Seles fully
appreciate everything that comes her way.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday it was a bronze medal, the prize for winning a playoff
with the much-admired ingenue, Dokic, a townie, and the youngest
kid on the Olympic tennis block at Homebush. They were losing
semifinalists, Dokic to the Russian, Elena Dementieva.
</P>
<P>
   After Seles took her best shot at Venus Williams and gold _
close, but no succor _ she was ``really down. I didn't even know
about the playoff thing, and when I found out about it I didn't
want to play at all. That's how depressed I was.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a nice thing happened. My good friend Mary Joe Fernandez
phoned me from the US, and she told me how fantastic it would be to
win a bronze. She won one at Barcelona in 1992. That kind of got me
going. I said, OK, I'm really going to come back and fight for
this. You know, to get all the way from a chance at gold to have
the bronze is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles knew she'd have to go for a quick kill. Giving away nine
years and a Dokic-supporting cast of 10,000 voices, she was still
tinged with weariness, emotional as well as physical, from her 6-1,
4-6, 6-3, civil war 24 hours before against Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so difficult mentally to play against a teammate. But
it was tough with the crowd and Jelena.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Serena Williams won their doubles semifinal by beating
Els Callens and Dominique Van Roost of Belgium, 6-4, 6-1. Their
opponents in the final Thursday will be Kristie Boogert and Miriam
Oremans of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a gold medal would be a fantastic thing for sure,''
Serena said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the good burghers of Sydney filling the silver oval
stadium Tuesday weren't hostile, they were homers of a
high-decibelic order. Their men _ Patrick Rafter, Lleyton Hewitt,
Mark Philippoussis _ had been as big a bust in singles as the lower
quality American guys, but now their girl could be a 17-year-old
heroine cast in bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Their cheers went only to her, whether Dokic made a point on a
Seles error or her own merit. Seles sometimes heard her coaches,
Billie Jean King and Zina Garrison, yelling encouragement through
the tumult, but it was her job to mute the mob as often as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   She was swift about it, as she needed to be: 56 minutes. Off the
blocks like Marion Jones, Seles darted hither and yon, firing her
double-barrelled groundies zestfully from both sides to stun the
kid by taking the first nine points, and a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic, a slight but whippy blonde, is, however, a fighter, too.
She rebounded in the second _ and with her the patrons _ as she
bottled Seles at 4-4. There a double fault to 15-30, an opening the
canny old pro used well. She'd been through so much, and knew what
to do. She'd been a better 17-year-old than Dokic _ probably better
than anyone else ever of that age, holder of four major titles
before her 18th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Seles jerked Dokic from sideline to sideline, squeezing mistakes
from her to dash ahead, 5-4, then 30-0. Dokic, undaunted, countered
with a drop shot and won a long rally. Thirty-all. Seles was tired.
She couldn't lose this game. A third set was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   There were only two things to do. Don't let Dokic hit another
ball or a vocal spectator hit another high note. She had never
ended a match in the big league like this _ perfect knockout
swings. But Seles, narrowing her vivid blue eyes, went for it. She
raised her left arm and cranked an ace, kicking it wide beyond
Dokic's forehand. It felt so good that she did it again. Curling
the ball out of reach, Seles had hooked her bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Silence. Then the respectful, sporting applause that she
deserved from the 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   They shook hands. A portrait of two kids born in the Balkans _
the crumbling Yugoslavia _ whose perceptive fathers, the kindly
Karolj Seles and the erratic Damir Dokic, had spirited them off to
better places to grow: Monica to the US, Jelena to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, then 18 after settling in Florida, Seles was invited to
represent Yugoslavia in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time I felt that tennis didn't belong in the Olympics.
But,'' Seles says, ``by 1996 I was a US citizen, and my father
thought it would be wonderful to represent my new country. I could
see he was right. It is such an honor, one of the few times you get
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   She went to Atlanta, the favorite, only to lose in the quarters
to Czech Jana Novotna, who seized the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be on that victory stand. Now I will, along with
Venus who, hopefully, will win the gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronze, worked by artists as noteworthy as Rodin, comes in all
shapes, sizes, and prices. Seles is a rich woman, but the small
disc is all the more precious because it cannot be purchased _
except with sweat, heart, and skill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
