<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
Q2387 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-YOUTH-VOTE-NNS &LR;      09-26 1922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VOTE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE GENERATIONS BEAT 
 &HT;     TRYING TO ATTRACT YOUNG VOTERS, POLITICAL GROUPS TURN UP THE
GLITZ 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
    &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 26, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With two photos, of Donnita Hathaway (NNS1), and
of Kristen Tunney with Troy Gryga and John Elrod (NNS2); for
information about purchasing art call 202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Optional trim to 1,600 words 
 &HT;     By MICHELE MELENDEZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) There's no war to protest. The economy is chugging.
There's no national strife to mobilize the masses.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the country's youngest eligible voters have
known only prosperity. They haven't lived through wartime drafts,
crippling economic depression or widespread blatant discrimination
against women and minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the most part, they don't vote.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous recent studies show that people younger than 30
generally don't care about casting their ballots. They don't see
why it's important or what difference it makes.
</P>
<P>
   But organizations that promote voting are beginning to craft
creative ways to capture their interest.
</P>
<P>
   The flashier programs say that voting is not only the right
thing to do, it's the cool thing to do. Cable's pioneering music
video channel MTV is urging its viewers to ``Choose or Lose.'' With
trademark shouting and muscle, the World Wrestling Federation is
pushing fans to ``Smackdown Your Vote!''
</P>
<P>
   And despite documented cynicism among young voters, some states,
including California, Florida, Massachusetts, Minnesota and Oregon,
have entertained lowering the voting age from 18 to as young as 12.
</P>
<P>
   While turnout in the United States is down overall _ less than
half the country's eligible voters went to the polls in the 1996
presidential election _ it's lowest within the youngest group. Four
years ago, 32 percent of 18- to 24-year-olds voted, according to
census figures. More than twice that share, 67 percent, of people
65 and older voted.
</P>
<P>
   The common explanation for the difference is that people develop
more interest in voting as they settle down, buy homes and raise
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older voters have always shown up more; that's nothing new,''
said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press. ``What's happening is the gap is getting wider
and wider.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer the Pew Center issued a report saying people younger
than 30 don't vote because they're adverse to politics and don't
think it matters who's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have other things on our minds,'' Sara DiFiore, an
18-year-old from Whiting, Ind., said at a recent WWF event. ``I
don't really think about whoever's president. Whoever wins, wins.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is common among a generation that grew up with the
overwhelming offerings of cable TV and the Internet, said Thomas
Patterson, a principal investigator with the Vanishing Voter
Project at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The project reported that almost three times as many people ages
18 to 29 knew who won this year's Super Bowl than who won the
highly publicized New Hampshire Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation is very much tied into the media. There's no
question about that,'' Patterson said. ``What they're not tied into
is the news media.''
</P>
<P>
   As young people's interest in politics has waned, several
organizations are aiming to make voting feel as natural as turning
on the television. The philosophy is: Get them while they're young
_ real young.
</P>
<P>
   Kids Voting USA, based in Tempe, Ariz., offers a curriculum to
teach children as young as kindergartners about informed voting.
Schools across the country, including those in Springfield, Mass.,
Newark, N.J., and Saginaw, Mich., use the program, which includes
mock elections and classroom discussions on civics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll vote for things like ice cream and recess. Who
wouldn't want to have ice cream and recess?'' said Paula Case, a
Kids Voting USA project manager. ``But then they find out it's `no
recess' and `garlic ice cream' and learn why research is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids Voting USA even sets up cardboard voting booths at official
polling sites so children can vote alongside their parents. ``The
reason to start so young is so the voting place becomes a familiar
place, not a scary place, so voting becomes a habit,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is helping to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, state legislatures have put up Web pages in
simple language to teach children about government. Youth-e-Vote
allows students to vote a week before the election for president,
governor and policy issues. And the Council for Excellence in
Government and its partners are promoting a ``Take Your Kids to
Vote'' campaign, suggesting activities for children and parents
counting down to the election.
</P>
<P>
   During every presidential election since 1992, MTV has peppered
the music of the day with its ``Choose or Lose'' series. This year,
four people in their 20s are traveling the country for MTV, talking
to young people about voting.
</P>
<P>
   Erica Terry, 27, one of the ``Choose or Lose'' correspondents,
said young people feel the presidential candidates don't address
them in their speeches or promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard for the kids to see the connection between
what's going on in their day-to-day lives and the larger picture,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, MTV and the Kaiser Family Foundation released
``Youth, Voting and the 2000 Election,'' a report based on a survey
of 800 18- to 24-year-olds. The report said that while at least
three out of four young people surveyed supported restrictions on
gun buying, funding for sex education in schools and helping the
uninsured receive health coverage, just 46 percent said they
planned to vote. The top explanations: They didn't know enough
about the candidates; they felt they could have more impact being
involved in their communities than by voting; and they felt
politics was ``all about money and lying.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore answered
questions from young people at a ``Choose or Lose'' forum taped in
Ann Arbor, Mich. Republican candidate George W. Bush has not yet
accepted MTV's invitation to appear.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation hoisted the youth voting banner
in August, kicking off ``Smackdown Your Vote!'' with a nonpartisan
coalition called Youth Vote 2000. Two of the WWF's most recognized
wrestlers, the Rock and Chyna, made saucy appearances at the
national conventions in August. Later that month, the WWF announced
that it had registered about 40,000 people during the voting
drive's first three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At a September WWF event in Rosemont, Ill., a Chicago suburb,
young fans crowded around a table with voting and registration
information.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning against a concrete wall in the arena, Erich Zilai of
Chicago pressed a pen to a blank registration form, turned to his
friend and said, ``'Cause the Rock told me to, I've got to vote
now.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old hard-core wrestling fan said he wouldn't have
registered if his favorite wrestler hadn't told him to and if the
WWF hadn't made it easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidates aren't speaking to me or other young people,''
Zilai said. ``I didn't think it was important before to vote, but
the Rock convinced me.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Rock admirer, Donnita Hathaway, 24, of Chicago, said she
had registered before but didn't feel moved to vote for president
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to me now, now that I'm paying taxes, thinking
about raising a family,'' she said. ``I hate to say this, but kids
are young and dumb. I was. But now that I'm older, it just makes
sense for me to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Several eager fans who ran up to the table walked away dejected
when they learned they weren't old enough to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Those young wannabe-voters have supporters. The past decade has
seen several proposals to lower the voting age at the local, state
and federal levels.
</P>
<P>
   The voting age was 21 until 1971. A constitutional amendment to
lower the age to 18 came amid protests of the Vietnam War;
18-year-olds could be drafted to fight but could not vote. In
1972's presidential election, the first with the younger voting
age, 50 percent of 18- to 24-year-olds voted. Participation in that
age group has dropped every presidential election year since.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to lower the age even further all have fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota State Rep. Phyllis Kahn, a Democrat who has pushed a
younger age for nearly 10 years, said she wanted to spark
discussion about young people and voting. In 1991, she suggested
reducing the age to 12, choosing that age because government
pamphlets are written at the reading level of a 12-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got an enormous amount of attention, including a lot of
ridicule, but a fantastic interest from kids,'' Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn now suggests a voting age of 16. ``We let our kids drive
when they're 16, when an irresponsible driver can do much more harm
than an irresponsible voter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fouts, a councilman from Warren, Mich., tried to lower the
voting age to 17 for the 1999 city election. His fellow council
members didn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts, who teaches government at Sterling Heights High School,
said young people need to feel included in the election process and
warned that their cynicism was simmering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students pick up on the phoniness,'' he said. ``They think
Bush and Gore will say anything it takes to get elected, but they
are making decisions today that will affect them for decades to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans for a Society Free From Age Restrictions, a national
youth-driven advocacy group, supports a younger voting age. After
all, members say, young people pay taxes, are citizens and should
have a say in their government.
</P>
<P>
   The group's president, Eric Anderson, a 21-year-old from St.
Louis, said age doesn't determine an informed voter: ``There are
people over 18 who don't know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Young people don't vote because ``there's a feeling out there
that we're choosing between the lesser of two evils,'' he said.
``But there are alternate parties young people should know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, for example. In 1998, he
campaigned as a member of the Reform Party like a rock star _
pumping music and gritty slogans during campaign stops. Young
people rallied around him, and he has credited their support for
helping him win.
</P>
<P>
   Known during his wrestling days as Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura,
he has agreed to moderate the ``Smackdown Challenge,'' a debate in
which the World Wrestling Federation has urged the Democratic and
Republican candidates to participate.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the tactic employed to get young people to vote,
experts looking at the numbers say the turnout is likely to slump
until some national issue inspires action.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these things help, but to be honest with you, I think
large societal forces change these things,'' said Kohut, of the Pew
Center. ``It's going to take changes in our national condition to
change these attitudes. It will happen. The economy is not going to
keep on rocking. Things won't be sedate all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   LF END MELENDEZ
</P>
<P>
   (Michele Melendez can be reached at
Michele.Melendez(at)newhouse.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
