<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-26 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RIVALS BATTLE OVER ISSUES AND HIT TALK SHOWS  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore clashed Tuesday
over rival plans to strengthen education and overhaul Medicare
before limbering up for the opening presidential debate with
televised question-and-answer sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pressed his claim of an ``education recession'' during the
Clinton-Gore years, at an appearance at a public school in Redwood
City, Calif., adjacent to Silicon Valley before joining his wife,
Laura, for a scheduled appearance on CNN's Larry King Live
interview talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Gore challenged Bush on education during an appearance at Wayne
State University in Detroit, and spotlighted differences with Bush
over rival blueprints to overhaul Medicare, the federally
subsidized health care coverage that benefits nearly 40 million
elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore later fielded questions from young people invited to the
Music Television network's ``Choose or Lose 2000'' program, a town
hall-style question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates worked the campaign trail as the bipartisan
Commission on Presidential Debates, host of every presidential
campaign debate since 1988, prepared to announce that the first
debate on Oct. 3 will include only Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Commission chairs Paul Kirk and Frank Fahrenkopf said
third-party candidates such as the Green Party's Ralph Nader and
the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan would be invited to attend only if
they had garnered the support of 15 percent of the voters in the
six nationwide surveys used to determine admission to the
nationally televised debates. Nader and Buchanan remained in single
digits in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a third-party candidate won admission was in 1992
when Texas billionaire Ross Perot, with public support as high as
30 percent, joined President Bush and then-Arkansas Gov. Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   This week, nationwide surveys showed Bush retaining a slight
edge over Gore in the popular vote, with his margin ranging from 2
percentage points to 6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore led in the state-by-state battle for electoral votes, with
public opinion polls giving him the edge in 26 states with 307
electoral votes. Bush led in 22 states with 180 electoral votes,
according to the daily summary maintained by the National Journal's
Hotline political newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate needs to win enough states to capture 270 electoral
votes to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail in California, Bush told 200 teachers,
students and supporters at a high school that his $48-billion,
10-year plan could bolster literacy, provide college scholarships
and help states create and implement standards to judge public
schools' annual performance. Parents of children at failing schools
would get $1,500 per child per year to pay for other schooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there are better days ahead for America _ and it
starts with making sure every kid gets educated in America,'' Bush
said. Citing statistics showing U.S. students' test scores trailing
many other industrialized democracies, Bush said that ``if America
doesn't lead the world in math and science, the next generation may
not lead the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore belittled Bush's education plan, saying the Texan's
proposed overhaul would give parents of children attending failing
public schools ``little tiny bits (of money) _ not nearly enough to
pay the tuition at a private school.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his 10-year, $115-billion education blueprint would
renovate crumbling schools, cut class size, hire 100,000 new
teachers and bring in new principals and ``turnaround'' teams at
troubled schools.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president continued to showcase disagreements with Bush
over Medicare a day after he reminded voters that Bush had
supported the proposed $270-billion cut to Medicare fashioned by
then-House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga. President Clinton twice
vetoed the GOP-backed measure before accepting a compromise $112
billion plan to cutback Medicare as part of a deal that balanced
the federal budget for the first time since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Gore contrasted his proposed $338-billion overhaul of the
middle-class entitlement and his plan to protect the program's
projected 10-year, $360-billion surplus with Bush's plan for a tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, mindful that the Clinton-Gore ticket had
rallied young voter turnout to win in 1992, tried to revive
interest among 18 to 24 year olds during the taped 90-minute MTV
town hall meeting at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore offered vivid warnings that next president will have the
opportunity to fill as many as four seats on the U.S. Supreme Court
that are expected to open up in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, dressed in an open olive-colored shirt, told the invited
guests that the high court jurists will interpret the Constitution
``for the next 30 or 40 years _ until you're my age,'' adding:
``You have a lot riding on whether or not civil rights, equal
rights, women's rights are protected in the philosophical choices
made by the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTV video introduction of Gore said, in part: ``He listened
to rock, rode a motorcycle and even smoked the herb.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said in the past that he occasionally smoked marijuana
in his younger days.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been invited to make a similar appearance but has not
yet accepted, an MTV spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll for MTV found that only 46 percent of Americans
aged 18 to 24 said they planned to vote on Nov. 7 _ compared to 64
percent of older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The MTV website featured a click-and-vote poll offering
respondents a chance to answer the question: ``Al Gore most reminds
me of? The choices included: ``My high school guidance counselor;
my Dad; the captain of my school's debate team; a traveling
salesman; or other.''
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their barnstorming, Bush and Gore launched competing
campaign ads. Bush's ad said that 58 percent of 4th grade students
in the nation's low-income schools ``can't read,'' calling that
evidence of ``an education recession in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the 54-year-old second term governor of Texas told voters
in the ad that ``if we really want to make sure no child gets left
behind in America, we need the courage to raise standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ad builds upon an campaign ad being aired in 17 states by
the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hit the television airwaves as well with a new 30-second
advertisement entitled ``Veteran'' that highlights the 52-year-old
Tennessean's service in Vietnam and his devotion to his wife of 30
years and his four children. The ad cites Gore's support to a tax
break for college tuition, welfare reform, a crime victims' bill of
rights and protecting children from violence ant the Internet,
added: ``Al Gore, he'll put his values to work for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM _ STORY MAY END HERE
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The parties' vice presidential candidates pressed their cases as
well.
</P>
<P>
   __ GOP running mate Dick Cheney said in Troy, Mich., that Gore
had ``failed to speak the truth'' on a variety of subjects _
particularly by offering ``distorted and demagogic''
characterizations of Bush proposal to provide prescription drug
coverage to senior citizens. Cheney's latest attack followed his
criticism of Gore on Monday for an alleged conflict of interest
because the vice president had favored continuing a moratorium on
royalties that U.S. companies pay to drill for natural gas in the
Gulf of Mexico. A Gore family trust owns stock in the Occidental
Petroleum Corp., a firm that benefits from the moratorium, said
Cheney, the former head of the oil field services firm Halliburton
Corp. Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway rejected Cheney's criticism,
saying: `When the facts about the issues aren't convenient to the
Bush campaign, they resort to negative personal attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Democratic vice presidential candidate Joe Lieberman pressed
the Democrats' message of the day in Union, N.J., telling senior
citizens at a facility that serves 700 seniors a week that a
Gore-Lieberman administration would ``protect Medicare for at least
another 30 years'' and provide senior citizens ``more choices for
their health care so they are never left powerless and broke.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wire service reports contributed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
