<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-LABOR-(TRIMS)     09-26 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LABOR-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LABOR CONVENTION, BLAIR ACCEPTS BLAME FOR PARTY'S DROP IN
POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIGHTON, England _ Prime Minister Tony Blair took personal
blame Tuesday for government actions that have sent the Labor
Party's resilient poll ratings plummeting this month, but he urged
the party to have confidence that it would defeat the Conservatives
and win a second term in the election expected in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the prime minister that's supposed to be the great reader
of public opinion,'' he said at the party's annual convention in
this English Channel resort in a speech aimed at restoring his
battered reputation. ``After the events of two weeks ago, it's no
wonder the government has taken a knock. It happened on my watch,
and I take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair was referring to a spontaneous fuel price protest by
farmers and truckers that attracted widespread public support and
provoked broad criticism of Blair _ who has long been credited with
having his finger on the public pulse _ for being highhanded and
out of touch. ``I am listening,'' he said pointedly, ``I hear, and
I will act.''
</P>
<P>
   He also conceded that two other high-profile moves had been
mistakes: a 75 pence ($1.10) increase last year in the weekly state
pension, which was scorned by recipients as miserly, and the
government's pet Millennium Dome project in London, which has drawn
far fewer people and cost far more money than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``75p,'' he said, uttering the words that have become the
protest chant of pensioners, who now make up nearly 25 percent of
the British electorate. ``I tell you now,'' Blair said, ``we get
the message.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the dome, he commented, ``Hindsight is a wonderful thing,
and if I had my time again I would have listened to those who said
governments shouldn't try to run big visitor attractions.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates to what was supposed to have been a rally to kick
off an election campaign have been bewildered at their party's
swift loss of public approval, and they enthusiastically greeted
Blair's unaccustomed expressions of contrition. ``Yes,'' he said to
an outburst of applause, ``there are things we have done that have
made people angry and we should be open enough, honest enough to
admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Blair delivered his address vigorously, with sweat visibly
staining the front of his blue shirt and running down his forehead.
He spoke with the furrowed-brow intensity, distant visionary gaze
and trembling voice that have roused the faithful in the past while
bringing scorn from critics who mock his oratorical skills as more
suitable for the pulpit than the stump.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the hall was upbeat, with delegates clapping their
hands before Blair's arrival to the rhythmic conference theme song,
Canned Heat's ``Let's Work Together.'' Many of them had been
dismayed at reports of cabinet infighting and bickering between
Blair and Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, the
second-most-powerful man in the government.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Blair is expected to call the next election for May, and
Tuesday's speech was filled with campaign-style attacks on the
Tories, who have found themselves ahead of Labor in the polls this
month for the first time since 1992. The Conservative leader,
William Hague, has sought to capitalize on the recent Labor
blunders, but Blair dismissed the sudden gains as transitory.
``Opportunism always knocks for Mr. Hague,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair proclaimed a long list of social progress accomplishments
by Labor and contended that the Conservatives had opposed all of
them and would reverse them if voted back into power. He portrayed
himself as a ``unifier, a builder of consensus'' and Hague as
someone seeking short-term advantage by dividing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want me to go out and exploit the asylum issue for
reasons of race,'' he said in a biting reference to Conservative
calls for immigration restrictions, ``then vote for the other man,
because I won't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Labor's rout of the Tories in 1997, Blair has devoted his
conference addresses to warning the party of the responsibilities
of managing success and the dangers of triumphalism and
complacency. Tuesday, he had the very different mission of
restoring Labor's confidence in its prospects for re-election _
considered a certainty until the recent fall in popularity _ and
repairing his own standing with the growing number of critics,
including many in his own party, who find him smug and
sanctimonious.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was not arrogance but the need to make tough choices
that held him back from responding directly to the fuel protesters'
demand for tax breaks and the pensioners' call for greater
participation in Britain's current prosperity. He said he would
never sacrifice public services for a voter-pleasing tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an arrogant government that chooses priorities,'' he
said. ``It's an irresponsible government that fails to choose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
