<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-BOXING-ARCHDEACON     09-26 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOXING-ARCHDEACON0927 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuban star gives Bennett a pounding
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - He had just fought Felix Savon _ the Cuban icon who may
well be one of the greatest heavyweights of all time _ and now
Michael Bennett was being asked if along with the punches he had
felt the historical and social weight of the bout.
</P>
<P>
   That's heady stuff for a boxer, but Bennett did his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``History does play a part, you know,'' the American heavyweight
said after his 91-kilogram quarter-final. ``When (President)
Kennedy had the option of pushing the button, I consider that a lot
of pressure. He didn't push the button and we're all here today.
And because of it, I'm happy and blessed and I was able to do
battle with a great warrior today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, the 29-year-old, smooth-domed captain of the U.S.
boxing team, and Savon, the two-time Olympic gold medalist and
six-time world champ, met Tuesday afternoon in what was billed as
one of the marquee match-ups of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The bout wasn't two minutes old when Bennett realized he had his
own Cuban Missile Crisis. He was feeling the pressure as the
6-foot-6 Savon peppered him with jabs, stood him up with some solid
right hands and quickly built a big lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett needed to push the button and could not. Because of it,
he is not here today.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was stopped with three seconds left in the third round
after Savon went head 23-8 and the referee invoked the 15-point
rule.
</P>
<P>
   With Bennett eliminated, Savon is a step closer to becoming only
the third Olympic boxer in history to win three gold medals.
Hungarian middleweight Lazlo Papp did it a half century ago and
Cuban heavyweight Teofilo Stevenson ruled in 1972, 1976 and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stevenson, the 33-year-old Savon towers over Cuban boxing
and life in his sports-fueled nation. Long ago, Fidel Castro
learned the athletic fields and arenas were the one level
battlefield where Cubans could compete with the arch enemy ``Yankee
Imperialists.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports became a source of pride, propaganda and proficiency in
communist Cuba. It was best shown in baseball, though boxing has
run a close second. Since the 1972 Olympic Games in Munich _ and
that's with boycotting the 1984 and 1988 Olympics _ the island
nation has won 23 gold medals in boxing, including seven of 12 in
Barcelona and four in Atlanta in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Savon was the star of the past two Olympiads, which is why
Castro held a special ceremony at the Karl Marx Theater in Havana
last month. Presenting the heavyweight with the national flag he
wanted him to carry into the Opening Ceremonies in Sydney, the
Cuban president called Savon ``a true revolutionary warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   At the World Championships in Houston in July 1999, it was Savon
who led a ringside protest after fellow Cuban Juan Hernandez lost
the title to a Russian on a terrible decision. Although ready to go
into the ring for his own title fight against Bennett, Savon
grabbed a Cuban flag and led his teammates in a march around the
ring
</P>
<P>
   Savon refused to fight unless the outcome was changed. It was
not, so Savon forfeited to Bennett. Five months later, the decision
was reversed. Hernandez got his title and the judges of the bout
were suspended for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Castro holds the heavyweight in special favor because he
continually refuses to be lured by foreign promoters trying to get
him to defect and turn pro. While he admitted he never has held as
much as $1,000 in his hands, he wanted nothing to do with Mexican
fight brokers who reportedly offered him $10 million to fight Mike
Tyson. In 1993, he was offered $5 million to defect in Puerto Rico.
In Atlanta, he was offered more and promoter Don King is said to
have a standing multimillion-dollar offer for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not everything,'' Savon has said in Cuban newspapers.
``He who abandons his fatherland has no love for anything in life
and there is no more beautiful family than the country where you
were born.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been well-documented, that mindset isn't always shared by
fellow Cubans. Whether it was due to political oppression,
barebones living conditions or the lure of money just 90 miles
away, many athletes have fled Cuba in the past decade. Several
defectors are now playing Major League Baseball and a few others
are dotting the rosters of various other Olympic teams here.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the 1996 Olympics, two top boxers _ Olympic gold
medalist Joel Cassamayor and world champ Ramon Garbay _ fled the
Cuban team. At the 1999 Pan American Games in Winnipeg, 11 athletes
and a coach defected.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the 241 Cuban athletes headed to Sydney were given a
special warning before leaving the island. As was reported by
foreign journalists, Felix Perez Roque, the Cuban foreign minster,
told the team: ``Each one of you must get ready to face aggression,
harassment, blackmail attempts and bribery. If anyone is thinking
of betraying his people, stabbing the fatherland, now or later,
that person will be incapable of looking us in the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett had a lot to gain with a victory. Not only would an
upset of Savon propel him toward the gold medal and launch a
much-hyped pro career, it would turn his life story into an instant
movie. Few athletes have a more colorful storyline than the
one-time small college football player from Chicago
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he hooked up with a shotgun carrying buddy, who robbed
a Toys-R-Us store. The other guy was caught and turned in Bennett,
who was dubbed ``The Toy Store Bandit.'' He got a 26-year prison
sentence that appeals reduced to 15 years. Good behavior got him
released after seven years.
</P>
<P>
   During his incarceration, he learned how to box and some 19
months after his July 1998 release, he was named the captain of the
U.S. Olympic boxing team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been given a second chance and I'll make the most of
it,'' he promised when he got to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bout, U.S. coach Tom Mustin said he felt Savon was
slipping, a claim that made Cuban coach Alcides Sagarrin laugh:
``Bennett is not a problem. The Americans did a lot of talking
before Atlanta and Barcelona, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
