<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. to face old nemesis Norway for women's soccer gold
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The U.S. women's soccer team arrived here after playing
at satellite venues and will face Norway
</P>
<P>
   today in the gold-medal match. It would be hard to find more
evenly
</P>
<P>
   matched, or familiar, rivals at the Olympics in any sport.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. squad, the reigning Olympic and World Cup champion,
began this
</P>
<P>
   tournament by beating Norway 2-0 before the Olympic torch was
even lit.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we played them I knew we would see them again,'' said
U.S. star
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm. ``They're a championship team, they
</P>
<P>
   have a lot of pride. They have a lot of personality players, and
it's no
</P>
<P>
   surprise to me that they've made it to the final. It's going to
be a
</P>
<P>
   difficult game, a hard-fought game.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier Olympic win for the United States merely evened the
score
</P>
<P>
   for the year at 3-3-1 between the two teams. The all-time series
stands
</P>
<P>
   14-13-2 in favor of Norway, the only team in the world to enjoy
an edge
</P>
<P>
   on the much publicized U.S. women. With each team knowing each
other's
</P>
<P>
   style and players so well, you might expect a chess match on
grass, but
</P>
<P>
   Hamm doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can throw all the tactics out the window,'' Hamm said. ``I
think
</P>
<P>
   it's going to come down to 90 minutes of who wants it more.
We've seen
</P>
<P>
   everything there is to see out of each other ... This game is
not
</P>
<P>
   about preparation; it's not about tactics. It's about will.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States certainly has done fine in that department.
The squad was lumped in the so-called ``Group of Death''
</P>
<P>
   bracket with Norway, China and Nigeria. China was the odd soccer
super
</P>
<P>
   power out as the United States and Norway advanced to the
semifinals to
</P>
<P>
   face teams from the easier bracket, one that contained a
disappointing
</P>
<P>
   Australian team. Norway beat Germany 1-0, and the United States
had its
</P>
<P>
   typically contentious match with Brazil in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   That game produced 41 fouls, four yellow cards for each team and
only
</P>
<P>
   one goal. Hamm's record 127th goal in international play was the
edge,
</P>
<P>
   but the Brazilians made her pay for it. Three of their four
yellow cards
</P>
<P>
   were picked up trying to contain _ or intimidate _ her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a physical game and at different levels you're going to
have to
</P>
<P>
   expect that, and you're going to have to deal with it,'' Hamm
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times it rattled us, but I think for the most part
we kind
</P>
<P>
   of endured and we got the result we wanted. It wasn't the
prettiest
</P>
<P>
   soccer, but we're in the final game. Hopefully we can just put
things
</P>
<P>
   together for one more game and get the result that we want.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I feel good. I think we've been very fortunate with
the
</P>
<P>
   health of everyone through this tournament so far. We need
everyone
</P>
<P>
   healthy to compete against Norway.''
</P>
<P>
   Although goalkeeper Siri Mullinix had only two saves against
Brazil, in
</P>
<P>
   the 70th minute she was able to deflect an attempt by Roseli,
knocking
</P>
<P>
   it wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one big save I had to make, and I made it'' Mullinix
said. ``I
</P>
<P>
   think that's what goalkeeping is about at the international
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the absence of retired Michelle Akers, Mullinix
</P>
<P>
   may be the most noticeable on-field change from the squad that
won the
</P>
<P>
   World Cup. She's replaced Briana Scurry as the starter in goal
and
</P>
<P>
   teammates seem to have accepted that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big thing that helped was that I was with the team
in '99
</P>
<P>
   training for the World Cup. At least they knew what I could do;
they
</P>
<P>
   knew who I was. They'd seen me play, at least in training,''
Mullinix
</P>
<P>
   said.
</P>
<P>
   She has already played several games against Norway and in one
had an
</P>
<P>
   outstanding performance. She said, ``They're a very direct style
team and
</P>
<P>
   they have two great forwards. They play a lot of long balls so
we're
</P>
<P>
   going to be aware of that, but we've worked with that all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway's Marianne Pettersen has two goals this tournament but
U.S.
</P>
<P>
   coach April Heinrichs has heaped praise on Hege Riise, saying
``Riise is
</P>
<P>
   a winner and the kind of player I would have on my team any day.
She
</P>
<P>
   finds ways to win. She's thoughtful and crafty, and I love the
way she
</P>
<P>
   plays.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also impressed with Norway's keeper, Bente Nordby.
</P>
<P>
   The United States., which beat Brazil in Canberra, is only now
getting to Sydney and experiencing the Olympic atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs said, ``There's a certain part of me that likes the
fact that
</P>
<P>
   at times it doesn't feel like the Olympics because we're on the
</P>
<P>
   outskirts. Then, it's just like any other tournament. Then it's
us
</P>
<P>
   against Norway. The outside factors don't come into play. As a
coach,
</P>
<P>
   those are some of the things you don't want to come into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm added, ``It's been difficult for us to feel the Olympic
fever
</P>
<P>
   because we've been at a satellite venue. But we've been watching
and
</P>
<P>
   following all the athletes involved. It's an athlete's dream to
</P>
<P>
   participate in the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. team is finally in Sydney, it's not in the
athletes'
</P>
<P>
   village.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 20 players and we could only have one house,'' said
midfielder
</P>
<P>
   Julie Foudy. ``We like each other, but not that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the team is staying in a hotel. The veteran Foudy
played every
</P>
<P>
   minute in the team's march to gold in Atlanta. Of the 1996
</P>
<P>
   Olympics she said, ``It was wonderful for us because that was
like a
</P>
<P>
   coming out party. It kind of started things.''
</P>
<P>
   The team now feels a responsibility to keep that momentum going
and to
</P>
<P>
   promote the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team, the Norwegian team, the Chinese team, want to
display the
</P>
<P>
   game the best way we know how. I think you're seeing a higher
level of
</P>
<P>
   soccer every single year, and not just from a couple of teams
but from a
</P>
<P>
   wide variety of teams,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   But two teams, the only ones to ever win a Women's World Cup,
have
</P>
<P>
   proved the class of the field. It's Norway vs. the U.S. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
