<SLUG> BC-NETWORLD0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Start-ups shopping for attention at Networld
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - More than 550 companies this week set up shop at
Networld+Interop, hawking their wares _ hard and soft _ with loud
music, giveaways and multimedia presentations as part of the show
drawing an estimated 50,000 to the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   At the far corner of the East Wing, down a ways from Cisco
Systems, Lucent Technologies and other multibillion-dollar
behomoths, is ``Start-Up City,'' a collection of low-rent booths.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their modest status, all want to be household names _ at
least in the homes of executives who buy technology.
</P>
<P>
   But what's in a name? Any company wants a name that will say
something about what it does, the service or product it hopes will
dominate some multibillion-dollar-a-year market. But you would also
love to have a name that grabs attention.
</P>
<P>
   YottaYotta Inc. thinks it has both.
</P>
<P>
   With about 40 employees, Kirkland, Wash.- based YottaYotta is
making storage systems for networks and companies that must handle
and stockpile huge amounts of data. YottaYotta has designed a
system meant to work faster as the amount of data increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our hardware, our software and our secret sauce,'' said
marketing chief Cindy Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage at Massachusetts-based OpenReach, said Vice
President David Kelly, is software that lets smaller companies have
the advantages of privacy when communicating among various
locations. Of course, OpenReach is not averse to a little
gratuitous attention either. Company employees at Networld+Interop
were wearing black T-shirts matched with mock camouflage pants of
orange, black and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   A range of technologies is on display in the East Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Radiata, for example, is a 45-worker San Jose, Calif., company
that is designing chips to be used in wireless networking devices.
Cereva is a Massachusetts company preparing a launch of optical
networking products.
</P>
<P>
   Giants like Cisco are often just looking to make sales, but what
newer entrants need more is exposure, said Jerry Caron, publisher
of Tele.com, a publication that covers the industry. ``Being seen
as participants, to say they are not still in the garage _ that is
very important. The see-and-being-seen is a soft benefit, but it's
tangible.''
</P>
<P>
   The cooling of Internet ardor has not dampened investor desire
for companies whose equipment and software makes Net commerce
easier or more efficient, he said. Cereva, for example, has raised
$66 million in two years. OpenReach has been given $21 million in
10 months since birth. And YottaYotta has drawn $24 million in less
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   That fervent interest in Net commerce is shared by $42
billion-a-year Hewlett-Packard, said chief executive Carly Fiorina,
who kicked off the conference Tuesday as keynote speaker. Ticking
off HP products, she told several thousand attendees that HP has
set out to adapt to the technology changes. ``We said that any
process, any asset, any application that could be digitized would
be and delivered over the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiorina, perhaps the highest-profile and most celebrated female
high-tech executive this year, said the moment is critical for all
the companies at Networld+Interop. ``I believe we are entering a
fundamentally different era in the Internet economy. I believe we
are entering the Renaissance of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
