<P>
   SPORTS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.27.00
</P>
<P>
   Typo leads surfers toward protest sites
</P>
<P>
   Kids' site offers more than Games
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME ONLINE: All stories and urls in this column are one
click away on ajc.com/enews
</P>
<P>
   WATCH FOR TYPOS: Visitors attempting to reach the official
Olympic Games Web site might get a surprise if their typing isn't
up to scratch. Australian activists, under the banner of the Sydney
Independent Media Centre, have nabbed the address www.olympisc.com
and are using it to promote a variety of causes, including
pro-squatting protests and aboriginal issues. ``The Sydney
Indymedia website will be a permanent record of our experience of
protesting the many social injustices highlighted and/or
exacerbated by the Olympics,'' the group announces on its site.
</P>
<P>
   www.olympisc.com
</P>
<P>
   SITE FOR KIDS: What's the best way for kids to keep up with the
Olympics? It might be Sports Illustrated For Kids' new site:
siforkids.com. The site features interactive games, trivia and
up-to-the-minute reports from Sydney. Kids can keep up with their
favorite Olympic athletes and events as well as test their
knowledge of Australian facts, battle kangaroos and create their
own fantasy Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   The SI For Kids Olympic site, located at http://www.sikids.com,
features the following:
</P>
<P>
   www.siforkids.com
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL FROM SYDNEY
</P>
<P>
   wparker(at)ajc.com 09/26/00 10:52 A.M.
</P>
<P>
   To: AJC readers
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Not a problem
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a problem.'' Three simple words that, when rolling off the
tongues of native Aussies, are more than a form of expression.
They're a promise to at least look into what the
customer/diner/weary Olympic traveler may have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's an order at a restaurant or the long, winding
directions a volunteer driver takes from the Sydney Airport to
Olympic Park, the overt friendliness of the locals is mystifying to
Americans used to just the opposite the opposite treatment in such
trying times. And almost always, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians are 19 million people who, for the most part,
are thrilled that the world is here. Despite the myriad
inconveniences. The talkative driver going on endlessly about his
``best mate'' in Florida and the cheerful late-night youth making a
special ``flat white'' at the coffee machine in the media village
pub have made such a long trip, and long day after long day, not
only bearable, but enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   Before these Games are over, I promise to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendy Parker
</P>
<P>
   DOWN UNDER DIARY
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad &AMP; Tobago sprinter Ato Boldon, who won a silver medal in
the 100, tells NBCOlympics.com he's confident of gold in his next
event:
</P>
<P>
   ``The 200 is mine to lose. Competitors have interesting things
to say, but I will save all my talking until Thursday night. And if
everything goes the way I plan, I don't expect it to be close.''
</P>
<P>
   www.nbcolympics.com
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE 09.27.00
</P>
