<HEADER>
A2550 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ROLLS0927-COX     09-26 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLS0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secret of browning put mid-century doughboys in the black
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The story of a classic American comfort
food begins with a false fire alarm, makes its way through a
Dumpster and is retold _ 51 years after it started _ in a suburban
Lantana kitchen by a retiree who helped create a minor baking
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should almost know they're ready by the smell,'' said Jules
Jacobsen, agreeing to brown 'n serve a batch of Brown 'N Serve
dinner rolls. ``They should begin to smell like fresh bread baking.
Then you got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven to 10 minutes later, Jacobsen pulls a pan from the oven,
raises one of the crisp rolls to his nostrils and breaks it open.
It looks and smells right, but it's too brittle. The package,
supplied by his guests, has no expiration date printed on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take 'em back. Get your money back,'' he says, disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare moment of bread-related frustration for Jacobsen,
who used the soft white rolls to secure a small place in American
culinary history.
</P>
<P>
   When the story begins, in 1940s America, there was no microwave
popcorn, no Taco Bell Chalupas. Only 25 percent of married women
worked outside the home, compared with 62 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, an Air Force gunnery instructor, made friends with a
cook named Joe Gregor. After they were discharged, both men settled
in Avon Park, a small town northwest of Lake Okeechobee where they
had been stationed during service.
</P>
<P>
   Gregor, a former milkman, opened a bakery, but he was attracting
only five or six customers a day. His rolls cooled too quickly,
customers told him. People wanted them hot for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Night after night, Jacobsen and Gregor would discuss ways to
cook the rolls partially, using chemicals or shorter cooking times.
Nothing worked. The gluten _ needed to keep the dough from folding
_ didn't have time to set if the rolls weren't cooked long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gregor, a volunteer firefighter, heard an alarm. He threw
his apron aside and yanked some half-baked rolls from the oven. It
was a brush fire, so the other firefighters said he could forget
about it and return to the bakery.
</P>
<P>
   On his work table, he found what he and Jacobson had been
searching for: partially cooked rolls that browned easily with a
few more minutes in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   But the two men couldn't figure out why the rolls held their
form _ until they bought an oven thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   The oven was leaking more than 100 degrees of heat, they
discovered, cooking the rolls only at 275 degrees instead of the
typical 450.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the whole secret,'' Jacobsen said.
</P>
<P>
   At this temperature, the gluten sets, but the sugar doesn't get
hot enough to caramelize and turn brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too simple. It was an accident,'' Jacobsen says, still smiling
at the memory. ``It wasn't brilliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, a promoter and advertiser, became Gregor's partner. He
packaged and gave out samples of ``Pop-N-Oven'' rolls to grocery
store clerks and their bosses, newspaper reporters, customers and
the Publix supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, 18 months after they started, the men were selling all
the rolls they could fit in the rumble seats of their cars, baking
two days a week and delivering on the other five. The regional
sales director for General Mills, who lived in nearby Tampa, sent a
batch to headquarters in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked at these pale, anemic-looking rolls in their
kitchen and threw them out,'' Jacobsen said.
</P>
<P>
   The salesman called quality control and demanded the product
testers dig the rolls out of the Dumpster, brown them and eat them.
</P>
<P>
   By the time negotiations with General Mills ended, Jacobsen and
Gregor sold rights to the rolls for $60,000. Jacobsen recalls a
period of intense secrecy. General Mills called the rolls ``Project
49'' and made the few employees with knowledge sign secrecy
pledges, according to a 1949 issue of the Minneapolis Sunday
Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen said the phone company told him his phone was being
tapped. A rival bread company? Jacobsen thinks so, but acknowledges
he can't prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives spirited the men to Atlanta for three days of
intense questioning. They couldn't sit together on the plane or
leave their hotel for meals. When it was over, they went to a
department store where executives bought Gregor's wife a pearl
necklace and Jacobsen's a silver dinner set.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills used the men's story to promote the new product in
ads and national newspaper stories. The company took professional
pictures of their happy, suburban families eating Brown 'N Serve
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But the images faded when Gregor filed suit, claiming the rolls
were his idea and Jacobsen didn't deserve half the proceeds. The
friendship ended.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen said company executives testified on his behalf, and,
after an 18-month trial, a judge awarded Gregor $31,000 and
Jacobsen $29,000. Gregor has since died, and the court records
could not be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills did not keep its Brown 'N Serve monopoly. Instead,
the company sent thermometers and instruction books on how to make
the rolls to commercial bakers around the country, hoping to boost
flour sales. Company archivist Katie Dishman said General Mills
probably stopped selling its own Brown 'N Serve rolls in the 1960s
or 1970s, but she could not pinpoint an exact date. Supermarkets
and several national companies continue to package their own brands
of Brown 'N Serve rolls. The rolls, in some small way, helped
change America. They were among the first products that allowed
regular people to serve restaurant-quality food at home without
labor-intensive baking, said David Pursglove, a Washington, D.C.,
analyst who has predicted food trends since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right in there along with the microwave oven,'' Pursglove
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, 81, went on to make a lot more money on another trend
_ suburban newspaper publishing. He sold the weekly North Jersey
Suburbanite in 1986 for millions. (He won't say how many.)
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Manalapan 27 years ago, then the Lantana area last
year. He admits he doesn't eat Brown 'N Serve rolls on a regular
basis, but every now and again he'll pick up a package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's All-American. It really is. A couple of GI's, pretty
stupid, dumb, falling into something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff researchers Sammy Alzofon and Geni Guseila contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   noahbierman(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
