<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2551 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WOMENS-MAGAZINES0927-     09-26 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENS-MAGAZINES0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUY ME, BUY ME, BUY ME!
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Three seconds.
</P>
<P>
   She figures that's how long she's got to grab you by the collar
and make you reach for your wallet. She uses the big guns: direct
eye contact, a bewitching smile and whispered promises of money,
power and sex. If she's successful, you leave the store with her
under your arm _ a glossy women's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The first magazine that shoppers pick up is more than likely the
one they end up buying, says Mandi Norwood, Mademoiselle's new
editor in chief. ``Your covers have to be making so much more noise
than anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just more visual racket than fellow women's titles such
as Glamour, Marie Claire, Jane or Cosmopolitan. ``Everything with a
front and back cover is a competitor. We live in such a
time-deprived world.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood joined Mademoiselle earlier this year after editing
three British magazines. She felt that Mademoiselle had devolved
into something generic. There was nothing unique, irresistible or
compelling about it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And so she and her colleagues gave the 65-year-old magazine _
the magazine credited with creating the makeover _ a makeover. It
joins Harper's Bazaar, National Geographic, Mother Jones and George
on the list of titles that have recently gone under the X-Acto
knife. Here are some of the tweaks the Mademoiselle team made to
its cover:
</P>
<P>
   The Magazine for Your Me Years _The target readership of
Mademoiselle ranges from 18 to 35, with a focus on 20- to
30-year-olds who are living in their ``Me Years.'' Those are the
years after college but before family, ``when you have time and
money to spend only on yourself,'' says the 35-year-old Norwood,
who is married and has two children. ``This time is absolutely
unique, and I felt like there wasn't a magazine out there
addressing it.''
</P>
<P>
   99% guilt free _ ``I like it because it gives the cover a
three-dimensional feel.'' Plus, it's a joke on women's obsession
with fat-free foods.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of model _ Mademoiselle has moved away from using
pure entertainers on its covers (its three previous cover subjects
were Minnie Driver, Neve Campbell and members of pop group TLC) to
models who act or host TV shows, ``multidimensional girls,''
Norwood says. James King has three starring roles in three new
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to be said for a picture of a girl who kind of
embodies the spirit of your magazine rather than a celebrity who
looks miserable,'' Norwood says. ``She has an ease about her, a
confidence. She looks sexy, she looks positive.
</P>
<P>
   When she's selecting a cover shot, Norwood looks for the
``tingle factor,'' she says. ``It's when you look at a picture and
it makes the sides of your face tingle.''
</P>
<P>
   Change of typeface _
</P>
<P>
   The new typeface ``looks cleaner, warmer, happier, friendlier,''
Norwood says. Its more rounded lines are like ``a happy smiling
face.... The appeal of magazines works on so many different
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Use of numbers _ ``It certainly beats putting, `Inside, a lot of
stuff.' It's a way of being really specific, and it gives a feeling
of value.''
</P>
<P>
   Naughty phrases _ The new Mademoiselle comes with a new attitude
of cheekiness, Norwood says. Cover lines from the last three
issues: ``14 rules we want you to break _ today!'' ``Be very bad
and get away with it every time'' and ``You got a promotion!
Coincidence or bitchcraft?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that there's a sense of mischief. Each one of us has
our own sense of playfulness and mischief. It just makes life more
fun. This gives people permission to live by their own rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It assumes a certain amount of self-confidence to start with.
Some other magazines perpetuate the myth of women analyzing and
agonizing. Women out there know what they want. They're getting up
in the morning and saying, 'Hello, world!'''
</P>
<P>
   The Sex Best Thing _ ``Young women are having sex, so it would
be ridiculous for us to do a magazine that didn't address sex
because it would be ignoring an important part of a woman's life,''
says Norwood, adding that magazines are the biggest and best
communicators of information on sex. She feels it's Mademoiselle's
duty to address those issues, with responsibility. ``Can you ever
know too much about sex? Probably not.'' However, Mademoiselle is
``not about the nitty-gritty of sex.... We like to be a little more
creative with our sex coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Million-dollar hair for under $30 _ Using a dollar amount is
another way to convey value, Norwood says. ``During the Me Years,
you want more bang for your buck. You want every single dollar to
go a million miles.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of ``you'' and ``me'' _ Using the words ``you'' and
``me'' makes the cover as personal as possible. ``Magazines are
very intimate purchases, almost like underwear,'' Norwood says.
``You don't want to feel like everyone's tried it on before you.''
</P>
<P>
   Peep Show _ ``We like men. Men are good,'' Norwood says. ``Women
are fascinated at this time in their lives with what men are
thinking. 'What is he doing when he's not with me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Wed Dreams _ Different approaches to tired topics, a focus on
lively writing. ``For a long time, women's magazines have been
accused of not having a sense of humor. If I can make people smile
or giggle, that's going to keep them coming back for more,''
Norwood says. ``Although perish the thought that we would be a
female Maxim.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: staci sturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
