<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-EURO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTING THE EURO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAST WEEK'S coordinated effort by central banks to shore up the
exchange value of Europe's new currency, the euro, confirms the
importance attached to stabilizing rates among the major
currencies. The effort, combining American and Japanese purchases
of the euro along with those of the European Central Bank, was at
least temporarily effective. Still, systemic changes will have to
be made in the European economy to place the euro on a sounder
base.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two years of existence, the euro has fallen more
than 25 percent, from $1.17 when it was launched at the beginning
of 1999 to 85 cents just prior to the intervention. The decline was
unexpected because Europe's economy is performing reasonably well.
Unemployment rates, while high in Germany and other countries in
comparison with America, are coming down. Inflation is low.
Business is generally brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Although Europeans have embraced new technology, elements in the
economy remain fairly rigid. Labor mobility _ willingness (or
necessity) to move from job to job _ has not matched American
performance and is hampered by cultural and language barriers that
make such moves more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   This helps explain the export of European capital to purchase
assets elsewhere that look more attractive than others at home. The
shift of assets deprives Europeans of maximum efficiencies and
simultaneously puts further pressure on the value of the euro. Much
of the outflow has come to America _ more than $80 billion in 1999,
immediately following arrival of the euro, and only slightly less
is forecast for all of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, Americans benefit from the flow of capital. It
means more investment in job-producing industries and businesses
and, above all, in further technological gains. In the long term,
however, Americans have to worry about a weak euro because it
inhibits Europeans' ability to buy American goods and services and
makes European goods and services more competitive in other
markets. Hence the American willingness to try to bolster the
exchange rate of the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is a long way from facing a crisis, though political
reaction to rising petroleum prices, exacerbated by the decline in
the euro, was quite strident. Making basic adjustments is a slow
process under the best of circumstances. But a strong European
economy is good for everyone, and a strong euro is both an
indicator and a contributor to it, just as a strong dollar has
helped both expand the American economy and shield it from
inflation during its long expansion. The central banks'
intervention may be most important for reminding everyone of those
fundamental facts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0288 </DOCNO>
