A2556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-POLIO-BOS &LR;      09-26 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-POLIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDING POLIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ERADICATION of polio is so close that it would be a tragedy
for humankind if this crippling disease were allowed to linger in
isolated pockets of the world. The United Nations agencies and
private organizations involved in the campaign need to redouble
their efforts to make sure the new 2005 deadline is met.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations had announced that the disease would be gone
by the end of this year, but that projection was premature. A
meeting will be held at UN headquarters Wednesday to plan the
climactic phase of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other things intervened _ conflicts, HIV/AIDS, debilitated
health systems,'' said Carol Bellamy, executive director of UNICEF,
explaining the missed deadline. If the UN and other international
organizations can eliminate smallpox, as they did in 1977, then
they can find the resources and the will to destroy the polio
virus.
</P>
<P>
   War is the prime reason for the failure to vaccinate children in
Angola and the Congo. Fighting is episodic, however, and
vaccination campaigns can go forward despite the poor highway and
communication systems. With enough money, personnel, and diplomatic
acumen to encourage combatants to declare a truce for polio
vaccination, the campaign ought to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win despite all the warring factions in the
world,'' said Bill Sargent of Rotary International, which has made
polio eradication a priority since 1988. ``Even they claim to be
concerned about children.'' A majority of the victims are under age
5.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the intractable AIDS epidemic, polio is an easily
solvable problem. The disease has been eradicated in the Western
Hemisphere, and only 1,148 cases were reported so far this year in
Asia and Africa. UNICEF and the World Health Organization are
committed to the campaign, as well as the US Centers for Disease
Control, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, and Rotary
International. Together these organizations have the clout and the
expertise to wipe out polio.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the UN meeting, the World Health Organization has
laid out an agenda for success. It calls for a series of National
Immunization Days, investigation of any paralysis cases for links
to polio, and mop-up immunization campaigns. The price of this
initiative exceeds $1 billion, and $450 million has yet to be
committed.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the UN meeting will make a fund-raising appeal
to foundations and other private donors Wednesday. The US
government, which has been generous in its support of the campaign
in the past, ought to make up any shortfall so that the 2005
deadline can be met. It's time to give polio a final push to
oblivion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
