<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-GIANTS-SERIES-HNS     09-26 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIANTS ARE AIMING FOR THE WORLD SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN SHEA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Giants want it all now. The World Series or
bust. If it's not a Fall Classic, in their minds, it'll be a
classic fall.
</P>
<P>
   After clinching the National League West last week, the Giants
made it known they wouldn't settle for anything less than a final
showdown with the New York Yankees, or any other team the American
League submits.
</P>
<P>
   But first there's this tiny matter of getting there, of winning
the first two rounds of the playoffs, of advancing past the mighty
Atlanta Braves, who appeared in five of the last eight World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who play at Dodger Stadium the next three nights,
are relatively new to October ball, especially late-October ball.
They made the 1997 playoffs but got bounced immediately. They were
in the 1989 World Series, but the only player from that team still
with the Giants is now their first-base coach, Robby Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to World Series experience, the Giants rank last
among the National League's four playoff teams _ pitchers Livan
Hernandez and Robb Nen played for the 1997 Florida Marlins, and
reliever Alan Embree was with the 1995 Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets list six players who appeared in a World
Series. The St. Louis Cardinals seven. The Braves have the most of
course, with 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important,'' manager Dusty Baker said. ``That's why the
Braves and Yankees have an advantage over everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Giants can say they have 13 players who've
participated in the playoffs (eight with their '97 team), but only
three have reached the World Series. In fact, the team has more
World Series rings on the coaching staff _ Baker, Thompson, Gene
Clines and Dave Righetti _ than the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream you don't want to wake up from,'' said Embree,
whose Indians fell to Atlanta in six games. ``From the first time I
began warming up, the adrenaline rush didn't end. I could tell you
everything about each of my (four) appearances. What happened, who
I faced, what the count was, who went in after me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only bad thing about a World Series is it goes by so fast,
you hardly realize you're in it. When it's over, you ask, 'What do
you mean it's over?'''
</P>
<P>
   Baker has great World Series memories of his three appearances
with the Dodgers, all against the Yankees, but he has no plans to
throw the Baseball Encyclopedia at his players. He'd prefer they
savor it themselves. And if anyone should say anything, it should
be the three pitchers who've been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easier for them to relay the feelings than for
me. They've been there more recently,'' Baker said. ``It helps if
you've had pitchers in the World Series because pitchers have the
most control of a game, and we have three. That's huge. i don't
want to psyche them out. I'd prefer to let them experience it. It's
like going to Vietnam. If you've never been there, no one can tell
you about it. You'd have to experience it for yourself. Until you
get to a World Series and feel the energy and vibrations, you have
no idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
