<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-WOMEN27-COX     09-26 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-WOMEN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Female executives are common on the `soft side' of business
 &HT;    By Caroline Hubbard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Trisha Harris arranged name tags before a
PTEKVentures networking party, she noticed only a few women's names
in the pile.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, vice president of communications at PTEK Holdings, was
surprised, despite being the only woman corporate vice president at
PTEK. She knows that PTEK's venture arm has yet to invest in a
woman entrepreneur. She knows that almost every woman she meets in
the Atlanta technology scene is in marketing, public relations or
human resources _ the ``soft'' side of the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she was surprised.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``new economy'' _ where executives are younger, dress
hipper and make decisions at Internet speed _ it is easy to forget
that one thing is pretty much the same: women's roles.
</P>
<P>
   Women for the most part aren't running Atlanta's new technology
companies or investing in them.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this phenomenon are hard to nail down. Some cite
discrimination, albeit subtle. Others argue that most women just
aren't interested in technology.
</P>
<P>
   The PTEK configuration is mirrored at technology companies all
over town. At Internet consulting firm iXL Enterprises, women head
public relations and human resources. But the chief executive,
chief operating officer and chief technology officer are all men.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeff Levy launched trendy incubator eHatchery last year, he
did it with men as chief operating officer, chief technology
officer and chief financial officer. Women were in charge of
facilities management, public relations and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the executives who are successfully launching their own
ventures also are men. Nationally, women headed only 4 percent of
IT companies that raised venture capital in 1999, according to
research group VentureOne. Just 40 percent of the IT companies that
raised capital in 1999 had at even one woman on their managment
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Though VentureOne doesn't break its gender data down by region,
experts suspect that Atlanta has even fewer female entrepreneurs
and start-up executives than other high-tech hotbeds.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, established technology companies churn out
female executives qualified to start their own companies, said Amy
Millman, executive director of the National Women's Business
Council. ``They have just been doing it longer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More women are entrepreneurs in places like San Francisco and
Boston because female venture capitalists hand out money in those
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Brosseau, president and co-founder of the Foundation of
Women Entrepreneurs in San Francisco, said that men are more likely
to fund men. She points to a study from National Foundation of
Women Business Owners that says 67 percent of female investors have
invested in women-led companies, versus only 40 percent of men
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about how the process is done, venture
capitalists fund people they know, people in their network, people
they went to school with, people they play basketball with,'' she
said. ``The good news is that once investors fund a woman-led
company, they are twice as likely to fund another.'' VentureOne
recently put out a list of the 33 most active female venture
capitalists in the country. No one from Atlanta made the list.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few female venture capitalists are in Atlanta, and none
are at the city's big firms.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Herron is at Intelligent Systems, which typically invests
small chunks of money in early-stage companies.
</P>
<P>
   She's been investing in technology companies on behalf of
Intelligent Systems since 1990 and would like to mentor young
women. But, Herron said, she would not invest in a company based on
the gender of its founders.
</P>
<P>
   As a venture capitalist, Herron has never felt men were
discriminating against her, she said. ``Sometimes, (being a women)
is an advantage because you stand out, as long as you are
credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Atlanta's top venture capitalists _ men like Alan Taetle
at Noro-Moseley Partners and Stephen Fleming at Alliance Technology
Ventures _ say they don't discriminate against women and, in fact,
wish there were more female entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl King, who is bucking the gender trend as chief financial
officer at software company Alogent, said she never feels openly
discriminated against. She gets plenty of calls from recruiters
trying to lure her to other companies. Still, she thinks being a
woman in a man's world is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to be one of only a handful,'' she said. ``When you
go to networking events, it is harder to go start conversations
when you are the only woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Women in Atlanta may voluntarily steer clear of technology
because it is such a male-dominated world, she said. ``It still
feels like an old-boys' network in some respects. It is always who
you know in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Tabor, who is trying to raise money for her
Atlanta-based online concierge service, Sparkfly, said men consider
a woman chief executive to be ``politically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``from a credibility standpoint, there have been
challenges,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts argue women don't get into technology because they
aren't encouraged in math and science in school. Many studies have
shown that girls tend to lose interest in such subjects during
middle school. At the Georgia Institute of Technology, the number
of female students still lags the number of males.
</P>
<P>
   Levy at eHatchery said he would love to hire more women but has
found few interested in becoming programmers or holding other tech
jobs. ``(The discrepancy) probably relates to the number of women
in graduate and undergraduate technology-based degree programs,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some women say they have stuck with ``soft'' jobs because they
don't want the hours that top executives typically work.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, women are a lot less likely to hold the
jobs with big salaries and large equity stakes.
</P>
<P>
   At a typical technology company in the IPO stage, the chief
executive officer makes $200,000 to $225,000 a year, and the chief
technology officer earns $140,000 to $165,000, according to Jim
Reda, a compensation consultant at Arthur Andersen in Atlanta.
Compare that to the corporate vice president of marketing, who
typically earns $105,000 to $130,000 and a vice president of human
resources who probably makes $70,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new economy soon may be more gender-balanced, experts agree.
Millman points back to the VentureOne statistics. In 1999, 40
percent of companies that got venture capital funding had at least
one woman on the management team. In 1997, that figure was 24
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a huge changeover,'' she said. ``In the next five
years, we are going to see a lot more women in (top) positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Herron said she sees more quality business plans from female
entrepreneurs in Atlanta these days. Some of these women likely
will be successful and will become role models and possibly
investors, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some technology leaders say they will work hard to encourage
more women to become entrepreneurs and high-tech executives. They
say women make good managers and that diverse management teams are
better at solving problems.
</P>
<P>
   Others claim to be gender-blind.
</P>
<P>
   Levy describes recruiting as a balancing act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is critical to have a diverse management team in
every respect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
