<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2560 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WORLDSPAN27-COX     09-26 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDSPAN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worldspan flying high as travel sites flourish
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As online travel agencies race to turn themselves into
flashy brands and household names, one Atlanta company is working
quietly behind the scenes and cashing in as more travelers turn
into Netheads.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever shopped for or bought an airline ticket through
the Web, chances are good you've visited a site powered by the
Worldspan booking engine, a massive hub of computers that processes
airline, hotel and rental-car reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a secret location in Atlanta, the Worldspan system now
handles 30 million airline reservations a year booked through
online agents, according to Worldspan, which also has headquarters
here. That's over half of all airline reservations made through
online agents.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to verify who leads in online agency bookings;
all data are supplied by the companies. Nonetheless, Worldspan's
client roster vouches for its claim. It books reservations for the
two most-visited travel sites: online agency Expedia.com and
name-your-own-price mammoth priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Orbitz, the travel agency owned by five top U.S.
airlines, will book via Worldspan after its launch next year. In
addition to the online agents, Worldspan powers the sites of its
three airline owners _ TWA, Northwest Airlines and Atlanta-based
Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet arrived as Worldspan needed a growth avenue apart
from its core business of supplying reservations systems and
services to traditional travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   The company was created in 1990 when Delta, Northwest and TWA
combined their scheduling and booking distribution systems. By that
time Sabre Inc. _ the largest computer reservations system company
based on revenue _ already had a head start among traditional
travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   Because Worldspan was slower to the starting gate, it was left
with just a sliver of the global travel agent market. The company
served 17,900 travel agencies locations worldwide, compared with
40,669 for Sabre as of June 1999, according to Global Distribution
Systems: Outlook for the 21st Century. In 1998, the Worldspan
system booked just 12 percent of all reservations made by travel
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the Internet as a clean slate,'' said Paul J. Blackney,
Worldspan president and chief executive. ``At one point, travel
agents booked between 80 and 85 percent of travel ... but business
is shifting to other channels that tend to be electronic. We wanted
to to be in the emerging part of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing the top spot, the company pounced on this new breed of
customers. The first big client was Expedia; later priceline
decided to use the Worldspan system to sift through the fares of
its airline partners.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the Worldspan engine works online: a cybershopper
logs on to an online agent, types in her destination and travel
dates and then hits enter. The site connects with Worldspan, which
searches through all participating airline itineraries for fares.
Within 10 seconds, the information is listed for the traveler, who
then selects the itinerary. Once a flight is chosen, Worldspan
books the ticket with the airline and creates an itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   As Worldspan was busy signing up online customers for its
reservation systems, competitors were creating their own travel Web
sites. Sabre, for instance, built a powerhouse in Travelocity.com.
Though Worldspan toyed with the idea of starting its own booking
site, it ultimately decided to stay in the back-engine business
because it wouldn't have to compete with the Web sites it powered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They elected not to build their own brand, and that gave them
a real edge,'' said Chicke Fitzgerald, a consultant to Worldspan
and other computer reservations companies and author of Global
Distribution Systems. ``You don't have to spend to promote the
brand. It's a really prudent business model.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldspan employs 3,450 workers, 1,950 in Atlanta. The company's
corporate offices are in the Galleria, but it never discloses the
location of its computer systems. The massive spread of
refrigerator-sized computers is so vital to Worldspan there is no
logo on the windowless red brick building where it is housed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Worldspan took in $637.3 million in revenue, according
to Global Distribution Systems: Outlook for the 21st Century.
Because it is privately owned, Worldspan isn't obligated to release
earnings information. Blackney said it has posted profits for at
least six years with margins in the double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have had the company preparing for an initial public
offering, but according to Blackney the company ``has no definite
plans for an IPO.'' He declined to comment further other than to
add, ``I think it is fair to say every company at some point in
time would like access to the public capital markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, last year, when any company with remote Internet ties
held an initial public offering, Worldspan kept a low profile. With
what seems to be a solid financial situation and ties to the
Internet, Wall Street would likely welcome an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could certainly sell it to the public at a good price,
and there is no question what the story would be,'' said Nick
Moore, a money manager with California investment firm Jurika &AMP;
Voyles, which has invested in Sabre.
</P>
<P>
   However, Moore added that Worldspan isn't without risks because
some travel sites are structured in a way that would allow them to
switch reservation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Blackney has led Worldspan for just under a year, but he is no
stranger to the travel industry or to technology. He spent 31 years
at United Airlines, where he helped build Apollo, the airline's
computerized reservation system, and was named chief executive of
the division in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo later merged with rival Galileo, and with that, Blackney
decided to retire from the travel industry. His retirement was
short-lived; in the middle of a 10-month stint as a senior vice
president at the American Medical Association, a recruiter called
with an offer from Worldspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this as a tremendous opportunity to be there for one
more turn of the screw and one more revolution,'' he said. ``It was
just too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   But as in any revolution, some players are sure to die off.
Competition, access to funding and lack of brand awareness could
push 80 percent of travel Web sites out of business within five
years, according to Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Blackney agrees the market will weed out some of those clients
but thinks the big names, like priceline and Expedia, are survivors
_ and presumably so is Worldspan.
</P>
<P>
   The market, he said, will continue to shift to online bookings.
``It's up to the consumer to decide how they want to purchase
travel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the business was going to change, and we could embrace
it or we could fight it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
