<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-APPEAL-BOS &LR;      09-26 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-APPEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CATCHES A BREAK WITH OK ON APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's richest software company has bought itself some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the US Supreme Court court declined to immediately
review the high-stakes antitrust case filed against Microsoft Corp.
by the US Justice Department and 19 state attorneys general.
Instead, eight of the nine justices agreed the case should follow
the normal appellate process.
</P>
<P>
   That means Microsoft will get two chances to reverse the
stunning defeat handed the company by US District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   First, Microsoft will get to make its case before the DC Circuit
Court of Appeals, a respected legal panel that has taken
Microsoft's side in earlier skirmishes. Then, Microsoft or the
government can appeal to the Supreme Court, once the lower court
has ruled. In any case, the entire process could delay resolution
of the case by a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman, Jim Cullinan, denied that Microsoft was
eager to drag out the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said all along that, honestly, we believe our appeal
is very strong,'' Cullinan said, ``and think whether it was heard
by the Court of Appeals or the Supreme Court, the District Court's
ruling would be reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Boston antitrust lawyer, Lisa Wood, said Microsoft has
good reason to keep the process moving in slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives them longer to compete in an unregulated form,
maybe taking advantage of the business practices that the judge
found problematic,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that the computer industry is changing so rapidly
that every month of delay will help Microsoft argue that the
original case against it is no longer relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Jackson found that Microsoft was a predatory
monopoly that used unfair business practices to crush rival
companies. As punishment, Jackson chose the corporate equivalent of
the death penalty: the breakup of Microsoft into two separate
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft appealed, but the Justice Department, eager to see
Microsoft's power curbed, wanted to speed up the appeals process.
Citing a rarely used provision of the antitrust laws, Justice
Department lawyers asked the Supreme Court to short-circuit the
usual appeals process and hear the case directly.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft countered that the case should follow the normal
process. Tuesday, the high court agreed, with only Justice Stephen
Breyer dissenting.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, in a written statement attached
to the court's brief order, noted that his son works as a partner
for a Boston law firm that is defending Microsoft against private
antitrust lawsuits. But Rehnquist said that he would not recuse
himself because there is ``no reasonable basis to conclude that the
interests of my son or his law firm will be substantially affected
by the proceedings currently before the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft critic Ed Black, president of the Computer &AMP;
Communications Industry Association, a major trade group, said he
was only slightly disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly had a preference to have this case go to the
Supreme Court,'' Black said, partly because it would have meant a
quicker end to the matter. ``We'd like to have certainty for the
industry and a positive outcome for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Black added, ``at the end of the day, it will not matter
that much, as long as the decision of the trial judge is upheld and
an effective remedy is imposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft supporter Jonathan Zuck, president of the Association
for Competitive Technology, who expects Microsoft to prevail, said
he was pleased the procedual issue had been settled. ``I'm just
happy that we've gotten through the legal wrangling and we're going
to back to the substance of the case,'' Zuck said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has done well in previous outings at the Appeals
Court. In 1995, the court upheld a consent decree worked out
between Microsoft and the Justice Department to resolve an earlier
antitrust dispute. US District Judge Stanley Sporkin had rejected
the decree, saying it was too lenient toward Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Appeals Court overturned a decision by Judge
Jackson, who had ruled that the 1995 consent decree barred
Microsoft from incorporating Internet browsing software in its
Windows operating system. The ruling cleared the way for Microsoft
to begin selling its Windows 98 software.
</P>
<P>
   In a controversial part of the ruling, two of the three judges
wrote that Microsoft had a right to add new features to its
products, even if this harmed competitors, if the new features also
benefitted customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had argued that because Microsoft has a
virtual monopoly on desktop computer operating system software, the
inclusion of powerful new features at no charge was simply a way
for Microsoft to crush rivals. The Appeals Court ruling has been
touted by Microsoft as a major blow to the government's case,
evidence that Microsoft is likely to prevail on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Wood, an executive of the antitrust section of the American
Bar Association, isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Appeals Court was responding to before was a very
limited factual record,'' she said. ``This is a very different
situation now. You have a very extensive trial record (and)
detailed fact-finding.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said the appeals court could well back away from its
previous ruling and uphold Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Wood predicted the Appeals Court will hear the case
on an expedited schedule, thus limiting Microsoft's ability to
delay the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the standard, routine schedule is going to apply
to this case,'' Wood said. ``There's nothing standard or routine in
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Appeals Court immediately ordered the two sides to
file proposed schedules by Monday, with responses scheduled for
Oct. 5 and final filings by Oct. 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
