<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-VISAS27-COX     09-26 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE CLEARS HURDLE ON BILL TO EXPAND FOREIGN VISAS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Senate voted 94-3 on Tuesday to advance
legislation that would dramatically increase the number of visas
for high-skilled foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats stalled a final vote by continuing to debate a broad
range of immigration issues. But given the nearly unanimous support
on the cloture vote to limit debate on the bill, the expansion of
so-called H-1B visas appears headed for passage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time we get to a conclusion and have a vote, and I
predict that the final vote on this bill ... will be 90 to 10,''
said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Passage in the Senate could give the bill the momentum it needs
to become law before Congress adjourns, perhaps as soon as next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The House was awaiting Senate action on the measure, which would
boost the current annual cap on H-1B visas to 195,000 from 115,000.
Tech companies say they need more foreign computer programmers and
engineers to fill numerous vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House is looking at what is going to happen in the
Senate,'' said Marc Brailov, a spokesman for the American
Electronics Association, a trade group that has been working
vigorously for the bill's passage.
</P>
<P>
   Lott forced the cloture vote, which ended with 40 Democrats
joining 53 Republicans. Lott had already blocked Democrats from
adding their immigration amendments to the bill, so the vote to
limit debate and move toward final passage guaranteed a ``clean''
bill with no controversial riders.
</P>
<P>
   The visa bill is the technology industry's top remaining
priority in Washington for this year at a time when both political
parties are competing for financial backing of the tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lopsided cloture vote, Democrats spent hours
discussing other immigration issues, such as granting amnesty to
more than 500,000 mostly Hispanic undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans charged that the other immigration issues were being
tossed into the H-1B visa debate to make GOP presidential
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, look bad in the eyes of
many Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to quit playing politics and do what's right
for this country'' by focusing on raising the visa cap, said Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. He said that Democrats did not bring up the
immigration amnesty issue until late July, when Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore was doing poorly in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with the numerous speeches by Democrats after they
had voted for the procedural motion, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
lashed out. ``I don't understand it, you're either for it or
against it,'' he said. ``Let us vote on it. ``
</P>
<P>
   The continuing debate on immigration issues has put the bill in
``never-never land'' on the question of when final Senate passage
will take place, said Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki. But he
said he believed the bill would come to a vote late this week.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.senate.gov
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
