A2572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-PIERCE-LEAGUE-BOS     09-26 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PIERCE-LEAGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SECURITY MONITORING PIERCE STABBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The investigation into the stabbing of Celtics guard/forward
Paul Pierce will be closely monitored by NBA security. While many
of the league's security personnel are in Sydney for the Olympics,
the NBA maintains a security presence in all of its cities,
generally people with a background in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   League spokesman Seth Sylvan said the customary procedure after
an incident such as the Pierce stabbing would be for the security
person to check in with the local police. The individual would have
access to police records and reports and would update the league as
the investigation proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   When Pierce recovers, there also is the likelihood that the NBA
will talk to him, Sylvan said &UR;  &LR; Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics notified the league once they learned of the
stabbing but have had no further contact with NBA officials, said
Rich Pond, the team's chief financial officer. But Pond noted that
neither the league nor the team can do much, given that the
incident occurred at a nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately,'' Pond said, ``the player is responsible for
himself. If we get any further information, we'll funnel it to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pond also noted that the scarcity of medical information being
dispensed is a direct outgrowth of the Reggie Lewis situation.
After Lewis's death, the NBA amended its bylaws to give players the
final say in the dispensing of private medical information. (This
does not include injuries suffered in a game.)
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, the Pierce family did not want to disclose any
medical information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in their hands,'' Pond said. ``If there is any
information to be released, we will be the conduit.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Players Association also is keeping an eye on the
investigation, but from afar, as its chief security man is in
Sydney. When he returns, he will check with league security
officials and the Boston Police in a routine followup procedure,
said union spokesman Dan Wasserman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-OWENS-HNS &LR;      09-26 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CELEBRATION COSTS NINER A WEEK'S PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ With steely eyes and a furrowed brow, San
Francisco 49ers coach Steve Mariucci resembled a disappointed
father forced to mete out a painful punishment to his wayward
child.
</P>
<P>
   But Terrell Owens didn't lose the keys to the car or the
privilege of playing with his video games for a week. He paid a
much heftier price for his nationally televised misbehavior in
Sunday's 41-24 win over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Owens has been grounded. The 49ers' leading receiver has been
banned from the team for one week. No practices. No meetings. No
film sessions. No game on Sunday against the Arizona Cardinals. And
no paycheck for that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a decision based on how we intend to conduct ourselves
here as football players and represent this organization,''
Mariucci said Monday in announcing Owens' banishment, which will
cost him $24,294.
</P>
<P>
   It is not technically a suspension because Owens will not be
removed from the 53-man roster. But semantics aside, the message
was clearly communicated: Behavior such as Owens' will not be
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   The entire 49ers organization is recoiling from the backlash of
a display that was fodder for highlight reels and sport talk shows
around the nation on Sunday night and Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   There it was, for everyone to see, replayed over and over thanks
to the magic of videotape _ Owens' two blatantly antagonistic
touchdown celebrations on the big blue star in the middle of Texas
Stadium, as well as his postgame statements, in which he showed an
utter lack of contrition. In fact, he said he would do it again,
despite the clear disapproval of his coach and many of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said Owens' suspension was a result of his actions on
the field but that his postgame statements ``certainly didn't help
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens apologized to his teammates in the locker room after the
game. And then, in speaking with reporters, he refused to offer
regret for his actions. Mariucci was asked if Owens explained that
contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not well enough,'' he said shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Owens angrily left the team facility after his meeting with
Mariucci, according to team officials, and headed home to Alabama.
He released a statement through his agent, David Joseph. It did not
include an apology.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he ``felt badly'' that his actions ``detracted from
what was a great team victory over the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``As most of you know, I am an intense and emotional player who
is driven to succeed. I also want to make clear that my actions
were not intended to taunt or insult the Dallas Cowboys
organization; rather I was simply tying to provide my team with a
positive spark. Finally, after the game, I stated that I would do
the celebration again, but by making that statement, I simply
intended to show that I believed my action would be a positive to
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens' teammates were informed of the team's decision before
Monday's afternoon practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That came as a shock to me,'' said rookie linebacker Julian
Peterson, who added he didn't think Owens should be penalized. ``I
had no idea he was going to get suspended or anything like that.
It's tough. All he was doing was going on emotion, but I guess it
was considered taunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players saw it as a decision made by the people with
offices upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really surprised, but I can't speak for anybody
else,'' tight end Greg Clark said. ``In a way, it's good they are
putting their foot down and saying how they want the organization
to be run.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens will probably not be punished by the NFL. The team
informed the league about its action, and this will likely be the
extent of it. According a league spokesman, it is a violation of
the collective bargaining agreement for a player to be fined twice.
Thus, it would appear the 49ers got to Owens before the NFL could.
</P>
<P>
   Owens will not be in uniform when San Francisco hosts Arizona on
Sunday. Owens leads the 49ers with 23 catches, 328 yards and four
touchdowns. His absence may be costly for a team that has won just
one game in four tries but has a good chance on its home field
against a 1-2 Arizona team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
