<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-INVESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ BETTING $100 MILLION ON GENOMICS INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. will invest $100 million in early-stage
life sciences companies in hopes of capitalizing on the genomics
industry's burgeoning demand for high-performance computing.
</P>
<P>
   As the first part of that investment, Compaq said it has already
dedicated a ``significant'' sum to Applied Genomic Technology
Capital Fund, a Cambridge, Mass. venture capital fund specializing
in genomics and bioinformatics start-ups. It did not disclose the
amount of the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq will put some of the $100 million directly in companies
and some in venture capital funds like AGTC that target the
genomics and bioinformatics fields. The company said its goal is to
spur the growth of discovery in life sciences and strengthen the
company's foothold in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This field is truly a revolutionary field,'' said Ty Rabe, the
company's director of high-performance technical computing
solutions. ``Not only is there a huge focus in the near term to
develop drugs, diagnostics, and therapeutics, but in the long-term
there will be applications for crops, materials, and information
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said he believes many of those advances will come from
today's start-ups. Celera Genomics, the Maryland company that
earlier this year announced it had decoded the human genome,
started with one Compaq high-performance system and grew to a
network of 700 systems in less than 18 months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, one of the world's largest suppliers of computing
systems, provides high-performance computing, data storage, and
information management products and services. The company began
working with genomics companies and research institutions more than
four years ago and now has relationships with renowned groups like
Celera, the Sanger Centre in England, and the Whitehead Research
Institute in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have established a leadership position working with large
research institutions and companies,'' Rabe said. ``But we needed a
more aggressive and proactive way to reach start-ups in the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said start-up companies would be expected to purchase
Compaq's systems and services when Compaq invests in them. No such
agreement is required when Compaq invests in companies indirectly
through venture capital funds, Rabe said.
</P>
<P>
   As the genomics field has advanced, it has become increasingly
dependent on computing systems that can process, store, and analyze
massive amounts of data at breakneck speeds. Analysts estimate that
spending by genomics companies on information technology will match
or exceed the industry's revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biology is now largely an information science,'' said Noubar
Afeyan, managing partner of the AGTC fund. ``It faces significant
computational challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Celera's work to map the human genome is a good example, Afeyan
said. The company took human DNA, chopped it up into millions of
pieces, examined them, and then put them back together like pieces
of a puzzle. The company used computers, he said, to systematically
match each piece to millions of other pieces to see which
overlapped.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, Afeyan said, are using computers to identify
gene variations that affect how individuals respond to drugs and
other medical treatments. Until a couple of years ago, he said,
researchers didn't even know the variations existed. Now, he said,
they are scanning more than 3 billion segments of DNA to spot the
roughly 5 million variations that distinguish one person from
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this and more is being feverishly developed in the
industry,'' Afeyan said. ``We can help Compaq identify the up-
and-coming companies, give them access and visibility in the field.
And Compaq can help the companies by providing leading- edge IT
solutions to these significant computational challenges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
