<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV PRESIDENT SAYS VOTE REQUIRES RUNOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite assertions by the Yugoslav opposition and
by world leaders that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic lost
Sunday's vote, his electoral machinery insists he and challenger
Vojislav Kostunica would head into a runoff vote in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidate Vojislav Kostunica, however, stuck to his
claim of outright victory and rejected a runoff vote as an
``insult'' to voters. In cities across Yugoslavia Tuesday night,
thousands of people agreed with Kostunica, banging pots and pans
and shouting anti-Milosevic chants in spontanteous street protests
against the government commission's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his angry tone and the nationwide protests, Kostunica
said the opposition would avoid ``careless moves which could raise
tensions in society. ... The truth is obvious and we will defend it
by all nonviolent means.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and European governments rejected the
electoral commission's estimates and the runoff declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure to award a first-round victory for the opposition
is highly suspect, given the other credible reports that came out
of the polling,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and his administration ``are not yet ready to give up
the ghost, but they haven't yet figured out what to do,'' said a
senior US official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the surprising announcement, which came only hours
after the regime's State Election Commission said there would be no
results until Thursday, further weakened Milosevic. Some said it
foreshadows his end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic fact from all of this is that Milosevic is
finished,'' said Eric Gordy, a Clark University sociology professor
and author of ``The Culture of Power in Serbia.'' ``The only thing
we don't know is how long that will be clear to the people in
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles A. Kupchan, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations, basically agreed. ``I'm convinced that Milosevic is on
the way out because things are flying apart all around him,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even among those who still believed Milosevic had some room to
extend his 13 years in power, the next few days were seen to be
critical in determining whether he still had the support of the
police and army.
</P>
<P>
   The commission asserted that Kostunica, a university law
professor, received 48 percent of the vote and Milosevic 40
percent. The commission called its results ``preliminary.'' It said
64 percent of registered voters cast ballots, compared to estimates
of 74 percent by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   If a runoff is held, the momentum has clearly swung against
Milosevic, analysts agree. And after giving the opposition and
independent election monitors time to collect their own tallies _
both give Kostunica roughly 55 percent of the vote _ it was unclear
how Milosevic would fare better in a second vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds as though he's trying to practice politics of the
previous era, and foster some sort of division between the
opposition,'' said Andrew C. Hess, professor of diplomacy at Tufts
University's Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy. ``He's stalling
for time to figure out if it's possible to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday that option seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vladan Batic, leader of the Serb Democratic Christian
Party: ``There is no second round of presidential elections ...
because our candidate won in the first round. We have material
evidence to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Zoran Djindjic, president of the Democratic Party: ``The
preliminary results are but a provocation made by the regime.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Serb Orhtodox Church Patriarch Pavle met with
Kostunica and said afterward: ``I hope that the ruling parties will
accept the electoral will of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   More pointedly, he also appealed to the army and police to
``defend the interests of people and state, and not of an
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, just minutes before the commission anounced its
results, President Clinton said it was clear that the opposition
had won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the government's attempts to manipulate the vote, it
does seem clear that the people have voted for change,'' Clinton
said in a speech at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated his administration's offer _ echoed by
European governments Tuesday _ that sanctions would be lifted
against the Serbian people if the election results were upheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the will of the people is respected, the doors to Europe
and the world will be open again to Serbia. We will take steps with
our allies to lift economic sanctions, and the people of Serbia,
who have suffered so much finally will have a chance to lead normal
lives,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions,include blocking international bank loans to
Yugoslavia, an oil embargo and denying visas to Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   But with the opposition party's disagreement with US and NATO
policy in Kosovo, where a NATO air war dislodged Serb troops more
than a year ago, Clinton said it would take time for a new
democratic government in Yugoslavia to establish normal relations
with the West.
</P>
<P>
   The US administration carefully worded its reaction to the
electoral commission. Lockhart said the administation would wait
until vote numbers were final and ``take a cue from the opposition
to see what their intentions and plans are.''
</P>
<P>
   In the the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, however, the
pro-Western government didn't hesitate at all to criticize the
announcement of a runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's buying time but I think everything will be in vain and
that the opposition would be making a huge, huge mistake by
accepting,'' deputy Prime Minister Dragisa Burzan told Reuters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1917EDT &QL; 
