</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDER-TRADING-TRIMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC CHANGES RULES ON INSIDER STOCK SALES
</HEADLINE>
 By GEANNE ROSENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crests and troughs in the AVT Corp.'s stock price are enough
to bring on a bad case of sea sickness.
</P>
<P>
   That complicates life for Roger Fukai, the company's interim
chief executive, whose fortunes have been tied to AVT, a maker of
communications software in Kirkland, Wash., ever since he left the
safety of a large corporation in 1988 for ``plenty of risk'' and a
boatload of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Like many corporate insiders at small high-technology companies,
Fukai, AVT's longtime chief financial officer, eventually found
himself with most of his wealth in his company's securities but
with many restrictions on how and when he could turn them into
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Fukai was only allowed to trade during ``window periods'' that
lasted for just a few weeks after the release of quarterly
financial results, and only when no major market-affecting news
like an acquisition was on the horizon. Trading before such
knowledge becomes public can violate federal insider trading law.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a little-noticed Securities and Exchange Commission rule
that will go into effect next month should make it easier for Fukai
and others like him to sell their companies' stock without running
afoul of insider-trading law. The rule will allow insiders and
other investors, such as top executives, board members or key
advisers, to buy or sell stock in their companies no matter how
much inside information they have.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: the trades must be made under plans created before
the investors knew about developments that could push up or drag
down the stock.
</P>
<P>
   While the new provision could theoretically affect many of the
estimated 16 million Americans who own shares in the companies they
work for, its biggest impact will be on senior managers eager to
unlock the wealth of their stock-and-options riches without veering
into legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fukai, for one, welcomes the change. ``Insiders will be able to
spend their time managing their business rather than explaining
normal wealth-diversification trades to outside investors,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And the investing public should also gain, securities law
experts say, because illegal insider trading should be easier to
prosecute. ``The new rule lets the commission go after the people
who really do have evil in their hearts,'' said John F. Olson, a
senior partner in the Washington office of the law firm of Gibson,
Dunn &AMP; Crutcher.
</P>
<P>
   The plan must either specify the number of shares to be bought
or sold on specified dates, or else provide a written formula or
computer program for future trading. An insider can also relinquish
control over trading decisions to someone who does not have inside
information.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For example, an executive could put in writing his intention to
sell 100 shares of company stock the first trading day of every
month to pay for his children's college educations. Then, even if
he later learned of merger negotiations that could make the stock
soar, or of possible accounting irregularities that could pummel
it, the sales would be legal.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new rule was approved by the SEC in August as an addition to
the regulations that fall under the Securities Exchange Act of
1934. It is the first SEC rule that specifically addresses illegal
insider trading. Until now, the agency has relied upon a more
general rule on securities fraud coupled with case law, said Meyer
Eisenberg, the SEC's deputy general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Christian J. Mixter, a former chief litigation counsel for the
SEC's enforcement division, said of the new arrangement, ``If you
comply, you're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The trading plans could allow corporate insiders to bolster
their chances of getting more cash for their securities over time
by providing for the sale of more shares when prices are higher and
fewer when prices are lower, said David Furbush, a lawyer with
Brobeck, Phleger &AMP; Harrison in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate lawyers, company compliance officers and others are
only now beginning to consider the ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the Intel Corp., management intends to look at the
alternatives under the new rule ``and decide whether they'll be
willing to let people take advantage of them,'' said spokeswoman
Cary I. Klafter. Securities firms are also studying the potential
applications.
</P>
<P>
   The interest is perhaps strongest in Silicon Valley, where
overnight Internet millionaires are especially eager to cash out
some of their holdings. ``We've had a lot of interest in selling
plans by management and founders of companies,'' said Furbush of
Brobeck, Phleger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely see it as giving birth to an industry,'' said
David Priebe, a partner at Wilson Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati, also
in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   The rule has not received much attention partly because it was
overshadowed by a related provision that banned companies from
giving important information and specific guidance on future
developments to analysts and professional investors before
releasing it to the public.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's new stipulations for trading plans could inspire
companies to release executives and other employees from the
``window of opportunity'' approach that many adopted to avoid even
the appearance of illegal insider trading. (Some executives have
previously given up control of their trading through trusts and
other legal devices to avoid facing insider charges, but could
never be sure that the arrangements would give them 100 percent
legal protection.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, as long as selling plans are set up properly, the window
``becomes irrelevant and people ought to be able to sell on a
regular basis throughout the year,'' Furbush said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just senior managers who stand to benefit from the
new rule, which takes effect on Oct. 23. In the more relaxed
atmosphere of many high-technology companies, it sometimes seems
that practically everybody working at them knows what research
breakthroughs or corporate deals are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Pia Chon, director of product marketing at RadView Software in
Burlington, Mass., said that virtually all employees ``are privy to
future technology, future acquisitions and revenue'' and other
important company information. The company has an insider trading
policy for all employees, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As more and more lower-level people own stock in their
companies, they, too, are subject to insider-trading rules. To
escape any suspicion, experts said, they too might want to consider
setting up an SEC-approved selling plan.
</P>
<P>
   Selling plans that meet the new SEC specifications could also
have the effect of reassuring shareholders, analysts say.
Currently, the publicly announced sale of a large stake by a senior
executive is often viewed as a management bailout, whatever the
real motive, they say, while a pattern of selling according to a
prearranged formula would be more likely to be viewed as a
diversification strategy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The trading plans being authorized by the SEC hold another
potential benefit: ridding the market of any doubt about whether an
executive who sells his company's stock knows more than he is
letting on about his company's prospects. No matter how honest
senior executives are, said Bob Gabele, director of insider
research at First Call/Thomson Financial, they certainly have a
keener understanding than the public of their companies' general
outlook. And, he believes, illegal trading in which insiders have
more specific inside information about an important company
development is not all that uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a large number of insider actions that cross the
line, and I'm not surprised when I see them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is a loophole in the new rule for those who set up plans
and then watch in horror as their company's stock price tanks, but
it comes at a price. They can cancel a trade without breaking the
law, said John C. Coffee, a professor and securities law expert at
Columbia, but they would then be unable to hide behind their
trading plan in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule has elicited little controversy, though some
securities lawyers have complained that it is vague and exceeds the
SEC's authority. Others believe the rule will help the SEC fortify
its enforcement powers while giving insiders some guidance on how
to comply with the law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some have long argued that untrammeled insider trading would
more quickly lead to stock prices that accurately reflect
companies' intrinsic value.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including the SEC, have long contended that lax insider
restrictions would create an unfair playing field that would damage
the integrity of the public markets.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few years, the SEC. has been losing legal
ground in court battles against illegal insider trading. The new
rule is a response of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are essentially adopting this rule to reverse a couple of
court of appeals decisions,'' Coffee said. ``I think it's going to
place us back to where we were three or four years ago, while
providing insiders the ability to sell more.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
