<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CONSISTENCY IN POLITICS: INCONSISTENCY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes _ recent days offering splendid examples _ one can't
help but conclude politics might better have been named (ITAL)
contradictions. (UNITAL)
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Monday is a fine demonstration. We are told
people ages 18 to 24 have strong opinions about the presidential
election, but less than half intend to vote. We get our first clue
right off the bat when it is reported only half of the 800 young
adults surveyed said they were registered to vote, and a mere 46
percent said they would vote.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are in the middle of a presidential political race so
close not even the professional pundits can stick with which major
party candidate they expect to win. Young Americans, however,
supposedly have strong opinions about the election; it's just that
only half of them are even registered to vote and not even that
many say they will vote.
</P>
<P>
   What's even goofier is the list of five reasons a published
account gives for their not planning to vote. Those reasons are: a
lack of information on the candidates; a belief that more can be
accomplished by community action than by voting; a sense that
politics is too driven by money and lies; a sense the country is
moving in the ``right direction''; and the sense of having little
in common with a major political party.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. These have to be about the most unreasonable bunch
of reasons ever cited. Furthermore, they are a terrific display of
ignorance _ not just political ignorance, but pure ignorance.
Besides being dumb on individual face value, they also contradict
one another. Young folk believe the country is moving in the
``right direction,'' but they have no use for the politics and
politicians who certainly helped get it moving that way.
</P>
<P>
   As for there being a lack of information on the candidates, not
even those who love and thrive on hating the (ITAL) big (UNITAL)
media suggest it's not easy to get a lot of information on the
candidates. How else could they conceivably justify their myriad
complaints about what they maintain is incorrect information
constantly presented in the mainstream press?
</P>
<P>
   While this may not be super big in the school of contradictions,
it surely, correctly can be considered rather contradictory. Even
the most ideological of publications agree with the reports in the
so-called big media a whole lot of the time.
</P>
<P>
   If going from screaming bloody murder to not saying anything
counts as a contradiction, then, boy, do we have one on the topic
of presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   When Republican George W. Bush dared, just had the unmitigated
gall, to suggest holding a couple of the three presidential debates
in formats that tended to restrict their airing to one major
regularly broadcast network for one and to a cable network for the
other, oh, my gosh, you'd have thought he was proposing to steal
from the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no. How awful, screamed the camp of Democrat Al Gore and a
great chunk of the political press and opinion writers.
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, it was declared, these debates must be broadcast on all
four major networks so we can be sure a lot of people will watch
them. It would be wrong, we were told, not to have them on all the
big networks _ else there could, and likely would, be entertaining
competition for the attention of sluggards who didn't really want
to watch any debates.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Bush and his camp got the formats he generally wanted and
Gore and his campaign and a lot of the press won by ensuring all
the debates will be available to ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, little problem here. NBC says it won't carry next week's
debate because it'll be broadcasting a baseball game, and Fox says
it'll only air that debate on its cable network because it wants to
screen a two-hour premiere of a science-fiction adventure series,
made by the same guy who made the movie ``Titanic,'' on its regular
network.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all those who saw the original contradiction have been
stone-quiet about NBC and Fox's no-debate decisions because they've
learned CBS will provide all the debates in Spanish for those who
have SAP. That, by the way, is Second Audio Program.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe, it's just that the last ones to see a contradiction
are those whose screaming caused it.
</P>
<P>
   In which case, maybe instead of concluding (ITAL) politics
(UNITAL) well might have been called (ITAL) contradictions,
(UNITAL) one might more correctly decide the better conclusion
might be (ITAL) contradictions, (UNITAL) should have been named
(ITAL) politics (UNITAL). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
