<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Sept. 27, and thereafter. For questions, contact Lesley
Goldberg at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-HOLLYWOOD (Los Angeles) -- In preparation for
Wednesday's congressional hearing on whether Hollywood is marketing
violence to youngsters, studios have agreed to several steps, MPAA
head Jack Valentia announced Tuesday, such as omitting previews for
R-rated films in videos of G-rated movies, and asking theater
owners not to show previews for R-rated films during G-rated
movies. But the plan, which does not mention TV ads, was blasted by
critics who call it insufficient. G-rated films are less than 5
percent of all releases rated by the MPAA. By Bill Hillburg. (Will
move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   BABY-BOOM (Los Angeles) -- Los Angeles and cities nationwide
have been hit with a baby boom of millennial proportions. Although
national figures have yet to be tallied, hospitals and
obstetricians confirm they have been up all year. And September --
traditionally a big month for babies -- has been particularly busy.
By Jordan Smith. (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-VOTE (Los Angeles) -- Say goodbye to election day, say
hello to election month. Beginning Oct. 16, Los Angeles County
voters can vote by touching a computer screen at nine locations --
which will be kept open for more than three weeks, including
Saturdays and Sundays, preceding the Nov. 7 presidential election.
The new technology promises to help multiply the number of county
voters who cast ballots in advance of election day, already
numbering 500,000 in major elections. By Dominic Berbeo. (Will move
on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
