<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP CALLS FOR FBI PROBE OF TAPE THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ The Bush campaign, clearly rattled by
questions about how a mock debate videotape ended up in the
possession of Al Gore, Tuesday demanded the FBI investigate the
vice president's campaign to determine who infiltrated their
operation and obtained the tape.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has avoided mentioning the matter so as not to
distract voters from his daily message. But the mysterious mailing,
arguably the strangest event of the campaign, had by Tuesday
evolved into a political issue, as Bush communications director
Karen Hughes all but accused the FBI of failing to fully
investigate Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any thorough investigation into how Bush campaign proprietary
materials ended up in the hands of the Gore campaign involves not
only the Bush campaign but also the Gore campaign,'' Hughes said.
``The Gore campaign has obviously had a problem, because they have
had to suspend one of their employees for boasting about the
presence of a mole. We think that is something that is very serious
and that ought to be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape, mailed anonymously but with an Austin postmark, was
sent along with a debate briefing book to former New York
Representative Tom Downey earlier this month. Downey, a Democrat
who was playing the role of Bush in mock debates with Gore, said he
viewed only 60 to 90 seconds of the tape before realizing it was
highly confidential and turning it off. He then turned it over to
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both sides have speculated wildly _ but not publicly
_ about who might be responsible, with each campaign insisting it
is not involved. Last weekend, the Gore campaign suspended a junior
staff-member, Michael Doyne, 28, for admitting he joked in an
e-mail to a friend about a well-placed Bush ``mole'' _ a turn of
events the Bush campaign quickly seized upon.
</P>
<P>
   But the matter has now become more than a whodunnit. Despite
concerns about letting the issue become a distraction, the Bush
campaign Tuesday nudged it into the political spotlight, implying
the FBI is not doing enough to resolve the matter and is perhaps
even showing some favoritism to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush officials were especially piqued that, as of Tuesday
morning, they had not received a return phone call from FBI
Director Louis Freeh, despite at least two phone calls from Bush
campaign manager Joe Allbaugh over the last three days. Hughes said
a lower-level employee returned the call, ``but our campaign
manager conveyed to him that he did not feel that was satisfactory,
and he would like to talk to the director.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials and FBI investigators also opened
themselves up to charges of political maneuvering last weekend,
Hughes said, when news that FBI officials suspected a traitor
within the Bush campaign was anonymously leaked.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI gave ``the appearance, at least, of playing politics in
the midst of a presidential campaign,'' Hughes said, calling even
such appearances ``wrong and inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Bush campaign dismissed accusations from
the head of the Texas Democratic Party that a senior Bush
strategist, Karl Rove, was somehow involved.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Beth Malcolm, the leading Democrat in Bush's home state,
was quoted in Tuesday's edition of the Austin American-Statesman as
saying the mystery had ``Karl Rove's fingerprints all over it.''
Hughes dismissed the charge as ``totally ridiculous,'' urging
reporters to ``consider the source.'' Rove, a legendary figure in
Texas politics with a reputation for devilish tactics, did not
return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign refused to address any of the issues raised by
the Bush aides. Douglas Hattaway, a Gore spokesman, simply said:
``This matter is in the hands of professional investigators at the
FBI. We are comfortable with that. For some reason, the Bush
campaign apparently is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes vehemently denied any high-ranking staff member was
involved, and said aides would be willing to take a lie-detector
test to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the people who have access to the tape. They are my
friends, they are my co-workers, they have worked with me for
years,'' she said. ``It's so ridiculous, I don't think it merits a
denial. What you are talking about here are people who have worked
tirelessly for years to elect Governor Bush president. We are not
interested in helping Al Gore in his debate preparations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
