<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SUES HARVARD, 4 INDIVIDUALS IN RESEARCH FUNDING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The U.S. Justice Department sued Harvard University and
four individuals Tuesday for up to $120 million for allegedly
mismanaging and defrauding a government-funded project to help
overhaul the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   The civil lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, charges that
Harvard and its two project managers billed the government for $40
million in work that was biased by insider dealings and investments
of the managers and their wives.
</P>
<P>
   Named in the suit were Andrei Shleifer, a well-known Harvard
economics professor, and his second-in-command, Jonathan Hay, a
legal expert and graduate of Harvard Law School. The lawsuit
alleges that the two ``abused their positions as high-level and
trusted advisers to and on behalf of the United States in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's $57 million Russia project, which ran from 1992 to
1997, was one of the U.S.'s top foreign-aid programs to westernize
the former Soviet financial system. The university was responsible
for giving impartial advice to Russian officials and policing
conflicts of interest among the Harvard advisers helping to
privatize state-controlled assets.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to the civil suit, Shleifer and his wife, Nancy
Zimmerman, invested $200,000 in gas and utility companies, such as
Gazprom, that were influenced by the plans he was helping to shape.
</P>
<P>
   Shleifer and Hay allegedly also used their employees to research
Russian oil stocks, and soon after bought hundreds of thousands of
dollars' worth, in a relative's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advice and services, even if of value and assistance to
Russia, were still fundamentally tainted by the financial self
dealing,'' said U.S. Attorney Donald K. Stern at a news conference.
``For its part, Harvard failed miserably in its obligations to
adminster this overseas project.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials denied responsibility for the alleged abuses.
Calling the privatization effort ``first rate,'' they said they met
all of their obligations to the U.S. Agency for International
Development, which funded the project.
</P>
<P>
   If improper conduct did occur, university officials added, the
blame lay with the managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a stand-up institution that takes our ethical standards
and contractual obligations very seriously,'' said Anne Taylor, the
university's general counsel. ``We know virtually nothing about
this alleged private conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the university wants to review the government's
evidence, and then may consider settlement talks. An earlier round,
before the suit was filed, did not reach a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the project managers also denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Hay _ who was fired by Harvard in 1997 after an initial federal
inquiry found problems with the project _ was accused of investing
in the oil stocks and, with Elizabeth Hebert, his then-girlfriend
whom he later married, creating a real estate firm to conduct
business that touched on his work with the project.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Shleifer, meanwhile, was accused of making the
oil-stock purchases with Hay, as well as investing money with his
wife in Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Shleifer's attorney, Earl Nemser, said his client was not
bound by the project's ban on investments and conflict of interest
because Shleifer was technically a consultant to the project, not
an employee. Nemser said Shleifer always remained an employee of
Harvard, even during a year when he was on a leave of absence to
lead the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a consultant, there were no restrictions,'' Nemser said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russia project was once a jewel in Harvard's
international-development efforts, which offer high-profile and
lucrative opportunities to faculty stars there. Several Harvard
professors continue to lead projects, some government related, to
help modernize or reform national economies.
</P>
<P>
   Shleifer served as principal investigator and project manager on
the Russia project, which was funded in 1992 and again in 1995
under two cooperative agreements between Harvard and USAID. Such
pacts typically assign responsibilities to all partners, unlike
pay-for-service contracts, where the grant recipient is accountable
for meeting the terms of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   USAID was not a target of the government's action. Rather, the
agency initially blew the whistle on the Russia project, finding in
an audit that the two managers had ``gained influence'' over
Russian financial markets and had ``abused the trust of the United
States government.''
</P>
<P>
   USAID cut off funding in 1997, after Harvard had removed
Shleifer and Hay from the project, university officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard officials said that under the cooperative agreement,
USAID had as much of a role to play in overseeing the project as
the university. They noted that USAID had a Moscow office but was
not aware of misconduct within the project.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also pointed out an acknowledgement by the U.S.
Attorney's Office that Shleifer and Hay were allegedly trying to
cover up their investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a reasonable person would understand that it would be
very, very difficult to catch this kind of private conduct,''
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern emphasized that Harvard was the chief guarantor of the
integrity of the project, and not USAID. Even if the managers'
advice to the Russians was sound, he said, the endeavor was
compromised. The lawsuit, he added, reflected heightened government
scrutiny of grant management by universities and other recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office began both civil and criminal probes
of the project three years ago. No criminal charges have been
filed, and Stern said that the evidence at this point might not
meet the standard of proof needed for criminal convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is based on the federal False Claims Act, which
increases penalties on those found defrauding the U.S. government.
Under the law, damages are tripled if fraud is proven. If the
government wins this case, the $40 million in alleged false claims
would grow to $120 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Harvard was named because of its deep pockets _
which grew even deeper Friday, with the announcement that its
endowment stood at $19 billion _ Stern demurred, just barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think Harvard will be good for the judgment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
