<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-APPEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS ARGUE REOPENING OF LEWIS SUIT APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Saying that his client has been put through ``absolute
torture both personally and professionally,'' a lawyer for Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. Tuesday asked a judge to reject Donna
Harris-Lewis's request that her appeal of a jury verdict clearing
Mudge of medical malpractice be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to stop, your honor,'' said William J. Dailey Jr., the
attorney for Mudge, who was the chief cardiologist for Celtics
captain Reggie Lewis at the time of Lewis's 1993 death. ``It has
been an absolute nightmare what he has gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   Dailey's entreaty capped a 3 1/2-hour hearing at which
Harris-Lewis, represented by a new team of lawyers, maintained that
her former lawyer, Neil Rossman, failed to pursue her appeal and
never told her it was at risk of being dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith tossed out
Harris-Lewis's appeal in July after she missed a filing deadline
required to continue it.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the stand Tuesday, Rossman, who represented Harris-Lewis
in the retrial of the lawsuit she brought against Mudge, said he
searched for issues to appeal but found none. Rossman also said he
delayed filing appellate documents in order to give Harris-Lewis
time to find a new lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And he produced letters he wrote to Harris-Lewis in which he
warned her that she was ``running out of time'' to pursue her
appeal and cautioned that ``you are wasting your money in
prosecuting any appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   But under questioning by one of Harris-Lewis's new lawyers,
Pamela Harris-Daley, Rossman conceded that he never gave
Harris-Lewis a specific deadline for continuing her appeal, even
though she had sent him a letter asking for that information.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Daley argued that, as a result, Harris-Lewis did not know
the appeal was at risk of being dismissed and is entitled to have
the appeal reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Dailey's argument that Harris-Lewis effectively
waived her right to appeal when she missed a filling deadline,
Harris-Daley said that ``it is unreasonable and illogical to
suggest that one could knowingly and intelligently waive a right
that one doesn't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Fremont-Smith took the matter under advisement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
