<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2605 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-GIRLFIGHT-$ADV01     09-26 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GIRLFIGHT-$ADV01-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S WOMEN'S TURN TO MAKE IT IN THE RING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Boxing has always provided an apt metaphor for films
about struggle and redemption. The troubled young man from the poor
background is locked in the frame with his adversary, the sweat
flies, there are close-ups of agonized faces and the architecture
of oiled and muscled bodies. As more and more women, including
Muhammad Ali's daughter, Laila, and Joe Frazier's daughter, Jacqui
Frazier-Lyde, take up the sport, it is almost inevitable that films
about women who box should follow, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Girlfight,'' a first feature by Karyn Kusama, which
opened Friday. It is the story of a sullen, gum chewing, muscular
girl from the underclass, played by Michelle Rodriguez, who
literally fights her way into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to take the classic boxing story, put a female
protagonist in it and subvert the form,'' said Kusama, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Like more traditional boxing movies before it _ ``The Champ,''
with Wallace Beery, ``Champion,'' with Kirk Douglas, or `Raging
Bull'' and ``Rocky'' _ ``Girlfight'' is about ``an outsider who
enters a world where she does not belong and finds a place for
herself,'' Kusama said. In fact, that description could apply to
Kusama: she had to struggle to get financing for the film from
reluctant studios.
</P>
<P>
   Movie companies wanted her to make her character a white girl,
``a celebrity starlet in an environment of material comfort,'' said
Kusama, who described trying to raise money for the film as ``a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman in a traditional male role is really scary for
people,'' she said. ``People felt she would be unappealing,
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusama added: ``I wasn't thinking of the movie in sociopolitical
terms. I thought it would be fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfight,'' which shared the Grand Jury Prize at the Sundance
Film Festival with ``You Can Count on Me'' and which also won the
Director's Award, provides a rare film portrait of the lives of
Panamanians and Dominicans, as well as Puerto Ricans, who inhabit
the world of boxing. ``It's modern, urban Latino,'' said Kusama.
Most movies about Latinos feature primarily Puerto Ricans, Kusama
said, but Latino ``doesn't mean one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Girlfight,'' the protagonist, Diana _ hair slicked down in
corn rows, with a strand falling over her eyes _ is prone to
starting fights in high school. There are sorrows buried in Diana's
family, including a mother who had committed suicide after being
physically abused by Diana's father (played by Paul Calderon).
Meanwhile, the father has pinned his hopes on her brother (Ray
Santiago), whom he wants to be a boxer but who really wants to be
an artist.
</P>
<P>
   When Diana goes to the neighborhood gym in search of her
brother, she decides she wants to box, too. But the trainer tells
her: ``You can't. Girls don't have the same power as boys.'' She
asks her father to pay for her training, but he won't hear of it.
So she steals from him and pawns her mother's locket. Soon she
meets another young fighter, Adrian (Santiago Douglas), and they
fall in love. When Diana takes a punch in the eye, she asks Adrian,
``Do you still like me with my black eye?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I like you more,'' Adrian replies.
</P>
<P>
   At first, when the lovers spar, Adrian can't bear to hit her.
``I love you, I really do,'' she tells him as they are locked in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say love kills you in the ring,'' one of the boxers says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in what the gym owner bills as New York's ``first
gender-blind amateur boxing event,'' Diana and Adrian are paired
against each other. But Adrian is reluctant. ``If you don't fight
me in this match,'' Diana says, ``you're less of a man than you
think you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusama admits that the idea of women and men fighting each other
in boxing competition is unlikely at the moment. But ``10 year ago
boys and girls wouldn't wrestle each other,'' she said. ``Now they
do it in high school and college championships. And the girls
sometimes win.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusama was drawn to boxing in 1992, when a friend took her to
Gleason's Gym in Brooklyn. A chain smoker, she hoped sparring would
curb her habit. She came to love the sport. ``I realized what an
intimate situation it is.'' It was as if the two people in the ring
had invaded each other's sense of space and time, she said. ``It
made sense to me that young boys from very, very troubled
backgrounds would seek out the physical contact and the emotional
contact with the trainers.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can really get hurt. On one occasion, Kusama was
knocked out by ``a really good woman boxer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can wear a breast plate, but it's not very effective to
punch someone on the breast. It makes more sense to go for the
organs or the brain, the liver, the kidneys.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kusama, ``There's a sort of decorum to the violence of
boxing that I took to be an idealized version of the world.'' Only,
she added, ``where in life do you have a referee?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxers are the most courageous people in the world, oh my
God,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The story for ``Girlfight'' grew partly out her own ``general
sense of isolation and alienation growing up,'' Kusama said.
</P>
<P>
   She was raised in St. Louis, where her father, a
Japanese-American, is a child psychiatrist and her mother an
educational psychologist. Kusama attended New York University Film
school and won the Mobil Prize for ``Sleeping Beauties,'' a 15-
minute short about two sisters with a telepathic connection.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from NYU, Kusama became, she said, ``the queen
of odd jobs,'' adding, ``I've tried to just get through life.'' She
met the filmmaker John Sayles through a baby-sitting job and became
his personal assistant. She was impressed by Sayles's commitment to
his art. She watched him develop his 1996 movie ``Lone Star'' from
inception to release.
</P>
<P>
   When Kusama wrote the script for ``Girlfight,'' Sayles's
longtime companion, Maggie Renzi, and her business partner Sarah
Greene, agreed to produce it, along with Martha Griffin. The budget
was $1 million. But all the film companies, including Sony Classics
Pictures, Fine Line Features, Miramax, passed.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1999, Kusama secured a backer. But two days before
pre-production began, the backer pulled out. Sayles came to the
rescue with a check for $1 million. Later, the Independent Film
Channel chipped in $300,000, which went to Sayles to offset his
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles said he had never doubted that the film would get a
distributor. He liked the idea of a woman as the main character in
a boxing movie. ``She doesn't want to be a `girly-girl,''' he said
on the phone recently. ``She's in chaos. Once in that world, there
is a kind of belonging.'' (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Kusama found her star, Rodriguez, at an open casting call. A
self-described ``Jersey City girl'' who is half Dominican and half
Puerto Rican, she grew up in a rough neighborhood. Members of her
family are Jehovah's Witnesses. She dropped out of high school and
later got her high school equivalency diploma at age 17. ``Life
educated me, honey,'' Rodriguez said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had decided to pursue acting because she hated the
idea of a 9-to-5 job. She then signed up with ``some cheesy agency
that, like, robs you for money,'' she said. The agency took photos
of her but failed to get her a job. Then she saw the notice for the
``Girlfight'' call in Backstage. ``I got there about one and a half
hours late, as always,'' she said. ``I'm pretty irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 350 other contenders for the part. ``She read
lines,'' said Kusama. ``It was a disaster. She had no concept of
what this process was. She didn't know that when you make a mistake
you don't berate yourself in the middle of the tape and roll your
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``we could not find anyone who could come close to her in
physical power,'' Kusama said. ``Michelle projects a lot of
intelligence, more like an animal intelligence.'' The director
decided to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The production hired an acting coach, and sent Rodriguez, who
had never boxed before, to a gym to get in shape. ``After a week
they said I was ready to spar,'' Rodriguez said. ``I turned into an
animal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked like I was on steroids because I was so buff.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was shot in Jersey City and New York. It was accepted
at the Sundance competition, and suddenly all the companies that
had rejected it began competing to buy it, Kusama said. Finally,
Screen Gems purchased it for $3 million. Kusama also made a deal
with Capitol Records to release the distinctive soundtrack with its
blend of hip-hop, flamenco and hand clapping.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama herself has given up boxing. She lives in the Fort Greene
section of Brooklyn with three roommates and is writing a new
script, which she describes as ``bio-fiction.'' She doesn't have a
production deal, but, with the release of ``Girlfight,'' she said,
she believes it will be far easier to get money for a movie this
time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,''she said, ``I will be playing a different kind of
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
