<HEADER>
A2609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-DIETITIAN0927-CO     09-26 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DIETITIAN0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox New Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How bad is it to rely on those pre-packed lunch meals with
mini pizzas, tacos, etc?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's no surprise that many of the pre-packed lunches are
relatively high in fat and sodium compared to something like a
turkey sandwich. But it's not necessarily any worse if the
alternative would have been a sandwich of high-fat lunch meat or
``junk'' food. This is especially true for children and teens,
whose calorie needs are high enough to allow room for some high-fat
foods. Just be sure other meals and snacks are relatively lean.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem may be what goes with the lunch: Where are
the vegetables and fruits so vital for good health? A meal finished
off with sugar-laden desserts or beverages-like the so-called
``juice drinks'' containing little or no juice-leaves a lot to be
desired. And that's true for meals that are pre-packaged or made at
home.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer pre-packed lunches, look for those without the
less nutritious fillers and add your own fruit, raw vegetables and
whole-grain bread. But you might question whether it's worth paying
more for a nutritionally incomplete, pre-packaged meal that you
must then supplement.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is couscous a whole grain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Couscous may look like a whole grain such as bulgur or brown
rice, but it is really just another form of pasta. Couscous is
commercially prepared by mixing coarsely ground semolina with water
and salt to form a dough that is rolled into tiny balls and dried.
A fast and delicious addition to a meal, couscous is steam-cooked
until fluffy. Most couscous is made of an enriched refined grain, a
good source of complex carbohydrates and vitamins, but not quite as
nutritious as a whole grain. Whole grains generally contain more
fiber than enriched grain products, as well as several vitamins,
minerals and natural phytochemicals. A few companies offer whole
wheat couscous.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that rye bread is healthier than wheat bread?
</P>
<P>
   A: You probably heard about a study published in the Journal of
Nutrition that reported that people who ate rye bread lowered their
blood cholesterol. However, there's more to this story. The study
was conducted in Finland, where rye bread is a dark, whole-grain
version not commonly seen in this country. American rye bread is
usually a refined grain product that is not nearly as high in
fiber. In the Finnish study, men who ate large amounts of this
whole-grain rye bread (about 20 percent of their daily calories),
dropped their LDL (''bad'') cholesterol about 12 percent in four
weeks. For some reason, however, the same diet did not affect the
blood cholesterol of women in the study.
</P>
<P>
   What we can infer from this and several other studies is that
whole grains_ whether rye, wheat or other grains_ are linked with a
variety of health benefits. People who eat more whole grains have a
lower risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   These Ask a Dietitian questions were answered by Karen Collins,
M.S., R.D. of the American Institute for Cancer Research.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
