<TEXT>
<P>
   TO TAX OR NOT TO TAX: California Gov. Gray Davis vetoed a bill
that would have forced the state's retailers to collect sales tax
on Internet transactions. Davis also signed a bill calling for a
three-year moratorium on Internet access taxes. The push in Georgia
to tax e-commerce sales, however, continues. This year the Georgia
Senate and House passed resolutions asking Congress to allow states
to tax Internet sales. Legislators believe Net sales are a
substitute for bricks-and-mortar sales and that sales tax receipts
will fall as e-commerce increases. They also say omitting
e-commerce taxes is ``unfair'' to other merchants. Opponents,
however, argue that e-commerce retailers and their employees
already pay property, income and other state and local taxes where
they are based. Critics also say taxing Internet transactions will
hurt efforts to attract high-tech industry to the state.
</P>
<P>
   VOICE WEB ACCESS: Intel Corp. says it will eventually sell
technology that allows companies to offer consumers voice access to
their Web sites. Spokesman Tom Beermann said users will be able to
use voice commands over a regular phone line to access everything
from stock quotes and traffic reports to restaurant reservations.
Intel made the announcement at the Networld +Interop show in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   COMBATING FRAUD: Online merchants and payment processors have
formed a coalition to combat Internet fraud. The Worldwide
E-Commerce Fraud Prevention Network, which includes Amazon.com,
American Express and Atlanta-based payment processor First Data
Corp., will share fraud prevention information and practices with
merchants. The goal is to improve security on the Web to attract
more consumers and reduce costs associated with fraud. Merchants
can sign up at the group's Web site, which also features an
eight-question fraud test.
</P>
<P>
   merchantfraudsquad.com
</P>
<P>
   MORE CASUALTIES: Denver-based Jato Communications Corp., a
high-speed Internet provider in danger of running out of cash, will
lay off 300 to 350 workers, scale back its nationwide business
plans and replace Chief Executive Gerald K. Dinsmore with one of
the company's founders, Leonard E. Allsup. In Chicago, Xpedior
Inc., which helps businesses build Web sites for e-commerce, said
it will cut 270 jobs, or 16 percent of its work force, and take a
third-quarter charge after its revenue dropped in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   PAYING UP ONLINE: Although consumers have been slow to embrace
it, electronic bill paying is expected to gain steam in the years
ahead, according to a new survey by Jupiter Communications.
Researchers expect 2.8 million to pay bills electronically next
year, compared with 700,000 this year and 100,000 last year. The
number is expected to grow to 40.2 million in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   HOT/COLD NET STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Entrust (ENTU), up 19% at $27.06. The e-business infrastructure
provider formed an alliance with Motorola (MOT) to develop
next-generation wireless solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Palm (PALM), up 6% at $55.50. The maker of hand-held computing
devices reported better-than-expected earnings
</P>
<P>
   Phone.com (PHCM), up 4% at $121. The software company continues
to benefit from its announced merger with Software.com (SWCM).
</P>
<P>
   eBay (EBAY), down 2% at $70.69. The online trading company
benefited from positive comments from Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Intel (INTC), down 4% at $43.31. The chip maker continues to
suffer from a warning about lower revenue.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.27.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
