u a BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-VALENTI     09-26 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-VALENTI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM INDUSTRY ANNOUNCES VOLUNTARY GUIDELINES
</HEADLINE>
   (With VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILMS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 19 has being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As executives of movie studios prepared to testify
at a Senate hearing on Wednesday, industry officials announced
steps Tuesday to limit the marketing of adult-rated movies to
children.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said at a news conference that major movie-making
companies had established a ``goal of not inappropriately
specifically targeting children in its advertising of films rated R
for violence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the film makers had agreed not to include children under
17 in focus groups used to test movies rated R because of violence
unless the children were accompanied by a parent or guardian. And
he said previews for such movies would no longer be shown before
G-rated movies in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The new steps are voluntary and include no enforcement
mechanism. Valenti said the association each year would review
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines, children under 17 are not supposed to be
allowed in R-rated movies unless they are with an adult. Movies
rated G are supposed to be suitable for children. There are two
ratings in between, PG (warning parents that some material may not
be suitable for children) and PG-13 (warning that some material may
be inappropriate for children under 13).
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said the industry was responding to criticism from a
report by the Federal Trade Commission, released Sept. 11, that
most adult-rated movies, recordings and electronic games were
marketed to children.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, executives of companies that make and sell
recordings and video games testified before the Senate commerce
committee and were sharply criticized by senators. Representatives
of companies that make movies had refused to appear on such short
notice, so the panel's chairman, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., called
a new hearing and summoned the movie executives.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said executives from the eight largest studios would
testify. They are the Walt Disney Co., DreamWorks SKG,
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Studios, Paramount Pictures, Sony Pictures
Entertainment, 20th Century Fox Film Corp., Universal Studios and
Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that some of them would announce efforts to limit
marketing that went further than those that the industry could
agree on.
</P>
<P>
   Studies of the relationship between violence in entertainment
and actual violent conduct are inconclusive. But polls show that
more than 80 percent of American adults believe there is a
connection, a popular view not lost on politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The commission report had led the industry ``to take a fresh new
look at the way we market films,'' Valenti said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing two weeks ago, senators were especially critical
of the practice cited in the report of using children as young as
12 in groups that test-marketed R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti indicated, though he did not say directly, that this
practice would be abandoned. He said children under 17 would
participate in focus groups only if accompanied by adults, and he
said some material that might be acceptable for 15- and
16-year-olds should not be shown to much younger children.
</P>
<P>
   He said the movie makers would also begin explaining the reasons
particular movies received an R rating _ whether for violence,
nudity, bad language or sexual content _ in print advertising and
on official movie Web sites and would include this information in
videocassettes.
</P>
<P>
   He rejected the suggestion that the movie companies should
simply stop all marketing of R-rated movies to children. Some
movies with an R rating because of violent scenes like ``Saving
Private Ryan'' are not only acceptable but worthwhile for some
children, Valenti said. He suggested that it was reasonable to try
to get children to persuade their parents to take them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, movie companies should be allowed to
advertise during popular programs like the Super Bowl, even though
many children would be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``How on earth,'' he asked, ``can you advertise anything that
some kids won't be watching?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
