<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2612 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-WOLF-$ADV01-2TAKES     09-26 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WOLF-$ADV01-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR SERIES AND ONE COMING SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dick Wolf eschews the expensive sports clothes and
open-necked shirts that are de rigueur for rival television kings
like Steven Bochco and David E. Kelley. Instead, with his
slicked-back hair, cuff-linked off-white shirt, expensive tie and
sleek suit, Wolf resembles a very successful businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Which he is.
</P>
<P>
   The busiest writer-producer on television, the 53-year-old Wolf
will have four shows on the air this fall _ including the
longest-running dramatic series on television, NBC's ``Law and
Order.'' A fifth Wolf show is planned for early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about television is you write it and six, seven
weeks later you're watching it,'' said Wolf, seated in the
commissary of Universal Studios, where his shows are written. ``And
nobody at any movie studio is making the kind of socially aware or
socially provocative feature films that you see almost every night
on television. Nobody. It's a genre that's disappeared. Except on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on Wolf's shows.
</P>
<P>
   His most anticipated new show is NBC's ``Deadline'' (Mondays,
9-10 p.m.), which starts Monday. In this drama series, Oliver Platt
plays a crusading columnist for a New York tabloid newspaper who
recruits graduate students to help uncover what the city's power
brokers often want to keep buried. The columnist, according to
Platt, is a kind of composite of Jimmy Breslin, Mike McAlary,
Murray Kempton and Mike Royko (although it's unlikely that these
columnists used graduate students to help them).
</P>
<P>
   Platt, a skilled 40-year-old character actor (``Bulworth,''
``Dr. Dolittle''), had been sought for years by television
producers. He even turned down the Dylan McDermott role on ``The
Practice.'' But last year Platt told a friend, David Kissinger,
president of programming at Studios USA Television, which is Wolf's
producing partner, that he was weary of traveling to movie sets and
missed his wife and three children in New York. Was there a New
York-based television series available?
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger told Wolf, who had been thinking of a newspaper
series. The role of the columnist was quickly designed for Platt.
The cast of ``Deadline'' also includes Tom Conti as the media mogul
who owns the tabloid and Bebe Neuwirth as an editor, as well as
Hope Davis and Lili Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to do a newspaper show,'' Wolf said. ``I
liked `Lou Grant.' I loved `Front Page.' And what I wanted to do
was deal with a columnist, not a reporter. The knock on newspaper
shows is that a reporter reports. He's a passive protagonist. He
has to wait for things to happen. A columnist doesn't. A columnist
is not limited by objectivity. A columnist can smell something and
say, `This is what I want to do.' A columnist can drive the action,
which is the essence of drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Platt said his only concern in taking the job was signing a
commitment for five years. ``It's scary,'' he said. ``But then
again you have the opportunity to collaborate with a guy like Dick
Wolf, to build a character from the ground up and establish a world
and spin it out. The oversimplified personal question I had was, Do
I want consistently good writing and to sleep in my own bed and be
with my family and have a steady gig, or do I want wildly erratic
writing and to sleep in hotels and come home exhausted from a film
set? Was there any doubt?''
</P>
<P>
   The series starts the same night another new Wolf show, ``Arrest
and Trial,'' is to make its debut on Channel 9 in New York. This
nationally syndicated show, to be seen five days a week on 170
stations, blends reality with dramatic re-creations as it follows
highly charged and violent criminal cases from the police
investigation to the verdict. Interviews with law enforcement
officers are interspersed with scenes enacted by actors portraying
victims and killers. Brian Dennehy, who won a Tony Award last year
as best actor for his performance in ``Death of a Salesman,''
serves as the host.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really fascinating for me is using real cops and real
prosecutors as well as file footage and some re-creations,'' said
Wolf, who is producing the show with Robert Port, president of
Maury Povich's Mo Po Entertainment. In contrast to successful
reality shows like ``Cops,'' the new series explores a crime by
re-enacting it through the use of often grainy film and tape that
seeks to blur the line between reality and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a crime junkie,'' Wolf said. ``Cops and prosecutors are
kind of unsung heroes. And this is a chance of getting real people
on camera and seeing who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf has been obsessed with cops and prosecutors for 25 years.
He grew up relatively affluent in Manhattan, the son of an
advertising executive. He attended Phillips Academy in Andover,
Mass., and the University of Pennsylvania, where he majored in
English. After graduation he worked in advertising for eight years.
``I did landmark advertising campaigns _ `Can't beat Crest for
fighting cavities!' Remember that?''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached 30, Wolf wanted to quit advertising and
write screenplays. In 1977, at the height of the skateboard craze,
he sold his first script to Universal: ``Skateboard,'' which was
made into a movie starring Leif Garrett. ``A memorable movie,''
Wolf said dryly. But he had a talent for writing commercial films,
and three were made: ``No Man's Land'' (1987), ``Masquerade''
(1988) and ``School Ties'' (1992), about anti-Semitism at a fancy
prep school. None of the films were especially successful (although
``School Ties'' is notable for featuring a cast of young actors who
later went on to become stars, among them Matt Damon, Ben Affleck,
Chris O'Donnell and Brendan Fraser).
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 11 years to get made and then made 11 cents,'' Wolf
said of ``School Ties.'' He added: ``I deserted the movie business
because of frustration. You can really get old waiting for pictures
to get made.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s, Wolf and his family had moved to Los Angeles
from New York. While writing film scripts, he also began working on
such television shows as ``Hill Street Blues'' and ``Miami Vice.''
In the meantime, he developed ``Law and Order'' for Fox, but it was
rejected by Barry Diller, who then ran the company. (Ironically,
Diller has now taken over Studios USA, which is producing the
show.) CBS also rejected it. Brandon Tartikoff, then the
entertainment chief at NBC, reluctantly agreed to take ``Law and
Order'' on the condition that Wolf also develop and work on a
series called ``Nasty Boys,'' about a Las Vegas police unit. To the
surprise of NBC, ``Nasty Boys'' died quickly. ``Law and Order,''
after a slow start, began building an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Cast turnover has marked the show _ partly because Wolf wants to
keep altering the characters to keep the series fresh, and partly
because some actors, like Benjamin Bratt, have wanted to move on to
film careers. In the new season, Steven Hill, who has long played
the grumpy district attorney, Adam Schiff, is being replaced by
Dianne Wiest.
</P>
<P>
   The actors on Wolf's shows speak of him with a bit of awe. ``I
get along with him fine, but I don't think he's an easygoing guy,''
said Jerry Orbach, whose career before ``Law and Order'' was, like
that of most of the actors on that show, on the New York stage.
``He's kind of a type A personality, on the phone a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Orbach added: ``I think Dick's special talent is that he crosses
a lot of lines and always surprises you. Some guys are good with
the police, some guys are good with the legal stuff, some have a
sense of humor, some are serious. Dick seems to have a little bit
of everything, and that's unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Law and Order'' and its spinoff, ``Law and Order: Special
Victims Unit'' (Fridays, 10-11 p.m.), which is in its second year,
``Deadline'' is set and filmed in New York. But its writing staff,
under Wolf, is based in Los Angeles at Universal Studios, whose
television division was sold to Studios USA.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth Wolf show, another spinoff of ``Law and Order,'' is also
in the works for NBC. Filming will probably start in December, with
13 episodes ready by the early summer, before the start of
threatened actor and writer strikes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's skills _ and his ambition _ are a bit grandiose, almost
like those of an old-time movie mogul. He is constantly on the run
between his home near Santa Barbara, where he lives with his wife
and three children, and the studio in Universal City, as well as
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always in evidence, whether he's in person or not,'' said
Platt. ``He's very hands-on. He's very collaborative. And he picks
extraordinarily talented people to run his shows.''
</P>
<P>
   To oversee ``Law and Order'' this season, for example, Wolf has
hired the 78-year-old Arthur Penn, the director of such celebrated
films as ``Bonnie and Clyde'' and ``The Miracle Worker,'' to serve
as the new executive producer. He replaces Ed Sherin, who had been
on the job for seven years and wanted to take a break.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Penn is a modest breakthrough for older
people on television, an industry where age discrimination is
notorious and writers, producers and directors over 50 or even 40
try to hide how old they are. Wolf is also using the 69-year-old
Ted Kotcheff, director of ``North Dallas 40,'' as executive
producer of ``Law and Order: Special Victims Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Wolf said. ``People are dropping off
credits on their resumes. They don't list `MASH' anymore because it
shows that they're older.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Wolf is blunt, energetic, a bit irascible and
independent-minded _ as well as highly successful _ seems to dazzle
and almost intimidate network executives. ``Dick's a bit of a
character; he's bigger than life,'' said Garth Ancier, president of
NBC Entertainment. ``He runs his organization like a well-oiled
machine. He has a very strong organization and has very, very good
taste in casting. He's shrewd. He gets you involved. He'll call and
say: `I have a great idea. Oliver Platt. I believe in him.' And
before you know it you're having breakfast with Oliver Platt. And
once you get Oliver Platt, you get Tom Conti and Bebe Neuwirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a call from Dick saying, `I want to bring in a new
D.A. on ``Law and Order,'' and I want to get Dianne Wiest.' How can
I complain about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger, the Studios USA Television executive, said: ``Happily
for us, he's married his talent with an insatiable ambition. Dick's
just not content to have one show on the air. He views himself as
building a company. His ambition is to try to duplicate the days of
MTM, which in some ways he's doing.'' (MTM, run by Grant Tinker and
Mary Tyler Moore, was a top television producer in the 1970s).
</P>
<P>
   Certainly ``Law and Order,'' entering its 11th season, has
stamped Wolf's career. Now that the show is the longest-running
drama series on network television, he has hopes of seeing it match
``Gunsmoke,'' which ran for 20 years, as the longest-running
prime-time drama series ever ``I want to beat `Gunsmoke,''' he
said. ``We're renewed until 2005. It'll be a shame if we don't go
for the record.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast to the characters on ABC's flashier ``NYPD Blue,''
officers and prosecutors on ``Law and Order'' are notable for their
absence of histrionics. Perhaps that is why ``Law and Order,''
although successful, has won only one Emmy as best drama series, in
1997, and why longtime cast members like Orbach and Sam Waterston
have never won.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is plainly annoyed. ``We've been wildly underappreciated by
the Emmys and the Writers Guild,'' he said. ``It's not flashy. It's
not showy. It's not that type of writing. Jerry Orbach keeps
saying, `Can't you guys put someone dying in my arms so I can cry
and take a long time and maybe win an award?'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such complaints, Wolf says he's doing exactly what he
wants to do, although the breakneck speed of television can leave
him bewildered and frustrated. ``I just try to hire extremely
obsessive people,'' he said. ``Otherwise it's so easy to get to
Episode 14, with eight to go. And you say, `Well, it's good
enough.' And once you say `it's good enough,' then it's bad, really
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like running a marathon. To churn out really A-level
work, it takes really obsessive-compulsive people.'' He laughed.
``Like me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
