<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LIBERANS-DEADLINE-BOS     09-26 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERANS-DEADLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE LIBERIANS FACE DEPORTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The notices, terse as they always are, came in this week's mail:
``We are writing to inform you that your employment authorization
expires on the 28th of September.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, 30-year-old Susan Shahda of Boston is worried about
how she'll provide for her two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Friday I won't have a job,'' Shahda said. ``What can I
do? I'm scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Shahda is one of the more than 10,000 Liberians who fled their
war-torn homeland in 1989 and have been living in refuge in the
United States ever since. They will lose their jobs Friday when
they become undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Emigres from the troubled West African nation, including an
estimated 4,000 living in New England, were granted temporary work
permits until conditions are safe for them to return. Though civil
strife continues in Liberia, their right to live and work in the
United States will become uncertain unless Congress or the White
House intervenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like that we have to live our lives like this. I can't
plan my life,'' said Mabel Dweh, who lives in Brockton, Mass. with
her two grown sons and daughter. ``We can't go back. Just by our
(tribal) name we would be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dweh, the notice of job termination in the mail is part of
an annual ritual, where each year at this time the president issues
a last-minute reprieve. A White House source said Saturday that
President Bill Clinton is likely to extend the Deferred Enforced
Departure for Liberians for another year.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Clinton would put Liberians in limbo for a 12th
year, even as they've watched Europeans and Asians who have
emigrated to the United States under similar conditions leapfrog to
become US residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say year after year, `We're going to send them back,' is an
aggravation of the trauma we've experienced,'' said Torli Krua,
president of the Liberian Community Association of Massachusetts.
``Another extension is a difficult thing. We are grateful, but
people can't live this way.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the Liberians who fled to the United States are
educated professionals who could afford the trans-Atlantic flight.
The United States didn't recognize them as refugees, so they
emigrated instead and were given Temporary Protected Status.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven-year civil war that displaced half of the Liberian
population and resulted in the deaths of more than 150,000 people
kept the United States from sending the Liberians back home.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in much of the country there is no electricity,
unemployment hovers at about 85 percent, political foes are still
in prison, and the government of President Charles Taylor remains
unstable. In fact, much of the West African region is in chaos:
Sierra Leone is in the midst of a bloody civil war, and warring
factions have destroyed much of Guinea and the Ivory Coast. A State
Department advisory warns Americans against traveling in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, as America _ particularly Rhode Island
and Massachusetts _ provided a safe haven for Liberians, they have
bought homes and raised children. While some say they would like to
return to their homeland one day, they say they know what going
back would mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no safety in the country,'' Dweh said. ``There is an
organized government but they have no control over the warring
factions.''
</P>
<P>
   When the civil war ended in 1997, US Attorney General Janet Reno
changed the status of Liberians from Temporary Protected Status to
Deferred Enforced Departure, a term that signaled they would
eventually have to leave. But Clinton has given extensions each
year since then because of the instability of the region.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, Congress granted residency to others
who had been here under Temporary Protected Status. According to an
aide of Rhode Island Senator Jack Reed, Congress in recent years
has allowed 4,996 Poles, 150,000 Nicaraguans, 200,000 Salvadorans,
and 52,968 Chinese to adjust their status to permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Reed sponsored a bill this session that would
allow Liberians to also become US residents. Reed said he will try
to attach the bill as a provision to one of several bills that will
be voted on before the session ends in early October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of simple justice. They are good people. They've
come here and they've worked hard,'' Reed said. ``They face an
uncertain prospect, if not fatal prospect, if they return to
Liberia.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed doesn't believe that racism is an underlying issue that has
kept US policy toward Liberian emigres intact. It has more to do
with avoiding setting a precedent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people deserve the opportunity to live more than year to
year,'' Reed said. ``Every year they worry that this year will be
their last in the US.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
