<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER VIDEOTAPE UPSETS FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
  By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The polite, if strained, cooperation that has long
marked the relationship between France's two leaders _ President
Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin _ came apart on
Tuesday, as their supporters hurled accusations of corruption and
political manipulation at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Each side said the other was trying to wiggle away from its role
in the growing scandal springing from a videotaped confession that
charges Chirac with running a illicit fund-raising scheme when he
was mayor of Paris and the leader of his conservative Rally for the
Republic party.
</P>
<P>
   While it is Chirac who is directly accused in the videotape, the
scandal has also engulfed Jospin since it became known on Monday
that his former finance minister had the tape for two years without
turning it over to authorities. On Tuesday night, authorities
officially placed the former minister, Dominique Strauss-Kahn,
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the parties seemed to be competing to tar each other with
the scandal, even as new evidence emerged suggesting that the man
who made the tape, a former party official who died of cancer last
year, was paid off not to go public with his story.
</P>
<P>
   Leading members of Chirac's party lashed out at Jospin for
denying any knowledge of the tape, which had been given to
Strauss-Kahn, in the summer of 1998. Jospin has said he knew
nothing of the tape until he read transcripts from it in the daily
Le Monde last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it astonishing that the prime minister, as soon as
there is a problem, never has any knowledge of it,'' said Michele
Alliot-Marie, the current president of Chirac's party. ``I find
that astonishing, even worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, at a Socialist meeting in Lyon, did not refer to Chirac
by name, but said that the uproar over Strauss-Kahn should not
overshadow the ``serious nature of the cases being investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marc Ayrault, the Socialist floor leader in the National
Assembly, went further, reminding Chirac that he would not always
enjoy presidential immunity. ``He should think twice about what
happens afterward, when justice can take its normal course.''
Ayrault said.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac has denied the charges on the tape made by Jean-Claude
Mery, a developer who was a member of the Rally for the Republic
governing committee in the 1980s. According to transcripts
published in Le Monde, Mery gave a detailed description of how he
ran a huge network of kickback schemes that netted the party
millions of dollars a year. On the tape, he says he worked under
the instructions of Chirac, and that he was even present one day
when Mery gave a Chirac aide about $700,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Mery, who had already spent five months in jail while a
magistrate pursued his investigation of the party for illicit
fund-raising, said on the tape that he was making it to protect
himself and because promises made to him had not been kept.
</P>
<P>
   The tape emerged when a journalist, Arnaud Hamelin, who had
helped Mery make the tape, took it to Le Monde. Mery had wanted the
tape to be made public if he died under suspicious circumstances.
The journalist was authorized to do what he wanted with the tape if
he died, as he did, of natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Le Monde said that investigators searching a bank
vault had found two letters Mery had written addressed simply to
``Mr. President.'' In them, he complained that he had only been
paid about $13,000 for staying quiet. The paper said one letter
appeared to be an original, suggesting it had never been sent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite searching the home and office of Strauss-Kahn on Monday
night, investigators have not yet found the original copy of the
Mery videotape. The weekly magazine L'Express, which first reported
that Strauss-Kahn had the tape, said it had been given to him by a
lawyer, who helped Mery make his tape, in exchange for a tax break
for one of his other clients, Karl Lagerfeld, the fashion designer.
Lagerfeld denied any impropriety in the handling of his taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss-Kahn, who was forced last year to resign his ministerial
post after allegations of false accounting at his law firm, also
denied all wrongdoing. He said Lagerfeld had eventually paid about
half of what he owed in a negotiated transaction that was a routine
way of handling such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss-Kahn urged everyone to focus on the real issue: the
implication of the chief of state in a scandal. ``The tree must not
hide the forest,'' he said Tuesday on Europe 1 radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
