<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-3COM-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      09-26 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM'S REPORTED LOSS IS LESS THAN ANTICIPATED 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ 3Com Corp. reported a smaller-than-expected
first-quarter loss Tuesday, citing a reorganization that included
its exit from the analog modem and network router businesses in the
previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 1, 3Com posted a loss of $59.2
million, or 17 cents a share, compared with earnings of $137.5
million, or 38 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Sales
fell 23 percent, to $933.8 million from $1.21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sales included $127.5 million from the businesses it left.
Excluding that revenue, 3Com's continuing businesses accounted for
$806.3 million in sales, a rise of 20 percent over comparable sales
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time charges and gains as well as income from
discontinued operations, 3Com's quarterly loss was $41.3 million,
or 12 cents a share. Analysts had expected a loss of 33 cents a
share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Before 3Com reported its results, its shares closed at $13.94,
down 6 cents, in Nasdaq trading. In after-hours trading, however,
3Com rose more than 15 percent, climbing as high as $16.06.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of 3Com had retreated from a 52-week high, reached before
the divestiture in July of Palm Inc., which many analysts
considered the most valuable part of the company. 3Com now has a
market value of $4.86 billion, while Palm, which handily beat
analysts' earnings estimates, is valued at $31.36 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The close of our first quarter marks the completion of our
restructuring,'' said Eric Benhamou, the chairman and chief
executive of 3Com, in a statement. ``The transformation milestones
and business objectives set forth in March 2000 and reaffirmed last
quarter were completed on or ahead of schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the spinoff of Palm and the reorganization, 3Com
is focused primarily on broadband products and wireless devices for
consumers and small businesses, and infrastructure equipment for
companies that provide telecommunications and Internet services.
The move cedes much of the market for corporate networks to Cisco
Systems Inc., which has proved to be the more aggressive
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   3Com said that, excluding sales from the exited businesses,
first-quarter sales for its commercial and consumer networks
business were $639.1 million, a 24 percent increase over the fourth
quarter. First-quarter sales for its carrier networking business
were $167.2 million, a rise of 7 percent compared with sales of
$156.7 million in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
