<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-CORPORATE-PR-NY     09-26 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CORPORATE-PR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS JAPANESE COMPANIES FALTER, A SURGE IN CRISIS MANAGEMENT  
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKI TANIKAWA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Tokyo Chamber of Commerce and Industry thought it
might be a good idea to prepare a handbook for member companies
interested in learning how to cope more effectively with the media
during a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Its idea was so good the chamber badly underestimated the
demand. The 1,000 copies it had printed in mid-July sold out in a
day. To catch up, it printed an additional 37,000, then 5,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate Japan has suddenly awakened to the need for crisis
control. Unsettled because of the public relations blunders
committed by big Japanese companies like Bridgestone, Mitsubishi
Motors and Snow Brand in recent weeks, Japanese managers are
scrambling to learn how to avoid the appearance of looking
irresponsible and uncaring.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in charge of general affairs or public relations are
collecting books and literature on crisis management, calling
consultants for seminars and training sessions, and rethinking the
way their companies handle public crises.
</P>
<P>
   Tatsumi Tanaka, a Tokyo crisis management consultant, said his
firm had been swamped with requests for lectures and seminars _ 10
times the requests he had been getting before July, when
revelations of corporate skulduggery seemed to start coming all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   First there was a scandal at Snow Brand, a leading producer of
milk and dairy products, which was held responsible for a food
poisoning that sickened more than 10,000 people. Then Mitsubishi
Motors admitted it had concealed customer complaints about faulty
automobiles for more than two decades. More recently, Bridgestone
has been criticized in the Japanese media over the defective tires
sold by the company's Firestone subsidiary, mostly in the United
States. Bridgestone officials, who at first seemed to treat the
scandal as a minor event in a foreign country, are now grappling
with public relations damage here in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading economic daily,
editorialized recently that while Ford conducted a highly effective
public relations campaign that blamed the tires, ``Bridgestone's
silence strategy failed in that it only bred mistrust in consumers
and investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Glen Fukushima, president in Japan of the consulting firm Arthur
D. Little, said: ``PR is not considered all that important. You can
see that from the fact that public relations is not a big industry
here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 200 public relations firms in Japan, a fraction
of the number in the United States, and the majority of them are
one-man operations. Most public relations work at these firms
revolves around product and service promotions and rarely deals
with crisis management.
</P>
<P>
   A survey done by the Tokyo Chamber of Commerce of member
companies showed that only 11 percent of the respondents said they
would contact a public relations firm or an advertising agency when
a major crisis hit their company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with the media in a crisis is where Japanese companies
are the weakest,'' said Atsushi Kuse, a crisis management expert.
Consequently, he said, their response to the public often deviates
wildly from what the public perceives as right.
</P>
<P>
   Companies implicated in scandal often admit to only a small
portion of what later turns out to be a systematic flaw in the
company's products or quality control, as was the case with
Mitsubishi and Snow Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, chief executives utter inadvertent remarks as they
flounder through news conferences. When Snow Brand's president,
Tetsuro Ishikawa, who resigned in disgrace in July, was confronted
with a reporter asking him why he decided to cut short the news
conference, Ishikawa replied under the gaze of TV cameras: ``You! I
haven't even been sleeping these days.'' The nationally televised
scene was broadcast repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate attitudes toward public relations in Japan have been
shaped partly by the country's postwar economic boom, when
manufacturers mass-produced quality products at what were
considered fair prices, industrial companies grew and people's
standard of living rose.
</P>
<P>
   The small number of consumer complaints were ignored or
suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   But the sensibilities of Japanese consumers have changed
drastically in recent years. Their tastes have diversified and they
are armed with information tools that they can use to compare
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan's society is changing,'' Tanaka said. ``Companies
haven't realized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Tanaka is called in by a scandal-hit company to
consult, he said, the management often remains dishonest. ``First,
they lie to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another new variable is the gradual demise of Japan's lifetime
employment. The readiness of many big companies to shed unwanted
workers is spawning a growing number of disgruntled workers who no
longer display the loyalty to their employers they once did.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Mitsubishi cover-up scandal came to light when an
insider tipped off transport ministry officials about the car
company's practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
