<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMMIGRANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROMISES BUDGET VETO OVER IMMIGRATION ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is threatening to veto a
multibillion-dollar spending bill unless Republicans agree to
include a provision allowing certain Latinos and other immigrants
to stay in the country, the White House confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration matter is of great importance to Hispanic
voters, a constituency that could make the difference in the
presidential race as well as in several races for the House, where
the Republicans' thin majority is under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats called it a question of basic decency,
saying a bureaucratic glitch has prevented otherwise eligible
immigrants from gaining permanent residency status. The measure,
sponsored by Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts,
would grant green cards to qualified immigrants who have been
living in the United States since before 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's veto threat had Republicans complaining of a White
House pattern of making policy to assist Vice President Al Gore in
what is shaping up as the closest presidential race in recent
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about electoral politics,'' said John Czwartacki,
spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Republican of
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are completely shameless,'' fumed John Feehery, spokesman
for House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, Republican of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway denied the charge. ``The president
is doing his job, and administering policies to help the American
people,'' Hattway said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton announced a $1.7 million grant to fight
domestic violence in New Mexico, a competititve state in the
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton announced he would release 30 million barrels
of oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, a move intended to
ease home heating oil costs. The annoucement came the day after
Gore called for the release of oil from the emergency reserve, and
is likely to benefit homeowners in the battleground states of the
industrial Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   There's no ambiguity who would benefit from the immigration
measure, titled The Latino and Immigrant Fairness Act. Hispanics
are a key voting groups in Florida, perhaps the most important
presidential battleground state. In California, Latinos could make
the difference in several House races _ contests the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee says could tip the balance of
power in the House from Republican to Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the Latino community, immigration issues hit
close to home,'' said Alejandro Perez, executive director of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus. ``You can get a sense of who is for
you and who is not. This will come up (in the campaigns), and the
records of Democrats and Republicans will be highlighted,'' Perez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats met with Clinton last week, winning a
promise that he would veto more than $36 billion in funding for
programs administered by the Commerce, State and Justice
Departments if the immigration measure was not included. Clinton
demanded that Democratic leaders prove they had the votes to
sustain the threatened veto, a test the congressional Democrats met
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The veto threat is a powerful tool. Since the agencies must get
funded, Congress could be forced into an unwanted, post-election
session to finish the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll back them up,'' confirmed White House spokesman Jake
Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Luis Gutierrez, Democrat of Ilinois, denied that
the pressure to pass the immigration bill was meant as a political
ploy. But he did hint at the potential for political fallout,
adding: ``If you want to show Latinos that you mean what you say,
this is the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the immigration dispute threatens to hold up passage
of a widely supported bill to extend special visas for skilled
workers, a measure Massachusetts techology firms say they
desperately need to fill job openings.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats charge that the Republican leadership is
refusing to bring the visa bill up for a vote, afraid that
Democrats would try to attach the immigration language to it and
force the Republicans into an up-or-down vote on an issue so
important to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're afraid of is charges of racism by the Democrats,
who like to charge racism any chance they get,'' Feehery said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
