<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Their Hearts' Desires 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; President Clinton &LR;  attended a book party for former adviser  &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; Begala &LR; 's ``Is Our Children Learning?'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster; $12), at
which the Washington Post overheard him telling reporters that
 &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  has a crush on actor  &UR; Jimmy Smits &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Hillary sees him, her knees start knocking,'' said
the president. Smits, for the record, is the pride of his
birthplace, Brooklyn, N.Y., where voters live.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HOW TO SUCCEED IN BUSINESS REALLY TRYING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The latest issue of Mademoiselle, a magazine that's gone beyond
prescribing the proper length of gloves for every occasion, gives
the working woman a few tips for ``on-the-job mind control'' when
the boss is nasty and demanding. Three of the easiest:
</P>
<P>
   _ Offer a handshake called the Topper, with palm facing the
ground when you extend it. This ``subtle power move,'' says
leadership trainer  &UR; Robert Brown &LR; , will tend to subjugate its
object.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mirror the boss' every move. ``When Boss Lady brushes her hair
away from her eyes, you do the same. She reaches for her water? You
sip, too.'' The boss will ``feel inexplicably positive toward you
afterward,'' says anthropologist  &UR; Kate Fox &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Look more intelligent by working with your tongue slightly
exposed, and keep your desk clear. ``Toys and personal photos are
associated with weakness,'' says  &UR; Perry Buffington &LR; , who wrote
``Cheap Psychological Tricks for Lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GOODS AND SERVICES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Revolution, a rave magazine that calls itself ``the new music
manifesto,'' describes Zero, a slushlike frozen cola drink to be
squeezed into the mouth:
</P>
<P>
   ``An interesting footnote: Packaged in a foil sack shaped like a
bottle, the product bears a strange resemblance to an intravenous
bag, especially when it's not frozen. However, company sources
confirm that Zero is intended for oral use only.'' For the
decaffeinated crowd, it also comes in cherry, berry and grape
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   _ W reports that 7-Eleven is introducing Heart and Soul, its own
line of cosmetics, this fall. Furthermore, for those who can't get
clothes fast enough, urbanfetch.com, a delivery Web site, promises
same-day service to New Yorkers who order their clothing by 1 p.m.
on a weekday. ``I think immediacy is a big dark horse for online
retailers,'' said retail analyst  &UR; Ken &LR; 
 &UR; Cassar &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barbara Bush &LR;  is so upset by negative TV reports about her
son's campaign, reports the New York Post, that her husband uses
headphones to watch the morning news. And reader  &UR; Harriet Jackson &LR; 
is staying inside and suffering the effects of the campaign:
Agore-aphobia.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
