<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.27.00
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris and John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Teens' tech savvy concerns, confuses parents
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lights, camera, auction! Movie buffs get shot at stardom
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dandy'' Oscar: Cagney's estate on the block
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For fans of celebrities, charity begins on the Net
</P>
<P>
   TECH GAP: The thing that concerns parents more than the
commercial exploitation of children is the impact of technology,
says Enola Aird, director of the Motherhood Project at the
Institute for American Values. ``It is changing the experience of
childhood,'' says Aird. ``All the traditional boundaries that
protected children from the adult world are coming down.'' Some say
it is arguably the most significant demarcation between generations
in history. Says Mary Kay Blakely, author of ``American Mom:''
``Not only are we being bumped off the demographic map,'' but
teenagers are ``bringing along a culture that we know diddly-squat
about. It's unseemly. We can't hand them the baton; they already
have the baton. They're inventing the baton.''
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S ENTERTAINMENT? Netheads who want to be in pictures are
going online to raise more than $500,000 for an upcoming feature
film that has no title, script or major studio behind it. Since
June, a Yahoo-sponsored Web site has been auctioning
``sponsorships'' to star, produce or play bit roles in the flick.
Adam Rifkin (``Mouse Hunt,'' ``Small Soldiers'') is writing a
script to display the diverse personalities of the online bidders
who already have been cast, including a kick-boxing champ, a
General Motors employee, a florist and a psychic. The auction
continues until Oct. 10 to fill four other acting roles and two
producing positions. A band to score the movie also is being
sought. The total budget, including online auction proceeds, is
$1.5 million, most of which was raised by four companies
underwriting the project.
</P>
<P>
   www.whowantstobeamoviestar
</P>
<P>
   .com
</P>
<P>
   CAGNEY'S LOOT: Want a piece of Jimmy Cagney? Then log on this
evening to ``AuctionLive: The Treasures of James Cagney,'' a live
show on the Pax Network from 6 to 7 p.m. (WPXA, VCR-Plus code
60485) and at ibidlive.tv. Up for grabs: items from the estate of
Cagney and his wife, actress Frances Vernon, including his best
actor Oscar for ``Yankee Doodle Dandy.'' The auction is being
conducted by Doyle New York.
</P>
<P>
   www.ibidlive.tv
</P>
<P>
   E-GIVING: Have a big heart, feel like a big spender, hang out
with bigwigs. That's the concept behind Stargiving.com, a new Web
site that mixes fame with philanthropy. Visitors can click on icons
of ex-NBA star Magic Johnson, Darius Rucker of Hootie &AMP; the
Blowfish, supermodel Niki Taylor or boxing legend Muhammad Ali.
When they do, the site's corporate sponsors kick in a donation (up
to a dime per visit) to the celebrity's favorite charity. The
celebrity with the most clicks wins, and his or her charity gets a
corporate donation. Visitors also can enter a raffle for a chance
to spend face time with their favorite celeb (hoops with Magic,
golf with Rucker, etc.). The only catch: To qualify for a celebrity
``experience,'' you must be at least 18 and submit you name and
phone number in case you win.
</P>
<P>
   www.stargiving.com
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
   The threat of Tropical Storm Helene drove hits to Marietta-based
the Weather Channel's Web site, weather.com, for the week ended
Sept. 24:
</P>
<P>
   LAST WEEK
</P>
<P>
   AVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   100 million67.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Page views for the week, up 47.7 percent from the average week.
</P>
<P>
   14.3 million9.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Average daily views soared 47.4 percent. They peaked Friday at
18.3 million, nearly double the normal daily figure.
</P>
<P>
   850,000600,000
</P>
<P>
   The number of unique visitors climbed 41.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Weather Channel
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.27.00
</P>
<P>
   SIGHTS &AMP; SITES
</P>
<P>
   Today is Getaway day in Living, so here are some extra travel
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Does morning chill
</P>
<P>
   having you feeling Fiji?
</P>
<P>
   Did this morning's temps, forecast to be in the high 40s,
trigger an urge for warmer climates? With its recent political
crisis resolved, resorts in Fiji are falling over themselves trying
to refill their rooms, offering price breaks of at least 35
percent. The island nation has launched a campaign called ``Warm
Days, Cool Deals''; the deals are good through March 31.
</P>
<P>
   www.warmdayscooldeals.com
</P>
<P>
   Site passes along
</P>
<P>
   savings at city sights
</P>
<P>
   CityPass is a program now available in seven U.S. cities that
allows pass holders to visit a group of top attractions at a cost
far less than if tickets were bought individually. The cities are
Philadelphia, Boston, Chicago, Seattle, San Francisco, Hollywood
and New York. (Wonder if the Braves have any spare time during the
current series with the Mets to do a little sightseeing?)
</P>
<P>
   www.citypass.net
</P>
<P>
   A site to do
</P>
<P>
   before you say `I do'
</P>
<P>
   Need some quick help planning that honeymoon to follow your
December wedding? Try this newly upgraded site, which comes
complete with free e-mail, message boards and chat rooms, and
related information.
</P>
<P>
   www.weddingwizard.com
</P>
<P>
   EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   'TOON TALK: Find out how modern-day animators create lifelike
movies for Hollywood, using everything from stop-motion effects to
Imax technology, in this live chat hosted by Pat Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on discovery.com
</P>
<P>
   CHAN CHAT: Get your kicks with martial arts action star Jackie
Chan as he talks about his chop-socky movie career and his new
cartoon on the KidsWB, ``Jackie Chan Adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on chat.yahoo.com
</P>
<P>
   ROCK RAP: OK, all you jabronis and roody poos, the Rock wants
you to vote. Talk to the World Wrestling Federation star about his
three championship belts and his unconventional political views.
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on chat.yahoo.com
</P>
