<HEADER>
A2629 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-GETAWAY27-COX     09-26 2667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GETAWAY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get in shape for holiday festival sprint
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Michelle Brooks and Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you strung all the Christmas lights illuminating Southern
celebrations each holiday season, it would probably stretch to the
North Pole and back. But before Santa squeezes down any fireplaces,
there are plenty of celebrations of fall colors and thanksgiving to
attend across the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast Tourism Society, an Atlanta-based organization
that promotes travel to the region, has released its quarterly Top
20 Events listing for the months of October, November and December,
compiled here.
</P>
<P>
   The year is rushing by. Enjoy one or more of these festivities
to savor the season, Deep South style.
</P>
<P>
   O C T O B E R
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 4-22: Gatlinburg Craftmen's Fair, Gatlinburg, Tenn.
Mountain arts and crafts event showcases quilting, woodcarving,
pottery, calligraphy and metal+work. 865-436-7479,
www.craftsmenfair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-8: BayFest, Mobile, Ala. Downtown Mobile hosts more
than 100 musical acts from genres such as jazz, R&AMP;B, rock, country,
Latin and gospe. 1-800-566-2453, www.bayfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-7: Unicoi County Apple Festival, Erwin, Tenn.
Celebrates the culture of the Southern Appalachian region. Includes
the Apple Festival Gospel Concert, the Blue Ridge Pottery Show and
an expanded children's area. 423-743-3000, www.unicoicounty.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-8: St. James Court Art Show, Louisville, Ky. As many as
300,000 visitors will converge on St. James Court and adjacent
streets to view displays of jewelry, metal sculpture, woodcarving,
pottery and glasswork. 502-635-1842, www.stjamescourtartshow.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-8: International Music and Cultural Festival, Lake
Charles, La. Downtown fest features top musicians from southwest
Louisiana, educational workshops, cultural performances and a
children's carnival. 1-800-456-7952, www.visitlakecharles.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-15: Georgia National Fair, Perry. A carnival midway,
fireworks and livestock exhibits, plus concerts by Kenny Rogers,
Loretta Lynn, the Coasters and other acts. 1-800-987-3247,
www.gnfa.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7-8: Prater's Mill Country Fair, Varnell. Held at an old
water-powered mill that still grinds corn and wheat, the festival
features crafts, a Civil War encampment, a petting zoo and
wandering musicians. 706-694-6455, www.pratersmill.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7-29: Oktoberfest, Winter Haven, Fla. A bit of Bavaria at
Cypress Gardens, with yodeling, alphorns, Southern belles dressed
as frauleins and feasts of bratwurst, German potato salad, kraut
and Bavarian beers. 1-800-282-2123, www.cypressgardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7: Brushy Mountain Apple Festival, North Wilkesboro, N.C.
See a horse-powered molasses mill at work, apple butter making,
Civil War and Revolutionary War re-enactments plus 350 arts and
crafts booths. 336-984-3022, www.applefestival.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 8: 20th Annual Taste of Charleston, Charleston, S.C.
Boone Hall Plantation becomes a showcase for more than 50
Charleston-area restaurants. Lowcountry boils, Gullah cuisine, the
Waiters' Wine Race, ice carving competitions and wine tastings.
843-577-4030.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 11-28: Natchez Fall Pilgrimage, Natchez, Miss. Eighteen
antebellum homes will be open for tours, plus entertainment every
evening. 1-800-647-6742, www.natchezpilgrimage.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 13-15: Trigg County Ham Festival, Cadiz, Ky. View the
world's largest country ham and biscuit, plus music acts, a quilt
show, classic cars, a carnival and kids' circus. 270-522-3892.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 13-15: Autumn Leaves Festival, Mount Airy, N.C. With the
fall leaves at their peak colors and mountain music by regional
artists filling the air, more than 100 juried craftsmen demonstrate
their skills. 336-786-6116.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 14: HUBfest, Hattiesburg, Miss. Street festival in
historic downtown setting with three stages of entertainment, arts
and crafts, food and a KIDSfest area for children. 1-800-238-4288,
www.theadp.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 14-15: A Day to Remember of Colonial Times, North
Augusta, S.C. Event focuses on the living history of Colonial times
with period dress, crafts demonstrations, traditional food and
re-enactments. 803-279-2323, www.southfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 18-21: Washington Parish Free Fair, Franklinton, La. _
Rodeo, musical entertainment, arts and crafts exhibits, Old
McDonald's Farm, midway rides, games and food. www.freefair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 21: International Gold Cup, The Plains, Va. _ Top
steeplechase jockeys compete in seven races over brush, timber and
fences. Also pony races and a Jack Russell terrier race.
1-800-697-2237, www.vagoldcup.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 28: 12th Annual Jack Daniels World Championship Cookoff,
Lynchburg, Tenn. _ Jack Daniel's Distillery hosts 30 teams that
compete for honors in five classes. Also features games, crafts,
pig races, music, square dancing and food. 931-759-6180.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 28: Guavaween, Ybor City, Tampa. It's Halloween _ Latin
style _ in this National Landmark District, with live music,
costume contests, the Mama Guava Stumble Parade and scavenger hunt.
813-621-7121, www.ybor.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 28-29: Alabama Renaissance Faire, Florence. Downtown
Wilson Park is transformed into a period fair with authentic
costumes, arts, crafts, wandering minstrels, elephant rides, music,
dancing and drama. 256-766-3234.
</P>
<P>
   N O V E M B E R
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 1-Dec. 31: Christmas in Charleston, Charleston, S.C.
Santa in Candy Cane Lane, the Holiday Festival of Lights, concerts,
a parade of boats and a tour of homes. 1-800-868-8118,
www.charlestoncvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 3-4: Louisiana Gumbo Festival, Ville Platte, La. Tribute
to South Louisiana Cajun culture features national entertainers,
swamp pop artists, Cajun cuisine (including a gumbo cookoff) and
arts and crafts booths. 337-363-5751.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 3-4: 38th semi-annual Bluegrass Superjam, Cullman, Ala.
National and local talents break out the fiddles, banjos and
dulcimers to play music with a Southern heritage. Also buck
dancing, string bands, gospel groups, mountain singers, food and
arts and crafts. 256-747-1650 or 256-734-0454.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 4-5: Peter Anderson Memorial Arts, Crafts &AMP; Food
Festival, Ocean Springs, Miss. Named in honor of the late potter,
the event is held in the historic tree-lined downtown district and
includes displays of jewelry, watercolors and stained glass.
228-875-4424.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 7-Jan. 2: Christmas at Biltmore Estate, Asheville, N.C.
George Vanderbilt's famous holiday celebrations are re-created with
hundreds of handmade ornaments and seasonal songs on the Banquet
Hall's 1916 pipe organ. 1-800-543-2961, www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 8-Feb. 24, 2001: Pigeon Forge Winterfest, Pigeon Forge,
Tenn. More than 6 million lights illuminate town streets and
Dollywood. Events include Wilderness Wildlife Week and the Smoky
Mountains Storytelling Festival. 1-800-251-9100,
www.mypigeonforge.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 9-12: 19th Annual Dickens Christmas Show &AMP; Festival,
Myrtle Beach, S.C. Costumed Dickens characters, vendors in period
dress, decorations, carolers, and an appearance by Gerald Dickens,
the author's great-great grandson. 843-448-9483,
www.dickenschristmasshow.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 10-Feb. 28, 2001: Gatlinburg Winterfest Smoky Mountain
Lights, Gatlinburg, Tenn. Besides the holiday sparkle of 2 million
lights in displays throughout town, this fest serves up a chili
cookoff and musical entertainment. 1-800-568-4748,
www.gatlinburg-tennessee.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 10-12: Native American Festival: Wilmington, N.C. Native
Americans in traditional dress share their customs, culture, food
and dances. See craft demonstrations of beadwork and pottery.
910-686-9518, www.poplargrove.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 11-12: Christmas City U.S.A., Biloxi, Miss. Holiday
activities at the Mississippi Coast Coliseum and Convention Center
include choirs, a children's crafts area, an exhibit of reindeer
and costumed characters from the North Pole. 228-896-9336.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 16-Dec. 30: Christmas Island, Somerset, Ky. General
Burnside State Park is transformed into a winter wonderland with
one of Kentucky's largest outdoor Christmas lighting displays.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-642-6287, www.lakecumberlandtourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 17-Dec. 27: Callaway Gardens Fantasy in Lights, Pine
Mountain, Ga. More than 3 million lights form more than a dozen
spectacular displays. Includes the Callaway Christmas Village,
featuring craftspeople demonstrating their skills, entertainment
and costumed characters. 1-800-225-5292, www.callawaygardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 17-Dec. 30: Rock City's Enchanted Garden of Lights,
Lookout Mountain. Over a half-million twinkling lights create 25
Christmas scenes. Also, nightly holiday concerts. 706-820-2531,
www.seerockcity.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 17-Dec. 31: Magical Nights of Lights, Lake Lanier
Islands, Buford, Ga. Twinkling stars, snowflakes and sparkling
lights along a 6 1/2-mile drive; also, Santa's Workshop and Holiday
Village. 770-932-7200, www.lakelanierislands.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 18-Jan. 31: Nights of Lights, St. Augustine, Fla. Follow
more than 1 million twinkling white lights across the Bridge of
Lions into the massive Castillo de San Marcos fortress. Events
include the Regatta of Lights, Las Posadas candlelight parade and
historical re-enactments. 1-800-653-2489, www.oldcity.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 21-Jan. 1: Winter Wonderland of Lights, Ashland, Ky.
Ashland, along with neighboring communities Boyd and Greenup
counties, is transformed into a holiday light showcase.
606-329-1007, www.winterwonderland.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 24-Dec. 30: Christmas in Roseland, Shreveport, La. The
188-acre park boasts 1 million lights, nightly entertainment, a
huge display of electric trains and intricately designed railroad
scenes. Sing along with school and church choirs. 318-938-5402.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 25-Dec. 3: Pirates in Paradise 2000, Key West, Fla. The
Historic Seaport &AMP; Harborwalk is transformed into a Caribbean
pirate's stronghold. Highlights include the Literature &AMP; the Sea
Writers Symposium, the Swashbucklers Film Festival, daily pirate
sails and sea battles. 305-296-9653, www.piratesinparadise.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 26-Dec. 2: Christmas on the River, Demopolis, Ala. A
weeklong festival including concerts and play performances, home
tours and an arts and crafts show. The grand finale is lighted, and
features animated floats accompanied by a tremendous fireworks
show. 334-289-0270.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nov. 30-Dec. 3: The Bizarre Bazaar's 25th Christmas
Collection, Richmond. Holiday marketplace featuring 440 exhibitors
selected from the best craft and gift shows in America.
804-673-6280.
</P>
<P>
   D E C E M B E R
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 1, 8, 15: Dickens of a Christmas, Roanoke, Va.
Victorian-style parade, costumed strolling performers, group
caroling, jugglers and magicians. 540-342-2028,
www.downtownroanoke.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 1-26: Christmas Town U.S.A., McAdenville, N.C. This small
textile town along the South Fork River is transformed as 375
trees, up to 65 feet in height, come to life with a half million
red and green lights. 704-824-3551, Ext. 260,
users.vnet.net/srankin/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 1-31: A Cajun &AMP; Creole Christmas, Lafayette, La. Holiday
festivities with a French Louisiana flair, featuring a festival of
lights, parades, tours of historic homes and plantations, and
performances by the area's best choirs. 337-232-3737,
www.lafayettetravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 1-31: Christmas New Orleans Style, New Orleans. Visits by
colorful historical characters, costumed carolers, free cooking
demonstrations, free nightly holiday concerts at St. Louis
Cathedral, tours of 19th-century homes and Kwanzaa and Hanukkah
events. 504-522-5730, www.frenchquarterfestivals.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 1-31: White Columns &AMP; Holly _ Christmas in Macon.
Thousands of lights illuminate the architecture as choirs perform
on downtown corners. Guided walking tours and carriage rides, tours
of garland-bedecked mansions. Performances from ``The Nutcracker''
to ``A Nigerian Christmas.'' 912-743-3401, www.maconga.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 2-3: Old Wilmington by Candlelight, Wilmington, N.C.
Historic homes and churches decorated for the holidays are
connected by streets lined with luminaries and festive music.
910-762-0492.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 2-3: Winterfestival _ a Celebration of Lights, Music and
the Arts, Tallahassee. Citywide event includes theater, music and
activities such as the Jingle Bell Run, a parade and the
Celebration of Lights. 850-891-3866, www.ci.tallahassee.fl.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 2-3: Marietta Pilgrimage Christmas Home Tour, Marietta.
Six decorated homes in the Church/Cherokee Historic District are
the focal point for day and candlelight tours. 770-429-1115,
www.mariettasquare.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 3-23: Christmas at the Old Capitol, Jackson, Miss. A
30-foot Mississippi cedar decorated in the style of 1870-1880s
stands in the rotunda. Underneath are period toys, including model
trains zipping around their tracks and through the miniature town
of Possum Ridge; includes Sunday musical performances.
601-359-6920, www.mdah.state.ms.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 7-8: Victorian Christmas, Thomasville. Locals in
Victorian finery welcome visitors with hot wassail and Christmas
delicacies, musicians entertain on the streets, jugglers perform,
carolers sing, and sleigh bells on horse carriages jingle.
912-227-7020.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 7-10: Victorian Front Porch Christmas, Opelika, Ala.
Opelika streets are transformed into a Victorian Christmas village
with Old World Christmas figures by local artist Jan Jones adorning
porches of more than 40 turn-of-the-century homes along with
lifesize Santas and angels. 1-800-321-8880.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 9: Annual Christmas Parade of Boats, Charleston, S.C. The
four-hour procession travels from Wando Terminal through Charleston
Harbor with a fireworks salute from Castle Pinckney, then along the
river to the Charleston City Marina. 843-762-2172, www.ccprc.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 9-10: 15th Annual Dickens of a Christmas, Franklin, Tenn.
Costumed characters _ including Scrooge _ mingle with the crowds,
strolling minstrels and ``living windows'' entertain, artists and
crafters demonstrate old-fashioned skills. 615-791-9924.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 9-10: Victorian Candlelit Christmas, Hattiesburg, Miss.
The streets of the historic district are lined with 15,000
luminaries. Visitors stroll or ride carriages and trolleys along
candlelit streets, by historic homes decorated in Victorian style,
to the sound of carolers. 601-268-3220.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 9-26: Christmas in Hopelands, Aiken, S.C. Guests are
treated to cookies and cocoa as they wander garden paths, taking in
more than 70,000 lights. Holiday concerts, a craft show and
self-guided tours of the Thoroughbred Racing Hall of Fame.
803-642-7631, www.aiken.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 10: Historic Tour of St. Augustine ``Olde World Christmas
Tours,'' St. Augustine, Fla. Sixteen historic bed-and-breakfast
inns put on their holiday finest and share holiday treats and
refreshments. 904-829-9438 or 904-829-0079,
www.staugustineinns.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 11: Christmas on the Coosa, Wetunka, Ala. Brightly
lighted floats and fireworks illuminate the dark waters of the
Coosa River, with riverbanks aglow with hundreds of flares. The
Elmore County Black Heritage Association also opens its museum.
334-567-5147.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 16: Salem Christmas, Winston-Salem, N.C. Moravian-style
observance includes candlelight tours at dusk. 1-888-653-7253,
www.oldsalem.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 29: Liberty Bowl, Memphis. Weeklong series of events
leads up to the game featuring two of the nation's best college
football teams. Activities include a parade down Beale Street,
black tie dinner at the Peabody and a pregame tailgate party at the
Mid-South Coliseum. 901-795-7700, www.libertybowl.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dec. 31: Orange Bowl Parade, Miami. A two-hour nighttime
spectacle with more than 100 floats, bands and groups.
305-371-4600, www.orangebowl.org.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Doug Hamilton, Michelle Brooks, Howard Pousner for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
