<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2631 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CELTIC-STABBING-BOS &LR;      09-26 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTIC-STABBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEEK SUSPECT IN STABBING OF BASKETEBAL STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR AND SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Police are looking for a local rap artist in the early
Monday stabbing that left Boston Celtics star Paul Pierce
recovering from numerous stab wounds, a police source said.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators Tuesday night sought to question 27-year-old
Michael McNeill _ a rapper with a history of arrests and ties to
the controversial rap group Made Men _ a close friend of Pierce who
helped drive him to the hospital adamantly denied media reports
that the stabbing was a revenge attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul does not know any of these guys, period,'' said Derrick
Battie, speaking publicly for the first time since he and his
brother, Tony Battie, witnessed the stabbing and intervened to stop
it. ``Neither does Tony, neither do I. . . . We've never had a
confrontation, ever, with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, two members of Made Men acknowledged being at the
party at the Buzz Club that Pierce had attended with two close
friends, but denied any involvement in the knifing.
</P>
<P>
   But a police source said the investigation was now focusing on
McNeil, whose ties to Made Men date back at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, McNeill recorded songs with Made Men front-man
Raymond ``Ray Dog'' Scott for the record ``Wiseguys,'' a
collaboration of rappers and former rivals from Boston's infamous,
hard-core gangs.
</P>
<P>
   McNeill recorded the track ``Manhood'' for the album, which
Scott promoted in 1998 as preaching unity and urging youth to
reject the hustle of guns, drugs and turf.
</P>
<P>
   But as recently as July, McNeill was arrested for driving a
stolen car and driving without a license. And in 1996, he and three
other defendants were charged with kidnapping and assault in a
brutal case in which they allegedly pulled in front of a hous in
the city's Roxbury section, dragged a bound and gagged man into an
apartment and held him prisoner until he broke through a window,
bleeding and screaming for help.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others arrested in that incident was Robert Daniels,
whom witnesses then identified as a member of Made Men.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of Made Men, Leroy Peoples, said he knew McNeill,
but that the rapper was not a member of the rap group.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from the industry,'' Peoples said. ``But he's not one of
Made Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Battie, whose brother, Tony Battie, plays for the Celtics, said
he had spent most of the day Monday at New England Medical Center,
where Pierce was recovering from stab wounds to the neck, face and
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, tedious 48 hours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Battie said that he, his brother and Pierce often go out and
spend time together, and are careful to steer clear of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Of Pierce, he said, ``I don't think Paul was a target. I would
not say any guys we hang out with are targets. It's just one of
those ignorant situations where someone gets unruly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald reported the attack on Pierce stemmed from a
confrontation Pierce had had the night before outside another
lounge. Other broadcast reports said that the assault was tied to a
dispute over a woman.
</P>
<P>
   While denying that Pierce was deliberately targeted, Battie did
not offer an alternative scenario of what happened to spur an
attack that seemed intensely personal.
</P>
<P>
   As police continued the investigation into the stabbing and the
nightclub where it occurred, Boston Police spokeswoman Mariellen
Burns said the Buzz Club was cited for assault with a dangerous
weapon on their premises and failing to notify police in a proper
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Police sources have said that the club's manager wrapped
makeshift bandages around Pierce's wounds but did not call police.
The sources said the manager later denied knowing about the
stabbing when police interviewed him.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said more citations may be forthcoming pending an
investigation into the troubled nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   The club's manager, Robert LaBerge, said he was not aware of the
citations and had not been contacted by police.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Pierce said the top draft pick from Kansas
changed rooms and was up and walking around. Hospital officials
upgraded his condition from fair to good.
</P>
</TEXT>
