<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON, SAMSONOV ARE BACK WITH BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the end, it was a meeting of the minds that got it
done.
</P>
<P>
   When push came to shove, the agents for Sergei Samsonov and Joe
Thornton pooled their resources in the form of a conference call
with Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell and the sides
came to agreement on three-year, $5.35 million contracts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The forwards are expected to have their physicals Wednesday
morning and join their teammates for practice at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Both Thornton and Samsonov are scheduled to be paid $1.55
million this year, $1.75 million next year, and $2.05 million in
the final year. There are also achievable bonuses built into the
deals, provided both 21-year-olds have quantifiably better years
than they've had in their first three.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deals leave right wing Anson Carter as the Bruins'
lone restricted free agent still unsigned, and he said this has
little effect on his situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circumstances are a little bit different in that they
signed their deals without having arbitration rights,'' said Carter
from Los Angeles. ``The fact that they've signed, I don't think it
changes anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who was represented by Mike Barnett, was thrilled and
relieved to get it over with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' said Thornton from his family's home in St. Thomas,
Ontario. ``I'm happy. I just wanted to play, and that's the bottom
line. I was kind of sick of sitting out. I just wanted to get it
done and start the season with the guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Barnett) told me to hang in there. I knew what we were going
for, he knew I wanted to play, so I think he hurried it up a little
bit. It was quite a surprise. Mike phoned me (Monday night) and
said we were pretty close. Other than that, I thought we were a
long ways away. I wasn't ready at all. I'm ready now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who was scheduled to fly in Tuesday night, said he's a
bit older and wiser as a result of the process. He said he
understood that being in the first class of entry-level players
under the initial rookie salary cap meant his second contract was
going to be tough sledding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I've been through this, I think the rest of it will be a
piece of cake,'' he said. ``We kind of were feeling it out for the
rest of the guys. I think that's why it lasted so long. The guys
coming up, they're definitely going to look at our contracts so
we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to play in one or two exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've missed a lot, but I don't think I'm up to
that condition of just throw me in right away, because it's a
different pace,'' said Thornton, who had been skating with the
London (Ontario) Knights junior team. ``It might take me a couple
of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Abbott, who represents Samsonov, said the fact that the
sides never really stopped talking helped the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``As testy as it ever got, there were never too many gaps in
communication of some kind and that was positive,'' said Abbott.
``To a certain extent, we also saw what was happening around the
market and it influenced them and influenced me. We both started to
accept a few points the other side had to make, which I think is
important from our standpoint, that's for sure and we got there.
But it was a tough one because of the ages of the players and maybe
the climate in terms of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said if there was one word to describe what they had all
gone through, it would be ``arduous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier you turn professional, the more arduous it is and
the more difficult it is because of the requirements of how long
you have to play before you get things like arbitration,'' said
Abbott. ``It was an intense process. We exchanged a lot of ideas, a
lot of proposals, there was a lot of disagreement, but we kept at
it. We got to a point where I think both sides are pretty
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Thornton and Samsonov were given identical deals
made a certain amount of sense to Abbott, considering Thornton was
taken at No. 1 overall and Samsonov No. 8 as well as what they've
done in their first three years of the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both young players, both drafted the same year, both
play for the team and are both top 10 picks,'' said Abbott.
``Statistically, they're not that far apart depending how you look
at it. Sure, there is an influence there.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, meanwhile, said he hadn't lost hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty well believe in the numbers we've been looking
for,'' said Carter. ``Unless there is an offer on the table that
really piques our interest, then it's the status quo. I really
don't think anything has changed. There's still a difference in
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked a lot in the last week, moreso than in the past.
That's always a good sign but we're no closer to a deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
