<HEADLINE>
OPPENHEIMER INVESTS IN FOLIO COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Substitute brackets for double parenthesis in Folio((fn))
throughout.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oppenheimer Funds has made a small investment in a new
company that is creating an alternative to mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, PersonaFund, will offer its own version of
folios _ securities that are packaged and sold in batches, or
baskets. Several companies already offer or plan to offer such
products. Perhaps the best known, Folio((fn)), sells customized
stock portfolios and charges customers a flat monthly fee to trade
them.
</P>
<P>
   Though many mutual fund executives question the appeal of
folios, Oppenheimer, the nation's 13th-largest manager of mutual
funds, is not the first prominent mutual fund manager to enter the
business. American Century Investments has invested in Folio((fn)).
</P>
<P>
   Instead of stocks, PersonaFund will offer baskets of
exchange-traded funds, from which customers can choose, based on
their investment goals. The folios of mutual fund-like products
that trade like stocks will carry a 0.5 percent yearly fee on top
of their own fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you add them together, it's still well under the fees of an
actively managed mutual fund,'' said Manoj Narang, chief executive
of Tradeworx, a year and a half old financial technology company
that is the majority owner of the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer bought a 15 percent stake in PersonaFund for less
than $5 million and has an option to buy another 15 percent, people
at both companies said. While Oppenheimer will not provide advice
from its equity fund managers, it will offer its fixed-income funds
and commodity investment products for use in the folios, since
exchange-traded funds are not available in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   PersonaFund, which will sell its folios through brokers, expects
to open for business in four to six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
