<SLUG> BC-NEW-WINDOWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT READY TO FIELD SERVER OPERATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hey there, big spender. Microsoft Corp. wants
you.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, a colossus in the desktop software market, Tuesday
kicked off a major effort to enter the lucrative world of high-end,
big-ticket computing.
</P>
<P>
   While the software giant has locked up the market for software
for personal computers and more powerful ``servers'' capable of
crunching large amounts of data, Microsoft has yet to penetrate the
most powerful echelons of computing.
</P>
<P>
   That market _ currently dominated by Sun Microsystems Inc.,
Hewlett-Packard Corp., Oracle Corp. and IBM _ is critical to
Microsoft, which must reach beyond its core desktop market and win
over users of ultrapowerful servers to keep up its historically
white-hot sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ballmer, chief executive of the Redmond, Wash., company,
said his company was ready to enter the field with an arsenal of
software, including a high-end operating system called Windows 2000
Datacenter Server, and a suite of business applications such as
Exchange 2000 Server, a messaging program, and SQL Server 2000, a
database program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the broadest product launch in Microsoft's history,''
said Ballmer, who conducted the launch like a two-hour pep rally.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, however, Microsoft must overcome a common perception
that its software is crash-prone, vulnerable to malicious hackers,
and has difficulty handling large-scale computers, analysts and
engineers say. Reliability, security, and the ability to
accommodate ever-larger computers are the three attributes most
prized by the kinds of customers Microsoft craves _ corporations
that pay top dollar to maintain large databases and complex Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McKay, a senior engineer for a Cambridge Internet
start-up, calls it ``bulletproof'' computing. ``One of the things
Microsoft would have to demonstrate is that it can securely operate
under hostile conditions'' 24 hours a day, seven days a week, said
McKay.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading programmers like McKay will be key to Microsoft's
success in this market, said Al Gillen, research manager for system
software at International Data Corp. in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   At the launch event, Ballmer did his best to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reliability is the area we've been pushed in the most,'' said
Ballmer. ``That should be completely dispelled by the work we're
talking about today. . . . We're putting a lot of emphasis on
reliability. A lot, a lot, a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Ballmer gets his message across, analysts believe
Microsoft is unlikely to persuade companies to switch to Windows
from their current systems from Sun, HP, or Linux _ all of which
are flavors of the Unix operating system. One reason is the time
and expense involved in converting existing complex computer
systems, said Gillen, who thinks Microsoft will have better luck
selling its software to new users with nothing yet in place, or to
companies looking to add computing capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Microsoft start displacing existing high-end Sun servers?
Not likely,'' said Gillen. ``Will they be competitive for new
purchases? You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun, whose Solaris operating system competes with Windows 2000
Datacenter Server, conceded nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got what they want,'' said Andy Ingram, vice president
of Solaris marketing at Sun in Palo Alto, Calif. ``The truth is,
they're where we were five years ago when we first introduced
Solaris. They've got a lot to figure out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
