<SLUG> BC-STATES-BALLOT-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  Lieberman Third Senator on Ballot Twice in Last 100 Years
</P>
<P>
   By Myron Struck
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 26 - If Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, the
Democratic vice presidential nominee, stays on the Connecticut
Senate ballot, he would be the third U.S. Senator to run for two
offices at the same time in the past hundred years, according to
the Senate Historian's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The first time a senator put his name before the voters twice on
the same ballot was in 1960 when Sen. Lyndon B. Johnson, D-Texas,
ran for vice president with Sen. John F. Kennedy, D-Mass., the
Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1988, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, ran for vice
president on the Democratic ticket headed by Gov. Michael Dukakis,
D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson won both votes, giving up his Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen was re-elected, but the Dukakis ticket fell to then-Vice
President George H. Bush and Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Historian's Office said the practice of holding dual
offices was once common, in the 19th Century, but there are no
Senate records at hand to show who did and who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
