<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PEER CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   The millionaire author and peer Jeffrey Archer was charged with
perjury and perverting the course of justice in a case that has
pursued him since the 1980s. The charges result from claims that he
asked a friend to provide a false alibi for him in a libel trial he
won 13 years ago against a London tabloid, which had reported that
he slept with a prostitute and bought her silence. Lord Archer, 60,
had to step down as Conservative candidate for mayor of London last
year when the accusation surfaced. The formal charges came hours
before he was to make his stage debut in the role of a suspected
criminal in a play he wrote called ``The Accused.''
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: ARMENIA PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Angry about a bill in Congress labeling as genocide the 1915
killings of hundreds of thousands of Armenians in Turkey,
protesters rallied outside the U.S. Consulate in Istanbul. The
House International Relations Committee is expected to approve the
bill on Thursday. Whether it reaches the House before adjournment
Oct. 6 is uncertain. The administration opposes it, arguing that
history should decide.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: PENSION REFORM
</P>
<P>
   The government is pursuing a plan to avert bankruptcy of the
pension system. Pensions would be lowered to 64.5 percent of final
salary from 70 percent by 2030, and contributions from employers
and employees would be increased to 22 percent. Payments of 4
percent of earnings into a private supplement would be phased in.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: AMATO SHIFT
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Italy's center-left governing coalition praised
Prime Minister Giuliano Amato for pulling out of the leadership
race and backing Rome's mayor, Francesco Rutelli, to run in the
general election next year. The center-left trails in polls against
the center-right opposition, led by former Prime Minister Silvio
Berlusconi. Walter Veltroni, leader of the Democrats of the Left,
the coalition's biggest party, said Amato had ``spoken like a man
of the state and someone who has the future and the unity of the
center-left at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: DRUG ARREST
</P>
<P>
   A former director of the federal highway police, Enrique Harari
Garduno, is under arrest in a continuing investigation of officials
linked to the Juarez drug cartel, police said. Harari Garduno is
accused of receiving more than $1 million and using military
vehicles to transport drugs, said Wilfrido Robledo, the drug
enforcement agency chief.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: EYE ON ELECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Resignation of the country's longest-serving provincial premier,
Roy Romanow of Saskatchewan, has lent credence to theories that he
may work in a ``unite the left'' movement in the next national
elections. In farewell interviews Romanow, a figure in provincial
politics since 1967, has talked about emulating Canada's right-wing
fusion attempts by forging an alliance of his New Democratic Party
and the governing Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: BOMBING SUSPECTS
</P>
<P>
   Two Indonesian soldiers arrested after a shootout on Sunday
planted a bomb that killed 15 people at the stock exchange on Sept.
13, police said. The announcement appeared to confirm the
government's assertion that rogue members of the military were
behind recent bombings in Jakarta. But there was lingering public
suspicion that the suspects were scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: U.N. SKIRMISH
</P>
<P>
   United Nations peacekeeping forces shot and killed a pro-Jakarta
militia member in a clash in East Timor, which voted to become
independent from Indonesia last year. Meanwhile the militia groups,
accused of killing three U.N. aid workers, demanded the return of
more than 1,000 weapons surrendered over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: ARMY INROADS
</P>
<P>
   The military said it had reclaimed a strategic road leading into
the town of Chavakachcheri, as well as several square miles of
territory near Sarasali, in its latest offensive to reclaim the
portions of the northern Jaffna Peninsula lost this spring to Tamil
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: NETANYAHU RULING
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's ruling on whether to indict the rightist
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is expected on Thursday.
Newspapers here report that he is disinclined to prosecute
Netanyahu, who would thus be free to re-enter politics and try to
coalesce the opposition to Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   CYPRUS: U.N. AIDE HOPEFUL
</P>
<P>
   Talks about the future of Cyprus ``are beginning to break new
ground,'' said a U.N. official, Alvaro de Soto, in New York. After
two weeks of separate talks with the Greek Cypriot leader, Glafcos
Clerides, and his Turkish counterpart, Rauf Denktash, de Soto, said
the decades-old dispute seemed to be moving toward a settlement.
Talks resume in November.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: CRUMBLING EMBARGO
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright expressed concern to
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee about recent French and
Russian flights to Iraq, which have severely weakened the
longstanding ban on air traffic to Baghdad. France, which allowed
an anti-sanctions group to fly from Paris last week, has approved a
second flight. Jordan may become the first Arab nation to violate
the ban, officials said in Amman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: FLOOD AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   About 172,000 people still face severe food shortages as a
result of spring floods, the World Food Program reported. Thousands
of farmers cannot grow food because the land is still waterlogged.
</P>
</TEXT>
