<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ELECTIONS(1000&AMP;TRIM)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC TRAILS IN FIRST ROUND OF DISPUTED YUGOSLAV ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The government-controlled Federal
Election Commission announced Tuesday night that President Slobodan
Milosevic was trailing his challenger, Vojislav Kostunica, but
rejected Kostunica's claim to an outright victory.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said the opposition candidate had fallen short of
the 50 percent required for a first round-win and called for a
runoff to take place on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders immediately called the commission's figures
fraudulent and said they would not take part in a runoff. They said
that Kostunica had won almost 55 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an offer that must be rejected,'' Kostunica said in a
statement. ``The victory is obvious, and we will defend it by all
nonviolent means. The people have given their political `no' to
Milosevic and his policies. Our first duty is to carry out that
verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The state television broke into the main evening news program
with the announcement that Milosevic, with 40.23 percent, had come
in second to Kostunica, with 48.22 percent, with a turnout of about
64.65 percent. Opposition members of the commission said they had
not been involved in the tallying.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition said that by its own figures, gathered from
election monitors in each constituency who had signed the returns
before they had been shipped to Belgrade for final approval by the
Federal Election Commission, Kostunica was beating Milosevic, 54.66
percent to 35.01 percent. The opposition said that the turnout had
been 74 percent, and that its monitors had counted more than 98
percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Kostunica declared that a second round was
unnecessary. ``There is no single reason, not moral or political,
by which we would accept such trampling on the electoral will of
the people,'' he said. But Kostunica promised to avoid ``careless
moves that could raise tensions in society, that could lead to
unforeseeable consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has called for rallies in Belgrade and other
cities for Wednesday night to defend Kostunica's apparent victory _
rallies that could prove to be confrontational, depending on the
response of the police.
</P>
<P>
   The risk for Kostunica is that if the popular will proves
insufficiently forceful, the boycott of a second round could allow
Milosevic to claim an unopposed victory and to remain president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 thousands of Belgrade citizens marched for three months
to defend the opposition's victory in local elections, which
Milosevic had challenged in the courts, before he relented.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Belgrade's squares were largely empty,
although some people were out on their terraces banging pots and
pans, and an independent radio station, Radio Indeks, said its
telephone lines were clogged by angry listeners. About 9 p.m., its
signal was jammed.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, Ljiljana Zivkovic, 50, an accountant, said
simply: ``They can't steal the votes anymore. We'll make them
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the opposition strongholds of Cacak and Novi Sad, large
spontaneous rallies were reported Tuesday night, with 15,000 and
5,000 gathering respectively, to protest the commission
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   In an important message, the leader of the Serbian Orthodox
Church, Patriarch Pavle, met Kostunica on Tuesday and urged
Milosevic ``to accept the electoral will of the people and
contribute to the welfare of the nation and the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement on state television that Milosevic was
trailing Kostunica was already an extraordinary admission that the
regime's campaign had gone badly wrong. It followed what officials
in the government have described as a furious debate about how to
handle the first electoral defeat Milosevic has ever suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals that Milosevic simply declare outright victory for
himself in the first round were apparently rejected as too
confrontational and risky.
</P>
<P>
   A second round, especially with Milosevic trailing, at least
kept his options open and could be taken by some Serbs as
democratic and nonconfrontational. It will be harder for Kostunica
to claim his victory has been stolen, given what would appear to be
near certainty that he would win a second round.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the tactic sought to buy time for the regime to
consider its next step, and perhaps to bargain for a secure exit,
especially with some Western governments sending word to Milosevic
that his position is untenable and he must consider how to save
himself from a system that could crumble rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big fraud,'' said Zoran Djindjic, leader of the
coalition that backs Kostunica, speaking of the call for a second
round. ``In last two days, we knew that they were preparing
something to get Milosevic into the second round. But we have proof
of our figures, and we will defend the people's vote to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Djindjic urged patience. He said the
opposition would demand to see the commission's figures, and
compare them with their own.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has 28 members, two from each coalition, but with
a majority appointed by the government. Opposition representatives
say they have been locked out of any counting.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the government has already conceded a massive defeat
in local elections _ the opposition will rule nearly 100 towns and
cities in Serbia _ but now Milosevic's own future is at stake, and
for the regime, the issue is an existential one.
</P>
<P>
   While a chilly Belgrade was quiet Tuesday night, with no rally
scheduled, people were angry. Snjezana, a 32-year-old shop
attendant, said: ``I'm not afraid. They can say whatever they want.
But they are defeated _ history. If we have to defend our victory
on the street, we'll do that. We've had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer of 35, Branomir Misic, said: ``We were out on the
street so many times. And this time we will be there again. There
is no way out for them.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential election, Milosevic and Kostunica had three
other competitors _ Tomislav Nikolic of the ultranationalist
Serbian Radical Party, who got 5.1 percent of the vote according to
the election commission; Vojislav Mihailovic of the Serbian Renewal
Movement, who got 2.59 percent; and Miodrag Vidojkovic of the
Affirmative Party, who got 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   People also voted for both houses of the federal parliament.
Although the opposition won more seats than Milosevic's ruling
coalition, he will control both houses and can form a federal
government with no other partners.
</P>
<P>
   He will do so because his allied party won the seats reserved
for Serbia's sister republic, Montenegro, after the election
boycott urged on citizens by Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic.
Djukanovic broke with Milosevic in 1997, but chose not to contest
these elections as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro itself, fears of a Milosevic move on Djukanovic
were receding. Special police troops remained on alert and were
guarding state buildings dressed in full combat gear and helmets,
but Deputy Prime Minister Dragisa Burzan said in an interview that
he believed that government fears that Milosevic might order the
Yugoslav army to take over government institutions or impose a
state of emergency in the rebellious republic were receding.
</P>
<P>
   `'If he survives he will be very dangerous,'' Burzan said of
Milosevic. ``But now he cannot influence the generals as he could
even yesterday. Some generals will hesitate now. He can make a mess
but nothing like on the scale we expected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
