<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2654 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e bc-GEORGE-BENSON-PREVIEW     09-26 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-BENSON-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT; 
BENSON IS BREEZIN'
</HEADLINE>
bc-GEORGE-BENSON-PREVIEW
cc,78p3  (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Friday' is Sept. 29, 2000.) 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Back in 1947, ``Little'' Georgie Benson was 4 and already a
budding r&AMP;b singer the first time he heard his guitar-playing
stepdad plug in and play jazz, Charlie Christian-style.
</P>
<P>
   Five decades later, Benson regularly straddles the pop, r&AMP;b and
jazz charts with a guitar sound that still owes a little something
to Christian, the jazz guitar pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of Benson's considerable success could have come
without his smooth-as-silk vocal delivery. Equally accomplished
guitarists such as Wes Montgomery, Blue Note session giant Grant
Green or even rocker Jeff Beck, for example, never broke through on
Benson's scale largely due to the fact that they don't sing.
</P>
<P>
   Benson was already well on his way to a singing career in his
native Pittsburgh when Green spotted him and advised him to become
a studio guitarist. The dividends were immediate, and Benson was
soon working in organ trios with Jimmy Smith and Brother Jack
McDuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about those organ groups -- and they were extremely
popular in the clubs and bars at the time -- there was room to
really solo,'' Benson, 57, recalled from his home in New Jersey.
``The band leaders wouldn't tell you what to play. The idea was to
keep a groove going which meant more people were buying drinks. You
learned the 'heads' (the tune's melody); then you just went to
town.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, who appears Friday at the Greek Theatre with jazz-r&AMP;b
chanteuse Brenda Russell opening, has been seeing a lot of activity
lately.
</P>
<P>
   A new album, ``Absolute Benson'' (GRP), highlighted by a
Latin-tinged remake of Donny Hathaway's ``The Ghetto,'' recently
topped the jazz charts while a two-disc career-spanning anthology
from Rhino/Warner Archives has just hit stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The George Benson Anthology,'' compiled partly by Benson,
includes 32 vocal and instrumental tracks cut between 1964 and
1998, including the Top 10 hits ``Give Me the Night,'' ``On
Broadway,'' ``This Masquerade'' and ``Turn Your Love Around,'' as
well as signature solo sides like ``Breezin','' ``Love Ballad'' and
a striking cover of the Beatles' ``The Long and Winding Road.''
</P>
<P>
   North Hollywood-based jazz guitarist Phil Upchurch, who played
on Benson's epochal ``Breezin' '' album and tour in the '70s,
recalls watching Benson move from clubs to the arena level as the
record took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breezin','' featuring Benson's languid Stevie Wonder-like
vocals -- which he sometimes used to scat along with single-string
solos -- sold more albums than any other jazz record before or
since and won a truckload of Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting to see him grow from playing in pickup bands
to being a big star,'' Upchurch said. ``And he hasn't changed a
bit. My top favorite guitarists of all time are George and Wes. Wes
played the sweet stuff and George has the fire. You can't outburn
George Benson.''
</P>
<P>
   An incredibly versatile musician, Benson can play in any style
with supreme taste, a rounded tone, terrific speed and always the
urge to swing. Yet his voice has proved to be far more marketable
to the public than his guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's understandable -- and I know it always upsets
the critics when I say that,'' Benson said. ``People will always
want to hear songs. Not everyone understands what a great guitar
solo is or where a complicated chord chart comes from or what it
takes to play tastefully. Pop songs will always be around.''
</P>
<P>
   On stage, though, Benson can be counted on to reaffirm his jazz
guitar credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Shadow Hills resident Michael O'Neill, who has held down the
rhythm guitar chair in Benson's touring ensemble since 1981, says
playing with Benson is ``like being paid to go to the highest-level
music university in the world. It's a direct hit of a master.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with cutting his new album, Benson was a visitor to
sessions for organist Jimmy McGriff's recent ``McGriff's House
Party'' disc. The guitarist's back-to-basics funk playing marked a
return to the early days of his 1966 release, ``The George Benson
Cookbook,'' still considered a jazz guitar touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play clubs anymore, but I sometimes miss those days,''
Benson said. ``The era of the multinight engagement -- you'd come
into a city and set up somewhere for a week. People would drop by
to jam. I mean, there was a lot of joy in jazz then. It wasn't big
business -- it was about playing.''
</P>
<P>
   ---GEORGE BENSON &QL; 
Where: Greek Theatre, 2700 N. Vermont Ave., Los Angeles. When: 7
p.m. Friday. Tickets: $30 to $60. Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
