<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS     09-26 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS SEEKS TO PREVENT GOVERNMENT SHUTDOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KAREN MASTERSON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress on Tuesday moved toward preventing a
government shutdown and making less expensive medications from
Canada and Mexico available to all U.S. consumers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Republicans and Democrats moved
further apart on the more difficult task of providing the elderly
with an affordable prescription drug plan, frustrating Houston-area
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote of 415-2, the House passed what is called a continuing
resolution, which would extend funding for federal agencies and
programs to Oct. 6, nearly a week beyond the Oct. 1 start of the
new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   As the resolution passed the House _ and as the Senate agreed to
take up the measure this week _ both parties admitted they may need
even more time and that another continuing resolution to Oct. 13
may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stay as long it takes and we'll pass continuing
resolutions as long it takes,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., said of both parties' attempts to complete their
legislative business and go home. ``I hope it's sooner rather than
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, at the very least, must pass 11 unfinished spending
bills that would fund everything from the U.S. Department of the
Interior, which controls federal lands and keeps national parks and
museums open, to the U.S. State Department, which conducts U.S.
foreign policy and runs embassies overseas. So far, only two
spending bills have been signed into law, both for the Department
of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers adjourn and turn full-time to their re-election
campaigns, they may have a prescription drug plan to boast about.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unlikely to be the hotly contested plan for the
elderly now at the center of partisan bickering on Capitol Hill and
between presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, drug companies sell drugs approved by the Food and
Drug Administration overseas at discounted prices. But U.S. import
laws prevent wholesalers from buying them back to sell to U.S.
consumers at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the White House agreed in letters exchanged earlier
this week to support a Senate-passed proposal that would remove the
so-called ``reimportation'' restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The provision _ currently a part of a U.S. Department of
Agriculture spending bill _ would eliminate the reimportation
restriction and provide $23 million for FDA to make sure the
incoming drugs are safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle's not over,'' Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., said at a
news conference Tuesday. ``The pharmaceutical industry has deep
pockets and they're going to spend a fortune on defeating this.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly $112 billion will be spent on prescription medication
this year, according to the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services. Dorgan said if market competition moderates prices by
just 10 percent, consumers would save $11.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, has been pushing prescription drug
plans for seniors for years. A September 1999 survey of his
district, conducted by the staff of the House Government Oversight
Committee, found that in some cases, drugs cost three times as much
in Houston as they do in Mexico, and twice as much as they cost in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seniors who paid for their trips to Mexico by getting
prescription drugs for their neighbors,'' he said. A new boarder
restriction, Green said, prevents people from transporting
pharmaceuticals for anyone but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a member of the Commerce Subcommittee on Health and the
Environment, and Rep. Jim Turner, D-Crockett, planned a news
conference today to push for a prescription drug plan for senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Houston-area Democrats support a House plan, and a
similar plan proposed by the Gore presidential campaign, that would
expand Medicare health insurance for the elderly to include
prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans support a plan to subsidize commercial prescription
drug insurance for senior citizens making under $14,600.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to President Bill Clinton earlier this week, Lott
and House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said ``the fundamental
disagreement over providing broad prescription drug coverage will
lead to inaction this year on this important issue.''
</P>
<P>
   While leaders of both parties said they would continue trying to
work out their differences, neither said they were hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
