<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HISPANIC27-COX     09-26 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic vote not key in battleground states
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The music was loud and Latino. The message was custom-made for
the crowd packed into Miami's Coconut Grove Convention Center for a
GOP rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Hispanics have become the most important electoral block in
the country,'' said George P. Bush, the Mexican-American nephew of
the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But barring large-scale, last-minute population shifts, George
P. is overstating the case in the current presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   After months of speculation about the Hispanic impact on the
race for the White House, the final six weeks of the battle will be
played out in states _ mostly in the Midwest _ where the Hispanic
vote will be miniscule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a demographic reality,'' said Rodolfo de la Garza, a
University of Texas government professor and vice president of
research for the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Save for New Mexico, which has only five electoral votes, and
Florida, which has 25 electoral votes and an atypical Hispanic
community, the battleground states are among those with the lowest
percentage of voting-age Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of the nation's growing Hispanic population
is clustered in five states: California, Texas, New York, Florida
and Illinois. Of those, only Illinois offers anything close to the
dynamic once viewed as a crucial factor in the election: the
ability of Republican George W. Bush to move traditionally
Democratic Hispanics into his column.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show California, New York and Texas are not in play as the
campaign moves into its most critical phase. Democrat Al Gore has a
solid lead in New York, and Bush will probably carry his home
state. Although Bush is battling for California, where the
voting-age population is 28 percent Hispanic, surveys indicate he
is a long shot at best.
</P>
<P>
   The race is much closer in Florida, where Bush is counting on
his brother Jeb, Florida's governor, to help deliver the state.
Florida's voting-age population is 15 percent Hispanic, but it is
atypical because of a large Cuban American population with
longstanding ties to the Republican Party and the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Dowd, who studies poll numbers for the Bush campaign,
notes that demographic changes in Florida's Hispanic community have
made it more difficult for a Republican to carry that state. New
immigration patterns have resulted in a major change in Florida's
Hispanic population: Non-Cuban Hispanics now outnumber Cuban
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, People with Cuban backgrounds make up only 5 percent
of the nation's 32 million Hispanics, but they vote Republican. A
recent national poll by Hispanictrends.com, which gave Gore a 59
percent to 28 percent overall lead among Hispanics, showed Bush
with a whopping 83 percent to 10 percent lead among Cuban
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, has huge leads among Hispanics of Mexican, Puerto
Rican, Dominican, Central American and South American descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hispanic population is not predominant'' in the
battleground states, said a top Bush adviser, adding, however, that
the nominee will continue to try to lure Hispanic votes to show he
is a different kind of Republican. ``It's something we are going to
continue to communicate and talk about no matter where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   That message is important for people such as Jeremy Gonzalez
Ibraham of Philadelphia, who is trying to help the GOP make inroads
in Pennsylvania's growing, though still relatively small, Hispanic
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the strategy we have here in Pennsylvania looks
beyond Nov. 7,'' he said, acknowledging that the Hispanic vote in
his state is relatively small, though potentially powerful. ``To
have an impact doesn't necessarily require you to have large raw
numbers. The question is how many of those numbers you can motivate
to get to the polls and vote for your candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Fee, spokesman for the Pennsylvania Democratic Party, said
Hispanics are becoming more important in state politics, but can
only make a difference this year if the presidential race in
Pennsylvania is razor thin.
</P>
<P>
   De la Garza, a student of Hispanic voting trends, says that's
generally the case in the battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have a very, very tight election for small
groups to influence them,'' he said. ``The Anglos would have to be
divided 49.8-49.8. If the majority population is going in one
direction overwhelmingly Latinos don't make much of a difference.
It's only when the majority is divided can Latinos realistically
hope to influence the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   But de la Garza believes Hispanics _ through Bush's message _
already have effected the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues of cultural division were killed off when Bush reached
out to Latinos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``different kind of a Republican'' tag Bush has hung on
himself has been a crucial part of his campaign since day one.
Depending on whose numbers you believe, Bush carried one-third to
one-half of the Hispanic vote in Texas in his 1998 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has continued that effort in the presidential race,
speaking Spanish on the campaign trail, airing Spanish-language
advertisements and distancing himself from GOP immigration
positions unpopular among Hispanics
</P>
<P>
   Though the message remains important to Bush, the numbers sho
the appeal to Hispanics may not be numerically crucial in the
campaign's closing weeks. The battleground states in which Bush and
Gore are concentrating their time and resources include 10 _ with a
total of 134 of the 270 electoral votes needed for victory. The
Hispanic voting-age population in these states is less than 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the battleground spectrum are New Mexico,
which, at 38 percent, has the highest proportion of voting-age
Hispanics, Arizona (19 percent) and Florida (15 percent). Those
states offer a total of 38 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Most polling in recent weeks has shown Gore leading Bush among
Hispanics. But new numbers released by New York pollster John Zogby
showed the candidates tied at 44 percent among Hispanics. The poll
was completed last week.
</P>
<P>
   A Reuters/Zogby national poll completed earlier last week gave
Gore a 57 percent to 25 percent edge among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the elder George Bush captured only 19 percent of the
Hispanic vote when he was ousted by Democrat Bill Clinton. In 1996,
GOP nominee Bob Dole pulled an anemic 13 percent of the Hispanic
vote.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
