<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-HUMMER0927-COX     09-26 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUMMER0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drug case is complex affair
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - Big guys do cry. And when they do, when they drop that
man-mountain act and show their gooey center, it can be more
convincing than a head slap or a hammerlock.
</P>
<P>
   Normally about as soft as slate, C.J. Hunter became a 330-pound
puddle when he began the public portion of his defense against
steroid charges. Those tears ran like a rivulet across a boulder.
</P>
<P>
   The lab has not yet determined whether Hunter's tears tested
positive for sincerity. The USOC will release those results
sometime after the 2004 Athens Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   That one scene, as Hunter double-clutched on his words while
considering the impact on wife Marion Jones, likely will go much
farther in the court of public opinion than all the nanograms of
science the international drug police can muster. We too often
judge with the heart. Look at how one kiss might turn a
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on you, you drug-testing bullies. You made C.J. cry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Jones is back on the track, attempting a feat
that would have been difficult enough even with a clear head. Now
if she does not win her five Olympic golds it will be because of
the politics of drugs and a hounding press. When all along it could
have been simply because she had taken on too much, the long jump
didn't suit her or the U.S. relay teams were depleted.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Jones does go for five under these
circumstances, she will cast in stone her status as one of the
greatest single-minded athletes in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   Never has so much Olympic drama played out around someone not
even in the Olympics. If only Hunter had married beneath him, none
of this would be a raging issue.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case the teary appeal didn't work, Hunter had Johnnie
Cochran in his corner ready to spring to litigation. C.J. O.J.
Doesn't anyone on his client list go by a full name?
</P>
<P>
   When Hunter proclaimed, ``I don't know what has happened, but I
promise everybody I'm going to find out,'' a person couldn't help
but wonder, too, how O.J.'s search for the real killer is going.
</P>
<P>
   If the urine is unfit, you still must acquit.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran has a long-standing relationship with Hunter, by
marriage. Back when she was 16, Jones was briefly suspended for
missing a mandatory drug test. Her mother sought out Cochran who
successfully brokered her reinstatement when it was all put off to
some mishandled paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter paints himself as a shot putter too indifferent to even
consider performance-enhancing drugs. An interesting approach, one
that future generations of suspects may keep in mind. Call it the
``Oh I'm just doing this until my application to beauty school gets
accepted'' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track and field is not that important to me, not to the point
that I'd do something like this,'' he said. That must be reassuring
to all the people he beat along the way.
</P>
<P>
   For all the world knew before this, Hunter was the glowering,
protective presence around Jones. Now, suddenly, he's the modern,
sensitive man, wanting nothing more than his wife to be fulfilled
and his children to be happy. The media consultant sitting to his
left must have been pleased.
</P>
<P>
   You thought this Olympic drug business was a confusing mess
before. Get ready to be really turned inside-out. The experts are
lining up on both sides of a case ready to explode beyond
proportion. Here a highly placed member of the International
Amateur Athletic Federation says Hunter once tested out at 2,000
nanograms of nandrolone per milliliter _ 1,000 times the permitted
amount. There a nutritional expert produced by Hunter says it was
all a byproduct of taking an over-the-counter iron supplement.
</P>
<P>
   If there are any obvious innocents to all this, they have yet to
step forward.
</P>
<P>
   Not certain factions of the international athletic community,
which ambushed the Jones home team with this test result at a
critical juncture of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Not the United States Olympic Committee, whose policy of secrecy
naturally leads to charges of a cover-up. Pretending to be clean
and righteous doesn't make it so.
</P>
<P>
   Not Hunter himself. He springs from the dirtiest event of track
and field, so it is difficult to buy the fact he would be careless
with anything he'd ingest. Crying is not a defense. Besides, there
aren't enough tears to wash away the dirt this has thrown on his
wife's moment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
