u s BC-OLY-SOFT-GEORGE27-COX     09-26 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOFT-GEORGE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There are tears in softball
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKTOWN, New South Wales _ There is crying in softball.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's Olympic gold medal game, won by the U.S. on a
dropped fly ball in extra innings, started a flood for both teams.
For the American women, who lost their air of invincibility in this
tournament but not their prize, and for the Japanese, who won every
game but this one, this was as wrenching as any World Series, as
dramatic as any trumped-up movie scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought for this country the best way I can and that is on
the softball field,'' said Lisa Fernandez, who clouded up during
interviews last week when the U.S. was in the midst of a shocking
three-game losing streak and did it again Tuesday when the
four-year mission to repeat as Olympic champions had reached its
successful conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not content,'' said Japan's Mariko Masubuchi, one of eight
pitchers to make it through this nine-day tournament without
allowing an earned run.
</P>
<P>
   The others were from China and Australia and Italy, along with
Michele Smith, Christa Williams and Lori Harrigan of the U.S. So
evenly matched were these teams that the gold-medal Americans, easy
winners at the original Olympic softball competition four years
ago, stumbled into Sydney's semifinals as the fourth-ranked team
with a mediocre 4-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   Even the medal ceremony was a close call. A driving thunderstorm
blanketed Blacktown Olympic Center just 10 minutes after the U.S.
had closed out a 2-1 comeback victory in eight innings. Do you
throw a tarp over an entire team and direct them to take the medal
stand in a monsoon?
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully the answer was no, but the half-hour delay in hearing
the national anthem was one more reminder to the Americans that
nothing is ever going to come easy in this game again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since '96, play has excelled in all countries,'' said Dot
Richardson, one of eight double-golden gals who debuted softball as
an Olympic sport at the Atlanta Games. ``It's just excellent
softball.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough to make one ache for Shiori Koseki. She is an office
clerk back home in Japan, not a softball pro. The sole ambition
listed on her Olympic biography sheet is ``To get the victory in
the Sydney Olympics.'' Tuesday night, when Laura Berg whistled a
spinning line drive toward her in left field, Koseki got flattened
by fate instead. Backpedaling and twisting on slippery grass, she
got a glove on the ball but couldn't keep it there. As Koseki
landed on her back, the ball popped out and Jennifer McFalls was on
her way home from second base, shutting the Olympic tournament down
by default.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Koseki sob after the game, wrapped in the embrace of
Japanese teammates at first and then several of the U.S. players,
you knew that way too much guilt was going to haunt her for way too
long. Unfair that she was charged with an error, given the lunging
effort. Unbelievable that the Americans won at all, given the mess
they made of their dominating reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The first meeting with Japan last week during the round-robin
games was an 11-inning loss made worse by four U.S. errors and 20
runners left on base. Thereafter followed a 2-0 loss to China in 14
innings and a 2-1 loss to Australia in 13. Just to make it to the
championship game, the Americans had to beat China and Australia on
the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Even former Palm Beach Community College star Crystl Bustos, who
hit three home runs in the tournament's first two games, ran into a
psychological wall. Tuesday's clincher, played in a 58-degree chill
with light rain falling throughout, featured one hit for the
winners and a comeback that began with Smith taking an 80-mph pitch
in the back for the team.
</P>
<P>
   The whole game turned when the Americans realized that Japan was
stealing catcher Stacey Nuveman's signs to Fernandez. That's how
Lisa's changeup, considered the best softball pitch in the world,
got smoked over the center-field fence for a home run in the fourth
inning. Here again Smith's savvy paid off in discovering the
problem. Four times she's been the MVP of Japan's professional
softball league. She speaks fluent Japanese, and apparently thinks
it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how supportive the girls were,'' Fernandez
said. ``They kept telling me, 'Keep fighting, Lisa. Stay with us.
We're gonna get you the runs.' Everyone had the emotion, all the
way down to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   To the end of the game and beyond, actually. Berg, for instance,
immediately called her twin sister, asleep at 3 a.m. in California,
to scream and laugh and describe exactly what a 2000 Olympic gold
medal looks like. Bustos thought about how good it will feel to get
home to California herself, and how sad it will be, too, with the
realization that a favorite grandfather died there during the
Sydney softball tournament. Fernandez took the medal off her neck
and placed it on U.S. coach Ralph Raymond, a quiet man who led the
Raybestos Brakettes women's softball team of Stratford, Conn., for
26 years but never imagined himself on the other side of the world
bringing honor to his country.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there are tears in softball, all right. A good cry, in this
case, for the resilient Americans and a pillow-soaker for the
devastated Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   A sign that softball, you might say, can be hardball, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
