<P>
   While the doping controversy surrounding C.J. Hunter is
unfortunate for the Games in general, and track and field in
particular, a side effect for NBC could be even more interest in
the pursuit of five gold medals by his wife Marion Jones, whose
efforts in the qualifying rounds of the 200 meters and the long
jump will be featured on tonight's prime-time telecast. Australian
heroine Cathy Freeman, fresh off her gold medal in the 400 meters,
is also running in the 200; while Gail Devers' attempt to get that
elusive gold medal in the 100-meter hurdles will be shown as well.
Stone Mountain resident Sharon Crouch is among the challengers to
Devers, who lives in Alpharetta. Two-time Tour de France champion
Lance Armstrong will get some air time, too, as the American
cyclist seeks his first medal in his third Olympics, while Georgian
Teresa Edwards and a host of players from the WNBA will anchor the
late-night telecast with the U.S. women's basketball game against
Slovakia. On MSNBC, Venus Williams' gold-medal women's tennis match
against Russia's Elena Dementieva will share the spotlight with the
United States-Cuba rematch for the gold medal in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prentis Rogers
