<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-DUBOSE0927-COX     09-26 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DUBOSE0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trouble in Tuscaloosa as AD declines DuBose's resignation
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - This summer, most Alabama football fans assumed that
Sept. 30 would be a day of celebration. It would be the season's
first game on campus, and the Crimson Tide would be 4-0 and well on
the way to a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when South Carolina comes to Tuscaloosa on Saturday,
the dominant moods in Bryant-Denny Stadium will be despair about
the present and uncertainty about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, which returned 18 starters from the 1999 SEC champions
and was ranked No. 3 in the preseason, has a record of 1-3. In the
lone win, Alabama needed 18 points in the fourth quarter to beat
Vanderbilt 28-10. In two of the losses, Alabama was dominated, by
UCLA 35-24 and by Southern Miss 21-0. The other loss came when
Arkansas drove 80 yards and scored with 64 seconds left to win
28-21 Saturday night in Fayetteville.
</P>
<P>
   Crimson Tide fans, not known for their patience, want to know
why. The vocal ones blame coach Mike DuBose, who survived efforts
to oust him a year ago and went on to be named SEC coach of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is 1-1 in the conference and can make another recovery.
If the Tide can win its six remaining conference games and if
Arkansas (3-0, 1-0 SEC) loses twice, Alabama can make it back to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it's not there (for the national title) doesn't
mean you don't have other goals,'' DuBose said. ``There's still the
possibility of winning the conference championship.''
</P>
<P>
   But every day, another story indicates problems in Tuscaloosa.
For example:
</P>
<P>
   After the season-opening beating at UCLA, with 30,000 Crimson
Tide fans in the Rose Bowl, DuBose was perplexed by the team's
performance, and his staff seemed baffled, too.Coaches,
particularly on the offensive staff, were second-guessing each
other in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Calloway has the title of offensive coordinator, but
quarterbacks coach Charlie Stubbs calls the plays. DuBose also has
heavy input when it comes to personnel matters and the game plan.
One radio report said that Stubbs, whose BYU-style passing offense
conflicts with the physical run-oriented style of Calloway, would
be leaving out of frustration at the end of the season. Both DuBose
and Stubbs denied the report.
</P>
<P>
   Various television analysts, including ESPN's Lee Corso and John
Mackovic, suggested that the Tide's three-headed approach to
offense has caused uncertainty and ineffectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of those guys who have all those ideas have been
fired,''DuBose said, bristling. ``So I'm not sure they really have
the expertise to make those statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's editions of the Birmingham News and Tuscaloosa News
reported that DuBose offered his resignation, effective at the end
of the season, to athletics director Mal Moore after the loss to
Southern Mississippi on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   DuBose confirmed the conversation with Moore but said it was a
private talk. Several assistants had been in the room, according to
the newspaper report. ``It was an emotional thing after the game,''
Moore said in that account. ``In a dressing room like that, it is
not an official meeting in that context, and I certainly took it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fans don't understand why a team that was so good a year
ago and lost only four starters can be so bad now. Alabama relied
heavily on the running game against Arkansas and looked more
confident in its approach. Maybe the Crimson Tide found its
identity in the loss, but the fans want to know why it took four
games into the season to figure out what the offense can and cannot
do.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been struggling with its tackling since the
opener with UCLA, when running back DeShaun Foster gained 187 yards
on 42 carries. On Saturday, with Alabama clinging to a 21-20 lead,
Arkansas drove the length of the field with a third-team tailback
to score the winning touchdown. The fans don't understand why
Alabama, with three nationally ranked recruiting classes in a row,
has only one win in September.
</P>
<P>
   Moore did not accept DuBose's resignation on Sept. 16. But he
said that DuBose, along with other members of the coaching staff,
will be evaluated at the end of the season, as usual. ``I think my
job is to support the team during the season, and we evaluate every
team and every coach at the end of their respective season,'' Moore
said. ``That will be done here. I'm supporting these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   After Alabama won the SEC championship in 1999, DuBose received
a contract extension though the 2004 season. His annual
compensation is just over $500,000. The university would have to
reach a settlement on those four remaining years if it made a
change.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, DuBose will do what he did last September, when it
appeared certain that his days as the head coach at Alabama were
numbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Press on. Press on. It's the only thing I know to do,'' said
DuBose, who played for Alabama 1972-74. ``I'm accountable. I'm not
trying to sidestep anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
