<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILMS-A     09-26 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILMS-ART-545(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIOS RECRUIT YOUTHS TO ASSESS APPEAL OF VIOLENT FILMS, DOCUMENTS
SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (With VIOLENCE-FILMS-VALENTI)  
 (Eds: Note language in marked graf in 2nd take, `There are ...)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Disney released the R-rated Sylvester Stallone movie
``Judge Dredd,'' about urban anarchy and street war, the studio
tested the film before a focus group that included more than 100
youths ages 13 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   MGM/United Artists tested commercials for ``Disturbing
Behavior,'' an R-rated horror thriller about troublemaking
teen-agers transformed into upstanding citizens, before more than
400 12- to 20-year-olds. A survey reported that they felt the
``standout scene'' was one of a blonde bashing her head into a
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Tristar's researchers interviewed 50 children ages 9 to
11 to evaluate concepts for the sequel to ``I Know What You Did
Last Summer,'' a tale of a serial slasher equipped with an outsized
ice hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence to indicate that attendance in the original
movie dipped down to the age of 10,'' explained a memorandum from
the National Research Group, the dominant market research
organization for major studios. ``Therefore, it seems to make sense
to interview 10- to 11-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   These incidents and others are recorded in confidential
marketing documents submitted by nine movie studios to the
government commission that investigated the marketing of violent
entertainment to children. Those documents show that some of the
biggest companies in Hollywood routinely recruited scores of
teen-agers and children as young as 9 to evaluate story concepts,
commercials, theatrical trailers and rough cuts for R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the movie industry's trade association, the Motion
Picture Association of America, announced steps to restrict its
marketing of R-rated films to under-age children. Among them is a
pledge not to use children under 17 in test screenings unless they
are accompanied by an adult. An R-rated movie requires that anyone
under 17 be accompanied by an adult because of explicit violent or
sexual content. The rating, like all movie ratings, is the
industry's own standard, subject only to its own policing.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, the MPAA chairman, said a report by the Federal
Trade Commission had prompted studios to take ``a fresh new look at
the way we market films.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's program is the latest consequence of the FTC's
sharply critical report on marketing practices in the movie, music
and video-game industries. Citing regulations prohibiting it from
releasing trade secrets, the report did not reveal the names of the
entertainment companies involved or the details of the marketing
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Those are contained in the supporting documents, which were
obtained by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Eight movie studio executives are scheduled to testify Wednesday
before the Senate Commerce Committee about their policies. At the
first committee hearing, two weeks ago, Valenti conceded that
perhaps marketing people ``stepped over the line'' but argued that
the location of that line was ``ill lit, hazily observed.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti maintained that ``we are not dealing with Euclid's
geometry where the equations are pristine and explicit.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the confidential marketing reports Tuesday,
Valenti said, ``I didn't know it was happening.'' He added that the
``practice of going to 10- and 12-year-olds is really not
acceptable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In their own marketing plans submitted to the FTC the major
movie studios offered a window into practices that can begin almost
as soon as a movie is conceived. Preliminary test screenings are
conducted months before films appear in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters hunt for moviegoers in the lines outside cinemas or
malls offering free tickets to people who match the age and ethnic
profile set by the studios. And the results ultimately can shape
promotions, advertising and decisions for a movie sequel.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the memorandums describing marketing strategy, movie
studios and video-game makers acknowledged that while they have
publicly identified 18- to 34-year-olds as their primary audience
for restricted movies and games, they needed the support of young
teen-agers. Toy tie-ins to PG-13 movies, which caution that violent
material may be ``inappropriate'' for children under 13, broaden
the promotion of those films to children as young as 4.
</P>
<P>
   The main company that gathers marketing information for major
movie studios is National Research Group of Los Angeles. Joseph
Farrell, the company's co-chairman, said that information is
gathered in a variety of ways, including telephone surveys and test
screenings of movies, commercials and theatrical trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the specifications that we carry out, including the
methodology involving focus groups, are prescribed by the
studios,'' said Farrell, who noted that no one under 12 is
``approached or interviewed or involved in discussions without a
parent's permission.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For test screenings, younger people are accompanied by parents,
Farrell said. He described the process of gathering information
from focus groups of younger children as unusual.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the FTC examined 44 R-rated films and 20 violent
PG-13 films distributed by the nine major studios over a four-year
period ending in 1999. Thirty-three of the 44 R-rated films or
advertisements for them were screened for under-age teen-agers and
children as young as 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' Farrell said of that
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall-out from the FTC report, Disney announced earlier
this month that it would not show R-rated films from any of its
units to focus groups with participants under 17 and would urge
theaters to more strictly enforce age restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But marketing plans from the company's units, Touchstone and
Hollywood Pictures, show that the studio has turned to younger
children for market research on R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Judge Dredd,'' Hollywood Pictures tested the
1995 film with a broad group that included a subset of 13- to
16-year-olds. The participants were asked to rate everything from
the movie's music and action to the film's ending and its hero,
played by Stallone. Participants also rated every movie scene, from
a robot ripping off a man's arms to a prison plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the company's researchers tested the movie's five
commercials before 1,800 people, who included participants as young
as 12. And those surveys, along with the earlier movie ratings,
detected a clear pattern of enthusiasm among one age group: young
teen-agers, particularly males.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Disney's Touchstone Pictures also turned to younger
viewers to test the appeal of trailers for an R-rated thriller,
``Enemy of the State,'' which starred Will Smith. One focus group
of 300 people included participants ages 12 to 14, according to a
research report. In addition, the company gathered a second group
of 300 African-Americans, which also included participants as young
as 12. The aim of the survey was to test the power of the movie's
trailers. That information would then provide critical insight
about which people were most likely to go to the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing plans for other films show the meticulous efforts made
by major movie studios to gauge the tastes of younger, often
under-age moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   When Columbia Tristar tested concepts for the 1998 teen slasher
sequel, ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer,'' it commissioned
research from a sample group of 500 people who had seen the
original movie.
</P>
<P>
   The sample was made up of 500 people 12 to 24. Of those, 100
were 9 to 11. In addition, researchers interviewed a group of 150
Latinos and African-Americans ages 12 to 24, and 50 more ages 9 to
11.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, as outlined in a memorandum from National Research
Group, was plain: ``to determine who are the most intense fans of
the movie by age, gender, ethnicity, et cetera, and what drives
their zeal. The results will help define the primary and secondary
targets and what about the movie most appeals to them. It will also
provide information on the key aspects of the original movie most
liked and guidance for direction of the second movie.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Columbia was even more aggressive about targeting a
younger audience for the futuristic science-fiction thriller ``The
Fifth Element,'' a PG-13 film starring Bruce Willis as a 23rd
century cabdriver turned galactic hero.
</P>
<P>
   The studio sought to advertise the movie on the children's
network Nickelodeon. MTV Networks, which oversees Nickelodeon,
refused to allow an advertisement because it considered the movie
inappropriate for its viewers, who are mostly under 12.
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE LANGUAGE IN FOLLOWING GRAF)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several gun battles, a couple of fight sequences and
some devastating bomb blasts,'' an MTV executive wrote to
representatives of Columbia. ``Finally the sexual situations are
well removed from Nickelodeon's sphere _ the talk show host
performing cunnilingus on a female singer.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio then unsuccessfully appealed the ban, arguing in part
that the science-fiction genre required a suspension of belief and
that the violence would be suspect to ``the children of today who
are more sophisticated.'' In addition, they noted in a memorandum:
``This film needs the audience that Nickelodeon provides to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest for the under-17 market reflects certain realities of
moviegoing habits. Studies from the Motion Picture Association of
America indicate, for example, that the group ages 12 to 17
accounts for 17 percent of movie audiences, a figure
disproportionate to their actual share of the population, which is
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When MGM/United Artists was preparing to release its R-rated
film ``Disturbing Behavior'' in 1998, researchers started tracking
the interest and awareness among a sample of 331 10- to
20-year-olds and a broader group of 400 12- to 59-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the studio screened two 30-second commercials among 438
moviegoers 12 to 20. In a scene-by-scene rating of the commercials,
viewers evaluated such fleeting moments as a ``needle toward
clamped eye'' and a girl bashing her head into a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stand-out scenes continue to be the blonde hitting her
head in the mirror,'' the researchers reported, ``Also enjoyed are
scenes of Holmes in confrontation with a strange man being menaced.
All of these factors lead to stronger performance of the
commercials among 15- to 17-year-olds. Those 18 to 24 remain
hesitant about the horror focus of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Universal Studios outlined its preparations to
promote the PG-13 movie ``The Mummy,'' which includes elements of
suggested violence, like a knifing murder in the shadows and the
mummy's theft of the eyeballs and tongue of a hapless victim.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's target audience consisted of two groups: frequent
moviegoers 12 to 34 and male fans of action films 10 to 24. To
reach the ``tweens,'' as the memorandum labeled the younger set,
the company created a plan to advertise on television shows that
attract extremely young viewers, like ``Pokemon,'' ``Power
Rangers'' and ``Spiderman.''
</P>
<P>
   The target market for Universal's ``Mummy'' merchandising
program was even younger: boys 4 to 14. The company developed plans
to distribute 6-inch action figures and 12-inch collector mummies
at Toys R Us, K-Mart and Target.
</P>
<P>
   To cap the marketing blitz, Universal Studios in Florida built a
haunted house maze for Halloween last year that included a mummy
character. The marketing report noted the potential impact:
``250,000 kids expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most blunt and candid appraisal of the youthful
audience for violent entertainment comes in two marketing
memorandums for restricted video games called ``Turok'' and ``Duke
Nukem Zero Hour,'' which features a foul-mouthed alien-annihilator
who, according to promotional material, is notable for ``spitting
more one-liners than Rodney Dangerfield while building the body
count.'' Both carry an ``M'' rating, which bars their sale to
children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising recommendations for ``Duke'' from GT Interactive
Software's 1998 marketing plan observe that because of the
restricted M rating for the video the target audience is identified
as males 17 to 34. ``The true target is males 9 to 34,'' the report
adds.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the memorandum was prepared, GT Interactive was
acquired by Infogrames Inc., a French company with offices in San
Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way we approach the marketing of mature
games,'' said Tom Richardson, a spokesman for Infogrames, ``That
doesn't reflect our philosophy. We make every effort to market
mature themes to mature audiences 17 and over.''
</P>
<P>
   In another marketing plan, Acclaim Entertainment, the makers of
the M-rated ``Turok'' series, explains why the primary audience for
the video remains males aged 12 to 17, even though these consumers
cannot buy the material by themselves. The ``Turok'' series has
sold more than 3 million units on the strength of weapons features
like the ``all-powerful Chest-Burster.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Turok' has an M rating, which may discourage parents from
buying the game and hinder clearance of a commercial airing in
shows primarily for children under 12,'' observed the marketing
report. ``However, the younger the audience, the more likely they
are to be influenced by TV advertising. Adults are more likely to
evaluate software purchases based on more extensive research.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
