<HEADER>
A2692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WENHOLEE-HNS &LR;      09-26 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SAYS DR. LEE IS NO HERO 
 

</HEADLINE>
 HO LEE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis
Freeh admitted to a string of mistakes in the Wen Ho Lee case
Tuesday, while seeking to puncture the image of Lee as a martyr of
selective prosecution and racism.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony to a joint hearing of the Senate Judiciary and
Intelligence committees, Reno said, ``Dr. Lee is no hero. He is not
an absent-minded professor. He is a felon.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeh also refused to back off the depiction of Lee as a serious
threat to U.S. security. ``The Department of Justice and the FBI
stand by each and every one of the 59 counts in the indictment of
Dr. Lee. Each of those counts could be proven in December 1999 and
each of them could be proven today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lee nor his attorney, Mark Holscher, could be reached
for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by Reno and Freeh did not assuage congressional
critics. Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., said he continued to feel,
``the investigation was very poorly handled.'' And Sen. Richard
Shelby, R-Ala., who chairs the Senate Intelligence Committee,
called the FBI probe, ``a gravely flawed exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   After the open Senate hearing Tuesday, Reno and Freeh testified
at a closed hearing before a House select committee on
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh and Reno Tuesday laid out the unclassified portion of
evidence they said proved Lee's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   That included a detailed depiction of the steps involved in
Lee's transferring and copying of classified nuclear weapons data.
</P>
<P>
   But the hearing left major questions unanswered, including what
happened to seven of the 10 tapes Lee created from classified
nuclear secrets and who, if not Lee, leaked to China nuclear
warhead information.
</P>
<P>
   And the Reno and Freeh testimony failed to explain how Lee, who
was identified as a potential security risk as early as 1982, could
have kept his access for many years to what one senator called,
``50 years and hundreds of billions of dollars worth of hard-earned
nuclear knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a former scientist at the top secret Los Alamos laboratory
in New Mexico, pleaded guilty earlier this month to mishandling
classified information, one count from what had originally been a
59-count indictment issued in December.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Lee had faced life in prison, but was sentenced
to only the nine months already served and was released Sept. 13
after the guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   Lee had been held in isolation since his indictment. At one
point, Lee was threatened with execution if he failed to cooperate.
He remained shackled for part of his time in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The government's sudden reversal in the Lee case sparked outrage
from supporters and criticism from President Clinton, who made
public comments questioning how Lee could be a ``serious risk one
day'' and be released the next.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to Freeh's and Reno's Tuesday testimony,
is that the plea agreement was the government's best chance to
recover still missing tapes made by Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea agreement, Lee must cooperate with federal
investigators for a year, including aiding efforts to recover
missing computer tapes containing classified information. Lee must
also submit to polygraph tests.
</P>
<P>
   A trial for Lee raised too much risk that nuclear secrets would
be pried loose by his defense attorneys during pretrial discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice and the FBI concluded that this
guilty plea, coupled with Lee's agreement to submit to questioning
under oath and to a polygraph, was our best opportunity to protect
the national security,'' said Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Reno reacted strongly to the suggestion that Lee, a U.S. citizen
born in Taiwan, was a victim of anti-Asian bias. ``Dr. Lee was
investigated and prosecuted based on his actions, not his race,''
Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general also sought to deflect a charge that Lee
was abused while held in confinement for nine months. Reno said Lee
was treated like other prisoners in the New Mexico facility where
he was held.
</P>
<P>
   And she produced a memo from a monitor of the Santa Fe County
jail who said in March, when Lee had been held for three months,
Lee claimed the jail staff was treating him ``very well.''
</P>
<P>
   While denying racism and unfair treatment of Lee, Freeh and Reno
admitted to several mistakes during the Lee case, including:
</P>
<P>
   Lead FBI agent Robert Messemer exaggerated evidence at an early
bond hearing for Lee that damaged the credibility of the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI focused on Lee as early as 1996 because he was
identified in a Department of Energy inquiry as a potential leak
candidate without doing its own review to eliminate other suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In March, while trying to wring a confession from Lee, FBI
agents reminded Lee that atomic spies Julius and Ethel Rosenberg
had been electrocuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confrontational interviews often call for tough statements,
but that implication was inappropriate,'' Freeh said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the most critical failure of federal law enforcement was in
not barring Lee from access to classified information sooner,
Senate critics said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been on the FBI radar screen since 1982, when he
``contacted a suspected agent of a foreign power (China) who was
the subject of an ongoing FBI counterintelligence investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   When confronted about that, Lee lied, the FBI said. In 1994, Lee
met with a senior Chinese weapons designer whom he'd met with on
trips overseas, furthering the FBI's belief that he had the
``opportunity, means and motivation'' to compromise nuclear weapons
secrets, according to Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   All that was known before it was discovered that Lee moved and
copied 400,000 pages of what the FBI insisted was ``extremely
sensitive nuclear weapons files.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's hearing, Reno and Freeh outlined Lee's methods,
which basically consisted of renaming classified files as
unclassified, calling the laboratory's computer help desk for
advice on moving those files and then borrowing a colleague's
computer terminal to download the now unclassified material onto a
tape.
</P>
<P>
   With those simple keyboard strokes, ``Lee created his own
secret, portable, personal trove of this nation's nuclear weapons
secrets,'' said Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Still unanswered is whether Lee shared that treasure trove of
secrets with the People's Republic of China, according to Tuesday's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI only found out moments after Lee agreed to enter a
guilty plea that he had copied the seven tapes still missing,
meaning ``there could be 14 or more'' tapes unaccounted for, Freeh
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
