<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2698 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-SOFT-MONEY-KRIST     09-26 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SOFT-MONEY-KRISTOL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW KINGS OF SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, September 27, and
thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By WILLIAM KRISTOL and JEFFREY BELL   
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans and conservatives around the country
desperately want Rick Lazio to beat Hillary Rodham Clinton in the
New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Lazio campaign is forcing them to rethink two of their
most cherished dogmas: Republican faith in soft money, the
unrestricted donations to political parties and outside groups that
are used to help campaigns, and conservative aversion to campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's reluctant acceptance Saturday of a
soft-money ban was a victory for Lazio. The New York Senate 2000
Committee, an arm of the Democratic senatorial campaign
organization that has been advertising on behalf of Clinton, was
spending more than $1 million a week of soft money on TV ``issue
ads,'' with a lot more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has raised more hard money (that is, individual
contributions directly to the campaign, which are limited to $1,000
a person) than Clinton. If the agreement to ban soft money more or
less holds, as pressure from the media may ensure, Lazio should
have an advertising advantage in the last month of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Republicans' belief that soft money is their friend.
Republicans, of course, as a pro-business party, have raised their
share of soft money. But the Democrats have now caught up and, in
fact, are moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Soft-money raising, focused on economic interests and
unconstrained by any legal limit on contributions, is particularly
suited to the Democratic Party of the Bill Clinton era _ a party
that is at once pro-business and pro-government and that is willing
to approach corporate interests with the prospect that government
policies can help or harm their industries. That's why the
committees that aid Democratic candidates for Congress are in their
best position in decades relative to their Republican counterparts
_ despite the Republicans' majorities in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Most competitive Republican candidates, on the other hand, have
an advantage in $1,000 donations and an even bigger advantage in
smaller contributions. Isn't it in Republicans' interest to revive
the hard money system by increasing individual limits and curbing
the soft money system? Rick Lazio thinks so. And others are coming
around to this view.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Clinton agree to a limit that could hurt her campaign?
Because she thought that not agreeing would harm her even more. She
was probably right.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom in Washington, especially conservative
conventional wisdom, is that campaign finance reform doesn't matter
as an issue. Conservatives resolutely refuse to learn any lesson
from John McCain's thumping of George W. Bush in New Hampshire,
when he made campaign reform his central theme _ or from McCain's
subsequent defeat after he veered from that message.
</P>
<P>
   But campaign reform turns out to have surprising political
salience. Conservatives should welcome this fact, since they have
no stake in the current system.
</P>
<P>
   The great conservative triumphs of our time came, after all,
before the rise of soft money: Ronald Reagan's near-victory, fueled
by small-dollar, hard-money donations, in his primary challenge of
1976; the conservative gains in the congressional elections of 1978
and 1980; and Reagan's winning presidential campaign of 1980. The
full flowering of the soft money system in 1996 has coincided with
a period of conservative political and policy retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too much to ask our fellow Republicans and conservatives
to rethink their self-defeating defense of the current corrupt
campaign finance system, and shape campaign reform legislation that
would be good for them and for the country?
</P>
<P>
   (William Kristol is publisher of The Weekly Standard. Jeffrey
Bell, a principal in Capital City Partners, a public policy
consulting firm, was an aide to the presidential campaign of Gary
Bauer.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
