<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2700 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-POVERTY-RATE-ART-370&AMP;     09-26 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POVERTY-RATE-ART-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOMES UP AND POVERTY DOWN, AGENCY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ariz., Ark., Calif., S.D., Utah, Va., D.C.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau reported Tuesday that median
household income topped $40,000 for the first time last year and
that the percentage of households living in poverty dropped to the
lowest point in more than two decades. It was the fifth straight
increase in median income, the first time that has happened since
the bureau started keeping track of household incomes since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual reports on income and poverty, the bureau noted
that median household income rose by 2.7 percent in 1999, to
$40,816, from $39,744 the prior year. It reported that 11.8 percent
of the population lived below the poverty line in 1999, down from
12.7 percent the year before. The poverty rate in 1999 was defined
as a household income of $17,029 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, the bureau's reports describe an economy
that is merely returning the country to where it was at the
beginning of the 1990s. But they also present a vivid picture of
sharp gains that occurred last year as the economic recovery
reached further down the income scale. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Median income for black ($27,910), Hispanic ($30,735), as well
as non-Hispanic white ($44,366) households reached the highest
levels ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Households in the bottom fifth of the income scale saw their
household earnings rise by 5.4 percent, the largest of any
quintile.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of people living in extreme poverty, defined as
having incomes that are less than 50 percent of the official
poverty line, dropped to 4.6 percent of the population, from 5.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 80 percent of the 2.2 million households that moved
above the poverty line in 1999 lived in the inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   _ While seven states _ Arizona, Arkansas, California, New York,
South Dakota, Utah and Virginia _ and the District of Columbia saw
their overall poverty rates decrease, no state saw a statistically
significant rise in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so striking about these numbers is that it shows that
the economic progress is not just restricted to Silicon Valley or
to the stock market,'' said Martin Bailey, chairman of President
Clinton's Council of Economic Advisers after reviewing the census
data.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, 1999 was only the second year in a row that median income
topped the $38,837 level of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Released six weeks before the election, the eagerly awaited
report often provides fodder for political campaigns. The Clinton
administration and Vice President Al Gore's campaign immediately
claimed credit for the robust results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly shows that progress has been made over the last
eight years,'' said Douglas Hattaway, a Gore spokesman. ``But the
central question of this campaign is how we build on our prosperity
to make new progress and to benefit everyone, not just a few.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas also sought to claim credit for the
economic progress that has been made in his state during the past
few years, pointing out that Texas' two-year average median income
rose 3.5 percent, higher than the 3.1 percent increase for the
country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign attributed the growth in income to policies he
pushed as governor, like the ``two biggest tax cuts in Texas
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The average two-year median income did rise faster than the
national rate and more than several states, including Alaska,
Georgia, Kentucky and Louisiana. But Texas' income growth was less
than that of states like Arkansas, Rhode Island and New York, and
the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, some downturns in the Census Bureau's
upbeat news. For the second year in a row the earnings gap between
men and women increased. Median income for women who work
full-time, year-round, fell slightly to $26,324 from $26,433, while
median income for men working full time rose to $36,376 from
$36,126.
</P>
<P>
   Median household income is the level at which half the 120
million households in the country bring in more money and half
bring in less. It is considered a more accurate measure than
average household income, which can be skewed by a relatively few
super-wealthy families.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, for the sixth year in a row, the gap between the
rich and the middle class and the poor did not change, and there is
a dispute among economists as to whether it may have increased.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's calculations of income do not take into
consideration some government benefits like the earned-income tax
credit, which has directed billions of dollars of cash assistance
to poor people who work. Census officials say factoring the tax
credit in would cause a closing of the income gap between the rich
and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the bureau does not factor in capital gains
earnings on the sale of stocks or property when calculating income
figures. Since the information on income is gathered from telephone
interviews, Census officials say people are generally not asked
about their capital gains income, since most people do not have
that information at their fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists say including capital gains income would greatly
widen the income gap between the affluent and the poor. They note
that the IRS reports that capital gains income rose to $427 billion
in 1998 from $163 billion in 1993, and that the great bulk of those
earnings went to tax filers with incomes over $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``One begins to worry that inequality has stabilized at a
historically high level,'' said Jared Bernstein, an economist at
the Economic Policy Institute, a liberal research organization. ``I
don't see any good reason in an economy as strong as ours, at this
point in the business cycle, that we don't seem to be nudging
income inequality down.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
