<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE STUDENTS GRILL GORE ON ABORTION, MUSIC 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ They spared him the dreaded underpants
question, but college students Tuesday grilled Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore on everything from abortion rights
to his music preferences.
</P>
<P>
   In a town hall meeting at the University of Michigan, broadcast
Tuesday night on MTV's ``Choose or Lose'' cable television program,
Gore urged young people to resist disillusionment and vote on Nov.
7. Recent polls indicate that fewer than half of registered voters
under age 25 will do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anyone tell you that it doesn't make a difference
and that you cannot change the world,'' Gore told 150 students
selected by MTV and Time magazine to ask questions during the
90-minute taping. ``You can change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who also has made recent television visits with talk show
hosts Oprah Winfrey, Jay Leno and David Letterman, watched as the
audience was shown his MTV-produced biography.
</P>
<P>
   Gore laughed as the reporter noted that the vice president was
``into PDA'' (public displays of affection) as a video rolled of
the now-famous big kiss he shared with wife, Tipper, on the stage
of the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the questions Gore fielded were dead serious.
</P>
<P>
   He explained to an anti-abortion woman student why he supports
abortion rights and promised a black male student that he would
make a ban on racial profiling ``the first civil rights act of the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV also has invited Republican nominee George W. Bush to
participate in a similar forum. He has so far not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   One student revealed that he was leaning toward voting for Green
Party nominee and consumer activist Ralph Nader. ``How can you
convince me that a vote for Al Gore is a conscientious vote and not
simply a vote for the lesser of two evils?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore went to work trying to earn the man's vote, and rattled off
a list of his own causes that are also popular with Nader
followers, including his support for the environment, consumers and
working families, and his push for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to vote your heart,'' he said, ``but I want to
convince you that I will do the kind of job that will make you
proud of our process and make our country the kind of place that
you want it to be.``
</P>
<P>
   Another student told Gore he was ``mad as hell'' that because he
is gay, he and his life partner won't get to enjoy the same
benefits and rights of marriage that straight couples have. Gore
responded that discrimination against gays and lesbians is
``indefensible,'' and there should be some way of legally
recognizing unions between gay couples.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said he opposes legalization of medicinal marijuana,
and took the side of musical artists' intellectual property rights
in the debate over free music distribution by such Internet
companies as Napster.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a similar MTV forum posed the famous ``boxers or
briefs'' question to President Clinton, which he deigned to answer
(``Usually briefs'') to mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was not subjected to any question that personal, but
students wanted to know what music was on his CD player (Sister
Hazel) and who might perform at his inauguration if he's elected
(Lenny Kravitz). &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
