<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ATTACKS GORE OVER LAGGING STUDENT TEST SCORES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ Education reform may be a top priority of
Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign, but the Republican
nominee passed the buck on three key educational issues on Tuesday
because, he said, he also believes in local control of public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Bush attacked Democratic rival Al
Gore over lagging student test scores during the Clinton-Gore
administration and vowed to use the White House to help other
states score the educational improvements that Texas has seen
during Bush's tenure as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If American students don't lead the world in math and science,
the next generation of Americans may not lead the world,'' Bush
said in an appearance at Sequoia High School in this Silicon Valley
community.
</P>
<P>
   But when three of his first four questioners tried to pin down
the Texas governor on tax vouchers for private schools, teacher pay
and classroom size, he insisted those issues should be decided by
state, not federal, officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush unsuccessfully tried to convince the Texas Legislature last
year to establish a limited voucher program for students from
low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state of California wants to do that, the state of
California can,'' he said. ``I believe in local control. I don't
believe in (federal) mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about teacher pay, he replied, ``You can't pay a good
teacher enough money,'' but added: ``I believe that teacher
salaries are the prerogative of the state governments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The states have the most responsibility for public education.
Therefore, I would suggest you write your governor and make sure
that he makes public education the No. 1 funding priority in
California, like I made education the No. 1 funding priority in the
state of Texas.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that last year teachers in Texas got a $3,000-a-year
pay raise, an accomplishment for which both the Republican governor
and Democratic legislators have claimed credit.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed raising teacher pay by as much as $5,000 in
some areas and supports $10,000 raises for teachers with special
certification.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government provides only about 7 percent of
public education funding, Bush would use part of that money as a
hammer to force schools to improve student performance.
</P>
<P>
   Public schools that are low-performing three years in a row
would lose part of their federal Title I funds for disadvantaged
students. The money, about $1,500 a year, would be given to
parents, who could use it to transfer their children to other
public schools or private or parochial schools. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
