<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPEC-MEET-NYT &LR;      09-26 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VENEZUELA'S PRESIDENT, OIL PRICING ON A SOAPBOX  

</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER 
 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ With oil prices at their highest level in a
decade and the United States and other industrial countries calling
for relief, heads of state and oil ministers from the 11 members of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries are to begin a
two-day summit meeting here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the group is more united than in the recent past, and
several of its members, including the host, Venezuela, anticipate
record oil revenue this year, the mood of the gathering promises to
be both celebratory and unbending.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting also offers President Hugo Chavez, who has played an
important role in the tripling of world oil prices over the last 18
months, a chance to step onto the world stage as a critic of the
rich and defender of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC has risen again,'' Chavez exulted in a televised speech
to his country on Monday. He described the price of crude oil,
which last week soared at one point to nearly $38 a barrel before
retreating some, as ``fair and just'' and said that with ``the
equilibrium of the universe hanging in the balance,'' he wanted the
oil producers' group to use its power to create ``a more just
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a century, they took millions of barrels of oil at
giveaway prices,'' Chavez said Sunday on his weekly radio program,
referring to the ``bad habits'' of industrial nations in another
preview of the arguments he is likely to make during the
conference. ``How nice it would be if they also lowered the prices
of things they sell to us, lowered the prices of computers,
medicine, cars and the interest rates on the foreign debt,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Rodriguez Araque, who is the president of OPEC and
Venezuela's oil minister, said no decision on a production increase
by OPEC would be made during the conference. The cartel's members
account for three-quarters of the world's proven oil reserves and
more than 40 percent of output.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer nations have been calling for such a step, but
Rodriguez said it would not be discussed until an OPEC ministers'
meeting on Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering here begins, though, with cartel members unsure
how to respond to the Clinton administration's decision last week
to release 30 million barrels of crude oil from the U.S. reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Since Thursday, after Vice President Al Gore's call for the
release of oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, prices have
fallen by about $4 a barrel. Tuesday in Washington, Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson said the administration would consider
releasing more oil in 30 days if prices do not stay down.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices were little changed Tuesday in New York, where the
November delivery price fell 7 cents, to $31.50 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, OPEC's biggest producer, initially dismissed
Clinton's move as ``an election ploy requested by Al Gore,'' but
upon arrival here Monday, Oil Minister Ali al-Naimi said the
American action ``will stabilize the price of oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Algeria's oil minister, Chakib Khelil, criticized the American
move as ``a very short-term measure that may give the wrong signal
that OPEC doesn't have enough capacity'' to meet market demand.
</P>
<P>
   His Libyan counterpart, Abdullah Salem el-Badri, said the action
by the United States ``comes at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   During the conference, OPEC members are also expected to
increase criticism of the calls made by industrial nations at the
International Monetary Fund talks in Prague over the weekend for
OPEC to contain the price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC members argue that the main sources of high prices at the
gasoline pump are high demand and exorbitant taxes in industrial
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done our part'' by increasing production by a total of
3.2 million barrels a day this year, OPEC's general secretary,
Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria, said at a news conference here Monday.
``If they want to bury their heads in the ground over the heads of
their citizens, that's up to them,'' he added, referring to
European nations that have led the call for lower oil prices as
many of their people have blocked roads and otherwise engaged in
public protest.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rodriguez argues that OPEC is already producing 2
million barrels a day more than the world economy needs and that
speculators are benefiting at the expense of consumers. In the last
six months, he said, ``OPEC was supplying the market more than was
required, and that means stocks are building somewhere.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
