<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPEC-MEET-OIL-2NDTAKE     09-26 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEET-OIL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CARACUS, Venezuela: building somewhere.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's gathering here is only the second in OPEC's 40-year
history intended to bring heads of state of member countries
together, the other having been a 1975 meeting in Algeria. Efforts
to organize similar events have foundered in the past, in 1980
because of war between Iran and Iraq and in 1990 with of Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela was chosen as the site in part because it holds OPEC's
rotating presidency, but also because OPEC's founding was largely a
Venezuelan initiative. On Sept. 10, 1960, with the price of oil
falling, Venezuela's energy minister at the time, Juan Pablo Perez
Alfonso, persuaded four Mideast nations to join him in ``securing a
steady income to the producing countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, though, Venezuela, which has the largest
reserves of oil outside the Middle East, earned a reputation in the
cartel as a quota buster, almost always willing to raise production
in an effort to compensate for falling prices. As the price of
crude oil fell below $10 a barrel and OPEC members drifted deeper
into debt, those complaints intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in February 1999, Chavez has become one of
the leading hawks within OPEC, creating the possibility of conflict
with more cautious members such as Saudi Arabia. Venezuela produces
2.65 million barrels a day, more than six times its domestic
consumption. Chavez hopes to use the windfall resulting from
expected petroleum revenue of $26 billion this year, up more than
$10 billion over last year, to help finance an ambitious $2.1
billion social works program he announced earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC has increased its production this year much more than is
necessary,'' he said recently. ``We must never allow ourselves to
fall to our knees again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to expand OPEC's influence further, the Venezuelan
president has also made it clear that he would like to see new
members enter the group. Early this month he invited Russia to
join, and he has said that the door is also open to Latin American
producers such as Ecuador, Colombia and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This meeting isn't only about oil,'' Chavez, a former army
colonel who in 1992 led an unsuccessful coup attempt, said on
Monday. He said it was also necessary for the oil group to take the
lead in discussing issues of ``poverty, inequality in the world,
foreign debt and the autonomy of nations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
