<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-GRAHAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SUSPEND GOALTENDER WHO BROKE ANKLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you think the Bruins have had a rough battle in
terms of signing their free agents, that could pale in comparison
to the fight they're likely to have on their hands with backup
goaltender John Grahame.
</P>
<P>
   Grahame broke an ankle under mysterious circumstances last
Saturday night/Sunday morning, and he has been suspended without
pay for being in violation of Article 5B of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   In general terms, the provision says that if a player can't
fulfill his contract for reasons that have nothing to do with his
job, the club doesn't have to pay him. Grahame could forfeit half
of his $500,000 salary.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League Players Association is expected to
file a grievance on Grahame's behalf, but the Bruins appear to be
within their rights. Article 5B reads: ``If the player in the
judgment of the club's physician is disabled or is not in good
physical condition at the beginning of the season or any subsequent
time during the season so as to render him unfit to play skilled
hockey, it is mutually agreed that the club shall have the right to
suspend the player for such a period of disability or unfitness and
no compensation shall be payable for that period under this
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   NHLPA spokesman Tim Wharnsby said, ``Our lawyers are still
looking into the matter. We don't have all the facts. We've talked
with (Grahame's agent) Don Baizley, but he has yet to get back to
us on the facts of the incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Grahame returned home to Colorado, where he was expected to
undergo surgery that will sideline him three months. Because of the
suspension, Grahame is not insured under the Bruins, but his
medical care is covered under the NHLPA.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a case of apparent willful disregard for the rules,
such as when former Canadiens defenseman Vladimir Malakhov took his
family skiing while he was supposed to be sidelined by a serious
injury or when Red Wings defenseman Uwe Krupp went sled-dog racing
when he was out of the lineup with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   In Grahame's case, the circumstances of what happened late
Saturday night have yet to come to light.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't got all the facts yet,'' said Bruins assistant
general manager Mike O'Connell. ``We've got to go by the letters of
the law. We're pretty sure what happened. I don't want to say
anything until I'm 100 percent sure.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he notified Grahame of the suspension before the
player headed west.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was upset,'' said O'Connell. ``I think he was upset
the whole thing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins want Grahame back once he is able to play, but it's
clear they are playing hardball. They have used the tools of the
collective bargaining agreement to limit the escalation of player
salaries, and now they're using it to suspend (and therefore not
pay) Grahame.
</P>
<P>
   The club is in the hunt for another goaltender, perhaps Wrentham
native Garth Snow, but O'Connell said they will likely wait until
after Friday's waiver draft to see who is available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
