<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEMANS0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Petit no small race to fans
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the top factory teams in the world will compete Saturday
in the third Petit Le Mans at Road Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-car field will feature teams from Audi, BMW, Panoz, Dodge
Viper, Cadillac and Corvette. The cars will be driven by many of
the same drivers who compete in the world's most famous endurance
race, the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
</P>
<P>
   The Petit, the first event licensed to use the Le Mans name
outside France, has become America's jewel in the crown. About
65,000 fans are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ticket sales are through the roof,'' said Mike Swaine,
executive raceway director at Road Atlanta. ``Through today, we've
sold close to as many tickets in advance as we did totally
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers would not have guessed in June 1998 that the circuit
would have this success. That month was when Don Panoz announced
his grand plan for the 10-hour, 1,000-mile race and the formation
of the new series.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, sports-car racing was in shambles. Drivers and
owners were demoralized, and they were in no mood to believe any
more promises; but they hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, when the concept first came up, I was a bit
dubious,'' said world champion driver Butch Leitzinger of State
College, Pa. ``In the last 10 years, there have been a lot of
investors and buyers come in and talk big and then within a year
leave with tails between their legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Panoz, who owns Road Atlanta and formed the American Le Mans
Series, ignored the naysayers. ``I was chided back then, but the
fans backed me with their feet by marching to the race track,'' he
said. ``I felt strongly if you gave the fans the best cars,
drivers, technology, they would come.''
</P>
<P>
   They came. The race drew approximately 45,000 fans last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panoz did everything he said he was going to,'' Leitzinger
said. ``I really do have to give it to him. He's done a good job.
It's not pie-in-the-sky ambition. He just wants sports-car racing
to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the success of the Panoz venture, Leitzinger is
driving for the Cadillac factory team. Leitzinger said he knew it
would take ``a lot of effort, a lot of work and a lot of money,''
but he did not know that Panoz would move a mountain, literally, to
get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   That mountain is directly across the track from the old paddock
area near the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had to dig 385,000 square feet from the mountain to
make room for new garage areas, pit access and room for fans to
move.
</P>
<P>
   In a little less than four months, millions of tons were moved
and cement was poured. The new paddock was ready barely in time for
the first Petit.
</P>
<P>
   It was an important face-lift for the 31-year-old, 700-acre
facility. Road Atlanta, hurting from a decade of neglect, was
revitalized and alive.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers were in awe. ``When we came back and saw what had
been done, it was quite a shock,'' Leitzinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine cars competed in October 1998. It was a small field
but a strong start.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the series the drivers and factory teams take
seriously,'' said Scot Allan McNish, the circuit's top driver in
the Audi R8. The ALMS had an eight-race schedule in 1999, two of
them at Road Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are 12 races, including two in Europe. Next
season, the number of races is up to 15, with additions in Europe
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
