<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASE0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. beats rain delay, South Korea to reach gold medal baseball
game
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - After an hour and 55-minute rain delay Tuesday, the
United States completed a come-from-behind victory over South Korea
with a dramatic ninth-inning solo home run by Doug Mientkiewicz to
advance to the gold-medal game against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Mientkiewicz, a first baseman in the Minnesota organization, hit
a towering shot over the right-field wall to give the U.S. a 3-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans face the imposing Cubans today for the gold medal.
It was more difficult for Team USA to get to the title game than it
was for Cuba, which beat Japan 3-0 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams go into the title match with one defeat in eight
games. Cuba, which easily defeated the U.S. team last week 6-1,
dropped its first Olympic game ever, to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, America rode the clutch performance of pitcher Roy
Oswalt in a steady downpour and were fortunate to get Korean
sidearm pitcher Tae-Hyon Chong out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Korea broke through in the third inning against Oswalt. Oswalt
walkedthe leadoff batter and gave up a double to Jin-Man Park,
putting runners at second and third with no outs. Soo-Keun Jung
followed with a sacrifice fly to left, and Byung-Kyu Lee hit a
double to left to drive in the other run.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2-0 Korea, and its contingent made much noise. But Oswalt
settled into a groove and kept the Americans close. After the third
inning, he retired 15 of 16 batters going into the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The United States scored its first run in the fourth inning:
Brad Wilkerson led off with a double to the right-field corner. He
was on third with two outs when John Cotton lined a double to
left-center field to drive him in.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States trouble with Chong continued. And it
seemed a break that he was taken out of the game with one out and a
runner on first in the seventh inning for lefthander Jin-Woo Song.
</P>
<P>
   Song gave up a single to right to Mientkiewicz, moving Mike
Kinkade to third. Kinkade was driven home on a sacrifice fly by
catcher Marcus Jensen to tie the game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Because of rain, the players were pulled off the field in the
eighth inning with the U.S. at bat, a runner on third, and one out.
When play resumed, the Americans loaded the bases with one out but
failed to get a run across.
</P>
<P>
   But no worries, as they say here. Mientkiewicz came through.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba 3, Japan 0
</P>
<P>
   New tournament format, same result. Orestes Kindelan drives in
runs and Cuba plays for the baseball gold.
</P>
<P>
   Kindelan, the cleanup hitter on Cuba's two gold medal teams,
drove in three runs with a pair of singles for a victory over Japan
in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing its all-red uniforms, the Big Red Machine of Olympic
baseball advanced to its third consecutive title game.
</P>
<P>
   International baseball leveled the field by switching from metal
to wood bats and allowing professionals in the Olympic tournament
for the first time. Cuba had its 21-game winning streak snapped and
had two more close calls _ a pair of one-run wins _ during the
preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   A team featuring 13 gold medal players was at its best when the
gold was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably they have better concentration and their pitching is
probably better than ours,'' Japan manager Kozo Ohtagaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, which sent eight top players from its major leagues to
the Olympics, got outhit, outpitched and _ during the game's
turning moment _ outcoached.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Ariel Contreras, Cuba's top pitcher, held a lineup
featuring four Japanese major leaguers to six hits while striking
out nine. Contreras, who mixes a 90 mph fastball with a nasty
breaking ball, allowed only four balls out of the infield in the
first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Japan's hitters were very good, but we have a saying
in baseball: good pitching stops good hitting,'' Cuba manager
Servio Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed by rain for 68 minutes in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, which lost the gold medal game to Cuba in 1996, chose not
to use top starter Daisuke Matsuzaka, who had only two days of rest
after his nine-inning start against South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it went with Tomohiro Kuroki, who took Hideki Irabu's
place as the top starter for the Chiba Lotte Marines three years
ago. Kuroki lost because he couldn't handle Kindelan.
</P>
<P>
   Kindelan's line-drive single to left drove in a run for a 1-0
lead in the fourth. A strategic mistake gave Kindelan a chance to
break the game open in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Ulacia reached on an infield single and took second on
Yasser Gomez's single. Kindelan came up with two outs, and both
runners advanced on Kuroki's first-pitch wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Even though first base now was open and Cuba's top run-producer
was at bat, the Japanese chose to pitch to him. The 36-year-old
power hitter lined the next pitch to left with a resounding
``Whack!'' for a two-run single, spinning and pumping his arm after
he rounded first.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese knew first-hand that Kindelan was dangerous _ he
hit a three-run homer and drove in four runs Sunday in Cuba's 6-2
preliminary-round win over Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared for him,'' Kuroki said. ``I got the ball up and
he got a hit. He's the best in the world, so it's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
