<SLUG> BC-PERU-PANAMA-395&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU CLOSING BRIBERY CASE OF TOP AIDE NOW AN EXILE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ As Panamanians denounced the arrival of
Peru's disgraced intelligence chief to seek asylum, a prosecutor
announced in Peru on Tuesday that she was closing the bribery case
against him.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence chief, Vladimiro Montesinos, was seen on
videotape apparently handing $15,000 to an opposition member of
Congress, presumably to win his support. News reports from Lima
said the prosecutor's decision, subject to review by superiors, was
made on the grounds that there was no official misconduct because
the congressman had not yet been sworn into office.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos, who had been a close adviser to President Alberto
Fujimori, arrived here early Sunday and has been given a 90-day
tourist visa as officials review his asylum request. He is said to
be staying in the home of the Peruvian consul.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the prosecutor's decision will affect his
asylum claim. It was not unexpected among political experts in
Lima, who had said Montesinos is the master of too many secrets
that touch Peru's highest levels of political and military power.
Many opposition politicians, who had accused him of murder, torture
and human rights violations, had made his arrest and trial a
nonnegotiable step toward any dialogue on Fujimori's call for
elections next year, a contest in which he will apparently not run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will only create more of a crisis,'' said Fernando
Llovera, a spokesman for Alejandro Toledo, who made a strong
showing against Fujimori in the first round of the recent
presidential election, before contending that the vote was fixed
and dropping out of the race. ``There are now several groups who
will no longer take part in any dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Several opposition legislators arrived here on Monday to ask
President Mireya Moscoso to deny asylum on the grounds that
Montesinos was fleeing criminal judgment, not political
persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian human rights groups held a modest protest Tuesday on
the same street where in 1979 they denounced an asylum request by
the deposed shah of Iran. The demonstrators said they wanted to
show their opposition to Montesinos' presence and their country's
reputation as a haven for political pariahs.
</P>
<P>
   The government Tuesday expelled seven Peruvians who arrived here
soon after Montesinos, including high-ranking military officers who
are his allies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Over the years, Panama has been the home in exile to, among
others, the shah, Gen. Raoul Cedras of Haiti and a former
Guatemalan president, Jorge Serrano Elias.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling I have is the same as 21 years ago, that of
indignation and impotence,'' said Miguel Antonio Bernal, a
political expert who said police nearly beat him to death in the
protests against the shah. ``Once again, Panama has been used as a
garbage dump and latrine for this type of rat. The truth is that
Panama is a business, not a country. These people come here with
money to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Aleman said his office was
reviewing the asylum request, which he said was political because
of Montesinos' role as an adviser and intelligence chief. Aleman
acknowledged that the decision to admit Montesinos was made only
after U.S. officials and numerous Latin American presidents had
called Moscoso to warn her that it was the only way to avoid a
bloody coup in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a sacrifice by the Panamanian people to help the
Peruvian people attain an open democracy,'' Aleman said. ``So it
fell to us to receive Montesinos. We are a political party that was
itself persecuted by the army. It was hard for us to make this
decision. But we did it for a brother country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, a vice president in the '90s, said other
countries had more resources and room for Montesinos. ``Why haven't
the Latin American presidents explained why they were so eager for
Panama to accept him?'' he asked. ``We no longer wish to be the
little country where they send dictators.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political experts said that Panama might have been hoping
to get off an American blacklist for not having done enough to
fight money laundering. ``This was a matter of hemispheric
cooperation to promote democracy in keeping with international
accords,'' Aleman said. ``I hope that is valued in some way. But
there was no quid pro quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Panama's sometimes troubling role as a haven may bring unwanted
costs, said Robert A. Pastor, a political scientist at Emory
University and a former member of the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panama has made its own democratic transition, and it is
moving to consolidate the rule of law,'' Pastor said. ``So to
excuse somebody who may have committed crimes in another country
does not do much to consolidate the rule of law in a hemispheric
context.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
