<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS PICK UP SIZE WITH NAZAROV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ In an effort to bolster their size up front,
the Anaheim Mighty Ducks acquired occasionally feisty right wing
Andrei Nazarov from the Calgary Flames on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks also will receive a second-round draft pick in 2001.
In exchange, Calgary gets the rights to 20-year-old promising
defenseman Jordan Leopold. Leopold, a junior at the University of
Minnesota, was Anaheim's second-round choice in 1999. He was the
44th overall selection in that draft.
</P>
<P>
   The trade for the 6-foot-5, 230-pound Nazarov figures to benefit
Anaheim's second, but more likely, its third line. The team was
able to part with the developing Leopold because it feels fairly
secure with its number of NHL-ready young defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Nazarov) is a big and aggressive guy who has an edge,''
said Anaheim general manager Pierre Gauthier. ``We said we wanted
to be bigger. He's had his ups and downs, but we're getting him at
the right age.''
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old forward set career bests last season in games
played (76), assists (22) and points (32) in his seventh NHL
season.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarov, a native of Russia, is remembered among local fans,
perhaps, for his stick-swinging incident with the Kings' Matt
Johnson a few years ago when Nazarov was a member of the San Jose
Sharks. But Nazarov, who totaled 22 penalty minutes during the
1996-97 season, cut that total to 78 minutes last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he is going to help us immensely,'' Ducks coach Craig
Hartsburg said. ``We needed to add size and grit and this guy can
play on one of the top three lines. He's still at an age where we
think he can get better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks roster, with the addition of Nazarov, is now at 29
players (three goalies, nine defensemen and 17 forwards). Anaheim
might reassign as many as six players before the regular-season
opener on Oct. 6, against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim sent defensemen Dean Malkoc, Chris O'Sullivan, and Peter
Podhradsky, right wing Maxim Balmochnykh, and goalie Gregg Naumenko
to Cincinnati of the American Hockey League during its second round
of roster cuts Monday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Greg Christensen contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
