<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS STAND BY INVESTIGATION OF LOS ALAMOS
SCIENTIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo  NYT8  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis
Freeh defended their handling of the Wen Ho Lee case on Tuesday,
asserting during a Senate hearing that Lee had committed a serious
crime when he removed what they called a portable library of atomic
secrets from the weapons lab in Los Alamos, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials said they remained convinced that had Lee's
case gone to trial federal prosecutors would have prevailed on each
of the 59 counts of the indictment against him. But they agreed to
a plea bargain, they said, based on a number of factors,
principally that the government was the victim of ``graymail'', a
defense strategy that would have forced prosecutors to reveal
``extremely sensitive'' nuclear secrets if they brought Lee to
trial. They said that Lee disclosed shortly before the plea bargain
that he had not only downloaded the information onto computer
tapes, but had made copies of the tapes _ a disclosure that Reno
and Freeh said they regarded as ``frightening'' because it meant
``that at least seven and as many as fourteen or more tapes
containing vast amounts of our nation's nuclear secrets remain
unaccounted for.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh admitted at the hearing that the government had
made mistakes in the investigation, but neither expressed regret
nor doubts about the case, which ended two weeks ago when Lee
pleaded guilty to a single felony charge of mishandling classified
nuclear weapons data. He was freed after nine months behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual joint statement that was written at the FBI, Reno
and Freeh presented what was, in effect, their most complete and
detailed rebuttal to date in response to complaints from the
federal district judge in the case, James A. Parker, and President
Clinton about whether the government had treated Lee unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   At the joint session of the Senate Judiciary and Intelligence
committees, none of the senators disputed the importance of the
information that Lee downloaded nor did they question the
seriousness of the crime to which he pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate over the information that Lee was accused of
placing at risk continued on Tuesday outside the hearing room when
a former top government nuclear weapons designer who testified in
Lee's defense only last month said that his remarks had been
misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   In a detention hearing for Lee, the designer, John L. Richter,
said that 99 percent of the data that Lee downloaded was
unclassified.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Richter, one of several scientific experts who
testified that the downloaded material was widely known, said in an
interview that he meant his comments to apply only to the software
and physics that underlie the computer codes that Lee downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Richter said his comments did not apply to other data that Lee
removed, including information about the dimensions of weapons and
about the physical properties of bomb materials.
</P>
<P>
   Still, lawmakers in both parties assailed Reno and Freeh for
what they characterized as mismangement of the case, missed
opportunities in the investigation and for their insistence on
keeping Lee in solitary confinement _ and sometimes shackled _ in
the months before the plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev., was sharply critical of the
government. ``This is a case in which there is very little, if any,
good news to tell and plenty of blame to go around,'' he said.
``The FBI, the Energy Department, the Justice Department all share
the responsibility for the poor handling of this matter from the
beginning, dating back to the early 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaints followed criticism from Parker, who presided over
the Lee case and called it a national embarrassment and from
Clinton, who said last week that he was quite troubled by the
government's insistence on pretrial detention.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans expressed skepticism about Clinton's comments.
Richard C. Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the intelligence panel said,
``The President's statements criticizing the conduct of the
presecution, as if it was conducted by an entity beyond his
control, was bizarre to say the least. The President knew exactly
what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh disputed the conclusions of some senior nuclear
weapons experts who have accused the government of exaggerating the
case against Lee because, they say, the information that Lee copied
onto computer tapes was known throughout the rarified circles of
nuclear weapons research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Lee created his own secret portable, personal electronic
library of this nation's nuclear secrets,'' Reno and Freeh said in
their joint statement. ``At the very least in doing so, he placed
these secrets at extraordinary risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The two officials said that the material that Lee downloaded
onto 10 computer tapes contained the ``electronic blueprints of the
exact dimensions and geometry of this nation's nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The data, they said, represented the ``complete nuclear weapons
design capability of Los Alamos at the time _ approximately 50
years of nuclear weapons development, at the expense of hundreds of
billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh sought to portray Lee as a scientist who, for
still unexplained reasons, downloaded through a series of computer
systems a vast amount of data that was unrelated to his work. When
he fell under suspicion, they said, he tried to conceal what he had
done by deleting files from the lab's computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Lee is no hero,'' Reno said. ``He is not an absent-minded
professor. He is a felon. He committed a very serious calculated
crime and he pled guilty to it.'' Reno said that she would
elaborate on her remarks in a closed session, which Shelby said
would be scheduled for a later date.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Lee's lawyers issued a statement in his
behalf: ``Nothwithstanding the egregious pretrial conditions that
were imposed on him, he still still believes that our system of
justice will prevail and he remains fully committed to honoring his
obligations under the plea agreement with the government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Freeh, who read parts of the statement, said said that when Lee
realized he was the subject of a criminal investigation, he took
several steps that heightened suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   He removed classification markings from documents and repeatedly
tried to enter secure areas of the lab after his security clearance
was revoked to engage in what the officials said was an effort to
conceal his misuse of Los Alamos computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to achieve his ends, Dr. Lee had to override default
mechanisms that were designed to prevent any accidental or
inadvertent movement of those files,'' the statment said. ``His
downloading process consumed nearly 40 hours over 70 different
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter's comments came after T.J. Glauthier, the deputy Energy
Secretary, said at the hearing that the scientist's assertion in
court that 99 percent of the data the former Los Alamos scientist
had downloaded was unclassified was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That statement is not correct when applied to the totality of
these files,'' Glauthier said of Richter's characterization of the
computer data.
</P>
<P>
   While physics and mathematical aspects of Lee's downloaded data
do appear in the open literature, he added, ``the way they are
assembled along with classified physical databases and specific
weapons configurations, which are also on the tapes, is highly
classified,'' Glauthier said.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes, he conceded, ``are not a complete recipe for
designing and building a nuclear bomb.'' But the data ``represent
the design know-how and physics information developed by our
nuclear labs over a period of 50 years and over 1,000 nuclear
tests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
