<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR GENE PREDISPOSING MEXICAN-AMERICANS TO DIABETES IDENTIFIED 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   An international research team led by scientists at University
of Texas Health Science Center at Houston has identified a major
gene that predisposes Mexican-Americans to adult-onset diabetes, a
discovery that promises earlier and better treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The finding pinpoints a new and unexpected pathway leading to
type 2 diabetes, the most common form of diabetes and the seventh
leading cause of death in the United States. The Hispanic frequency
of the disorder is triple that of the nation's overall frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand what happens in diabetes, the interaction of
genetic and lifestyle factors, you have to have a gene,'' said
Craig Hanis, a UT-Houston professor of biological sciences and
principal study investigator. ``Now that we have a gene, we can
find out what goes wrong and target those defects rather than the
symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery marks the first time an analysis encompassing the
entire human genome has led to the identification of a gene
responsible for a complex, common disorder caused by genes and
lifestyle factors, a groundbreaking technique that could enable
other researchers to find genes that make people susceptible to
common chronic illnesses, such as hypertension, asthma and
psychiatric diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery is the product of 19 years of research in Starr
County, Texas, a predominantly Hispanic county where the rate of
diabetes is higher than anywhere else in the state and several
times the national rate. Hanis' team studied blood samples from 346
sibling pairs from the county.
</P>
<P>
   Type 2 diabetes afflicts an estimated 135 million people
worldwide, including 15 million Americans. It is caused by insulin
deficiencies that allow a dangerous build-up of the sugar glucose
in the blood that can lead to stroke, blindness, heart disease,
kidney failure and limb amputations. It costs the United States $98
billion a year to treat and its frequency is on the rise worldwide,
mostly because of obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Hanis said he thought it would be 5 to 10 years before the
discovery leads to better treatment and longer than that before it
leads to treatment that prevents type 2 diabetes from occurring
Treatment options currently include insulin injections, pills and
diet and exercise recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The newly identified gene accounts for about 14 percent of the
prevalence of type 2 diabetes in the Mexican-American population
(and about 4 percent of Europeans, a sample of whom were also
involved in the study.) But Hanis said he thinks the team will be
able to explain about 50 percent of the genetic component for
diabetes when it identifies another gene that works in conjunction
with the newly discovered one.
</P>
<P>
   The research was published in the October issue of the journal
Nature Genetics, which came out Tuesday. Submitted 1 1/2 years ago,
its publication was delayed by requests by journal editors for a
series of supporting studies to verify the discovery, so surprising
were the results. In the interval, another diabetes gene discovery
was published.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell and colleagues' accomplishment is a `tour-de-force,' ''
said Dr. Allen Spiegel, director of the National Institute of
Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases in Phoenix. ``Actually
identifying susceptibility genes for diseases such as diabetes with
complex as opposed to simple (hereditary phenomena) has proved
exceedingly difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual development, the team found that the variation in
the gene that causes diabetes susceptibility occurred in the ``junk
DNA'' that scientists previously thought separates functional
portions of a gene. Hanis said the discovery serves as a lesson
that scientists need to stop ignoring such sequencing, even though
it will make discovery more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The newly discovered gene, called CAPN10, tells the body how to
make a protein called calpain-10, which breaks down other proteins,
activating or inactivating them. Hanis said the team never would
have thought to consider the calpain family if it had merely
searched for genes using the conventional technique.
</P>
<P>
   The team used a technique called ``positional cloning.'' It
exploits statistical analysis and landmarks along chromosomes to
zero in on target genes without prior knowledge about what the
genes normally do.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the team demonstrated a link between increased risk of
diabetes among the 346 Starr County siblings and a gene located
near one end of chromosome 2. No one studying a genetically complex
disease had then been able to take the next step of identifying the
specific gene indicated by the linkage.
</P>
<P>
   Hanis has conducted research and screened Starr County residents
for diabetes through the UT-Houston field office in Rio Grande City
that he and colleagues established in 1981. The team collected
family histories, clinical data and DNA samples while alerting many
residents for the first time that they had the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Hanis said his team will continue working with the Starr County
group, investigating what happens with diet and insulin changes and
searching for other genes. He said he expects other team members
and scientists will follow up with laboratory work, including
research into the discovery's pharmaceutical potential.
</P>
<P>
   Other authors of the paper included researchers at the Virginia
Mason research Center in Seattle, the University of Chicago, Tokyo
Women's Medical University, the University of Lund in Sweden and
Technical University in Germany. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
