<HEADER>
A2739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
r l BC-HIGH-TECH-DATING-TAG &LR;      09-26 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-DATING-TAG </SLUG>
  
 Romances that click  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAMELA H. SACKS   
 c. 2000 Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Quickly and surely, the dating game is going high tech.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women in droves are using the Internet to make social connections
these days. Some people want a long-term partner. Others seek friends who
can share entertainment activities and sports. And there are those who are
perfectly satisfied with a pen pal.
</P>
<P>
   Four people from Central Massachusetts agreed to talk about the pros and
cons of high-tech dating. All are members of The Right One and Together, a
dating service billed as the largest in the nation that is increasingly
turning to computerized methods to make matches. Those interviewed are
identified only by their first names.
</P>
<P>
   Tony, who works as a consultant in quality assurance engineering at Compaq,
spends his days at a computer. And it is to the computer that he has turned
in an effort to find that special someone.
</P>
<P>
   Tony, 45, wants to meet a woman who is a doer, not a homebody. He prefers to
be with someone who is athletic and competitive. It will be a plus if she
plays golf; he is a devotee of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Separated for 17 months and about to be divorced, Tony says he will keep
looking until he finds a permanent relationship, and high-tech methods might
shorten the search.
</P>
<P>
   ""It's another mechanism that gets you out to meet people,'' he says
matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is now home to hundreds of sites that hold out the possibility of
finding love online. Some charge a fee, while others are free. Many of them
are crammed with personal ads. One more sophisticated site that's now 14
years old, Matchmaker.com, claims it has 2.6 million registered members and
25,000 people signing up each week.
</P>
<P>
   The sites range from the staid to the bizarre. One site allows a user to set
up a blind date between two people by sending e-mails inviting them to meet
at a certain time and place. Neither knows the other's name. The e-mail
message instructs each recipient to wear a small flower as an identifier.
The site reminds the cyberspace matchmaker: ""After that ... it's up to love
to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, use of the Internet as a social negotiator has become so popular
that The Right One and Together, with roughly 100 bricks-and-mortar sites
across the country, is about to launch its own online division.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the organization, which has an office in Worcester, has used its
enhanced computer databases, with their reams of personal information on
each individual, solely as a resource for its ""relationship consultants''
to pair members. The service costs $1,000 to $3,000, depending on the number
of matches it guarantees in a certain period of time.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next couple of months, members who pay an additional fee will be
able to gain direct access to the databases _  secure sites protected from
public scrutiny _  and then select an appealing profile and arrange a date
by e-mail through a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is melding its regional databases into a national online
file that will allow users to find companionship while traveling on business
or on vacation, says Paul A. Falzone, chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion in Internet use over the past three years has compelled the
company to develop the ""user-friendly key to romance,'' as Falzone calls
it, or get frozen out of the matchmaking business.
</P>
<P>
   ""We're in a drive-through mentality society,'' Falzone says. ""People want
immediate results.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony says that before joining The Right One and Together, he used a Web site
that allowed him to post his photograph and to describe himself and the
criteria he was seeking in a mate. He quickly connected with a woman whom he
initially found appealing. As the relationship progressed, she became more
and more dependent, he says, telling him he was the love of her life. He
broke it off.
</P>
<P>
   ""She was clinging to me,'' he remembers. ""I felt suffocated.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly, a 45-year-old divorcee, used a similar Web site. She came away
disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   ""I did meet several men, but I found that through the Internet, people
misrepresent themselves,'' she says. ""They are shorter and 10 to 15 pounds
heavier than they say.
</P>
<P>
   ""I'm honest and out there,'' she adds. ""I assume people are what they say
they are _ and they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Those experiences come as no surprise to Norman P. Tonelli, a West
Brookfield therapist. He says that while the online world can be helpful to
people who are not comfortable with the night life scene, it also comes with
risks. They can range from connecting with a person who is dangerous to one
who is socially inept, a characteristic that does not necessarily come
across in an exchange of e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of disappointment expressed by Beverly is not uncommon, Tonelli
says. In describing themselves, people often embellish their looks and
accomplishments to make up for real or perceived shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ""They are making up for the fact that face to face they are not skilled,''
Tonelli says. ""People meet and there are certain things that never came
across online. The Internet has its limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Falzone says that part of the problem involves unrealistic expectations. He
recalls a 72-year-old man who didn't want to date anyone over 50, claiming
he was too full of life for an older woman.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the movie star pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   ""I have to tell some women, "Tom Cruise isn't in our membership,' ''
Falzone says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those waiting to find a soul mate seem to remain upbeat about their
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Company consultants, for their part, plumb the depths to arrive at an
accurate picture of each member.
</P>
<P>
   To join the service, an applicant must submit to a 90-minute interview and
complete a form containing about 100 questions on a broad range of personal
attributes and interests. The company performs background and criminal
record checks. With the aid of a computer program, members are matched on
one dozen or more characteristics in common.
</P>
<P>
   James, 26, a software engineer, joined two months ago and has had one date.
It didn't work out, he says, but he describes the pairing as ""a valiant
try.''
</P>
<P>
   ""The more things you try that you have a chance at, the better off you'll
be,'' he remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen women have come and gone from Tony's life since he joined The
Right One and Together. With little effort, he can reel off a precis of each
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   He dated the first woman for three months. Then she got nervous about his
presence in her life while her divorce was in the works. He is frank to
admit that the second woman was not impressed with him. The third was very
nice, he says. But there was no chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Tony was eagerly anticipating the next date, which already had
been arranged.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns expressed by Tonelli are echoed by 56-year-old Bob. He has
spent his entire professional life in the computer business, but has little
interest gaining access to the dating company's database. A computerized
list of member profiles is just that _ a list, he points out.
</P>
<P>
   Falzone concedes that he has yet to develop a formula that will guarantee
that spark between two people who in many other ways appear likely to hit it
off.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly says it is just that lack of certainty that has led her to suspect
that computer dating may not address her needs after all. She has been
matched with seven men; none went beyond the second date.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the men were compatible enough, she says, but the chemistry was
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ""It's too planned,'' she reflects. ""I like the idea of eyeing someone
across a room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
