<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      09-26 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, IN A TACTICAL VICTORY, GETS CASE RETURNED TO APPEALS
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-OUTLOOK, MICROSOFT-COURT) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court handed a major tactical victory
to the Microsoft Corp. on Tuesday when it rejected the government's
plea to immediately hear the appeal of its landmark antitrust case
and instead returned the proceeding to a lower court.
</P>
<P>
   The decision gives Microsoft greater breathing room to pursue
its appeals, relieves the company of any pressure to return any
time soon to the bargaining table and, in the absence of a
settlement, could have the effect of prolonging a final court
judgment by a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
   It returns the case to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia, which in the past has shown a greater
receptivity to Microsoft's legal defenses than the trial judge. And
it is virtually certain to have the effect of leaving the
supervision of the federal case in the hands of the next
administration, which Microsoft executives hope will be open to
reconsidering both the merits of the lawsuit and the order to break
up the company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives applauded Tuesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that we're moving on with the process,'' said Steven
A. Ballmer, the chief executive of Microsoft, in an interview in
San Francisco, where the company was announcing an alliance aimed
at capturing the high-end of the corporate computing world. ``We
are confident in our case on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Justice Department officials on Tuesday began
the process of preparing for a new round of court appearances. ``We
look forward to presenting our case to the court of appeals as
expeditiously as possible,'' said Gina Talamona, a department
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's decision, the government had tried to
short-circuit the uncertainties associated with bringing the case
to the Court of Appeals by going directly to the Supreme Court
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that the case against Microsoft involved issues of
``immense importance to our national economy,'' the Justice
Department had urged the Supreme Court to invoke a rarely used
procedural rule to bypass the appeals court, quickly review the
case and uphold the order issued by Federal District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson three months ago to slice Microsoft into two
smaller companies. After a 78 day trial, Jackson ruled in April
that Microsoft, the world's largest software maker, had repeatedly
violated federal antitrust law, bullied rivals and stifled
competition and innovation. In June, Jackson ruled that the company
should be broken up but stayed that order pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had opposed the government's request for immediate
Supreme Court review, saying it ``would impose an extraordinary
burden on the court'' and that there was no reason to depart from
the normal procedure of using the appeals court to narrow the
complex legal issues and voluminous trial record.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court, in a perfunctory three-sentence
order, agreed. It directed that the case be sent to the court of
appeals. The appeals court had already decided that seven judges _
not the usual three-member panel _ would hear the proceeding and
that it would move quickly. The full court has 10 members, but
three have recused themselves from this case for undisclosed
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the Supreme Court's announcement, the court of
appeals ordered the government and Microsoft to submit scheduling
proposals for its proceeding by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Following its usual practice when it denies reviews, the Supreme
Court did not announce the actual vote among the nine justices. But
in a published dissent from Tuesday's decision, Justice Stephen G.
Breyer said he had voted to hear the appeal because the case
``significantly affects an important sector of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed in reaching a final decision may help create legal
certainty,'' Breyer wrote. ``That certainty, in turn, may further
the economic development of that sector so important to our
nation's prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the court's decision dramatically reshapes the
contours of the case and is a big legal win for Microsoft on
several levels. Foremost among them is the timing of the case.
</P>
<P>
   For both Microsoft and the government, the timeline is crucial.
Experts have raised concerns that fast-paced changes in both the
technology and the marketplace may make the proposed remedy of
splitting Microsoft both irrelevant and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have long feared that it was to Microsoft's
advantage to stretch out the time of the case as long as possible.
For its part, Microsoft has denied that it is interested in delay,
maintaining that its primary goal is getting the case dismissed as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, Ballmer denied Tuesday that the company
had opposed immediate review by the Supreme Court in an effort to
slow down the legal process.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us the best resolution will be a court decision that
allows us to continue to innovate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court includes two judges who in 1998 handed a legal
victory to Microsoft in a separate but related case. They ruled
that Jackson was wrong on the law when he ordered Microsoft to
immediately unbundle its Windows operating system and its Internet
Explorer Web browser. Earlier this year Jackson took the unusual
step of criticizing the appeals court ruling, saying that it
ignored antitrust precedents laid down by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   After they deliberate over the next few months, the seven judges
on the appeals court have a wide range of options, including
sending the case back to Jackson for further proceedings consistent
with their ruling, a process that could further delay a final
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   After the court of appeals rules, the case could still go to the
Supreme Court. But, since the Supreme Court is under no obligation
to review the eventual decision of the appeals court, that court
could have the last word, although that may not be known until some
time in 2001 or later.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Tuesday's decision virtually assures that the
government's case will wind up under the control of a new
administration that could, if it wanted, either drop the federal
lawsuit or seek to rekindle settlement negotiations on less-onerous
terms than those offered by the Clinton administration. It remains
to be seen how closely the next administration would work with the
attorneys general in the 19 states who have brought a parallel
antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an unusual statement attached to Tuesday's decision, Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist defended his decision to participate
in the Microsoft case even though his son, James C. Rehnquist, is a
Boston lawyer representing Microsoft in private antitrust
litigation that could be affected by the outcome of the
government's antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said his son had no financial interests in the outcome
of the case, and that he did not believe that his impartiality
``might reasonably be questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision by this court as to Microsoft's antitrust liability
could have a significant effect on Microsoft's exposure to
antitrust suits in other courts,'' Rehnquist said. ``But, by virtue
of this court's position atop the federal judiciary, the impact of
many of our decisions is often quite broad. The fact that our
disposition of the pending Microsoft litigation could potentially
affect Microsoft's exposure to antitrust liability in other
litigation does not, to my mind, significantly distinguish the
present situation from other cases that this court decides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
