<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-FUNDING-ART-1,000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY CHIEFS TO PRESS FOR ADDITIONAL FUNDING FOR EQUIPMENT,
TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's senior commanders will warn Congress
on Wednesday that the armed services are struggling with aging
equipment, shortages in spare parts and shortfalls in training that
will require billions of dollars in new spending, officials said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry H. Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, and the commanders of the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marines,
will argue that the nation's front-line combat forces remain ready
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   But they will also warn that the readiness of some support units
has fallen, despite two years of budget increases approved by
President Clinton and Congress, officials familiar with their
prepared testimony said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the state of today's military, the chiefs will also focus
much of their testimony on tomorrow's forces. They plan to argue
that the Pentagon's procurement budget, the money for new weapons
and equipment, has not risen quickly enough to begin replacing
aging weapons and equipment built during the Reagan years in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The chiefs' testimony comes in the middle of a highly charged
political debate over the American military, and the officials said
that the warnings would offer ammunition to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument that readiness remains high among combat forces
undercuts accusations from some Republicans, including Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, that American military might is fraying. At the
same time, their warnings about other readiness problems and aging
weapons echo many made by Bush and by other military officials in
recent weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the chiefs will use Wednesday's hearings to
begin making the case for increases in spending and the size of the
force, now at 1.4 million troops, although they may not propose
specific figures.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration has increased the procurement
budget to $60 billion, from $43 billion three years ago, the chiefs
believe they need at least $70 billion or more as new weapons
arrive in the years ahead, a senior defense official said. Others
have suggested the number should increase to nearly $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an aging force structure _ in terms of airplanes,
ships, tanks, et cetera _ where obsolescence will start to come
into play,'' an official familiar with the chiefs' prepared
testimony said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't accelerate the pace of replacing ships and
airplanes,'' the official added, ``we are not going to maintain the
steady-state requirements to keep the age of the force at the
current level _ not to mention modernizing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Debates over the Pentagon's budget have always been political
ones, but the hearings before the Armed Service committees of the
House and the Senate on Wednesday are expected to cast this year's
debate in an increasingly partisan hue.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has already adopted a $295 billion defense budget for
the fiscal year that begins on Sunday, and Clinton has signed it.
That has prompted administration officials to complain that the
timing of the hearings in the weeks before Election Day was simply
a partisan effort to force the chiefs into voicing readiness
concerns being raised by Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, the senior Democrat on the Senate's
Armed Services Committee, said he had urged that the hearing be
postponed until after the election, only to be overruled by the
committee's Republican chairman, Sen. John W. Warner of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should put the chiefs in a position where
they're caught in a political crossfire,'' Levin said. ``I don't
know how it's avoided in this setting, given the timing.''
</P>
<P>
   The chiefs appear intent to use the hearings as a platform to
begin making their case for increased defense spending under the
new administration, regardless of who wins in November.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have proposed increasing defense spending, with
Bush calling for $45 billion more over the next decade and Vice
President Al Gore going even further to propose spending another
$80 billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   While the officials said the chiefs have not yet completed
specific budget requests, it was clear that the shortfalls they
cited would cost more to fill than the $4.5 billion and $8 billion
annually the two candidates have proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chiefs' appetite will be larger than anybody can
satisfy,'' a senior defense official said in an interview on
Tuesday. ``We are going higher, but they want to go higher still.''
</P>
<P>
   The current debate over the military's readiness _ and its
budget _ began two years ago when the chiefs at the time appeared
before similar hearings and warned that the reductions in forces
and spending after the Cold War had left them strapped.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Clinton proposed increasing Pentagon spending by
$112 billion over six years. With additional funding from Congress
and emergency supplements to cover peacekeeping operations like the
one in Kosovo, the Pentagon's budget is now projected to grow by
nearly $160 billion, rising from the newly adopted budget of $295
billion to $332 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   With the debate over spending intensifying, the administration
recently increased the Pentagon's future budgets by another $19.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the chiefs would emphasize steady
improvements in readiness, citing gains in morale, among other
things, following increases in pay and benefits. One official said
that the real impact will be felt in the year ahead as spare parts
and other equipment the budget increases paid for begin reaching
bases around the country.
</P>
<P>
   However, the chiefs are expected to argue that current readiness
continues to face strains because of the high pace of operations
overseas, which forces the services to give a lower priority to
those forces not deployed.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that a fighter wing based in Italy, for
example, can maintain peak performance, but it comes at the cost
for similar units in the United States, which must make do with
scarce parts and less money for training.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent weeks, senior military officers have warned of
readiness problems. In testimony before a subcommittee last week,
the Army said it needed $4.6 billion to purchase new weapons, from
Abrams tanks to Apache helicopters. The Navy's inspector general
warned in a report released last week that the readiness of the
service's aircraft had declined because of shortages in spare parts
and training.
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped down as commander of forces in the Persian Gulf in
August, Gen. Anthony C. Zinni, warned of growing strains on
American troops. In an interview he, too, warned that the military
is stretching the life out of aging equipment _ a point the current
commandant of the Marine Corps, Gen. James L. Jones, is expected to
make on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I climbed in a CH-46 helicopter when I was a lieutenant in
Vietnam,'' Zinni said. ``My son is a lieutenant and he climbs into
the same helicopter.''
</P>
<P>
   With increasing warnings about readiness from the senior ranks,
Secretary of Defense William Cohen met with the chiefs early this
month and cautioned them not to use politically charged debate as a
means to argue for increasing their budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, said Cohen told them
``not to beat the drum with a tin cup in hand to try to generate
more pressure for defense spending but, on the other hand, to talk
honestly about pressures they face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
