<HEADER>
A2748 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-CASES-HNS &LR;      09-26 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CASES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court will consider a Houston
father's argument that men should have the same rights as women in
gaining citizenship for their foreign-born children.
</P>
<P>
   A high-court decision in Joseph Boulais' favor could lead to
American citizenship for his Vietnam-born son, which would block
deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, acting six days before the official start of their
new term, also said Tuesday that they will decide whether the PGA
Tour can require disabled golfer Casey Martin to walk the course
during professional tournaments, as his competitors do.
</P>
<P>
   In a case from Alabama, the court will determine if
non-English-speaking residents can sue a state agency to force it
to administer driver's license tests in foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, which begins its new term Monday, is expected to
decide these cases by July.
</P>
<P>
   Boulais, who never married the Vietnamese mother of his son,
Tuan Anh Nguyen, argues that the federal Immigration and
Nationality Act's stricter requirements for American fathers
seeking U.S. citizenship for their children violates the
constitutional requirement that laws treat men and women equally.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers must establish their foreign-born child's paternity
according to state regulation, by acknowledging fatherhood in a
sworn written statement or getting a court decree before the
offspring reaches age 18. Mothers, to secure their child's U.S.
citizenship, must show that they gave birth to the child.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Nguyen was an American automatically by virtue of
his American father, Boulais did not prove his son's paternity
until it was too late to secure him U.S. citizenship. The
Immigration and Naturalization Service had classified Nguyen, who
fled Vietnam before the fall of Saigon in 1975, as a legal
immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   The INS, which seeks to deport Nguyen because of a
sexual-assault conviction, says the law is valid in making it
easier for mothers to gain their child's citizenship. Motherhood is
easier than fatherhood to document legally because mothers must be
present at the birth, the INS says.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, in passing nationality laws, also has broad
constitutional authority to set citizenship rules, the INS said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans-based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed
with the INS in April, prompting Boulais to appeal to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The golf case concerns whether a federal law banning bias
against disabled people applies to professional sports leagues and,
hence, requires the Professional Golfers' Association of America to
accommodate Martin's disability, a congenital vascular condition
that makes walking painful.
</P>
<P>
   Martin says the Americans with Disabilities Act requires the PGA
to accommodate his disability by allowing him to use a golf cart
during competition.
</P>
<P>
   But the PGA counters that the disability law does not apply to
sports leagues, which must have one set of rules for all players to
protect the integrity of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
against the PGA in March, saying a golf course is a public
accommodation that the federal law requires be made accessible to
disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA, in its appeal to the Supreme Court, says the ADA was
never intended to require a professional sport to ``waive a
legitimate competitive rule to enable a would-be participant,
disabled or not, to more successfully compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule the tour is defending requires golfers to walk the
course during tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alabama case, the state Department of Public Safety says
the federal 1964 Civil Rights Act does not allow
non-English-speaking residents to legally challenge the agency's
policy of testing applicants for driver's licenses in English only.
The state, while defending its English-only test as important to
road safety, says the 1964 law requires residents to take their
grievance to the U.S. Transportation Department, which is
responsible for providing funds to the state agency.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in Alabama argue that the English-only tests
discriminate on the basis of national origin in violation of the
1964 law, which prohibits state agencies that receive federal funds
from discriminating.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed. In
other cases:
</P>
<P>
   The justices agreed to consider whether the Constitution permits
police, without a warrant, to use high-tech heat-detecting
equipment to discover whether criminal activity is occurring in
someone's home.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon police, using a thermal imaging device, detected high
heat levels being emitted inside Danny Lee Kyllo's home, a possible
sign that high-intensity lights were being used to grow marijuana.
Kyllo was arrested and convicted of intentionally manufacturing
marijuana. Because of his otherwise clean record, his 63-month
prison sentence was reduced to one month.
</P>
<P>
   Kyllo appealed his conviction, arguing that the thermal imaging
of his home violated his Fourth Amendment protection from
unreasonable police search.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will consider whether Montana prison officials can
prevent prisoners from providing lawyerly assistance to fellow
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners argue that Montana's policy violates their First
Amendment right to free speech. The state counters that its
compelling safety need to monitor prisoners' correspondence trumps
their constitutional right.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with
the inmates  &QL; 
