<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-VISAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO ALLOW MORE FOREIGN HIGH TECH WORKERS STALLS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER HOYT 
c.2000 HOUSTON CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate agreed Tuesday to consider legislation
expanding the number of high-tech foreign workers allowed to work
in the United States, but the measure has been caught up in a
partisan dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats want to expand the bill to lower immigration barriers
for almost a million people, including amnesty to hundreds of
thousands living in the United States illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have blocked the proposal, which has White House
support, and accused Democrats of playing politics in an election
year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats said they want to add the lower immigration
barriers to a bill to fund the Commerce, State and Justice
departments in 2001 and warned Republicans that without the changes
President Clinton would veto the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, a top legislative priority for the nation's
high-tech industry, would increase the number of H-1B visas for
highly skilled foreign workers from the current 115,000 a year to
195,000 annually through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   With employment at an all-time high, computer companies and
allied services say there are not enough American workers for all
the high-tech vacancies now. This year's visas had been allocated
by the end of March and under current law the number of high-tech
visas for foreign workers is set to drop over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical to our information technology age; it's critical
to our high-tech companies,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch told Democrats on the Senate floor that the bill was
``being held hostage because you want to give amnesty to 500,000
illegal immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said, ``I think the Democrats are
embarrassing themselves by making it clear they're not really for
this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats countered that they support increasing the number of
high-tech visas, adding that fairness dictates giving a similar
break to immigrants who are unskilled or semi-skilled as outlined
in the proposed Latino and Immigrant Fairness Act.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``would rather risk delaying passage of the H-1B
visa bill than vote for the Latino and Immigrant Fairness Act or
risk the political consequences of voting against it,'' said Sen.
Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the Latino legislation would ease
restrictions on immigrants from Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras
and Haiti to become permanent residents. The rules were relaxed in
1997 for Nicaraguans and Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would allow illegal immigrants who entered the
United States before 1986 to apply for permanent residency and
would reinstate a provision of immigration law that had allowed
immigrants to remain in the United States while waiting to receive
their green cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pro-business and pro-family,'' Daschle said. ``It is
modest and it's long, long overdue. We do not intend to let this
Congress end until it is signed into law.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said it could
be three or four days before the Senate votes on the H-1B
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
