<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-STRATEGY-NYT &LR;      09-26 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STRATEGY TIES ECONOMY, EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For decades, political scientists have considered
the economy the single best predictor of the electorate's mood.
Good times favor incumbents, bad times insurgents. And so for Gov.
George W. Bush, one challenge has loomed high above the others in
his quest for the White House: how to defeat a sitting vice
president in good times.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Bush led Gore in polls even as the economy hummed
along. But his lead has vanished. And the issue that once seemed to
play so well for him, character, has diminished in importance, the
polls show.
</P>
<P>
   It is largely for that reason, many political analysts say, that
Bush has adopted a new slogan: ``education recession.'' Ostensibly,
it refers to what he calls a ``crisis'' in the nation's public
schools. But at its heart, the slogan is also meant to raise alarms
about the health of the nation's economy in the not-too-distant
future.
</P>
<P>
   And in raising those red flags, the analysts say, Bush has
turned his signature issue, education, into a weapon for slashing
at the central arguments for electing Vice President Al Gore: peace
and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's advantage on the economy is critical for Bush to try to
overcome,'' said Evans Witt, president of the Princeton Survey
Research, a polling firm. ``If you say we're in a recession long
enough, it certainly has an economic connotation, even if you are
using it to discuss education.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director, acknowledged as
much, saying, ``The point of this is that, while the economy is
strong, there are problems in society.''
</P>
<P>
   In his acceptance speech last month at the Republican National
Convention, Bush accused President Clinton and Gore of having
``squandered'' the opportunities of the economic boom. But during a
tour of the West Coast this week, he painted a darker picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some warning signs in America,'' he told an audience
in an elementary school near Portland, Ore., on Monday. Then he
ticked them off: Gasoline prices spiraling out of control. Farmers
struggling to survive. The nation in danger of losing its
technological edge. And illiterate youths on the cusp of
criminality.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some places, there is a recession in America,'' Bush said
on Tuesday at a high school in northern California. ``In some
school districts there is a recession, and this country needs to do
something about it early, before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   At times he sounded like John F. Kennedy warning the nation
about a ``missile gap'' with the Soviet Union in the 1960 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If American students don't lead the world in math and science,
the next generation of Americans may not lead the world,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising concerns about the economy represents something of a
tactical shift for Bush, who has spent much of the campaign
attacking Gore's character and credibility. But several recent
polls indicate that voters now see little difference between the
candidates in terms of their morality and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much harder for Bush because he can't hammer at character
anymore,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said Bush would have trouble tapping into
voters' anxieties about the economy, because there is so little
there to tap. According to a Fox News poll taken last week, 60
percent of voters said they thought the country is headed in the
right direction, one of the highest readings since January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And a Gallup Poll conducted in June showed that only 22 percent
of Americans said that the most important issues in the race were
economic, compared to 69 percent who felt that way in the fall of
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes much sense,'' said James Campbell, a
professor of political science at the State University of New York
at Buffalo who has studied the impact of the economy on
presidential elections. ``There are no obvious clouds on the
horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup Poll, said
he could see the logic to Bush's strategy because voters care
deeply about economic issues even in good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not top of mind this year,'' Newport said. ``But when we
mention the economy, people say, `Oh yes, that will be very
important. How the candidates handle the economy is important.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also said that raising concerns about the economy
could strike a chord with working class voters, typically families
who earn less than $40,000 a year and live paycheck to paycheck.
Polls show those people tend to be swing voters whose allegiances
could easily change if they felt the economy were turning sour.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, aides to Bush said their internal polls had shown that
the slogan ``education recession'' had played well among
independent voters and women.
</P>
<P>
   Witt noted that many such swing voters live in the industrial
Midwestern states where the race is being most closely contested,
including Missouri, Michigan, Pennsylvania and Ohio. And they are a
group that might find Bush's plan for across-the-board income tax
cuts appealing, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has hit pretty heavily on the idea that Gore's tax cut
may leave people out,'' Witt said. ``That's a point that I think
might resonate with some people in this group. Because they are on
the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts also said they thought it was clever of Bush to
tie two issues together in a way that could undermine Gore's
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a subliminal quality to it,'' said Stephen Hess, a
presidential scholar at the Brookings Institute, a nonpartisan
policy organization. ``It reminds us that there is more that can go
wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
