<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2754 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEBATE-TAPE-HNS &LR;      09-26 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-TAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ The FBI should focus more attention on
the presidential campaign of Democrat Al Gore in investigating the
mysterious delivery to a Gore adviser of confidential
debate-preparation materials from Republican George W. Bush, a Bush
spokeswoman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Communications Director Karen Hughes said that the campaign
has been cooperating fully with the FBI since a videotape of a Bush
debate practice session and related documents turned up in the Gore
camp two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was sure that no one in the Bush campaign had
anything to do with compromising the materials, but she said she
didn't know if the FBI has adequately investigated the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm suggesting that a thorough investigation of how the Gore
campaign ended up with proprietary Bush campaign materials involves
not just the Bush campaign but also the Gore campaign,'' Hughes
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, a package bearing an Austin return address was
delivered to the Washington office of former Democratic congressman
Thomas Downey, who had been helping Gore prepare for the debates. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; After determining that the package contained Bush debate
preparation material, he turned it over to the FBI. Downey, who
said he watched part of the videotape before realizing what it was,
also withdrew from his role as a debate coach for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The first of three debates between Bush and Gore is scheduled
for Tuesday night in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that only high-level Bush staffers had access to the
materials. She said the originals had been located and that the
copies had to have been prepared and provided to the Gore campaign
by ``some unethical means.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself later commented on the matter in an interview with
MSNBC. ``I just want to know what's happened,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this: Someone who is for me for president didn't send
the material up there. I look forward to finding out what the facts
are. Somebody, I guarantee you, is sweating bullets because they
are beginning to home in on this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Published reports last weekend quoted unnamed sources as saying
the FBI was focusing its investigation on a Bush campaign worker.
</P>
<P>
   In a story posted on its Web site Tuesday night, The Dallas
Morning News identified that worker as an Austin woman who employed
by Bush's media consultant, Mark McKinnon. She came to FBI
attention after agents obtained a security camera film of her
mailing a package, the News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Yvette Lozano, 30, told the Dallas newspaper that the package
she was photographed sending Sept. 11 from an Austin post office
contained a pair of khaki trousers her boss was returning to a
clothing chain.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano said FBI agents questioned her Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying, `Those weren't pants in that package,'''
Lozano said. She denied having any knowledge about the Bush debate
package.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that several high-level Bush staffers have been
interviewed by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the more questions the FBI asks, the more nervous
people at the Gore campaign are getting,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign on Saturday announced that it had put a
staffer, Michael Doyne, 28, on paid administrative leave while Gore
officials investigated a report that Doyne had boasted about the
Democratic campaign having a mole in the Bush camp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials said they believed Doyne's boast was a
joke, but Hughes said, ``We think that is something that is very
serious and it ought to be looked at.``
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane responded that the FBI can decide
how to handle its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're experts in this area,'' Lehane said. ``I think people
should be careful about trying to politicize an FBI investigation.
I think if you look at the way we handled the issue, it speaks
volumes. Once Mr. Downey received this unsolicited tape, he
immediately contacted his lawyer and turned it over.``
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Bush campaign was still waiting for a return
phone call from FBI Director Louis Freeh to discuss the
investigation. Bush campaign manager Joe Allbaugh called Freeh on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A Freeh subordinate returned the call, but that wasn't
satisfactory, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said Tuesday that
she believes the Bush campaign sent the videotape to the Gore
campaign as a ``dirty trick'' to distract from issues and
potentially create a character issue if Gore kept the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just absurd,'' Hughes responded. ``I ask you to
consider the source, to immediately discount that.``
</P>
<P>
   Malcom said the incident ``has Karl Rove's fingerprints all over
it,'' referring to Bush's chief campaign strategist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, when Rove was working on the campaign of former Gov.
Bill Clements, a private investigator reported finding an
electronic listening device in Rove's Austin office. Political
consultant McKinnon _ then working for Clements' opponent, Gov.
Mark White _ suggested that the bug created a political distraction
and that Clements' campaign had more to gain from planting it than
anyone in the White camp.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI investigation of that incident was inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters R. G. Ratcliffe and Patty Reinert contributed to this
story &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
