</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Sept. 26, 2000 --
RODEO-DRIVE-COX -- Shopping on Rodeo Drive in Beverly Hills, Calif.
is not for people with champagne tastes and Bud Lite budgets. It is
the place where the truly wealthy come to buy, while the rest of us
window-shop and wonder how the decimal points got so far to the
right. Tourists taking photos on Rodeo Drive. (D.L. Stewart/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- ENERGY-OIL-CONGRESS --
Republican senators accused the Clinton administration Tuesday of
tapping the emergency petroleum reserve to help Al Gore's
presidential bid. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who has said
that politics played no role in Friday's decision to tap 30 million
barrels of oil from the government reserve, told members of the
Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee that the
administration remains committed ``to let the market dictate
prices.'' Richardson before Tuesday's hearing. (Susana Raab/The New
York Times) -MAGS OUT, NO SALES-
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- SCI-PARROTS-BOS --
``Many animals have a lot more intelligence than they're given
credit for,'' says Irene Pepperberg, a visiting professor at MIT.
Pepperberg asks Alex, a grey parrot, to identify a green key.
Pepperberg believes her work shows animals don't merely respond to
stimulus, as behaviorists argue, but actually think. For
Pepperberg, years of testing her 23-year-old parrot, Alex, confirm
that birds with a walnut-size brain can do more than mimic or learn
rote behavior; she said her parrots reason, comprehend, and
calculate at the level of a 4-year-old child.(Wendy Maeda/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-3-- For
truly observant Jews, kosher restaurants were traditionally the
only alternative to staying home or going to Grandma's. Il
Patrizio, an upscale Kosher restaurant in Midtown. (Carol
Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-2 --
For truly observant Jews, kosher restaurants were traditionally the
only alternative to staying home or going to Grandma's. Il Patrizio
is one of the city's kosher restaurants. Two dishes served are
carpaccio di tonno (tuna), bottom and padellata di carcioffi
(artichoke and potato). (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- KOSHER-RESTAURANTS -- For
truly observant Jews, kosher restaurants were traditionally the
only alternative to staying home or going to Grandma's. Shallots in
Midtown is one of the city's new kosher restaurants. (Carol
Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- TECH-RETAIL-BOS --
Online retailer Send.com gets ready for the Christmas season,
contemplating everything from hiring extra workers to marketing
against both Amazon.com and Wal-Mart. Michael Lannon, chief
executive of Send.com, with some of the items available from his
company. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WESTBOROUGH, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 2000 --
TECH-INFORMIX-BOS -- Informix is one of a growing number of
technology companies that abandoned Silicon Valley because it
became too expensive. Informix's two presidents, Peter Fiore, left,
and Jim Foy outside the company's offices. (Tom Landers/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- PROFILE-PIERCE-BOS -- Celtics
coach Rick Pitino is surrounded by reporters after visiting Paul
Pierce at the New England Medical Center, Monday. Pierce was doing
well after doctors sewed up knife wounds in his face, neck, and
back including one that penetrated his abdomen and diaphragm and
hit his lung. Medical sources say he should recover enough to soon
play basketball for the Celtics. (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- CONGRESS-LEE -- FBI
Director Louis Freeh and Attorney General Janet Reno defended the
government's case against nuclear scientist Wen Ho Lee Tuesday,
saying the prosecution would likely have succeeded if they had gone
to trial. Reno and Freeh confer Tuesday during hearings before a
joint session of the Senate Select Intelligence and Judiciary
committees. (Susana Raab/The New York Times) LITE -MAGS OUT, NO
SALES-
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) REDWOOD CITY, Calif. -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN
-- Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate,
speaks to students at Sequoia High School, Tuesday. Bush is blaming
the Clinton-Gore administration for an ``education recession'' in
the public schools and promising in a new TV ad to raise school
expectations. He said Tuesday that ``better days'' are ahead.
(Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ANN ARBOR, Mich. -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN --
Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate,
during the taping of MTV's ``Choose or Lose'' show at the
University of Michigan sponsored by MTV and Time magazine, Tuesday.
With a new poll out this week indicating that less than half of the
under-25 crowd will definitely vote in the November contest between
Gore and Republican George W. Bush, Gore tried to personalize the
election for MTV's young viewers as he appealed to them to ``fight
through'' any disillusionment. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- GORE-BIANCHI -- When Vice
President Al Gore isn't quite sure about some obscure detail of his
health care plan, he will end his remarks with a fleeting, almost
unnoticed question: ``Isn't that right, Sarah?'' Sarah is Sarah
Bianchi, a 27-year-old Atlanta native, who is deputy domestic
affairs adviser to the Gore campaign. But the title understates the
way Gore has come to depend on her. Bianchi, in a Washington on
Monday talking with a colleague about an upcoming meeting. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LUANDA, Angola -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- POLIO-BATTLE-BOS-7 --
More than 40 years after the last big epidemic of polio swept
through the United States, spreading hysteria across the nation, a
global effort to eliminate polio is in its final stages. This week,
the United Nations will hold a polio summit, where world leaders
and public health specialists will pledge to stop transmission of
the virus with the goal of being able to certify its demise by
2005. Health workers look for children during a sweep of the region
in July to administer the polio vaccine. In the background is one
of hundreds of buildings destroyed during Angola's civil war.
(Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LUANDA, Angola -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- POLIO-BATTLE-BOS-6 --
