<P>
   (NYT22) CENTERVILLE, Ohio -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- PUMPKINS-COX -
There's more to pumpkin than jack-o'-lanterns, and more to eat than
pumpkin pie. Just ask Bonnie Mercuri of Bonnybrook Farms in
Centerville. She's been growing specialty pumpkins for four years
and this year her harvest of cooking pumpkins ranges from an
oversized muffin-shaped blue pumpkin called Queensland Blue to tiny
Wee B Little specimens that are true pumpkins, not gourds. Cooking
pumpkins clockwise from the top: Jarrahdale, Whangaparoa, Winter
Luxury Pie, Rouge 'Vif d'Etampes, Long Island Cheese (center),
Queensland Blue, Buckskin. (Jim Witmer/Dayton Daily-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- MRSCLINTON-DETRACTORS --
Being first lady isn't a job, Hillary Rodham Clinton said early
this year in Manhattan, ``it's a role.'' While making her one of
the most famous women in the world, her performance in that role
has driven nearly a decade of dinner-table speculation about the
scale of her ambition and the state of her marriage. Clinton is
greeted by supporters during a visit to the Riverdale Young Men's
and Young Women's Hebrew Association, Tuesday. (Librado Romero/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) REDWOOD CITY, Calif. -- Sept. 26, 2000 --
BUSH-CAMPAIGN-2 -- Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
candidate, greets students at Sequoia High School, Tuesday. Bush is
blaming the Clinton-Gore administration for an ``education
recession'' in the public schools and promising in a new TV ad to
raise school expectations. He said Tuesday that ``better days'' are
ahead. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- VIOLENCE-KIDS-FILMS --
As the executives of movie studios prepared to be grilled at a
Senate hearing on Wednesday, the industry on Tuesday announced new
steps to limit the marketing of adult-rated movies to children.
Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said at a news conference that each of the major
movie-making companies had set a ``goal of not inappropriately
specifically targeting children in its advertising of films rated R
for violence.'' Valenti, right, listened to Federal Trade
Commission Chairman Robert Pitofsky, left, during a hearing before
the Senate Judiciary Committee on violence in the media last
Wednesday. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ALEXANDRIA, Va -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- NURSING-EDEN-COX --
The retirement and nursing home complex are part of a movement to
bring more humanity, respect and companionship into nursing
facilities. Called the ``Eden Alternative'' after the biblical
story, the effort was founded almost a decade ago by
Harvard-trained geriatrist, William Thomas. It has spread to about
300 homes in the United States and abroad. Mary Bangura, left, a
nursing student at T.C. Williams High School, and Michelle
Bernsohn, center, at the Goodwin House nursing home, help residents
in the dementia unit make cupcakes for visiting preschool children.
(Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Sept. 26, 2000 --
RODEO-DRIVE-COX -- Shopping on Rodeo Drive in Beverly Hills, Calif.
is not for people with champagne tastes and Bud Lite budgets. It is
the place where the truly wealthy come to buy, while the rest of us
window-shop and wonder how the decimal points got so far to the
right. Tourists taking photos on Rodeo Drive. (D.L. Stewart/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- ENERGY-OIL-CONGRESS --
Republican senators accused the Clinton administration Tuesday of
tapping the emergency petroleum reserve to help Al Gore's
presidential bid. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who has said
that politics played no role in Friday's decision to tap 30 million
barrels of oil from the government reserve, told members of the
Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee that the
administration remains committed ``to let the market dictate
prices.'' Richardson before Tuesday's hearing. (Susana Raab/The New
York Times) -MAGS OUT, NO SALES-
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- SCI-PARROTS-BOS --
``Many animals have a lot more intelligence than they're given
credit for,'' says Irene Pepperberg, a visiting professor at MIT.
Pepperberg asks Alex, a grey parrot, to identify a green key.
Pepperberg believes her work shows animals don't merely respond to
stimulus, as behaviorists argue, but actually think. For
Pepperberg, years of testing her 23-year-old parrot, Alex, confirm
that birds with a walnut-size brain can do more than mimic or learn
rote behavior; she said her parrots reason, comprehend, and
calculate at the level of a 4-year-old child.(Wendy Maeda/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- KOSHER-RESTAURANTS-3-- For
truly observant Jews, kosher restaurants were traditionally the
only alternative to staying home or going to Grandma's. Il
Patrizio, an upscale Kosher restaurant in Midtown. (Carol
Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
