<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- GORE-BIANCHI -- When Vice
President Al Gore isn't quite sure about some obscure detail of his
health care plan, he will end his remarks with a fleeting, almost
unnoticed question: ``Isn't that right, Sarah?'' Sarah is Sarah
Bianchi, a 27-year-old Atlanta native, who is deputy domestic
affairs adviser to the Gore campaign. But the title understates the
way Gore has come to depend on her. Bianchi, in a Washington on
Monday talking with a colleague about an upcoming meeting. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LUANDA, Angola -- Sept. 26, 2000 -- POLIO-BATTLE-BOS-7 --
More than 40 years after the last big epidemic of polio swept
through the United States, spreading hysteria across the nation, a
global effort to eliminate polio is in its final stages. This week,
the United Nations will hold a polio summit, where world leaders
and public health specialists will pledge to stop transmission of
the virus with the goal of being able to certify its demise by
2005. Health workers look for children during a sweep of the region
in July to administer the polio vaccine. In the background is one
of hundreds of buildings destroyed during Angola's civil war.
(Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe)
</P>
