<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT study yields diabetes information
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A 19-year study of adult diabetics in Texas has
led to a surprising breakthrough: a gene carrying seemingly useless
``junk DNA'' makes some people likely diabetes targets.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the mutated gene, described in an article today
in Nature Genetics, opens new pathways for preventing the disease
and possibly treating some of the nation's 15 million diabetics.
Diabetes, feared because it can lead to strokes, blindness, heart
disease, limb amputations and kidney disease, is the seventh
leading cause of death in the United States. And Texas has a bigger
problem than most other states.
</P>
<P>
   The gene carrying the junk DNA is ``not quite as junky as we
thought it was,'' said Craig Hanis, a biology professor at the
University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston. Hanis, who
works in the school's Human Genetics Center, collaborated with
Graeme Bell, a University of Chicago professor who led the study's
international team. They discovered the gene, named CAPN10, on
chromosome 2.
</P>
<P>
   They also found that the gene produces a protein called calpain
that could play a significant role in treating diabetes, Hanis
said.
</P>
<P>
   The newly identified gene interacts with other genes and
lifestyle factors, such as diet and exercise, making some people
more prone to adult-onset, or type-2, diabetes. Type-2 is the form
diagnosed in 90 percent to 95 percent of diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you have a particular form of the gene does not
mean you're not going to develop diabetes,'' Hanis said. ``You have
an increased risk.''
</P>
<P>
   One in 10 Texans has the disease, a proportion significantly
higher than the national rate of one in 17 Americans. The disease
also is several times more prevalent _ and more deadly _ to African
Americans and Mexican Americans than to whites.
</P>
<P>
   The gene also is more common in Mexican Americans and Pima
Indians, but Hanis expects to find it across ethnic and racial
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas researchers studied a group of Mexican Americans in
Starr County, Texas' poorest county, where about 98 percent of the
population is of Mexican heritage. About half of the population has
diabetes or has a family member who does, Hanis said. Health care
workers are seeing type-2 diabetes, normally diagnosed in adults in
their 40s or older, striking children as young as 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' said Maria Ofelia Saenz, who is 70 and lives in
Rio Grande City. Saenz took part in the study and has three sisters
and several aunts with diabetes. She knows others, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother-in-law was a diabetic and she died of complications.
She had one leg amputated,'' Saenz said. ``I have friends on
dialysis. I get scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Saenz takes medicine to control diabetes, which produces high
levels of sugar in the blood. People with diabetes have defects in
the body's ability to produce or secrete insulin, but scientists
are just beginning to learn why.
</P>
<P>
   People with the mutant gene can reduce the risk of getting
diabetes by exercising and eating fewer fats, salts and sugars,
said Sharon Brown, UT-Austin's associate vice president for
research. Brown works with Hanis' study group to improve their
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Hilda Guerra, a nurse and field manager of the Starr County
study office, said when she started with the study 19 years ago,
Starr County had no kidney dialysis centers. Now it has four, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra said she was grateful to the community for taking part in
the study and was thrilled by the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' she said. ``Once you know what you're
targeting, you can get them better medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Those treatments, however, are probably five to 10 years away,
said Catherine McKeon, senior adviser for genetic research at the
National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major discovery,'' said McKeon, manager of the
institute's $3.5 million grant to the researchers. ``It leads us to
a new set of genes ... in places to look that we haven't looked
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers had not previously looked at junk DNA for a diabetes
susceptibility gene, Hanis said. This particular gene, which
carries DNA that was not believed to have any role in regulating
the body, was found to be a commonly mutated gene that can change
how other genes perform. Humans, who have nearly 3 billion units of
DNA, are 99.9 percent similar. But changes in the DNA sequence
cause mutations and produce variations among people.
</P>
<P>
   Bell and one of his colleagues, Nancy Cox, developed an analytic
technique that pinpointed the gene in 1998. But because the finding
was so unexpected, Nature Genetics asked the researchers to confirm
it with other studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know there is a genetic susceptibility to diabetes in
every population, and finding the genes that underlie that
susceptibility ... is the challenge that faces us,'' Hanis said.
``What we've done today is knocked one down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
