<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONSERVATION GROUP HONORS TURNER
 &HT;    By KAVITA KUMAR
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The League of Conservation Voters presented CNN
founder Ted Turner with a lifetime achievement award Tuesday night
to recognize his stewardship of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone were going to compile a list of environmental heroes
in the world, one giant on that list would surely be Ted Turner,''
said Deb Callahan, president of the national environmental
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only as a philanthropist has he done so much,'' Callahan
said, ``but he made CNN the voice in the mainstream media for
environmental and conservation issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Turner Foundation, Turner has given $50
million annually in grants to organizations that work for clean
water, clean air, renewable and efficient energy use, wildlife
protection and policies to reduce population growth.
</P>
<P>
   Through his funding of the United Nations Foundation, Turner has
also shed light on issues of sustainable energy and protecting
ecosystems and the biodiversity they contain.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing her father, Laura Turner Seydel remembered how
when she was growing up, he refused to install air conditioning in
their home, even during the brutal Southern summers.
</P>
<P>
   He taught her to pull weeds out by the roots with her hands when
she was just 7 or 8 years old, she recalled. And when driving in
the car, he would stop 10 times in a half hour to pick up a piece
of trash from the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really walks the walk and talks the talk,'' Seydel said.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting his award before the crowd of 350, Turner said the
world is at a critical time in its development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have information through global communications and the
Internet. And if we don't make it, we only have ourselves to blame,
because we have all the information we need to make it through,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner touched on the wide disparities between the rich and
poor, reducing military budgets, ridding the world of nuclear
weapons, the overzealousness with which the U.S. guards its border
with Mexico, and the need for family planning to control the
rapidly increasing world population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge challenge _ but we're up to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And senators,'' he said, addressing the officials in the room,
``something that really bothers me is all of the trash along the
roads. If every state had deposit laws, all the poor people could
pick it up and make money doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavita Kumar's e-mail address is kkumar(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
