u i BC-YUGO-US-DIPLOMACY-NYT     09-26 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-US-DIPLOMACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRAISES THE BRAVE VOTERS OF YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Surprised by the sweep of the vote for the
opposition presidential candidate in Yugoslavia, but cautious about
gloating, President Clinton praised the ``brave people'' there on
Tuesday for choosing change and sought to embolden them by offering
to lift economic sanctions if they prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has dealt with President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia as a noxious central character in foreign policy
throughout his presidency, warned that although Milosevic has lost
legitimacy he may try to ``cling to power at the expense of his
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the public wariness, born of watching Milosevic
manipulate his way out of seemingly impossible corners, the Clinton
administration has concluded that he has finally lost his magic.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is Milosevic invincible in the eyes of his people,
senior administration officials said, noting that signs of fissures
within Milosevic's ruling circle spelled the beginning of the end.
</P>
<P>
   Telling evidence of paralysis is appearing within the regime,
these officials said. Student leaders, who had been arrested and
harassed before the election, have been left alone by the police
and the military in the last 48 hours. The barrage of official
propaganda over state media has virtually ground to a halt as
various acolytes of Milosevic have given varying accounts of the
vote tally, creating a picture of confusion in the inner sanctum.
</P>
<P>
   And the decision on Tuesday by Milosevic to call a second round
of voting on Oct. 8 was interpreted by administration officials as
a desperate effort to buy time.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Milosevic did not announce an outright victory
means that he either failed to set up a sufficiently swift scheme
to steal votes or that he would have had to steal too many to make
a credible claim, officials said. In contrast to Milosevic's weak
election operation, the opposition movement managed to organize a
fast parallel vote count, enabling them to announce a 54.7 percent
victory for their candidate, Vojislav Kostunica, over Milosevic's
35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's forces announced on Tuesday that preliminary results
showed he had finished second with 40 percent, and the opposition
had won with 48 percent. With neither side reaching more than 50
percent, a runoff was needed, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they hoped that in the
next two weeks the opposition would create even more of a steam
roller and that Milosevic would not be able to withstand.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also possible, Balkan experts in the administration
said, that Milosevic could try to cut a deal with Kostunica. And it
is conceivable, given his past behavior, that Milosevic could
create some kind of crisis: either an intervention in Montenegro,
the smaller republic in Yugoslavia, where the leadership boycotted
the election _ or a cancellation of the election altogether.
</P>
<P>
   And as they assessed the uncertain situation in Belgrade and
other urban centers, the administration tried to weave a delicate
balance between showing support for the opposition, which it helped
finance, and keeping a distance so as not to offend Yugoslavia's
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, a proud Serbian nationalist, is stridently
anti-American and has repeatedly said that if he came to power he
would not allow Milosevic, who has been indicted for war crimes by
the tribunal in the Hague, to be handed over for trial. He has
strongly criticized the West's war in Kosovo and the presence of
NATO peacekeepers there.
</P>
<P>
   Extending a hand of friendship to the opposition _ and urging it
to keep its courage _ Clinton said in a speech at Georgetown
University Law Center that Serbia, the dominant republic in
Yugoslavia, would have much to gain with a change of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the will of the people is respected, the doors to Europe
and the world will be open again to Serbia,'' Clinton said. ``We
will take steps with our allies to lift economic sanctions and the
people of Serbia who have suffered so much finally will have a
chance to lead normal lives. I hope that day is arriving.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also acknowledged differences with the opposition, whose
forces benefited in the last year from $25 million in support from
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am under no illusions that a new government in Serbia would
automatically lead to a rapprochement between the two of us, and
any new leader of Serbia should pursue, first and foremost, the
interests of its own people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the support for the opposition was unequivocal. The
French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine, said that France, as the
current president of the European Union, would reward an opposition
victory with the rapid lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hour of change has struck in Belgrade,'' Vedrine said.
``Something has begun with this vote which is no longer to be
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In what administration officials saw as an encouraging sign, the
German Chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, persuaded the Russian
president, Vladimir V. Putin, to join him in a statement in Moscow
on Monday that stressed the vitality of the Serbian opposition and
the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia can be removed from Milosevic's camp, then his
isolation will be almost complete, officials here said. One of the
comfort factors that Milosevic has traditionally offered his top
cronies is the notion that there is always some major country for
them to turn to.
</P>
<P>
   The administration even took small cheer from the fact that
Milosevic invited election observers to come from China _ he
declined to accept them from anywhere else _ but that the Chinese
observers failed to show up.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton pointed out, there was no certainty that the
Yugoslav drama would end without violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not underestimate Milosevic's desire to cling to power at
the expense of the people: I have witnessed it, lived with it and
responded to it first-hand,'' Clinton said, referring to the war in
Kosovo last year and NATO air raids in Bosnia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In some quarters, Milosevic's desire for a second round of
voting was seen as an effort to try to organize military and police
units that would fight, if necessary. ``His strategy has always
been: string them out and then beat them up,'' said one official,
recalling the scenes in 1991 when Milosevic called out tanks
against protesters in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly 10 years later, it seems that the Serbian people have
given more votes to a charismatic, single opposition leader,
Kostunica. And after four lost wars _ over Slovenia, Croatia,
Bosnia and Kosovo _ it seems that many in the military and the
police have voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question now is how Milosevic will go out and who he will
take out with him,'' said one administration official who has been
at the center of Balkans policy. ``Finally the people stood up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
