<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIABETES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS FIND GENE FOR TYPE 2 DIABETES
</HEADLINE>
  By NICHOLAS WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A novel gene associated with development of Type 2, or
adult-onset, diabetes, a major and growing public health problem,
has been identified from study of Mexican-Americans in Starr
County, Texas, a population with an unusually heavy burden of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The finding, if confirmed, will be the first discovery of a gene
involved in the most common kind of Type 2 diabetes. Although some
5 percent of cases of the disease are caused by defects in single
genes, which are relatively easy to find, the most common kind of
Type 2 diabetes is thought to be caused by several contributing
genes.
</P>
<P>
   In multigenic diseases, which include many of the most common
afflictions like Alzheimer's, asthma, diabetes, heart disease and
schizophrenia, the contribution from every gene is so small that
each is hard to identify.
</P>
<P>
   To their surprise, the researchers at the University of Chicago
and the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston found
the gene is one not known to have anything to do with sugar
metabolism, which is disturbed in diabetes. Its role is obscure,
they said, but once it is understood, it should reveal a new
biochemical pathway involved in diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The diabetes finding has a broader significance in that the gene
is the first in a multigenic disease to have been identified by
scanning the whole genome _ the full complement of human DNA _ in a
systematic way.
</P>
<P>
   Though a few such genes have come to light through guesswork,
genomewide scans are the most promising method for uncovering the
roots of multigenic disease. The diabetes work was done mostly
before the human genome sequence became available, and such studies
should be much easier in future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first published account of tracking down a DNA
sequence variation that appears to account for a multigenic
character'' by scanning the whole genome, said Dr. Francis Collins,
director of the National Human Genome Research Institute. ``It is a
pathway we hope to travel frequently, so it's a relief to see
someone has actually done it, albeit at great effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The Type 2 diabetes gene has been discovered through an
eight-year effort which involved comparing the DNA of patients and
their siblings unaffected by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The gene has been named calpain-10 after a family of known genes
it resembles. Calpain-10 and other genes involved in its pathway
may provide new targets for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The gene variations associated with diabetes were discovered
first among the Mexican-American families of Starr County, in South
Texas. They have since also been found, though at lower frequency,
in other ethnic groups, including the Pima Indians of Arizona, who
have the highest known incidence of Type 2 diabetes, and Europeans
from the Botnia region of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   The team of researchers who brought the gene variations to light
include Dr. Graeme I. Bell of the University of Chicago, who
directed the genetic analysis; his colleague Nancy J. Cox, who
devised the statistical tests to pinpoint the causative DNA
variations; and Dr. Craig L. Hanis, of the University of Texas
Health Science Center at Houston, who led the clinical analysis of
the Starr County patients. Their findings are published in
Wednesday's issue of the journal Nature Genetics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
