<SLUG> BC-EXP-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, IN A TACTICAL VICTORY, GETS CASE RETURNED TO APPEALS
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court handed a major tactical victory
to the Microsoft Corp. on Tuesday when it rejected the government's
plea to immediately hear the appeal of its landmark antitrust case
and instead returned the proceeding to the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The decision gives Microsoft greater breathing room to pursue
its appeals, relieves the company of any pressure to return any
time soon to the bargaining table and, in the absence of a
settlement, could have the effect of prolonging a final court
judgment by a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives applauded Tuesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that we're moving on with the process,'' said Steven
A. Ballmer, the chief executive of Microsoft, in an interview in
San Francisco. ``We are confident in our case on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Justice Department officials on Tuesday began
the process of preparing for a new round of court appearances. ``We
look forward to presenting our case to the court of appeals as
expeditiously as possible,'' said Gina Talamona, a department
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's decision, the government had argued that the
case against Microsoft involved issues of ``immense importance to
our national economy,'' and had urged the Supreme Court to invoke a
rarely used procedural rule to bypass the appeals court, quickly
review the case and uphold the order issued by Federal District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson three months ago to slice Microsoft
into two smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had opposed the government's request for immediate
Supreme Court review, saying it ``would impose an extraordinary
burden on the court'' and that there was no reason to depart from
the normal procedure of using the appeals court to narrow the
complex legal issues and voluminous trial record.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court agreed when it directed that the
case be sent to the court of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Seven appeals court judges are to hear the proceeding. After
they deliberate over the next few months, they have a wide range of
options, including sending the case back to Jackson for further
proceedings consistent with their ruling, a process that could
further delay a final resolution.
</P>
<P>
   After the court of appeals rules, the case could still go to the
Supreme Court. But, since the Supreme Court is under no obligation
to review the eventual decision of the appeals court, that court
could have the last word, although that may not be known until some
time in 2001 or later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KODAK-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      09-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KODAK-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KODAK STOCK PLUNGES 25 PERCENT ON SUDDEN DROP IN SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co., citing a sudden and as-yet-unexplained sales
decline in every one of its businesses, warned investors Tuesday
that its third-quarter earnings would be as much as 25 cents a
share below expectations and that, if sales do not pick up,
fourth-quarter earnings might disappoint as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a strong August, we're seeing slowness everywhere,'' a
perplexed Robert H. Brust, Kodak's chief financial officer, told
analysts in a hastily arranged conference call Tuesday. ``We're
combing the woods to see what's causing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Brust said that third-quarter revenue would probably fall short
of expectations by $200 million to $300 million. Most troubling, he
said, the declines were coming at the tail end of September,
traditionally the strongest part of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems certain if the drop is a one-time blip or a sign of
long-term woes, but investors clearly expect the worst. They sent
Kodak stock plunging $14.81 a share Tuesday, or 25 percent, to
$44.19, the lowest level in more than six years.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Kodak had predicted earnings of $1.56 to $1.66 a
share, while the analysts' consensus was $1.60 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts lowered their earnings estimates for this year and
next by about 10 percent and pulled their buy recommendations off
the stock. ``There's clearly a loss of faith in the company,'' said
Charles L. Hill, director of research at First Call/Thompson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Kodak's announcement was particularly
shocking in that the mood among retailers at Photokina, the huge
photography exhibition in Germany that is held twice a year and
ended this week, was very upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense we got is that demand is robust, and that Kodak's
third quarter seemed on track,'' said Jonathan Rosenzweig, an
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Theories were rife on Wall Street on Tuesday about what went
wrong. Some analysts suggested that high energy prices and the wet
summer had cut into consumer vacations, curtailing picture-taking.
</P>
<P>
   But others suggested that Kodak's retail customers were trying
to lower their inventories and might rush back with large orders in
October. They noted other photography-related companies were having
similar woes. For example, Lexmark International, which makes
photo-capable printers, also issued an earnings warning, partly
attributable to sluggish sales of inkjet printer cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trends don't change overnight, and people don't stop taking
pictures overnight,'' said Ulysses Yannas, an analyst with Buckman,
Buckman &AMP; Reid and one of the few to maintain a strong buy on Kodak
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there a universal pall over the photographic industry.
Stephen Giordano, the president of Digital Now Inc., which sells
equipment and software to convert photographs to digital images,
says he is seeing ``explosive growth'' in sales. ``Kodak's digital
business should be growing as fast as we are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji Photofilm USA recently told analysts that its film sales
were sluggish but its photographic paper sales were strong. And
Michelle Lampmann, an analyst for Infotrends Research Group, says
all digital cameras are selling well.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, until Tuesday, Kodak, which is based in Rochester, N.Y.,
seemed to be flying high, too. It had met or exceeded earnings
expectations in the last six quarters. It had not faced a price war
in film for a while, its digital losses had been greatly reduced,
and its cost-cutting programs were on track.
</P>
<P>
   It has also made headway in sales on the Internet. Just this
week it revamped its Web home page to look less corporate and more
like an Internet home for amateur photography enthusiasts. ``That
should really help them drive revenue from the Web,'' said Lia M.
Schubert, an internet research analyst at Infotrends.
</P>
<P>
   But Web sales and such will never offer Kodak the lush profit
margins of conventional film, and that means the company has less
leeway to combat setbacks. ``With a lower-margin mix of products,
film sales have to work even harder to make up for shortfalls,''
said Benjamin A. Reitzes, an analyst at PaineWebber. ``And that's
put a long-term cloud over the company.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kodak's problems may be more macro than micro. Analysts
have told First Call that they expect sluggish third-quarter
earnings reports from retailers, too. And Jack L. Kelly, a
conglomerate analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., noted that Rockwell
International, Ingersoll-Rand and many other capital goods
companies had issued earnings warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kodak's problems may represent just another dot to connect in
a picture of an economy that is slowing across the board,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its cause, the sales decline could not have come at a
worse time for Kodak. Its raw materials prices have skyrocketed,
while a persistently weak euro caused a $50 million
currency-translation hit to third-quarter sales.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's graphics business is struggling, as digital technologies
continue to supplant the need for Kodak films. Kodak's own digital
portfolio still loses money. And Fuji is doubling its capacity for
making films and papers in the United States early next year, a
move that many analysts expect might set off a price war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales decline has made it impossible for us to offset
these other issues,'' Brust said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f bc-LATINA-WOMEN-LADN     09-26 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINA-WOMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINA BUSIESS ON FAST TRACK
</HEADLINE>
bc-LATINA-WOMEN-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Businesses owned by Latinas are a growing economic force, but
their use of traditional sources of capital has not grown in
proportion, according to a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spirit of Enterprise: Latina Entrepreneurs in the United
States'' study by the National Foundation of Women Business Owners
says nationwide there were 382,400 Latina-owned businesses
generating $67.3 billion in sales in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Latina market is actually the fastest growing market in the
small business sector, said Mary Rodrigues, spokeswoman for Wells
Fargo, which sponsored the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a huge market,'' Rodrigues said.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1987 and 1996, the number of Latina-owned firms in the
United States grew by 206 percent; their sales rose 534 percent,
and their employment numbers grew 487 percent, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Some 54 percent of Latinas surveyed started their businesses
with $10,000 or more, compared to 44 percent of all business
owners. Just over half of Latina entrepreneurs had bank credit.
</P>
<P>
   Bank capital carried by Latina business owners has not changed
drastically in the past two years. In 1998, 24 percent of Latinas
surveyed had less than $25,000 in capital available and 24 percent
had $100,000 or more. Today 22 percent have less than $25,000 and
29 percent have $100,000 or more, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Latinos) are a little more conservative and prefer to work on
internally generated capital, but you have the financial community
aggressively courting them,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for
the Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, California ranked first in the nation for Latina-owned
businesses, with 130,000 businesses that employed 148,400 people
and generated sales of nearly $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to continue to be a very, very important
community,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo has been particularly interested in Latina
businesses because of their fast rate of growth, Rodrigues said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo launched a Latino Loan Program three years ago with
a goal of lending $1 billion nationally to Latino men and women.
Last year the bank upped its goal to $3 billion over the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of 1999, we had loaned more than $500 million to
Latino business owners nationwide,'' Rodrigues said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many people think Latina businesses are new, the survey
found they have an average of 12 years in business, which makes
them considered less risky prospects for loans, Rodrigues said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Rosenthal, spokesman for the National Foundation for Women
Business Owners, pointed out that two-thirds of the survey
respondents were born in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were intrigued at how well-established Hispanic women are
as business owners,'' he said. ``They also retain some very strong
ties to their heritage and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation sees the study results as a kind of wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are opportunities for Latina entrepreneurs to develop
their business plans and to approach banks with their business
needs. And it's also an opportunity for the banks,'' Rosenthal
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
