<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CHENEY-VOUCHERS-NYT &LR;      09-26 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-VOUCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MICHIGAN, CHENEY IS SUDDENLY QUIET ON SCHOOL VOUCHER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Mich. _ For weeks Dick Cheney, the Republican
vice-presidential nominee, has promoted the Bush campaign's plan to
take federal money away from failing public schools and give it to
parents to use on educational alternatives, a plan that Democrats
describe as a voucher system that would hurt public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But when Cheney came to Michigan this week _ a swing state where
a ballot initiative calling for a voucher system has become a
political minefield and drawn the opposition of the Republican
governor, John Engler _ he was virtually mum on the subject. He did
not mention it at all on Monday in a speech at an elementary school
in Traverse City, not even when he was asked to comment on vouchers
by a woman in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for the state to decide,'' Cheney told the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later why he did not mention the Bush plan, Cheney said
that he had taken the woman's question to refer to the Michigan
voucher proposal _ a debate the campaign does not wish to inject
itself in. And he said he simply did not have time to describe the
Bush plan.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly every other school stop Cheney has made, he has
promoted Gov. George W. Bush's plan, in which public schools that
fail to meet standards for three years in a row would lose their
federal Title I money, which is earmarked to educate poor and
disadvantaged students. The plan calls for giving the money to the
states, which would then give it to parents of the children in the
failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign tends to avoid the term ``vouchers,'' which it
fears is politically loaded, preferring to think of the money as
``portable.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the campaign does not call the plan a voucher plan, he
said Tuesday: ``You can call it a voucher if you want, but it
relates to the federal funds. We haven't described it as a voucher;
it's really the most choice for the parent. They can spend it if
they want on a tutor; they can use it to send their kids to another
public school; they can use it for private school if that was their
wish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0424 </DOCNO>
