<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW--COLUMN-SFCHRON &LR;      09-26 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO IS NO. 1 _ OR NO. 32  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
San Francisco is often smug about its climate and other natural
charms.
<P>
   The local convention and visitors bureau touts the city as
``everybody's favorite'' and this past weekend it once again topped
the list of Conde Nast Traveler magazine's top U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, readers of Travel &AMP; Leisure magazine gave
San Francisco the edge over New York and London as their favorite
city in the world thanks to its ``red-hot restaurant scene and
booming economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Money magazine chose San Francisco as ``the best
place to live'' among the 300 biggest U.S. metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   But as many Olympic stars in Sydney have discovered, clean
sweeps are difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh-annual ranking of the best U.S. cities for small
business by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet and Entrepreneur magazine, released
Friday, San Francisco placed a distant 32 out of 60 large
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   The gold, silver and bronze were won by Fort Worth-Arlington,
Texas; West Palm Beach-Boca Raton, Fla.; and Raleigh-Durham-Chapel
Hill, N.C., respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The best showing by a big Northern California city was San Jose
(No. 15), followed by Sacramento (No. 29), San Francisco and
Oakland (No. 47).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by the results; the economy is about as robust
as one could ask for and it seems to me we have numerous
entrepreneurial startups,'' said John Marks, president of the San
Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to surveys,'' he added lightheartedly, ``my
reaction is to brag a little when we come out on top and to
question the methodology when we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Dun &AMP; Bradstreet's survey was not a popularity contest. To
determine the best cities for small-business activity, D&AMP;B first
used its credit and marketing file of 11 million U.S. companies to
segment businesses with fewer than 20 employees by metropolitan
statistical area.
</P>
<P>
   It then created rankings based on four categories: percentage of
businesses less than 5 years old, employee growth from January 1999
to January 2000, overall job growth over three years based on U.S.
Bureau of Labor Statistics and risk of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco and the other Northern California cities placed
reasonably well in job growth and getting businesses started but
lagged in keeping them going.
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;B economist Iris Geisler said California cities rank
consistently near the bottom on the risk-of-bankruptcy scale.
(Sacramento tied with Riverside-San Bernardino as worst in this
category.) But Geisler said higher failure rates might indicate
entrepreneurs have a greater appetite for risk and not necessarily
a negative business climate.
</P>
<P>
   No city scored well in all categories. For example, Las Vegas
ranked No.1 in new business formations and three-year economic
growth and No.2 in employee growth but near the bottom in risk of
bankruptcy (No.55 out of 60).
</P>
<P>
   ``The dominance of Southern and Southwestern cities in our study
is driven by the percentage of new business starts among the entire
business population in each of these cities,'' said Geisler.
</P>
<P>
   She called the absence of any California metropolitan area from
the top 10 ``somewhat surprising'' but noted that every large
California big city did better this year than in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Chamber of Commerce spokeswoman Carol Piasente
said the cost of doing business in San Francisco _ such as premium
office space that goes for $100 a square foot per year, houses that
sell for a median price of $510,000 and high labor costs _ are
enough to put off many small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY BUSINESS AWARDS: The Small Business Administration
bestowed its minority owned business of the year awards on Monday.
Business Technologies and Solutions Inc. of Beaver Creek, Ohio, was
named National Minority Small Business Firm of the Year, but nine
other businesses received regional recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The winner from Region IX, made up of California, Arizona and
Hawaii, is Ruby Caffrey, president of SMF Systems Corp. in San
Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   Caffrey and her husband, Tom, an SMF executive vice president,
have built SMF into a better than $150 million-a-year computer
products and services company over the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1994, the two focused on selling information technology
products and services to companies. Then they got involved in the
SBA's Section 8(a) program that helps small companies owned by
socially and economically disadvantaged persons obtain federal
government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about two-thirds of SMF's business is with federal
agencies, including the Naval Facilities Command in Washington,
D.C., and the General Services Administration in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of entrepreneurs have the perception that the government
is a pain in the neck to deal with, that there's a lot of red tape
and it's hard to get paid,'' said Tom Caffrey, who previously
worked for an automated manufacturing systems company called RGL
Inc. in San Francisco. ``But with the Procurement Reform Act and
e-commerce, it's become a lot easier to deal with the government.
''
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Caffrey, a Chinese American from Oakland, and Tom Caffrey,
an Irish-Japanese American from Seaside Heights, N.J., note that it
is no longer necessary to be an ethnic minority to qualify for the
Section 8(a) program. Owners of businesses in disadvantaged
economic areas also may win federal government contracts through
the SBA program.
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTION: In last week's column, I garbled the title of Edward
Tian, one of Red Herring magazine's top 10 entrepreneurs of the
year. He is co-founder of AsiaInfo and CEO of China Netcom.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton(AT)sfchronicle.com
</P>
</TEXT>
