<SLUG> BC-WINDOWS--PRODUCTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SERVES UP NEW PRODUCTS 
 &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
To hear Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer tell it, the really big news
for the software giant Tuesday was not its victory in legal
maneuvering before the Supreme Court but the launch of a family of
products designed to boost the company's share of the lucrative
``enterprise'' market.
<P>
   Microsoft took over San Francisco's Warfield Theater to announce
the release of Windows 2000 Datacenter Server, the latest version
of its business operating system, and a slew of related products
with names like BizTalk Server 2000, Commerce Server 2000 and Host
Integration Server 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new products are designed not for desktop PCs, but for the
giant servers that power computers for major companies and Web
sites. So far, this market has been dominated by the Unix operating
system running on proprietary hardware with expensive specialized
chips made by Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and others.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft hopes that its new software will change the
balance. Ballmer said more than 100 enterprise customers, including
Ford, Home Shopping Network, Honeywell, Lycos, Panasonic, Radio
Shack and Turner Broadcasting, have already decided to adopt the
new Microsoft products in place of the Unix-based software they had
previously relied on.
</P>
<P>
   The event was a marked contrast to February's0 launch of the
desktop version of Windows 2000, when the company brought rock star
Carlos Santana and Star Trek's Patrick Stewart to the Bill Grahan
Auditorium to help it celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the event featured a two-hour parade of CEOs from
corporate customers, consulting companies and hardware
manufacturers. Instead of the giant mock-up of a laptop, the stage
decor this time consisted of a lineup of refrigerator-size servers
made by Compaq, Dell, Hewlett-Packard, IBM and Unisys.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman and chief
software architect, was nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The software won't be marketed through retail channels, but only
in bundles with hardware and services from such companies. Only
four of the new products are actually shipping today. The others
are due by the end of the year, or in the case of a new product
called Mobile Information 2001 Server, in the first half of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer and his partners on stage stressed that the new programs
would provide critical ``abilities'' _ reliability, scalability and
manageability _ that earlier versions of Windows had not.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that ``reliability is where we've been pushed the most,
based on people's experience with Windows 95 and 98,'' he said
Microsoft had responded with more testing, tighter certification
programs, and an array of support programs and uptime guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of emphasis on reliability _ a lot, a lot, a
lot,'' he said. One customer, FreeMarkets.com, said it has already
achieved 99.999 percent uptime with the new software.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies used the occasion to announce new server
systems. HP CEO Carly Fiorina, appearing on videotape, and Compaq
CEO Michael Capellas, live onstage, both touted new ``32-way''
servers, each with 32 Intel processors. Later, in a panel
discussion, Unisys CEO Lawrence Weinbach said both HP and Compaq
are actually reselling his company's 32-chip server.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
