A2794 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-HACKETT-LADN--(SL     09-26 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HACKETT-LADN--(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER POLO A BETTER FIT THAN BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Hackett's childhood dreams involved making diving catches
and showing off his strong arm. The dreams just didn't involve
doing it in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett envisioned growing up to be a star shortstop for the New
York Yankees. Instead, he turned into the star goalkeeper for the
U.S. national men's water polo team. The former UCLA All-American
has been a member of the national team since 1991 and is widely
regarded as one of the best in the world at his position, making
him a key part of the U.S.' hopes of reaching the medal round if
they can get by Greece today.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite sport was baseball,'' Hackett said. ``It just so
happened, though, that this is the sport that was best for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett, 30, turned to water polo when a growth spurt in high
school left him feeling his agility wasn't as good and baseball was
out of his future. The Syracuse, N.Y., native had grown up rooting
for the Yankees and playing on Little League all-star teams.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't even start playing water polo until his freshman year
of high school, when he was looking for a way to get out taking a
standard P.E. class. Water polo seemed the best option since he
didn't like the other fall sports offered for boys.
</P>
<P>
   His days as a field player lasted less than two weeks when his
lack of a swimming background made it difficult for him to keep up
with the pace of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The size that made him abandon baseball _ even though current
Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter is 6-foot-4 _ is one of Hackett's
greatest assets as a goalkeeper. He is 6-6, with an arm span of
6-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking up space is the object of the game, so that definitely
gives him an advantage,'' U.S. head coach John Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can pose a problem for shooters,'' Hackett said of his
size. ``They may not realize how much range I have. They go for the
far post, but it doesn't take me long to cover the cage.''
</P>
<P>
   His success is a product of more than just size, though.
</P>
<P>
   Even after years of playing among the elite, Hackett continues
to diligently study the game, looking for minute aspects he can
fine-tune, how to better read his teammates or what to expect from
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very prepared,'' Vargas said. ``He anticipates well and
knows what's going to happen before it happens. It's hard to trick
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett's devotion was bred at UCLA, where he was part of a
freshman class overflowing with goalkeepers and he was the only one
without a scholarship. Hackett decided then that if he was going to
endure the rigorous workouts, he was going to do whatever it took
to make sure he got to play in the games, too.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a spot on the junior national team that summer and
gained valuable experience against European teams. When he returned
to Westwood for his sophomore year, Hackett took over as the
starting goalkeeper. By the time he left, he had played in three
NCAA national-championship tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great goalie back then,'' said Guy Baker, who coached
Hackett's final season at UCLA. ``Everyone knew Danny was going to
be an Olympian.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett made the 1996 Olympic team but played just one quarter
the entire tournament as the U.S. finished a disappointing seventh.
He's not sure how much longer he'll play, so a medal in Sydney
would be the perfect way to ensure he doesn't leave another dream
unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's become my prime focus,'' Hackett said. ``It's one thing
to make the Olympics. To be up there on the medal stand is another
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hit me as hard last time because I wasn't the one
out there playing most of the time. When you're the starting
goalie, a lot rests on you. I think I'll take it a lot more
personally this time if we don't win. I want to come home with a
medal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
