A2795 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FAIRE--MERCHANTS-SFCH     09-26 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRE--MERCHANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THE WORLD'S A STAGE FOR FAIR MERCHANTS 
 &HT;     BY CARRIE KIRBY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
To get into the business of selling high-end soap products, Sidney
Rice had to learn which ingredients make the smoothest soap and
what to charge.
<P>
   That was the easy part. The real challenge was figuring out how
to explain modern concepts like ``aromatherapy'' and ``Web site''
without breaking the illusion that her customers are shopping in a
16th century alchemist's shop.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of doing business at the Northern California
Renaissance Pleasure Faire, where vendors try to balance the
romance of bygone times with the reality of making a buck.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where a mass-produced candy dish sells at Target for
a mere $7.99, the fair provides a venue for craftspeople to make a
living selling their handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   Each weekend during its seven-week run, 9,000 to 10,000
customers come to the fair in Vacaville off Interstate 80 to watch
jugglers, eat turkey legs and snap up banners, jewelry and other
crafts.
</P>
<P>
   All the merriment is set in 16th century England, when Elizabeth
I was on the throne and Shakespeare was on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The ambience works. ``I couldn't imagine having 4,000 people
walk into a shop in San Diego,'' said Rice, who sometimes sells two
or three times as much soap at the Pleasure Faire as she does at
street fairs at home in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, she scours flea markets and garage sales for
the straw baskets and heavy metal pitchers that give her booth the
look of an alchemist's workshop. The fair's &LR;   &LR; shtick _ including
fanciful product names like ``the Philosopher's Stone'' _ helps her
sell, said Rice, who also works part time for Williams-Sonoma while
she ramps up her business.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Northern California fair's 153 craft booths, many are
one- or two-person operations such as Rice's.
</P>
<P>
   A few have expanded over the years to become robust, full-time
businesses. Take Michelle and Ray Amsbury of Whittier (Los Angeles
County), who, with eight employees, have earned as much as $800,000
in a single year making decorative tiles, Christmas ornaments and
beads.
</P>
<P>
   While Michelle Amsbury and two sales assistants run a booth at
the Pleasure Faire, Ray Amsbury runs another at the Harvest
Festival in Del Mar (San Diego County). The events are part of a
year-round circuit of Renaissance and Christmas fairs in which the
couple do business.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 30 years of fairs, Michelle Amsbury has as many
costumes as most people have clothes. Over that period, she has
learned to pepper her speech with Elizabethan phrases _ a ``good
morrow'' here, and ``I thank thee'' there.
</P>
<P>
   But she drops the pretense when it's time for customers to pay.
``It's clearer to use regular English,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fair in Vacaville holds workshops for merchants in language,
costume and Renaissance lifestyle. If they really want to delve
into their roles, merchants can also take a ``hawking'' class,
where they learn the oldest form of advertising _ shouting the
virtues of products to any potential customers who pass by.
</P>
<P>
   Modern conveniences like credit cards are acknowledged with a
little finesse: Some shops refer to them as ``Lady Visa and Master
Card,'' and merchants hide their cellular phones and credit card
machines in the back.
</P>
<P>
   These vendors are vital to the fair's business. Not only do they
populate the make-believe English village that the whole fantasy
rests on, but economically, they contribute 20 percent of the
Northern California fair's revenue, said General Manager David
McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the fair's income, which is expected to near $1
million for the seven-weekend run from September to mid-October,
comes from the $17.50 entry price, parking and sales of food,
drinks, games and official fair merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Vacaville site is legally a temporary one, vendors
have to build new booths from scratch each year _ building costs
range from $100 for a modest wooden cart to $5,000 for a roomy
boutique. Many artists make these booths modular so they can take
them apart and move them to another festival later.
</P>
<P>
   Artists pay $200 for a space for the full seven weeks, then cut
the fair in for 15 percent of their revenues. If merchants
demonstrate their crafts for the crowds, the fair takes a smaller
cut _ 10 to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Glass blower Pete Lanigan said demonstrating has a fringe
benefit: It attracts customers by showing them why a handmade vase
is more valuable than a factory-made one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love taking someone who thinks glass is something that comes
from Kmart and showing them how it's done,'' said Lanigan, who puts
on an elaborate demonstration at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of 50 or more gather on the half hour to watch him
repeatedly thrust a blob of glass on the end of a pipe into a
red-hot furnace, blowing through the pipe until the blob grows into
a stylish decanter.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a booth at the fair is competitive, since only a half
dozen or so new shops are accepted each year. New merchants must
submit samples of their wares months in advance for the fair to
review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask that you use natural materials. We're not going to be
selling blenders,'' said fair spokeswoman Shannon Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Once they make it in, a Renaissance festival can be a
craftmaker's dream market, since about 50 percent of visitors to
the Northern California Faire buy a craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are paying to get in the door, they're already ready
to spend money,'' said James Dillehay, editor of the Craft Marketer
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Most merchants who do fairs year round say they make a good
middle-class living, with large operations like the Amsburys'
regularly pulling in six figures in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some merchants fail to make a satisfactory profit and
opt not to return, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants, including Rice, the soapmaker, have branched out
onto the Internet, where they hope customers will look for them in
the long months before the fair reopens.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to say whether online sales will become a major
part of their business. Some merchants say online sales don't carry
the ``now or never'' feeling of a live event.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Renaissance Pleasure Faire, the Internet also
can't recreate the scent of roasting turkey or the sounds of
madrigals in the air.
</P>
<P>
   For now, fair officials say they aren't worried about the impact
of the Net on its operations. ``The fair's sales experience can't
be duplicated on a Web site,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   For many merchants, the best part about selling at the fair is
the constant interaction with customers. It's like an all-day focus
group _ they find out which products are most popular and get
suggestions for new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Rice says she's gotten special orders for gift baskets and
landed new wholesale accounts from customers she met at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Artists say nothing is comparable to being there in person for
customers. ``They'd have to see me, even if I was stuffed,'' said
knifemaker and potter Jon Schulps, who after 31 years has tried
leaving his booth to his staff to run on occasion. ``It doesn't
work. Sales went way down.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby &LR; (AT) &LR; sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
