<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     09-26 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT-COM LUNCH MIGHT BRING BUFFETT INTO INVESTING'S CYBERAGE  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Wouldn't you like to be a fly in the soup at this lunch?
<P>
   Next week, eight young Bay Area dot-commers will have a private
lunch with legendary investor and self-proclaimed technophobe
Warren Buffett at Stars restaurant in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Budlong _ a single, 35-year-old, semiretired Internet
millionaire _ won the lunch at an auction Saturday night benefiting
Glide Memorial United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Budlong placed the winning bid of $25,000 and plans to bring
seven friends _ all Web workers in their 20s and 30s _ to the meal.
He also invited comedian Robin Williams, who cohosted the event.
Glide says Williams will attend.
</P>
<P>
   Glide made a concerted effort to reach people like Budlong this
year, and it paid off big. The fund-raiser grossed $700,000
compared with only $240,000 last year. (More on how they did it
below.)
</P>
<P>
   Budlong didn't even know Buffett was up for auction until he got
to the event at the Galleria Design Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants season-ticket holder originally intended to bid on a
jersey signed by right fielder Ellis Burks. But when he saw Buffett
on the block, he decided to spend ``an amount I would put into a
startup investment'' to win the lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a big fan of his,'' he says. ``I read a book
about him, `The Warren Buffet Way,' a few years back. I like how he
looks at intrinsic value.''
</P>
<P>
   Budlong says he wants to keep the lunch ``very informal,
conversational, not too structured. What I want to know is, what
does he think of the Internet as an investment vehicle? Is he at
all beginning to understand it?''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett has famously avoided technology stocks because he
doesn't buy what he doesn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   On his company's Web site ( &LR; www.berkshirehathaway.com &LR; ), Buffett
writes, ``Being a lifelong technophobe, I tiptoed into the computer
world only a few years ago. If you have any ideas about how we can
make these pages more useful, just drop me a line (not e-mail
though; I haven't made that much progress).''
</P>
<P>
   Budlong figures Buffett knew what he was getting into when he
agreed to the auction. ``If you open this opportunity to the
public, and put it in the heart of Multimedia Gulch, he has to know
he's going to end up with some Internet guys, and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   An electrical engineer, Budlong worked for Hewlett-Packard and
several startups before becoming the first employee of
Classifieds2000.com. In 1998, the Santa Clara company was acquired
by ExciteAtHome for $50 million in Excite stock, which was worth
$300 million a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Budlong worked at Excite until last year. Since then, he has
been investing in Net startups and is on the board of three _
Giving Circle.com, an e-commerce platform that lets retailers give
part of their sales to charity; Voter.com, a political portal; and
Cybermoola, a prepaid Internet shopping card for teens.
</P>
<P>
   He also is involved with several nonprofits, including one that
is trying to build a world-class rose garden on the grounds of the
state Capitol in Sacramento dedicated to global peace.
</P>
<P>
   Budlong admits that he would like to get Buffett interested in
his companies and charities, ``but I don't want the lunch to be one
long sales pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows the odds of hooking Buffett on tech stocks are very
long. ``But if there is a chance, this is a good chance,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As a value investor, Buffett might be happy to know he wasn't
the most-expensive item at the auction. Two people paid $30,000
each to have the Glide Ensemble, a 140-voice choir, perform at two
separate events.
</P>
<P>
   And when dinner with Robin and Marsha Williams went for $14,000,
the fun-loving couple agreed to have a second dinner with another
bidder for $14,000 and a third dinner for $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   When the winners came up to pay for their prizes, John Warner,
Glide's fund developer, asked what they did for a living, and most
of them were Internet types.
</P>
<P>
   ``We completely rebranded the event to attract a younger,
hipper, trendier crowd,'' Warner says. ``We changed the name (from
Raise Your Spirits to Soul of the City). We designed new graphics.
We moved it out of a stuffy old hotel into the Galleria.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Glide marketed the shindig through e-mail
lists (such as the A List) and Web sites (including Craig's List).
That boosted attendance from 650 last year to 1,200 this year.
</P>
<P>
   A high-tech company called Lante Corp. ``completely digitized
our silent auction,'' Warner adds. ``Instead of writing your name
on slips of paper, you bid on computers. And there were people
walking around with wireless Palm Pilots, so you could increase
your bids.''
</P>
<P>
   Glide wanted to send the message: ``Hey, this is a sophisticated
nonprofit that does believe in technology, that does believe in the
digital divide. It made a huge statement.''
</P>
<P>
   And it worked. ``There were a lot more people in the room and a
lot more monied people in the room,'' Warner says. ``You know the
stereotype _ young, rich dot-commers _ there were tons of them.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER TRADING _ PART II: As part of its crackdown on insider
trading, the Securities and Exchange Commission is getting tougher
on the relatives of corporate executives.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when a person traded stock on inside information
obtained from a family member, the SEC had to prove that the person
violated an explicit ``duty of trust or confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule 10b5-2, which takes effect Oct. 23, assumes that a such a
duty automatically exists between insiders and their spouses,
children, parents and siblings.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean?
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example. Suppose a husband passes company secrets to
his wife, who trades on the information and/or passes it along to
someone else, who trades on the tip.
</P>
<P>
   To prove illegal insider trading, prosecutors in the past had to
show that the husband said something like, ``Honey, this is top
secret, you have to keep it to yourself and not abuse it,'' and the
wife said, ``Sure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, prosecutors won't have to prove that such an
exchange took place. It will be up to the spouses to prove that a
duty of trust and confidence did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SEC says, when it comes to members of the immediate
family, we presume there was a duty of trust or confidence, unless
you can prove otherwise,'' says attorney Jared Kopel of Wilson
Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC noted that the new rule does not automatically apply to
domestic partners, stepparents or stepchildren, although they may
be liable if they have a ``history or pattern'' of sharing
confidences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience in this area indicates that most instances of
insider trading between or among family members involve spouses,
parents and children, or siblings; therefore, we have enumerated
these relationships and not others,'' the SEC writes.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on 10b5-2 and 10b5-1 _ the other new
insider trading rule I wrote about yesterday _ go to
 &LR; www.sec.gov/rules/final &LR;   &LR; /33-7881.htm &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender(AT)sfchronicle.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
