<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle of the Baptists
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After two decades of wrangling, the Baptist
General Convention of Texas and the Southern Baptist Convention are
headed for an Olympic-size showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Which takes home the gold will be up to Texas Baptist messengers
at their state convention in late October. The messengers, under a
recommendation made by their executive board Tuesday, will decide
whether to yank more than $5 million in financial support from six
seminaries from the Southern Baptist Convention, a national group.
</P>
<P>
   The board also asked Texas Baptists to approve a budget plan
that would allow the state convention to earmark the millions of
dollars it sends to the national body for specific programs,
circumventing the historical way the money has been divided.
</P>
<P>
   It is viewed as a bold move for the moderate Texas convention,
which is risking the loss of conservative churches, to make a
statement that it does not support the national convention's
conservative theology or political agenda. The Baptist General
Convention of Texas is the largest Baptist state convention in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Baptists contribute nearly 14 percent to the Southern
Baptist Convention's Cooperative Program, the money pool used to
finance missionary work, seminaries, Baptist agencies and
administrative costs. The national body uses a funding formula to
designate where the money goes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Texas convention wants to bypass that formula,
requiring its proposed $19.1 million Cooperative Program
contribution be used:
</P>
<P>
   _ Predominantly to finance the national body's mission work.
</P>
<P>
   _ For Texas students already enrolled in the six Southern
Baptist Convention seminaries, capping the state's contribution to
Southern Baptist Convention seminaries at $1 million. The majority
of that amount is expected to go to Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, but that would be half of the
seminary's current contribution from the Texas convention.
</P>
<P>
   _To not finance the national convention's Ethics and Religious
Liberty Commission, which currently is receiving about $750,000
from Texas Baptists. The state convention contends the agency
supports a political agenda that violates the time-honored Baptist
tradition of separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   _To barely help the national body's governing board by giving
$10,000, down from the current Texas Baptist contribution of about
$750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The change would benefit Texas seminaries that cropped up after
conservatives solidified their control of the national Southern
Baptist Convention and one longtime Texas school that wants to
obtain seminary accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new proposal, George W. Truett Seminary at Baylor
University in Waco would receive $1 million _ more than double its
current funding _ and Logsdon School of Theology at Hardin-Simmons
University in Abilene would get $750,000, more than seven times
what it receives now. The Hispanic Baptist Theology School in San
Antonio would get a $500,000 infusion to use toward obtaining
seminary accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Baptist leaders said they want to give money to the state
seminaries that promote ``responsible academic freedom'' instead of
what they see as the right-wing fundamentalism being taught in the
national convention's seminaries. National leaders contend Texas
leaders are more liberal than moderate and seminary teaching is
about staying true to Jesus Christ and the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   National Baptist leaders also argue the Texas convention is
going to force a split between the two organizations and that state
leaders do not reflect the sentiments of Texas Baptists in the
pews.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree no one can predict how the changes, which are
expected to pass at the state convention, will effect either
convention. Individual Texas churches, for instance, may decide to
send money to directly to the national body to make up the deficit.
The Southern Baptist Convention may decide it cannot take any money
from the Texas convention that does not adhere to the Cooperative
Program funding formula.
</P>
<P>
   Two things are certain: the Baptist General Convention of Texas
is at a critical crossroads and what happens here will have a
national impact.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
