<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker's tranquil N.Y. trip
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - One man graced the back page of all three tabloids
Tuesday. That the man was Vinny Testaverde, Jets quarterback and
center of the latest Big Apple tempest, was proof that time lessens
all furors, even those involving the furious John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The man who required the conveyance of an unmarked police van
and the construction of a special bullpen canopy when he came here
in June was essentially left alone this trip. Upon arrival in
Manhattan on Monday, Rocker walked into the lobby of the Grand
Hyatt without escort or incident. For Tuesday's game, roughly 500
officers were on duty at Shea Stadium _ up from the usual
complement of 45 but down from the 600 of June. This show of force
seemed most benign. At 4:30 p.m., Rocker stood just inside the
stadium press entrance talking on his cell phone; there were police
all around, but they didn't appear to be guarding him.
</P>
<P>
   Approached by three New York writers before the game, Rocker was
actually sort of beguiling. Would he consent to an interview?
``Ummm,'' he said, drawing it out, pretending the suggestion had
left him torn. ``I'm going to say no today.'' Even the writers
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 12 months, John Rocker has done his best to be
noticed. What's remarkable about the tail end of the 2000 season is
how little stir he makes apart from his pitching. And even his
critics -- this correspondent remains one -- must admit that he's
pitching splendidly. He has become the unchallenged closer for a
bullpen that is about to win the Rolaids team championship, no
small achievement.
</P>
<P>
   It is again possible to envision a World Series that ends with
John Rocker on the mound, throwing Strike 3 past Tino Martinez.
Rocker's season began with a suspension and then, in short order,
tracked a path from welcome-back ovations to on-field moonings to
an abrupt loss of pitch command to heated exchange with the writer
of the infamous Sports Illustrated article. On June 5 he was
dispatched to the minor leagues, and more than a few folks would
have bet that he'd thrown his last fastball as an Atlanta Brave.
</P>
<P>
   But an injury to Rudy Seanez forced the Braves to recall Rocker
within the week, and in the weeks since he has mostly kept quiet
and thrown strikes. Has Rocker changed? ``I don't spend a lot of
time around him, so I don't really know,'' Tom Glavine said. ``But
he's been pitching better, and he seems less volatile, more at
ease. It doesn't seem like he's waiting for someone to get on him
and then jump back at (the critic). He's less confrontational.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkable than the muting of Rocker is the capacity
of this team to absorb his excesses and still position itself to
win yet another division title. In the end, professionalism trumped
one man's psychodrama. ``If there was any place it was going to
happen,'' Glavine said, ``this was it.''
</P>
<P>
   On John Rocker's first trip back to New York, he was the focal
point of the tabloids' back and front pages. The second time
through, he was just another guy come to do a job. To borrow his
words from last autumn, full-blown hysteria had become a tired act.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
