<SLUG> BC-OLY-BEACH0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. makes rainy day golden memory
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ This was no day for the beach. Rain splattered against
the bundled crowd's brightly colored ponchos. High winds rendered
nearby Bondi Beach deserted except for a few incurable surfers.
Sunscreen and shades stayed inside pockets and purses.
</P>
<P>
   It was, however, a day for the U.S. beach volleyballers. On
soaked sand, Dain Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana flustered the favored
Brazilians and saran-wrapped the gold medal today.
</P>
<P>
   Final score: 12-11, 12-9. That's two men's golds in two Games
since the sport of suds, skin and sun (usually) was initiated in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took one match at a time,'' said Blanton, reciting an old
bromide but a necessary one because his pair was one of the last to
qualify. They were 0-4 this year against Jose Marco Melo and
6-foot-7 Ricardo Santos.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of those four were one-sided in any way,'' reminded Melo,
whose adopted beach name is simply Ze Marco. ``Every (tournament)
is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few beach-garbed spectators who were Sydney's
version of shirtless NFL wackos in January, the only bathing-suited
types were the four players. But the atmosphere that has made this
venue popular was intact.
</P>
<P>
   Each scored point was an excuse for fans to stand and dance to
blaring pop music. Brazil followers, the party animals of any
Games, added to the festivities with horns blowing and flags
waving. Rather than medals, the ambience suggested the twosomes
were playing for a keg of beer.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed more beach than volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans engaged in two hours of athletic give-and-take
with the formidable foes from the beach hotbed. They warded off
four set points in the opening set. The second lasted 66 minutes,
with sides rarely stringing together two points.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Fonoimoana blocked a shot Brazil failed to return.
Blanton stood transfixed, in shock, as his teammate approached with
an embrace. They fell onto the sand and locked in a long hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a release from a lot of hard work,'' Fonoimoana
said.
</P>
<P>
   The elements made their work harder than ever. The Americans
prefer a dry course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control the weather, but I was a little concerned,''
Blanton said. ``Ours is a fast game, a power game. We want the ball
to be light to serve aces. The rain was no help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians' favorite status might have been a hindrance.
``They came in with a lot of pressure,'' Blanton observed,
especially with the top-seeded Brazilian women settling for silver
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' Blanton said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was some day at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   CHRSTINE NESBITT / Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   U.S. teammates Eric Fonoimoana (left) and Dain Blanton celebrate
their upset victory over the Brazilian team today at Bondi Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-seeded Americans beat the favored Brazilians 12-11,
12-9 for America's second gold medal in beach volleyball at the
Games. F3
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
