r s BC-OLY-POE0927-COX     09-26 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-POE0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic fairy tale comes to a sad ending
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - The ultimate American Olympic fairy tale has come to a
sudden, sad ending.
</P>
<P>
   Taekwondo gold medal favorite Kay Poe, an Olympian only because
of her best friend's supreme act of generosity, crashed in her
first match Wednesday. Tense and passive, according to her personal
coach, Poe succumbed to Hanne Hoegh Poulsen of Denmark 5-3 in the
under 49 kg class.
</P>
<P>
   The result left Poe and her dearest pal, Esther Kim, shattered.
It was a cold splash of water to the face after a dreamy four
months during which they were hailed worldwide for Kim's decision
to bow out of the U.S. Trials finals in deference to Poe's
dislocated kneecap.
</P>
<P>
   And it frustrated Poe's coach, Jin Won Kim -- Esther's father.
He said his presence alongside the mat might have made a
difference. Only the national team coach is permitted to work the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she walked in here, I could tell she was very tight from
the pressure,'' said Master Kim, who watched in horror from the
front row. ``I saw her face (and thought), 'Oh, what's wrong with
her?' I was beginning to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make her more comfortable. Tell a joke. Make her laugh.
He (Young In Cheon) is a good coach, but he probably doesn't know
her well.''
</P>
<P>
   Poe, first place at the Trials, had trained almost non-stop for
a week while holed up in the dorm-like athletes village. ``I've
been on pretty strict lockdown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, second place, shopped, attended sports events and the
Opening Ceremony, been fawned over by the Sydney hierarchy,
received heaps of praise from the Olympic family and media and
stayed in a spiffy hotel as guest of Juan Antonio Samaranch. She
walked into an IOC executive board meeting and was greeted by a
videotape of her gig on ``Oprah,'' her most cherished of the pair's
national TV appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Now, who was the real winner here?
</P>
<P>
   Both of them, as Kim, 21, has insisted since May. ``People said
there's not two winners in the same division,'' she said before
Wednesday's fight. ``But we made it possible for two to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Poe, who said Wednesday her knee was fine, would have been
unable to stand, much less defend herself, against Kim at the
Trials. So Kim, in effect, withdrew -- a gesture that reverberates
still through an Olympics splotched by positive drug tests and
selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   Kim never has expressed regrets. ``It's not like I'm throwing my
dream away,'' she said. ``I was just passing it along.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim confessed that she misses basking in taekwondo's debut as an
Olympics medal sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feel of the ring . . . to look up and see the U.S. (crowd)
cheering for me,'' she said wistfully. ``I'm here to see Kay fight.
It doesn't change the fact that I would like to be fighting, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim alternately stood and sat as she watched Poe, top-ranked in
the field of 12, push ahead in points 3-1 after two periods. Even
then, Master Kim's confidence level was low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kay must attack, be aggressive, get inside,'' he said later.
``The other girl is tall, with long legs. Kay gave her too much
space.''
</P>
<P>
   During the break before the final period, Poe looked up toward
the first row. Master Kim shouted instructions and Esther
demonstrated a technique known as the trap that they wanted her to
apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miscommunication,'' Master Kim said. ``I think there were some
mixed signals.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Poe says she absorbed their advice. However, as
the period began, it was the Dane who attacked, earning two quick
points. She broke the tie inside the last minute with two more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play my normal game,'' Poe said. ``I was playing a
safe game. I was feeling a little apprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim, in tears, had rushed backstage to console Poe. They hugged.
Kim told her, ``Good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Poe, meeting the media, was dry-eyed until a question came about
her family and supporters in attendance. She began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Kim is normally the incessant talker. This time, as her father
waited with a reporter, she rushed past, waving a hand and
muttering, ``I don't want to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
