r s BC-OLY-TAYLOR0927-COX     09-26 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TAYLOR0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Angelo Taylor hopes to live his dream of a gold medal
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - Kicking back, alone and with time on his hands, Angelo
Taylor runs the race over and over in his head. Never the whole
jaunt around the red rubber of the Olympic Stadium track. Just
snippets.
</P>
<P>
   He's out front. Always, first across the finish line _ taking
home gold in the 400-meter hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I never visualize catching anybody or holding them off,''
Taylor said. ``It's just me in front, like I'm actually running.
I'm not seeing who is behind me. I'm coming off that last hurdle
and sprinting for home.''
</P>
<P>
   If he can live out his dream today in the 400 hurdle final,
Taylor would succeed his former Georgia Tech training partner
Derrick Adkins as Olympic champion and follow old Southwest DeKalb
(Ga.) High School teammate Terrence Trammell to the medal podium.
Trammell, 21, captured the silver in the 110 hurdles Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor comes to the final a slight favorite with a world-leading
time of 47.62 seconds, but he has a definite rival in Llewellyn
Herbert, who has a best of 47.93. The South African hurdler beat
Taylor in three head-to-head races leading up to the Games. In
Taylor's favor, he won the season's marquee invitational meet in
Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to capitalize off of my mistakes,'' Taylor said.
``I've been leading a race, I'll make a mistake and he's passed me.
He's strong, no doubt. He runs a smooth race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to run clean over the hurdles. If I run clean, he
can't beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the early round races here, Herbert, who has a Southern
California look with the blond hair and wrap-around sunglasses, has
steadfastly avoided being drawn into a war of words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just see in the finals,'' Herbert said, asked about his
rivalry with Taylor. ``I'm not talking about anybody now.''
</P>
<P>
   The two matched up in the same semifinal heat Monday, with
Herbert finishing just slightly in front. Obviously, both held a
back for the final. What could work in Taylor's favor is his knack
for being able to make adjustment during the rounds of major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   The 400-meter sprint over 10 hurdles takes tremendous stamina,
alone. But it's magnified when rather than a single race, you have
three hard races over four days as is the case at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like having to run the two rounds before the final because I
can adjust to the track,'' Taylor said. ``That's to my advantage. I
haven't had a clean race (over the hurdles) in Europe all year. But
in the final at the Olympic trials I did, because I had a chance to
run on the same track for three days and make the adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my strength, I can run three straight days fast. Some
guys would prefer one race and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was a multi-event track star at Southwest DeKalb, along
with playing basketball and football. The summer of `96 he didn't
take in the Games, because he was in Houston competing in the
Junior Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   At the Junior Olympics, he anchored a 1,600-meter relay team
from the East Atlanta Track Cub that set a world record. Also on
the team was Tucker High's Dwight Phillips, Taylor's roommate here
who's in the long jump finals Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since `96, it's been my goal to win the gold medal,'' Taylor
said. ``It's real important to me. I want to go out there and run a
fast time. My goal is definitely a gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
