<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK0927-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones ready to get back on the track
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY - After a couple turbulent days, hounded by a drug
scandal involving her husband, it's understandable if Marion Jones
is eager to get back to business on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Only it won't be a carefree day at the Bondi Beach.
</P>
<P>
   As the track and field competition resumes today, the
24-year-old Jones shoulders her busiest single workload a
first-round sprint at 200 meters in the morning, followed by a
second-round heat in the evening, and then an hour later qualifying
in the long jump. None of this preliminary stuff, though, figures
to pose an immediate threat advancing towards her quest to win five
gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   But with NBC scrambling for ratings, Jones' return couldn't have
come sooner for network brass who've lucked into a soap-opera of
sorts. Since she sprinted off with gold in the 100 meters, an
international scandal has broken out amid allegations U.S. track
officials covered up a positive drug test by her husband,
shot-putter C.J. Hunter. By the couple's side at a Tuesday press
conference stood prominent defense attorney Johnnie Cochrane Jr., a
family friend who will represent Hunter against the doping charges.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to be left alone to prepare for four remaining Olympic
events, Jones said, ``This has been a very difficult last couple of
days for C.J. and I, and I am here pretty much to show my complete
support for my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The network figures to break away long enough from the Jones
story to replay the men's 400 hurdles and women's 100 hurdles,
where several local athletes have a shot at gold including
Southwest DeKalb product Angelo Taylor in the men's hurdles.
Georgia Tech assistant coach Chris Huffins begins first-day
competition in the men's decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   The day's only other final has ``The Great Dane,'' world
record-holder Wilson Kipketer, favored for gold in the 800 meters.
This is the Olympic debut for Kipketer, who a Kenyan who hadn't
completed Danish citizenship requirements in time to run in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones, the only real intrigue on the track is whether she
can hit a qualifying mark early in the long jump and allow herself
to conserve some energy. The long jump final in two days, coupled
with both relays, loom far more challenging than the 200 sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Jones isn't a polished a long jumper. At last year's World
Championships, she won the long-jump bronze medal and then suffered
an injury in the 200 that knocked her out of the competition. She
arrives at the Games ranked third in the world, with a best of 23
feet, 1/2 inch.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta silver medalist Fiona May of Italy and Tatyana Kotova of
Russia are favored ahead of Jones. Another intriguing challenger is
Heike Drechsler, gold medalist in Barcelona and silver in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I decide to jump the pressure is going to be there
simply because I've had some problems in the past,'' Jones said.
``What I have been hearing from some of my biggest supporters is
really all it takes is one big jump, one big jump, and the
competition could be over. So that's what I am hoping.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
