<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-DETRACTORS     09-26 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-DETRACTORS-ART-(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY'S FAME A TWO-EDGED SWORD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Photo NYT
21 has been sent. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Being first lady isn't a job, Hillary Rodham Clinton
said early this year in Manhattan, ``It's a role.''
</P>
<P>
   While making her one of the most celebrated women in the world,
her performance in that role has driven nearly a decade of
dinner-table speculation about the scale of her ambition (Does she
want to be president?) and the state of her marriage (Why does she
stay with him?).
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Rorschach test,'' she has said, for what Americans are
struggling with in their working and married lives. A political
cartoon in the wake of the O.J. Simpson murder trial _ one of
thousands that Clinton has inspired _ captured her ubiquity in pop
culture as it lampooned her peculiar gift for making people
suspicious: ``More bad news. The bloody glove fits Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Her fame is a two-edged sword, allowing her into a political
arena where no first lady has dared go before, but where many of
the people do not like her. She is the first spouse of a president
to have a law degree, to deride the baking of cookies, to testify
before a grand jury and to try to use her fame as a springboard to
elective federal office.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her role as first lady _ a protean performance veering from
secretive boss of a failed health care plan to self-effacing
advocate for children, from suspect in an Arkansas land deal to
victim in America's most famous sex scandal _ has created a
potential roadblock to her winning a seat in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   One of three New Yorkers has an unfavorable opinion of her.
Nationally, four of 10 Americans disapprove. Her Republican
opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, is building much of his campaign around
these negative ratings, in the hope that they will grow. His
television advertisements end with the refrain, ``You just can't
trust her.'' In a national fund-raising letter, Lazio said he could
sum up why Americans should send him money in six words: ``I'm
running against Hillary Rodham Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The eagerness of non-New Yorkers to spend money to keep Clinton
out of Congress is a reason the New York Senate race is shaping up
as the most expensive in history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined comment for this article, but a campaign
strategist acknowledged that voter disapproval was ``out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters have been annoyed by her move to New York. They have
faulted what they say is her Hillary-knows-best tone. Some suspect
that calculated ambition kept her in the White House during the
scandal involving an intern, as she stuck with a philanderer so she
could run for the Senate. Others are taken aback by her willingness
to endure the gossip about her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's strategy for dealing with her negative ratings has
been to try to grind them into dust. ``These are things you can
overcome by doing, by doing the work,'' said Mark Penn, her
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   In 18 months, Clinton has traveled to every county in the state,
paid extraordinarily attention to local concerns and explained her
family-friendly policies in sometimes numbing detail.
</P>
<P>
   The grinding process helps explain why a race that seems so
compelling from a distance can sometimes be so soporific when
viewed up close, as Clinton instructs her supporters on the fine
points of milk prices, pediatric procedures and upstate airfares.
The strategy, though, appears to be working.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Clinton signaled her interest in the Senate early
last year, polls showed the percentage of Americans with a negative
opinion of her jumped from the low 20s, where her unfavorable
numbers had fallen during the Lewinsky scandal, to nearly 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those negative ratings have since declined in New York, although
not nationally. For most of this year, about a third of registered
voters in the state have said they have an unfavorable opinion of
her, while less than half view her positively, according to several
New York/Times/CBS polls. With the election six weeks away, about
one-third of those planning to vote for Lazio say they support him
because he is not she.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton opened a 9-point lead over Lazio, according to a
Times/CBS poll conducted in the days immediately after their debate
in Buffalo in mid-September, although other polls have shown them
to be more evenly matched. All the polls showed that she has
narrowed a gap among suburban voters, while apparently cutting into
one of the surprise anomalies of her candidacy _ a decidedly chilly
reception among white women. Lazio held a commanding lead in June
among white women. According to The Times/CBS poll, that lead had
slipped by last week, but remained at 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   As Election Day nears, many New Yorkers, especially undecided
voters who have paid little attention to the race, are being forced
to re-examine what, if anything, irritates them about Clinton, and
to decide whether they are irritated enough to vote for Lazio. He
remains a relative unknown to more than a third of voters and his
negative ratings have risen sharply, to 28 percent from 10 percent
since June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to like her, but I can't,'' Dr. Barbara Barnett, an
emergency room physician with two children, told seven women in her
book club on the night of the first Clinton-Lazio debate. ``I lost
respect for her when she stood by him during Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate in Buffalo was actually on the air as the book club
convened, but the television was off in the Westchester County home
of Mary Ushay. The women would catch highlights later, and several
of them would judge that Clinton had won it handily and that Lazio
had come across as a bully.
</P>
<P>
   The juicy debate in Ushay's living room in Eastchester had
little to do with the policies, campaign appearances or TV
advertisements of candidate Clinton. Nor did it deal with Lazio,
other than to wonder who he is and why he's running.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the women, as they acknowledged to a reporter who sat
with them, obsessed on a first lady who was more soap-opera
character than Senate aspirant. The book-club members, all white,
married, middle-class residents of Westchester County, said their
lives were much too busy to pay careful attention to Clinton's
campaign. The four Democrats, three Republicans and one noncitizen
said they routinely tossed her fliers in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   What intrigued them, instead, was the woman who stumbled as
``co-president'' when she took command of health-care reform, who
steeled her way through Whitewater, who seethed about ``a vast
right-wing conspiracy'' before her husband admitted his affair.
</P>
<P>
   The book readers from Westchester (the week's book was Barbara
Kingsolver's ``The Poisonwood Bible,'' one of Clinton's favorites)
have been watching, wondering and arguing about her since rumors
about the president's affairs first came out.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insinuated herself into their lives with her 1992
appearance on ``60 Minutes,'' when Bill Clinton denied an affair
with Gennifer Flowers (he later admitted it under oath) and she
said, ``You know I'm not sitting here, some little woman standing
by my man like Tammy Wynette.''
</P>
<P>
   They remembered, too, how cold her body language seemed around
the president during the impeachment fight. They had been amazed
that her marriage survived and felt sorry for daughter Chelsea. But
when Clinton announced last year she was running for the Senate and
moving to Westchester, the women said they felt used and
manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent her moving here,'' said Diane Cohen, 43, a homemaker
from Pelham, the mother of two and a Republican. ``My guess is the
minute she loses, if she loses, she'll be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ushay, the host, a mother of three and a Democrat, said that
Clinton might do a lot of good for New York. Echoing the other
women in the room, all of them mothers, she said Clinton knew more
about children's issues and would probably do more for families
than Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a junior senator from New York having an
incredible in with someone who might be president,'' said Ushay,
41. ``And yet, I don't want her to be my senator. She has so much
baggage. She must have known what people would be talking about.
Yet she still ran. I think she thinks a lot of herself.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of two Republicans in the room, all the women
said that Clinton could win their vote _ but that it would not be
enthusiastic or without regret. They were finding it all but
impossible, they said, to separate the soap-opera character of
eight years from the Senate candidate of the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just resent that she wasn't strong enough to leave him and
go out on her own,'' said Barnett, 37, the emergency room physician
and a Republican who described herself as undecided. ``We finally
had the opportunity to have a strong first lady. But she used her
marriage for personal gain. I can't get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   A half block from the White House, Penn, the pollster and one of
Clinton's strategists, sat in his second-floor office on
Pennsylvania Avenue and listened to a summary of what the eight New
York women had agonized about.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't surprised. He has heard much the same thing before,
from his own polls and from focus groups. Carpetbagger. Pushy
do-gooder. So hungry for power that she put up with a bad marriage.
For Penn, these negative ratings are yesterday's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to erase those concerns,'' he said. ``Voters
are going to balance them against how hard she has worked, what she
stands for and what they think she'll do for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn takes credit for devising Clinton's
grind-the-negatives-to-dust strategy. ``No one has followed this
problem, or issue, more than I have day and night for a year and a
half,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy for Clinton is an updated, New York model of a
product the pollster has been selling for years to Clinton's
husband. A focus on small issues (school uniforms, emergency phone
numbers, V-chips) helped President Clinton pull out of a public
opinion nose-dive during his first term. It also helped him to hang
on to his job through the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   On his desk, Penn had poll results from the New York Senate
debate. The results, like those of several polls, showed Clinton
winning among women, many of whom said they were put off by Lazio's
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every woman had seen the debate,'' he said, ``the rest of
the campaign would effectively be canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was on track, Penn said, in her slow and deliberate
transformation from first lady icon to credible New York candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incredible standard that Hillary has to meet that
no one else has to meet,'' he said. ``She is making steady
progress. The average New Yorker has really got a chance to see who
she is and not who they thought she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the time that Clinton has spent campaigning in the
state, Penn said, there is now a ``a very big difference between
the New York Hillary and the national Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``national Hillary,'' however, who is the household
name. That's the woman who rubs four out of 10 Americans the wrong
way. And she is the money machine behind the New York Senate race,
both for herself and her adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   She has raised more than $22 million, about 60 percent of it
from outside New York, while enabling her adversaries to collect
$39 million, much from of it from out-of-state Clinton haters.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani raised $23.3 million before he quit the race
in May, and Lazio has since collected $15.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   None of this counts millions in soft money collected by
political parties, of which the Democrats have spent at least $5
million praising Clinton and attacking her opponents. Lazio has not
collected soft money but advocacy groups and political committees,
many of them using money raised outside New York, have bought TV
commercials to help him. Last weekend, both campaigns struck an
agreement to stop using unregulated campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Hillary money bubbles up in places like Mobile, Ala., where
in early September Lazio arrived by chartered jet for a
$500-a-plate shrimp-and-grits breakfast. It was a ``hard money''
event, meaning that it collected donations of up to $2,000 from
individuals, money that can be spent directly on Lazio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a spiral staircase in a handsome Greek Revival home
with four white columns out front, Lazio spoke to 90 people for
about five minutes and received $45,000 in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Lazio nipped in and out of Mobile, the local
newspaper, The Mobile Register, ran an editorial cartoon that
explained the metaphysics of the breakfast. On the right side of
the cartoon stood Clinton, with a big smile on her face and her
body drawn in the shape of a pudgy punching bag. A sign above her
head said, ``$500 a pop.''
</P>
<P>
   A man with ``NY'' on his back and boxing gloves on his hands
said to a fellow pugilist from Alabama, ``Be my guest, my
distinguished Southern friend.'' The Alabamian replied, ``After
you, my noble brother from the North.'' A tiny elephant cartoon
exclaimed, ``Republican unity, thy name is Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's applause line in his brief speech came when he promised
to ``bring the Clinton era to an end.'' That was according to
several people inside the room. The event was closed to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But after Lazio left the house, in pursuit of more anti-Hillary
money in Louisiana and Texas, four Alabama Republicans, three men
and a woman, stayed behind to elaborate on what it is about Clinton
that's worth sending money to New York to stop.
</P>
<P>
   For David A. Bagwell, 54, a Mobile lawyer who has a son in
college and who said that for him ``$500 is a lot of money,'' the
irritation started with health care in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was it we know what is right and we'll tell you what
is best, it was we are going to do this in secret because you
aren't smart enough to understand,'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Hooks, 53, whose husband owns a tugboat company in
Mobile, said she saw through Clinton the first time she saw her on
``60 Minutes'' in 1992. Hooks remembers thinking that this ``is a
woman who wants power, who wants control, who wants to be on the
national stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The four Republicans said they expected and feared that Clinton
was using the Senate race in New York as a steppingstone for a run
at the presidency. They had had their fill of Bill Clinton, they
said, and the prospect of his wife in the White House made them
furious.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Peebles, a real estate agent from Mobile, said that New
Yorkers might not be able to fathom the depth of conservative
Southern antipathy for the Clintons. He explained that many
Southerners see the president as a scalawag, someone who has
betrayed the values and traditions of the South. The president's
wife, Peebles said, has quite literally become a carpetbagger,
albeit in the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marriage of a scalawag and a carpetbagger,'' Peebles said.
``You cannot be more objectionable in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Objections to Clinton, of course, are not confined to the South.
For years, polls have shown that a broad slice of the American
public cannot abide her, often for reasons that people have trouble
putting into words.
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton became a Senate candidate, the White House
strategy for knocking down her negative ratings was to encourage
her to retreat to the shadows of public attention.
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, the longtime political adviser to the Clintons,
said the rule of thumb was, the less visible she was, the better
her numbers were in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That rule of thumb was discovered halfway through the first
term, when Clinton's troubles with Whitewater and health care had
made her an anchor on her husband's presidency. In some polls, she
was less popular than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been difficult for Hillary to fit into the perceptions
and expectations of the role of first lady,'' said the Rev. Donald
G. Jones, her friend and her mentor when she was growing up in
Chicago. ``The office of first lady is one of the most unevolved.
Perceptions people have of it are pretty much fixed by Barbara
Bush, Nancy Reagan, Jackie Kennedy, by people who minded their own
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a professor of ethics at Drew University in Madison,
N.J., said Clinton would be relieved to shed ``the baggage that she
carried around as first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the persistent percentage of Americans who view Clinton
negatively, Carville said they could no more keep her out of the
Senate than they could keep her husband out of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can win easy with a third of the voters hating her,''
Carville said, warming to the question. ``If she wins this thing,
they'll be jumping off bridges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
