<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-OUTLOOK-NYT     09-26 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TRIES TO KEEP BUSINESS AS USUAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (With MICROSOFT-TRIAL, MICROSOFT-COURT) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Microsoft has long maintained that the
government antitrust case would do nothing to alter its business
practices or long-term strategy. And Tuesday, as it won at least a
procedural victory in the case, the company had another opportunity
to make its point.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Microsoft has accelerated a range of business
and technical initiatives, continuing its strategy of adding
software applications to its operating systems _ like the browser
that brought on the antitrust scrutiny _ and moving into new
computing markets ranging from the largest mainframes to the video
game business.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, at a long-planned event, Microsoft and a group of
industry partners unveiled operating system software intended to
take the world's largest software publisher into the very high end
of the corporate computing market. And Microsoft executives took
the opportunity to reiterate that the antitrust suit would have no
effect on the company's aggressive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the Supreme Court decision on Tuesday not to take
a direct appeal of the antitrust ruling, leaving it in the hands of
the court of appeals, Steven Ballmer, Microsoft's president, said:
``I'm happy to get on with the legal process. This is really a
positive procedural step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market on Tuesday initially reacted positively to the
decision as well. The company's stock jumped up as much as 5
percent before settling back to close at $62.69, up 2.35 percent
for the day, but still near the company's 52-week low of $60.38.
</P>
<P>
   While most legal experts saw the Supreme Court's decision, which
could extend the legal process by as much as a year, as a qualified
victory for Microsoft, some noted that its effect might not be
entirely positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly a victory for Microsoft,'' said David Yoffie,
a Harvard Business School professor, ``because the appeals court
has historically been more favorable to Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and other analysts added that the decision could prolong
the period of uncertainty that the company faces leading to
declining employee morale and holding down the company's stock
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just prolongs the agony,'' said George Colony, president
of Forrester Research, a Cambridge, Mass., computer consulting
firm. ``I think they should get it over fast. I'd want
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever agony Microsoft might be feeling, two and a half years
after the antitrust case was brought, it is nonetheless pushing
ahead on several fronts to move into new markets and consolidate
existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   In its most ambitious strategic shift since December 1995, when
it decided to ``embrace and extend'' the Internet market, the
company embarked in July on an ambitious strategy called .Net,
essentially creating a set of programs resembling an operating
system that will live on the Internet rather than on individual
desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Then this fall the company firmed up plans to try to compete
with videogame giants Nintendo, Sega and Sony, previewing its first
Microsoft-branded computer system, the X-box, to be sold at the end
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Microsoft added the final piece of its computing
strategy, initially sketched out by the company's former chief
technology officer, Nathan Myhrvold, almost a decade ago: to
produce operating systems stretching from the smallest handheld
computers to the most powerful supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's move into the market for large corporate computer
systems, bringing it into even sharper competition with companies
like Sun Microsystems and Oracle, is viewed as a significant shift
by analysts, who said it would require a fundamental change in
Microsoft's corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now Microsoft's NT operating system has never made it
into the largest enterprises,'' Colony said. ``Microsoft loved to
throw software over the corporate wall and checks came back from
the other side, but they never crossed over the wall to get their
hands dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   That business approach has been why the largest computer users
such as companies like J.P. Morgan have largely ignored Microsoft's
corporate computing efforts until now.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer said this so-called enterprise portion of Microsoft's
business already represented about $4 billion of the company's
annual revenue. Ballmer, who took over from Bill Gates as
Microsoft's chief executive earlier this year said Gates, who
remains chairman, has shifted his focus to the company's technology
strategy and has taken the title of chief software architect.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft's desire for new frontiers appears to be
unabated, several industry executives cautioned that even with its
dominance of operating systems and office software, the company was
bumping up against real limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately there are only a small number of A teams at
Microsoft by definition,'' said Yoffie, ``and their ability to
conquer all areas of computing is going to be difficult or
impossible when they are fighting against other A teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Other executives said that the company's Achilles heel may be
that it is trying to accomplish too much, too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What IBM had accomplished in 30 years Microsoft has taken on
in just six,'' said Andrew Heller, a former IBM executive and
computer designer. ``They haven't executed with the same level of
control and process IBM developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said its top-of-the-line Windows 2000 Datacenter
operating system was now available from 12 computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also introduced eight new server software programs
intended for electronic commerce and large system computing
applications. These programs are at the heart of the company's .Net
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ballmer was generally bullish on the company's new push
into the very highest part of the computer business, he
acknowledged that there remain some industry sectors where
Microsoft will have a tough time displacing its entrenched Unix
competitors such as Sun and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have quite an uphill battle in the next
generation telecommunications sector,'' he said. Because there has
been a strong tradition of Unix in the telecommunications network
market, which is one of the largest users of high end computers, it
will be difficult for Microsoft to break in to that market, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
