<HEADLINE>
SPRINT SEARCHES FOR JOBS FOR 300 WHOSE POSITIONS ARE BEING
ELIMINATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE KING  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Sprint Corp. division based in Houston will eliminate 300
positions that no longer fit the company's ``strategic direction,''
a spokeswoman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The computer help-desk employees who work with clients of
Sprint's Enterprise Network Services Group, formerly Sprint
Paranet, will be moved into other jobs within Sprint or hired by
the client company they support, said Laura Lisec, a Sprint
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The ENS group employs about 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Lisec said the company had found new jobs for half the employees
and was looking for jobs for the others.
</P>
<P>
   A transition period will prevent any of the employees from being
out of work, Lisec said. But where jobs have been identified,
employees will be moved as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find them positions,'' Lisec said.
</P>
<P>
   She did not know if displaced employees would be offered jobs in
the city of their existing jobs. But she said every effort would be
made to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint acquired Paranet Inc. for $375 million in 1997 as a
ticket into the computer network management business. Paranet
helped companies integrate complicated voice and data networks. ENS
performs a similar function.
</P>
<P>
   But Lisec said Sprint wanted to back away from the support piece
of the business. The company is doing away with computer help-desk
jobs at client sites across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just basically because it doesn't fit with our strategic
direction, and it's not a part of the business that we consider to
be growing,'' Lisec said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Sprint had not determined how the support duties would
be handled when the positions are eliminated. But the company could
probably cut costs by outsourcing the work, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   News of the cuts Tuesday came the same day Sprint's FON stock
hit a 12-month low of $24.31. The stock closed at $25. Sprint's PCS
stock, which tracks the Westwood company's wireless business,
closed at $31.50.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of Sprint's merger plans with WorldCom Inc., the
FON stock spiked at $75.94. But since the merger was called off in
July, the stock price has been low.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sprint warned investors that its third-quarter profit
would be less than expected. Company officials said they expected
earnings of 45 cents to 47 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   One industry source said the job cuts could be a reflection of
that news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, when a company misses earnings, they look for places
to cut,'' he said. ``Economically, 300 jobs is not a big deal. But
it's a start in something.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Schaaf, senior analyst with Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., said she had not heard about the job cuts at ENS,
but she speculated that they might offer a window into the
company's future sans WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be part of a bigger plan, and I don't know what
the bigger plan is,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
