r f BC-SECURE-HACKERS-KAN &LR;      09-26 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURE-HACKERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI TRACKS IMPACT OF CYBER CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Computer hackers, computer espionage,
telephone fraud and other computer crimes cost area companies more
than $20 million in 1999, according to an FBI survey released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first survey of its kind of metropolitan area companies,
corporate computer security specialists told the FBI that hackers
stole proprietary information, sabotaged systems and vandalized Web
sites. Three companies said they had each lost more than $5 million
to computer hacking or fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Eight companies said attacks on their systems resulted in the
theft of proprietary information.
</P>
<P>
   The results were based on anonymous surveys completed by 189
Kansas City area companies earlier this year. More than one in four
of those companies said their computer systems had been hacked in
the prior 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a lot of people think of security, it's guns, gates and
guards,'' said Scott Williams, supervisory special agent for the
FBI's Kansas City cyber crimes office. ``People need to be thinking
that it's guns, gates, guards and computers.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI office in Kansas City has about 20 open computer crime
cases, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, the number of hack attacks or the financial
loss that caught Williams off guard. More troubling, he said, was
that 11.8 percent of the 189 companies did not know whether their
computer systems had been attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like not locking the doors on your store,'' Williams
said. ``You have to take the same precautions in the cyber world.
Many of us have come to rely on computer equipment to the degree
that we've forgotten how to handle things manually.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey results were tabulated by Central Missouri State
University.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was released as the FBI office in Kansas City met
with 95 computer security professionals to establish a local
chapter of InfraGard, an FBI-sponsored networking group designed to
allow computer professionals to meet and discuss security problems.
The group was formed in Cleveland, and chapters are operating in
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said large companies seemed to be willing to accept
large computer-related losses. He said, however, that a large
number of smaller companies in the Kansas City survey reported that
they had lost up to $100,000. Those companies do not have the
resources to handle that type of loss, or deal with hackers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the ones we have to protect,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   An executive with Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. gave a more
personal view at the session.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dolci, head of security for KCP&AMP;L, said the utility
formerly had workers open and close switches controlling the power
grid. Those switches now are controlled by computer. And those
computers are regularly under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Hackers at ``5,000 different (Internet) sites come at KCP&AMP;L
every month,'' using automated scans to try to break into the
utility's computers, Dolci said. ``It's just constant, 24 hours a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolci said KCP&AMP;L had joined InfraGard, and he urged other
companies to join.
</P>
<P>
   David Black, manager of research and development for Kansas
City-based eSecurityOnline.com, called the group ``definitely a
must.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll know someone in that group who is going to have the
same problem as you, and you can compare notes,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said it was difficult to determine how much Kansas City
companies had lost to computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than $20 million a year; beyond that it's difficult
to come up with a figure,'' Williams said. ``It's in the tens of
millions in the KC area alone.''
</P>
<P>
   One company the FBI works with reports that hackers hit its
computer system 100,000 times every month.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide survey earlier this year by the Computer Security
Institute and the FBI found that 643 companies reported losing $265
million to computer hackers in 1999. The number has been escalating
each year for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents of sabotage tripled in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 of the 189 companies in the Kansas City survey said
their computer systems had been hacked, and more than a third of
those said their systems had been hacked six or more times in the
last 12 months. The companies said the attacks came both from
outside and inside the company.
</P>
<P>
   More than 75 percent of the companies that responded to the
survey said they were concerned that their computer systems would
be hacked.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies said they had not reported computer attacks to
law enforcement agencies, citing reasons ranging from bad publicity
to not being aware that the federal agency would be interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intrusions are rarely reported; people are very afraid of
negative publicity,'' said Stan Paulson, an FBI intelligence
analyst from Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Central Missouri State will repeat the survey in
February, said Richard D. Sluder, a professor and director of
special projects for the College of Education and Human Services at
the university.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
