r a BC-OLYMPICS-SOFTBALL-KAN     09-26 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-SOFTBALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER, DAUGHTER SHARE OLYMPIC GOLDEN MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE DeARMOND  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKTOWN, Australia _ Moments after the U.S. softball team
clinched an Olympic gold medal with a 2-1 victory over Japan, the
Australian heavens opened up and turned the field and grounds into
a sea of mud.
</P>
<P>
   Slogging through it, to the edge of the right-field seats, U.S.
left fielder Christie Ambrosi blew a kiss to her mother, Mimi, and
yelled, ``I love you!''
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Ambrosi had given so much to see this moment in person: her
youngest daughter winning an Olympic gold medal. Mimi had sold her
house in Overland Park, Kan., to finance the trip for herself and
her sister, Carol Briant.
</P>
<P>
   As the rain fell, so did tears of joy down Mimi Ambrosi's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give up my life for this moment,'' she said Tuesday as
Christie mounted the medal podium with the rest of her teammates.
``She is so special. We've both come so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Ambrosi was speaking in terms of time and near tragedy, not
the miles between Kansas City, Mo., and the land Down Under. While
an athlete at Blue Valley Northwest High School, Christie Ambrosi
was so upset by circumstances that led to her parents' separation
and later divorce that she was hospitalized for depression.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, however, mother and daughter shared the
sweetness, no matter how hard the wind blew or the rain fell.
</P>
<P>
   In left field, Ambrosi had tracked down a line drive off the bat
of Japan's designated hitter, Haruka Saito, to open the game,
making a running catch.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there was the cocklebur for Ambrosi of having been allowed
to play only defense the last two games of the Olympic tournament,
replaced in the batting order by designated hitter Michele Smith.
But that dissolved with the victory.
</P>
<P>
   And afterward, daughter and mother explained how deep their bond
ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be here if it wasn't for my mom,'' Christie said.
``With everything that we've been through together, she's an
inspiration to me. I just get choked up even thinking about my
mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Ambrosi, who sat in the front of the American cheering
section, said: ``I live for my kids. I've got three kids, and this
is my baby. She has done it all herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is 30; my other daughter is 27. Christie's 23. I have a
granddaughter that's 2 and one on the way. I've got everything.''
</P>
<P>
   What Mimi Ambrosi has back in Overland Park now is a one-bedroom
apartment. She was unable to arrange a loan to take the trip, so
she decided to sell her home.
</P>
<P>
   She had fixed it up that just the way she wanted it, for her
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great house,'' she said. ``I made it great. I did
everything. I did floors, walls. I knocked down walls. I made a
beautiful home.''
</P>
<P>
   A house, however, was nothing compared with where her heart told
her she had to be this September. Christie, on tour with the U.S.
team all summer, was not supposed to know about the sacrifice her
mother made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow it got out,'' Mimi said. ``She found out and was very
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Christie: ``I yelled at her.''
</P>
<P>
   What kind of a woman sells her house so she can afford to watch
a softball tournament?
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom,'' Ambrosi crowed. ``A great parent, a wonderful parent
who would do anything for her children.''
</P>
<P>
   The long summer tour was tough enough. But it was made harder by
legal challenges brought by players not selected to the Olympic
team. Sorting that out required two reselections of the team, with
Ambrosi sweating out each.
</P>
<P>
   She wondered whether sacrificing her final year of eligibility
at the University of California at Los Angeles, whether her
mother's sacrifice of her home, could be for naught. Not until
August was the roster final.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that kept me going through the summer was my
mom,'' Ambrosi said.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged being devastated when the U.S. team lost three
straight round-robin games in the Olympic medal-round qualifying.
She was the would-be hero in the third loss, 2-1 to Australia,
having singled in the Americans' run in the top of the 13th inning.
</P>
<P>
   A two-run home run by Australia's Peta Edebone in the bottom of
the inning extended the American losing streak to three games. The
last time the U.S. team had lost three games in a row had been a
1982-83 stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, however, rallied for five straight victories,
getting moral support along the way from the U.S. baseball team,
including manager Tommy Lasorda, and the U.S. women's soccer team,
including stars Mia Hamm and Brandi Chastain. They came to games to
cheer the softball team.
</P>
<P>
   After the gold-medal game, players, relatives and friends
huddled in the lightning and drizzle to make plans for celebrating.
And the Ambrosis talked about this being the third gold medal won
by a Kansas City area athlete at these Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Nott won the first in weightlifting. Maurice Greene won the
second in track. Now it was Christie's turn for gold.
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Ambrosi supplied a final perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``My house-selling was happy,'' she said. ``Who cares I'm in an
apartment? I've got all these great things. Nobody can have this.
</P>
<P>
   ``She threw me a kiss and said, `I love you.' We knew. We
knew.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
