<SLUG> BC-PA-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOP TARGET OF DEMOCRATS IN SENATE APPEARS UNBOWED 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ The Democrats' high-priority targeting of Sen.
Rick Santorum for defeat this year is proving to be an uphill
struggle so far for his challenger, Rep. Ron Klink.
</P>
<P>
   After a divisive primary fight, Klink has had trouble raising
the television money he needs for the expensive Philadelphia and
eastern state markets. These are Democratic strongholds, yet polls
show two-thirds of the voters do not recognize the name of Klink, a
Democrat from western Pennsylvania. But the congressman insists he
will soon have the traction for a homestretch victory.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Santorum, with at least eight times the war chest
of his challenger, has taken to the tube with ease all over the
state for much of this month. His mellow, family-man ads of the
``pop up'' sort seen on music cable channels are designed to take
the bite off his early political image as a House iconoclast and
Newt Gingrich acolyte.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got this multimillion-dollar fog machine out there making
him look like a Kennedy Democrat,'' complains Klink, a four-term
House member from the steel mill region near Pittsburgh who has
struggled to heal the wounds from his primary victory. ``The most
frustrating thing for me is the money,'' he admits while buoyed
that Senate Democrats who find Santorum personally abrasive have
begun lending a fund-raising hand in the hope of cutting the
Republicans' 54-to-46 advantage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a roll of 30,000 donors, Santorum is busy raising even
more television money as a campaign ``imperative'' now that his
double-digit polling lead shows some possible wavering. His
treasury exceeded $10 million even as Klink, a former television
news reporter, labored for his first $1 million after taking a
mortgage on his home to win the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron Klink is running the Democrats' prepackaged campaign that
we're all right-wing Gingrich nuts,'' Santorum complained,
insisting he had spent the past six years proving otherwise in a
mix of intense constituent services and carefully chosen causes,
like his prominent sponsorship of a welfare overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more Rick Santorum in that legislation than anybody
else in the House or Senate,'' said Santorum, a 42-year-old senator
who had a former welfare mother introduce him at a Republican
dinner here and tell of her new career as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   For all the underdog hobbles of 49-year-old Klink, his spirits
are rising after a parched summer of fund-raising. His perceived
statewide strength is that like Santorum, he is anti-abortion and
anti-gun control. But this has not served him well in seeking the
donations of liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But an emergency infusion of $800,000 from the Senate Democratic
campaign committee in Washington is buying him his first two weeks
of television commercial time, with more aid likely. ``The odds are
shortening,'' a Senate Democratic worker insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope Vice President Al Gore's rise in popularity will
energize the Democrats' 500,000-voter edge in state registration
and propel Klink toward an upset. But, as a House member, Santorum
showed strong resistance to the coat-tail effect in 1992 when his
heavily Democratic district voted only 30 percent for President
George Bush while Santorum was re-elected by 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by Gore's surge in this swing state, Klink maintains
he will win because his party has the more popular positions on the
most urgent issues. But state analysts say there is no sign yet
that Klink is scoring significantly with his opposition to
Santorum's proposals to privatize some Social Security investment
and to use health maintenance organizations in dealing with the
prescription drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats grossly underestimated what a good politician
Rick Santorum is,'' said Jennifer Duffy, the Senate editor for the
Cook Political Report, a Washington newsletter that tracks
campaigns. ``He's taken a solid step toward the center,'' said
Duffy, referring to what Democrats denounce as Santorum wiles.
</P>
<P>
   These include the senator's slight moderation on gun control in
accepting trigger locks, despite his 100 percent rating from the
National Rifle Association. Democrats also underline as cynical the
quiet demeanor of Santorum, in contrast to his signature brashness,
when President Clinton's impeachment trial proved unpopular with
the public.
</P>
<P>
   In their first debate, Klink pressed the fact that Santorum once
voted for a resolution that included raising the retirement age to
70. The senator said this was part of a larger omnibus package to
control entitlement programs and that he had since opposed any age
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klink is running as a little Gore and his message is getting
sharper, more populist,'' said G. Terry Madonna, the political
science chairman at Millersville University in Lancaster, who
conducts the Keystone Poll. ``The polls have been tightening, but
Klink still needs to get his name recognition much higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman accuses the senator of having tried to head off
this contest by letting three of his top staff aides work for the
Republican challenger two years ago in Klink's re-election campaign
for the House. The senator scoffs at this as routine politicking
and questions whether ``there's some personal vendetta'' driving
the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   There seems no love lost between the two politicians, and both
are proven battlers who upset incumbents with aggressive campaigns
in their first campaigns for House seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a productive six years and has given me a lot of
pride and confidence,'' Santorum said, sounding far from the
vulnerable incumbent at the top of the Democrats' target list.
``We've earned another six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Klink sounds no less confident. ``People are focusing now on the
issues, and we're in this ballgame,'' he maintains with his old
anchorman timbre. ``Santorum has taken extremely conservative,
far-out positions, and he cannot run away from his record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
