<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIES-SETTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION HOUSES   APPROVE $512 MILLION SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christie's announced on Wednesday that it had approved a $256
million settlement of civil claims that, along with its archrival,
Sotheby's, it cheated buyers and sellers as far back as 1992.
Forty-eight hours earlier, Sotheby's disclosed that its board
approved its half of the $512 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Sotheby's, whose former chairman and majority
shareholder A. Alfred Taubman is paying $156 million of the auction
house's $256 million payment, Christie's said in a written
statement on Wednesday that the auction house together with its
parent company, Christie's International, is coming up with all the
money itself.
</P>
<P>
   While Sotheby's is a publicly traded company, Christie's was
taken private two years ago when it was bought by Francois Pinault,
the French takeover investor, for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both auction houses are able to use $50 million of their
payments in the form of certificates issued to clients toward
future consignments.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's chief executive, Edward J. Dolman, said the
settlement ``will have no impact on our operations,'' yet auction
house experts say that the $256 million is bound to affect its
financial health. In the three years before it went private,
Christie's reported pretax profits of a little more than half of
its $256 million payment.
</P>
<P>
   Andree Corroon, a spokeswoman for Christie's, declined to
comment on where the auction house will get its financing.
</P>
<P>
   The civil class-action lawsuit grew out of a three-year-old
federal antitrust investigation contending that top officials from
the two auction houses colluded on an array of business practices
including fixing the prices it charges buyers and sellers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
