</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTER CONTROVERSY AT TIP OF BIGGER DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ As the shot-putter C. J. Hunter, husband of Marion
Jones, denies that he knowingly took banned substances, the entire
system of drug testing in the United States has come under fire
from the international Olympic hierarchy. These international
officials consider the Americans hypocritical, laggard and
deceptive in their handling of doping cases.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials are firing back in what has become the newest
Olympic sport: verbal skeet shooting. The recrimination has
symbolized the messy state of drug testing internationally and the
lack of trust and cooperation undermining renewed efforts to curb
the widespread use of performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   For years, members of the International Olympic Committee have
suspected that U.S. officials have been covering up positive drug
tests, even as the Americans have criticized the international
committee for its own deficiencies and lack of willpower to catch
cheating athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, the IOC has absorbed a battering from
Congress, the White House, corporate sponsors and the news media on
the issues of corruption in the Salt Lake City bribery scandal and
of its suspect resolve on doping.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a published report here said that Hunter had tested
positive for the steroid nandrolone in July in Oslo, and the IOC
was quick to confirm the story. On Tuesday, the committee said that
Hunter had tested positive four times this summer for the steroid.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who is America's top shot-putter but did not compete
here because of a knee injury, is also the husband of Jones, the
most visible U.S. athlete at these Olympics. She has won a gold at
100 meters and is going for gold in four other track and field
events
</P>
<P>
   The IOC made Hunter's case an issue and sent a harsh message to
U.S. Olympic and track officials: Don't complain about the rest of
the world until you address your own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel, yes, it's OK to criticize,'' said Gerhard Heiberg, an
IOC delegate from Norway. ``At the same time we feel your house is
not in order. We feel you do not tell us the truth what is
happening in the United States. You want us to be open instead of
sweeping everything under the carpet. That has to go for the U.S.
as well. We're a little irritated.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Tuesday, Hunter said that he had not
taken any performance-enhancing steroids. He said nutritional
supplements, which he called improperly labeled and packaged with
quality-control problems, had led to the positive drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes are warned repeatedly not to take nutritional
supplements for this very reason.
</P>
<P>
   The supplements are classified as food and not as a drug, and as
such are not regulated by the Food and Drug Administration.
Steroids, which can improve performance by allowing athletes to
train harder, can legally be sold in supplements even if not
labeled, as long as no medical claim is made, said Dr. Don Catlin,
who operates the Olympic drug-testing laboratory at University of
California in Los Angeles and is a member of the IOC's doping
agency.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympics, if an athlete takes a banned substance, that
athlete can be suspended, even if the substance was ingested
inadvertently. Andreea Raducan was stripped of her gold medal in
the gymnastics' all-around competition after she had tested
positive for a banned stimulant included in a cold medicine given
to her by the Romanian team doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Nandrolone, for which Hunter tested positive, has been easily
detectable for many years. Recently, though, the steroid has been
showing up in a number of positive tests involving high-profile
athletes. Improperly labeled nutritional supplements may have
caused the positive tests, but that does not exonerate the
athletes, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's buyer beware,'' Catlin said. ``If it's in your body, you
take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is why Hunter's positive tests were not revealed
until now. The International Amateur Athletic Federation, which
governs track and field, says Hunter was suspended on Aug. 24, yet
USA Track and Field has yet to make that announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arne Ljungqvist, an IOC delegate from Sweden and the chief
medical officer of track and field's world governing body, has
criticized the U.S. track and field federation for what he called a
failure to report in a timely manner 12 to 15 positive drug tests
in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the criticism of American drug-testing procedures has
come from outside the United States. Dr. Robert S. Voy and Dr. Wade
Exum, the past two medical directors of the USOC, have both
criticized the Olympic committee for what they say is a lack of
resolve in catching drug cheats. Exum has claimed in a lawsuit that
as many as half of the American athletes who have tested positive
have gone unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC has denied the allegation. It will, however, have its
drug testing conducted by an independent agency after these games.
Dick Pound, a member of the IOC executive board and the chairman of
its World Anti-Doping Agency, suggested that if the USOC were
serious, it would have begun independent testing before the Sydney
Olympics, not after.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The public attack on the Americans has caused U.S. officials to
respond with equally caustic remarks. Prince Alexandre de Merode of
Belgium, the IOC's medical director, has said that five American
athletes had been permitted to compete at the 1988 Summer Games in
Seoul after testing positive before those games. Mike Moran, a
spokesman for the USOC, said that all disputed cases had been
investigated at the time and that all athletes in question had been
exonerated. The charge was outrageous, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Masback, chief executive of the U.S. track and field
federation, met with Pound here on Tuesday to express his
displeasure with the way his federation had been portrayed as
behaving improperly in handling doping matters.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Masback said USA Track and Field had
been the first sports federation in the world to conduct
out-of-competition testing and had conducted more tests for more
substances and caught more cheats than any other federation.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said that USA Track and Field was making an honest effort in
a system flawed in many ways: laboratories do not report results
for up to eight weeks and forward insufficient paperwork; tests are
sometimes improperly conducted; organizations do not conduct
follow-up investigations of suspicious tests for months or years;
the science of drug testing does not always withstand legal
scrutiny; the IOC-accredited laboratories rely on various Olympic
bodies for financing, and laboratory directors are reluctant to
testify against the shoddy work of other facilities for fear that
they will lose income from drug-testing referrals.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans cannot be trusted, Masback said, then the
agency created by the International Olympic Committee or track and
field's world governing body should begin administering all drug
tests for the American federation. ``Let them see the frailties of
the system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Masback said that the 12 to 15 tests under discussion had been
conducted at an IOC-accredited lab in Indianapolis. The laboratory
apparently was not simultaneously notifying the various sports
bodies _ the United States and International Olympic Committees and
the international and American track and field federations _ of
positive results, as is required, Masback said.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four athletes were exonerated because when their urine
samples were divided into halves for testing, one half of the
sample tested positive while the other tested negative. A failed
test is not declared unless both the so-called A and B samples test
positive.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The remaining sticking point between USA Track and Field and the
international federation involves confidentiality. The U.S. system
states that an athlete will not be suspended, or his name forwarded
to the IAAF and made public, until after the A and B samples are
tested and a lengthy set of appeals is exhausted. Some appeals have
carried on for four years.
</P>
<P>
   This is too long, according to the IAAF, which suspends athletes
after the A sample is declared positive. The international
federation is also demanding to see test results involving U.S.
athletes who have been cleared by the U.S. federation so that
cover-ups can be detected if they occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
