<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH-SPEED ACCESS VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Softbank Corp., one of the world's largest investors in
Internet-related businesses, is starting a third venture aimed at
increasing access to the Internet at high speeds. IP Revolution,
the new unit, plans to offer the service over fiber optic cables
sometime next year, according to an application filed with
regulators in Tokyo. Two other efforts by Softbank to provide
high-speed Internet services have faltered, in part because of
technical complications. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACTION BY JAPAN REGULATORS
</P>
<P>
   Japanese financial regulators conducted a surprise inspection of
J.P. Morgan, which is to be bought by Chase Manhattan Corp. Morgan
officials said the Securities and Exchange Surveillance Commission,
Japan's securities industry watchdog, was examining records in
Morgan's Tokyo office. The regulators also punished West LB
Securities Pacific Ltd., a unit of Germany's largest state-owned
bank, by temporarily suspending some of its operations in Japan
after uncovering illegal transactions involving subordinated
loans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHIP COMPANY HAS STRONG RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   The British shipping and cruise line Peninsular &AMP; Oriental Steam
Navigation Co. said half-year net income jumped 17 percent, to 151
million pounds, or about $213 million, on strong gains in its ports
unit and shipping joint venture. Sales rose 19 percent, to 1.98
billion pounds, or about $2.79 billion. Full-year profit for the
shipping joint venture, P&AMP;O Nedlloyd, will exceed analysts'
expectations, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT FALLS AT IRISH AIRLINE
</P>
<P>
   The Irish national airline Aer Lingus PLC reported net profits
of 51.9 million euros in 1999, down 30 percent from 74.6 million
euros in 1998, despite a 12 percent increase in revenue to 1.134
billion euros. The company carried 6.5 million passengers in 1999,
an increase of 13 percent. The Irish government is expected to sell
the airline in a public offering early next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE BOARD MEMBER RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Esser, the former chairman of Mannesmann AG, resigned from
the board of the Vodafone Group, the world's largest mobile
telephone operator. Esser had joined the board on an interim basis
after Mannesmann was acquired by Vodafone for $183 billion in the
largest takeover ever. Esser was paid $27 million in severance
pay. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
