<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Antitrust Case Is Sent to Appeals Court
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court handed a tactical victory to Microsoft when it
summarily rejected the government's plea to immediately hear the
appeal of its landmark antitrust case and instead returned the
proceeding to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia. The decision gives Microsoft greater breathing room to
pursue its appeals, relieves the company of any pressure to return
any time soon to the bargaining table and, in the absence of a
settlement, could prolong a final court judgment by a year or
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak Stock Plunges 25 Percent on Sudden Drop in Sales &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co., citing a sudden and as-yet-unexplained sales
decline in every one of its businesses, warned investors that its
third-quarter earnings would be as much as 25 cents a share below
expectations and that, if sales do not pick up, fourth-quarter
earnings might disappoint as well. Kodak said third-quarter revenue
would probably fall short of expectations by $200 million to $300
million. Kodak stock plunged $14.81 a share Tuesday, or 25 percent,
to $44.19, the lowest level in more than six years.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Slump on Kodak
</P>
<P>
   Warning Stocks fell sharply after an earning warnings from
Eastman Kodak worried investors. The Dow Jones industrial average
dropped 176.83 points, or 1.6 percent, to 10,631.32. The Nasdaq
composite index was down 52.12 points, or 1.4 percent, to 3,689.10,
and the Standard and Poor's 500-stock index fell 11.82 points, or
0.8 percent, to 1,427.21.
</P>
<P>
   Insider Trading Curbs to be Eased
</P>
<P>
   A little-noticed Securities and Exchange Commission rule that
goes into effect next month should make it easier for corporate
insiders to sell their companies' stock without running afoul of
insider-trading law. While the new provision could theoretically
affect many of the estimated 16 million Americans who own shares in
the companies they work for, its biggest impact will be on senior
managers eager to unlock the wealth of their stock-and-options
riches without veering into legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer Wants to Sell Hemophilia Drug Directly to Patients
</P>
<P>
   Unable to manufacture enough of a new drug for hemophiliacs,
Bayer Corp. has taken the unusual step of asking patients to apply
directly to the company to receive the drug rather than getting it
from a pharmacy or another distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Steps Taken on Bioengineered Corn
</P>
<P>
   Moving to address safety concerns, agribusiness companies took
steps to limit the chances that bioengineered corn unapproved for
human consumption could end up in food.
</P>
<P>
   3Com Loss Is Less Than Forecast
</P>
<P>
   3Com reported a smaller-than-expected first-quarter loss, citing
a reorganization that included its exit from the analog modem and
network router businesses in the previous quarter. Before 3Com
reported its results, its shares closed at $13.94, down 6 cents. In
after-hours trading, however, 3Com rose more than 15 percent,
climbing as high as $16.06.
</P>
<P>
   Document on Ford Rollover Tests
</P>
<P>
   Ford told its tire suppliers a decade ago not to conduct without
Ford's approval a driving test of the rollover tendencies of sport
utility vehicles and other light trucks, an internal Ford document
shows. But there is disagreement between Ford and its critics over
how the document should be interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC Prepares for Summit Meeting
</P>
<P>
   With oil prices at their highest level in a decade and the
United States and other industrial countries calling for relief,
heads of state and oil ministers from OPEC are to begin a two-day
summit meeting here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's Approves Settlement
</P>
<P>
   Christie's approved a $256 million settlement of civil claims
that, along with its archrival, Sotheby's, it cheated buyers and
sellers as far back as 1992. Sotheby's had already approved its
half of the $512 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Corning Seen in Deal for Pirelli Unit
</P>
<P>
   Corning, the leading supplier of glass fiber, is expected to
announce that it has agreed to acquire the fiber-optic
telecommunications business of Pirelli, the Italian tire and cable
maker, for about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fast Train May Not Rival Air Travel
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is about to roll out its long-delayed $1.7 billion Acela
Express high-speed rail service between New York City and Boston.
But it may not be as competitive with airlines as was first
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Ads on Gun Safety
</P>
<P>
   The Advertising Council and the National Crime Prevention
Council began distributing a public service advertising campaign
this week advocating safe gun storage.
</P>
</TEXT>
