<HEADLINE>
OLYMPICS COVERAGE ON TV FAILS TO DRAW AS MANY VIEWERS AS EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE ROCK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For the last 12 years, Ron Barr has listened
to impassioned sports fans while sitting in front of his radio
microphone. He's the host of ``Sports Byline USA,'' a nationally
syndicated sports call-in show out of San Francisco that is
broadcast in Kansas City on KMBZ-AM.
</P>
<P>
   And he has no doubt what the general reaction has been to this
year's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ho-hum,'' Barr said Tuesday by telephone from California.
``Nobody cares. It's terrible. There used to be an enthusiasm. But
now, the enthusiasm has been replaced by apathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it Olym-pathy.
</P>
<P>
   A convergence of factors _ the time difference (16 hours between
Kansas City and Australia), the September timing, the immediate
Olympic coverage available on the Internet _ have rained down on
network executives at NBC. The ensuing shower could wash out the TV
ratings, which so far are the worst in at least 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than 170 million people have watched at least some
of the Olympics in its first 11 days, viewership is lagging well
behind the slightly more than 16 million households that the
network conservatively promised advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   On the recent bright side, NBC's Day 11 Monday-night coverage
was the most-watched night to date with a 15.8 rating (each ratings
point equals about 1 million American households) and 68 million
people tuning in.
</P>
<P>
   Before this week's ratings uptick, this month's Olympic
telecasts had shown a 19 percent ratings drop from the 1992
Olympics in Barcelona, Spain, and a 32 percent drop from the '96
Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong? Start with the time difference.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the biggest events are taking place in the early-morning
hours in the United States, leaving NBC in a coverage predicament.
The network has chosen to broadcast nothing live. The problem is
that most fans already have found out what happened long before the
events are shown at night.
</P>
<P>
   The official Web site of the Games, www.olympics.com, generated
187 million hits for the Atlanta Games in 1996 and 634 million two
years later for the Winter Games in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sunday, the site already had surpassed 6 billion hits.
People are not waiting for NBC's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   So why not live coverage? Who would watch at 4 a.m.? Too few
people, said Cameron Blanchard, director of NBC Sports
Communications, from Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research has shown that 9 percent of the viewing audience is
available in the wee hours of the morning _ 9 percent, n-i-n-e.
It's nothing,'' Blanchard said. ``This is business. We paid $705
million for the rights for Sydney. And we are not in the business
of putting on the Olympics when no one's available to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers in such northern American cities as Seattle, Detroit and
Buffalo, N.Y., have the option of watching the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp.'s live Olympics coverage. Blanchard, however,
says people are not getting out of bed to do that.
</P>
<P>
   A second key factor is that these Olympics are taking place in
September, rather than July or August. That's because they are
being held in the Southern Hemisphere _ in fact, the last time the
Games were in Australia, 1956 in Melbourne, they were held Nov. 22
to Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   If they were any earlier than September, it still would be
winter in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans' lifestyles are different in September than in June
or July. People have less time for television,'' said Neal Pilson,
former president of CBS Sports who now runs the TV sports
consulting firm of Pilson Communications. ``There's school and work
and two-job families. It's just a less-relaxed lifestyle once we
get into September.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the 1988 Olympics in Seoul, South Korea, also were held
the last two weeks of September and had a double-digit time
difference from the United States. Yet ratings for them were 17
percent higher than current ratings for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pilson said, ``I don't believe that the Olympics are in
any difficulty. They're getting huge numbers. They're just not as
huge as people expected.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Ryun, a former Olympic runner, said there was
something of a hangover effect from the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything from there is going to be something of a letdown,''
the Kansan said. ``When you've hosted the Olympics, and everything
is instantaneous, that's a lot different than what we're
experiencing now. Not only that, but we're not the host.''
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that having either the Summer or the Winter
Olympics now every two years _ rather than them being in the same
year, as they were until 1994 when the Winter Games were moved _
minimizes the effect. Still others say the acceptance of
professional athletes _ basketball and baseball players, for
example _ has robbed the Games of their amateur appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that there was a shortage of feel-good U.S.
gymnastics stories emanating from Australia. The Americans didn't
win any gymnastics medals, and there was no Kerri Strug moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week we didn't have the water-cooler story like we
did in Atlanta,'' NBC's Blanchard said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that, in an Olympic year that should have Kansas
Citians celebrating the accomplishments of local gold medalists
Maurice Greene, Tara Nott and Christie Ambrosi, there's more talk
instead about the 2-2 Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a few people, but we're not getting too many who want
to watch (the Olympics),'' Brad Hunt, bartender at Connie's
Genessee Inn, said this week. ``Just not interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian McTavish and Malcolm Garcia contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
