<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SPEED TRAINS GETTING OFF TO A SLOWER THAN EXPECTED START 
</HEADLINE>
  (Travel Column) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business travelers, still toting up the fiscal and psychological
costs of the summer's air-travel gridlock, are soon going to be
hearing a lot more about the future promise of ``high-speed rail.''
</P>
<P>
   High-speed rail conjures up images of blazing bullet trains in
Japan, or of the sleek 175-mile-an hour and faster trains that now
link cities in Europe on new rail-beds built for real speed. In
this country, Congress is currently weighing passage of a bill that
would enable money-hemorrhaging Amtrak to borrow $10 billion for
high-speed rail projects around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the lobbying to pass the bill intensifies, Amtrak
is about to finally roll out its long-delayed $1.7 billion Acela
Express high-speed rail service between New York City and Boston,
which is seen as a prototype for domestic high-speed rail projects.
The new train, which will be promoted as a way for business
travelers to avoid the crowded skies, will reach speeds of 150
miles an hour on portions of its run.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Vranich, a former Amtrak executive and a leading
proponent of developing new public-private compacts to replace
Amtrak and build a viable system of high-speed rail lines that will
strategically link to the nation's air-travel system, says not so
fast.
</P>
<P>
   He means literally not so fast, by the way. Vranich says that
the new Acela Express trains are not true world-class high-speed
trains and will be too slow to really compete with air shuttle
service. Furthermore, he says, the overall $10 billion high-speed
rail package being figuratively hauled by the new Acela Express is
really a pork-barrel bonanza that will spend money on unnecessary
projects and leave the United States lagging behind Europe and
Japan in having an effective high-speed rail system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, Amtrak said the Acela Express was supposed to
travel between New York and Boston in 2 hours and 55 minutes, with
further improvements in time,'' said Vranich, who was a member of
the congressionally appointed Amtrak Reform Council before he
resigned in July, claiming that Amtrak was a money-pit and that the
only effective reform would be to discard it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule keeps getting longer,'' Vranich said of the Acela
Express. ``The last thing I heard, it was going to be 3 hours and
15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the new Acela is going to take as long as 3 hours and
20 minutes to travel between New York and Boston, said Rick
Remington, an Amtrak spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's not competitive,'' Vranich argued. ``To be
air-competitive on that route, you really have to come in at under
three hours. The bottom line is that when the Acela express is up
and running full blast, I regret to say not enough airline
passengers will be diverted to rail.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's Remington replied, ``Joe Vranich had the opportunity to
make that argument with the Amtrak Reform Council, but chose to
quit. Thirty-six states from Maine to California, on the other
hand, are now working with Amtrak to expand service or invest in
high-speed rail projects. The traveling public is responding with
the highest ridership in Amtrak's 29-year history.''
</P>
<P>
   Vranich, who is the author of the book ``Super-Trains: Solutions
to America's Transportation Gridlock'' (St. Martin's Press, 1991),
said that he isn't opposed to the Aleca Express per se.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is Amtrak is going to be 30 years old next
year. After 30 years and billions of dollars _ bottom line _ here
is what we have in terms of a modern high-speed train: The Acela
Express in the year 2000 will travel between New York and Boston
only 40 minutes faster than the 1956 schedule between New York and
Boston of the Advance Merchants Limited, a train run by the old New
Haven Railroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Remington said that the first Acela Express trains are expected
to be delivered by the end of this week. After a crew shakedown
period, he said, the trains should be carrying the first passengers
within a few weeks. ``But until we've got a train on our hands,
we're not setting a date'' for the start of service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vranich argued that, whatever the merits of the much-heralded
Acela Express, a politically beholden bureaucracy like Amtrak is
incapable of planning and delivering a national network of ``true
high-technology, high-speed trains that tie in with the aviation
system'' in strategic, high-traffic areas of the Northeast, Midwest
and coastal California.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he asserted, is that ``politicians all over the
country are standing up to say what a wonderful thing this $10
billion high-speed rail spending bill is, because some of the money
is going to be spent in their districts.'' He said the bill and
other high-speed initiatives have defined ``high speed rail'' in
such a way that much of the funding will go to slower trains and
what he believes is unnecessary long-distance rail service.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Vranich said true high-speed rail, requiring a new
public-private financed infrastructure and even the building of new
tracks like the ones laid down in Europe to handle trains traveling
at 200 miles an hour, was the smart way to plan to alleviate
air-traffic strain that will only get worse in coming years, he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all these other countries can set up viable high-speed rail
systems, why can't we?'' Mr. Vranich said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
