<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-ANIMALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WAR-WEARY ANGOLA, ANIMALS OFFER A PEACEABLE KINGDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola _ First came the elephants, with ears flapping
and trunks swinging. Then came the antelope, skittish and shy,
dancing on slender hooves.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 people _ cabinet ministers, military officers,
businessmen and journalists _ dropped by last week to welcome the
33 animals that were flown from South Africa earlier this month to
inhabit Quicama National Park, Angola's first wildlife reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want, with this eloquent gesture, to demonstrate our
solidarity with nature and to bring beauty back to one of the most
important parks in the country,'' Fatima Jardim, the minister of
fisheries and environment, said at last week's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement inevitably left some people dubious. Animal
rights activists in South Africa howled about the potential dangers
of poachers and land mines. Some Western diplomats worried that the
animals would be eaten by hungry Angolans. (Angola, which suffers
from severe shortages of food, understandably runs short of
optimism on most days.) Still, the story was big news in this
war-ravaged country, where people long for distractions from the
grinding hardships of daily living.
</P>
<P>
   Radio soap operas draw huge audiences here and entire
communities turn out each year to elect local beauty queens. On the
day that the crowd gathered to watch the antelope, for instance,
hundreds lined up to see 16 young women in tiny bikinis and
sparkling high heels compete for the title of Luanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way for us to see that Angola isn't just about war,''
said Amelia Veloso, 25, who sat in the audience. ``It's a way for
us to feel like we have culture and we're part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Older people still proudly remember the days when thousands of
elephants, buffalo and antelope wandered through the 3-million acre
reserve, which was established in 1938 and sits just 43 miles
outside Luanda, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   They remember too how the animals were killed and stolen after
the civil war began in 1975 by soldiers, hunters and the hungry.
Today the vast expanse of grasslands and thickets are almost bereft
of large animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything had been shot and poached and killed,'' said Wouter
van Houven, the president of the Kissama Foundation, the nonprofit
group that manages the park.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation built a fence and hired guards to protect the 15
elephants, 10 kudu and 8 eland. They were donated by South Africa,
which has a surplus of the animals. As the animals were flown in on
several flights, van Houven found himself defending the project.
</P>
<P>
   No, there aren't any land mines in the park, he insisted. No,
there aren't rebels fighting nearby. And no, the government is not
wasting public money. The foundation, he said, relies entirely on
private donations.
</P>
<P>
   There was one fatality, however. One elephant stumbled as the
cargo plane was landing, fell on her sternum and suffocated.
Undeterred, foundation officials say they still plan to import 300
elephants from Botswana next year.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, they hope, foreign tourists will fill luxury lodges on
the banks of the nearby Cuanza River. This month, however, the
crowd was made up of Angolans eager for a bit of good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day that we offloaded those elephants, some people stood
there crying,'' said van Houven, who is also a professor of
wildlife management at the University of Pretoria in South Africa.
``The rest stood with their mouths open with awe because they've
never seen a live elephant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
