A2952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NBC-FOX-NYT &LR;      09-26 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NBC-FOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC ENDS BID FOR BASEBALL, SO FOX LANDS SIX-YEAR CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC and baseball are parting ways.
</P>
<P>
   The network told officials of Major League Baseball on Tuesday
that it would not agree to pay at least double its current $80
million-a-year rights fee, ceding all the broadcast rights to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have informed Major League Baseball that we have passed on
their offer,'' said Ken Schanzer, the president of NBC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will end its association with baseball with the American
League Championship Series next month.
</P>
<P>
   A news conference to announce the Fox deal is expected
Wednesday, television executives said. They also said that ESPN
rejected a demand to renew its division series rights, which will
be part of the Fox contract. ESPN was being asked to more than
double its fee of about $6 million a game for about six division
series broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has made a six-year, $2.5 billion offer to own all the
national broadcast rights and retain its Fox Sports Net and Fx
cable rights. For the last five years, it has paid $575 million to
carry the Saturday Game of the Week, alternated All-Star Games and
World Series with NBC, showed one league championship series while
NBC showed the other, and televised divisional series games.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will now take NBC's All-Star Game and postseason rights plus
ESPN's divisional series rights.
</P>
<P>
   Divisional series games have never thrilled the networks,
because their ratings are low.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball had originally sought a tripling of Fox's payments to
retain what it had, largely to mimic ESPN's new six-year,
regular-season $810 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   By making its new deal, Fox is guaranteeing highly rated World
Series every year for six years _ although the event's rating are
in a downward trend _ along with lower-rated League Championship
Series games.
</P>
<P>
   The added games will fill Fox's October programming schedule but
will also force it to sell considerably more commercial inventory.
And as the network with the weakest ratings, Fox will be faced with
stiff counterprogramming from its three major rivals; when NBC was
splitting the rights, it did not diminish the value of baseball by
putting its best shows against the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   For NBC, this is its second leave-taking from baseball in the
past 10 years. CBS paid $1.06 billion for all the broadcast rights
commencing from 1990 to 1993. The deal lost an estimated $500
million for the network.
</P>
<P>
   NBC returned in 1994 in a revenue-sharing partnership called the
Baseball Network with ABC and Major League Baseball. It provided
baseball with no cash up front, and the partnership then unraveled
because the players' strike eliminated revenues from the 1994
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and ABC left acrimoniously, charging that baseball had dealt
unfairly with them.
</P>
<P>
   NBC vowed not to make a deal with baseball again until the 21st
century. But four months after the divorce, NBC made the five-year,
$400 million deal that will conclude with its ALCS telecasts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
