<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERRY-MURDER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI MAN'S LOVE STORY ENDS IN MURDER, SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jerry Cassaday sat in his recliner and looked
out on the lake behind his apartment in Odessa. Nearby were
reminders of his life: a photo of his three boys, a photo of his
ex-wife and a photo of his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away was his .22-caliber rifle.
</P>
<P>
   It had all gone so wrong, and he had been such a fool.
</P>
<P>
   Cassaday, an ex-cop, had murdered a man in Michigan for the
woman he loved. Now he believed she had lied to him.
</P>
<P>
   On a February day this year, Cassaday decided he would not go to
prison. Ex-cops can't go to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Cassaday wouldn't take secrets to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   A locked briefcase under his bed would see to that.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month Cassaday's girlfriend sat in a Flint, Mich.,
jail, charged with conspiring with Cassaday to kill her husband.
She has pleaded not guilty. Authorities, her attorney said, bungled
their investigation and built their case on fabricated evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence in that briefcase, now laid out in Michigan court
files, tells a story of love, deception and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Cassaday's life had been so different. His family
described him as a high-spirited guy with a great sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   For nine years he was a Cass County sheriff's deputy who was
proud of his work chasing thieves, robbers and even killers.
Eventually he became a lieutenant. In his spare time he took his
sons hunting.
</P>
<P>
   But problems in the department prompted his resignation in 1994.
Later he separated from his wife. Drug and alcohol problems dogged
him, too.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the security detail at Harrah's North Kansas City
Casino &AMP; Hotel, and that led to a job in Reno, Nev. He dealt cards
there at Harrah's Casino. But Cassaday still had problems making
payments on his late-model Ford F-150 pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day last year, a woman walked into the casino.
</P>
<P>
   She was Sharee Miller, who at 27 was more than 10 years younger
than Cassaday. She was an attractive, supportive and seemingly
wealthy woman from Flint. She stayed in the plusher hotel suites,
and Cassaday heard stories about her money, jewelry and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Harrah's first saw Jerry and Sharee together in the
early summer of 1999, when she was in town for a Mary Kay Cosmetics
convention.
</P>
<P>
   One of the employees, Carol Slaughter, told a Michigan detective
that the couple had big plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry told me...they had gone out and they had looked at
homes...in the half-million-dollar (range),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Miller was just married. In April 1999 she had
married Bruce Miller, a General Motors Corp. autoworker who ran an
auto salvage yard on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Sharee opened the business in the mornings while Bruce slept,
and then he took over in the afternoon before he started the third
shift. She also cared for three children from a previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Cassaday heard about Bruce Miller's other side. Cassaday came to
believe Sharee's husband was an organized crime figure with a hand
in drugs and money laundering. And he believed that Sharee would be
killed if she tried to leave her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Between her visits to Reno, Miller and Cassaday kept in touch
through the Internet. They sent each other hundreds of e-mails and
spent hours corresponding in private chat rooms, court records
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your fool for life, Jerry,'' Cassaday would sign off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love your brat, Sharee,'' she'd answer.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so lighthearted. In a Sept. 23, 1999, chat
session, Cassaday learned about Sharee's recent pregnancy. Cassaday
certainly was the father, and he pressed for details.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next part will be hard....I lost my baby, Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Cassaday responded.
</P>
<P>
   As he watched the screen, more secrets about Sharee's husband
tumbled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would ever tell you that he hits. I got in
trouble because I was with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassaday demanded more details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharee, you can tell me now, or in person when I beat it out
of him,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Cassaday believed from the message that Sharee's injuries were
so bad she had to go to the hospital, but she told the doctors she
had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me start having bad thoughts of killing him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did he hit you?'' Cassaday demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``...Jerry, I can't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassaday pushed for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't hit me, Jerry; he raped me....I lost the baby
because of the force.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Cassaday wrote: ``The things you told me ripped me
in half.... No one, I mean no one, is going to get away with the
things he has done to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood lightened the next month with news that Miller was
pregnant again, this time with twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby, it's all gonna be fine soon,'' Cassaday tapped out on
his computer. ``We will live a wonderful happy life together.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, after Cassaday had moved back to Missouri, he received
electronic pictures of the sonograms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the e-mails you sent me about the baby,'' Cassaday
wrote. ``Please don't stop sending me this stuff....I love you so
much honey.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Cassaday MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
