u f BC-FORD-FIRESTONE-NYT     09-26 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-FIRESTONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD MEMO IN 1990 RESTRICTED TIRE SUPPLIERS' ROLLOVER TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Ford Motor Co. told its tire suppliers a decade
ago not to conduct without Ford's approval a driving test of the
rollover tendencies of sport utility vehicles and other light
trucks, an internal Ford document shows.
</P>
<P>
   The document is of interest because most of the 101 deaths
blamed on Firestone tires in complaints to regulators have occurred
in Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles that flipped over when a
tire failed. But there is considerable disagreement between Ford
and its critics over how the document should be interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Steven M. Pavsner, a personal injury lawyer in Greenbelt, Md.,
who obtained the document in litigation, contended that it showed
that Ford was trying to limit research into rollovers. ``They don't
want a written trail,'' he said, adding that he planned to
distribute copies of the document to lawyers suing Ford in Explorer
cases.
</P>
<P>
   But Donald F. Tandy, a former Ford engineer who wrote the
document, said that the company was conducting driving tests at the
time as part of the development of a computer model of rollovers.
Ford and its tire suppliers were using the computer model, and Ford
had made a decision that it would conduct at its test track in
Arizona all of the real-world tests needed to establish that the
computer model fairly represented reality, Tandy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we were in charge of validating the model,'' said
Tandy, who worked for Ford as a ``vehicle dynamics'' engineer until
1995, when he joined an engineering consulting firm in Houston that
does a lot of work for Ford and other automakers. Tandy discussed
the document at Ford's request.
</P>
<P>
   The document, dated Sept. 6, 1990, also says that Ford
instructed tire makers to provide its officials with oral, not
written, summaries of the results of computer simulations. The
statement is likely to interest congressional investigators, who
have been upset that Ford has not produced the results from
Explorer tire tests conducted in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Ditlow, the executive director of the Center for Auto
Safety, a Washington-based advocacy group that works closely with
personal-injury lawyers, said that the reference to oral summaries
showed that Ford was trying to conceal information. ``It's showing
that you need to hide the results of the test,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy denied this. Engineers for tire makers were just learning
to use the computer model then and were producing sometimes wildly
different results from day to day and then writing elaborate
reports based on inaccurate data, he said. Ford had asked the tire
makers' officials to discuss their results first because this was
simpler and because it did not want to spend years explaining every
test result in litigation, which has happened anyway, Tandy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summary reports would be inaccurate because they'd do
something wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Krusel, a Ford spokeswoman, said that Ford was still
looking for the tire test results requested by Congress and
believed that the results would confirm an affidavit by a Ford
engineer last week that all of the tests were done properly and did
not show a problem. ``We have a vested interest in finding this
document because it confirms'' the affidavit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pavsner said that he planned to distribute copies to other
lawyers in the hope that it could be used against the automaker in
the many cases involving Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles that
rolled over after Firestone tires failed.
</P>
<P>
   Pavsner obtained the document when he sued Ford unsuccessfully
this summer in the case of a Ford Aerostar van that rolled over
when it was hit by a larger van.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Tandy, the document was also initialed by James
Avouris, another Ford engineer who produced the affidavit last week
that the Explorer had been tested.
</P>
<P>
   John Lampe, the executive vice president of
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., a unit of the Bridgestone Corp. of
Japan, complained in congressional testimony last week that the
tire maker had not understood how the stability of sport utility
vehicles differed from cars, and had missed the significance of
tire failures on Explorers as a result. Federal data shows that
most tire-related deaths in Explorers and other sport utility
vehicles occur because of rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   The directive that barred driving tests of rollovers by tire
suppliers was quite explicit. ``No testing by a tire supplier in
the near or limit condition for J-turn is to be conducted w.o. Ford
supervisory approval as well as having Ford personnel at the
site,'' it said, using a common abbreviation for the word
``without.'' In a J-turn test, the vehicle is driven at fairly high
speed, typically 55 miles per hour, and then turned sharply,
inscribing the letter ``J,'' as viewed from above.
</P>
<P>
   The test is one of the less stringent for vehicles' tendency to
roll over. Independent experts, including federal regulators, have
begun using a so-called ``fish-hook'' turn, in which a driver does
a J-turn and then turns back suddenly in the opposite direction
from the semi-circle. The fish-hook turn simulates what might
happen if a driver exits a highway on a curved ramp and comes
around the ramp at fairly high speed only to swerve to avoid
backed-up traffic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
