<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MYSTERIOUS TALE OF A DEBATE TAPE GETS STRANGER  
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The strangest story line of the presidential
campaign to date _ the case of the stolen Bush debate materials _
got a whole lot stranger Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The day started with reports in Texas newspapers quoting
Democratic officials who said the Bush campaign itself had mailed
the debate materials to an adviser to Vice President Al Gore as a
sort of dirty trick intended to raise suspicions of Democratic
thievery. The reports prompted Bush's spokeswoman to issue a stern
denial on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, Bush himself was on MSNBC denying the
Democratic charges while asserting that the real thief was
``sweating bullets'' because FBI agents were ``beginning to hone
in.''
</P>
<P>
   And by late afternoon, The Dallas Morning News had reported in
its online editions that FBI agents had focused their investigation
on an employee of the advertising firm doing Bush's campaign
commercials. The employee, Yvette Lozano, could be seen on a Postal
Service surveillance videotape mailing a package on Sept. 11, at
about the time that the debate materials would have been sent, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Her explanation? She was returning a pair of $19.99 Gap khaki
pants that her boss, Mark McKinnon of Maverick Media, had bought on
the Internet. McKinnon even produced the pants for a reporter from
The Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI spokesman refused to say whether agents had interviewed
Lozano. ``All I can say is we have initiated a preliminary
investigation,'' said the spokesman, Paul Bresson. ``At this point,
we can't even determine if any federal laws have been violated.''
</P>
<P>
   The tale began on Sept. 13 when former Rep. Thomas Downey
received a package with an Austin, Tex., postmark containing a
video of a mock debate between Bush and Sen. Judd Gregg, as well as
some briefing books. Downey turned the materials over to the FBI,
which opened an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It took its first bizarre turn a week ago when the Gore campaign
suspended a 28-year-old campaign worker who had bragged to a friend
that the Democrats might have a ``mole'' inside the Bush campaign.
Gore's aides say there is no mole and that the suspended worker,
Michael Doyne, had made the story up.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications director,
complained that the FBI did not seem to be taking Doyne's case
seriously enough and was instead spending too much time
interviewing Bush campaign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the FBI and the federal law enforcement agencies would
follow up on that boast by looking at computer hard drives to
determine whether in fact there is any substance to those
comments,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes also rejected out of hand assertions by Molly Beth
Malcolm, chairwoman of the Texas Democratic Party, that the
pilfered debate materials were actually sent to Downey by Karl
Rove, Bush's chief political consultant. Democrats contend Rove
bugged his own campaign office during the 1986 gubernatorial
campaign in order to cast aspersions on the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was certain that none of Bush's top advisers would
have sent the materials, adding, ``I'm sure they'd all be happy''
to take lie detector tests to prove their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Kym Spell, a spokeswoman for the Gore campaign, responded,
``This matter is in the hands of professional, experienced
investigators of the FBI. The Gore campaign is comfortable with
that. For some reason, the Bush campaign is not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
