<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES BAN ON ADS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDARHURST, N.Y. _ Declaring that advertisers were directing a
``barrage of materialistic marketing'' at children, Hillary Rodham
Clinton on Tuesday called on the federal government to ban
commercials aimed at preschool children, and to prohibit
advertising inside public elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the second of two days of campaigning directed at
Jewish audiences, said the Federal Trade Commission should be
authorized to ban advertising that it determines is intended for
children susceptible to manipulation. She also called for
legislation that would prohibit the marketing of materials to
children in elementary schools, as in book covers with
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many companies simply see our children as little cash cows
that they can exploit,'' Clinton said as she introduced what her
advisers described as a new theme in her campaign, a topic that she
raised with increasing vigor throughout a day of campaigning on
Long Island and in Manhattan and the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that advertisers target the youngest of our
children,'' she said. ``Imagine. They are advertising to children
who have not yet even reached kindergarten. They are trying to get
these children to be influenced in what they want to buy and own.''
</P>
<P>
   She offered scant details of how such a regulation might be
accomplished, including, for example, how the government would
distinguish between an advertisement intended to influence adults
and one intended to manipulate children. Clinton's aides said that
under her proposal, that determination would be left to the trade
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission made a similar a proposal in 1978. Congress
responded two years later by stripping its authority to issue such
regulations, and Clinton essentially called for that authority to
be restored.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is reminiscent of the kind of proposals that formed
the bedrock of President Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign, in
that it strikes what many politicians believe is a particularly
receptive chord among voters on an issue that Clinton's opponent is
unlikely to dispute her on.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio responded to Clinton's proposal not by attacking it, but
rather by offering a list of contributions she had received from
corporations that, he said, were guilty of the kind of offenses she
criticized. Lazio's spokesman, Dan McLagan, said that she did not
have the grounding to make such a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody likes kids,'' McLagan said. ``Her program sounds
nice, but it's difficult to take her seriously because she's a
wholly owned subsidiary of Hollywood and the entertainment
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
