<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE GAME IS LISA'S SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It wasn't Lisa Fernandez's most overwhelming
pitching performance. After all, she issued a walk as early as the
first inning, gave up a single as early as the second inning and
even allowed a home run as early as the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   And she only managed eight strikeouts during her eight innings
of work and actually was roughed up for three hits.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States-Japan gold-medal softball game was over,
when she happily joined the triumphant mob scene at home plate with
her teammates, when she paraded around the stadium holding the
American flag, Fernandez once again had validated her status as the
greatest player in her sport.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she were only a mere shadow of herself, she was good
enough to beat a resourceful Japan team 2-1 _ a team that had gone
8-0 since arriving in Sydney. And she was good enough to add
another Olympic medal to her burgeoning trophy case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning this gold medal feels even better than the 1996 one in
Atlanta because we had to overcome so much adversity to do it,''
said Fernandez moments after the her team had scored an unearned ru
the proceedings in the bottom of the eighth. The Japanese left
fielder misjudged a fly ball hit by Laura Berg when the rain
started drenching Blacktown Softball Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely didn't have my best stuff and struggled
throughout the game. And that's what makes this gold medal so
sweet. It seemed like we struggled the whole time we were here and
no one gave us a chance when we lost those three games in a row.
But we hung in there, never gave up and came out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans pulled off a most unlikely revenge trifecta _
beating the three teams that had upset them earlier in the
tournament, China, Australia and Japan, in one harrowing 24-hour
period to contin reign atop the softball universe.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez played the decisive role in the remarkable comeback,
silencing Australia 1-0 on a one-hitter Monday night and then
coming back Tuesday night without any rest and repulsing a fast,
clever Japanese team that seemed to be on the threshold of
dethroning the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa wasn't at the top of her game tonight, but she showed
what a warrior she was by hanging in there and getting the job
done,'' said her catcher, Stacey Nuveman, who tied the game at 1-1
in the fifth inning with a two-out single, the Americans' only hit.
``She showed t a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez allowed only two earned runs and seven hits in 29
innings in her four pitching appearances here, but it's what she
did the past couple of evenings that stood out far more than even
her 25-strikeout masterpiece in a losing effort last week against
the Aussies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. coach, Ralph Raymond, has such respect for Fernandez
that he passed over a couple of rested pitchers with solid
credentials, Lori Harrigan and Christa Williams, to go with the
Long Beach native who graduated from St. Joseph High.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wise decision by Raymond, just as it was a wise
decision by Walter Alston back in 1965 when he pitched Sandy Koufax
on two days rest instead of Don Drysdale in the seventh game of the
World Series between the Dodgers and Minnesota Twins. Koufax
affirmed Alston's faith in him by shutting out the Twins on two
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez affirmed Raymond's faith in her with a heroic effort
on a night when her fastball didn't have its usual speed and when
her infielders, especially shortstop Crystl Bustos, made several
deft plays to rescue her from certain trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a total team effort _ everyone contributed in some
way,'' said Fernandez. ``When we fell behind, my teammates kept
encouraging me each time we'd come off the field. They'd say, `Just
keep fighting. Just keep fighting.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And Fernandez did just that, especially after Reika Utsugi had
perfectly timed a changeup and sent it over the center-field fence,
barely eluding the grasp of Berg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have it together in the early going and I think
they were reading my pitching signs,'' she said. ``I definitely
think I was `picked' on that home run. She was waiting for that
changeup, knew it was coming. We changed our signs after that.''
</P>
<P>
   And after that, the hustling team from Japan _ its tiny center
fielder, Hiroko Tamoto, would do a Maurice Greene imitation when
going to her position and then bow to an adoring crowd _ never was
able to solve Fernandez's array of pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez was emotional afterward _ as were all her teammates _
as she sang the national anthem and kept waving the American flag.
She would say she felt patriotic and a keen love for her country
because her father, Ricardo Fernandez, was one of the refugees who
escaped Cuba after the Bay of Pigs in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad I'm able to represent the United States and do
something nice for a country that gave my father a place to live
under a government not run by a dictator,'' said Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   She would go on to say how good she felt and how appreciative
she was of her teammates and how wonderful it was to be able to
overcome all the hardships of the past 10 days. Ralph Raymond
listened quietly and later saluted his biggest star.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a gamer Lisa is!'' he said. ``I never hesitated one
moment about pitching her tonight. When you have her talent and her
heart, you have to go with her. I wanted to win that gold and I
just knew Lisa would bring it home.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez certainly did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-26-00 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
