<DOCNO> NYT20000926.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-26 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-HAUCK-NYT &LR;      09-26 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HAUCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE G. HAUCK, 88, FORMER NEWS EDITOR OF NEW YORK TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Pa. Ohio, Mich.. Fla.)   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence G. Hauck, a former news editor of The New York Times,
died Sept. 26 at a hospice in Winston-Salem, N.C. He was 88 and
lived in High Point, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In almost three decades at The Times, Hauck oversaw a diverse
array of the newspaper's operations, from managing United Nations
reporting in Paris to directing coverage of the Republican and
Democratic National Conventions in two election years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Hauck was the editor of regional editions when The
Times first experimented with remote makeup and printing for the
Western United States and in Europe. Hauck oversaw the selection
and editing of articles in New York that were sent by
teletypewriter to both Paris and Los Angeles for printing. The
Paris edition lasted until 1967, when it was merged with the Paris
edition of The Herald Tribune into what then became The
International Herald Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles edition, distributed in 13 Western states,
including Alaska and Hawaii, lasted for two years; it became a
victim of production costs in the pre-computer era.
</P>
<P>
   Hauck joined the newspaper in 1948 as a copy editor on the
foreign desk. Before that, he worked as a reporter and editor for
Ohio newspapers and for The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He was born on Aug. 11, 1912, in Fairview, Pa. At the time, the
town had a population of 571. After graduating from Ohio University
in 1933, he worked at a series of small Ohio newspapers, then at
The Detroit Free Press, before joining The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hauck married Esther L. Kernan in 1941. The two later divorced,
and Hauck married Ann Kinney McLean in 1964; Mrs. Hauck died in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II, Hauck became a Navy pilot, ending the war with
the rank of lieutenant commander; he served in South America and in
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to The Associated Press and covered the United
Nations for two years. In 1948, he joined the foreign desk of The
Times and oversaw a special operation set up to cover sessions of
the United Nations General Assembly. In 1951, he moved to Paris
when the General Assembly held its meeting there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, he joined the Washington bureau as a night news editor.
Over the next decade, he also taught journalism at Brooklyn College
and New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Hauck was promoted to news editor in 1976; he retired the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career at The Times, Hauck wrote articles on
subjects ranging from novels by Iris Murdoch to a trip to the
Adriatic port town of Dubrovnik, then in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   After retirement, Hauck moved with his wife from the Upper West
Side of Manhattan to Lake Worth, Fla. He moved to North Carolina
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hauck leaves no immediate survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
