<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPANISH-RADIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO TO BROADCAST ALL NEWS, ALL THE TIME, ALL IN SPANISH  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When WNNY-AM (1380) turns on its microphones
Wednesday at noon, the station will become the New York region's
first all-news, all-the-time Spanish-language radio station. To
many industry analysts, that is a sign of advertiser interest in
the growing buying power of the nation's Hispanic listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Mega Communications, a privately owned Hispanic radio
conglomerate, recently bought the station, which had been known as
WDKM, in a deal valued at $45 million. It then changed its call
letters to WNNY, switching its Spanish-music format to all news.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-language radio market in New York could generate an
estimated $85 million in annual revenues, and there are already
five stations catering to its audience. Those stations already
capture about 10 percent of the region's radio listeners.
</P>
<P>
   WNNY will have a news staff of about 40 people and broadcast a
format similar to that of WINS-AM (1010) and WCBS-AM (880). While
the station has only a 5,000-megawatt signal, it easily reaches
areas of Upper Manhattan, the Bronx and northern New Jersey that
have dense clusters of Hispanic residents, company officials said.
Stations like all-news WCBS and WINS, as well as the Spanish
station WADO-AM (1280) transmit at 50,000 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One in five people in New York is of Hispanic origin,'' Adam
Lindemann, the president of Mega Communications and the heir to his
father's cellular telephone fortune, said in an interview
yesterday. ``One in 10 stations in New York are Spanish, so if you
just correlate radio stations with population, there are about half
as many as there should be.''
</P>
<P>
   James Marsh, an analyst at Prudential Securities, said that
there was some concern about whether WNNY's 5,000-megawatt
transmitter had the power to draw enough listeners, and that some
feared advertising revenue might be drying up across the board. But
Marsh said that returns in the radio industry had been fairly
favorable, especially in the Hispanic market, to which advertisers
were increasingly turning.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of Mega Communications seems to be a testament to
that, he said. The company, based in Silver Spring, Md., has grown
in four short years from a fledgling startup to the country's
fourth-largest Hispanic radio broadcaster, boasting 20 stations,
all on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Lindemann said that the company's research suggested that many
Spanish listeners were interested in news more geared toward them.
The success of the music and talk format stations in bringing
advertisers to Spanish outlets and the success of WINS and WCBS
have made it easier to persuade advertisers to sign on, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
